<SLUG> BC-FEDERAL-LOSANGELES-2takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOFT-SPOKEN JUSTICE DEPARTMENT OFFICIAL SEEKS TO REASSURE L.A.
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BETH BARRETT and GREG GITTRICH 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Reforms of the Los Angeles Police Department can
be worked out without undermining local control, the country's
civil rights chief, Bill Lann Lee, said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking out for the first time since the U.S. Justice
Department's ultimatum to city officials a week ago to fix the LAPD
or face a civil rights lawsuit, Lee said he wants to make the LAPD
a better organization through managerial changes that will assure
the constitutional rights of all citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (Justice) Department has no desire to take over or to
hamstring the operations of the local police,'' Lee said in a
telephone interview with the Daily News. ``The officers in the
field will not be hampered.We just want to make sure the LAPD is
doing the best job it can.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will work hard to support the local police; the people of
Los Angeles will see that,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Lee declined to discuss the specifics of the four-year federal
civil rights investigation, punctuated by the Rampart corruption
scandal.
</P>
<P>
   His comments came as city leaders were huddling for what
promises to be a series of high-stakes negotiations this week.
Sources say city officials want the Justice Department to be more
forthcoming on the strength of its case.
</P>
<P>
   If not, the city, acting on limited information, would either
have to agree to settle the case through a consent decree retaining
some local control through a jointly selected mediator or risk
losing in court and suffering even harsher penalties.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, according to many who have known him during a long and
prestigious career as a civil rights attorney in Los Angeles, is
committed to consensus building. He was a central figure in a
comprehensive federal consent decree with the Metropolitan
Transportation Authority in 1996 that controls funding for a large
portion of the city's troubled public transportation system.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a belief in trying to work out difficult controversies;
that's the main thing I think I bring to the table,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Around City Hall, several officials were flattered by visits
from the acting assistant attorney general for civil rights prior
to May 8's meeting, where he announced the civil rights ``pattern
and practice'' lawsuit had been authorized.
</P>
<P>
   Councilwoman Laura Chick said Lee introduced himself several
weeks ago, stressing his local ties and his desire to do the best
for a city he has affection for.
</P>
<P>
   ``He very much wanted me to remember he's a person of Los
Angeles, that he knows and cares about Los Angeles,'' Chick said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that struck me the most was how much he didn't want
to play the role of the occupying army. He wanted the local
authority leading the way. He was not heavy handed.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee, 51, hardly looks or acts the part of a tough negotiator and
litigator. At last week's meeting, 14 of the city's most powerful
leaders had to lean forward to decipher his softly spoken words.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I happen to believe that often the best resolution on
civil rights matters is when the parties can work it out
themselves,'' Lee said, his voice barely audible on the phone. ``I
think there's an opportunity to bring a lot of people together here
for a potential settlement. There's a chance to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to approach this in the spirit of cooperation,''
he added. ``All points of view will be heard. People will be rising
to the occasion.''
</P>
<P>
   Both his former colleagues and adversaries see Lee as something
of an invisible man with a unique ability to hammer out agreements.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Klein, head of litigation for the law firm Riordan &AMP;
McKinzie, squared off in the early 1990s when Lee was leading the
NAACP Legal Defense and Educational Fund's crusade to force the MTA
to improve bus service.
</P>
<P>
   Klein, the MTA's longtime outside counsel, was tasked by the
agency with staving off a costly and potentially embarrassing
lawsuit a similar situation to the one the LAPD now faces.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember the first meeting in their offices but I don't
remember if Lee was there or not,'' Klein recalled. ``That's very
revealing because that's the kind of guy he is. I wouldn't be
surprised if he was there and I didn't realize it, and didn't
realize he was co-equal or above everyone else there.''
</P>
<P>
   If Lee were still involved, Klein said the MTA consent decree
likely would have succeeded without the current ``legal fireworks''
that have pitted the MTA against bus advocates in lengthy
litigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that Bill's a savior,'' Klein said. ``It's just that
once he left there was no one still there like him.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee said he hasn't kept up with the MTA consent decree since
leaving Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Born and raised in the Bronx borough of New York City, Lee comes
from a humble background. His parents owned a small laundry and he
credits his father, who suffered anti-Chinese taunts despite his
proud military service, with providing the inspiration for a career
in civil rights law.
</P>
<P>
   (more)
</P>
<P>
   Lee says he's still stirred by the memory of the American flag
given to his mother at his father's funeral nine year's ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched my father sometimes being demeaned or taunted,
because he was a lowly laundryman and didn't speak English well,''
Lee said. ``But he had this abiding belief of American promise,
which he'd learned in the American Army.''
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from Bronx High School of Science, Lee
benefited from an affirmative action program at Yale University,
winning a scholarship designed to recruit minority students. He
graduated with honors in 1971 and went on to Columbia University
Law School, where he graduated in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Before President Bill Clinton appointed Lee as acting assistant
attorney general for civil rights in December 1997, Lee was the
Western Regional Counsel for the National Association for the
Advancement of Colored People Legal Defense and Educational Fund;
before that he worked at the Center for Law in the Public Interest.
</P>
<P>
   Civil rights attorney Connie Rice, who worked with Lee at the
NAACP, said he has a genius for inspiring trust in his opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't mind if his opponents take the credit,'' if a
satisfactory deal is struck, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican-controlled Senate has refused on two separate
occasions to confirm Lee's nomination by Clinton. The Senate
majority has decried Lee as a liberal with an affirmative action
agenda, citing his opposition to a California initiative ending
affirmative actions programs as proof.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate, however, chose not to reject Lee outright by
recording its vote. That allowed Clinton to appoint Lee ``acting''
chief of the federal Civil Rights Division, a move that would allow
him to serve until Clinton leaves office in January.
</P>
<P>
   While Lee has made an immediate good impression with city
leaders, his personal reassurances still leave many unanswered
questions among city officials.
</P>
<P>
   In his public comments on the Justice Department's findings and
demands, Riordan has argued that the city, not a federally
appointed monitor, should control the police force's day-to-day
operations and implement the required reforms. The mayor also has
been unflinching in his support of LAPD Chief Bernard C. Parks.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations over the terms of the consent decree are scheduled
to begin this week. The city's negotiating team is Riordan's Chief
of Staff Kelly Martin, City Attorney James Hahn, Police Commission
President Gerald Chaleff and Chief Legislative Analyst Ron Deaton.
</P>
<P>
   Councilman Mark Ridley-Thomas, who has known Lee for years, said
the civil rights chief has made every attempt to stress that the
federal government is here to help the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Lee) wants L.A. to do what it needs to do, and what it hasn't
done, which is to get to the bottom of the problems in the
department,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a strong supporter of the LAPD,'' Lee said. ``We just want
to make sure all the laws are lived up to and that the LAPD is
doing the best it can for all citizens.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
