<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS QUIET ON BIZARRE FINISH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ First, the Los Angeles Lakers lost control of the
game. Then they lost their grip.
</P>
<P>
   The closing minutes of Sunday's 117-98 defeat to the Phoenix
Suns turned into just a series of pratfalls and high jinks. You
half expected Dennis Rodman to suit up and join the fray.
</P>
<P>
   It started with Rick Fox, who played a mere two minutes in the
second half and perhaps needed to unleash some frustration. With
3:58 left, the Lakers down 19 points, Fox for some reason
intentionally fouled Clifford Robinson, then briefly scuffled with
him, drawing a technical foul.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-one seconds later, Fox did the same thing, grabbing
Robinson from behind as soon as he caught the ball. Robinson
laughed, while Fox exchanged words with official Joey Crawford, who
gave Fox a second technical and an automatic ejection.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Fox was in no mood to offer insight, walking past a
reporter without speaking, while teammate John Salley ran
interference.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not talking,'' Salley said. ``You don't want to get
cursed out. He's not talking.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Horry waved off any questions about the incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ask Rick about that one. I can't answer for him,'' he said.
``I don't know what was going on with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Phil Jackson made the next oddball move, calling a timeout
with 18.4 seconds left, the Lakers down 21 points. Before play
could resume, Suns coach Scott Skiles retaliated with a pointless
timeout of his own. Then Jackson called one more, with 14.7 seconds
left.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson didn't offer any explanations afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were just having fun; we were just having fun,'' Ron Harper
said. ``Part of the game. He called timeout, we called timeout.
Hey, all in fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Home cookin': The upside for the Lakers is that, assuming they
put away the Suns on Tuesday, they'll have only four or five days
to wait for the conference finals to start. In the meantime,
they'll take solace in playing at home.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers are 5-0 in the postseason at Staples Center, after
going 36-5 there this season. This, they said, is what the
homecourt advantage in the playoffs is for.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played 82 games, and we earned it, to be able to head back
home,'' Harper said.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns' victory Sunday was their first in eight meetings with
the Lakers this season, and they are 0-4 at Staples.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's 3-1, they're going home, where they've dominated,''
Skiles said. ``We have in the last month of the season become a
good road team. ... We're certainly not intimidated to go back
there and play.''
</P>
<P>
   Blasted: The Lakers made defense their calling card this season,
then misplaced the entire deck Sunday, when the Suns scored 71
points in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very strange,'' Glen Rice said. ``That's one of those
nightmares, and we're a very capable team, and something like that
should never happen. And we just gotta hope it never does again.''
</P>
<P>
   Being Willis Reed: A sprained right ankle supposedly threatened
to keep the Suns' Clifford Robinson off the court, but it was hard
to tell as he cruised to a career-playoff-high 32 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``God is great. God works miracles, and evidently Cliff wasn't
feeling any pain out there,'' teammate Penny Hardaway said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
