<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-HEAT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIAMI TURNOVERS LET KNICKS EVEN SERIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Honest-to-goodness basketball returned to this
Eastern Conference semifinal Sunday. So did equality.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks, facing an almost unmanageable 3-1 deficit, rallied
behind Charlie Ward (20 points, 9 in the final 4:04) and squared
this best-of-seven affair at 2-2 with a 91-83 victory over
error-prone Miami.
</P>
<P>
   The series has been reduced to a best-of-three, with Game 5
Wednesday night in Miami. The Heat needed at least a split here;
they got that but still left town quite upset.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a gift,'' said a disgusted Alonzo Mourning, who
accepted the role as chief gift-giver with nine turnovers. He also
missed three big free throws down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``You almost gotta be mistake-free in a series like this,''
Mourning said. ``We gave them gifts, constantly.''
</P>
<P>
   The Heat turned it over 17 times, which the Knicks gratefully
turned into 28 points (a 14-point edge in that department). The
Knicks did an about-face from Game 3 and outscored Miami, 17-6, on
second-chance points. Miami still had a rebounding advantage,
48-37, but the Knicks controlled the boards in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had times where we struggled,'' said Patrick Ewing (12
points, 11 rebounds, 1 block), ``but we still played with a lot of
energy and emotion. I think that is what got us over the hump.''
</P>
<P>
   New York had enviable balance offensively _ yes, it finally
broke 90 _ with Ward leading all five starters in double figures.
Allan Houston had 17 (after a scoreless first quarter) while
Latrell Sprewell cavorted for 16. Mourning led Miami with 27. The
redoubtable Dan Majerle had 13 points, 12 rebounds, and 4 steals in
a losing cause.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks were forced into desperation mode and, as has been
the pattern when these two teams meet in the playoffs, the loser
tends to bounce back. No one has been able to win two straight over
their last nine playoff games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Up and down. Up and down. That is the way we always play
against each other,'' said Miami's Tim Hardaway.
</P>
<P>
   New York led at every checkpoint and actually had a double-digit
lead (10 points) for the second time in the series. (Miami has yet
to experience that thrill.) A late run in the third quarter gave
the Knicks a 66-57 lead heading into the fourth and Miami never got
closer than 5 over the final 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say they didn't have their chances. Coach Pat
Riley said it was ``mind-blowing'' that, despite the Heat's erratic
play, they were still in position to steal it in the final four
minutes. The Knicks led, 84-78, when Mourning missed three of four
freebies. Instead of a 2-point game, it was 5.
</P>
<P>
   Then, on the Knicks' next possession, Houston missed a
3-pointer, but Ewing knocked away the rebound and Ward saved it
from going out of bounds. The point guard, who went 32 minutes,
then converted a runner in the lane to make it 86-79 with 1:51
left. (He was fouled, too, but missed the free throw.) He scored
the final 9 points for the Knicks, eliciting chants of ``Charlie,
Charlie'' from the Madison Square Garden faithful.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that sealed the game,'' said Knicks coach Jeff Van
Gundy.
</P>
<P>
   Riley had not liked what he saw in practice Saturday and hoped
that something would change by game time. But turnovers, missed
assignments, and overall sloppy play prevailed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the game that I was afraid we were going to play,'' he
said. ``They had a lot to do with that. But I don't think our focus
and our concentration (was there), being aware of just how much
they needed this game. We were absolutely careless. We made more
mistakes defensively than we made in the previous three games.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley had tried to stress that a victory would have all but
knocked out the Knicks. Instead, he and everyone else are looking
at a knock-down, drag-out affair _ again _ that looks every bit
like it will go the full seven. There hasn't been a Heat-Knicks
series that hasn't gone the distance yet. This one doesn't look
like it will be the exception.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
