<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-GOODY-AZR </SLUG>
  
 WHAT IF ART DIDN'T IMITATE LIFE, BUT WAS IT?
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; BILL GOODYKOONTZ  &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QL; 
(PHOENIX) - We spend so much of our time consumed by television -
what if it consumed us literally?
</P>
<P>
   What if you woke up one day and found yourself living inside
your favorite shows, alongside your favorite (and not-so-favor ite)
characters?
</P>
<P>
   A day in the TV life:
</P>
<P>
   You awake, sweating from an other Regis nightmare in Frasier
Crane's well-appointed apart ment, with Dharma (or Greg, depending)
silently snoozing be side you. You stop on your way from the
bedroom to the kitchen to admire the Seattle skyline. Man, what
swell digs.
</P>
<P>
   But you're in a hurry - you've got to get to your job at the
White House (I know, it's in Washington, D.C., not Washington
state, but this is TV world - normal laws of reality and physics
don't apply). Best job you've ever had, work ing for President
Bartlet along side Leo, Toby, C.J. and the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Not that your last job was anything to sneeze at. Nothing offers
the security of being safety inspector for the Spring field Nuclear
Power Plant, a job from which it is apparently im possible to be
fired, as your successor, Homer someone or other, has proved time
and again. Four fingers - what do you expect?
</P>
<P>
   Walking to the car that Titus customized for you, you notice
smoke coming out of the neigh bor's house, accompanied by the usual
screaming and crashing. That Malcom kid seems OK, but the other
boys drive you crazy. It would almost be funny if you didn't live
right next door.
</P>
<P>
   Josh's secretary is now your own, and the calendar she hands you
is full. Oddly, it's almost all personal stuff. For instance,
you've got to find someone to cut your hair - there is no way
you're going back to the butcher who allowed Felicity to sacrifice
her lucrative locks on the altar of young-star independence. Kids!
</P>
<P>
   You've also got to find a birth day gift for your father-in-law,
Arthur Spooner, who you can't help but notice bears a remark able
resemblance to Frank Cos tanza, only in a less-funny show.
</P>
<P>
   But first and foremost you've got to call your lawyer, Bobby
Donnell. (Yes, he's in Boston, but this is still TV, so it's a
local call with a 555 prefix.) It's good you found him - Ally over
at Cage, Fish &AMP; Associates was never available to take your calls,
al ways busy defending women ac cused of smothering their
89-year-old husbands with their gigantic breasts and such - an
actual plot too ridiculous even for this dream.
</P>
<P>
   No time for lunch - you've decided to buy Arthur a book. But the
only bookstore nearby is that one in Once and Again, and you'd
rather not read again than set foot in that pretentious yup pie
joint. (Plus for half the year, it occupied NYPD Blue's ad dress.)
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, a stabbing pain in the gut doubles you over. Even
though you've collapsed, you re fuse the Third Watch ambulance
crew's offer of a ride to the hospital, preferring to crawl the
entire distance on your belly rather than spend time with them.
</P>
<P>
   When you reach the emer gency room, Dr. Carter gives you the
news - your appendix is hot; it has to come out immediately. Dr.
Benton is busy, but luckily, Dr. Shutt has agreed to do the
operation, even though he is a neurosurgeon at a different Chi cago
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   But he cancels at the last minute, and just before you're put
under, you see Dr. Hanlon - a cosmetic surgeon - heading your way
with a scalpel. Horrified, recalling her work opposite Jim Carrey
in Dumb and Dumber, you bolt, appendicitis or not, figuring that
Chicago Hope will be canceled before you get your bill, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Happily, the pain miraculously disappears - it's TV, remember -
freeing you up for dinner at Artie Bucco's place, because you're
convinced that that's not where Tony Soprano got food poisoning. I
mean, if he had, Artie would be dead, right?
</P>
<P>
   You stop back by the office, which is now the basement of the
FBI building, to tell Scully (or Mulder, depending) that you're
going to take Nurse Hathaway (or Dr. Greene, depending) to the
Warsaw for a few beers with Drew (or Kate, depending) and the gang.
</P>
<P>
   Scully scoffs, for the ump teenth time, and says she's think ing
about going to Roswell if you don't soon make up your mind about
next season.
</P>
<P>
   Harrumph. Women. (Or men, depending.)
</P>
<P>
   Driving to the bar, a cop pulls you over for speeding. He identi
fies himself as Detective Sipow icz, and for no reason whatsoever,
he starts screaming at you. Luckily, Detective Briscoe pulls up and
the two begin screaming at each other, so you get away clean.
</P>
<P>
   What a day. You decide you'll just head home, which is now the
cool brick number that Michael Wiseman lives in on Now and Again.
You're so tired it takes only a second for you to fall asleep after
Buffy (or Angel, depending) tucks you in.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
And you dream they never can celed Freaks and Geeks. &QL; 
Reach Goodykoontz at Bill.Goo dykoontz &LR; ArizonaRepublic.com or (602)
444-8974.
</P>
