<HEADER>
A5127 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-ANALYSIS-B     05-15 1010
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX PROVING MEN OF POSITION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ It's early. Do you realize how often you will hear
that today?
</P>
<P>
   People who have pinstripes coursing through their veins and
``NY'' stitched on their baseball caps will tell you how early it
is. You will hear it from worriers, augurs, and cynics. You'll
innocently ask someone the time and they'll turn it into a Red Sox
monologue. ``Don't get too excited,'' they'll begin, ``It's early .
. . ''
</P>
<P>
   You shouldn't listen to these people. I think sports fans are
the only ones who keep the It's Early cliche alive. I can't recall
sitting in a movie theater, raving about the beginning of an
excellent film, and having the person next to me whisper, ``Chill
out, man. It's still early.''
</P>
<P>
   It is May 15th and, after their long weekend at Camden Yards,
the Sox are the first-place team in the American League East. It's
early. And it doesn't make a difference. A month from now, the Sox
will be in first or hovering around it. Two months from now, it
will be the same. They aren't going anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   They are a bunch of guys interested in reading baseball's fine
print. They love pitching, bunting, hitting cutoff men, and _ this
is what they consider an exotic dessert _ circling like taloned
carnivores when a team makes a mistake. They have a starter (Pedro
Martinez) and reliever (Derek Lowe) so dominant that you can
combine their ERAs and the number you get _ 1.80 _ still will fall
short of 2. They have a dynamic player, Donnie Sadler, who could
audition as the fleet Mercury if there is a play staged about the
gods of Roman mythology.
</P>
<P>
   Sadler helped win Sunday's game by doing basic things such as
flawlessly executing his end of a 7-6-2 putout in the fourth
inning. He also turned what should have been a single into a double
in the fifth, simply by running hard around first. Ask him about it
and he'll shrug. He's been running hard since his childhood in
Valley Mills, Texas. Then, he would build up his speed by
spontaneously racing against his cousins.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would say, ``Let's run to such and such place.' And we'd
run there, just to see who could get there first,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox, though, will not travel south quickly. The only way
they will go south is if they take a road trip such as the last
one, to the Near South.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in 23 years, a Boston team came here and
swept a four-game series from the Orioles. The Sox won Sunday's
game, 10-1. After losing Nomar Garciaparra and Carl Everett to
injuries in Game 1, the Sox outscored the Orioles, 24-2, over the
next three games (it was 35-6 for the series).
</P>
<P>
   The only disclaimer there is that the Orioles are dreadful. For
the entire series, it always seemed that Mike Hargrove was walking
from the dugout to the mound to rescue a sorry pitcher. He should
get used to this errand. If I were a corporate executive looking
for good advertising space, I would try to put my company's logo at
the base of the Camden Yards mound. Really, that's all Orioles fans
see when they're watching on TV: Hargrove walking to the mound with
his hand out, asking one beleaguered pitcher for the ball so he can
give it to another.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox don't have that problem. They will be fine. There is no
bogeyman hiding in an AL closet, waiting to jump out at them. And
even if there were, they wouldn't be worried.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to look at a team's character,'' Darren Lewis said.
``Are they playing for each other? Do they help one another out? Is
everybody trying to go deep? We're not a Rotisserie team. We just
know how to play the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``That play (in the fourth) when Troy (O'Leary) played the carom
and made the throw? That was huge. Those parts of the game are
overlooked.''
</P>
<P>
   There are other things, too. You should see how the Sox
interact. You should have seen how ecstatic Martinez was to see
Sadler when he was recalled from the minors on Friday. ``Little
man,'' the pitcher called to the 5-foot-6-inch Sadler, ``let me see
you!'' When Sadler's bags were temporarily lost in US Airways
limbo, you should have seen how Sadler moved about the room and was
able to collect spare equipment, mostly from a man, Jeff Frye, who
made the team at Sadler's expense.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously the fans don't see that side of the Sox, but they like
to, as manager Jimy Williams would say, watch these kids perform.
As early as Thursday afternoon, it was apparent that the Sox and
their fans would have been comfortable staking ``Welcome To
Massachusetts'' signs in Maryland soil.
</P>
<P>
   There were Sox fans in local bars and restaurants. There were
even fans chanting ``Yankees Suck'' outside an Inner Harbor hotel
at 3 o'clock Saturday morning. Yes, this definitely felt like the
South _ the South Shore.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say the Sox don't have major flaws. They may
prove me wrong, but I can't see how a team with such a weak right
infield can win a World Series. If I were manager for a day, I'd
make Jose Offerman a full-time DH, and move Sadler to second. It
wouldn't matter if he hit .202. Sadler has such range that he could
make up for some of the defensive deficiencies of Mike Stanley and
Brian Daubach (Don't ask me how I would rotate three DH types in
Offerman, Stanley, and Daubach. Who do you think I am, Jimy?).
</P>
<P>
   As the Sox were packing for Toronto Sunday &UR;  &LR; night, Williams was
asked what it's like to be around his team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope I'm phrasing this the right way,'' the manager began.
``I don't know all about their backgrounds and what all their
families are like. I don't know who is from the rich part of town
and who is from the poor part. But all of them could be from the
same place. Know what I mean? They've all got an honest enthusiasm
for this game. They love to play. They have something that makes me
think they were raised in a certain way, with a certain ethic.''
</P>
<P>
   I imagine that's something else that will be unchanged between
now and the next few months.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
