<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 00:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5128 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-ORIOLES-BO     05-15 1058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-ORIOLES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX SWEEP ORIOLES, TAKE AL EAST LEAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ For a few moments, Red Sox pitcher Brian Rose
sounded like a clone of his coach, Joe Kerrigan, expounding on his
mechanics.
</P>
<P>
   Then he caught himself. This wasn't about technical mastery,
what Rose did Sunday in pitching the Red Sox into first place in a
10-1 rout that completed a four-game sweep of the Orioles, the
first by the Sox in Baltimore in 23 years.
</P>
<P>
   This was about something more primitive, something that could
not be detected merely by rerunning a videotape. This was about
Rose, looking taller than he ever has, coming off the mound in the
fifth inning, pumping his fists once, twice, three times after
winning a pitched battle against the heart of the Baltimore order,
B.J. Surhoff and Albert Belle.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can throw the mechanics out the door, at a time like
that,'' Rose said. ``It was just me against him. Somebody's got to
give. You can only throw so many pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   This was before the Red Sox, once again playing without Nomar
Garciaparra and Carl Everett, broke open a close game with their
second straight eighth-inning eruption, scoring seven runs as the
Orioles imploded from a toxic mix of wretched defense and clueless
relief pitching.
</P>
<P>
   This was when the Orioles, desperate to end what is now a
seven-game slide, were down just a run, 2-1, after Rose walked Mike
Bordick with one out and the bases loaded.
</P>
<P>
   Rheal Cormier was throwing in the Sox bullpen. Surhoff, the No.
3 batter in the Orioles order, was in a deep slump (1 for 20) but
always a dangerous hitter with the bases loaded, batting .412
lifetime with five grand slams.
</P>
<P>
   Four times with a 1-and-2 count, Surhoff fouled off pitches,
including a line drive down the right-field line that landed a foot
foul. Rose missed with a pitch, took a deep breath, then threw
Surhoff a changeup. Surhoff popped it up to shortstop Donnie
Sadler.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was fortunate to make a good pitch, got him swinging off his
front foot, and he popped it up,'' Rose said.
</P>
<P>
   Now came Belle, dubbed the A-Bomb by one Baltimore writer both
for his explosive bat and his volatile temperament. Rose challenged
Belle with eight straight fastballs, which normally is as advisable
as a reporter asking him a question.
</P>
<P>
   But with a full count, Belle hit a fly ball to right field,
where Trot Nixon, drifting back, lifted his glove and made the
routine catch.
</P>
<P>
   Rose, no longer waiting to exhale, made his triumphant return to
the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the best I've ever seen him throw,'' said center
fielder Darren Lewis. ``He had a lot of velocity and he was hitting
his spots.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be Rose's 91st and last pitch of the afternoon, as a
bullpen that strung together 12 1/3 scoreless innings here polished
off the Orioles, with Cormier and John Wasdin pitching two innings
apiece. But it was clear that Rose had done more than leave the Sox
in position to win their fifth in a row.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tremendous, I think, to build on something like that,''
manager Jimy Williams said of Rose, who has pitched well in three
of his last four starts, allowing just three earned runs in 17
innings in those three games, all wins. ``Surhoff fouling off all
those pitches, throwing that many pitches, and then getting outs.
That was pretty impressive.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's certainly got to feel good about himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis had given Rose a 1-0 lead two batters into the game with a
home run off Orioles ace Mike Mussina. It was his first homer since
June 14.
</P>
<P>
   ``When D-Lew hit that home run,'' left fielder Troy O'Leary
said, ``we felt like we had a chance today.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary helped preserve that lead in the fourth, when he played
Jeff Conine's double deftly off the wall and threw to shortstop
Sadler, whose strong relay to the plate cut down Harold Baines, who
was originally signed by wooden-legged Bill Veeck and now, at age
41, runs like him.
</P>
<P>
   Sadler hustled his way to the Sox' second run in the top of the
fifth, turning a catchable blooper into a double, then scoring on
Jose Offerman's ground single. The Sox made it 3-1 against Mussina
when Brian Daubach led off the sixth with his eighth home run of
the season and third in the last five games, a drive into the
left-center field bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Mussina, an elite pitcher in the last year of his contract, now
has given up a league-leading 14 home runs, a primary reason he is
off to the worst start of his career at 1-5.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't complain about seven innings and three runs,'' he
said. ``I can't. I wish it would come out better. I wish we'd get
some better breaks and I wish a lot of stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   So many wishes, so little time. How about wishing that Orioles
reliever B.J. Ryan could throw a strike, instead of starting the
eighth inning by walking the bases loaded, then going 2 and 0 on
Mike Stanley before manager Mike Hargrove yanked him for Jose
Mercedes. Ryan threw 18 pitches, 14 of them balls. Stanley wound up
walking, too, which was charged to Ryan. Everyone who walked
scored.
</P>
<P>
   How about wishing that second baseman Mark Lewis had fielded
Sadler's ground ball, which skipped past him for what was
generously scored a three-run double? How about wishing that the
Sox stopped hitting, instead of going single, single, and Nixon's
two-run triple?
</P>
<P>
   How about wishing that the season somehow could start over for
the Orioles, who on May 3 were in second place, a game ahead of the
Red Sox, but now, after losing seven in a row and 11 of their last
12, are 7 1/2 games behind the first-place Red Sox?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is blame for all of us,'' said Hargrove.
</P>
<P>
   Count the last three games of the '99 Division Series, when he
was still managing Cleveland, and his last seven games against the
Sox, Hargrove has seen his teams outscored, 79-24.
</P>
<P>
   After Saturday's 5-1 loss, in which Orioles reliever Mike
Trombley threw only balls (four) and home run pitches (three),
Hargrove was asked if that was the season's low point.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' he said. ``We haven't played tomorrow yet.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's where things stood on Mother's Day: the Orioles
approaching tomorrow with dread, Rose and the Sox approaching it as
if it can't come fast enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``First place?'' Lewis said. ``Awesome.''
</P>
</TEXT>
