<HEADLINE>
PHOENIX RALLY DRAWS GUN FOES, FRIENDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY BETH DEFALCO  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
(PHOENIX) - As thousands of mothers marched around the nation,
activists on both sides of the gun-control issue clashed in Phoenix
at Patriots Square park.
</P>
<P>
   It was moms against moms, as 600 gun-control supporters filled
the square and about 300 pro-gun protesters surrounded it during a
peaceful Mother's Day demonstration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women have a proud history of changing history,'' said Lila
Schwartz, the former League of Women Voters president, to the
rousing applause of the moms who want gun control.
</P>
<P>
   Women on both sides brought supporters: husbands, dads,
boyfriends, family members and children also carried signs and
chanted on the heated streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm protesting with dignity and don't want any
confrontations,'' said Chris McCarty, a member of the Second
Amendment Sisters, an organization for women who denounced strict
gun control.
</P>
<P>
   The 61-year-old grandmother has her own concealed-carry permit,
but she left her weapon at home Sunday, May 14, so she wouldn't
appear threatening.
</P>
<P>
   The gun advocates surrounded the park, stationed at each
cornered entrance chanting ``Freedom!'' and holding signs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Million Mom Madness: Don't lock up my right to defend our
children,'' one sign read.
</P>
<P>
   Pro-gun supporters tried to drone out pro-control speakers with
the sound of their horns as they drove by.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the park, women demanded gun registration and licensing,
longer waiting periods, manufacturer regulations and an end to
gun-show loopholes.
</P>
<P>
   Several mothers, all of whom had lost loved ones to gun
violence, addressed the crowd surrounded by 60 linked children's
silhouettes made of cardboard. Each cutout stood for a child that
died this year in Arizona. A .44-caliber slug was shot through the
heart.
</P>
<P>
   The mothers reminded onlookers that they vote by wearing ``I
vote'' bumper stickers on their backs.
</P>
<P>
   Since 12-year-old Paige Anderson of Glendale realized she
couldn't yet vote, she amended her sticker to ``I will vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Her mother, Gerry Anderson, co-organized the event rather than
attend the one in the nation's capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have gone to D.C., but I needed to be here today,''
said Anderson, whose brother was killed while on a fishing trip.
</P>
<P>
   The only guns allowed in the park were the ones carried by 20
Phoenix police officers who patroled the area. The gun-control
supporters had secured a permit for the park first, forcing
protesters to keep to the street.
</P>
<P>
   Not all protesters, however, left their guns at home. Douglas
Robertson, 20, protested with a dual holster attached; a Glock 9mm
on one side and a .357 Magnum revolver on the other. Together the
guns had 27 rounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not afraid of muggers,'' Robertson said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach the reporter at &QL; 
Beth.DeFalco(at)Arizona &QL; 
Republic.com or (602) 444-7114. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
