<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SET PLAYS HELP REVOLUTION STAY IN FIRST PLACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ There is little similarity between the
success rate of free kicks in soccer and, say, free throws in
basketball, though they serve a similar purpose. In fact, only
about 10 percent of set plays result in scores in soccer.
</P>
<P>
   So it was a rare feat, indeed, that the Revolution could convert
all three of their free kicks in a 3-1 win at D.C. United Saturday
night, and rarer still that each shot was taken by a different
player.
</P>
<P>
   Even more unusual, though, is the fact that the Revolution have
been in first place in the Eastern Division of Major League Soccer
for nearly a month. They have played five straight games without a
loss for the first time in their five-year history, and a win over
Colorado Wednesday would complete their most productive six-game
stretch ever.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution are finding ways to win.
</P>
<P>
   D.C. United controlled the tempo and had the best chances to
score. But the Revolution remained composed, coach Fernando Clavijo
made effective substitutions by adding Mike Burns and William
Sunsing in the second half, and Jeff Causey saved a Jaime Moreno
penalty kick.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution's goals occurred against the run of play. But it
is a mark of this team that it was able to capitalize. And it is an
indication of increased savvy that the Revolution were able to
raise the level of their game at crucial times.
</P>
<P>
   Each free kick was taken from nearly the same spot on the field,
about 25 yards and on the left side of the goal, not as much a
coincidence as it might seem, since the Revolution were
counterattacking and gaining the advantage on defenders.
</P>
<P>
   Wolde Harris simply lasered the first one, skimming it along the
wet RFK Stadium grass and under the D.C. wall, which jumped over
the ball in unison. Mauricio Ramos curled a left-footed free kick
around the left side of the wall in the 66th minute, and Imad Baba
curled a right-footed kick around the right side of the wall in the
82d minute.
</P>
<P>
   Each goal was set up by some resourceful individual play.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution quickly recovered after falling behind, and
Harris drew a foul from Carlos Llamosa before tying the score.
</P>
<P>
   With the Revolution under siege early in the second half,
Sunsing replaced Johnny Torres and, the first time he touched the
ball, was taken down from behind by Carey Talley. That allowed the
Revolution to readjust, and served as a warning of their ability to
counterattack, a weapon that would make the difference in the
second half.
</P>
<P>
   Defender Ted Chronopoulos anticipated a United pass, then went
on a one-man counter, leading to Ramos's tiebreaking free kick.
Baba and Chronopoulos cleared away shots with Causey beaten, and
Causey saved the penalty in the 78th minute. Then, Sunsing broke
away and was fouled from behind to set up the final score.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution were rewarded for persistence, resourcefulness,
and some skillful feats. But they were clearly not the superior
team, as United displayed better technique and ball movement.
Moreno gave a clinic in the midfield, though Burns discouraged him
somewhat in the second half. And the Revolution seldom played
through their midfield choreographer, Ramos.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took advantage of what they gave us and countered really
quickly,'' Harris said. ``But we need to work on possession and
where people need to be and when.
</P>
<P>
   ``My touches were not up to par. But we created our own luck and
you can't say we weren't working hard.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
