<SLUG> BC-TEN-ITALIAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORMAN CLAIMS TITLE IN SOCCER-MAD ROME 
</HEADLINE>
 OPEN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ The Eternal City went passionately pazzo _ crazy _
Sunday. A stranger might have thought that the Pope was handing out
dispensations in St. Peter's Square or Julius Caesar had
reappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing that minor, however. A local soccer team, Lazio, had won
the Italian championship for the first time in 26 years (only the
second in more than a century) by beating Reggina, 3-0, while
70,000 in Olympic Stadium howled and crooned. They celebrated madly
for hours, ripped up souvenir patches of the turf, and the town
went up like a Roman candle in an all-night revel.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, next door, where 7,000 had gathered in the sunshine
at Il Foro Italico, many of them wearing earphones to keep track of
the game by radio, a Swede named Magnus Norman was having a happy
bash of his own on a terra cotta tennis court. Magnus's magnum opus
was the dethroning of Brazilian Guga Kuerten to win the Italian
Open, 6-3, 4-6, 6-4, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, I heard the soccer crowd, the cheering and the
singing,'' said Norman, his game's startling, unheralded leader at
No. 1, for now. ``But it didn't bother me. I wanted to know the
score myself. Lazio's my team. Why? Their coach is a Swede, Sven
Goran Eriksson, and I've met him a few times. What did bother me
was all the helicopters (police security) for the soccer.''
</P>
<P>
   What bothered Kuerten, the 1997 French Open champ who beat
Patrick Rafter in last year's final here, was the combination of
Norman and an aching back. Kuerten, after taking an injury timeout
for treatment at 0-2 in the fourth set, played somewhat better, but
couldn't deal with his own erratic shotmaking and the Swede's
aggression.
</P>
<P>
   Kuerten said his back ``was stiff'' _ surely not as stiff as
countless Romans Sunday &UR;  &LR; night _ but ``Norman was fitter than me.
You've got to be in the best fitness to play all these tough guys,
tough matches. I have to get there by the French.'' Nursing the
back, he had been out almost a month.
</P>
<P>
   This was the 23-year-old Norman's ninth career title. Although
he tied Pete Sampras and Andre Agassi for the most in 1999 (five),
none of his collection had anywhere near the cachet of the Italian,
the fourth of the season's Masters Series, the nine tournaments
rating just behind the four majors.
</P>
<P>
   Norman took over the summit of the newly minted Champions Race
from third-round loser Agassi after defeating Lleyton Hewitt in a
Saturday semifinal. Loser of merely one set (to Kuerten) all week,
the Swede said he knew he was No. 1 but ``not the best,'' not in
the universe of Sampras and Agassi.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I'm feeling better about No. 1,'' he said. ``I know I can
beat a big guy (Kuerten is No. 6) in a big final. I believe I'm
strong enough physically and mentally to win the French (May
29-June 11), but I've still got Hamburg and Dusseldorf before. It's
a tough schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   Norman, a born and bred clay-lover, said his epiphany had
occurred last year on, of all footings, a grass court, Wimbledon.
``It was a second-round win over Fabrice Santoro. I lost the next
round to Greg Rusedski, but I left as the new Magnus Norman. I
started hitting the ball early. You have to on grass. And it felt
good. I've been doing it ever since.''
</P>
<P>
   That approach differs from the usual baseline hugging-European
dirt-kickers. Norman takes the ball sooner, and from inside the
baseline whenever he can, the Agassi-style ping pong. It kept
Kuerten running, trying to do too much to the ball with too little
time.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Kuerten served poorly (48 percent to the champ's 78),
so it didn't help much that he won the ace race, 15-14. He was
constantly in the briars of break points, fending off 19 of 24. It
was a Kuerten crowd. The man impersonating a mop, in hair and
physique, is irresistible. He raised hopes by fighting off four
match points in a ragged but enthralling ninth game of the fourth
(7 deuces, 20 points, 10 minutes), to 4-5, then pushing Norman to a
break point. But Kuerten botched a forehand return, and it was soon
over in 3:10.
</P>
<P>
   Norman, a lean and quick 6 feet 2 inches, the picture of
athleticism in remarkable retrieving, crushing inside-out
forehands, and leaping smashes, became the third Swedish champion
of Italy, following Bjorn Borg (1974, '78) and Mats Wilander ('88).
``I watched Mats win on TV,'' he said. ``This is an important
tournament in Sweden. I know Bjorn. We belong to the same club
(Kungliga) in Stockholm.
</P>
<P>
   Borg left Il Foro 22 years ago vowing never to return, and
didn't. The generous Romans kept pelting him with coins because he
was beating their guy, Adriano Panatta. Money figured Sunday, too.
Norman, brought up in the small town of Filipstad, known for its
bakeries and bread, departed with more bread ``than I ever dreamed
of'' _ $400,000. It descended on him in a check, not silver.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
