<SLUG> BC-SPINOFF-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
1ST INTEL SPINOFF FOR STATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN SIDENER AND JANE LARSON  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(PHOENIX) - After 21 years in Arizona, Intel Corp. spins off its
first new company into the state economy today, May 15.
</P>
<P>
   Intel, maker of the chips that power most of the world's
computers, is debuting an Internet-based company,
DevelopOnline.com, which enhances collaboration among companies
that make products such as cellular phones and software.
</P>
<P>
   Cell phones and many other appliances are built very
differently, with one company designing the product and its
components and building it from the ground up.
</P>
<P>
   That's starting to change, with companies like Qualcomm Inc.
licensing a key technology to others instead of making phones
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   DevelopOnline will use the Internet to create a sort of online
workshop. A small start-up company with a new antenna for a cell
phone, for example, could electronically browse for a phone from
one manufacturer and a battery from another, then build a virtual
model to see if the pieces work together.
</P>
<P>
   The system would reduce from years to months the time it takes
to convert a concept into a product, said Alan Steinberg, one of
Intel's first employees when it moved to Chandler and the new
firm's chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   Steinberg said the new system could be compared to the way
personal computer manufacturers build their products, buying
components from many manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't see Dell doing a lot of development work,''
Steinberg said. ``They're an assembler.''
</P>
<P>
   Intel's clout attracted $15 million in out-of-state venture
capital from 3i Technology Partners, a $300 million fund based in
Palo Alto, Calif., and Carlyle Venture Partners, a $210 million
fund and part of Washington, D.C.-based Carlyle Group.
</P>
<P>
   Tempe-based eStreetCapital.com will invest up to $500,000 in the
spinoff.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Hald, a MicroAge co-founder and co-chairman of the
governor's task force on the new economy, said he expected the
out-of-town money to lead to investment in other Arizona companies.
</P>
<P>
   To make the whole thing work, Steinberg must convince other
major electronics companies to become strategic partners that would
assemble a sort of library of proven technologies.
</P>
<P>
   Steinberg said Intel decided to spin off the firm to venture
capitalists to make it easier to attract other major players.
</P>
<P>
   The company launches with 30 former Intel employees. It will
move to Tempe's Mill Avenue CenterPoint development in September.
</P>
<P>
   Steinberg plans to have 100 employees by year's end.
</P>
<P>
   A hot technology idea spilling out of a big-name company is a
common story in the Silicon Valley, but it's a first for Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the whole point of the New Economy,'' said Ed Denison,
president of the Arizona Software and Internet Association. ``This
is how most regions do it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-00 0029EDT &QL; 
