<HEADER>
A5134 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-SADLER-BOS     05-15 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-SADLER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SADLER QUICKLY BECOMING A FACTOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ When the weekend began, Donnie Sadler was wearing
Red Sox, that would be Pawtucket-issue red socks, and he was
playing out his baseball dream in Toledo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going to the minors is all part of it, I guess,'' said Sadler,
who lost out on a roster spot in Boston when the Sox fled Florida
last month. ``When I got sent down, it was definitely frustrating,
but that's all just part of what you have to learn to overcome.
Yeah, I got sent down, but it wasn't like it was career-ending, or
they were saying, `You've had your shot and you're not coming
back.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Sadler's days in the minors looked forgotten for good Sunday in
Boston's 10-1 thumping of the Orioles. Batting ninth, he knocked in
three runs with a pair of doubles. He also finished off the
defensive gem of the day as the relay man in the fourth-inning
cutting down of Harold Baines at the plate, preventing what would
have been the tying run for the struggling Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   Sadler can run. In fact, he may have the fastest set of legs in
the American League. He also can throw the leather, be it at
shortstop, where he was Sunday, or filling a hole in the outfield.
And Saturday's homer, coupled with his two-hit, three-RBI
performance Sunday, showed that he has the stick to stay
comfortably north of Rhode Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our big guns are out,'' said Boston center fielder Darren
Lewis, referring to injuries to Nomar Garciaparra (hamstring) and
Carl Everett (quadriceps). ``But that doesn't matter. We've got
guys that can play. Guys like Scott Hatteberg, Jeff Frye, and
Donnie Sadler _ they're a big part of our success, and they don't
get the credit they should.''
</P>
<P>
   Sadler's contribution wasn't lost on Sox starter _ and winner _
Brian Rose (3-2). If not for Sadler's laser peg to the plate to cut
down Baines, Rose would have been working with a 1-1 tie and a
runner (Jeff Conine) in scoring position. Instead, the inning was
finished after the O'Leary-to-Sadler-to-Jason Varitek relay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to say thanks, first, to the defense,'' said Rose.
``Sadler played some tremendous defense, and he got that clutch
hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Sadler's other fine finish came in the eighth, admittedly with
little pressure with the Sox in command, 10-1. Ranging to his left,
he cut down a hot Albert Belle shot, recovered the loose ball, and
fired across to erase Belle by a half-step.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hit that pretty hard,'' said Sadler. ``That gave me the
time to make the play, and (Mike Stanley) made a nice play picking
up my one-hopper.''
</P>
<P>
   The fourth-inning relay to cut down Baines had Sadler meandering
to shallow left-center as O'Leary fielded Conine's ball off the
wall. It took a nice play to pick up O'Leary's throw, turn toward
the plate, and fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Jose) Offerman is the trailer there, and I've got to go on
what he's telling me, whether the play's at third or home,'' said
Sadler. ``And he was yelling, `Four . . . four . . . four.' So I
turned and threw as hard as I could, and it happened to be on the
money.''
</P>
<P>
   It's depth that wins pennants, more than power hitting, more
than speed, often more than pitching. Sadler looked like a perfect
``depth'' guy as spring training progressed, but the Sox were
hooked on the idea of keeping Gary Gaetti (since retired) and
relying more on Frye and Andy Sheets to be the depth guys.
</P>
<P>
   But all that began to change when Garciaparra hurt his leg
running out a grounder in the first inning Thursday night. By the
bottom of the inning, the All-Star shortstop was headed to the
15-day disabled list, and by the end of the night the call was
being made to Toledo for Sadler.
</P>
<P>
   Sadler arrived here on a broken relay of sorts. His itinerary,
Toledo to Pittsburgh to Baltimore, left him here without his
luggage. He had to scurry around the clubhouse for a glove
(Garciaparra's) and cleats (Frye's) to get back in the bigs. By the
third inning Sunday, his luggage arrived.
</P>
<P>
   By late Sunday, he was doing everything but singing the anthem,
selling hot dogs, and heating up the popcorn machine.
</P>
<P>
   Now he's in that precarious position of wanting to keep it all
going, but knowing that Garciaparra's return is inevitable and
Everett's injury is not long term. When the big guns come back, the
little guys, the depth destroyers, have to wait their turns.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, that really doesn't matter to me,'' he said. ``It's
all part of knowing your role. Right now, Nomar's got to take a
break, and I've got to go out there and show I can be consistent _
be consistent and wait your turn, and hope it all works out all
right.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-00 0033EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
