<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SHAUGHNESSY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NY LOVES CHARLIE'S HUSTLE 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It's fitting that in an NBA playoff series that keeps
stats on third-down efficiency and red zone scoring, the player who
wins the game is a former Heisman Trophy winner.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks have Seven Blocks of Granite. The Heat have Monsters
of the Key Biscayne Causeway. This is smashmouth basketball and the
team that blocks and tackles best is probably going to win.
</P>
<P>
   It's a perfect setting for Charlie Ward. The guy who torched
Nebraska in the 1994 Orange Bowl to win Bobby Bowden's first
national championship at Florida State scored the Knicks' final 9
points in a 91-83 victory over Miami Sunday. This Eastern
Conference semifinal is tied, 2-2, and commissioner David Stern
gets more drudgery in the only remaining competitive series of the
final four.
</P>
<P>
   In 32 Mother's Day minutes at Madison Square Garden, the
6-foot-2-inch Ward finished with 20 points on 8-for-13 shooting (3
of 6 from international waters) and added 7 rebounds, 4 assists,
and 3 steals.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a consummate pro,'' said Heat coach Pat Riley. ``The play
that said it all about him came at the end of the game when he ran
down a loose ball, pirouetted as he was diving out of bounds, then
threw a down-and-out pass (to Latrell Sprewell).''
</P>
<P>
   In those final minutes, when the game was on the line, Ward was
everywhere, burying jumpers, saving loose balls, and hitting a John
Havlicekian bank shot as he floated down the lane, off-balance,
with 1:51 left.
</P>
<P>
   The six-year veteran (Ward and Patrick Ewing are the only active
Knicks who played for Riley) is not given to great quotations or
animation. New York columnists dread Ward interviews. The sessions
are bore-fests laced with abject Dukespeak and praises for the
Almighty. Sunday, on the day he enjoyed his career playoff high,
Ward had a little fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I should have my own team,'' he said with a smile.
``For the first time, I felt like Allan Houston and Latrell. But
I've been in that position before, in football, where you're the
man and everyone is looking to you to make the plays and you make
the plays. (Today), I felt like that again.''
</P>
<P>
   It was like that. Miami was within 5 points, close to taking a
virtually insurmountable 3-1 series lead, when Ward took over.
First, he rebounded an Alonzo Mourning free throw miss. Then he
made the diving save and the down-and-out pass. Then he scored on
the funky drive to push the lead to 7. After a Mourning dunk, Ward
canned a 12-footer, and finally a stake-driving 3-pointer with 36
seconds left to make it 91-81. Ballgame. It was Ward's best finish
since he beat the Cornhuskers in Miami in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charlie always plays like that,'' said Knicks coach Jeff Van
Gundy. ``You can count on him to hustle on a nightly basis.
Whatever you emphasize to the team, Charlie tries to do. He
rebounds and hustles. He tries to do exactly what we need and we
need more people to follow his lead.''
</P>
<P>
   It's been a rough NBA ride for Ward. A native of Georgia, he was
a good enough athlete to win the Heisman Trophy and get drafted in
baseball (Brewers in 1993 and Yankees in '94) and basketball (a
Knicks first-round pick in '94). Like Doug Flutie, he was
considered too small and tricky for the NFL. San Francisco genius
Bill Walsh was known to say that Ward had the instincts and winning
ways of Joe Montana. But Ward served notice that he would play
basketball unless he was drafted in the NFL's first round _ he went
unselected in the '94 football meat market.
</P>
<P>
   Knicks fans and media have portrayed him as a hustling guy who
might be playing the wrong sport. Every high school basketball team
has one or two football studs moonlighting on hardwood and Ward's
never been embraced like Earl Monroe, or even Micheal Ray
Richardson. He's not flashy and he's not a thug, which makes him an
aberration in his own locker room. He's the slow and steady fire.
That's why it was so weird to have Woody Allen, Soon-Yi, David
Duchovny, and Tea Leone standing and chanting his name at the end
of a playoff game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy for him,'' said Sprewell. ``Especially when you're
here, at home. If it wasn't for Charlie, this would have been
tough.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He was tremendous for us,'' added teammate Kurt Thomas. ``He
did everything he was asked to do _ diving on the floor, getting
after balls, blocking shots, everything.''
</P>
<P>
   America cares little about the Heat and Knicks _ 24 guys who
could not have been the men who shot Liberty Valance _ but Gotham
is agog. Only Rudy Giuliani's love life is bigger these days. Even
though the games are ugly, folks can't wait for the next Garden
Party Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Game 5 is Wednesday in Miami _ where Charlie Ward did his best
work on the gridiron all those years ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-00 0034EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
