r s BC-BKN-LAKERSIDE-LADN     05-15 0576
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERSIDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSTEAD OF FADING, SUNS LOOK LIKE SUNS AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ If the motivation is either death or a mini-vacation,
seems you'd best opt for lights out as the greater inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   The Phoenix Suns, left for dead by most, looked very much alive
Sunday afternoon in Game 4 of their playoff series against the Los
Angeles Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns played like the team that won 53 games in the regular
season. Jason Kidd like a star with a healthy ankle. Cliff Robinson
like the guy seen in the regular season. Rodney Rogers like the one
who just won the NBA's Sixth Man award.
</P>
<P>
   Disobedient like, the Suns were told to play dead and instead
took a bite out of the Lakers' postseason plans, jumping out to a
commanding lead and then never letting up in a 117-98 victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers could have swept the series with a victory Sunday and
had nearly a week off before the next round. Instead, they came out
flat and never rose.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thing was, we knew they were very overconfident,''
Suns guard Penny Hardaway said. ``We knew that they weren't going
to come out and play hard from the beginning. They wanted to just
coast like they have in the last two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we got going, they couldn't turn it back on. It was
fortunate for us that they came out with such a lackadaisical
attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   The Suns led by 14 at the end of the first quarter and by 23 at
the half.
</P>
<P>
   If the Lakers smelled blood, it was their own. They trailed by
29 points at one point and never got closer than 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they came out and were going to see how we were going
to attack,'' Kidd said. ``We felt like if we were just going to
throw in the towel, they were going to jump on us. I think they
found out early that we were coming to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Hardaway said a key was to jump on the Lakers early.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides Game 1, they really haven't come out and attacked us
in either game,'' he said. ``They've been kind of coasting, turning
it on, turning it off. They've been able to put runs together to
come back on us at will. If we get a lead, we have to protect it
and make them fight a little harder.''
</P>
<P>
   The Suns got a superb overall game from Kidd, who turned a
triple-double with 22 points, 10 rebounds and a career playoff-high
16 assists.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just a stat line,'' Kidd said. ``To me, the important
thing is we got the win. I felt good, the ball was going in today,
and I was being more aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Kidd, shooting just .292 percent in the first three games, was 8
of 13 from the field and hit 4 of 6 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson has been under attack for disappearing in the
postseason - his career scoring average is six points less in the
playoffs (10.3) than the regular season. And he was plagued Sunday
with a sprained ankle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of those things where everything started to
click,'' Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers shot .486 from the field in the regular season and .439
from the 3-point line. In the first three games against the Lakers,
he shot .306 percent and missed on all 12 of his 3-point attempts.
Sunday he scored 17 points (6 of 11, and two 3-pointers).
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time our offense is rolling like this, we're tough to
beat,'' Hardaway said. ``If we can roll like this in L.A., we'll be
getting another one.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think,'' said Kidd, ``we're back in this series.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
