<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS NEED A BIT MORE WORK ON KNOCKOUT PUNCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Obviously the Los Angeles Lakers heard all the people
prematurely dissecting their Western Conference finals matchup with
Portland and got disoriented. They came out Sunday against the Suns
and played like that was Rasheed Wallace in Cliff Robinson's body
and Brian Grant in Corie Blount's and Scottie Pippen in Rodney
Rogers'.
</P>
<P>
   All those Lakers flaws the Trail Blazers were going to expose in
the next round, the Suns exploited in a 117-98 victory at America
West Arena that forced a Game 5 in the best-of-seven Western
Conference semifinal series. It will take place Tuesday at the
Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers' lack of a capable backup center loomed large when
Shaquille O'Neal picked up three fouls in the first half and was
saddled with five by the eighth minute of the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was their patchwork bench, which was hanging by a
thread by halftime. Buoyed by Blount and Rogers, the Suns' reserves
outscored their Lakers counterparts 17-8 in the opening 24 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   And power forward never looked more like an oxymoron than when
describing the Lakers' A.C. Green, who was powerless to stop
Robinson. Just a few minutes into the game it was obvious the
sprained ankle that cast some doubt as to whether or not he would
be able to play Sunday would bother Robinson more than Green would.
</P>
<P>
   The 11th-year veteran blew through the Lakers' defense like a
tornado. The devastation he wrought was absolute: 23 points in his
first 21 minutes and 32 points and nine rebounds for the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   It was so ugly, coach Phil Jackson minced few words when he
briefly joined the players in the locker room at halftime. ``He
basically told us that we needed to get our butts in gear,'' said
guard Glen Rice, who had a hard time getting out of first, missing
10 of 14 shots.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you didn't need six NBA championship rings to come up
with Jackson's pearl of wisdom. Anybody could see the Lakers were
badly outhustled from the start.
</P>
<P>
   But of course. The Lakers always seem to play this way in Game 4
of a possible sweep.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Kidd slipped the Suns into fifth gear as though he were at
the controls of a Ferrari, dishing out eight of his 16 assists in
the first quarter as the Suns' transition game whirred. In the
first half alone, they had 12 fast-break points to the Lakers'
four.
</P>
<P>
   All you really need to know about the Lakers' get-up-and-go is
this: Kidd, sore left ankle and all, finished as the game's high
rebounder with 10. He had eight defensive boards, more than any
Laker had altogether save for Robert Horry and O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   Led by Robinson and Kidd, the Suns hung 71 points on the
scoreboard in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers wish that was a typo.
</P>
<P>
   New York and Miami basketball fans who caught a glimpse of the
71-48 halftime score on their way out the door to dinner probably
assumed it was a final.
</P>
<P>
   Truth to tell, the Lakers wouldn't have minded if a mercy rule
had spared them from having to play the second half. By the time
the fourth quarter rolled around, the Lakers were so
discombobulated Rick Fox was acting like Portland's tempestuous
Wallace.
</P>
<P>
   Fox was ejected with 3:27 remaining and the Lakers trailing by
20 when he collected his second technical foul for venting his
frustrations about having Robinson's sneaker prints all over his
body.
</P>
<P>
   Kobe Bryant chose another way - one no less curious - to try to
save a little face. At one point in the fourth quarter he sidled up
to Blount, a former Lakers teammate, and said, ``We need the
practice. I'm glad you all did this to us. See you in L.A.''
</P>
<P>
   That Kobe, he's such a kidder. Right?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think so,'' said Blount, who got bent all over again
when he recounted the conversation. ``I think he was very
serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant was right about one thing; the Lakers need a lot of
practice on their knockout punch. They showed in Game 3 in
Sacramento in the first round of the playoffs and again here on
Sunday that it doesn't carry much sting.
</P>
<P>
   Green carried the analogy one step further. ``We haven't proved
that we have a knockout punch yet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Considering the Lakers had the Suns down for the count, the fact
they couldn't put them away really hurt. The Lakers, that is.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a shame,'' Rice said.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, well. One game does not a series change. The Suns don't have
the Lakers on the ropes. Yet.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers can put the ``gel'' back in Los Angeles by coming
together Tuesday and playing 48 minutes of inspired defense. You
know, like they did way back in Game 1 of the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``The feeling we have is that we've got to come out Tuesday and
return the favor,'' Rice said. ``If we're going to be a contender
for a championship we can't have lapses like we did (Sunday).''
</P>
<P>
   It was the most accurate Rice had been all afternoon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
