<HEADLINE>
NORTHRIDGE TAKES NCAA SOFTBALL PLAYOFF BERTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ They earned their reprieve. Now to see what
they'll do with it.
</P>
<P>
   The Cal State Northridge softball team learned Sunday night it
qualified for the NCAA Tournament for the ninth consecutive season.
The Matadors will face Arkansas in a double-elimination regional in
Norman, Okla., on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   What happens now is up to the players. For the past three
seasons, CSUN has been undone by infighting and bickering.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998 and '99, the bad blood surfaced in the postseason and
the team quickly exited from the regionals. This time, it happened
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   A month ago, Northridge was sailing along, leading the Big West
Conference at 13-1. It dropped one game to Long Beach State, then
lost three more at Fullerton. Goodbye conference title.
</P>
<P>
   Outside influences (mostly parents and fans) started whispering
to some players that coach Janet Sherman a) wasn't coaching well;
b) wasn't using them correctly; c) both. Some players listened,
others didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, there was dissension. It got worse as the losses
mounted. Players started arguing about on-the-field play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like dominoes,'' pitcher Sarah Farnworth said. ``All this
fighting is petty. We know we're good enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, after the Matadors dropped two of three against UC Santa
Barbara, it was hello postseason uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   Sherman hoped a week off, followed by a regular-season-closing
weekend at Utah State would help.
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors split Friday, then won Saturday to finish 26-24-1
the fewest number of victories at CSUN since a 17-14 record in
1979.
</P>
<P>
   Yet strength of schedule helped. Northridge won 18 games over
ranked teams (although, they lost to Arkansas 1-0 in a tournament)
and lost only once to an unranked nonconference opponent
(Tennessee).
</P>
<P>
   So now, the Matadors find themselves in a familiar place:
bickering into the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   If they remain united, they could win the region. If not, it
could be a quick two and out.
</P>
<P>
   ``After all the B.S.,'' outfielder Jessica Creith said, ``the
only way we can go is up.''
</P>
<P>
   What losses mean: In Marquis Brignac, the football team loses
depth at running back. The loss of Hassan Abdul-Malik, however, is
tantamount to losing Ronnie Lott.
</P>
<P>
   At least, that's what Northridge football coach Jeff Kearin
says.
</P>
<P>
   Kearin wanted to build the defense around Abdul-Malik, the
5-foot-10, 185-pound sophomore who redshirted last season. Kearin
also wanted to put him on the cover of this season's media guide
and tout him as a preseason All-American.
</P>
<P>
   But none of that will happen because Abdul-Malik and Brignac, a
former Taft High of Woodland Hills standout, are heading to Valley
College.
</P>
<P>
   Brignac already has withdrawn from school. Abdul-Malik is
finishing the semester.
</P>
<P>
   Abdul-Malik, who sat out last season with a hamstring injury,
said he's leaving because he doesn't believe the administration
supports football.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not experiencing that college football atmosphere at
Northridge,'' he said. ``I see the interest in students is going
down the drain. Nobody talks about football. I know people that
don't think we have football. It's depressing.''
</P>
<P>
   Abdul-Malik said he considered Pasadena City and Mt. San Antonio
colleges but chose Valley because former Northridge coach Ron
Ponciano is an assistant there.
</P>
<P>
   Kearin calls the departure ``a big loss to the program. I
thought we had addressed his concerns.''
</P>
</TEXT>
