<HEADLINE>
HULL, LEGISLATORS NO CLOSER TO FIX OF SCHOOL FUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY CHRIS MOESER  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
(PHOENIX) - On one side stand legislative leaders looking for ways
to raise $300 million more a year for education without Gov. Jane
Hull's sales tax increase.
</P>
<P>
   On the other is Hull herself, vowing to battle on for her 0.6 of
a cent tax increase for teacher pay, smaller class sizes,
universities and community colleges.
</P>
<P>
   After a week of meetings, neither side is talking of compromise.
But each suggests that the other is caving.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's garbage,'' Hull aide Jaime Molera said about rumors
spread by opponents that Hull had abandoned her plan. ``The
leadership had not engaged the issue, so the governor challenged
them to come up with something.''
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Jeff Groscost, R-Mesa, said: ``The governor found
in talking to my members that the tax increase was going over like
a lead balloon.''
</P>
<P>
   Groscost and Senate President Brenda Burns remain steadfastly
opposed to a tax increase. Both are pursuing alternatives to Hull's
plan that could take weeks or months to work out, suggesting that a
special session on the issue could come this summer rather than
this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get the feeling it could almost unravel before we get
started,'' said Rep. Sue Gerard, R-north-central Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Hull aides remain convinced that if they called a session in two
weeks, a plan close to the governor's would pass. At the end of the
regular session, for example, 18 senators said they supported the
idea.
</P>
<P>
   But GOP leaders say otherwise. And they have the power to make
any special session a rough one.
</P>
<P>
   Groscost is looking at three areas: across-the-board budget cuts
in non-education areas; closing tax loopholes or adding taxes for
services not currently taxed; and using some of the state's $3.1
billion tobacco settlement. Other ideas also have been raised.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are ways to fund this at the level the governor
wants to without a tax increase,'' Groscost said.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's tax produces $450 million a year. Groscost is
shooting for about $300 million, or the amount in Hull's plan that
would go directly to the classroom. He favors eliminating the extra
money for colleges and other programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Universities right now are not in a crisis,'' Groscost said.
</P>
<P>
   He suggested $100 million to $120 million could be found in
budget cuts. He refused to offer examples, adding that staffers are
preparing a menu of potential cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Longtime lawmakers predicted a long, nasty fight over cuts.
</P>
<P>
   The tax ``loopholes'' Groscost and others are examining include
sales tax exemptions on lottery tickets, legal and accounting fees,
newspaper advertising, and service industry areas that aren't
taxed.
</P>
<P>
   Groscost sees up to $500 million in such exemptions. From that
list, he predicted lawmakers could come up with an additional $100
million to $120 million.
</P>
<P>
   Critics, including Burns and Gerard, argue that closing such
exemptions would be the equivalent of raising taxes.
</P>
<P>
   And Burns, R-Glendale, says such structural changes could take
months to work out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe we can do something significant for education
without increasing taxes or dramatically changing the tax base,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   She emphasized that any money for education must be spent in the
classrooms and not on bureaucracy. Burns and Groscost point out
that education funding has increased dramatically in the past three
years but that few of those dollars have reached teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Burns is also interested in another plan that would send
education money directly to schools, bypassing school boards and
district offices. But that idea also would take months to work out.
</P>
<P>
   Later this week, Hull will continue her tour of the state to
pitch the sales tax. She has hinted that if lawmakers fail to act,
she would take to the campaign trail, backing lawmakers and
candidates who support her.
</P>
<P>
   Molera didn't downplay the possibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an issue even at the presidential level,'' he said.
``We still hold out hope they'll do something. The governor is
going to continue to push this as long as it takes.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach the reporter at Chris.Moeser(at)Arizona Republic.com or (602)
444-8069. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
