<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATHLETICS SINK MARINERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN HICKEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ If, as many in both clubhouses believe, the
two best teams in the American League West met this weekend in
Oakland, the A's are a leg up on the Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   The A's are also one-half game up on the Mariners in the West
after Oakland's 7-2 victory over Seattle Sunday, the A's taking
three of four from the Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   It would be accurate to say that the A's walked all over the
Mariners. It would be equally accurate to say that the Mariners
walked all over themselves. Not just Sunday, when Mariner pitchers
walked 10 batters, but on the road trip, with Seattle issuing 44
walks in seven games (2-5).
</P>
<P>
   That's an average of almost seven walks per game, and you don't
have to be Noah Webster to know that spells trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really believe in this pitching staff,'' distraught pitching
coach Bryan Price said. ``That's why this is so disappointing. I'm
an understanding guy, but I'm getting to the point where I don't
understand the plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The plan is OK, but our execution of the plan is what I don't
understand.''
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, Price's pitchers are all but conceding the first
pitch of each at-bat. Sixty percent of the pitches Seattle has
thrown this year have been for strikes, but only 53 of the first
pitches have been strikes. That's led to the Mariners pitching from
behind in the count. And that goes directly to the strength of
opposing offenses.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle began the road trip ranked second in the AL for fewest
walks. They've since fallen to seventh, a tumultuous tumble this
deep into a season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're overloading the offense,'' manager Lou Piniella said.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the Mariners are scoring enough runs to win, even
if they only picked up two Sunday. Piniella figures the M's scored
enough to win five of the seven games on the trip. To lose five of
the seven rankled both Piniella and Price.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pitchers are asking too much of the hitters when they're
giving up eight runs a game,'' Price said. ``To tell the offense
they've got to score 10 runs for us to win a game on the road
doesn't work.
</P>
<P>
   ``The basics of pitching haven't changed. You need to get ahead,
you need to make the hitter defensive and you need to let the
hitters get themselves out. This is nothing new. But we're not
sticking to the plan.''
</P>
<P>
   The seven-game road trip has been little more than a succession
of walks that led to runs. And, eventually, defeat. Of the 44
opponents who drew walks on the trip, 13 scored. Three more came
with the bases loaded, driving in runs.
</P>
<P>
   It was more of the same Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the six walks allowed by starter Paul Abbott resulted
in runs. A two-out, two-run homer by Miguel Tejada in the second
and a two-out, three-run homer by Jason Giambi in the fourth were
both triggered by walks. If Matt Stairs doesn't walk in the second
and Terrence Long doesn't walk in the fourth, Tejada and Giambi
don't get to hammer their points home.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to give up runs, you want to a see a line
like, `one run, three hits,' '' Price said. ``Instead, what I'm
seeing is `two runs, one hit.' I don't know what the problem is,
but I know that we'll solve it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever it takes to get this turned around, we'll do it.''
</P>
<P>
   So Seattle heads home for a series in Safeco against Minnesota
while Oakland basks in the glow of taking three of four from the
team the A's privately suggest _ but won't publicly admit _ is the
team they have to beat if they want to win the West.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all going to be about pitching,'' A's manager Art Howe
said. ``The team that wins this division is going to get better
pitching than the others.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on that, the A's have to like their chances. Sunday's
starter Gil Heredia has a 2.52 ERA after allowing two runs in 52/3
innings against the Mariners. That's the third-best ERA in the
league behind Pedro Martinez and Rick Helling.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Abbott's ERA is soaring toward the stratosphere since
he joined the rotation. Starting twice on this road trip, Abbott
has allowed 10 runs in 92/3 innings and his six-walk, seven-run,
four-inning effort Sunday was as painful for him to pitch as it was
for his teammates to watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't be effective when you can only throw one pitch for a
strike,'' Abbott said. ``I could throw the fastball for strikes,
but nothing else. I was brutal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I was trying to do too much, but I struggled
with the changeup all day. What I did, basically, was make it easy
for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that the A's need much help. Giambi had nine RBIs in the
four-game series and the A's, twice four games under .500 (4-8 and
9-13), have won 11 of their past 16 to move ahead of the Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like where we sit,'' said Giambi, the major league leader in
homers (16) and RBIs (46). ``It's nice to be here. Everyone
predicted us to live up to this, and it's nice to be doing well
after we started out so poorly.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners are on the other side of that coin. Seattle started
out quickly, twice getting to five games over .500, but since being
13-8, the M's have dropped nine of their past 14 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pitching,'' Piniella said, ``has to get better.''
</P>
<P>
   And in a hurry.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter John Hickey can be reached at 206-448-8004
</P>
<P>
   or johnhickey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
