 PM-BUDGET-NYT 
 (sw) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For MONDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Monday, May 15.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-CRIME (Kwamashu, South Africa) _ In this impoverished
township of mud shacks and stunted dreams, the killers prowl, the
bullets sing and most people no longer hope for justice. And when a
national team of inspectors visited the local police station last
year, they quickly discovered why. More than 200 criminal cases
were assigned to detectives who were either dead or dismissed from
the force, the team's confidential report shows. By Rachel L.
Swarns.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Locator map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   PHILIPPINES-LOVEBUG (Manila, Philippines) _ If what local
investigators suspect is true, the virus that brought some of the
world's most sophisticated computer networks to a halt this month
was hatched in a noisy inner-city neighborhood where residents live
under corrugated steel roofs and raise fighting cocks in their
front yards. By Wayne Arnold.
</P>
<P>
   YUGO-WARCRIMES (Djakovica, Yugoslavia) _ With winter over, teams
from the international war crimes tribunal in the Hague,
Netherlands, have resumed their digging in Kosovo, searching for
bodies and other clues that would back the indictment of the
Yugoslav president, Slobodan Milosevic, and four of his top allies
in Serbia on charges of genocide committed before and during NATO's
bombing of Yugoslavia last spring. So far, in the 195 sites
examined last year, the number of bodies found has been less than
initially reported to the tribunal _ in part because of apparent
Serbian tampering with the graves. But the investigators have 300
sites to examine this year, and in just three weeks this spring
have exhumed 160 bodies. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   PERU-POLITICS (Lima, Peru) _ Two weeks before the final round of
Peru's presidential election, international observers say they
again have serious concerns that President Alberto Fujimori may be
preparing to steal enough votes to ensure he wins a third term. By
Clifford Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-PRESIDENT (Istanbul, Turkey) _ The inauguration of a
reform-minded judge as Turkey's 10th president on Tuesday will cap
a year of extraordinary change here. The choice of Sezer seems to
be a turning point, since it is the latest in a series of events
that, taken together, suggest that Turkey may be ready to embrace
political reform. By Stephen Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GENE-RESEARCH (Undated) _ Some patients have become wary about
providing their tissue for genetic research. In fact, a few have
demanded money up front before providing tissue. Others are writing
contracts spelling out what they are entitled to if they help
scientists find genes. Some experts on patent law say that it would
be unfortunate if patients start demanding financial rewards for
participating in genetic research. A special report. By Gina
Kolata.
</P>
<P>
   L.A.-FED-CONTROL (Los Angeles) _ The Justice Department's
announcement last week that it was prepared to file a civil rights
lawsuit against the Police Department was embarrassing news for
this city. But it was only the latest in a series of federal
actions and oversight efforts that in some important ways have made
greater Los Angeles a virtual ward of Washington. By Todd S.
Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GORE (Nashville, Tenn.) _ Two months after Al Gore triumphantly
claimed enough delegates for the Democratic presidential
nomination, his campaign is still struggling to reorient itself
toward the general election. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   NY-GIULIANI (New York) _ On the verge of reaching a final
decision about the future of his campaign for the U.S. Senate,
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani found himself confronting an array of
conflicting advice from a divided group of advisers, some of whom
have financial, political and career interests riding on whether
Giuliani pursues his campaign against Hillary Rodham Clinton. By
Adam Nagourney.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-LOBBYISTS _ In the struggle over Medicare coverage of
prescription drugs, beneficiaries have suddenly found themselves
competing against hospitals, nursing homes and other health care
providers that want access to the same pot of federal money. By
Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   GULF-WAR-MCCAFFREY _ One of the top U.S. commanders in the
Persian Gulf War, Gen. Barry McCaffrey, came under investigation
after a member of his unit complained that his troops had pummeled
retreating Iraqi forces in an unprovoked attack two days after a
cease-fire went into effect. Military investigators, who fielded
the anonymous complaint and completed a secret report in 1991,
exonerated McCaffrey. But questions about the attack were revived
this week by a magazine report that quotes senior Army officers,
including an officer who fought alongside McCaffrey, as saying the
attack was unjustified. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   FCC-CHAIRMAN-PROFILE _ Profile of William Kennard, chairman of
the FCC. By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ECON-LIMITS (Washington) _ The Fed's great experiment in letting
the economy run in order to test the limits of how much growth can
be achieved without inflation appears to be nearing an end. Judging
that rapid advances in technology were making businesses and
workers more productive in ways that tempered upward pressure on
prices, the Fed instead has given the economy more or less free
rein to find its own limits. It may now have found them. By Richard
W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   AIG-INSURE (Undated) _ When the American International Group,
one of the world's biggest insurance companies, holds its annual
meeting in New York on Wednesday, it will be confronted by several
shareholder proposals challenging the dominance of Maurice R.
Greenberg, its chief executive. By Joseph B. Treaster.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   ARNAULT-PROFILE (Paris) _ A look at the Internet ambitions of
Bernard Arnault, the financier who is chairman of the French
prestige brands conglomerate, LVMH Moet Hennessy Louis Vuitton SA.
To holdings that include Louis Vuitton, Christian Dior, Tag Heuer
and Dom Perignon, Arnault has added stakes in online companies like
eBay, Datek and LibertySurf, and has started an Internet incubator
called Europ(at)Web. By Andrew Ross Sorkin.
</P>
