BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    NEW &AMP; NOTABLE (a) 
 &HT;    (Duplication warning: MOVING IN ``E'' AND ``L'' categories) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By ANNE STEPHENSON(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 Special for The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are Anne Stephenson's capsule reviews of new books:
</P>
<P>
   ``HALF A HEART''
</P>
<P>
   By ROSSELLEN BROWN
</P>
<P>
   (FSG, $24)
</P>
<P>
   Miriam Vener is a doctor's wife whose perfect life in suburban
Houston includes an elegant house, walk-in closets, good clothes,
terrific husband and kids. She knows, however, that if her old
friends (who are no longer her friends) came to visit, they ``would
have trouble getting past the gatehouse Gestapo unless they looked
like they had arrived to do some heavy cleaning.'' They knew Miriam
during the 1960s, when, as a civil rights activist in Mississippi,
she had an affair, and a child, with a Black professor named Eljay
Reese. Their daughter, Ronnee, was raised by her father (she was a
baby when Miriam last saw her) and is now 17. When Miriam sends her
a letter, it is a surprise that she answers, but not the last
surprise Ronnee will bring as she re-enters her mother's life.
Brown (''Tender Mercies,'' ``Before and After'') is a master at
rendering the tentative dynamics between mother and daughter, two
of the best women characters to come along in years. It's good
summer reading. Enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   ``ANGUS''
</P>
<P>
   By Charles Siebert
</P>
<P>
   (Crown, $18.95)
</P>
<P>
   Oh, but the dog lovers will fall for this one. Look at that
face. Look at that name. Angus was a Jack Russell terrier puppy,
and for just shy of 11months he lived with Siebert and his wife,
Bex. All but the epilogue of this ``memoir'' is narrated by Angus
himself, in a voice that is uncanny - not cute, not altogether
lovable, but terribly real and affecting. The story begins as Angus
lies dying after he is attacked by coyotes near a cabin where his
owners have sought refuge from city life. Siebert and Bex are
looking for him. Angus hears them calling, and as he waits for them
to find him, he contemplates the intense and sometimes rocky
association he has had with these people. What, exactly, is the
relationship between dogs and human beings? What did his people
want from him, and did he meet their needs? Angus is not sure, but
he looks at the questions with an intelligent and often alien
sensibility that makes for a moving (but never hokey) book. Angus
did well to inspire it in such a short lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   ``CRADLE AND ALL''
</P>
<P>
   By JAMES PATTERSON (Little, Brown, $25.95)
</P>
<P>
   In this rewrite of his long-out-of-print 1980 novel
``Virgin(beginitalic),'' (enditalic)Patterson has the world in a
religious frenzy over the mysterious pregnancies of two teenage
virgins, one in an Irish village, the other in Boston. One will
give birth to the child of God and one to the child of the devil,
but only Patterson knows who is chosen and who is cursed. His
heroine is Anne Fitzgerald, a strikingly attractive former nun (and
current virgin) who now makes her living as a private investigator
and is brought in by authorities to look into the immaculate
conceptions. Anne still loves the priest who propositioned her when
she was in the convent, and, don't you know, he shows up in the
middle of the virgin controversy to throw Anne into a romantic
tizzy. When they walk on the beach together, she knows they are a
handsome couple ``because several people passing us gave us a
sideways look.'' It's like that in this novel - when the action
isn't frenzied, it's dopey. A film version can't be far behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``APRONS: ICONS OF THE AMERICAN HOME''
</P>
<P>
   By Joyce Cheney
</P>
<P>
   (Running, $24.95)
</P>
<P>
   There are women today who have never worn aprons, and we say
bully for them. Now, Cheney tells us that aprons are not just
icons. They are ``textiles,'' and they are collectible. Cheney
herself has 400. In 1994, she decided to ``express my own
understanding of aprons'' by creating a display on a clothesline in
New Mexico. People who saw them were smitten. They wanted to touch
them, to try them on. Children asked ``What are they?'' And so
Cheney organized an exhibit of aprons and wrote this book, which is
full of the real thing - aprons made of flour sacks or neckties,
aprons trimmed with rickrack, smocked aprons, embroidered aprons,
aprons with matching oven mitts. Granted, as aprons go, these
represent perfection - there's not a splotch of tomato sauce in
sight. Their effect is like that of those old pickup trucks you
also see in books: All polished and posed, they seem to smile at
you from the page. That, we suspect, has to do with the power of
memory, and bully for that, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
