<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIRE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOS ALAMOS VICTIMS CLING TO FRIENDSHIP, PRAYER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY BY  JUDD SLIVKA  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
(GLORIETA, N.M.) - There wasn't much wearing of the Sunday best,
save for the pastor whose wife grabbed his suit in the hour she had
before the firefighters pulled them out of their home.
</P>
<P>
   There were shirtsleeves and wrinkles, dirt-spotted jeans and
soccer jerseys.
</P>
<P>
   Three boxes of tissues sat on a card table at the back of the
chapel. By the end of the service, only one and half were used.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the Cerro Grande wildfire burning around Los Alamos grew
to more than 40,000 acres and more than 1,000 firefighters fought
to keep it from further decimating the Santa Clara Pueblo
Reservation, people gathered to pray Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   As firefighters tried to take advantage of the last day of good
weather forecast for a week, more than 250 people gathered in
Pojoaque Pueblo for a Catholic Mass while another 300 gathered at a
conference center in Glorieta.
</P>
<P>
   They sang and prayed and thanked God for pulling them through
and that no one was harmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe in a God who pushes cars together. I don't
believe in a God who says `This house will burn and that house
won't,'' said Doug Partin, pastor at the Los Alamos Christian
Church. ``I believe in a God who's a source of strength for
everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Prayer and song sessions have been held every night since Los
Alamos was evacuated and some of its former tenants took up
residence in a Baptist conference center's lodgings. Mostly, they
give the residents something to do, something to think about other
than their homes and what they left behind.
</P>
<P>
   Julie Davis' home wasn't burned, wasn't even close to the fire.
But she came out to Glorieta, anyway, to see whether she could find
some friends who had lost their home. And she had come there to
thank God for sparing her house.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we can get back into our house, we plan to open it up to
people,'' she said. ``We have several rooms because the children
have all moved out. It's the right thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   There were tears inside the conference center, a few hugs and a
loud, belted rendition of What a Friend We Have in Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   Children were summoned to the front of the chapel to pick up
flowers to give to their mothers, and it seemed as if every woman
above the age of 16 had a carnation for Mother's Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lesson we should come away with here is about the
priorities in our lives,'' Partin said. ``The priorities in our
lives are not the creature comforts that we value so much. It's the
family and friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside, though, there was a different mood. Frustration is
building among area residents, especially those from White Rock who
were evacuated early Thursday when officials thought the city was
in danger of burning down.
</P>
<P>
   The fire has stayed about three miles from the city, and
authorities say they think they can contain that edge of the fire
even as it continues to sweep across the Santa Clara Reservation.
</P>
<P>
   Residents of White Rock _ and Los Alamos _ had been told it
would probably be another 10 days before they are allowed to move
into their homes again. But White Rock residents learned late in
the day that they could return to their homes today.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating that we can't get in there,'' Rod
Christiansen of White Rock said. ``I've got a bunch of chickens and
turkeys and I've got a cousin on the police force and I asked him
to sneak in every once in a while to give them water so I wouldn't
have to dig too deep a grave when I get back. I've got a 45-pound
turkey. Can you imagine how deep I'd have to dig to bury him?''
</P>
<P>
   At the National Guard headquarters in Santa Fe, Los Alamos
residents who lost homes were allowed to get on school buses and
ride around the scorched sections of the city.
</P>
<P>
   Louis Jalberg was not among them. Though he watched his quadplex
burn on television an hour after he evacuated it, he refused to get
on the bus.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got some photos, some papers out, but that's it,'' he said.
``A few things for the kids. All our antiques, all our mementos
burned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw it on flames on TV. What do I need to go back and see it
for?'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
