<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLEGE BASKETBALL NEARS PEAK OF SLIMY CHAOS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Pro basketball's answer to ``Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire'' was answered Sunday by 23 college underclassmen and
one high school kid, all of whom applied by the deadline for early
entry to the NBA draft.
</P>
<P>
   The timing was unfortunate, breaking as it did the hearts of 23
mothers on Mother's Day. Most were hoping for a college degree for
the son for whom they bought new clothes every two weeks during his
growth spurt.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, a 2000 Lexus will go a ways toward mending that
broken heart.
</P>
<P>
   While a handful of these youngsters will have purchasing power,
such as Texas' 7-foot junior center, Chris Mihm, most of them
appear to have flunked classes in statistical probability.
</P>
<P>
   Since only 58 players will be chosen from a group of more than
1,000 letterman seniors at the Division I level, plus the
underclassmen, plus players from smaller schools, as well as the
rapidly improving pool of international players, the odds that most
of these early entrants will get an NBA sniff are smaller than
Bobby Knight's reservoir of humility.
</P>
<P>
   Moms, don't sell those '76 Country Squire station wagons yet.
</P>
<P>
   But as was mentioned here recently, many players will find the
odds of turning pro better than the odds of turning in a
self-written term paper (see the University of Minnesota under Clem
Haskins).
</P>
<P>
   Parallel with that trend is the penchant for unhappy players to
switch schools. Transfers that were once occasional in college ball
are now nearly epidemic.
</P>
<P>
   The result is near-chaos for the big-time college game (see your
NCAA basketball tourney bracket).
</P>
<P>
   Few places have been as badly hurt by these trends as the
University of Washington. After losing two players early to the
pros (Patrick Femerling and Mark Sanford), the Huskies under coach
Bob Bender have been slugged by transfers. The latest was point
guard Senque Carey, the UW's best returning player, and the fifth
quality contributor to find another college instead of returning to
Bender.
</P>
<P>
   Reasons are numerous. One often overlooked is Bender's own
dalliances with a transfer.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies' reappearance in the tournament in 1998 and 1999
made Bender a hot commodity for coaching vacancies. But after
high-profile, heavily chronicled negotiations with Texas and then
Vanderbilt, Bender returned each time to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   He was rewarded handsomely for his loyalty. Yet there was a
price.
</P>
<P>
   While it's hardly Bender's fault he became popular, his
wandering eye was not only dismaying to the players he brought to
Seattle, rival recruiters love the potential lack of stability, and
pound it into a bruise on the Huskies.
</P>
<P>
   Since this is America, Bender is not only entitled to better
himself, the system encourages it. The athletes should be granted
the same rights, too.
</P>
<P>
   An NCAA scholarship is, after all, a contract renewable annually
and is not guaranteed for the four years of eligibility. That
one-way arrangement was abused heavily by Bender's predecessor,
Lynn Nance, whose spring run-offs of players became something of a
Husky tradition.
</P>
<P>
   To his credit, Bender has not run off any players, even when he
could have used a scholarship for a more productive player. But
after his springtime flirtations with other schools, it would seem
neither a surprise nor a shame that his players get happy feet,
too.
</P>
<P>
   At least a job-switching coach isn't forced to sit out a year,
as is the punishment for Division I player transfers. Then again,
the NCAA has never been about being a democracy as much as it has
been about being a plantation.
</P>
<P>
   If there is a need to sort through the swarminess, here's a
thumbnail guide to the state of college ball:
</P>
<P>
   -- When a youth-ball street agent tells a high school kid,
``Man, these shoes and sweats look fine on you,'' he usually means:
Nike owns me. Nike's about to own you. And you're going to a
Nike-contract college.
</P>
<P>
   -- When a player says, ``I always wanted to be a
Husky/Cougar/Duck/Rutabaga/Fighting Bacteria,'' he usually means:
Unless I'm not getting at least 20 minutes a game by my sophomore
year.
</P>
<P>
   -- When a transferring player says, ``I'd rather play closer to
home,'' he usually means: I haven't seen my hometown girlfriend in
three weeks, and she just gave me an X-rated phone call.
</P>
<P>
   -- When a coach who stays put says, ``I just couldn't leave
these kids here,'' he usually means: Man, I can't believe they
coughed up the ski condo AND the lakefront home.
</P>
<P>
   -- When a grumbling player says, ``I'm not sure what coach wants
from me,'' he usually means: One more call from that Fresno State
assistant, and I'm outta here.
</P>
<P>
   -- When a player who declares for the draft says, ``I'm doing
this for my family,'' he usually means: Maybe all these freeloaders
will finally leave me alone.
</P>
<P>
   -- When a player's mother calls a coach and says, ``You're not
treating my boy right,'' she usually means: You're costing me a
four-bedroom split level, and you don't even want to think about me
catching up to your sorry behind.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Art Thiel can be reached at 206-448-8135
</P>
<P>
   or artthiel &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
