<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 01:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5152 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-OLY-WOMEN-BASKETBALL-     05-15 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-WOMEN-BASKETBALL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NEIL HOHLFELD  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
The growth and popularity of the WNBA can be tied directly to the
gold medal won by the U.S. women's basketball team at the 1996
Olympic Games in Atlanta.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The gold-medal team provided an impetus for the first successful
women's professional league. Four years later, however, the WNBA
might be an obstacle for the Olympic team's defense of its gold
medal.
</P>
<P>
   The regular season in the WNBA concludes Aug. 9. The last date
the title game could be played is Aug. 27. The Olympic team plans
to gather in Colorado Springs, Colo., on Aug. 14 and leave for
Australia on Sept. 4.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. will play its first Olympic game Sept. 16 vs. South
Korea, the first of five preliminary-round games in an eight-day
span.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 11 players who have been selected for the 2000 U.S. team,
10 will play in the WNBA, with only veteran Teresa Edwards sitting
out. Another player will be added to the Olympic team, with Sheryl
Swoopes of the Comets the apparent front-runner.
</P>
<P>
   A hectic summer? Without question.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think it's going to be difficult,'' said 6-5 center Lisa
Leslie, the leading scorer on the 1996 Olympic team who now is with
the Los Angeles Sparks. ``It's something we've never dealt with
before. We're going to be asked to play our WNBA season and have an
eye on getting ready for the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have to really be aware of staying strong but not
getting fatigued. We're going to lift weights every other day, and
I'm sure at times we're not going to feel like doing that. But
that's part of what being in the Olympics this year is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Leslie and Olympic teammates Edwards and DeLisha Milton were in
Houston on Sunday to take part in the Olympic Media Summit. U.S.
coach Nell Fortner believes the players will accept the challenge
of trying to maintain strength during the WNBA season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing we've asked them to really focus on is to
maintain their weight program,'' Fortner said. ``An athlete can
decondition during a season if all they are doing is playing a
game, having a shootaround in the morning and playing another game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot have that happen. They have a weight program that
they're being asked to do. Plus, if they aren't getting up and down
the floor a lot, we've asked they get on a treadmill or a bike and
put in some extra time.
</P>
<P>
   ``These players are being asked to do more than anybody else in
the Olympics is being asked to do. But that's what it is to be an
Olympian this year. If you want that gold medal, then you'll do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards, who will turn 36 this summer and take part in her fifth
Olympics, is one player who won't have to be concerned about the
grind of the WNBA season. She has declined to sign with the league
since the American Basketball League folded in December 1998, but
she said she has hired a personal trainer who will push her to get
in top physical shape.
</P>
<P>
   ``My workouts are probably going to be harder than the girls who
are playing in the WNBA,'' Edwards said. ``My days are going to be
filled with two-a-days for the next three months.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the first time a U.S. women's basketball team will be
forced to juggle its schedule around a professional league. In
1996, the WNBA did not exist.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. team started a pre-Olympic tour nearly 10 months before
the Atlanta Games. It played 52 games in seven countries and
traveled more than 100,000 miles. The U.S. went 59-0 in that tour
and swept to the gold medal with eight straight wins.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went through that, but it was over a longer period of
time,'' Leslie said. ``Plus, we had the advantage of playing in our
country at the Olympics. This year, we're going to somebody else's
back yard. You know everybody's going to be gunning for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The main competition for the gold this year is expected to come
from Russia, Cuba, Brazil and host country Australia. The U.S. is
in the same bracket in the preliminary round with Russia and Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing in Australia's home court will be tough,'' Fortner
said. ``The parity in the women's game internationally is much
closer than in the men's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we've got a lot of experienced players who are very
talented and some young players who can add a lot. We're going over
there with our guns loaded.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps. But will their tanks will be full?
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-00 0121EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
