<DOCNO> NYT20000515.0031 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 01:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5153 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-OLY-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     05-15 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
IF the WNBA is the best women's basketball league in the world, it
stands to reason that the thrice-defending champion Comets are the
best team in the world not created from an entire nation's talent
pool.
</P>
<P>
   So it seems strange that the Comets, who could be four-time
defending champions when the Olympics begin, may not be represented
on the U.S. Olympic team in Sydney in September. They were
conspicuous by their absence from the news-conference dais at the
Olympic Summit on Sunday, although their being in Washington to
play an exhibition game would have precluded their presence
regardless of their Olympic status.
</P>
<P>
   Which, at present, is nonexistent.
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia Cooper is gone, having left the team last fall for
personal reasons, and Tina Thompson, although technically still
under consideration, figures to fall victim to the numbers game at
her position. I say may, however, because Sheryl Swoopes, albeit
apparently somewhat to her own amazement, remains one of a number
of candidates for the still-vacant 12th spot on the roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``They sent me a packet in the mail last week,'' Swoopes said.
``I wasn't expecting it, because I sort of felt like I was out of
the picture.''
</P>
<P>
   No. Coach Nell Fortner, in town for the Olympic Summit over the
weekend, confirmed Sunday that Swoopes was very much in the
picture. But Fortner also seemed to be saying that Sheryl will have
to earn the spot and must be further ``evaluated'' based on how she
performs over the coming WNBA season.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, that might seem fair enough. Except Swoopes is
Swoopes, about the closest thing the women's game had to a Michael
Jordan when it emerged from relative obscurity in the mid-1990s to
actually become a marketable commodity in the U.S. And her best
years may lie ahead.
</P>
<P>
   You make stars like Sheryl, the top vote-getter for last
season's WNBA All-Star Game, the centerpiece of your program. You
bend over backward to accommodate special talents such as hers. You
don't make her jump through hoops to shoot hoops for the
motherland. It's not like she didn't want to be part of the
national team over the WNBA's offseason. In good conscience, she
couldn't.
</P>
<P>
   The sole reason Swoopes isn't a slam dunk to be representing the
U.S. in Sydney is because personal circumstances _ the residue of a
difficult divorce and the demands on a suddenly single mom with a
2-year-old _ made it impossible for her to join the team for its
training sessions and subsequent globe-trotting.
</P>
<P>
   Swoopes, a '96 Olympian, hasn't played with the national team
since the winter of 1999. When she begged off most recently, she
found herself off the ``A'' list.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't afford to just leave (son) Jordan for two months
while I left to play basketball,'' she said. ``I wasn't in a place
where I could do that.''
</P>
<P>
   While Swoopes professes to possess no hard feelings about not
being given preferential consideration, her stature is such that
she should be catered to, particularly under her trying
circumstances. But, says Fortner: ``I find it hard to believe you
would have to talk somebody into playing on the Olympic team.''
</P>
<P>
   Except Swoopes doesn't need to be persuaded. She only needs to
be asked. Not in August, either. Now. It's beneath her to have to
audition. They wouldn't make Michael do it, would they?
</P>
<P>
   Coop's case is different, yet similar. Twice the WNBA's Most
Valuable Player some 10 years after she helped bring home the 1988
gold medal from Seoul, she politely excused herself from the
national team the moment the Comets completed their three-peat.
</P>
<P>
   She was seeking some much-needed time and space to, as she said,
``go through the grieving process'' after the deaths of her mother
and teammate Kim Perrot. A better tack with Cooper perhaps would
have been to give her as much of both as she needed while saving
her spot, no questions asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``No hard feelings,'' Coop said. ``I've got (a gold medal). I'm
pulling for the team to get another.''
</P>
<P>
   And we must assume they will, Comets or no Comets in the mix.
But at least one Olympian admitted she would feel more secure if
Houston's WNBA dynasty were certain to be represented.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only person that really comes to mind, that I really wish
was on our team, is Sheryl,'' said Lisa Leslie of the rival Los
Angeles Sparks. ``I feel we do need her.''
</P>
<P>
   For the record, Leslie isn't lobbying for Swoopes because
they're best girlfriends. She's simply being pragmatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, it's not about chemistry,'' the Sparks' brightest
spark said. ``It's about what a player can bring to the court and
what our team needs. At this point, I feel Sheryl could really help
us. She's very versatile, and she plays great defense. Defense will
enable us to win.''
</P>
<P>
   As a Comet, Swoopes knows plenty about winning.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-00 0122EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
