<DOCNO> NYT20000515.0032 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 01:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5154 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-REDS-ASTROS-HNS &LR;      05-15 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-REDS-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
Considering the rarity of the occurrence so far this season, any
win is a big win for the Astros. And while their latest was worth
only one game in the standings, it carried major weight in the home
clubhouse.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Astros snapped a two-game losing streak with a 10-3 victory
over the Cincinnati Reds on Sunday night before a sellout crowd at
Enron Field and a national ESPN audience.
</P>
<P>
   In a game that was as much a battle as it was a war, the Astros
won on both counts. Scott Elarton pitched seven solid innings and
likely earned an immeasurable amount of respect for a pitch that
hit Ken Griffey Jr. in the back.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the game, Reds starter Steve Parris hit Astros first
baseman Jeff Bagwell in the left thigh before umpire crew chief
Alan Clark issued warnings to both benches.
</P>
<P>
   Presumably, both pitches were thrown with a purpose, considering
some bad blood that developed in Saturday's game when both clubs
felt the other engaged in some unnecessary showmanship.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how the game is played,'' Bagwell said. ``That's as far
as I'll go with that. Anyone who knows anything about how the game
is played knows what was going on.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros won for only the fourth time in their last nine
games. They had lost 11 of their last 15 games against the Reds,
dating to last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was character-check time,'' said Astros shortstop Bill
Spiers, who was 3-for-4. ``Not to make it sound drastic, but we
needed a win. Actually, we need a bunch of them.''
</P>
<P>
   If they can consistently duplicate Sunday's performance, the
victories would start coming with more frequency. The pitching
staff held the Reds to three runs and six hits, while the offense
churned out 10 runs and 13 hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll keep winning if we play good defense, pitch and hit _
all the things we haven't done at the same time for most of the
year,'' Bagwell said.
</P>
<P>
   Elarton held the Reds to two runs on four hits in seven innings,
and Bagwell and catcher Mitch Meluskey paced the offense with three
RBIs apiece. The bullpen, which blew leads each of the previous two
days, held off the Reds to secure Elarton's second victory and his
first at Enron Field. Elarton and Shane Reynolds are the only
Astros pitchers to win a game at home this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Psychologically, this is a big win,'' Astros manager Larry
Dierker said. ``They beat us a lot last year, and they beat us the
first two games of this series. They kind of had us on our heels.''
</P>
<P>
   A psychological victory also could be claimed, considering the
way the Astros' starting pitchers have performed on the current
homestand. They have compiled a 3.95 ERA in the six games, and that
number drops to 2.62 if you exclude Elarton's seven-run,
four-inning outing against the Rockies in his previous start.
Perhaps as impressive is the fact they've allowed only four homers
in 38 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now everyone in the rotation has had a good outing here except
(Jose) Lima, and we hope he has one (tonight),'' Dierker said. ``I
think we've gotten past the psychological barriers of pitching in
this ballpark.''
</P>
<P>
   Elarton allowed both of his runs in the first inning on Dante
Bichette's single up the middle. The Reds managed to advance only
two runners into scoring position against Elarton after the first
inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't look too good after the first inning, but he settled
down,'' Dierker said. ``To put six zeros on the board against that
club and in this ballpark is tough to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros tied the score in the second on a single by Spiers
and a double-play grounder off the bat of Roger Cedeno, who brought
home Meluskey.
</P>
<P>
   Meluskey's three-run homer gave the Astros a 5-2 lead in the
fifth. He is hitting .444 (12-for-27) with two homers and nine RBIs
in his last eight games.
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell's RBI double pushed the Astros' lead to four runs in the
sixth. The two-out hit was timely in more ways than one for
Bagwell, who had only two hits in his previous 23 at-bats. Bagwell,
who was 2-for-3 with three RBIs, is hitting .239 in his last 12
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel better,'' Bagwell said. ``It's a good sign for me to
hit a ball to right field. Sometimes in baseball you can know what
you're doing wrong and not know how to fix it. It's easy to say and
hard to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Reds added another run in the eighth when catcher Eddie
Taubensee led off with an infield single and scored on Juan
Castro's triple into the left-field gap off righthanded reliever
Joe Slusarski. Jose Cabrera worked the ninth inning to close out
the victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros scored four runs (two earned) off Manny Aybar in the
bottom of the eighth, giving Cabrera some breathing room. Bagwell
had a two-run single in the inning, and Moises Alou _ activated
from the disabled list less than two hours before the game _ also
drove in a run in the inning with a double into the left-field gap.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was nice to see, because in this park you have to keep
putting runs up there,'' Spiers said. ``You never know what's going
to happen here.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
