<HEADLINE>
IT'S A MERE JUMPING-OFF POINT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Inserts paragraph marks in second half of story) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Why did Jason Kapono even bother putting on a UCLA
tank top for one season if he knew he'd be trying the NBA's
patience less than a year after his high school graduation?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he thought Steve Lavin really had somethin' going.
</P>
<P>
   Lavin does. It's college basketball's version of skydiving.
He'll pilot the plane up a few thousand feet, then hand out
parachutes. One per customer.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of yelling ``Geronimo,'' it's ``Kapono, wait for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Funny thing is those who !ital!don't jump look like they're
scared. Wazza matter, Earl Watson? Are ya yellow?
</P>
<P>
   The only thing scary about this whole rip-cord mentality is that
there isn't any way to stop it, locally or nationally. It's the
NCAA epidemic, and its hands are tied.
</P>
<P>
   It sounds stupid, but there's gonna be a day when a junior high
kid calls his own news conference at the school cafeteria after
recess and, with his P.E. teacher/agent standing behind him, tells
the world he's ready to join the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   And the NBA will welcome him to the party. ...
</P>
<P>
   --Bully for Bob Knight. The weekend's over and he hasn't been
forced into any anger management counseling. ...
</P>
<P>
   --As talented as Allen Iverson is, he doesn't make his team
better. ...
</P>
<P>
   --Who are the Dodgers trying to fool with those billboards?
That's someone's drawing of Raul Mondesi leaping for a ball at the
wall. ...
</P>
<P>
   --Going into the weekend, the D'backs' magic number was 124 to
tie and 125 to clinch the West outright. ...
</P>
<P>
   --Check the early warning signs of the Dodgers' bullpen woes: On
this day in 1919, the Brooklyn Dodgers and Cincinnati Reds went 12
scoreless innings. Then Al Mamaux came in and gave up 10 runs to
the Reds in the 13th. ...
</P>
<P>
   --There's a chance that some ex-big-leaguers will be picked for
the Olympic baseball team. So, yup, Orel Hershiser could be joining
Tom Lasorda down under by the time August rolls around. ...
</P>
<P>
   --The ball Pete Rose purportedly hit for his 4,000th career base
knock goes on auction this week. Pete's betting it's the real deal.
...
</P>
<P>
   --Celebrity sighting: Eric Dickerson, Deacon Jones, Sugar Ray
Leonard, John Robinson and Charles White are scheduled to attend an
open-to-the-public gathering at Yankee Doodles in Santa Monica on
Thursday from 6 to 8:30 p.m., promoting ESPN Classic's programming
lineup of great moments in L.A. sports history that'll air Saturday
and Sunday. ...
</P>
<P>
   --The best current pro athlete with the best golf handicap is,
according to Golf Digest, Arena Football League quarterback Peter
Tom Willis of the Tampa Bay Storm. ...
</P>
<P>
   --Given the chance to own a team in any pro sport, John Elway
knows one he'll never go after.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't touch baseball if they gave it to me,'' he told the
Rocky Mountain News. ``They have no (salary) cap and the players
run that whole deal.'' ...
</P>
<P>
   --Don King says the recent Lennox Lewis-Michael Grant fight was
so bad, people were calling his office to get a refund - and it
wasn't even his fight.
</P>
<P>
   That would be a natural assumption, though. ...
</P>
<P>
   --That four-team Spring Football League that started a few
Saturdays ago with a game between the Los Angeles Dragons and some
team from Houston that drew about 200 at the Coliseum? It's already
suspended operations.
</P>
<P>
   So the Dragons, who included kicker Chris Sailor, go down 0-1.
Meaning, combined with the Avengers' 0-5 record, L.A. isn't missing
out on any pro football.
</P>
</TEXT>
