<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, May 14, moved Saturday and are repeated Monday.
</P>
<P>
   On the dress page:
</P>
<P>
   PEACEKEEPING-REVIEW (Undated) _ Call it Democratic Man's Burden.
He watches TV news. He sees a child starving in Somalia,
eviscerated by shrapnel in Sarajevo or maimed by rebels in Sierra
Leone. He feels morally affronted, angry and a little guilty. He
demands Something Be Done. So it begins _ the peacekeeping
imperative. From Haiti to East Timor, Angola to Iraq, the Western
democracies _ and especially the United States, with its news media
as its tireless, outrage-sniffing hound _ have claimed a stake in
almost every fight, especially those that produce television
pictures of pitiless tyrants harming innocents. By Blaine Harden.
(Moved in the `i' category)
</P>
<P>
   KIDS-POLITICS-REVIEW (Washington) _ Call it the infantilization
of politics. Ever since President Clinton won re-election four
years ago with child-centered issues like school uniforms and
literacy and stopping teen-age smoking, candidates have
increasingly behaved as if they are auditioning for the role of
Santa Claus. But it was Clinton who built a whole presidential
campaign around kids, telegraphing his empathy for working parents
by watching children make model airplanes, or dropping into a
school that requires uniforms, or reading along with towheaded
tykes. By Alison Mitchell. (Moved in the `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moved in the `a' category:
</P>
<P>
   ADULTERY-POLITICS-REVIEW (Undated) _ Until fairly recently,
American voters punished candidates who made them aware of their
personal complications. The presidential prospects of Nelson
Rockefeller and Adlai Stevenson, it is said, were hurt by their
divorces. Eventually divorce became politically acceptable, but
adultery was still a no-no. Now, as William Bennett points out, not
only is adultery no longer politically fatal for candidates, but
even such ``complicating factors'' as lying to the public about an
affair, or carrying on with an underling, seem to matter less and
less. By Melinda Henneberger.
</P>
<P>
   GENES-PATENTS-REVIEW (Undated) _ In December, an obscure agency
known as the European Patent Office erroneously issued the first
patent to allow the cloning of a human being. More alarmingly, it
may have granted scientists the right to change the genetic makeup
of the entire human species. This case of ``Brave New World'' meets
the Marx Brothers will not be untangled soon. The appeals process
for overturning the patent is sure to take years. By Anthony
Ramirez.
</P>
<P>
   COPENHAGEN-THEATER-REVIEW (New York) _ Playwright Michael
Frayn's `'Copenhagen'' arrived on Broadway last month after a
critical and commercial success in London. The three-character play
about the unsettling philosophical implications of quantum physics
is a hit here, too. Ben Brantley, theater critic of The New York
Times, called it ``the most invigorating and ingenious play of
ideas in many a year.'' But does anyone understand it? By Rick
Marin.
</P>
<P>
   CHILD-COSTS-REVIEW (Undated) _ It now costs about $160,140 to
raise a middle-class child through age 17, according to a
government report. That's up from $25,229 in 1960 ($69,333 in
1980), seemingly a huge increase. But that 1960 figure, adjusted
for inflation, would equal $141,998 today, so the cost of bringing
up baby has risen only about 13 percent since 1960. By Tamar Lewin.
With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   BASKETBALL-HERO-REVIEW (Undated) _ The Basketball Hall of Fame
is considering the induction of a long-forgotten Italian immigrant
bowling-alley owner from Syracuse, N.Y., Danny Biasone, who back in
the mid-1950s literally saved the game at a time when the future of
the young NBA was in doubt. By Charles Paikert.
</P>
<P>
   CATHOLIC-BISHOPS-REVIEW (Undated) _ The selection of Edward Egan
as archbishop of New York is illustrative of the appointments made
by Pope John Paul II. The pontiff has reshaped the American church
hierarchy as perhaps none of his predecessors has. He has filled
vacancies with men who share his own vision of how the church
should be run. The process has been gradual, but its effect has
been profound. By Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   DOOMSDAY-REVIEW (Undated) _ Let's face it: Y2K was a bust. Now
with the Year 2000 almost half over, the opportunities for a
millennial end time are narrowing. In fact, the last big chance may
come May 17, when the Sun and five planets will form an unusually
tight alignment. By George Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   PHILOSOPHERS-TEXT-REVIEW (Undated) _ The writer Paul Strathern,
who earned a philosophy degree at Trinity College in Dublin, has
been distilling most of the world's best-known philosophers to 90
minutes. A godsend in this era of the short attention span, the
series begins with ``Socrates in 90 Minutes,'' wittily compressing
his life and works, and proceeds to Locke, Augustine, Descartes,
Sarte and others. Excerpts from the books.
</P>
<P>
   CONTROLLED-CATASTROPHES-REVIEW (Undated) _ In the wake of the
Los Alamos wildfire, some imaginary deliberate disasters are
reported.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week.
</P>
<P>
   Also moved in the `i' category:
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-AIDS-REVIEW (Undated) _ Across Africa, there have been
countless incidents of quack AIDS cures being sold, some even
supported by government officials. But South African President
Thabo Mbeki is the only leader to have questioned the mainstream
theories on what causes AIDS. AIDS activists, long annoyed by South
Africa's inaction, are now shocked by the attention the issue is
getting. But Mbeki's refusal to accept standard scientific thinking
remains puzzling to almost everyone. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-REBELS-REVIEW (Undated) _ The Colombian government,
frustrated by its inability to end thirty years of war against two
major guerrilla movements, is now seeking peace by granting both
guerrilla movements the one thing they want most: uncontested zones
that they can call their own territory. The government has in
effect formally recognized that it doesn't exercise full
sovereignty over all its territory, leaving the two zones a kind of
neverland where it is not clear who is in charge _ or how the zones
fit into the rest of the country. By Larry Rohter. With graphic.
</P>
<P>
