<HEADLINE>
BEST SELLERS: PAPERBACK BOOKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For release on Sunday, May 21)  
(Eds: This file is the abbreviated best-seller list for paperback
books. See BESTSELLERS-PAPER-L-NYT for the full version that
includes how many weeks each book has been on the list.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rankings reflect sales figures for the week ending May 6 at
almost 4,000 bookstores plus wholesalers serving 60,000 other
retailers, statistically weighted to represent sales in all such
outlets nationwide. The number of titles within the two
subdivisions of nonfiction can change from week to week, reflecting
changes in book buying.
</P>
<P>
   An (x) following a book's ranking indicates that a book's sales
are barely distinguishable from those of the book above. A (b)
indicates that some bookstores report receiving bulk orders for a
book.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FICTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. RIVER'S END, by Nora Roberts. (Jove, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   The daughter of a glamorous Hollywood couple
</P>
<P>
   must cope with her family's horrifying past.
</P>
<P>
   2. WE'LL MEET AGAIN, by Mary Higgins Clark.
</P>
<P>
   (Pocket, $7.99.) A woman tries to free herself
</P>
<P>
   of people's suspicion that she murdered her
</P>
<P>
   husband.
</P>
<P>
   3. THE KILLING GAME, by Iris Johansen. (Bantam,
</P>
<P>
   $6.99.) A forensic sculptor hopes to find her
</P>
<P>
   murdered daughter's remains.
</P>
<P>
   4. WHERE THE HEART IS, by Billie Letts. (Warner, $12.)
</P>
<P>
   A pregnant teen-ager finds help and caring in a small
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma town.
</P>
<P>
   5.(x) CARNAL INNOCENCE, by Nora Roberts. (Bantam, $7.50.)
</P>
<P>
   A concert violinist visiting Innocence, Miss.,
</P>
<P>
   becomes enamored of a man suspected of being a serial
</P>
<P>
   killer.
</P>
<P>
   6. THE BLUEST EYE, by Toni Morrison. (Plume, $12.95.)
</P>
<P>
   The story of an 11-year-old black girl _ pregnant by her
</P>
<P>
   father _ who prays for blue eyes.
</P>
<P>
   7. THE RIGHT HAND OF EVIL, by John Saul. (Ballantine,
</P>
<P>
   $7.99.) When a family moves into its ancestral home,
</P>
<P>
   terrible secrets begin to emerge.
</P>
<P>
   8. BLACK FRIDAY, by James Patterson. (Warner
</P>
<P>
   Vision, $6.99.) A secret militia lays siege
</P>
<P>
   to New York City.
</P>
<P>
   9. FORTUNE'S HAND, by Belva Plain. (Dell, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   A young attorney's ideals are tested when he joins a
</P>
<P>
   prominent law firm.
</P>
<P>
   10. TOM CLANCY'S NET FORCE: Night Moves, created by
</P>
<P>
   Tom Clancy and Steve Pieczenik. (Berkley, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   Computer terrorism in 2011.
</P>
<P>
   11. LAKE NEWS, by Barbara Delinsky. (Pocket Star, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   To escape a scandal in the big city, a singer flees to
</P>
<P>
   her seemingly idyllic hometown.
</P>
<P>
   12. SERPENT, by Clive Cussler with Paul Kemprecos.
</P>
<P>
   (Pocket, $7.99.) The Andrea Doria's remains yield
</P>
<P>
   treasures that point to a deadly conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   13. THE TESTAMENT, by John Grisham. (Island, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   A reclusive billionaire, a burned-out lawyer and
</P>
<P>
   a missionary are brought together by a startling
</P>
<P>
   secret.
</P>
<P>
   14. HARRY POTTER AND THE SORCERER'S STONE,
</P>
<P>
   by J.K. Rowling. (Scholastic, $5.99.) A British
</P>
<P>
   boy, neglected by his relatives, finds his fortune
</P>
<P>
   attending a school for witchcraft.
</P>
<P>
   15. THE SAVING GRACES, by Patricia Gaffney. (HarperTorch,
</P>
<P>
   $6.99.) The close friendship that binds four women is
</P>
<P>
   put to the test.
</P>
<P>
   16.(x) CUBA, by Stephen Coonts. (St. Martin's, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   With Castro about to die, the United States sends a rear
</P>
<P>
   admiral to Cuba to salvage lethal weapons.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NONFICTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. THE SEAT OF THE SOUL, by Gary Zukav. (Fireside/S&AMP;S,
</P>
<P>
   $12.) How daily activities can be enhanced by feelings
</P>
<P>
   of meaning and purpose. (b)
</P>
<P>
   2. GIRL, INTERRUPTED, by Susanna Kaysen. (Vintage, $12.)
</P>
<P>
   A memoir of mental illness.
</P>
<P>
   3. A CHILD CALLED ``IT,'' by Dave Pelzer. (Health
</P>
<P>
   Communications, $9.95.) The autobiography of a man
</P>
<P>
   who survived his mother's abuse. (b)
</P>
<P>
   4. ANGELA'S ASHES, by Frank McCourt. (Touchstone/S&AMP;S,
</P>
<P>
   $14 and $7.99.) An Irish-American writer recalls his
</P>
<P>
   childhood amid the miseries of Limerick.
</P>
<P>
   5. BELLA TUSCANY, by Frances Mayes. (Broadway, $15.)
</P>
<P>
   An American remembers a spring and summer spent in the
</P>
<P>
   romantic sections of Italy.
</P>
<P>
   6.(x) THE LOST BOY, by Dave Pelzer. (Health
</P>
<P>
   Communications, $10.95.) The author of ``A Child
</P>
<P>
   Called `It''' recalls his life in foster homes. (b)
</P>
<P>
   7. THE PERFECT STORM, by Sebastian Junger.
</P>
<P>
   (HarperPerennial, $14; HarperPaperbacks, $6.99.)
</P>
<P>
   The story of the nor'easter of 1991, focusing on a
</P>
<P>
   single crew.
</P>
<P>
   8.(x) THE ELEGANT UNIVERSE, by Brian Greene.
</P>
<P>
   (Vintage, $15.) A presentation of superstring
</P>
<P>
   theory, which attempts to mediate between
</P>
<P>
   quantum mechanics and general relativity.
</P>
<P>
   9. THE MILLIONAIRE NEXT DOOR, by Thomas J. Stanley
</P>
<P>
   and William D. Danko. (Pocket, $14.) An analysis
</P>
<P>
   of the lives of wealthy Americans. (b)
