 By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   They say necessity is the mother of invention, but desperation
can also be its source. In Colombia, a government frustrated by its
inability to end three decades of warfare with two major guerrilla
insurgencies is now seeking peace by granting both movements one of
the things they crave most: uncontested territory they can call
their own.
</P>
<P>
   The move is not without logic, though its many critics contend
that the logic is deeply flawed. The idea was that pulling troops
out of what were already rebel strongholds could create an
atmosphere of good will in peace talks. But that hasn't really
happened so far, and so the effect has been somewhat different:
Colombia has formally recognized that it doesn't exercise full
sovereignty over all its territory.
</P>
<P>
   That has left the two zones a kind of never-never land where it
is not clear who is in charge or how the zones fit into the rest of
the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are seeing, in a sense, the hollowing-out of government in
critical regions of Latin America and its replacement by
individuals who are, in fact, introducing a narco-government, a
small narco-empire,'' said Peter Romero, the State Department's
senior official for Latin American affairs, last week.
</P>
<P>
   The creation of these two insurgent-controlled areas began 18
months ago, when the government ceded 16,000 square miles to
Colombia's largest guerrilla group, known as the FARC, in an effort
to jump-start peace talks. But the talks have faltered, and the
FARC has only become more powerful. It acts increasingly like a
parallel government and is now planning a ``peace tax'' on wealthy
people and companies in the zone.
</P>
<P>
   The government's move also left Colombia's other big rebel
group, known as the ELN, intensely jealous. So the group began a
sabotage and kidnapping campaign, to which President Andres
Pastrana responded last month by agreeing to concede it a second
zone.
</P>
<P>
   Latin America has had its share of insurgencies, but even at the
height of the Central American civil wars of the 1980s there was
never an arrangement quite like this. Guerrillas exercised de facto
control of parts of El Salvador and Contras ranged freely over
northern Nicaragua, but they certainly did not do so with the
consent of the governments they were fighting.
</P>
<P>
   The latest concession has not gone over well with ordinary
Colombians, especially those who must live in the area that is to
become a haven for the ELN, or Army of National Liberation. In
February and March, residents blocked highways to protest the plan,
pointing to the creation of the earlier guerrilla safe zone as a
naive experiment gone totally wrong.
</P>
<P>
   As originally envisioned in the agreement with the FARC, or
Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia, only soldiers and police
were to be withdrawn from the so-called zone of disarmament, which
is larger than Connecticut, Massachusetts and Rhode Island
combined. But the FARC eventually drove mayors, judges,
prosecutors, tax collectors and priests out, implanting its own
authority _ and inviting in coca producers.
</P>
<P>
   So in all but name, the first demilitarized zone is now an
entity beyond the Colombian state's control. Hence the sardonic
nickname given it by its 60,000 residents: Farclandia. Passengers
landing at the airport in San Vicente del Caguan have their
passports and luggage inspected by rebels; guerrillas staff the
city hall and residents have to deal with them when they need
police protection or a road paved.
</P>
<P>
   The ``zone of encounter'' that is now to be handed over to the
ELN is barely one-tenth the size of the FARC zone, or roughly the
size of Delaware, but its location is much more strategic. So the
dent in Colombian sovereignty may be just as great, even though
this time Pastrana has promised that all civil authorities in the
area ``will continue in the exercise of their functions,'' and
international observers will be allowed in to assure that the ELN
is honoring the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Pastrana's action is all the more surprising given the
importance that Latin American governments traditionally attach to
the concept of national sovereignty. To maintain the notion
untarnished, countries like Mexico and Venezuela, for example, have
turned down offers of U.S. assistance after natural disasters, and
Chile's government, though full of officials who were persecuted
while Chile was under military rule, repeatedly cited sovereignty
in demanding that Britain release Gen. Augusto Pinochet.
</P>
<P>
   But historical experience also says that sovereignty is one of
those ideas, like the rule of law or military subordination to
civilians, that is more honored in the breach than in practice in
Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   In Colombia's case, sovereignty in remote areas often consists
of little more than a flag and a national anthem. Guerrillas and
drug traffickers can move into areas like Caqueta and Putumayo
precisely because the state has never bothered _ or been able _ to
build roads, schools or hospitals there, and the forlorn, neglected
peasants there feel only the most tenuous of connections to the
authorities back in Bogota.
</P>
<P>
   The Colombian state is scarcely alone in failing to back up
assertions of sovereignty with meaningful actions. Many residents
of the area in the heart of the Amazon, where Colombia, Peru and
Brazil share a border, carry the identity cards of all three
countries and use their currencies interchangeably, as if the
frontier did not exist. None of those countries, however, has a
history of reliably supplying services like medical care and
education there; for these, citizens have had to depend on
missionaries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
