<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: A bird in the hand
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ I was walking up from the far part of the back
yard. My wife was waiting at the door. When I was hardly halfway to
the house, she yelled to me.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a bird in the bedroom.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' I yelled back, ``you'd better do something about it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I just did,'' she said, disappearing into the house and
shutting the door after her.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, that's her one cure-all: Tell me, turn around and walk
away.
</P>
<P>
   A bird in the house. Oh me, oh my. I can sympathize with a bird
in a house.
</P>
<P>
   It sees a window. There's the outdoors. It has only to fly
through the opening, and it's free.
</P>
<P>
   Then _ THUD! _ all of a sudden it's knocked silly by something
it can't see. The bird recovers its senses and takes off flying
again for the opening, almost there, almost free ...
</P>
<P>
   The invisible force field brings it down again.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine the bird's anguish, its fear, its frustration, time and
again banging its head against a barrier it has no way of
comprehending, window glass.
</P>
<P>
   Ever have a day like that? Yeah, me too. I can easily envision
what it must be like to be a bird caught in a house. I'd do what I
could.
</P>
<P>
   I tiptoed into the bedroom, looking this way and that, up and
down and around the room.
</P>
<P>
   Right away, I spotted the bird clinging to a window curtain,
already having given up, already having resigned itself that
there's no way out of this death trap.
</P>
<P>
   Sneaking up behind it, I reached out my hand ever so slowly and
then _ SNATCH!
</P>
<P>
   I couldn't believe the luck. I got it in one.
</P>
<P>
   It was hardly a handful, but exquisite in every way. There's no
beauty quite so sleek as that of aerodynamics.
</P>
<P>
   I stared into the black, black, blackness of its eyes, and it
stared into mine. I knew what the bird was seeing. The bird was
seeing death.
</P>
<P>
   The only question in its mind was whether I'd eat it feet first
or head first. It bobbed its head. Here, it was saying. Be quick,
please.
</P>
<P>
   I was quick. I quickly walked outside, stretched out my hand and
gave it a little boost in the release, as if it needed any.
</P>
<P>
   Wings flapping as hard as wings have ever flapped, it took off
straight up, thinking at any second it'd be brought crashing down
again by the invisible force.
</P>
<P>
   But not this time. This time it soared, circling a wide, upward
spiraling circle way above house and trees, and then it was gone.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine the elation, the exhilaration, the freedom!
</P>
<P>
   Ever have a day like that? Neither have I. But I've seen what
it's like.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(AT)txucom.net; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915; website, http://www.coxnews.com/newsservice.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
