<HEADER>
A5319 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e BC-JACKIE-CHAN-IN-SHANGH     05-15 1431
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKIE-CHAN-IN-SHANGHAI-NOON-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACKIE CHAN GOES WEST 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Jackie Chan with Owen Wilson in a scene
from ``Shanghai Noon.'') 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago. 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    Jackie Chan is doing a little redecorating.
 &HT;    He's being interviewed at New York's posh Essex House, but the
furniture layout doesn't meet his standards. So he picks up a heavy
oak chair and moves it _ and the reporter sitting in it _ to a new
spot.
 &HT;    So he's not just strong, he's picky.
 &HT;    ``I like things to be perfect,'' he says.
 &HT;    They aren't far from it, at least where his career is concerned.
The Hong Kong action star has succeeded where so many have failed
in breaking into the American and international markets. After
earning a mere $5 million for the smash hit ``Rush Hour'' (1998),
he's receiving triple that for ``Shanghai Noon,'' a comedy/action
Western set to open May 26.
 &HT;    And the money was apparently well spent _ Disney is so confident
in the film's prospects that a screenwriter is already halfway done
with the sequel.
 &HT;    Being Jackie Chan does have its sore spots _ literally, as he
point out with an informal ``damages tour'' of the impact his
penchant for flamboyant stunts has had on his body.
 &HT;    ``Concussion, bleeding, stitches,'' he says, pointing to his
head.
 &HT;    He touches his nose.
 &HT;    ``Broken three times,'' he says.
 &HT;    Teeth: ``Four gone in bad jump.''
 &HT;    Scalp: ``Ripped open.''
 &HT;    Fingers: ``Sprained, broken, broken, nearly ripped off.''
 &HT;    Shoulder: ``Broken.''
 &HT;    Other shoulder: ``Broken.''
 &HT;    Elbow: ``Broken,'' he says. ``Many times.''
 &HT;    Legs: ``Broken, broken, broken.''
 &HT;    Ribs: ``Cracked. Bruised. Fractured.''
 &HT;    Knees: ``Twisted, broken, crushed.''
 &HT;    Which doesn't mean you should expect to see him taking it easy
in ``Shanghai Noon.''
 &HT;    ``Oh, I do these stunts for one reason,'' he says. ``It's so
much fun. I love it _ I love the challenge!''
 &HT;    Occasionally, he admits, things get out of hand.
 &HT;    ``Well, once I do Hong Kong action movie where I am supposed to
jump from window to tree,'' he recalls. ``It seems easy, but then
the tree branch break and I fall a couple of hundred feet.
 &HT;    ``I got a concussion so bad that the blood was pouring out of my
ear and wouldn't stop for hours,'' Chan says, shrugging. ``No big
deal.''
 &HT;    ``Shanghai Noon,'' based on an idea by Chan, is set in the Old
West, with Chan as a member of the Chinese Imperial Guard who teams
with a roguish train robber (Owen Wilson) to rescue a kidnaped
Chinese princess (Lucy Liu).
 &HT;    ``It's like `The Odd Couple' with horses,'' Chan says.
 &HT;    It's the latest step in an incident-filled life which began in
Hong Kong on April 7, 1954, after what he says was a horrific
11-month pregnancy which ended when his mother delivered a 12-pound
boy via Caesarean section.
 &HT;    The delivery was delayed, he says, because his impoverished
parents couldn't afford the $26 to pay for the surgery.
 &HT;    ``A female doctor approached my father with a deal,'' the actor
says. ``If my father would allow her to adopt me, she would pay for
my mother's surgery and medical expenses.
 &HT;    ``In Hong Kong, poor children were regularly given to their
wealthier friends,'' he adds, ``but my parents always said that
they knew I was a special one. They said no to this doctor, and our
family friends helped them pay the expenses.''
 &HT;    His childhood was spent surrounded by luxury, Chan says, though
his family couldn't share in it.
 &HT;    ``We didn't have much money,'' he says, ``but we lived in a
mansion where my father was a cook and a handyman for the French
ambassador to Hong Kong. My mother worked in the laundry room of
their mansion.
 &HT;    ``I think it taught me humility,'' he concludes, ``and that you
have to work so hard in order to achieve anything in this life.''
 &HT;    His father reinforced that lesson with a strict physical
regimen.
 &HT;    ``He would wake me up at dawn for tough workouts of running,
lifting bags of sand and doing military-style push-ups,'' Chan
recalls. ``We would also spend hours practicing martial-arts moves.
At 5, I learned the basics of Northern-style kung fu.''
 &HT;    The following year, when his parents took jobs in Australia,
Chan stayed behind as a student at the China Drama Academy, where
he spent 10 years as a virtual indentured servant to a famed
martial artist, Yu Jim-yuen.
 &HT;    ``He was a tough master,'' Chan says. ``He gave you food,
protection and the best training in the world, but there was a
steep price.
 &HT;    ``I don't know how I survived,'' he concludes. ``Sometimes I say
`Thank you' to my childhood, because it was the toughest training
of all.
 &HT;    ``I guess I cannot complain,'' he admits. ``Some students at
that school are washing dishes now in China _ they are the ones who
should be complaining. I have it easy.''
 &HT;    His turning point came when, to help the school make ends meet,
its students were given permission to work as film extras. Chan
took to stunt work immediately, and at 17 left school to pursue a
career in films.
 &HT;    ``Being a stunt man made me old before my time,'' he says. ``I
was risking my life for a few dollars a day. But they kept hiring
me. I was called whenever the most dangerous scene needed to be
shot _ I have no fear.''
 &HT;    From stunt work, he moved to acting in low-budget movies, then
higher-budget actioners such as Bruce Lee's ``Fists of Fury''
(1972).
 &HT;    ``They kept calling me the next Bruce Lee,'' Chan recalls, ``but
I didn't like the comparison. He kick high, I kick low. He never
smiles, I like to smile. I didn't want to be Bruce Lee _ I wanted
to be Buster Keaton and Fred Astaire.''
 &HT;    It took a while for American audiences to warm to his unique
combination of comedy and action.
 &HT;    ``Before `Rush Hour' I had many flops in America,'' Chan says.
``I insisted on the scene in `Rush Hour' where I'm hanging from a
street sign on Hollywood Boulevard _ it was my way of saying, `It's
all or nothing this time.'''
 &HT;    ``All'' came out the winner, as the film grossed $160 million
worldwide and jumpstarted his American career. Needless to say, a
sequel is in the works, due in 2001.
 &HT;    Which means more trouble for Chan as he tries to keep up with
his voluble co-star, Chris Tucker.
 &HT;    ``Oh, that guy Chris gave me a lot of problems,'' he says,
laughing. ``First time I meet Chris, he keep talking, talking,
talking. I have to finally say, `Excuse me.' I go to bathroom, call
my manager and say, `He don't shut up! And I don't know what he's
saying. He talks so fast.'''
 &HT;    The sequel will feature that patented Chan action, of course,
though he admits that at 46 his action days are numbered.
 &HT;    ``I think three more years,'' he says thoughtfully. ``Things
hurt now. But the good thing is that these action films are leaving
a good foundation for my next career. When I'm done with action
films, I want to do stuff like Michael Douglas _ I want to do
drama.''
 &HT;    For now, though, he still loves the stunts.
 &HT;    ``I look out a window 20 stories high, I know I can jump out of
it safely,'' he says cheerfully. ``That's because I only jump down
a couple of floors, and then jump to another roof and then jump
onto a ledge and then jump to the ground.
 &HT;    ``Do you think I'm nuts?''
 c.2000 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Cindy Pearlman is a Chicago-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
