<SLUG> BC-THE-RED-HOT-CHILI-PEPPERS-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOT AGAIN: THE RED HOT CHILI PEPPERS ARE BACK IN A GROOVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of the Red Hot Chili Peppers.) 
 By GARY GRAFF  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    Dave Grohl doesn't let his band, Foo Fighters, open for just
anybody.
 &HT;    He was a member of Nirvana, after all, which set standards of
credibility for modern rock bands that have endured since the early
1990s.
 &HT;    But when the Red Hot Chili Peppers invited Foo Fighters to play
several months' worth of dates during this spring and summer, Grohl
didn't hesitate.
 &HT;    ``I can't really think of many other bands that we'd do it
with,'' Grohl says. ``We've been asked by lots of bands to be the
opening band du jour, but it seems like with the Chili Peppers it's
kind of an honor, because they're an institution in their own
right.''
 &HT;    That institution dates back 22 years, since frontman Anthony
Kiedis and bassist Flea _ a.k.a. Michael Balzary _ founded the
Chili Peppers while they were students at Los Angeles' Fairfax High
School.
 &HT;    With carefree irreverence _ including stage appearances naked
except for strategically placed tube socks _ the group has mixed
funk, punk and rock into a distinctive sonic brew that owes props
equally to the MC5, Iggy Pop, the Sex Pistols and George Clinton,
who produced its second album, ``Freaky Styley'' (1985).
 &HT;    It's also been a survival story, with the Chili Peppers carrying
on despite the drug-overdose death of guitarist Hillel Slovak,
other members' addictions _ one of which Kiedis chronicled in their
1992 hit ``Under the Bridge'' _ a stream of eight other musicians
who have joined Kiedis and Flea in the group over the years, and
the distinction of being the band that fiddled while Woodstock 1999
burned.
 &HT;    Nonetheless, Kiedis claims that the band never considered
quitting.
 &HT;    ``It never occurred to us not to do this,'' he says. ``At least
not seriously.''
 &HT;    Actually, the Chili Peppers haven't simply survived, they've
thrived. Their latest album, ``Californication'' (1999), is a
multimillion-selling smash that won a Grammy Award and has spun off
the radio hits ``Scar Tissue'' and ``Other Side.''
 &HT;    Drummer Chad Smith calls the new album ``a rebirth'' for the
band. It is their first since ``One Hot Minute'' (1995), which,
despite selling a million copies, was perceived as a disappointment
both creatively and commercially.
 &HT;    Smith credits that rejuvenation to the band's reunion with
guitarist John Frusciante, who was only 18 when he joined the group
in 1988, and was on board for its breakthrough albums ``Mother's
Milk'' (1989) and ``Blood Sugar Sex Magik'' (1991).
 &HT;    ``The chemistry with the four of us is the best lineup, I think,
to make Red Hot Chili Peppers music,'' Smith says. ``I was anxious
to see if that would work again. It's really like getting a second
chance. We're all in a really good place. It's exciting again _
we're playing music for fun and enjoying ourselves.''
 &HT;    Frusciante was struggling with a debilitating drug addiction
when he unexpectedly quit in 1992, while the Chili Peppers were
touring in Japan and shortly before they were due to headline that
year's Lollapalooza festival. He tried his hand at a solo career,
but most of his time away from the group was spent either taking
drugs or trying to get off them.
 &HT;    It was Flea who first raised the idea of Frusciante returning to
the band. After visiting him in rehab, he felt that Frusciante was
genuinely clean. The Chili Peppers were without a guitarist, after
the departure of Frusciante's replacement, Dave Navarro of Jane's
Addiction, so he thought the time might be right to bring everybody
back together.
 &HT;    He broached the subject with Kiedis and Smith while the three
were watching a Los Angeles Lakers game on television.
 &HT;    ``He said, `What do you think about bringing John in again?'''
Smith recalls, ``and I was like, `Wow. Really?'
 &HT;    ``Because when he left, it was bad, really bad _ especially
between him and Anthony,'' Smith says. ``They weren't even
talking.''
 &HT;    But it didn't take long for the group to see that Frusciante had
indeed changed course and had rediscovered the passion for music
that had driven his first stint as a Pepper.
 &HT;    ``He was just so happy to be playing, and it's all about the
music and (being) in his favorite band, and it's really like that
again,'' Smith says. ``Now he's really focused, and he's really
inspiring to play with.
 &HT;    ``It's like, we were in the studio all day and all night. Then
he goes home and plays guitar to, like, the Ramones' `Rocket to
Russia,''' the drummer adds. ``He learns every little solo on the
Led Zeppelin BBC record. The next day he'll say `What did you do?'
and I'm like, `I went home and slept, dude.'
 &HT;    ``He's just all about music and art, all day long,'' Smith says.
``That's just what he lives for now.''
 &HT;    With Frusciante back on board, the Peppers repaired to Flea's
garage to jam out the songs for ``Californication.''
 &HT;    ``For our band, it's really important to just get in a room and
make noise and have that spontaneous musical interplay,'' Smith
says.
 &HT;    Co-producer Rick Rubin helped to hone the final list of cuts, as
well as developing the title track and a few others.
 &HT;    ``I think we're getting better at writing songs,'' Smith says.
``It just sounds relaxed. It sounds like how we did it _ we just
got in there and got good performances, like we were really
prepared ... We were happy to be playing together again, and that
probably comes through.''
 &HT;    Smith and the others simply hope the feeling lasts. They've
taken steps to protect it _ most notably reducing the grueling
rigor of their tour schedule, which they believe contributed to
members' drug addictions in the past.
 &HT;    ``With us, it seems like something always happens,'' Smith says
with a laugh, but he quickly adds that he's confident that this
time it will last.
 &HT;    ``When things go well and everyone's in a good mood, and you
make a good record and everybody's digging it, that really makes
things go a lot smoother,'' the drummer says. ``So I think we're
looking forward to some really good times ahead.''
 c.2000 Gary Graff  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Gary Graff is a Beverly Hills, Mich.-based free-lance
writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Californication,'' consult the
