<SLUG> BC-WRESTLING-CONQUERS-TELEVISION-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THROW BUSINESS: WRESTLING TAKES TELEVISION BY STORM 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of The Rock of the World Wrestling
Federation.) 
 By KEVIN SNOW  
 c.2000 TV Guide Canada  
 Not to be published in Canada before June 3. 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every television show needs something unique if it's to
flourish.
</P>
<P>
   It can be a unique character, such as ``Seinfeld's'' Kramer. It
can be a favorite setting, such as the Central Perk coffee house on
``Friends.'' It can be a unifying story line that people can relate
to, such as ``Frasier's'' search for romance.
</P>
<P>
   But while network writers and producers struggle to find hooks
to keep viewers coming back every week, the World Wrestling
Federation continues to make it look easy.
</P>
<P>
   Love it or hate it, there appears to be no stopping the WWF
juggernaut. It has taken the term ``sports entertainment'' and
turned it into four hours a week of prime-time excitement, 52 weeks
a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Raw Is War'' airs Mondays, originating as a live broadcast on
the USA Network. Week in and week out, ``Raw'' tops the national
cable ratings, and on May 1 it grabbed more than 7 million
households, equivalent to a 9.1 rating.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Thursday-night ``Smackdown!'' may have
single-handedly saved UPN. It has become the struggling network's
most-watched program, giving it a stranglehold on the coveted 18-34
male demographic _ particularly impressive, considering that UPN
isn't even available in some parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
   It's difficult to pin down the secret to the WWF's success.
Unpredictability and improvisation are two of its strong suits, but
far from the only ones. Recently we sat down with four WWF stars to
discuss some of the keys to their popularity. &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; STRONG FEMALES &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There's no denying that the WWF has more than its share of
beautiful women, but they definitely don't see themselves as window
dressing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just about sex,'' says the single-named Tori, a
member of the infamous D-Generation X crew. ``Any sexual aspect is
good and desirable by the viewers, but it's about being physical as
well. The women are continuing to step up to the plate, and that
was really headed up by Chyna.''
</P>
<P>
   Men and women alike are drawn to Chyna, billed as ``The Ninth
Wonder of the World'' and her ability to tackle all obstacles. She
became the first woman to compete in the ``Royal Rumble'' and
``King of the Ring,'' and has even held the Intercontinental Title.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to know that, here in the WWF, you can actually do
it all,'' Tori says.
</P>
<P>
   She rejects criticism from some fans who believe that the WWF's
women are exploited or condescended to.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can see them tripping on the boy-girl thing,'' she says.
``You know, boys ought not to be hitting girls. But this is
entertainment. It's suspension of disbelief.''
</P>
<P>
   Is there anything Tori wouldn't do in the ring?
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in a pudding match,'' she says with a smile. ``I
always thought I'd refuse that. Basically, if it's all in the
context of the story line, I don't think anybody would have a
problem with it.'' &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; GETTING PHYSICAL &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the outcome of the matches is known before the wrestlers
get into the ring. Get over it _ millions of fans have. And however
``fake'' wrestling may be, its physicality is definitely real.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Chris Benoit. Billed as ``The Crippler,'' Benoit is one
of the WWF's most physical wrestlers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of my character is my aggressiveness and tenacity in the
ring,'' the Canadian-born grappler says. ``But a lot of people
don't realize what goes on outside the arena.''
</P>
<P>
   For Benoit, that means maintaining a rigorous workout regimen,
healthy diet and proper sleep _ despite the WWF's tough travel
schedule, which includes more than 200 live shows every year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unlike most sports, we don't get an offseason with three or
four months of recuperation time,'' Benoit says. ``It's a
demanding, year-round, 24-hour-a-day, seven-days-a-week schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   He has suffered numerous injuries during his 14-year career _
among them a broken ankle and torn elbow ligaments _ but none of
them rivals being knocked unconscious in the ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the worst feeling,'' Benoit says. ``You wake up staring
at the lights on the ceiling, hearing people screaming, and you
don't know where you are or what you're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   All the same, he says, he has no regrets about his choice of
career.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a childhood dream,'' he says. ``We get our bodies
thrown around a lot, and it beats the heck out of our joints _ I
even have a hard time getting out of bed some mornings.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this is all I've ever wanted to do.'' &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; CHARISMA COUNTS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you're curious about the importance of a wrestler's
personality, there's no better person to ask than Chris Jericho.
``Y2J'' is as well known for his humorous ramblings and smart-aleck
remarks as he is for his trademark finishing move, ``The Walls of
Jericho.''
</P>
<P>
   Ask him one question, and he'll take over the rest of the
conversation.
</P>
<P>
   So, Chris, how important is it for a wrestler to have charisma
and personality?
</P>
<P>
   ``In the year 2000, I believe that one of the most _ if not the
most _ important thing in the business is to have charisma, a
charismatic character, and to have a persona that entertains
people,'' Jericho says. ``A good character is someone that people
can identify with, attach to and care about.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are sports entertainment,'' he says. ``It's very important
to be a great athlete who can wrestle a tremendous match, but I
think the most important thing is to entertain the people, and to
have the interview skills and the charisma that people can see.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I step in the ring, I look at it like one big
party, and I'm the party host,'' Jericho adds. ``It's up to me to
make sure that people have a good time. I'll always do my best to
make sure that happens, and I'll do whatever it takes to get a
reaction from the people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to make sure that they leave the arena thinking, `I had
a good time, and Chris Jericho was tremendous tonight.''' &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; STAR POWER &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The WWF has a starmaking machine that rivals old-time Hollywood
at its peak. Sure, The Rock and Stone Cold Steve Austin may be the
top draws, but they're only two of the organization's numerous
stars.
</P>
<P>
   To understand that, simply watch a telecast or attend an event
to see how the crowd reacts when Too Cool starts dancing or when
the entrance music is played for Edge and Christian.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unquestionably, nobody builds a star better than the WWF,''
Dwayne Johnson says.
</P>
<P>
   He should know, because as The Rock he has become one of the
most popular wrestlers ever. He hosted ``Saturday Night Live'' in
March, his book ``The Rock Says'' (Regan Books, 2000) went to No. 1
on the New York Times best-seller list and he recently finished
shooting a role as the Scorpion King in ``The Mummy 2.''
</P>
<P>
   He insists, however, that his success is based less on his
personal appeal than on the WWF's canny shaping of its product to
win over mass audiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm surrounded by phenomenally gifted athletes and extremely
creative writers,'' Johnson says. ``The WWF is a team effort _ we
all work together in terms of helping each other and complementing
each other's styles.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of ingredients for our recipe for success
here.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Kevin Snow is the sports editor for TV Guide Canada, based in
North York, Ontario.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on the World Wrestling Federation,
consult the official Web site at www.wwf.com. And don't forget to
visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-00 1010EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
