<DOCNO> NYT20000515.0058 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 10:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5322 &Cx1f; tab-z
w a BC-JOHN-WOO-DIRECTS-MISS     05-15 1259
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOHN-WOO-DIRECTS-MISSION-IMPOSSIBLE-2-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEXT TO `IMPOSSIBLE': JOHN WOO TACKLES `MISSION: IMPOSSIBLE 2' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of John Woo directing Tom Cruise in a scene
from ``Mission: Impossible 2.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    Thousands of fans may devour John Woo's movies again and again,
savoring the Hong Kong action auteur's every film virtually frame
by frame.
 &HT;    But Woo himself isn't one of them.
 &HT;    ``I never like to watch my movies twice,'' says Woo, who
achieved cult-legend status with his blood-drenched epics ``The
Killer'' (1989) and ``Hard-Boiled'' (1992) before scoring in
America with ``Broken Arrow'' (1996) and ``Face/Off'' (1997).
``I've done it. I put it on the side and go to another thing _ I
just want to keep moving on.
 &HT;    ``My friends will ask me about a line: `In ``The Killer,'' there
was a line that blah-blah-blah. It was very interesting.' I'll say,
`Yes. But I don't remember.'
 &HT;    ``Sometimes I watch television and I'll switch channels,'' Woo
adds. ``I'll see a shot of a helicopter blowing up and think, `That
looks pretty nice.' I'll watch a little longer, and `Oh, that's my
movie. ``Broken Arrow.'' Ah. Oh, yeah.'
 &HT;    ``Even my favorite movies _ `The Killer' and `Face/Off' _ I can
only watch one or two times.''
 &HT;    Woo's latest film treads familiar ground, picking up where Brian
De Palma left off with ``Mission: Impossible'' (1996). It's Woo who
puts Tom Cruise through his paces in the May 24 sequel, however, so
it won't feel entirely the same.
 &HT;    ``Mission: Impossible 2'' follows superspy Ethan Hunt (Cruise)
as he embarks on a fresh assignment, one which involves teaming up
with a sassy thief (Thandie Newton) and his support team _ among
them returning player Ving Rhames _ to thwart a nefarious plot of a
former colleague (Dougray Scott).
 &HT;    ``When Tom asked me to do `Mission: Impossible 2' I was very
surprised,'' Woo says, relaxing on a couch at the Four Seasons
hotel in Los Angeles. ``I told him I was very interested in working
with him, because I like him and respect him as an actor and a
filmmaker.
 &HT;    ``But the one condition I had was that the movie had to be all
about character, all about humanity,'' he says. ``My kind of movie
is always about character, and I told him that, frankly, I didn't
like the first `Mission: Impossible' _ the story confused me and it
was a little too cold.''
 &HT;    The director is an easygoing sort and, though his English
sometimes falters, he gets his point across.
 &HT;    ``I also told him that I don't like to make high-tech or sci-fi
movies,'' Woo says, ``because I'm not good at them. I like to watch
them, but I don't know how to make them. So I said, `If the film is
all about people being human, I'd love to do it.' That's what Tom
wanted, too.''
 &HT;    Which is a good thing, because Cruise is not only one of the top
stars on the planet, but also the producer of ``Mission: Impossible
2.'' Still, Woo says, he never fretted about the risk of losing
control of his film in midstream.
 &HT;    ``I knew Tom respected me a lot,'' he says. ``He wanted to work
with me for a reason. He liked my style, and he wanted me to keep
my style.
 &HT;    ``I never worried about power,'' Woo adds. ``It wasn't in my
mind that Tom was a big star. I knew he was a big star, but when we
talked and worked together, we were like friends. I just wanted to
create a story, make my hero look special and have all the other
characters look perfect.''
 &HT;    ``Mission: Impossible 2,'' Woo devotees will be pleased to
learn, incorporates all of the director's usual stylistic
flourishes.
 &HT;    ``The slow motion, the guy firing two guns, the doves _ I like
the imagery,'' he says. ``In `Mission: Impossible 2' you see a dove
after a door blows off. Tom walks by the door and a white dove
flies across the frame, leading him out.
 &HT;    ``The idea came up on the set,'' the director says. ``I wanted
to use a dove to represent Ethan Hunt _ Ethan is as charming and
pure as a dove. I just wanted to give the character a little more
spirituality and have it be poetic.''
 &HT;    There's a fine line between unifying personal imagery and having
his movies seem like retreads of his earlier work, but Woo doesn't
seem concerned.
 &HT;    ``I don't worry about repeating myself,'' he says. ``I just
shoot the things I like.
 &HT;    ``When I met Tom, he wanted to do something very challenging,''
the director says. ``He told me he'd never fired a gun in his
movies. He also told me how much he liked Bruce Lee. I thought,
`OK, great.' That gave me a lot of inspiration on how to design
great action for Tom. And he did almost every stunt himself.
 &HT;    ``So I don't worry about repeating myself,'' Woo concludes. ``I
just try to use the imagery in a new way.''
 &HT;    Next up is ``Wind Talkers,'' a World War II drama that will
reunite him with ``Face/Off'' star Nicolas Cage. The film concerns
the relationship between two Marines, one white and the other a
Native American.
 &HT;    ``It's based on a true event,'' Woo says excitedly. ``During the
war the Marines used the Navajo language as a code, and the
Japanese couldn't get it.
 &HT;    ``The story is about these men who don't understand each other,
but get to know each other and work together,'' he adds. ``It's a
story about friendship and honor. I'm so glad to be working with
Nic again, and we're about to start the rest of the casting.''
 &HT;    If code-breakers getting to know each other doesn't sound much
like the high-kicking action epics which made Woo famous, well,
that's the whole point. The director, now an American citizen who
resides with his family in Los Angeles, is living his dream and
making the films he wants to make.
 &HT;    ``I still want to do a musical,'' he says. ``I also want to do a
Western. I'd love to do a musical like `Singing in the Rain'
(1952). `West Side Story' (1961) is one of my favorite musicals of
all time.
 &HT;    ``I'm crazy about Westerns, about John Wayne and John Ford, and
Sergio Leone films _ I just want to make one,'' Woo says. ``Another
thing I want to do is make a movie like `Lawrence of Arabia'
(1962), a big epic. That's one of my biggest dreams.
 &HT;    ``There's a lot I want to do,'' he concludes, ``and one of the
great things about being in America is that I'm getting the
chance.''
 c.2000 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
