<DOCNO> NYT20000515.0067 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 10:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5367 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-MONEY-TRAUSCH-BOS &LR;      05-15 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEY-TRAUSCH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROYAL FASCINATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN TRAUSCH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; A tiara exhibit is ridiculous. It is also stunningly
irresistible, which explains the crowds filing into the darkened
room full of jeweled head pieces at the Museum of Fine Arts in
Boston since March 1.
</P>
<P>
   People laugh, sure. They make smart remarks: ``Wouldn't wear
that to the grocery store.'' Or ``Not with tennis shoes. I don't
think so.'' Or the all-encompassing, ``UnbeLIEVable.''
</P>
<P>
   They stand in jeans, sweatshirts and modern sensibilities,
feeling superior at first because, after all, they are Americans,
surrounded by the twinkling grandeur of mostly dead or irrelevant
European and Russian aristocracies. They are enlightened voyeurs
peering into the avaricious past and the raging ego of Napoleon,
who wanted the ladies of his court to dazzle the world with their
diamonds even as he made it tremble with his military might.
</P>
<P>
   Look at poor Empress Marie Louise, posing for her portrait with
that load of rocks pressing into her forehead. Even the names of
the stones sound heavy _ the diamond of the King of Sardinia, the
Mazarin VIII, the Grand Mazarin, the Fleur de Pecher.
</P>
<P>
   Who could wear a Valkyrie Wing Tiara with a straight face, even
if Wagner nights at the Paris and London operas demanded it? And
those intricately designed pieces crafted into garlands, wheat
shafts, autumn leaves _ and an owl, yet, gripping a branch with its
claws, wings spread wide, surely got somebody giggling at the
party, especially after a few glasses of bubbly.
</P>
<P>
   And yet a person lingers, face reflected in the glass, wondering
how the thing would look, how the Londonderry Tiara's 1,141
diamonds would feel, all in one place, above the eyebrows, or
simply held in the hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you are wearing important jewelry it gives you the
feeling that you can go out and conquer the world,'' says exhibit
curator Diana Scarisbrick, a British art historian who specializes
in jewelry.
</P>
<P>
   She wrote hundreds of letters to private collectors, museums,
and jewelry houses to bring the 80 pieces to Boston. Her inquiries
got some stiff responses: ``Send my mother's tiara to Boston! Are
you mad?''
</P>
<P>
   We are still a rambunctious colony in some minds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tiara symbolizes royalty, grandeur, rank. It has nothing
to do with today's casual attitudes. It's amazing to me that the
people of Boston are so fascinated with the exhibit,'' says
Scarisbrick.
</P>
<P>
   More than 80,000 people have visited ``Crowning Glories,'' which
will be up until June 25 and will not go on tour. The allure is not
only the jewels but the prestige. Bostonians, and most Americans,
are fascinated with royalty _ maybe because they were once subjects
of the crown, or maybe just because they are human beings, ever
curious about their presumed ``betters.''
</P>
<P>
   The cluster of viewers is thick around a garland-style tiara
similar to the one Princess Diana wore when she married Prince
Charles. There is no photograph of her. This is not her tiara. Her
name printed on a card is enough to draw a crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Princess Grace is another magnet, and so is Rose Kennedy, who
borrowed a tiara from the Countess of Bessborough when the Kennedys
were presented at court in 1938. Political and Hollywood royalty
still rule here.
</P>
<P>
   Over in the museum gift shop the imitation tiaras sell briskly
for as little as $8. Young girls and their mothers plunk them on
their heads, looking like fairy princesses at a Halloween ball.
Shop clerks wear them, too. It's as if they had all received those
coveted invitations of long ago, embossed with the directive:
``Tiaras will be worn.''
</P>
<P>
   The shop is full of modern-day status symbols _ bracelets,
including one priced at $7,000; pendants, earrings, plates, tea
kettles, and scarves designed to tell the world that the owner has
class.
</P>
<P>
   There's no shortage of avarice and ego in America 2000. Perhaps
some future exhibit will display it _ Rolex watches, Armani suits,
Italian leather, Porsches and BMWs, gold bathroom fixtures,
silk-threaded wallpaper, designer coffee, and imported truffles.
Viewers might laugh, too, and make a few condescending cracks about
what past generations held dear. Diamond ankle bracelets, Gucci
bags, and granite kitchen counter tops _ UnbeLIEVable.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Susan Trausch is a member of the Globe staff. She can be reached
by e-mail at trausch(at)globe.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
