<HEADLINE>
LEGEND SIDES WITH SUSPECTS IN ESTONIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN WHITMORE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLINN, Estonia _ To the police, the Voitka brothers are pretty
much run-of-the-mill robbery suspects. But for much of the public
and some media here, the two siblings have become folk heroes.
</P>
<P>
   Aivar and Ulo Voitka had evaded the law for 15 years, by hiding
in Estonia's thick, dark forests. Police arrested them in February,
after a six-hour siege at a deserted farmhouse.
</P>
<P>
   The Voitkas, who are awaiting trial, have captured the public
imagination. Many here associate them with Estonia's ``Forest
Brothers,'' partisans who in the 1940s escaped to the forest to
fight Josef Stalin's occupying Red Army.
</P>
<P>
   Like the real Forest Brothers, the Voitka brothers originally
went underground to resist the Soviet authorities, who ruled
Estonia until 1991. They took refuge in the forest in 1986, when
they were teenagers, to avoid being drafted into the hated Soviet
Army.
</P>
<P>
   But Aivar, now 32, and Ulo, 31, stayed in the woods long after
the Soviet Union broke up in 1991, and Estonia regained its
independence.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the two have been wanted by Estonia's police in
connection with a series of store robberies.
</P>
<P>
   Before and after their capture, the press took up the fugitives'
cause, and they became almost mythical figures.
</P>
<P>
   One rock band recently released an album titled ``The Voitka
Brothers' Forest Songs,'' singing the praises of the two men. And
one bakery said it plans to market a special bread honoring the
brothers, with their faces on the label.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has become like the legend of Jesse James in America,''
said Mart Laar, Estonia's prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to running Estonia's government, Laar, 40, is
considered one of the country's foremost experts on the Forest
Brothers. A historian, Laar has written a book about the
anti-Soviet resistance movement titled ``The War in the Woods.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Red Army occupied Estonia, along with Latvia and
Lithuania, in the 1940s, tens of thousands of people fled to the
dense forests to resist.
</P>
<P>
   Some were escaping arrest and deportation. Others formed an
organized armed resistance movement and engaged the Russians in
battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Forest Brothers considered it their duty to uphold the
nation's spirit of resistance while demoralizing and intimidating
the Soviet authorities,'' Laar wrote.
</P>
<P>
   They blew up newly erected Soviet monuments. And, in defiance of
a Soviet ban on Estonian national symbols, they flew the country's
blue, black, and white flag from tall trees and buildings.
</P>
<P>
   They also ambushed army patrols, wrecked power lines, and
assassinated local Communist Party leaders. Moscow, meanwhile waged
a war to wipe out the guerrillas, a conflict that historians
estimate claimed about 50,000 lives.
</P>
<P>
   And although Soviet forces by the early 1950s had neutralized
the resistance, the last Estonian forest brother was not captured
until 1978, eight years before the Voitka brothers took refuge in
the forest.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Brian Whitmore is a Globe correspondent based in Moscow.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
