<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUPLE SHOULD BE IN FINE SHAPE FOR RETIREMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. We do not plan to add money to the taxable accounts, but will
reinvest all dividends until 2011. We will each add $2,000 a year
to the IRA accounts, and add $35,000 a year to the 401(k) plan.
What is the likelihood of reaching our income goal by 2011, and
continuing that income stream at an inflation-adjusted level in the
years beyond that? Are we aiming too high? Would you change the
portfolio mix? We have no heirs to preserve capital for.
</P>
<P>
   J.J., Sharon, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I think you should be in excellent shape. If your overall
portfolio produces average annual returns of 9 percent for the next
11 years, and if you add $7,500 a year to your tax-deferred
savings, you will accumulate $1,168,209.
</P>
<P>
   If your plan is to build the fixed-income side of your portfolio
to provide your $40,000 income, you would need $615,000 in that
account, leaving you with a little more than $550,000 which you
could leave in stock investments to protect yourself from future
inflation. Especially since you will have that $10,000 annual
pension income coming in after five years of retirement.
</P>
<P>
   The main question I have is whether you have thought about the
inflation which is likely to come between now and the time you
retire. If inflation averages 3.5 percent, by the year 2011, it
will take $58,398 to buy what $40,000 buys today. Thus you would
need a fixed-income portfolio of a little less than $900,000 to
supply the desired income stream. Both that calculation and the
preceding one presumes a 6.5 percent yield from the fixed-income
holdings. That would not be as comfortable, cutting your stock
portfolio to a little more than $268,000. But again, given the
effective raise you will get when the pensions begin, you should be
in good shape.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My mother, a long-time widow and retired school teacher, has
asked me for investment advice. She has handled her own affairs and
done quite well but is now 87 and feels a change may be needed. She
has income of $51,088 from sources other than her investments, owns
her own home and lives simply. She has an arrangement where she is
guaranteed entry in a retirement center at any time she might chose
to do so. I am concerned she is getting too much income and thus is
paying too much income tax. I am thinking she should move money to
stocks or stock funds that will increase in value but not provide
much income. What do you suggest?
</P>
<P>
   A. P., Austin, Texas &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. You're in a sort of ticklish situation is what I think. Yes,
its true your mother certainly has a lot more of her assets in
bonds and other fixed-income holdings than she needs to have, since
she has other sources which fully cover her income needs.
</P>
<P>
   But there are more reasons than an income stream for holding
bonds, and one of them is that over the long term they are safer
than stocks. They suffer jolting reverses when interest rates rise,
but they tend to recover once interest rates reverse, and they
inevitably do. So while this portfolio is similar to that of many
people your mother's age, it seems likely to me that this was
designed as it has been as a means of holding down risk rather than
providing an income stream.
</P>
<P>
   The first thing that you must do in advising your mother is to
make sure that you do not suggest moves which will make her
uncomfortable. My mother is the same age as yours _ and she can
remember the stock market crash of 1929 and the Great Depression
that followed quite vividly. So she might not be comfortable with
the moves you are suggesting.
</P>
<P>
   The second point that I would make is delicate. Presumably you
will at some point be an heir to her estate. People inheriting
stock enjoy the step-up rule when it comes to the base cost of the
stocks inherited. It seems to me that if you suggest moving large
portions of the portfolio to stocks that you may be open to an
accusation of supplying self-serving advice.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, I suggest that you have your mother seek out a
financial adviser or an attorney who would, on a purely fee basis,
establish a strategy for handling her investments. Once the
strategy is clearly established and the market allocations set down
in writing, you could again step into the picture to carry out the
specifics of the broad plan that she has outlined. The cost of
obtaining such advice should not be high relative to the total
portfolio, and the peace of mind it should afford both of you would
probably be great. And don't be surprised if you find out that the
portfolio is the way it is because thats the way she wants it.
Portfolios rarely obtain their character by accident.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am looking for a safe investment for the money I recently
received from the sale of my home. I am in a retirement home which
costs $2,250 a month. I get $1,100 a month from Social Security,
and will need to draw $3,000 a month from my savings. Will my money
see me through? I have no debts.
</P>
<P>
   D.W., San Marcos, Calif. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I think you should be in good shape if you put the proceeds
from your home sale in more CDs _ although you should shop for the
CDs carefully. Entering this week the nation's highest rate for a
five-year CD of $100,000 or more was 7.72 percent. The highest rate
for CDs under $100,000 was 7.70 percent. In contrast, the national
average rate for five-year CDs of $100,000 or more was 6.28
percent, and the under $100,000 was 6.01 percent.
</P>
<P>
   To assure your CD savings will be fully insured by the FDIC, I
suggest you go with a $100,000 CD at one institution, and a $56,000
CD at a different institution.
</P>
<P>
   Will your money last you out? It should. If you achieved a
portfolio average of 6.5 percent, you could withdraw at a rate of
$3,000 a month for more than 20 years before depleting the savings
pool.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Hooker can be reached at The Boston Globe, P.O. Box
2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
