<HEADLINE>
CONDO OWNERS FRONT-LOAD AND CENTER IN STUDY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Includes Neptune facts box text table.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MOHL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Peg Fuller has hit the wash-and-wear jackpot.
</P>
<P>
   She and every other condominium owner at Summit Terrace in
Reading, Mass. are going to get new, high-tech, front-loading
washers and dryers worth about $2,000 from Maytag in return for
participating in a US Department of Energy water and energy
conservation study this summer.
</P>
<P>
   It's the sort of real-life test the government and manufacturers
should do more often. Not only will it show whether so-called
front-loading washers live up to their promise, but it should help
consumers decide whether spending two to four times more for a
washer and dryer will really pay off down the road in energy and
water savings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to show there are two price tags for an
appliance,'' said Dan Reicher, the assistant secretary of energy.
``There's what you pay at the store and there's what you pay to
operate it. And what you pay to operate it is far, far greater.''
</P>
<P>
   He's right. But it's often hard to look 10 years down the road
when you're spending $2,000 right now. ``That's a lot of money,''
Fuller said. ``At my age'' _ 68 _ ``it would outlast me. For a
family with children, it might be worth the expense.''
</P>
<P>
   The Maytag Neptune washer that's at the heart of the Reading
experiment borrows heavily from front-loading technology that's
been around for years in Europe but is only slowly gaining
acceptance here. Front-loading washers are everywhere in Europe but
represent only about 3.5 percent of the US market.
</P>
<P>
   Front-loading washers look much like dryers, but instead of a
tumble-dry system they use a tumble-wash system. The system
requires less than two-thirds of the water needed in a top-loading
washer and, because there's less water, less energy is needed to
heat the water.
</P>
<P>
   The absence of the agitator that's found in the center of
top-loading washers also has benefits. Clothes don't get pummeled
and tend to last longer. And the spin cycle can run at 1,000
revolutions per minute rather than 500, which means more water is
wrung out and drying time is shortened. On paper, at least, the
only negatives with front-loaders is that it's hard to let clothes
soak and difficult to throw a sock in once the wash cycle has
started.
</P>
<P>
   Maytag and the DOE ran their first test of front-loading washers
in the rural town of Bern, Kansas, in 1997. The water and energy
usage of 100 residents was tracked before and after new Maytag
front-loaders were installed. The results: water savings of 38
percent and energy savings of 56 percent. Officials estimated if 20
percent of US households used those washers, the country would save
26 billion gallons of drinking water a year and enough energy to
heat 800,000 homes.
</P>
<P>
   Lynette Strathman, one of the lucky residents of Bern
(population 200), said she was skeptical that her family's dirty
clothes would get clean using half as much water. She has three
sons and a husband who is a welder.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it really does work,'' she said, adding that clothes come
out of the washer's spin cycle almost dry. She said she has
persuaded her aunt and other friends to buy Neptunes, despite their
high price. ``They pay for themselves,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Like Bern, Reading has a problem with water. The typical Reading
family pays a water and sewer bill of $1,045 a year, the
fifth-highest among communities served by the Massachusetts Water
Resources Authority and four times the national average.
</P>
<P>
   DOE officials plan to start tracking the current water and
energy usage of the 66 condo owners in June. In August, Fuller's
14-year-old Maytag washer and dryer (never serviced once, she
notes) will be given to charity and replaced with Maytag's Neptune
Navigator washer and dryer. Two months later we'll know how much
energy and water they save.
</P>
<P>
   Maytag, based in Newton, Iowa, started making its Neptune line
of front-loading washers in 1997. It has sold close to a million of
them by now, but that's still a tiny fraction of the market. Maytag
officials aren't complaining. The company reportedly makes enormous
profit margins on the Neptunes, four to five times what it does on
its regular washers and dryers.
</P>
<P>
   The souped-up Navigators that Fuller and her fellow condo owners
in Reading will get aren't even on the market yet, although Fuller
said officials told her they will retail later this summer for
about $2,000. That's up about $500 from the current Neptune
washer-dryer price.
</P>
<P>
   For people like me (I've ruined so many clothes my wife won't
let me near the family wash), the Navigator seems great. It's so
big you can wash eight king-size sheets at once, you can customize
washing cycles for individual family members, and there's a ``stain
brain'' that tells you what type of wash cycle works best for the
55 most common stains.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the new bells and whistles are not likely to
increase the energy and water savings. The Navigator washer uses
the same amount of water and spins faster (1,000 rpms vs. 800) than
the old Neptune, but energy savings probably won't increase because
the new Navigator has an on-board heater to make sure the water
reaches the proper temperature. Apparently, hot water heaters can't
be trusted, but that's another story.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fleet credit card fees
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FleetBoston Financial Corp. is imposing a $35 annual credit card
fee on customers who use their cards infrequently or not at all.
</P>
<P>
   For a moment it looked like FleetBoston was trying to slap fees
on customers who pay off their balances each month, but after some
initial bobbing and weaving Fleet officials insisted they are
merely trying to cover their costs in dealing with customers who
make few transactions with their cards.
</P>
<P>
   Citing rising interest rates, Fleet recently hiked the fixed
rates of many of its cardholders an average of 2.5 percentage
points. Several customers called me afterward to say they were
being allowed to keep their fixed rate but would have to pay a $35
annual fee.
</P>
<P>
   ``They aren't making any money on me. That's why they imposed
the annual fee on me,'' said Marianne Stephenson of Danvers, who
said she hasn't used the Fleet card much and never carries a
balance. Stephenson said she immediately canceled her card.
</P>
<P>
   Banks in the late 1990s tried to impose annual fees on customers
who didn't carry a balance and didn't incur interest charges, but
Joseph Saunders, chief executive of FleetBoston's credit card
business, said that isn't the case here.
</P>
<P>
   He said FleetBoston can make a decent profit on customers who
don't carry a balance as long as they use their card to make a
healthy number of transactions. But he said the bank loses money on
customers who just keep the card as a backup or rarely use it. The
new annual fee is meant to cover the bank's costs in dealing with
those customers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MediaOne expands bundling
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Trying to corral more of its customers' dollars, MediaOne this
week begins packaging basic levels of digital cable television,
local phone service, and high-speed Internet access for $100 a
month.
</P>
<P>
   That's a savings of nearly $27 a month over the standalone
prices of each service. Or you can look at it as getting free local
phone service if you buy all three. You can knock another $10 off
the package price if you buy your own cable modem.
</P>
<P>
   But keep in mind the price will go up if you want more than
basic service. For example, a calling area beyond your home town
and adjacent communities will cost more _ $12.95 extra for
metropolitan service and $22.95 extra for unlimited calling in all
four Eastern Massachusetts area codes. If you want more than the
175 channels included with digital cable, you also have to pay
extra.
</P>
<P>
   Bundling is likely to expand even more in the future as AT&AMP;T
completes its acquisition of MediaOne and adds long-distance phone,
wireless, and other services to the mix.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Mohl is a member of the Globe staff. He can be reached at
617-474-2510, by e-mail at mohl(at)globe.com, or at The Boston
Globe, P.O. Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
FRONT-LOADER FACTS &QL; 
 &QL; 
Maytag's Neptune line of front-loader washers cost $1,000 and up
but offer significant savings on water and energy and reportedly
clean clothes better. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Water - A load of laundry requires 23 gallons of water, as opposed
to 40 gallons with a top-loading washer. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Energy - Because less water is used, there is less water to heat.
The spin cycle of 800 revolutions per minute (1,000 rpms in the new
Neptune Navigator) also wrings more water out of clothes and saves
on drying time. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Cleaning - Agitators in top-loading washers increase wear and tear
on clothes. In front-loaders, clothes are tumble washed much like a
dryer. Maytag says the system extends the life of clothes, results
in less bunching and removes stains better. &QL; 
 &QL; 
High-tech - The new Neptune Navigator comes with on-board heater to
insure accurate water temperatures, offers tips on how best to
remove up to 55 stains and allows users to customize 24 different
wash cycles. &QL; 
 &QL; 
SOURCE: Maytag, Department of Energy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-00 1104EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
