<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000515.0071 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 11:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5372 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-POPE-SUCCESSOR-2ND &LR;  &UR; T     05-15 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPE-SUCCESSOR-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... of creation.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   --Healthy. The cardinals were shocked when Albino Luciani, who
in 1978 became Pope John Paul I, died after just 33 days in office.
The papacy is an increasingly taxing job, and the cardinals are
expected to demand a certain level of vigor.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Ciro Benedettini, a Vatican spokesman, said it would be
inappropriate to comment on the topic of papal succession while
there is still an active pope in the chair of St. Peter. But
experts in Italy and the United States interviewed for this story
generally agreed that the world's cardinals, in their own unique
way, are already politicking, trying to demonstrate to one another
their intellectual heft, knowledge of world affairs, and an ability
to communicate through public appearances.
</P>
<P>
   The two candidates most often mentioned as possible successors
are Cardinal Francis Arinze of Nigeria, the president of the
pontifical council for interreligious dialogue, and Cardinal Carlo
Maria Martini of Italy, the archbishop of Milan.
</P>
<P>
   Arinze would be the first black pope in modern times; there is
some debate over the race of Gelasius I, an African who was pope
from 492 to 496. Although he is from Africa, he is also a Vatican
insider. He would be a powerful choice symbolically, not only
because he is black but also because he is from the southern
hemisphere, but at age 67, he may be too young.
</P>
<P>
   Martini would be the first Jesuit pope, making him a favorite of
many American Catholic intellectuals, and he is a highly regarded,
frequently published scholar of scripture and spirituality.
However, he is viewed as too liberal by some.
</P>
<P>
   Other oft-mentioned candidates include Cardinal Lucas Moreira
Neves of Brazil, another Vatican insider from the southern
hemisphere, but a man who is in ill health; Cardinal Dionigi
Tettamanzi of Genoa, who, at age 65, is considered young but is
popular among cardinals and considered a possible compromise
candidate, Cardinal Achille Silvestrini, a moderate who is prefect
of the Vatican's Congregation for Oriental Churches.
</P>
<P>
   However, it is possible the next pope is not even a cardinal yet
_ Giacomo della Chiesa had been a cardinal for just four months
when he was elected Pope Benedict XV in 1914.
</P>
<P>
   It is impossible to weigh what to look for from the next pope
without considering the strengths and weaknesses of the current
pope. Numerous scholars said John Paul II will be remembered for
his successes at outreach to other religions and to the farthest
geographic corners of the church, but also for his intolerance of
liberal thinking and dissent within the church.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the world he's been a marvelous pope, but for the church
his legacy is going to be more problematic, because there's a good
deal of division now within the Catholic community,'' said Thomas
Groome, a Boston College theologian. ``The cardinals are astute
observers of the mood of the church, and I don't think we're going
to get a right-wing ideologue. Their own love for the church and
the tradition would signal that we need somebody who can sweep a
broad swath of inclusion down the mainstream of Catholicism.''
</P>
<P>
   In coming years, scholars say, the shortage of priests will
force a debate about priestly celibacy and the ordination of women,
although change on either front is unlikely soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``A number of aspects to this pope's pontificate have to be
continued, such as outreach to other religions and other
Christians, concern about the Third World, and outreach to the
poor,'' McBrien said. ``But the more challenging things will be
internal: how to restore a greater sense of unity, raise the morale
of those committed to working for the church on a full-time basis .
. . and limit the powers of the Roman curia. The ancient title of
pontiff means supreme bridge maker, and the pope has to be someone
who tries to reach out to all sides.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Michael Paulson reported from Boston and Jeff Israely from Rome.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
