<DOCNO> NYT20000515.0076 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 11:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5382 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-R-CATHOLIC-BISHOPS-RE     05-15 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-CATHOLIC-BISHOPS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTHING SUCCEEDS LIKE CONTROLLING SUCCESSION 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (The Week in Review)  
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last week, Roman Catholics in New York began to take the measure
of their next archbishop, Edward M. Egan, who has been bishop of
Bridgeport, Conn., for more than a decade. At a press conference
Thursday, hours after the Vatican announced the appointment, the
archbishop-designate showed himself to be multilingual, answering
questions in English, Italian and Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   Egan comes to his new post with a reputation as an effective
administrator and fund-raiser. But another way to view the bishop's
selection is from the perspective of the appointments made by Pope
John Paul II. Simply put, the pontiff has reshaped the U.S. church
hierarchy as perhaps none of his predecessors has. He has filled
vacancy after vacancy with men who share his own vision of how the
church should be run _ and not just in the United States, but in
other parts of the world as well.''
</P>
<P>
   The process has been gradual, but its effect has been profound.
John Paul, moreover, has begun a second round of appointments,
selecting prelates to succeed bishops he himself once appointed.
</P>
<P>
   By 1989, in his 11th year as pope, John Paul had chosen leaders
for the archdioceses of Baltimore, Boston, Chicago, Detroit, Los
Angeles, New York, Philadelphia and Washington; these archbishops
traditionally become cardinals. In the 11 years since, he has
repeated the process, with Cardinal Adam Maida in Detroit
succeeding Cardinal Edmund Szoka, who was chosen in 1981; Cardinal
Francis George in Chicago replacing the late Cardinal Joseph
Bernardin, appointed in 1982; and now Egan in New York succeeding
the late Cardinal John O'Connor, appointed in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   John Paul may go on to select new archbishops for Philadelphia
and Washington, to succeed Cardinal Anthony Bevilacqua, who was
appointed in 1988, and Cardinal James Hickey, a 1980 appointment.
Both men are long past the official church retirement age of 75.
The pope has also named new archbishops for major sees like
Atlanta, Denver, St. Louis and many others.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the number of appointments, the Rev. David M.
O'Connell, president of the Catholic University of America, in
Washington, said John Paul II has ``had the most influence of any
pope in modern times.''
</P>
<P>
   Longevity has helped. Elected in 1978 at a relatively youthful
58, John Paul II, who turns 80 on Thursday, has reigned longer than
any other 20th-century pope _ longer than all but six of his 261
predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   But more than simply benefiting from a long life, John Paul II
has demonstrated that he knows which characteristics he wants in
the men in the front ranks.
</P>
<P>
   Taken individually, the current crop of U.S. cardinals are known
for various strengths. Chicago's George, for example, is highly
regarded as an intellectual; Cardinal William Keeler in Baltimore
is considered a leader in ecumenical relations.
</P>
<P>
   But the cardinals share important, basic qualities. They are
``doctrinally steadfast,'' thoroughly loyal to the Vatican, said
Chester Gillis, associate professor of theology and Catholic
studies at Georgetown University in Washington. ``I think there's a
premium put on obedience to Rome, particularly for cardinals,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   In short, they are not inclined to innovation. In 1980, the pope
warned some of the Latin American bishops against embracing
political ideas arising from liberation theology, which states a
preference for the poor. Speaking in Mexico that year, he said
church leaders must safeguard ``the purity of doctrine.''
</P>
<P>
   These days the U.S. bishops are more cautious than they were 15
years ago, when the National Conference of Catholic Bishops engaged
in sweeping pastoral letters on such broad and highly charged
topics as war and peace, and American capitalism.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see no moves by the bishops to write a major pastoral
letter,'' said the Rev. Thomas Reese, editor of the Jesuit magazine
America, who is an authority on the bishops' conference. ``They
passed Ex Corde Ecclesia the way the Vatican wanted it,'' he said,
referring to a long-discussed document on the relationship between
Catholic colleges and the church hierarchy, adopted by the bishops
last November. It contained a controversial provision that will
require theologians to obtain a mandate from their local bishop
certifying that what they are teaching is fully within church
doctrine. ``The new generation of bishops,'' Reese said, ``is not
going to argue with the Vatican on these issues.''
</P>
<P>
   That new generation will be leading the church for some years.
(It is a group of prelates that in the United States remains
overwhelmingly white, even as recent immigration has made the
people in the pews more ethnically diverse, a change that will take
some time to make itself more apparent in the hierarchy.)
</P>
<P>
   Reese, who studies appointments to the College of Cardinals in
Rome, said that more than 90 percent of its voting members _ the
prelates under age 80 _ owe their status to John Paul II. The
120-member body will select his successor.
</P>
<P>
   ``His influence will not end with his death,'' Gillis said.
``His influence will go on for a number of years after his
papacy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-00 1115EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
