<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   HAMILTON-JORDAN _ Twenty years ago, Hamilton Jordan was the
gatekeeper who controlled access to the most powerful man in the
country, a brash newcomer to Washington who moonlighted as
Georgetown's most notorious pubcrawler. Today, former President
Carter's chief-of-staff has no power than any other Little League
assistant coach. Between one life and another, he went through a
divorce, has survived cancer three times, run for the U.S. Senate
and lost, and gone from a thirtyish Beltway climber to a sedate
middle-aged Buckhead father of three young children. In his book
``No Such Thing As a Bad Day,'' Jordan reflects on the bumps in the
road and what he's learned in a life out of the public eye. We
profile Jordan at 55, a political has-been who believes he's never
been more alive. (Skube, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 45.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Jordan kicks off a round of local book-signings this week.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE-MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   HEARING-AIDS _ What's that you say? Disposable hearing aids?
Yes, they last 30 days and are surprisingly affordable. The hearing
aids will be rolled out over the next two weeks, and are aimed at
boomers with their compact style. Because of the disposable
batteries, the microphone can be much larger and the batteries much
smaller, so you get a more powerful hearing aid in a tiny size.
(Lore, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 20. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT-ARTS
</P>
