<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 11:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5388 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-R-KIDS-POLITICS-REVIE     05-15 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-KIDS-POLITICS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CHILDREN'S HOUR: HUGGING AND KISSING YOUR WAY INTO THE WHITE
HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating)  (The Week in Review)  
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ At first glance, it was hard to say whether the
scene looked more like a television chat show or a ``Saturday Night
Live'' parody. There on a Washington stage last month sat Gov.
George W. Bush, his wife, Laura, and two prominent Republican
officeholders, both women, all in a semicircle and awaiting their
first guest.
</P>
<P>
   On cue, out walked an adorable second-grader with a giant white
bow in her hair, along with one of her teachers. As the women
beamed, Bush asked 7-year-old Elena Douglass, ``How is it here in
the nation's capital? Are you having a good time?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, sir, very,'' she whispered into her hand-held microphone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me too,'' confided Bush, who was using her to showcase his
interest in literacy and foreign language instruction.
</P>
<P>
   Call it the infantilization of politics. Ever since President
Clinton won re-election four years ago with child-centered issues
like school uniforms, literacy and teen-age smoking, candidates
have increasingly behaved as if they are auditioning for the role
of Santa Claus, and not running for public office.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, politicians have always kissed babies. And yes, even in
1988, both George Bush, the father, and Michael Dukakis were vying
to be the education president. But it was Clinton who built a whole
campaign around children, displaying his empathy for working
parents by watching children make model airplanes, or dropping into
a school that requires uniforms, or reading along with towheaded
tykes.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dole, his Republican opponent, once complained, ``You give
President Clinton five minutes on television, he'll mention
children 15 times.''
</P>
<P>
   This time around there are no complaints. Everybody's doing it.
Just try to count how many times over the last year that Bush has
read ``The Very Hungry Caterpillar'' to kindergartners to
demonstrate his commitment to literacy. He said it was his favorite
book from childhood _ no matter that it wasn't published until
1969, a year after he graduated from Yale.
</P>
<P>
   Or how about Al Gore in New Hampshire, where he not only knelt
to read ``Tikvah Means Hope'' to 6-year-old Nikkita Gottling, but
bought her the book and autographed it?
</P>
<P>
   These days, Gore can regularly be found in schools, eating in
the cafeteria or sitting at a student's desk. This habit may even
have raised the level of debate. At one high school, students were
discussing the Plessy vs. Ferguson case of 1896, in which the U.S.
Supreme Court upheld the concept of separate but equal facilities
for blacks and whites.
</P>
<P>
   Voters have put education and the decline of civic and cultural
values at the top of their list of concerns. The boomers have made
raising children an obsession, while more and more women voters are
trying to balance motherhood and work.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you will check out your Jeep Cherokee, you will see the
vanity mirror is on both sides,'' said Alex Castellanos, a
Republican political consultant. ``It's now on the driver's side
and the soccer mom has her hand on the steering wheel. The soccer
mom is 70 percent of consumer spending. Two out of three new
college entrants are women. The economic power has shifted and
she's still the key swing voter in suburban America.''
</P>
<P>
   What better way to play gender politics than by having a child
on your lap? It telegraphs warmth, empathy and understanding.
``Everyone who is running for office has to bend over backward to
show that they know what it's like to be a typical American
family,'' said Rachel Gorlin, a Democratic media consultant.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who wanted a demonstration of the emotional power of an
encounter with a child had only to watch Clinton hug a boy on
crutches at the funeral for Cardinal John O'Connor of New York,
leaving the other dignitaries looking stiff and remote by
comparison. Still, a few lonely voices in both parties deplore the
dumbing down of political dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It atrophies the muscle of political debate,'' says Jeff Faux,
a liberal Democrat at the Economic Institute, a Washington policy
research center, who argues that it all started with Ronald
Reagan's success with political imagery.
</P>
<P>
   William Kristol, the editor of The Weekly Standard, blames
Clinton. ``The kid card is used as a trump and it trumps all
debate,'' he said. ``You say this is good for our kids and that's
the end of it, instead of here are the arguments for and against
the measure.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, Bill Bradley and John McCain, the primary candidates
who ran on ``authenticity'' and ``substance,'' lost.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, politicians are using people as props more than ever.
They hold small panel discussions with people who agree with them,
to highlight some policy proposal. The elderly are paraded for
discussion of Social Security. Nurses stand around listening to
talk of health care.
</P>
<P>
   Most Republicans say they are delighted they have a nominee with
some of Clinton's political skills and an ability to soften their
party's image. ``Unfortunately, politics is about symbols and I
don't even think you can overdo it,'' said David Horowitz, whose
pamphlet ``The Art of Political War'' has been circulating among
House Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Several recent polls have shown Bush in the lead, and making a
strong showing among married women, a swing group that Clinton won
in 1996. So don't be surprised to see Bush and Gore surrounded by
children, reading away like school librarians, right up to
November.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-00 1119EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
