<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A-0516-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer Q&AMP;A
 &HT;    By Jane Greig
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service AUSTIN, Texas _ Q: We have a one-quart
<TEXT>
Thermos bottle with a busted glass liner, (filler No. 24F). Where
we can go to get a replacement?_ Ed M.
<P>
   A: A new liner is available from Thermos by calling (800)
831-9242 ($10.40 includes S &AMP; H). The now-famous vacuum flask was
invented by Sir James Dewar in 1892. A contest was held to devise a
new moniker. A Munich resident won with Thermos from the Greek
``Therme'' meaning hot.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why does bottled water _ Aquafina for example _ carry an
expiration date? What happens to it?
</P>
<P>
   _Marty S.
</P>
<P>
   A: It starts to smell. A spokesperson for Aquafina says the
expiration date is a guideline to the water's best flavor. Since
the plastic container is gas-permeable, it eventually absorbs
environmental odors. So if it was in your pantry next to the onion
bin, it might taste like eau d'onion after a few years. The water
can be consumed safely long after the two-year guideline, and will
stay potable until it is opened.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My back yard is full of snails. Some are bigger than a half
dollar. What kind of snails are they? What do they eat besides my
aloe vera plant?
</P>
<P>
   A: Probably the brown garden snail, Helix aspersa, says
entomology expert John Jackman, of Texas A&AMP;M Extension Service.
They eat almost anything and love humidity. Baits work to control
them, but so does a saucer of beer (they sip then drown). Snails
are hermaphroditic, having both male and female organs, which
explains why frequent mating is possible.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I just returned from an overseas Peace Corps assignment and
brought wood carvings home. Some are inlaid with mother-of-pearl.
How do I care for them?
</P>
<P>
   _J. Jones
</P>
<P>
   A: Less is more when dealing with pieces like yours, advises
Martha Grant from the Objects Conservator. Keep the wood out of
sunlight, dust with a soft brush or cloth without polish. Keep
curious hands off such items as body oils may cause damage.
Constant temperature and humidity forestall contraction and
expansion of the wood. A priceless item? Consider visiting with a
professional. Call the American Institute for Conservation of
Historic and Artistic Work at (202) 452-9545 for local
conservators. Q: We will be taking our grandson on his first
airplane trip this summer. The lady at the ticket counter told us
he would not need a photo ID. However, the tickets are printed
saying you must have a photo ID to board. Does he in fact need
this, and if so, what would you use for a 9-year-old? We will be
flying on American Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jan H.
</P>
<P>
   A: Your grandson won't have any problems. Only fliers 18 and
older are required to show a picture ID for domestic flights,
according to American Airlines. Of course, if you were taking him
abroad, he would need a passport. Consider having a consent for
medical treatment form completed by his parents. Send me a stamped,
self-addressed envelope to receive one.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My wife was beneficiary of a life insurance policy from her
mother, who was an employee of the Ohio school system. The policy
was paid, but income tax was held out and had to be paid. I thought
life insurance was tax free. Is this a new policy of the IRS?
</P>
<P>
   _ Don M.
</P>
<P>
   A: Generally, life insurance benefits are not taxable, but there
are some exceptions, notes Stuart Bradfordof the Internal Revenue
Service. Was the life insurance policy through the Ohio school
system as opposed to one purchased independently from an insurer?
</P>
<P>
   Payments made ``by or for an employer because of an employee's
death'' are counted as income and are therefore taxable. For more
information, call (800) 829-1040. Ask for a copy of ``Your Federal
Income Tax,'' a k a Publication 17.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I had my wife's minivan converted for wheelchair use, and the
by-product was a seat bench that will never fit in the van again.
It's gray fabric, and should fit in any 1998 Chrysler minivan. It's
free to a good home.
</P>
<P>
   _ Fred Cantu
</P>
<P>
   A: Free is just about as good as it gets. If you can use this,
contact Cantu at fredcantu(at)hotmail.com.
</P>
<P>
   UPSHOT/UPDATE/UPROAR:
</P>
<P>
   More than one feline-ophile chastised me for not mentioning the
possibility of a medical condition causing a change in litter-box
use. Any major change in a pet's behavior should routinely trigger
a call or visit to the veterinarian. Stress, however, is often a
contributing factor in such behavioral changes.
</P>
<P>
   Family vacation time is rapidly approaching. Here is a tip from
reader Clark Stevens to help children on long flights. EarPlanes
(adult or children's sizes) moderate the effects of changing
pressure. While not recommended for infants, youngsters and those
with colds may experience relief. Pick up EarPlanes at area
retailers such as Eckerd Drugs and Walgreens, or order by calling
Cirrus Products at (800) EAR-6151.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Jane Greig at P.O. Box 670, Austin, TX 78767; (512)
445-3697; e-mail jgreig(at)statesman.com or fax (512) 445-3968.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
