<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Connectix ready for PC useBy Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE DESKTOP
</P>
<P>
   At one time a Mac-only piece of software thwarted by an
injunction, Connectix not only has had said injunction overturned,
but their Sony Playstation emulation application is now available
for the PC. Virtual Game Station ($30; www.connectix. com; for the
PC and Mac) gives high-end computer users access to some of the
best _ and worst _ Playstation games without owning a console.
Extremely demanding, CVGS is not recommended for low-end computer
owners as it fancies 3-D acceleration hardware and prefers a 400Mhz
processor or a G3 or G4 Mac. With such horsepower, however, the
software is stable and, once installed, instantly recognizes Sony
discs over regular CD-ROMs and launches automatically. Connectix
does not claim to emulate all Sony games and even the ones it does
accommodate won't necessarily run smoothly or accurately, but with
a fair-sized library of perfectly compatible games, CVGS does
``broaden consumer price,'' as it purports to intend, and allows
for Playstationing at work, during a long commute via one's laptop,
or at home when the TV isn't available.
</P>
<P>
   A light, airy, wind-wispy game by nature, Wilco Publishing's
Hangsim ($39; www.wilcopub.com; for the PC) is their first,
stand-alone flight simulator. More renowned for their add-on and
expansion packs to Microsoft's superlative Flight Simulator
franchise, Wilco has found a rarely treaded sim niche in hang
gliding. The gusty/breezy meteorological events and phenomena
represented in Hangsim seem accurate and appropriately daunting at
times; vast, beautiful aerial photography landscapes and the
variety of craft simulated -_ from basic hang glider to
para-gliders to ultralights _ all offer a great lazy game for the
sky pilot in all of us. A few glitches and graphic flaws are
forgivable considering the pace of wild blue yondering, though the
pace itself is sure to turn off many gamers. Nicely added features
such as HUDs, waypoint challenge and competition modes still don't
change the fact that Hangsim is all about blowing in the wind _
without actually stepping outdoors. That's just silly.
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE CONSOLE
</P>
<P>
   A follow up to last year's surprise side-scrolling hit, Tomba 2:
The Evil Swine Return ($40; www.playstation. com; for the
Playstation) revisits the charming pink-haired caveman freak,
Tomba, as he once again sets himself up against a drove of
malevolent swine who have managed to kidnap his girlfriend, Tabby.
Like the original, Tomba 2 offers an engaging mix of seek and
baconize mission quests infused with quirky platform gameplay.
Character charm sets this game above other banal Mario Brothers
clones as it is decidedly lewd, a crassly sassy take on the ``jump
and squash, throw and duck, hop up, hop down, climb swing and
pounce'' genre. Moreover, RPG puzzle-solving elements and a 3-D-ish
feel in an otherwise 2-D environment give Tomba 2 a depth of play _
literal and figurative _ not attained by similar games.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
