</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-GEAR0516-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Add some sizzle to your Sega
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   MadCatz has taken the deficient Sega Dreamcast controller and
corrected its flaws. The Dream Pad ($30; www.madcatz.com) has six
excellently placed, fully programmable buttons as opposed to the
scant four on Sega's default controller. It's also wide and
comfortable enough for adult-sized hands with two effective analog
shoulder triggers, a smooth analog thumbstick and a ``floating''
D-pad. The stylish, ergonomic Dream Pad also utilizes anti-slip
rubber gripper padding that keeps the controller comfortably in the
gamer's hands. In fact, Madcatz Dream Pad is superior in nearly
every way _ almost flawless, save for one nagging fault: The
controller programming button sits right where you're likely to
rest your thumb if you aren't pressing any of the action buttons.
An accidental brush of the program button in the middle of fast
action will suddenly disable all functions or reconfigure the
controller on the fly. Very frustrating. Other than that, perfect.
Madcatz saves Sega.
</P>
<P>
   A JOY STICK, MINUS THE JOY
</P>
<P>
   While InterAct's Cyclone Digital Joystick ($39;
www.interact-acc.com) offers an impressive list of features _ nine
programmable buttons, a hat switch, throttle slider, rotating
stick, USB and serial port connections, and a symmetrical button
splay that makes it lefty friendly (lefties unite!) _ the unit
still comes at a fair price. But there's a reason: The thing is
pretty much junk. The Cyclone's actual stick is so loose and floppy
that maintaining any form of control is almost impossible, and even
small movements lead to large changes in direction or lurches in
motion. In addition, the Cyclone's base is so small and light that
any excited movements result in the joystick sliding across your
desktop or toppling into you. Thus, what you've got here is a
peripheral that sorely misses the thrust of intuitive user
interfacing. Destined for the big joystick bargain bin in the sky.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
