<HEADER>
A5398 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-LANE-COLUMN0516-COX     05-15 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN0516-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Summer outlook _ big blows, blazing bark
 &HT;    By Mark Lane
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Florida has the best day-to-day weather
around, but the megaweather is a killer.
</P>
<P>
   People in other states speak nonchalantly about weather in the
easy short-term. They complain about a sudden late freeze in April.
We complain about oceanic-temperature cycles brewing monster
hurricanes.
</P>
<P>
   They whine about snow melting late. We talk about what
percentage of our forests will be aflame by August.
</P>
<P>
   The short-term picture here is, as always, mild and boring: high
in the 80s, low in the 70s, with a chance of afternoon showers. But
the big picture? Powerful hurricanes, wildfires, loss of coastline,
mobile-home-seeking tornadoes and the worst drought in more than a
half century.
</P>
<P>
   Microweather: gentle breezes on the coast. Megaweather:
forecasters announcing that this year's hurricane season will be as
bad or worse than last year's.
</P>
<P>
   Weather reports in other states are filled with descriptions of
this week's air mass from Canada or a lingering low-pressure area.
Florida weather reports, in contrast, have an epic sweep. They tell
of year-long El Nina cycles, decades-long drought cycles and
100-year storms.
</P>
<P>
   Short-term, there's not a cloud in the sky. Long term: well,
global warming might raise the sea level and finally solve Miami's
political problems.
</P>
<P>
   Even though spring has been a succession of warm days and
mildnights, the forecast for the summer is shaping up as bad news.
</P>
<P>
   Scattered wild fires and drought punctuated by hurricanes.
</P>
<P>
   Doppler radar readings predict late morning frogs, clearing by
afternoon, followed by scattered evening locust.
</P>
<P>
   The hurricane season predictions came from the National
Oceanographic and Atmospheric Administration. NOAA is the
government agency that administers the atmosphere. Can't you tell
from the name? Last week, NOAA announced that under its
administration, at least 11 tropical storms will brew in the
Atlantic and Caribbean this year. Seven are expected to become
full-fledged hurricanes, three will become major hurricanes.
</P>
<P>
   The annual hurricane season prediction is one of those official
rituals that mark the changing seasons in nearly seasonless
Florida. Schoolchildren get restless for the end of the year, the
air conditioners click on, people plant in their yards and NOAA
tells us to brace for the upcoming hurricanes. Summer's almost
here.
</P>
<P>
   With official spokesman-style understatement, the NOAA people
say we will experience what they call ``an unusually active
hurricane season.'' That means people fleeing to high ground,
boarding up houses and listening to reporters in very cool rain
slickers yelling above the pounding surf on The Weather Channel.
</P>
<P>
   There are families that still have boxes of C-size batteries and
garages cluttered with plywood and bottled water from last year's
</P>
<P>
   ``unusually active hurricane season.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason NOAA expects things to turn out this way is La Nina,
a weather pattern in the Pacific Ocean. It's lasting longer than it
</P>
<P>
   should. The pattern occurs when ocean temperatures are unusually
cold.
</P>
<P>
   This is happening at the same time Atlantic temperatures are
unusually warm. Add to this the prevailing winds east across the
Atlantic, factor in the sudden drop in the Nasdaq, take into
account, Pedro Martinez's 67 strikeouts this season, and the
computer model will tell you to invest in plywood futures because
big winds are going to blow.
</P>
<P>
   So that's the outlook for summer:
</P>
<P>
   Warm and lazy days with the smells of outdoor grills and flaming
pine trees wafting through the air.
</P>
<P>
   That warm feeling of parched lawn crunching under your bare
feet.
</P>
<P>
   Enjoying the quiet that descends on the neighborhood during a
heat-wave-induced power outage.
</P>
<P>
   The simple pleasure of sitting on the porch listening to the
sounds of neighbors hammering plywood sheets over their windows
while the tiny speakers of weather radios honk their warnings in
the distance.
</P>
<P>
   Joining the crowd at the beach and at the last store that hasn't
yet run out of batteries and duct tape.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it's the most wonderful season of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lane is a columnist for The Daytona Beach (Fla.)
News-Journal. He may be reached at mark.lane(at)news-jrnl.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
