<SLUG> BC-NFK-ETHIOPIA0516-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Starving again
 &HT;    By Don Melvin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Very few of us can imagine what it means to be truly
hungry.
</P>
<P>
   We know how it feels when lunch is late or there's no snack
after school. But we have no clue how it feels to eat less than we
need for months on end. We can't conceive of going days eating
nothing, until our arms are no bigger than sticks, our bodies are
weakened by diarrhea, and there is nothing to do but lie down on
the ground and die.
</P>
<P>
   That is happening to hundreds of people, including children, who
live in an area called the Horn of Africa. The Horn is a point of
land on the eastern side of the continent that juts into the Indian
Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say that unless help from other countries arrives fast,
between 8 million and 12 million people could face starvation.
</P>
<P>
   The worst problem is in Ethiopia, where 8 million people may
starve. But hunger also haunts people in parts of neighboring
countries, including Eritrea, Somalia, Djibouti, Kenya and Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   Famine _ widespread hunger and starvation _ usually has more
than one cause. During normal times, the people in Ethiopia are
some of the poorest in the world. Some eat only what they can grow.
Others are wandering herders who live off their cattle, sheep or
goats. Nearly half the people in the country live on less than $1 a
day.
</P>
<P>
   The country is an extremely dry place. Farmers use old-fashioned
methods. They do not have the ability to pipe water to their land.
When the rains do not come, as has happened in Ethiopia for the
past three years, people cannot grow crops to eat. Pastures dry up,
leaving nothing for animals to eat, and they die.
</P>
<P>
   War has made the problem worse. For two years, Ethiopia and
Eritrea have fought over where the border between the two countries
should be. Each government spends about $1 million a day on its
military. That is money that instead could feed many of the people
who now go hungry.
</P>
<P>
   Famine has devastated the area before. The rains fail every few
years, and wars often flare up. There was a famine in 1973. And
during a famine in 1984 and 1985, about 1 million Ethiopians died.
But help from people in other countries, including the United
States, saved millions more.
</P>
<P>
   Now ``humanitarian'' agencies _ organizations that assist people
in trouble _ say the rest of the world needs to help again. Some
people argue that other countries shouldn't help because the
governments spend money on war instead of food. But other people
say the people who are suffering have nothing to do with the war.
</P>
<P>
   War or no war, humanitarian workers say, help is needed so
children and their parents don't go hungry _ really hungry
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
