<SLUG> BC-NFK-NEWSFLASH0516-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fire ravages Los Alamos
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   One thousand firefighters in New Mexico struggled last week to
control a blaze that was set on purpose by the National Park
Service.
</P>
<P>
   The Park Service started the fire May 4 to clear brush at the
Bandelier National Monument, which is near the town of Los Alamos
(where the atomic bomb was developed in the 1940s). Controlled
burns often are used by the Park Service to prevent worse forest
fires later. But this fire raged out of control in the dry, windy
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   The fire sliced through 20,000 acres and destroyed about 260
homes and damaged 20 others. About 25,000 people were evacuated,
and 150 National Guard members were called in to maintain order and
prevent looting.
</P>
<P>
   JUDGES DEBATE ELIAN'S FATE
</P>
<P>
   Three judges must decide if a child as young as Elian Gonzalez,
6, understands enough to seek asylum in the United States.
``Asylum'' means ``safe refuge.'' If Elian is granted asylum, he
will be protected by America and won't have to return to Cuba as
his father wishes.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. government says Elian's father speaks for him and
therefore the boy shouldn't be considered for asylum. A federal
judge agreed, but Elian's American relatives asked the 11th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals, which is a higher court, to reconsider
that decision.
</P>
<P>
   The 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals is located in Atlanta.
The three judges are expected to rule in a few weeks. That decision
might not be final, however, because the losing side could appeal
again.
</P>
<P>
   LEGISLATORS CLOSE TO FLAG DEAL
</P>
<P>
   The South Carolina House and Senate are ironing out final
details of a bill that would remove the Confederate flag from atop
the state capitol. The flag would be repositioned nearby at a
Confederate monument on the Statehouse grounds.
</P>
<P>
   The House bill differs slightly from the one already passed by
the Senate. The House, for example, calls for the flag to be flown
on a 30-foot pole but the Senate specifies a 20-foot pole. The two
houses must agree on details like those before a flag bill can be
sent to the governor for his final approval.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Gov. Jim Hodges has said he would sign any bill the
Legislature passed to remove the flag.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
