A5403 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN0516-CO     05-15 0605
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN0516-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Society pays the price for youths' entitlement
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ In California, Steven Vincent Bell laughed
out loud when a county judge invoked the ``three strikes and you're
out'' law and sentenced him to 35-years-to-life in prison for
stealing a bicycle. Even ``60 Minutes'' got into the act and
elevated the thief to national fame as a result of what they felt
to be a prime-time example of judicial folly.
</P>
<P>
   I mean, after all, it was only his third residential burglary,
and he'd only stolen a bicycle worth $300. Maybe the authorities
should have cut him a little slack. Maybe he's not a real thief.
Maybe he's just a slow learner, and being busted twice already for
housebreaking wasn't enough to get his attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hang in there, everybody,'' the thief shouted to the courtroom
as he was being shown out _ in shackles. ``We'll be back to see
these losers another day.''
</P>
<P>
   Who's he calling losers?
</P>
<P>
   According to teens who show up in my friend Gail's courtroom, a
judge out on the Oregon coast, folks who obey laws and live within
the framework of social responsibility are losers and when asked to
defend their thieving ways, the young bandits candidly explain.
``Because I wanted it.''
</P>
<P>
   Two or three years ago, the social studies teacher across the
hall from my classroom decided to run a survey on her 8th-graders'
values. The results were scary. All but 9 of the students felt it
was okay to take something (they avoided the word ``steal'') if
they really wanted it and couldn't get it any other way.
</P>
<P>
   Because they really wanted it? That predicates entitlement?
</P>
<P>
   A couple of nights ago, Gail was filling me in on a situation in
her neighborhood. It seems a band of teenagers are roaming that
beachfront community at night, stealing boats from folks' yards,
and selling them for drug money. Then when the boat owners complain
to the police of being left high and dry, these morally-challenged
thugs feel it is perfectly within their rights to terrorize the
victims for their grievous acts. A neighbor two houses down, has
become a virtual prisoner in her home since reporting her boat
stolen.
</P>
<P>
   To most of us, theft is an incomprehensible act. We were taught
not to take what doesn't belong to us _ period. But lately there
seems to have been a shift in attitudes _ it's not okay to steal
from a friend, the kids tell us, but it is okay to knock over
Wal-Mart for some jeans and jelly sandals.
</P>
<P>
   Like that clown in California, they just don't get it either.
</P>
<P>
   In Mr. Bell's case, breaking and entering is an avoidable
situation. Crowbars and picklocks don't just jump into our hands
without warning. Joints don't get cased by accident. There's no
reason for this guy not to have figured it out the first time. He
breaks in. He's caught. Why isn't that enough of an indication to
him that what he has done is unacceptable, illegal, and will
eventually land his lawbreaking backside in a cell?
</P>
<P>
   But our guy perseveres and repeats the process, and then when
he's caught and convicted a third time, he has the absurd nerve to
scream FOUL and call his jury ``losers.'' This guy needs to be in
custody to protect himself from his own stupidity.
</P>
<P>
   But in a way he's right. We are the losers. We're the ones
paying the taxes to fill the belly of the jerk who stole our
bicycle.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or e-mail: eschuett(at)nwwonline
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
