<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 11:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5418 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT     05-15 1106
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPEALS COURT QUESTIONS USE OF PEPPER SPRAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (EDITOR'S NOTE: Charles Levendosky, editorial page editor of the
Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune, has a national reputation for First
Amendment commentary. His e-mail address is
levendos(AT-sign)trib.com.)  
 By CHARLES LEVENDOSKY   
 c.2000 Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The peaceful anti-logging protesters, who had pepper spray
blasted into their eyes at close range, won another chance to sue
the law enforcement agencies and officials involved _ nearly three
years after the incidents.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 30, 1997, the protesters filed a lawsuit claiming that
the application of pepper spray to the eyelids and faces of
nonviolent protesters constitutes excessive and unreasonable force
in violation of their Fourth Amendment rights.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, the Ninth U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
reversed the lower federal district court judge's decision against
the protesters.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court said that only a jury can decide whether the
force used against the protesters to effect their arrest was
reasonable under the Fourth Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   In the fall of 1997, at three separate locations, law
enforcement officials of Humboldt County and the city of Eureka,
Calif., used pepper spray against nonviolent and unarmed young
women and men who were protesting the logging of old-growth
redwoods in the Headwaters Redwood Forest.
</P>
<P>
   Pepper spray, sometimes called oleoresin capsicum (OC) after its
active ingredient, is derived from hot peppers. When applied to the
eyes, it has an immediate and painful burning effect that may last
for hours, even after dousing the eyes with water. It swells the
eyes shut and makes it difficult to breathe. Medical studies show
it can cause asthmatics to convulse and die.
</P>
<P>
   A protester called the pain caused by the pepper spray, ``the
worst pain I have ever experienced in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   In one of these incidents, four women protesters entered former
Congressman Frank Riggs' Eureka office. Riggs supported the
logging. The women dropped wood chips on the floor and chained
themselves together in a circle with heavy steel cylinders over
their arms.
</P>
<P>
   The police video tape of how law enforcement treated these
protesters tells the story in chilling and vivid detail.
</P>
<P>
   With cold deliberateness, a deputy sheriff dips a Q-tip into a
cup filled with pepper spray. He walks slowly over to 16-year-old
Maya Portugal, who is sitting quietly with a soft, brown hat on her
head. A city police officer forces Maya's head back and pries open
her right eye. The wet Q-tip is swept across her lower eyelid. The
girl stifles a sob. The officers repeat the process on her left
eye. She shakes her head as if to dislodge the intense pain.
</P>
<P>
   The officers crouch as they shuffle over to the next woman in
the circle. The men show no anger. Their actions are calculated and
purposeful. The eyes of all four women are swabbed with pepper
spray.
</P>
<P>
   The women still refuse to unchain themselves. Then the officers
select one of the women, Terri Slanetz, and tell her they will use
a direct spray. She pleads, ``Why are you using chemical weapons on
us? You have other options.'' To no avail. A police officer pulls
her head back by her ponytail. And a deputy sheriff leans over her
and shoots pepper spray directly into her closed left eye, from a
distance of not more than four inches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other options'' is precisely why the court of appeals reversed
the lower court's ruling. Law enforcement officials had numerous
other options, the appellate court pointed out. Officers could have
cut through the steel sleeves joining the protesters with a Makita
grinder as had been done safely hundreds of times before. Officers
did not attempt to negotiate with the protesters, did not attempt
to wait them out, nor did they attempt to physically remove them.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the county sheriff's office and the city police
department used pepper spray on the peaceful demonstrators _ in
violation of their own general orders and policies.
</P>
<P>
   Humboldt County's general order concerning oleoresin capsicum
states, in part: ''This aerosol is furnished as a defensive weapon
for the protection of department members ... and is intended for
use in those cases wherein a member of the Department is attempting
to subdue an attacker or a violently resisting suspect.''
</P>
<P>
   The Eureka Police Department's policy states: ``OC shall not be
used to harass or punish a prisoner.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the California Department of Justice ``recommends that
Oleoresin Capsicum be used only against violent or hostile
subjects.''
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court noted repeatedly in its decision that the
demonstrators posed no threat to the police, to the themselves, or
to the public at large. Most of the protesters were women. Not one
was armed. All were passive in their protests. None of the
protesters offered active resistance to the police.
</P>
<P>
   Humboldt County and Eureka law enforcement officials claim they
used pepper spray merely as a ``pain compliance technique'' to get
the cooperation of the protesters. The appeals court nixed that
approach.
</P>
<P>
   The unanimous decision of the three-member court states: ``a
'pain compliance technique' using pepper spray does not permit the
police immediately to stop inflicting pain the moment the
protesters comply with the officers' demands.''
</P>
<P>
   The appellate court stressed that the only crime the nonviolent
protesters had committed was trespass, and that ``militates against
finding the force used to effect an arrest reasonable.''
</P>
<P>
   Reading the court records closely leaves the impression that the
police intended to inflict pain _ immediate and sustained, severe
pain _ because they were frustrated with the protesters.
</P>
<P>
   The Ninth Circuit Court decision gives fair warning to law
enforcement agencies in the nine western states and territories
under its jurisdiction that they had better discourage the use of
chemical sprays against peaceful demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
   The court concludes that only a jury can decide, according to
the facts in these incidents, whether reasonable force was used to
effect the arrest of the protesters. Therefore, the protesters have
a right to sue the law enforcement officials in a federal district
court _ again.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Mark Hughes of Denver, Colo., who handled the appeal
for the protesters says the court has upheld the American tradition
of civil disobedience. ``It is one of the very fundamental rights
that the founders of the country wanted to preserve.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, will law enforcement agencies pay attention?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
