<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 13:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5444 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-CHINA-TRADE-HNS &LR;      05-15 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TRADE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     DON'T REWARD THE BULLY OF BEIJING 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAVID SCHNEIDER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In appreciating the great contributions to world
civilization, you have to think about China. Silk, bronze casting,
tea, porcelain, calligraphy and the magnetic compass. Perhaps,
though, we could have done without the gunpowder.
</P>
<P>
   Three Chinese philosophies are simply inspiring: the moral law
of man and the goodness that binds human relationships espoused by
Confucius; the harmony between nature and man propounded by Lao Tzu
in the Tao Te Ching; and ``Chen Ai,'' or universal or all-embracing
love, advocated by Mo Tzu.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, the imagination is staggered by the problems and
challenges of governing China, with its immense population in
excess of 1.2 billion, its constant floods and environmental
difficulties, along with the country's transition to at least a
partial market economy.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, you have to wonder why Beijing's leaders behave the way
they do, making a mockery of Confucius, Lao Tzu and Mo Tzu; you
have to wonder what we can or should do about it.
</P>
<P>
   China has made the Tibetans a minority in their own country.
Tibetan Buddhist lamas, monks and nuns have been tortured or
killed. And China's government refuses to negotiate with the Dalai
Lama, Tibet's spiritual leader and a recipient of the Nobel Peace
Prize.
</P>
<P>
   Consider that China is damaging Tibet ecologically through
strip-mining, deforestation and nuclear waste disposal.
</P>
<P>
   And China has made Tibet a militarized zone.
</P>
<P>
   According to the U.S. State Department's ``China Country Report
on Human Rights Practice for 1999'' published earlier this year,
Chinese authorities continue to commit serious human rights abuses
in Tibet.
</P>
<P>
   In China itself, state authorities have arrested more than
10,000 members of the Falun Gong and restricted the rights of
Catholics and Protestants. And remember the Tiananmen Square
massacre?
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Nancy Pelosi, D-Calif., cites evidence that China has also
broken every trade agreement it has entered into.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, China signed agreements that it would not use forced
labor, but in its 1998 report, the State Department said China
ignored or denied cases of forced labor identified by U.S. Customs.
</P>
<P>
   China has expanded into Tibet for much the same reasons that
Germany in 1939 expanded into various parts of Europe; it wants
some Lebensraum (some living room) and is claiming that Tibet was
part of China, much as the Germans claimed that a great deal of
Europe had been part of Germany. Never mind that Tibetans are,
well, Tibetan!
</P>
<P>
   (Of course to be fair, we did much the same thing to American
Indian nations when we conquered the West for the good old USA. I'm
sure American Indians can relate to the horror of the spiritual and
cultural destruction of Tibet.)
</P>
<P>
   With China we have delinked respect for human rights and trade.
</P>
<P>
   That's why there is such a controversy now about the crucial
vote in the House of Representatives at the end of May for
extending to China ``permanent normal trade relations'' (or PNTR,
previously known as the ``most favored nation'' status). The
Clinton administration, backed by heavy Republican support, wants
PNTR for China.
</P>
<P>
   What many in Congress desire is the opportunity to review
China's human rights conduct every year. That is the situation now.
Once PNTR is enacted for China, Congress loses that right.
</P>
<P>
   Fearing defeat for the legislation, some members of Congress _
led by Rep. Sander M. Levin, D-Mich. _ propose a compromise. It is
backed by the Clinton administration and by former President George
Bush. The compromise would mean approval of PNTR for China, but it
would set up an advisory committee, appointed by Congress and the
president, to monitor human rights in China.
</P>
<P>
   Advisory?
</P>
<P>
   This seems to be yet another layer of bureaucracy that affects
the traditional role of congressional review.
</P>
<P>
   Isn't it easier to just read the State Department's twice-yearly
human rights report on China?
</P>
<P>
   Free trade really means there are no rules. Fair trade means a
balance, including responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   Congress should vote in favor of fair trade and vote no on
``permanent normal trade relations.'' Perhaps it will help China to
act in accordance with its ancient values. And maybe it will be
good for us not to kowtow to a big bully.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David Schneider is a lawyer and writer.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
