<DOCNO> NYT20000515.0110 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 13:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5445 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      05-15 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GIULIANI THE HUMAN 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ For one day anyway, New York Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani has never seemed so attractive a human being.
</P>
<P>
   As he stood in front of a small group of City Hall reporters,
searching and stumbling his way into a long overdue admission about
his ruined marriage, Giuliani faced the world with a raw,
heavy-hearted vulnerability that becomes an arrogant man.
</P>
<P>
   It distinguished him from all the other holier-than thou,
family-values-spewing Republicans who have been exposed as
hypocrites.
</P>
<P>
   When Republican Reps. Henry Hyde, Bob Livingston and Newt
Gingrich, and Sen. Dan Burton were so revealed, each was about as
attractive as a 3-week-old corpse found at the bottom of a
Dumpster.
</P>
<P>
   This is because, unlike Giuliani last Wednesday, the Capitol
Hill foursome were devoid of humility or any public posture that
resembled genuine remorse or regret. Defiantly, haughtily, each man
appeared to be sorry only that his misdeed had been found out by
the hated news media.
</P>
<P>
   (Hyde added insult to injury, as well as to basic human
intelligence, by characterizing his five-year-long extramarital
affair with a married woman, conducted while he was in his mid-40s,
as ``a youthful indiscretion.'')
</P>
<P>
   For one day, the customarily defiant and haughty Giuliani did no
such thing.
</P>
<P>
   In what New York Times reporter Elisabeth Bumiller called ``an
extraordinary, emotional news conference,'' the second-term mayor
turned a regular press briefing into ``an unusually intimate
confessional.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Giuliani has been roundly blasted in retrospect for
blindsiding his estranged wife with public acknowledgment of their
doomed marriage, Bumiller wrote:
</P>
<P>
   ``It was unclear whether Mr. Giuliani had planned beforehand to
announce the possible separation at the news conference, or whether
he wandered into the remarks as reporters questioned him. Since the
mayor learned he has prostate cancer, he has become increasingly
personal and introspective in his news briefings.''
</P>
<P>
   This supports what most people with a life-threatening disease
will tell you: The experience has a potent way of clearing all the
superfluous clutter from one's personal dinner table. Priorities
shift dramatically; the trivial and disingenuous fall to the bottom
of the list.
</P>
<P>
   As the clean, awesome truth of mortality establishes itself
front and center, keeping up false ``appearances'' becomes a
wasteful and useless indulgence.
</P>
<P>
   For my money, the most impressive of Giuliani's ``confessions''
were not the references to his broken marriage to Donna Hanover or
to his relationship with a ``very good friend,'' Judith Nathan.
Rather it was his answer to whether he was concerned about a
political backlash to his personal travails.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, you know, I don't really care about politics right now,''
he said. ``I don't. I'm thinking about my family, the people that I
love and what's, what can be done that's honest and truthful and
that protects them the best.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not thinking about politics. I'm not; politics comes at
least second, maybe third, maybe fourth, somewhere else. It'll all
work itself out some way, politically . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the cause _ be it prostate cancer, too many accidental
shooting victims of the police, a busted marriage, or all of the
above _ something wonderful and refreshing happened to Giuliani the
day he uttered those words.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of maintaining his stance as a smug, dispassionate,
grudge-holding autocrat, he donned the mantle of deeply humbled,
struggling, responsibility-taking human.
</P>
<P>
   Why, he even stopped blaming journalists for his problems.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the media had ``caused'' the damage to Giuliani's
marriage, the mayor said:
</P>
<P>
   ``No, the media makes the damage much worse; it didn't cause the
damage. I take responsibility for everything I've done. And you
have every right to ask me, and I have a right to answer or not
answer.''
</P>
<P>
   The day after the confessional, Giuliani was back to his old
ways. When he wanted to talk about a food drive and reporters
wanted to talk about his wife's accusations of another ``other
woman,'' the mayor ``berated reporters,'' according to Bumiller,
and returned ``to his more combative, and familiar, public
persona.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he had come to agree with Nelson Warfield, one of
Giuliani's longtime critics within the Republican Party.
Pooh-poohing the notion that all the public laundry hanging could
humanize the mayor's image and help him in his U.S. Senate fight
against Hillary Rodham Clinton, Warfield told the Times:
</P>
<P>
   ``None of this helps. It's mere happy talk to suggest it
humanizes him. Nobody needs to be humanized this way.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, centuries of history indicate otherwise. Often, real
grace comes only after a spectacularly messy, humanizing fall.
</P>
<P>
   For one day, Rudolph Giuliani seemed to be reaching for that
grace. Had he continued, he might have been on the path to winning
a far greater prize than a seat in the U.S. Senate:
</P>
<P>
   His soul.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her electronic mail address
is salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-00 1301EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000515.0111 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 13:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5446 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      05-15 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     DOWN IN THE DUMPSTER IN SAN FRANCISCO 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROB MORSE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ ``Horse trading'' will be associated with San
Francisco journalism for years to come, the way ``expletive
deleted'' is associated with Richard Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go sell it to the Chronicle.'' That's the Ben Bradlee
character's dismissive line in the 1976 movie ``All the President's
Men,'' and it stuck the way ``horse trading'' will now.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's just because I'm a San Francisco columnist who wishes
he was wilder, but I always liked the wildness of earlier
generations of San Francisco journalists, including the antics of
William Randolph Hearst and legendary Chronicle Editor Scott
Newhall.
</P>
<P>
   The words ``horse trading'' were used by lawyer Joseph M. Alioto
in Clint Reilly's lawsuit to keep the Hearst Corp. from buying the
San Francisco Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   When Alioto asked San Francisco Examiner Publisher Tim White if
he had been ``horse trading'' editorial page favors with the mayor
at lunch, White said he had.
</P>
<P>
   White, a man who was generally well-respected at both the
Examiner and the Chronicle (which he was due to take over), was
suspended from his job. Since then, everyone else here has had a
hard time focusing on their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   As a lawyer at the Federal Building said to me last week,
``Being in the spotlight isn't pleasant, is it? Now you see what
it's like.''
</P>
<P>
   The day after White was suspended, I was standing with a friend
in front of the Examiner building when a man stopped and confronted
us.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Examiner ought to be ashamed of itself,'' he said, and
point by point told us why. He was a newspaper reader, and he felt
betrayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking a lot about this at work,'' he said. ``We're
probably not going to buy the Examiner again.''
</P>
<P>
   My colleague and I had nothing to say in response.
</P>
<P>
   If we hadn't been so tired and confused, to use another suddenly
popular phrase, there were a lot of things we could have said.
</P>
<P>
   We could have said that our publisher's lunches with the mayor
don't affect what we do in the newsroom. We could have pointed to
the Examiner's investigation of San Francisco's minority
contracting, which has propelled a continuing FBI investigation and
led to U.S. grand jury indictments.
</P>
<P>
   I could have said that I'm the guy who so infuriated the mayor
that he said he wouldn't use the Examiner as toilet paper.
</P>
<P>
   The man berating us wasn't in the mood to hear how tough we'd
been on the mayor. He was angry about ``horse trading.''
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco Examiner is dying, and it can't even die with
dignity. Even the president of the Hearst Corp., Frank Bennack,
showed no attachment to the newspaper that was the beginning of
William Randolph Hearst's empire.
</P>
<P>
   At one point in his courtroom testimony, Bennack mentioned the
Hearst-owned Houston Chronicle. He said to the judge, ``We like
Chronicles, your honor.''
</P>
<P>
   By the way, I'm more upset than this column sounds. But I'm kind
of burned out and need to save my energy for deeper humiliations to
come.
</P>
<P>
   Last week I spent three days in the courtroom, and it wasn't
pretty. These are just a few things I heard about the Examiner, all
spoken by Hearst's own witnesses and executives.
</P>
<P>
   We're not world-class, and neither is the Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   OK, we knew that. Everyone knew that. But Bennack, a no-nonsense
witness, came right out and said so.
</P>
<P>
   You have to face your failings, and boy, have our failings been
shoved in our faces lately.
</P>
<P>
   I don't mind that Bennack said he didn't know if Examiner
columnists are world-class columnists, because he doesn't have time
to read all his columnists every day.
</P>
<P>
   I suppose he'll read this, though.
</P>
<P>
   We're a failing newspaper. We knew that too. We're even failing
at going out of business.
</P>
<P>
   We always thought we were successful at a few things, however,
like keeping a watch on Mayor Willie Brown and his dealings.
</P>
<P>
   We continue to do that, while the mayor continues to run San
Francisco as his wholly owned subsidiary. You can even feel his
reach in the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   Brown must be laughing all the way to the next party, enjoying
the sweetest of revenge on this newspaper. Second-sweetest, after
Clint Reilly's.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, yes, one more small wound among the gut-shots we took in
court. We found out we're garbage.
</P>
<P>
   Newspaper economist James N. Rosse was asked to explain the
meaning of a ``negative purchase price,'' specifically the $66
million Hearst wants to pay the Fang family to take the Examiner
off its hands.
</P>
<P>
   Rosse, a witness called by Hearst, said it's a fee like
``garbage disposal,'' paying someone to take away stuff you don't
want.
</P>
<P>
   Once we were proud to line parakeet cages. Now we're being taken
to the landfill.
</P>
<P>
   No respect. No dignity. No recycling bin. We're garbage.
</P>
<P>
   At least that's better than the way I feel right now.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-00 1302EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
