<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 13:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5463 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-WOMEN'S-HEALTH-RESEAR     05-15 1217
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN'S-HEALTH-RESEARCH-MED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESEARCH COULD LEAD TO BIG ADVANCES IN WOMEN'S HEALTH  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 By REBEKAH DENN  
 c.2000 HealthScout.com  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by The New York Times Syndicate) &LR;  &QL;
<P>
   One of the startling things about Shirley Beresford's research
is that it isn't considered startling anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Beresford, an epidemiology professor at the University of
Washington, is a principal investigator with the Women's Health
Initiative, which is tracking the health of 162,000 post-menopausal
women, making it the largest project dealing with women's health in
the nation's history.
</P>
<P>
   A study of that magnitude dealing with women's health _ and the
mere idea of including women as clinical research subjects _ would
have been unheard of as recently as the late 1980s. But the past
decade has brought about a revolution in women's health research,
and the next decade is expected to bear some of the fruits of that
science.
</P>
<P>
   The Women's Health Initiative is a 15-year study being conducted
at 40 clinical centers across the United States, and it is expected
to provide a wealth of information. It will evaluate the effect of
a low-fat diet on preventing breast and colon cancer and heart
disease; the effect of hormone-replacement therapy on combating
heart disease and osteoporosis; and the need for calcium and
vitamin D supplements in preventing osteoporosis and colon cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The study reflects areas where Beresford has concentrated her
past research _ research, she says, that has the potential to make
a difference in women's health and lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really wanted to be involved, if I possibly could,'' she
says.
</P>
<P>
   The initiative, which will also examine women's risk factors for
certain diseases and strategies to adopt healthier lifestyles _ is
a juggernaut in the field. But it's far from the only advance in
women's health research.
</P>
<P>
   A recent study by the Pharmaceutical Research and Manufacturers
of America found a 75 percent increase since 1991 in the number of
drugs in development for diseases that disproportionately affect
women, such as osteoporosis, depression, and autoimmune illnesses
like lupus. The study cited 60 drugs alone currently in development
to treat breast cancer, and 38 for ovarian cancer.
</P>
<P>
   In another advance, The Society for the Advancement of Women's
Health Research _ an agency that only came into existence a decade
ago _ recently kicked off a campaign titled ``Women Can Do,''
encouraging women to volunteer for clinical medical research
studies. In years past, women would have been excluded from
standard medical research studies because of fears they would
become pregnant, or their hormonal cycles would skew the results.
</P>
<P>
   The more women get involved in such studies, the agency reasons,
the more the scientific world will know about how their bodies
react to diseases and their treatments. And the more doctors will
recognize that the 150-pound male _ once considered the ``average''
patient _ is only half the story.
</P>
<P>
   BIDDING THE 'BIKINI APPROACH' FAREWELL
</P>
<P>
   It's all part of a victory over what was dubbed ``the bikini
approach'' in a recent issue of the Harvard Women's Health Watch
newsletter _ the view that the field of women's health covered
nothing more than the reproductive organs and the breasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there have been incredible advances in terms of the
pharmaceutical industry,'' says Phyllis Greenberger, executive
director of the Society for the Advancement of Women's Health
Research, one of the agencies credited with getting the research
ball rolling in 1990 by lobbying Congress to establish the National
Institute of Health's Office of Women's Health.
</P>
<P>
   But there are still serious gaps in knowledge to be filled, she
says. Most past research on treatments for common killers such as
heart disease _ the leading cause of death in both women and men _
was based on studies of male subjects, Greenberger says. Now, it's
crucial for researchers to look at how the same treatments for
those same diseases might affect men and women differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not one-size-fits-all,'' she says, noting how safety
studies involving air bags in cars were focused on men and led to a
standard later found to potentially endanger children and shorter
women.
</P>
<P>
   Some individual researchers are already breaking the gender
barrier.
</P>
<P>
   In one study, Pascal J. de Caprariis, medical director of
virology at Hoffmann-La Roche Laboratories in Nutley, N.J., says he
is investigating whether women and men react differently to
medications fighting HIV, the virus that causes AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   To encourage participation in the studies _ and in many cases,
to make it possible for women with family responsibilities _
Caprariis and his researchers have added amenities like child care
and transportation to the clinic for participants.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't understand how difficult it is for women with
children to get into any clinic setting,'' Carprariis says.
</P>
<P>
   Another encouraging sign, women's health advocates say, is a
long-awaited study just getting under way at the National Institute
of Medicine, one of the four national academies created to advise
the federal government on health issues.
</P>
<P>
   According to the institute staff, the year-long, $650,000 study
will attempt to look at the state of current research into women's
health issues, the areas where more research is needed, and the
barriers that must be overcome for research to be completed.
</P>
<P>
   NOTABLE ADVANCES IN LAST 9 YEARS
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a recent report by the National Institutes of Health
showed significant progress in women's medicine in the last nine
years, while highlighting the need for far more work.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, while there have been ``noteworthy'' advances in
chemotherapy for breast cancer, the report says, more research must
be encouraged into new ``designer estrogens'' that can provide the
benefits of hormone-replacement therapy with fewer side effects.
And while new factors have been discovered that affect the risk of
developing colorectal cancer, many women are still not screened for
the disease.
</P>
<P>
   Greenberger's agency sees ``the next frontiers'' of women's
health research as including heart disease, metabolism and
digestive diseases, and musculoskeletal health. In a broader
approach, the agency is also encouraging researchers to look at
differences between the genders at all levels, from organ systems
down to the sub-cellular level.
</P>
<P>
   The Women's Health Initiative should also help bring changes as
results of its research come to light.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever new information comes from such studies, Greenberger
says they will have a broader benefit than just improving women's
lives. Any new information about the way the human body responds to
diseases and treatments, she says, will benefit all humans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just about women's issues and it's not just about
women's health. It's about everybody's health,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   __
</P>
<P>
   (The HealthScout.com Web site is at http://www.HealthScout.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
