<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOP OR NOT? NEW MAGS WITH ADVICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I wasn't surprised to learn that Susan Wyland, the editor of the
new magazine Real Simple, used to edit Martha Stewart Living, and
not just because the two magazines have a similar look. Five years
ago this month, Martha predicted that the next big lifestyle trend
would be ``de-accession.''
</P>
<P>
   ``De-accession'' was Martha's way of saying ``simplify,'' or, as
she explained at the time, ``It's simplify, simplify, simplify.''
</P>
<P>
   The prophetic word sounded strange in Martha's mouth. Martha
Stewart simplify? It's oxymoronic. Martha probably will never
de-access, but if she did, the results might resemble what readers
will find in Real Simple, the magazine that asks the question: Can
simplicity be too complicated?
</P>
<P>
   Real Simple is aimed at ``today's overextended, overcommitted,
overscheduled woman,'' according to a press release. Judging from
the content of the May issue, the target audience is someone who's
not so overextended that she can't find time to read about how to
``streamline'' her life by acquiring a $450 Salvatore Ferragamo
shoulder bag.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, a cottage industry in publishing has sprung up
around simplicity. Elaine St. James's book ``Simplify Your Life''
has been enormously popular. Other simplicity gurus have jumped in
and written books aimed at people fed up with overworking and
overconsuming, people who feel a need to pare down their
possessions and their commitments. Of course there's a big gap
between feeling the need to simplify and actually doing it. Some
people just like to read about it.
</P>
<P>
   Real Simple is aimed at the woman who'd like to simplify her
life, but can't, or won't. She's overcommitted. She feels guilty.
At the end of another weary day of work, she can flip through Real
Simple and imagine how elegantly pared down her life could be if
she didn't have children, a husband, aging parents, pets, grocery
shopping, cooking, bills, cars, doctors' appointments. If she
didn't have to face reality. Maybe she can buy some simplicity,
this $2,500 night stand, that $750 lamp, both ``objects that
soothe,'' according to the text. At those prices, they'd better.
</P>
<P>
   Real Simple pays lip service to the concept of simplifying your
life, but it's really all about acquiring more stuff. It's
simplicity for voyeurs, in the same way Martha Stewart Living is,
for many readers, a fantasy of gracious living.
</P>
<P>
   Suggestion: Simplify your life by not buying Real Simple.
Instead, pick up the premiere issue of Lucky, ``A New Magazine
About Shopping'' from Conde Nast. It's the first magazine to
unashamedly celebrate the joys of shopping. It's verges on shopping
pornography, but at least it's not masquerading as something it's
not.
</P>
<P>
   Lucky is aimed at young women lucky enough to be able to afford
to shop their brains out. I was fascinated by a two-page layout of
46 makeup items designed to make you look as if you're not wearing
makeup. But my favorite feature was ``Ask Dr. Shopper.'' Mim
Udovitch fields several questions, including a desperate cry for
help from ``Barefoot and Baffled,'' who bought a $350 pair of
Christian Louboutin sandals and can't bring herself to wear them
anywhere because no place she goes is good enough for them. Dr.
Shopper advises her to confront her label-and-cost prejudices and
accept the sandals as fully realized members of her wardrobe: ``In
some deep, unconscious pocket of your soul, you feel that your
sandals are looking down on you, and sandals, like horses, can
sense fear. Even if they're mules.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
