<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5494 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-TEACHERS-TAXES-HNS &LR;      05-15 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEACHERS-TAXES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TAX EXEMPTION FOR TEACHERS FACES LEGISLATIVE CRITICISM 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By CHUCK FINNIE and ROBERT SALLADAY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ California Gov. Gray Davis' bold plan to
permanently exempt public school teachers from having to pay state
income taxes is getting a chilly reception from Democratic and
Republican lawmakers who must approve the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans ripped the income tax exemption as ``special
interest'' politics that both discriminates against teachers in
private schools and leaves other workers, such as low-wage day care
providers, police officers and firefighters, out in the cold.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Davis' fellow Democrats in the Legislature questioned
whether the proposal would lead to improved education for students.
They also echoed Republican concerns about selective tax breaks.
</P>
<P>
   This year the state is expecting an unprecedented $12 billion
more in tax revenues than what was calculated when Davis released
his budget in January. Budget revenues are up 20 percent this year,
one of the largest increases in state history.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature must approve the final draft of the spending
plan by June 15. The Davis proposal would cost California $545
million in the fiscal year starting July 1, according to the
governor's office. The state has approximately 283,000 credentialed
public school teachers.
</P>
<P>
   The measure would provide $500 in annual state tax relief to
each beginning teacher and $1,350 to experienced teachers earning a
salary of $50,000, the governor's office said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know I value all work, whether you're a janitor, middle
manager or a CEO, and I take a back seat to no one in my respect
for people who put themselves in harm's way, such as firefighters,
policemen, paramedics,'' Davis said, when asked why he was singling
out one profession.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I really believe we have to make a simple declarative
statement that above all else, teaching matters,'' he said. ``This
is the single most important profession to us in the year 2000 and
that's the statement I'm making.''
</P>
<P>
   The California Teachers Association (CTA), one of Davis' biggest
supporters during his 1998 campaign for office, embraced the
proposal wholeheartedly.
</P>
<P>
   The state projects a shortage of 300,000 public school teachers
over the next 10 years and the CTA called the income tax exemption
idea an innovative bid to draw talented people to the profession.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are pleased. We think it is a creative move. It shows some
respect for the teaching profession. It is a way of dealing with
the teacher shortage,'' said Bob Cherry, the CTA associate
director.
</P>
<P>
   If enacted, state officials said they believe it would be the
first such income tax exemption in peacetime for any occupation in
American history.
</P>
<P>
   It also is likely to test Davis' political sway with the
Legislature and perhaps highlight already strained relations with
lawmakers in his own party, some of whom have criticized the
governor for being high-handed and leaving them out of the loop on
important policy discussions.
</P>
<P>
   After Davis' call for the income tax exemption on Saturday,
Democratic leaders sounded genuinely caught off guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a governor named Gray, this is bold, thought-provoking
stuff,'' Assembly Speaker Bob Hertzberg, a Democrat from Los
Angeles, said in a statement released by his press secretary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly he wants to attract and retain qualified teachers,''
Hertzberg said. ``But his proposal takes state tax policy into
uncharted waters. If we do this for teachers, how do we treat other
professionals working for the public good?''
</P>
<P>
   Democrat Kerry Mazzoni, chairwoman of the Assembly Education
Committee, said she saw little that is useful in the income tax
exemption plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are some inherent problems with it. I don't
think freeing teachers from state income taxes attracts gifted
people into the profession,'' said Mazzoni, who is from San Rafael.
</P>
<P>
   ``Generally,`` she said, ``the rhetoric around teacher salaries
will not become intellectually honest until we begin talking about
12-month contracts'' under which public teachers would receive
higher pay, but also be expected to work year-round.
</P>
<P>
   Mazzoni added that she believes a tax exemption for teachers
would invite demands for similar treatment from police officers,
firefighters and social workers.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Baugh, the Assembly Republican leader, accused Davis of
attempting to carve up the state's budget surplus to reward his
political friends in the state public teachers union.
</P>
<P>
   ``The proposal is a terrible precedent. It leaves out dozens of
over-worked, under-paid noble professions such as day care
operators, nursing home attendants, police and firefighters,''
Baugh said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This appears to be special interest politics at its worst. It
does imply that teachers in private schools are less noble than
those in public schools,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Baugh, who is from Huntington Beach, said a GOP plan to give an
across-the-board state income tax exemption to anyone earning less
than $25,000 a year is a fairer way to assist Californians in
important, but often low-paying service vocations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
