<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SISTERS-INTERRUPTED-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM ASHES OF WORCESTER FIRE EMERGES A TALE OF TWO SISTERS 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: Photos of the sisters are being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
888-346-9867 or 888-603-1036.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOANNA WEISS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELLSWORTH, Maine _ They have an undeniable family resemblance,
especially when they're nervous or shy: the same pout, the
downturned, almond-shaped eyes, the thin lips pressed together.
When Tim King saw the picture in the newspaper, he had to look
again.
</P>
<P>
   It was a photo of Julie Barnes, the 19-year-old homeless woman
arrested after the deadly Worcester (Mass.) fire in December. But
it could almost have been his adopted daughter, Jennifer, a sweet
and bashful 16-year-old, born near Worcester, whom he and his wife
had guided through years of special education, with constant
advocacy and protectiveness.
</P>
<P>
   He brought the newspaper to his wife, and asked her, ``What was
Jennifer's mother's name?''
</P>
<P>
   The last name was Barnes, Debb King replied. And then, she said,
``He had tears in his eyes. He said, `Julie Barnes. That's
Jennifer's sister.' '
</P>
<P>
   It was December, a few weeks after the fire, and only the
ghastly outlines of the tragedy had trickled up to Maine: a
terrible blaze in a giant warehouse, six firefighters dead, 17
children orphaned. And a homeless couple charged with manslaughter,
two scrubby souls who set the fire by accident, and ran from the
building without telling anyone.
</P>
<P>
   But the facts fit together. Jennifer King, a former foster
child, had a biological sister named Julie, three years older. The
Kings hadn't seen or heard from her in more than a decade. And in
those intervening years _ years when Jennifer was riding a bike,
learning to baby-sit, traveling to Nashville and Disney World _
Julie Barnes had shuffled between parents' houses, dropped out of
high school and drifted to the streets.
</P>
<P>
   Now she was in jail, pregnant by a troubled man 22 years her
senior, her face downcast and disturbingly familiar. To see their
own daughter's features, on somebody hopeless and lost, reminded
the Kings of their own quiet fears: that without close supervision
or family support, Jennifer could have wound up lost herself.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings are not a textbook family, not wealthy or powerful or
perfect. But they are close-knit, committed to their daughter, and
eager to connect with the near-stranger they saw in the photograph.
They want Jennifer and Julie to get together, but their goals are
more ambitious than that. They want to help Julie get out of jail,
to give her some of the attention and support that one sister
received, but one seems to have missed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we had to do something,'' Tim King said. ``It's almost
like Julie is part of our family, as well.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer King was born Leeann Barnes, a tiny, sick baby that
state social workers removed from her mother at 5 days old.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Debb Bull, 30, was a single mother of two, living
in Auburn, Mass. She had taken in foster children before, at a
friend's suggestion. But she was soon to give it up. She found it
too wrenching to care for a child and then say goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   Still, when a social worker called about a newborn girl, and
``concerns about the mother,'' Debb quickly agreed to take the
baby. And she felt an instant affection for the too-small child who
spent her first week in the hospital, swimming in tubes, suffering
from seizures and a stomach ailment, pneumonia and asthma.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, Debb was able to bring Leeann home. And for the next few
years, Evelyn Barnes would come to the house for regular visits,
ordered by the state Department of Social Services. She would bring
her two other children, both toddlers. Julie was the middle child,
a quiet girl with a broad smile, which she would flash if given a
cookie or a toy.
</P>
<P>
   As for Leeann, it was clear from the start that she would
struggle. She was slow to learn and remember things; her speech was
slightly impaired. A social worker once said she was
``non-adoptable.'' But when the state moved, after three years, to
take custody of her, Debb hired a lawyer, adopted Leeann, and
changed her name to Jennifer.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, Debb decided it was best to pull away from Evelyn
Barnes, to consolidate her new, official family: 3-year-old
Jennifer and two older children, now 12 and 13. She kept track of
Barnes and her daughters for awhile, through a social worker, but
eventually lost touch.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Tim King, a local government official, moved in
across the street. He had an easygoing, joking manner and an
instant affection for her children; he potty-trained Jennifer
himself. Twelve years ago, Tim and Debb were married. Though
Jennifer had already been calling him ``Poppy,'' Tim formally
adopted her a few years later.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings moved to Rhode Island and later to Ellsworth, Maine, a
small community adjacent to Bar Harbor, with a spacious new high
school and a picturesque historic district. Tim, 47, is the city
manager. Debb, 46, owns a travel agency nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer lives with her parents in a small, yellow Cape-style
house, where her bedroom is filled with dolls and makeup cases. Her
parents will soon help her paint it purple, the same color as the
dress she recently wore to a prom for teenagers with disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Though small for her age _ slender and wiry, she looks more like
12 _ she is a teenager now, and treads the fuzzy line between
girlhood and adolescence. She hangs dinosaur posters and trades
Pokemon cards, but she loves the Backstreet Boys, and from time to
time, reports a crush.
</P>
<P>
   Her relationship with her parents teeters, too, between
affection and a teenager's shy embarrassment. When Debb calls her
``Sweetie bugs,'' Jennifer lowers her head, half-smiling,
half-pouting, and grumbles, ``Mom. Don't call me that.''
</P>
<P>
   Adolescence poses a new challenge for the Kings, who have
learned to care for Jennifer through instinct and dogged
involvement. They want her to be part of the world, and fought to
place her in a mainstream program at the high school.
</P>
<P>
   But they know she needs supervision, pointing to a day that,
when they learned of the Worcester fire, made them gasp with
recognition. About two years ago, at her sister Nancy's house,
Jennifer plugged in an electric lamp and settled down to watch
cartoons. Nancy heard the smoke alarm, ran downstairs, and saw that
the lamp was on fire. Jennifer was so focused on the television
that she hadn't noticed the flames.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings also fear the dangers other people can inflict on a
naive girl who is looking for more freedom. They recently grounded
her for visiting a friend's house without leaving a note. They
always want to know where she is going.
</P>
<P>
   But while they worry about Jennifer, they also boast of her
successes. ``She's just a great kid,'' Tim says. She reads at the
third-grade level, makes the honor roll each term, and visits the
local elementary school to help teach second-graders to read. She'd
like to work at a day-care center someday.
</P>
<P>
   Debb wants Jennifer to stay in high school as long as she can,
and then to get a job. ``How far is she going to go? Well, we don't
know,'' she said. But she is certain of this: ``I don't think
pushing grocery carts and doing minimum-wage jobs . . . is good
enough for her. I think she can do better.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
