<HEADLINE>
THIS IS A TEST FROM THE BOSTON GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; This is a test from the Boston Globe at 2 p.m. Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-00 1401EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000515.0126 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 14:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5499 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-SISTERS-INTERRUPTED-2     05-15 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SISTERS-INTERRUPTED-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 ELLSWORTH, Maine: ... do better.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The future, like the past, seems far more bleak for Julie
Barnes, some 280 miles away. Last fall, she scratched out a
transient existence in shelters and warehouses, free but sometimes
hungry or cold. This winter and spring, she has lived in a
Framingham, Mass. jail, sharing a cell and wearing prison garb, but
receiving at least one benefit she likely did not before: prenatal
care for the child who will be born before summer.
</P>
<P>
   The baby's father is Thomas Levesque, a hollow-cheeked man who
often was Julie's companion on the streets. They fought regularly,
sometimes violently, but they usually clung together. And they
squatted together in the Worcester Cold Storage and Warehouse Co.
building on the night of Dec. 3, before a fight and a knocked-over
candle led to the deadly fire.
</P>
<P>
   Three days later, after a manhunt, the pair was arrested. The
city was still in mourning; the six lost men had yet to be
recovered. The memorial, attended by 30,000 firefighters, had not
yet taken place. The warehouse was still smoldering.
</P>
<P>
   Julie Barnes and Levesque were placed in the custody of the same
state that had taken Julie's sister, Leeann, 16 years earlier. Bail
was set at $1 million apiece.
</P>
<P>
   In the years before, when the Department of Social Services
intervened less completely in Julie Barnes's life, she drifted
between her divorced parents' homes, living at times in New
Hampshire and at times in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   She was a quiet, baby-faced girl who carried small cats in her
backpack, wandered without a coat on cold evenings, and carved out
a secret hideaway in the hedges near her house. Acquaintances said
she was ``slow,'' a fact reflected by her childlike handwriting and
her enrollment in special education classes, before she dropped out
of high school.
</P>
<P>
   And they said she often bragged about relationships with men _
including Levesque, who, like Julie, has been described as slow.
Now, he lives at the state prison in West Boylston, Mass. awaiting
a pretrial conference in early June.
</P>
<P>
   The case is now in the discovery phase, said Julie's
court-appointed lawyer, Louis Aloise. Lawyers are studying reports
about the fire and considering motions. A trial probably would not
begin until the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, Julie Barnes waits in a maximum-security section of
the Framingham jail. She has had visitors: her mother, her mother's
companion, her mother's friends. But the days in jail have not been
easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's sad about being confined,'' Aloise said. ``She's still
having a difficult time comprehending why she has to stay in
jail.''
</P>
<P>
   In February, Julie's bail was reduced to $75,000, and Levesque's
to $250,000. Neither defendant's family has the money.
</P>
<P>
   Neither do the Kings. But they hope to raise it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer King has always known she was adopted. Her parents like
to tell her that they picked her out from hundreds of babies,
charmed by her smiling face.
</P>
<P>
   So when they pieced together the facts about Julie Barnes, they
told Jennifer right away. You have another sister, they said, and
she's in trouble. That much, Jennifer understands.
</P>
<P>
   ``She kind of got blamed,'' she told a visitor recently. ``It's
kind of sad.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings also told Jennifer about their plan for Julie's
future, devised after hours of family discussions and conversations
with lawyers. They want to bring Julie to Maine.
</P>
<P>
   They would take her to court appearances, Debb King says, and
help set her up with a more comfortable, nurturing life in between.
They hope she can live in a shelter or a halfway house, or possibly
with them. They want to persuade her to put her baby up for
adoption _ or, at least, to connect her quickly with a network of
social services.
</P>
<P>
   Debb King started to work on the project in December, sending
letters to senators and governors and state representatives. Only a
few responded. She called attorneys who had experience dealing with
disabled clients. Only a few called back.
</P>
<P>
   She understands the delicacy of the situation, the tremendous
grief that followed the Worcester fire, the human urge to find _
and punish _ the person who's responsible. Helping Julie, she
realizes, might not be a popular goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's been so publicized, I don't think they want to
get involved,'' she said. ``I get sympathy, but that's about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Debb hopes to visit Julie soon, and wants to take her for an
independent psychiatric evaluation before the trial. She feels a
sense of urgency, with the baby due next month.
</P>
<P>
   She has enlisted the help of Sister Lucille MacDonald, a local
nun who runs a homeless shelter and a transitional home for
pregnant women. She is accustomed to people with criminal records,
single mothers, the homeless.
</P>
<P>
   And she thinks Julie Barnes has a better chance for a fresh
start far from Worcester, in a place where few would recognize her
on the street _ except, perhaps, as someone who bears a striking
resemblance to Jennifer King.
</P>
<P>
   Julie Barnes knows about Jennifer, and is interested in meeting
her, Aloise said. As for the Kings' ambitions, Tim is more
hesitant. He wants to see her released on bail, but he knows the
cost is high.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's as realistic as their being able to raise $75,000,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings are trying. They have set up a bank fund, and are
hoping for donations. They continue to search for help.
</P>
<P>
   And they try to answer the questions their daughter raises at
the dinner table. Jennifer is curious about, and anxious to meet,
the sister who looks so much like her. She often asks when Julie is
coming to Maine. She wants it to be soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to help her,'' she recently told Debb. ``She's my
sister.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
