<HEADLINE>
ON NEW CD, PEARL JAM WANTS TO BE HEARD THROUGH BOTH EARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Amid a radio climate clogged with angry, testosterone-fueled
acts like Korn, Limp Bizkit, and Kid Rock, the Seattle band Pearl
Jam is suddenly standing out as elder statesmen. Pearl Jam had
spewed a similar anger when it helped launch the grunge movement in
the early '90s, but has since matured into a career act that favors
craftsmanship over blind rage.
</P>
<P>
   Pearl Jam's new single, ``Nothing As It Seems,'' even has a
pensive Pink Floyd-like sound. Written by bassist Jeff Ament, it is
``a dark, heavy tale,'' as he puts it, stemming from a conversation
overheard during a couple's breakup.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, it's a song about judgment and not always
understanding what is going on with another person,'' Ament said in
a telephone interview last week.
</P>
<P>
   The changes in Pearl Jam over the last decade are quite apparent
on its new album, ``Binaural,'' which comes out Tuesday. While
there are still some blistering rock tracks, the best songs are the
softer meditations, laced with atmospheres provided by new
co-producer Tchad Blake, who has worked with Suzanne Vega, Neil
Finn, Lisa Germano, and the American Music Club.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever thought that slower songs would outdistance the rockers
on a Pearl Jam album? Certainly not rock radio stations, some of
which have balked at the new single. KROQ, the Los Angeles giant,
did not play ``Nothing As It Seems'' when it was released, but has
since relented.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody in the band felt good about the song, because it was
different from what we had done before,'' said Ament. ``And as
artists, you're always trying to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   The new album is a demanding record and will take some extra
listening for many Pearl Jam fans. The results are mixed. Give the
band credit for sonic experimentation, but there's a sense that the
band may actually have spent too much time in the studio. The
recording process, under Blake's tutelage, ``was more methodical
this time and took a year,'' said guitarist Mike McCready, who
admitted that the slowest songs initially came out better. Because
of dissatisfaction with how they sounded, the band asked former
producer Brendan O'Brien to come in and remix them.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the rock tracks have problems. The opening
``Breakerfall,'' despite a sharp McCready guitar intro taken from
The Who's ``I Can See for Miles,'' never fully lifts off. Nor does
``Evacuation,'' a muddy version of a rote rave-up. A better effort
is ``Grievance,'' a punky, Eddie Vedder-penned tune in which he
sings of how the innocent are crushed in American society. Thus:
``I pledge my grievance to the flag.''
</P>
<P>
   Vedder also contributes the bizarre but likable ``Soon Forget,''
in which he plays a ukulele and sings about a money-hoarding loser
who dies ``clutching benjamins'' in his hand. ``Ed and Chris
Cornell (formerly of Seattle peers Soundgarden) had talked about
how hard it is to write a sad song on ukulele,'' said McCready.
``So Ed took that as a challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the key move for Pearl Jam is that Vedder has stepped
back to let his bandmates write more songs in recent years. ``It's
definitely more democratic now,'' said Ament. ``If Ed wanted us to
make an album of just his songs, we'd probably do it. But it makes
it better for the band if he's giving us respect back.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the best new songs come from rhythm guitarist Stone
Gossard. His standout is ``Thin Air,'' a gentle accoustic-flavored
love song that Vedder sings to perfection. ``There's a light when
my baby's in my arms,'' goes the central verse. It is Pearl Jam at
its least complex _ and as pretty a song as these guys have ever
done.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parting Ways,'' with a lovely cello line topping a lyric about
another pair of lovers contemplating a breakup, is the album's
final song.
</P>
<P>
   The album title, ``Binaural,'' means to ``listen with both
ears,'' said McCready. It also was the name given to the dummy
placed in the studio by the eccentric Blake, who put microphones in
each of its ears. ``We had it looming over us,'' McCready said with
a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   This may be the most cerebral album Pearl Jam has made. It runs
against the grain of contemporary rock radio, but despite its
glitches, shows a band still breathing plenty of life.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're having a good time and we'll probably do up to eight of
these new songs on the road,'' said McCready, whose group plays the
Tweeter Center Aug. 28 and 29. ``This feels like a rebirth for us.
I know that sounds like Spinal Tap, but I'm really excited. It's
always good to push boundaries.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
