<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-FALL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S JUDGMENT DAY FOR TELEVISION NETWORKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are more than 200 million television viewers in the United
States, and the networks absolutely love, honor, and cherish each
and every one of them.
</P>
<P>
   But there are some TV watchers the networks love best of all:
media buyers. It is those presumed savants of the advertising world
who advise their clients to buy commercial time on this sitcom or
that drama, and it is they who will be judge and jury as the annual
``upfront'' presentations begin in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Commercial revenue being the lifeblood of television, this week
is crucial for NBC, CBS, ABC, Fox, UPN, and the WB as they take
turns unveiling their fall lineups before about 1,000 media buyers,
corporate bigwigs, and reporters. Sure, the upfront means an end to
suspense for fans of shows such as ``Sports Night,'' ``City of
Angels,'' and ``Felicity'' because they'll finally learn whether
the programs have been canceled or renewed. But the upfront
showcase is primarily about dueling for dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Clips from dozens of new pilots will be screened, network
executives will test the legal limits of hyperbole in lauding said
pilots, and the big names of prime time will drop by to sprinkle a
little stardust on the proceedings. ``This is their first target
audience, and they want to generate excitement about their new
shows, because Madison Avenue is going to commit literally billions
of dollars to these shows,'' said J. Max Robins, a senior editor at
TV Guide. ``They want to wow them.''
</P>
<P>
   Some networks, of course, are under more pressure than others to
deliver a boffo performance. According to numerous advertising
executives, the Fox and WB networks _ which suffered through
lackluster seasons _ have the most to prove. But CBS and NBC also
have holes to fill; the Peacock Network in particular needs to show
it has regained its Midas touch when it comes to comedies.
Front-running ABC, meanwhile, needs to coo only six words in the
ears of skittish advertisers: ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire.''
The network may even add a fourth night of the ratings blockbuster,
more bad news for competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only does it eat everything in its path but it creates a
built-in audience to expose other ABC programs,'' said John Rash,
senior vice president at Campbell Mithun Esty in Minneapolis.
``Everyone in the industry is still trying to figure out why `Who
Wants to Be a Millionaire' is so successful.''
</P>
<P>
   While they continue scratching their heads about that, the TV
picture will get clearer in other respects this week. Based on
Globe interviews and forecasts published in USA Today and Variety,
the fall season shapes up as a parade of familiar faces in new
guises.
</P>
<P>
   The current season has been notably strong when it comes to new
dramas (``The West Wing,'' ``Once and Again,'' ``Judging Amy''),
and notably weak when it comes to new comedies (only Fox's
``Malcolm in the Middle'' is a bona fide hit). But the networks
seem determined to try, try again. NBC is expected to dump
``Veronica's Closet,'' finally answering the prayers of TV critics
everywhere, while also brooming ``Stark Raving Mad'' and ``Jesse.''
That will clear room for new sitcoms, including a detective comedy
starring Michael Richards (Kramer on ``Seinfeld''). Moreover,
according to Variety, NBC may take the bold step of moving
``Frasier'' from Thursday at 9 p.m. _ one of the premier slots in
prime time _ to Tuesday, and replacing it with critically acclaimed
``Will &AMP; Grace,'' which now airs on Tuesday. NBC averted a major
problem Sunday when the cast of ``Friends'' accepted a contract for
two more years.
</P>
<P>
   ``NBC faces a challenge because they've had a bunch of slippage
in more time periods than the other guys,'' said Bill Cella,
executive vice president of broadcasting and programming at
Universal McCann in New York. ``The `Millionaire' juggernaut has
affected their Thursday night.''
</P>
<P>
   At ABC, 5 of the 11 new pilots are also sitcoms, including
``Lost and Found,'' starring Geena Davis as a single woman who
marries a widower with children. According to USA Today, CBS is
likely to weigh in with a sitcom starring Bette Midler and another
with former ``Cybill'' star Christine Baranski, while the WB will
offer ``Hype,'' a comedy about a Las Vegas showgirl, and UPN is
likely to offer two sitcoms, ``Girlfriends,'' about the friendship
of four women, and ``One on One,'' a look at the life of a TV
sports reporter. Fox, meanwhile, is hoping the producing team of
Marcy Carsey and Tom Werner (``That '70s Show,'' ``Roseanne'') can
deliver another hit with ``Don't Ask,'' a comedy starring John
Goodman as a gay father in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's looking for a comedy,'' said TV Guide's Robins.
</P>
<P>
   But advertisers are looking for evidence that the networks have
figured out ways to put a new face on the increasingly stale sitcom
format. ``There are a lot of sitcoms out there that look and sound
alike,'' said Steve Grubbs, executive vice president of broadcast
buying at BBDO Inc., a New York advertising agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking for concepts that are a little different,'' added
Grubbs. ``If you look at the successes over the past few years, the
shows that have really broken through to become hits are those that
have utilized a formula that hasn't been on the air for a while or
that have created a whole new genre: `The X-Files,' `The Simpsons,'
`Millionaire.' ''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Grubbs predicted that the quest for little-used genres
might make this the year when the variety show has a comeback. The
``reality'' genre also might gain more steam, despite the debacle
of Fox's ``Who Wants to Marry a Multimillionaire?,'' if CBS is
successful this summer with ``Survivor'' and ``Big Brother.''
</P>
<P>
   Network-owned shows are expected to have the upper hand in
getting on the schedule because of the profits they bring in
syndication, meaning that independent producers and studios will
fight uphill battles. ``It seems that 30 to 40 percent of the shows
they are looking at are owned by the networks,'' said Michael A.
Guariglia, a former CBS sales executive who is now director of
national broadcast buying for Hill Holliday Connors Cosmopulos.
``Those are the ones that are going to get special attention.''
</P>
<P>
   However, certain superstar producers will be able to buck the
trend. At Fox, for instance, three good bets include ``The
Teachers,'' a drama about a Boston-area high school from David E.
Kelley (``The Practice,'' ``Ally McBeal''); ``Don't Ask,'' the
Goodman comedy; and ``The Street,'' a show about Wall Street
brokers from Darren Star (``Beverly Hills 90210,'' ``Sex and the
City''). At NBC, ``Law &AMP; Order'' producer Dick Wolf will supervise
a new drama about an investigative reporter, titled ``Deadline''
and starring Oliver Platt.
</P>
<P>
   This week will either answer or dash the prayers of fervent fans
of certain shows. Devotees of NBC's canceled ``Freaks and Geeks,''
for instance, have been waging a long-shot crusade to get another
network to pick up the show. Fans of ``Homicide'' may see a return
of series star Andre Braugher in an ABC drama called ``Gideon's
Crossing.'' The legions who can't get enough of ``The Fugitive''
may see a remake surface on CBS with Tim Daly of ``Wings.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
