<HEADER>
A5508 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-CULTURE-SEX-BOS &LR;      05-15 1698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-SEX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AND YOU THOUGHT YOU KNEW ABOUT THE SEXUAL REVOLUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOT LEHIGH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When a revolution passes far enough into history that the
revolutionaries start dying of old age and long histories begin to
appear, it's time for a look back at the epoch.
</P>
<P>
   Which means the moment has arrived to consider the sexual
revolution.
</P>
<P>
   After all, Alex Comfort, the British physician whose book ``The
Joy of Sex: A Gourmet Guide to Lovemaking'' became an early '70s
emblem of the avant-garde, passed away in March at age 80, almost
as David Allyn's ``Make Love, Not War: The Sexual Revolution, An
Unfettered History'' came into print.
</P>
<P>
   Allyn's book chronicles the erotic liberation that supposedly
started with the publication of Helen Gurley Brown's ``Sex and the
Single Girl'' in 1962, gathered momentum with the women's
liberation and gay and lesbian movements, reached its apex (or
nadir) with wide-release pornographic films, open marriages, and
spouse-swapping in the 1970s, then receded before the onset of
herpes and AIDS in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   That trajectory has become part of the sacred and irreverent
history of the baby boom. But if, as Oscar Wilde quipped, the one
duty we owe history is to rewrite it, what can be said of the era
of Eros?
</P>
<P>
   Herewith, a few things you may not have known about sex, but
which, after the revolution, you would hardly have been afraid to
ask. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Ages of innocence and experience &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One occupational hazard of being a baby boomer is a tendency to
confuse their generation's history with that of the world. Yet a
scrupulous review of the historical record suggests that boomers
were neither the first to have sex nor even the first to rebel
against a conservative social ethic.
</P>
<P>
   Consider this account: ``Many people, especially the young,
wanted to experiment with sensual pleasures _ drugs, `free love,'
new kinds of poetry and decorative designs.
</P>
<P>
   Sound familiar? Well, if you're a boomer, it should . . . to
your great-great-great-grandparents. It's a description of the
sexual revolution that swept Europe and North America after the
Crimean War (1853-56) had rattled the moral code of the time.
</P>
<P>
   War has long occasioned a rethinking of societal mores, and if
the culture of questioning coincident with the Vietnam War
catalyzed the most recent sexual revolution, the Crimean War and
World War I seem to have had similar effects in their eras.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been at least three sexual revolutions in the last
150 years,'' notes Dennis P. Sugrue, a clinical psychologist and
president-elect of the American Association of Sex Educators,
Counselors, and Therapists. ``Then . . . in the next generation
there is a kind of pulling back.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Bedtime stories &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While college students may have tumbled into bed in the '60s and
'70s with the abandon that comes of altered consciousness, as a
whole young Americans weren't nearly as promiscuous as the term
``sexual revolution'' suggests.
</P>
<P>
   Not, at least, according to what is widely recognized as the
best information, ``The Social Organization of Sexuality,'' a
data-packed tome based on in-depth 1992 surveys of 3,432 adults by
a team of University of Chicago social scientists.
</P>
<P>
   Two demographic groups in that study can be said to have come of
age during the daze of the sexual revolution. Among men born
between 1943 and 1952, 53.4 percent said by age 30 they had had
four or fewer sex partners. For men born between 1953 and 1962, 51
percent said the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   For women born between 1943-1952, 82.2 percent claimed four or
fewer partners by age 30. Among those born from 1953 to 1962, 77.5
said they had had four or fewer partners by the same age. &QL; 
 &QL; 
A (not so brave) new world &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although conservatives regularly paint American culture as
hopelessly dissolute, by the standards of our European
contemporaries, we are actually pillars of sexual rectitude.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1998 paper, a team of sociologists compared attitudes in 24
European and Asian countries on four issues: premarital sex,
teenage sex, extramarital sex, and homosexual sex.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans are among the most sexually conservative in the
Western world,'' reports Eric Widmer, an assistant professor of
sociology at the University of Geneva and coauthor of the scholarly
paper about sexual attitudes.
</P>
<P>
   For example, with 80 percent of Americans surveyed saying
extramarital sex was always wrong, we were among the least tolerant
of adultery.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-one percent of Americans said premarital sex was always or
almost always wrong, making us prudes by European standards. For
example, only 6 percent of Swedes frowned on premarital sex, and
only 25 percent of Russians said nyet. &QL; 
 &QL; 
The kids are all right &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the last year, The New York Times, The Washington Post, and
Talk magazine have all done stories about the supposed nonchalance
with which young teens engage in oral sex.
</P>
<P>
   And yet others insist that paints an inaccurate portrait of
today's teenagers. One who holds that view is William Strauss,
coauthor of ``Generations,'' the social history documenting the
conflicting values, attitudes, and aspirations of each generation.
Strauss, who with coauthor Neil Howe has studied (and surveyed)
members of the generation born after 1982 for their book
``Millennials Rising,'' due out in September, sees a set of
distinctly different sexual attitudes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They speak more openly about sex than boomers did when they
were teenagers, but their attitudes are more conservative than you
would have heard from teenagers in the 1960s,'' says Strauss. In
part, he says, that's a reaction against the generations above
them, in part a testament to the new peer-group power held by high
school girls.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is now more acceptable to be sexually abstinent or to go
slow,'' says Strauss. ``If in the 1960s there was more going on
than adults knew, in the year 2000 there is in all likelihood less
going on than adults think.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he stresses evidence is lacking, Dr. John Bancroft,
director of the Kinsey Institute, agrees that young people seem
more sexually circumspect.
</P>
<P>
   ``The impression one gets . . . is that we have been moving from
a more liberated to a more cautious era at the end of the 20th
century,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   For all the talk about enduring changes that find their root in
the so-called Sexual Revolution, the clearest differences are two:
society became more tolerant of premarital sex and women began to
catch up with men in sexual experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Premarital sex is now widely accepted, which means that both
men and women move into relationships with more knowledge, more
experience, and more expectations,'' says Shirley Zussman, a
Manhattan-based sex and marital therapist.
</P>
<P>
   And though gender differences still exist, the University of
Chicago study reveals a greater parity of experience for those who
came of age since the mid-'60s.
</P>
<P>
   Consider: 54.4 percent of women born between 1933-42 were
virgins when they married, and 21.9 percent of men. Among women
born after 1953, some 20 percent were virgins, only about 4 percent
higher than men's also lowered figure.
</P>
<P>
   Another sense of the change comes from these figures: 67 percent
of women born from 1933-42 reported having had only one sexual
partner by the time they turned 30, with 25.5 percent saying two to
four partners, and 2.6 percent saying they had had sex with five or
more people.
</P>
<P>
   However, for women born from 1952-62, only 35.6 percent claimed
just one partner, while 40 percent said two to four partners, and
22.4 percent said they had had sex with five or more people.
</P>
<P>
   And though unmarried women ages 18 to 29 had fewer partners in a
given year than unmarried men of the same age, as a population
segment, they were slightly less likely to have had no sexual
partners at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``The double standard lessened during this time,'' says
Bancroft, of the Kinsey Institute.
</P>
<P>
   But if women have claimed the right to stigma-free sexual
experience, most of that sex takes place within a defined
relationship of some sort, says Shirley Glass, a Maryland clinical
psychologist and relationship expert.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though women are having sex earlier and more frequently,
they still tend to link sex with an emotional attachment, and that
is across the board, premarital and extramarital,'' Glass says.
``That has been one of the most consistent gender differences.''
</P>
<P>
   And if the country has essentially accepted sexual liberation
for the unmarried, we have not experienced the sort of widespread
loosening of marital ties that once might have been expected with
the advent of open marriages, group marriages, and swinging couples
that made headlines in the late 1960s and '70s. Indeed, Edward O.
Laumann, the University of Chicago sociologist and lead author of
``The Social Organization of Sexuality,'' says that only about 4
percent of Americans have sex with someone other than their spouse
in any given year. &QL; 
 &QL; 
You can talk talk talk about it &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One last legacy is a cultural candor that hasn't gone away,
despite the conservative backlash against erotic excess.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pick up any women's magazine and there are three or four
articles about how to make better love, how to please your partner,
how to orgasm, and so forth,'' says Sugrue, the association
president.
</P>
<P>
   Not only just any women's magazine, actually. Cosmo Girl, meet
Maxim Guy. The so-called lad mags feature the same kind of how-to
articles, with advice for men on how to please women.
</P>
<P>
   That reflects a widespread acceptance of, and emphasis on,
relational sex for pleasure's sake _ but responsible pleasure.
What's happened, argues David Brooks in his new book, ``Bobos in
Paradise,'' is that mainstream America has appropriated the
bohemian value of sexual pleasure-seeking but imposed on it a
bourgeois emphasis on self-control and respectability.
</P>
<P>
   ``The erotic section in Barnes &AMP; Noble owes more to the
University of Iowa writing program than to anything subversive,''
says Brooks. ``What was countercultural and daring . . . has been
subsumed into respectable mainstream culture.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
