<HEADER>
A5516 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-SHUTKIN-BOS &LR;      05-15 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-SHUTKIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENVIRONMENTALISM THAT FACTORS IN THE PEOPLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT BRAILE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
THE LAND THAT COULD BE 
Environmental Environmentalism and Democracy in the Twenty-First
Century 
By William A. Shutkin. MIT Press. 340 pp. $27.95. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In ``The Land That Could Be,'' William A. Shutkin argues that a
new era of ``civic environmentalism'' is underway in America,
rooted in a kind of democracy that revives communities and
political participation, reconciles racial and socioeconomic
inequities, and reverses the recent tide of privatization with
renewed public investment.
</P>
<P>
   If that sounds ambitious, it is. Shutkin is the latest of
several authors seeking to redefine environmentalism, making it
more egalitarian and less elitist, more hopeful and less gloomy, a
movement that ultimately finds a comfortable place for people in
nature.
</P>
<P>
   For Shutkin, civic environmentalism is already healing the
nation's cultural as well as ecological ills, reflecting the
desires of 19th-century Vermont conservationist George Perkins
Marsh and 20th-century Harlem poet Langston Hughes, who in
different ways called on America to engage ``in the project of
becoming co-workers with nature.''
</P>
<P>
   Civic environmentalism ``marries these two American visions,
creating a whole equal to the task of rebuilding America's
communities from the ground up, of repairing the damaged social and
environmental fabric that is American society at the beginning of
the twenty-first century,'' Shutkin writes.
</P>
<P>
   As promising as that may be, Shutkin _ who cofounded Boston's
Alternatives for Community &AMP; Environment and teaches at MIT and
Boston College _ is not up to the task of exploring it. There is
much to praise in his book, but it suffers from thin reporting and
breezy analysis, driven by euphemism more than evidence to suggest
that civic environmentalism is more accomplished than it actually
is.
</P>
<P>
   More troubling is Shutkin's ambivalence toward rural America. On
the one hand, he sees civic environmentalism occurring in urban,
suburban, and rural America, offering four case studies reflecting
that. On the other hand, he is often dismissive of rural America,
based on a questionable sense that the country's worst ecological
threats are necessarily in cities, imperiling the poor and minority
people who by and large live there.
</P>
<P>
   He at one point describes rural New England villages as
pristine, when those who have spent time in them would be hard
pressed to characterize them that favorably. At another point, he
seems surprised to discover hard times in rural Colorado.
``Although there are few people of color in Routt County, save for
the migrant ranch hands and ski resort workers who pass in and out
of the area, there is poverty and disaffection.''
</P>
<P>
   At best, this ambivalence suggests an author at odds with
himself, wanting to write a book that is not exclusively urban, but
not sure how the rural landscape fits in. Part of Shutkin's
difficulty lies in environmentalism's historic bias against the
urban landscape, which Shutkin sketchily chronicles, but rightfully
criticizes. That bias dates at least to Thoreau and persists to
this day in a pastoral-chic enclave of elitists who simply will not
get their hands dirty with real ecological problems, urban or
rural. And that enclave is growing.
</P>
<P>
   But at worst, Shutkin's ambivalence reveals a politically
correct, urban-chic bias, fostering an urban environmental elitism
no more constructive or defensible than the rural environmental
elitism he criticizes. Yes, many cities are wastelands and many
urbanites are at risk. But has Shutkin seen what logging has done
to rural Maine, mining to rural Montana, nuclear weapons testing to
rural Nevada? Shutkin fails to discern the enclave from the rest of
rural America, whose struggles are largely being ignored by both
the pastoral-chic and urban-chic celebrants of American
environmentalism.
</P>
<P>
   Shutkin adequately details the country's ``civic decline'' and
its ecological harm. But his six-point solution (democratic
process, community and regional planning, education, environmental
justice, industrial ecology, and place) reads more like a
candidate's position paper or consultant's mission statement than
an environmentalist's vision.
</P>
<P>
   And his case studies are unconvincing. The Dudley Neighborhood's
urban agriculture experiment in Boston is impressive, but
incipient. Oakland, Calif.'s, Fruitvale Transit Village is
underway, but just one project. Both pose contradictions he skims
over. He rants, for instance, about the waste sites in cities like
Boston and Oakland, yet is nonchalant about the liability and
toxicity issues in cleanups crucial to the cities' efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Shutkin's study of Routt County's ``community-based conservation
and conservation-based development'' is his weakest, describing so
many plans, strategies, and visions without much happening on the
ground that, he concedes, residents joked about being ``blinded by
vision.'' And his study of New Jersey's ``smart growth, community
planning, and cooperation'' is much the same, a compilation of
planning activities neither new nor remarkable, or new and
remarkable but not yet effecting change.
</P>
<P>
   Shutkin has admirably tried to articulate a shift in American
environmentalism. He needs to ponder harder about why it is
occurring, where it is evident, and whether it really will make a
difference in how Americans see their relationship with nature.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Braile is a Globe correspondent who covers the
environment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-00 1412EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
