<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 14:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5518 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-SAUNDERS-BOS &LR;      05-15 1088
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-SAUNDERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICA THE CHEESY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL REZENDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
PASTORALIA 
By George Saunders. Riverhead. 188 pp. $22.95. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Four years ago George Saunders's first story collection,
``CivilWarLand in Bad Decline,'' established him as a searing
satirist with a peculiar sensibility that allows him to wreak havoc
on a cheesy American landscape that is often uproariously
implausible yet sickeningly familiar. In ``Pastoralia,'' the title
story of his latest collection, Saunders returns with a favored
device that introduces us to another of his imaginary theme parks
set approximately 15 minutes into the vaguely Orwellian future.
</P>
<P>
   This time we're ushered to a futuristic exhibit of prehistory
where a hapless cave man employee, ``Thinking Positive/Saying
Positive,'' is being pressured by the corporate powers that be to
inform on his harried cave woman co-worker. Her offenses include
exhibiting pathetic modern-day human behavioral traits, such as
smoking and using ``freaking English'' instead of cave woman
grunts, to bemoan her sorrowful efforts to support her drug-abusing
son and ailing mother.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part this is fiercely funny. But when the twist
comes _ slowly, subtly, in a wave of unwanted recognition _ it's a
piercing indictment of the paranoia and boosterism that define the
modern workplace.
</P>
<P>
   Saunders's trademark theme parks are absent from the remaining
stories here. Which isn't necessarily a blessing, since we are
taken instead to that terrifying terrain that has become so
pervasive that many of us pretend it doesn't exist: the strip
malls, food courts, and tacky subdivisions plastered along the
infinite ``Self-Storage Parkway'' at the schlocky fringe of the
American Dream. Of course, we've all been hit with good-sense
warnings about suburban sprawl. But Saunders focuses on the
repellent personal stories at the vast existential margins,
conjuring a desert of discount outlets such as FoodSoQuik,
DrugTown, and HardwareNiche _ all the while reminding us there are
real people out there.
</P>
<P>
   People like Neil Yaniky, a diminutive, balding figure trapped in
a motivational seminar at a nondescript Hyatt, whose chief concern
is that everyone there will be able to tell ``he was a big stupid
faker, because he had no career, really, and no business, but only
soldered little triangular things in his basement, for forty-seven
cents a little triangular thing, for CompuParts, although he had
high hopes for something better, which is why he was here.''
</P>
<P>
   In many ways Yaniky is Saunders's prototypical antihero: a
physically repugnant, self-loathing product of anonymous housing
tracts and fast food restaurants burdened with clinging dependents,
low-wage employment, and radically attenuated hopes and dreams.
</P>
<P>
   But hopes and dreams nonetheless. At a minimum, Saunders's
characters inevitably hope for a better job _ something a tad
classier than, say, a gig waiting tables at ``JoySticks,'' where
each member of the all-male wait staff is obliged to offer the
occasional glimpse at a certain anatomical part, hoping the
customers don't send his ``Cute Rating'' plunging from ``Honeypie''
to ``Stinker.'' Yet it is painfully clear that, in their wildest
dreams, what Saunders's characters really yearn for is just the
slightest assurance _ from an unfeeling spouse, an uncaring parent,
or the unforgiving world at large _ that their utterly anonymous
and painfully insignificant lives somehow matter.
</P>
<P>
   By and large, these are people who play by the rules only to
suffer profound disappointment. In ``Sea Oak,'' a horror story set
in a mythical housing tract where ``there's no sea and no oak, just
a hundred subsidized apartments and a rear view of FedEx,'' a
doting aunt with a grotesque surprise for her nieces and
grandnieces suddenly asks, ``Why do some people got everything and
I got nothing?''
</P>
<P>
   In many cases, the dream of being merely seen assumes ridiculous
proportions. In ``The Falls,'' an office gofer who admits having
spent ``the best years of his life swearing at a photocopier'' idly
imagines a better life: ``If only he could escape BlasCorp and do
something significant, such as discover a critical vaccine. But it
was too late, and he had never been good at biology and in fact had
flunked it twice. But some kind of moment in the sun would
certainly not be unwelcome.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Saunders is under 40, it can safely be said that he is
already a master of the self-flagellating interior monologue. Time
and again, his characters roam the subdivided earth berating
themselves for their looks, their innumerable failures of nerve,
and their inability either to luck into fame or to rack up the sort
of improbable achievements that would garner the most singular
assurance society has to offer: a TV interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``If only he could be part of some great historical event like
the codgers he saw on PBS who had been slugged in the Haymarket
Riot or known Medgar Evers or lost beatific mothers on the
Titanic,'' the office gofer laments. ``His childhood dreams had
been so bright, he had hoped for so much, it couldn't be true that
he was a nobody.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is true _ though maybe not. For there are chinks of
strange light refracted through the darkness of Saunders's satire.
Admittedly, we leave most of his characters resigned to their
subsistence-level doom. Yaniky, for instance, returns to his
miserable home filled with motivational self-knowledge and the
determination to evict his clinging, mildly retarded sister from
the premises _ only to weaken at the sight of ``the poor dorky
thing.'' And in ``Firpo in the World,'' when an overweight
youngster ridiculed by his mother and most of his neighbors is
finally told that he's beautiful and that God loves him, the words
come only at the moment of his death from the motorist who has just
collided with his bicycle.
</P>
<P>
   But Saunders allows other characters moments of undeniable
grace, however twisted. In ``The Barber's Unhappiness,'' an
overweight, middle-aged hairclipper still living with his mother
somehow finds the courage to ask an unattractive woman for a date _
opening a door to unfathomable possibility.
</P>
<P>
   And in the final story, ``The Falls,'' that self-flagellating
office gofer is suddenly presented with a chance to become all that
he has yearned to be. It's an unexpected and truly frightening
prospect, and at the same time a perfect ending for this second,
striking collection.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-00 1414EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000515.0136 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 14:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5521 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-LATINOS-BOS &LR;      05-15 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-LATINOS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASSESSING THE LIVES OF US LATINOS PAST AND PRESENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TATIANA WITH RIBADENEIRA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
Harvest of Empire: A History of Latinos in America 
By Juan Gonzalez 
Viking. 346 pp. $27.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the latter part of the last century, the growth of Latinos in
this country _ particularly in California and Texas _ sparked a
heated backlash against newcomers. In this country of immigrants,
the battle cry became to seal off our borders and take away any
rights from those we deemed not to belong.
</P>
<P>
   It wouldn't be the first time Americans expressed such nativist
feelings; we have suffered many xenophobic waves. But as Juan
Gonzalez explains in ``Harvest of Empire,'' the United States has
only itself to blame for this immigrant influx. America reaps what
it has sowed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Latin America had not been raped and pillaged by U.S.
capital since its independence,'' argues Gonzalez, ``millions of
desperate workers would not now be coming here in such numbers to
reclaim a share of that wealth.'' Gonzalez, a journalist and Puerto
Rican community activist, carefully buttresses that argument with
hundreds of interviews and painstaking research. The result is a
sweeping study of the US role in the Americas, its consequences,
and the state of Latinos in this country today.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez carries out this ambitious undertaking expertly,
presenting eye-opening facts and wonderful histories of Latino
families. At times, however, his extensive research interrupts his
prose, making some parts of his account burdensome.
</P>
<P>
   In the first section of the book, cleverly called ``Roots,'' or
``Las Raices,'' Gonzalez juxtaposes the development of colonial
societies on the American continent, showing how the culture of the
English-speaking northern settlers differed radically from that of
their Spanish-speaking counterparts to the south. He broadly
examines the two societies' approaches to race, religion, land, and
politics to explain why the United States evolved into a superpower
while Latin America declined.
</P>
<P>
   It's a history lesson unknown to most Americans. When Spain's
colonies were moving toward independence in the early 1800s,
Gonzalez points out, they ``were far richer in resources,
territory, and population than the infant United States.''
</P>
<P>
   What happened? American imperialism _ both political and
economic.
</P>
<P>
   In an indictment of American actions toward its neighbors,
Gonzalez describes how this nation usurped Florida and a chunk of
Mexican land north of the Rio Grande, pretended to protect Latin
America's nascent nations from future European colonization, and
then proceeded to conquer Latin America itself. The leaders of this
country acquired Cuba and Puerto Rico after the Spanish-American
War, expanded into Panama to build the canal, and encouraged the
creation of financially dependent and politically manageable banana
republics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Branches,'' or ``Las Ramas,'' the book's second section, is
the most compelling. Gonzalez relates the stories of a handful of
families, including his own, to explain immigration patterns from
various Latin American countries. We learn why these people fled
their homelands for our shores, as well as how they were received
and adjusted to life in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, we meet the Gonzalezes, who came from US-controlled Puerto
Rico to New York in 1946. We meet the Canales family of South
Texas, which traces its lineage in the area _ then Mexico _ to the
1640s. We get to know Luis Del Rosario, who came from Cuba in 1979,
and learn how the US government has helped Cubans settle here since
the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez introduces us to the Dominican Lucianos, who fled a
US-tolerated dictatorship and the mayhem that followed its
US-supported toppling; the Whites, West Indians who lived and
worked in the segregated Panama Canal Zone; the Mendez family, who
escaped from a violent, drug-infested Colombia. We also meet
Guatemalans, Salvadorans, and Nicaraguans who were forced to
emigrate because of US-backed civil wars in their countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harvest,'' or ``La Cosecha,'' the book's culmination, is a
veritable paella, filled with so many ingredients that it borders
on being too freewheeling. Gonzalez examines Latino political
activism during the last 50 years, reveals little-known cultural
contributions Latinos have made to this country, and debunks
prevailing myths about Latin Americans. No, they don't come here to
soak up welfare benefits, but contribute significantly to US
society in taxes and Social Security payments. Latino immigrants do
not steal jobs from US citizens, but have improved local economies
by taking lower-wage jobs that others don't want.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez also dissects the impact of free trade in Latin
America, the battle over language, culture, and assimilation, and
the Puerto Rican experience, recommending that the United States
make its last colony an associated republic.
</P>
<P>
   In the epilogue, Gonzalez enumerates changes in national policy
toward Latinos, including ending the cheap labor market in Mexico,
colonial status in Puerto Rico, US militarism in Latin America, and
the economic blockade in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez overreached, perhaps, in ``Harvest of Empire.'' But as
the number of Hispanics in America is expected to swell to more
than 40 million by 2010, his passionate portrayal of a people whose
encounters with the United States in their lands and ours has been
difficult and heart-wrenching needs to be part of the national
dialogue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-00 1415EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
