<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-CROOKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN HIS OWN LEAGUE, WOODY ALLEN HAS FIGURED OUT HOW TO WIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL BLOWEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's the morning after the New York Knicks beat the Miami Heat
in the second game of their playoff series, and just a few hours
before Woody Allen will show his latest film, ``Small Time
Crooks,'' to an audience of Harvard students at the Harvard Square
Theater before it opens Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in clothes that seem leftover from his days as a
stand-up comic in the Village in the '60s _ brown corduroy pants
and a beige crew-neck sweater over a blue-striped button-down shirt
_ Allen speaks openly and easily about these two predominant
interests of his, basketball and movies. And about their striking
similarities.
</P>
<P>
   There's a moment in his new film when Allen's character and his
incompetent colleagues are tunneling through a cellar wall in the
basement of a cookie store in an attempt to rob a bank a few doors
down. One guy is shoveling the dirt onto another shovel held by a
second guy, who transfers the load into a trash bag. To Allen's
mind, that's not very efficient. When he comments on it, though,
one of his cronies shouts out something about teamwork. And while
the real-life Allen has written, directed, and starred in 31 films
over a movie career that started in 1965, he understands the value
of teamwork as well as any NBA head coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``For years the problem with the Knicks was bad casting,'' he
says. ``It was like having a good, solid movie with a dull cast.
Five years ago they had no interesting players. They might grind
out a win but it wasn't fun to watch. Now they have a star _
Latrell Sprewell. He's a charismatic leader. They're fun to watch .
. . and they win, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm much more liberal than any coach,'' he says, pursuing the
connection. ``I let the actors change lines, make suggestions,
whatever they want. That's why I cast people like Tracey Ullman and
Jon Lovitz and Elaine May in this picture. I want them to make
suggestions. To feel comfortable with their characters.''
</P>
<P>
   And no NBA head coach has had the kind of longevity and success
that Allen has managed in his competitive team sport. It has helped
that his small but devoted American following is supplemented by
huge popularity in Europe. But a prime reason Allen has succeeded _
in an industry where the Monday-morning box-office reports are now
read the way the NBA standings are, as a definitive record of
winning and losing _ is that he's very good at managing the
movie-biz version of the salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep my budgets down,'' he says. ``The average movie is made
for $34 million, $35 million, and I made this one for $15 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the actors know that we can't offer them $10 million or
$20 million per picture,'' he continues. ``I send them the script
and if they want the part, they'll do it. It's $50,000 and that's
it. I was very lucky to get Sean Penn for `Sweet and Lowdown.' It's
the movies' equivalent of pro bono work.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
He shall scrimp and save &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What about casting himself?
</P>
<P>
   ``My acting talents are very limited,'' says a suddenly serious
Allen. ``I can play low-lifes, which is what I am, and an
intellectual _ because of the way I look _ which I am not. People
have this impression of me as an intellectual but I'm like Ray, the
guy I play in the movie: I'd rather stay home and eat turkey
meatballs and drink beer and watch sports on television. Honest.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's all the talk about limited budgets but Allen is
suddenly reminded of a time early in his career when he was married
to Louise Lasser, and they played in a regular poker game with
other couples.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played for very little,'' he recalls. ``Maybe you could
lose $100 or $150 a night. Slowly, that started to climb until one
night I heard Louise say to the wife of a composer friend, `I'll
see your $1,500 and raise you $1,500.' That was it.''
</P>
<P>
   This aversion to high-rolling is an attitude that has helped him
as he enters his fifth decade of filmmaking.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not as vulnerable if the stakes are low,'' he agrees.
``Also, I've been very lucky to have studio people and producers
who protect me. Arthur Krim at United Artists. And Mike Medavoy.
And now (producer) Jean Doumanian. I'm very lucky to have had them
for patrons.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Small Time Crooks,'' an obvious homage to ``The
Honeymooners,'' Allen mixes sight gags and jokes with self-assured
character development.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I started, I didn't have much confidence,'' he says of
how his approach has changed over the years. ``So in those early
films _ `Take the Money and Run' and `Bananas' _ I was going for
gag, gag, gag. I was afraid to stop. Now, I get the laughs from the
characters.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mooning over `The Honeymooners' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And one character that Allen himself laughs at is Jackie
Gleason.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was writing for (Sid) Caesar on `Your Show of Shows'
with all those great guys _ Larry Gelbart, Neil Simon, Carl Reiner
_ we were doing satirical, smart, cerebral material,'' says Allen,
with just a hint that the gang on the 23d floor looked down on the
broader, more physical comedy that Gleason represented.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought much of it until I started watching Gleason on
TV in reruns,'' says Allen. ``And they can say what they want about
`I Love Lucy' and `The Dick Van Dyke Show' _ and they were very
good _ but I think `The Honeymooners' is the funniest show in the
history of television. And Gleason is really a genius. When I was
writing this one, I thought of Ray as Ralph and Tracey Ullman as
Alice and Michael Rapaport as Art Carney. When that show is on, we
stop whatever we're doing and just laugh. And it's not the kind of
laugh that requires homework.''
</P>
<P>
   If ``Small Time Crooks'' is a tribute to ``The Honeymooners,''
why didn't Allen _ whose black-and-white work is so rich _ shoot it
the old-fashioned way?
</P>
<P>
   ``I love black and white,'' he says, passionately. ``But the
laboratories are so ill-equipped to deal with it. They always have
trouble. . . . The film bubbles up. . . . They just don't take the
kind of care and attention required.''
</P>
<P>
   Another element to Allen's career that has remained steadfast is
that he never directs other people's work. Although, at times, he's
been tempted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone sent me this novel `King of the Jews' by Leslie
Epstein, and I read it and it's a real tour de force,'' he says,
referring to the Brookline-based novelist who heads the creative
writing program at Boston University. ``It's a bravura piece and
he's quite a wonderful writer. And it's a wonderful piece of
imaginative writing in the same class as `One Hundred Years of
Solitude.' I've also read some of his other books and I really like
his Goldkorn stories. But I don't do other people's work.''
</P>
<P>
   In one of Allen's most recent film appearances, as the primary
subject in Barbara Kopple's ``Wild Man Blues,'' a movie about
Allen's European tour with a jazz band, there's an uncomfortable
moment. Toward the end of the movie, Allen and his wife, Soon Yi
Previn, are sitting in his parents' apartment while his mother
berates him.
</P>
<P>
   Did his parents see the film? And what did they think of their
performances?
</P>
<P>
   Allen shrugs. ``My father will be 100 this year and my mother is
94,'' he says. ``They loved the picture. It's me they don't like.
She really does wish I'd become a pharmacist.''
</P>
<P>
   But she must be the only one.
</P>
<P>
   It's time for Allen to hop over to Harvard. ``It's great how
this little college tour has worked out,'' he says. ``Without
planning it this way, I'll be home to watch the Knicks tomorrow
night.'' And Allen, who built his reputation on his comic skills at
depressive schtick, smiles. He seems happy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
