<HEADLINE>
&HT;     DREAM LOCATION FOR BUSINESS? TRY LOW-TECH LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BLAIR TINDALL  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA ROSA, Calif. _ The Silicon Valley may bask in the new
economy limelight, but low-tech shines in Santa Rosa.
</P>
<P>
   In Forbes magazine's second annual ranking of the ``Best Places
in America'' to do business, Santa Rosa took third place, showing
commercial strength in forest products, food, communications and
retailing.
</P>
<P>
   Austin, Texas, and Atlanta were first and second in the ranking,
which was released Monday and appears in the magazine's May 29
issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of these businesses are started by people who come here
for the climate, the proximity to the coast and the lifestyle,''
said Kenneth Blackman, the manager of Santa Rosa, a city of 114,000
that is 60 miles north of San Francisco. Blackman said municipal
officials encourage businesses by streamlining the review process
for companies' expansion plans.
</P>
<P>
   One high-growth Santa Rosa company singled out by Forbes is G&AMP;G
Specialty Foods. Its best-selling product is Goldy's Cheese Dip,
but the company also makes a variety of hummus, baked brie and
other cheese spreads, according to co-owners Chris Glab and Rick
Goldberg, who moved the company from San Francisco in August 1998.
</P>
<P>
   According to the magazine, other winners in Santa Rosa's economy
are Amy's Kitchen Inc., which produces vegetarian convenience
foods; Lasercraft Inc., a picture-frame etching business; and
Flowmaster Inc., which makes gas-efficient mufflers that are
popular with race car drivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``High housing and wage costs are reducing the area's
attractiveness for non-high-tech firms,'' the Forbes article says
of the Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   In its survey Forbes focused on broad economic indicators
including wages and employment growth. The rankings were based on a
range of financial data, mostly gathered from the federal
government, and all crunched by regional economy experts at the
Milken Institute in Santa Monica, the magazine said. The statistics
measure jobs and earned income as well as output in several
critical technology sectors.
</P>
<P>
   ``A smaller metropolitan area like Santa Rosa has an easier time
showing up on the list with its high growth rate,'' said Tim
Ferguson, assistant managing editor of Forbes and editor of its
Best Places list. ``It has benefited mightily from the migration of
wealth in the Bay Area and from its good-living industries.''
</P>
<P>
   The other top areas listed by Forbes, in order, are: Boulder,
Colo.; Boise City, Idaho; San Diego; Orange County, Calif.; San
Antonio; West Palm Beach, Fla.; Colorado Springs, Colo.; Fort
Collins, Colo.; Oakland, Calif.; Seattle; Charlotte, N.C.; and Fort
Worth, Texas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
