<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-GUIDE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVIES RECENTLY REVIEWED IN THE BOSTON GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ! 1/2 ``Battlefield Earth'' Hollywood pulp sci-fi. It's heavy,
dated, and lifeless despite the best efforts of John Travolta to
pump some energy into it. He plays a comic monster/heavy, doing
nasty things to everybody, drenched in self-pity at being stuck on
such a ratty little planet as Earth, never dreaming that
freedom-loving, cave-dwelling humans mean to kick him off the
planet. (PG-13) &QL; 
 &QL; 
!! 1/2 ``The Big Kahuna'' Kevin Spacey and Danny DeVito as
industrial-lubricant salesmen at a convention in Wichita, trying to
conceal their anxiety and despair. Spacey is his usual stylishly
sardonic self, and DeVito is soulful. But the piece's talkiness
betrays its stage origins, and its fortune-cookie philosophizing
increasingly tests the ingenuity of both stars. (R) &QL; 
 &QL; 
!! 1/2 ``Center Stage'' The story is old, but the energies are new
in another variation on kids dying to make it as performers, in
this case with a thinly veiled version of the American Ballet
Theatre. The likable young ensemble cast, which includes ballet
dancers Ethan Stiefel, Amanda Schull, and Sascha Radetsky,
overcomes predictability and the frequent echoes of predecessors.
(PG-13)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
! ``Decline of Western Civilization, Part III'' Penelope Spheeris's
documentary on contemporary LA punk-rock fans. Most of them are
street kids who hang together and panhandle for beer money _
touchingly innocent beneath their body piercings, spiked hair, and
everything-sucks attitude. All too aware that they're more discards
than rebels, they're heartbreaking in their seeming acceptance of
their own defeat and their attempt to be family to one another.
(Unrated) &QL; 
 &QL; 
!! ``Human Traffic'' A Welsh take on contemporary 20-somethings who
hate their jobs and live for getting together at weekend raves,
where they dance and do drugs. But it plays like ``Trainspotting''
Lite. Lorraine Pilkington is the standout. (R) &QL; 
 &QL; 
!!! ``Time Code'' Mike Figgis drags Hollywood film into the digital
age. Using state-of-the-art video cameras and shooting in real
time, he then projects four separate stories simultaneously on
quadruple screens. The result has some of the immediacy of breaking
TV news as seemingly disparate people converge on an LA office
building housing a small film-production company in crisis _ as,
indeed, are they. A lot of it is claptrap, but its tabloid moves
keep you involved; so does Figgis's envelope-pushing use of the new
technology. (R)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-00 1419EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
