<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Tuesday, May 16:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-PALESTINIANS (Jerusalem) _ Ledeall: Violence in the West
Bank and Gaza on Monday included exchanges of gunfire between
Israeli soldiers and Palestinian police; the Israeli Cabinet
approved the transfer of three villages near Jerusalem to the
Palestinians Jewish settlers plan an anti-Barak rally. By Deborah
Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and map.
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-AFRICA (United Nations) _ The U.N. Security Council on
Monday will discuss sanctions on Ethiopia and Eritrea. By Barbara
Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   ETHIOPIA-ERITREA (Dateline to come) _ Developments in the
fighting between Ethiopia and Eritrea. By Ian Fisher. (With map)
</P>
<P>
   SIERRA-LEONE-ASSESS (Freetown) _ On the role Liberian warlord
Charles Taylor is playing in Sierra Leone's current conflict. The
story will include the day's developments, including the release of
some peacekeepers. A news analysis by Norimitsu Onishi.
</P>
<P>
   GUATEMALA-FIRES (Ceibal) _ Huge fires caused by squatters
threaten nature reserve and Mayan ruins. By David Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and map.
</P>
<P>
   DOMINICAN-ELECTIONS (Santo Domingo) _ On the situation on the
eve of Tuesday's presidential elections. By David Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   GULF-WAR-MCCAFFREY (Washington) _ Folo on the accusations of
Gulf War misconduct against General McCaffrey. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-U.S.-TORTURE (Geneva) _ A U.N. committee on torture is
scheduled to release a report on the United States. By Elizabeth
Olson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-WOMEN (Washington) _ The Supreme Court rules, 5-4, that
the core civil section of the Violence Against Women Act is
unconstitutional. That section allowed victims of gender-motivated
violence to sue attackers for damages in federal courts. By Linda
Greenhouse. (1400 words)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-GUNS (Washington) _ President Clinton discusses gun
control measures. By Neil A. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   FORESTS-ENVIRON (Washington) _ Environmental groups are
galvanized and the logging industry is scrambling to figure out how
to fight the fight over the 43 million acres of forests that
President Clinton has set aside to be free of roads. It's a tale of
advertising, grass-roots organizing and other advocacy on what both
sides see as their top environmental priority for the year. By
Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-POLL (Undated) _ Results of the latest NYT/CBS News
poll. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SOCSEC-CANDIDATES (Rancho Cucamonga, Calif.) _ George W. Bush
and Al Gore both make major policy speeches on the future of Social
Security. Bush fleshes out his plan for allowing people to invest
part of payroll taxes in the market while Gore explains his plan to
pay down the debt and use the interest saved to shore up Social
Security. By Alison Mitchell and James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   SOCSEC-ASSESS (Washington) _ How the Bush and Gore plans work
and stack up against each other. A news analysis by Richard W.
Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS (Undated) _ News from the campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   COLUMBINE-REPORT (Littleton, Colo.) _ The sheriff's department
releases its report on the Columbine High School shootings. By
Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   LOS-ALAMOS-FIRE (Los Alamos, N.M.) _ Developments in the New
Mexico fire. By James Sterngold.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MODIFIED-SEEDS (Undated) _ Farmers are already freely using
genetically modified soybeans in Brazil _ even though such seeds
there are outlawed. Now, Brazil is deciding whether to make the new
technology legal. And there is a growing sense that what happens in
Brazil _ the world's No. 2 soybean producer after the United States
_ could tip the balance on genetically altered crops worldwide.
Should Brazil reject biotechnology's lure, it would be a big
setback for American companies that have already been hurt by
fierce resistance in Europe. But if Brazil's huge agricultural
sector joins the biotechnology fold, it may someday be difficult
for consumers anywhere to find any food free of genetically
modified material. That is because the United States, Brazil and
Argentina _ the No. 3 producer _ together grow 80 percent of the
world's soybeans, an extraordinarily versatile crop that is pressed
into oil, processed into food, and added to countless foods. By
Anthony DePalma.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Nasdaq was lower, but other market measures
were up in mid-afternoon trading. At 2:15 p.m., the Nasdaq
composite index wsd down 20 points, the Dow Jones industrial
average was up 154 points and the S&AMP;P 500 was up 17 points.
Treasury prices were slightly higher. European stock markets were
slightly lower: London was down 0.58 percent and Frankfurt down
0.89 percent. The Nikkei closed down 0.25 percent, and the Hang
Seng index ended down 1.53 percent. By Jonathan Fuerbringer.
</P>
<P>
   WIT-EOFFERING (Undated) _ Wit Capital has agreed to acquire
EOffering, the online investment-bank affiliate of ETrade Group
Inc., for about $328 million in stock. As part of the deal, ETrade
will acquire Wit Soundview's retail-brokerage business, with about
100,000 accounts, and take a stake in Wit Capital. By Patrick
McGeehan.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-AIRLINES (Sao Paulo, Brazil) _ Looking at the worsening
financial problems confronting Brazil's four major domestic
airlines, which have utterly failed to recover from the currency
crisis of January 1999. All four lost large amounts of money last
year, and creditors have repossessed the airplanes of Vasp, the
weakest of the four. By Jennifer L. Rich.
</P>
