<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 14:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5541 &Cx1f; sci-z
u v BC-SCIENCE-TIMES-BUDGET-     05-15 1360
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCIENCE-TIMES-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans the following  &UR; Science
Times &LR;  stories for papers of Tuesday, May 16:
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CO2-EMISSIONS (Undated) _ As the economic and political
difficulty of reducing carbon dioxide emissions becomes ever more
obvious, a move is under way to manipulate the carbon cycle so that
it will remove more heat-trapping gases from the air. But the
ambitious idea is surrounded by questions of potential risks and
obstacles. Some researchers are looking for ways to remove carbon
from industrial emissions before they are released. But more
promising, many believe, are prospects for increasing the
absorption of atmospheric carbon dioxide by what is called the
terrestrial biosphere: the whole complex of living things on land,
mainly plants and various tiny inhabitants of the soil. The
expansion of these carbon reservoirs, or ``sinks'' in vegetation
and soil has been sanctioned under the 1997 Kyoto Protocol. By
William K. Stevens. (2050 words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SPACE-STATION (Undated) _ The space station is falling,
slipping gradually from its position. To blame: sun spots. But now,
NASA is preparing to launch on Thursday the space shuttle Atlantis
on an 11-day mission to nudge the space station upward by 20 to 25
miles, a temporary solution until a Russian craft arrives to help
keep it in place. By Kenneth Chang. (1665 words0
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT1.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HANDEDNESS-GENE (Undated) _ The latest word on what makes
people left- or right-handed comes from a geneticist at the
National Cancer Institute laboratory here who has been working for
years with yeast and mutant mice and has developed a theory that he
believes explains why 9 of 10 people in all cultures are
right-handed, why left-handed parents are more likely to have
left-handed children and why identical twins often have different
handedness. Most people, he says, have a specific dominant gene
that makes them right-handed. But about 20 percent of people lack
the right-handed gene, and these people without the gene have a
50-50 possibility of being right-handed or left-handed. By David E.
Rosenbaum. (1350 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT2.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HANDEDNESS-FACTS (Undated) _ Nine fascinating facts about
lefties. Among them: a disproportionate number of lefties seem to
be geniuses (Einstein), artists (Leonardo, Michelangelo, Picasso)
and athletes (Babe Ruth). A disproportionate number also seem to be
criminals (Jack the Ripper, Billy the Kid).
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HANDEDNESS-FAME (Undated) _ A list of famous lefties, among
them Alexander the Great, Michelangelo, Leonardo de Vinci, James
Baldwin, Cole Porter, Greta Garbo, Marilyn Monroe and Judy Garland.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-LOS-ALAMOS-RESEARCH () _ How the fire there is affecting
research at the lab. By George Johnson (1000 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BAPTISTA-BIRDS (Undated) _ A conversation with Dr. Luis F.
Baptista, chairman and curator of ornithology and mammalogy of the
California Academy of Sciences, based in Golden Gate Park. He has
spent a lifetime studying the mating habits, songs and language of
birds and has written some 127 papers on them. By Claudia Dreifus.
(1600 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-VOLCANO-RECOVER (Undated) _ The eruption of Mount St. Helens
_ its 20th anniversary will be marked on Thursday _ has radically
changed the way that biologists look at the creation and recovery
of natural landscapes. By Carol Kaesuk Yoon. (1600 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT4,5.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WATCH (Undated) _ News and notes on science: Items on the
impact of volcanic eruptions on a moon of Jupiter, spices that keep
keep bacteria from being killed in radiation and possible
implications of the findings, and the 5,000-year history of El
Nino. By Henry Fountain. (670 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CYBERSEX (Undated) _ For most people, forays into cybersex
are relatively harmless recreational pursuits. But experts in the
field say that the affordability, accessibility and anonymity of
the Internet are fueling a brand new psychological disorder _
cybersex addiction _ that appears to be spreading with astonishing
rapidity and bringing turmoil to the lives of those affected. By
Jane E. Brody. (1850 words)
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ The Personal Health column: In
treating cybersex addiction, the aim is not to deprive those
afflicted with access to computers or sexual outlets but to prevent
their abuse. Before treatment for any disorder can begin, a proper
diagnosis must be made. Someone has to recognize that a problem
exists and the person afflicted has to acknowledge that he or she
needs help to overcome it. As with other addictions, denial is a
common element in cybersex addiction, and people typically maintain
that denial until the bottom falls out. By Jane E. Brody. (1300
words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SCHIZOPHRENIA-SMELL (Undated) _ In schizophrenia, the sense
of smell is impaired. People with schizophrenia often display what
psychiatrists describe as a ``blunting'' of emotional response that
makes it difficult for them to relate to others. But they also,
researchers have found, show deficits in their ability to detect,
identify and remember odors. Now a new study, appearing in this
month's American Journal of Psychiatry, suggests that these
abnormalities in the sense of smell have their root in abnormal
brain structure. By Erica Goode. (790 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GENETIC-SCREENING (Undated) _ While genetic screening tests
are remarkable diagnostic tools, they are not without potential
harm to those who happen to carry a deleterious trait. As a
physician who routinely orders such tests, I thought I long
understood this dynamic. But I needed my wife, Kate, for a more
definitive lesson. Her pregnancy raised the point, after she tested
positive for a genetic disorder. By Howard Markel, M.D. (1050
words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HEART-ELDERLY (Undated) _ Three large new studies are
challenging the safety and benefits of clotbusting drugs for older
people suffering heart attacks, particularly those 75 and older.
The drugs fail to benefit many such heart attack patients, and
those 75 and older may be at higher risk of death from bleeding,
strokes and a ruptured heart, two of the studies found. By Lawrence
K. Altman. (1000 words)
</P>
<P>
