<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOYS-R-US-STREET </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOYS R US SOARS PAST EARNINGS ESTIMATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (Stock price cited in last graf does not reflect market close)  
 By JUSTIN DINI   
 c. 2000 TheStreet.com/N.Y. Times.com   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Toys R Us Inc.(TOY:NYSE), the world's largest toy retailer,
reported a 41 percent rise in first-quarter earnings Monday
sweeping past earnings estimates, as a result of higher sales in
its worldwide toy and juvenile businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The Paramus, N.J.-based company said earnings before one-time
items for the quarter rose to $24 million, or 10 cents a diluted
share, from $17 million, or 7 cents a share, in the year-earlier
quarter. Analysts surveyed by First Call/Thomson Financial had
projected earnings of 6 cents a share in the latest quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Sales for the quarter totaled $2.3 billion, compared with $2.2
billion in the first quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Including a pretax gain of $315 million from the initial public
offering of its Toys R Us Japan Ltd. unit and a loss of $9 million
related to its ToysRUs.com Internet operations, earnings totaled
$215 million, or 93 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   ``The completion of our previously announced Japanese
subsidiary's IPO allows us to continue to report 48 percent of the
future earnings of this strong, independent company and to continue
to receive royalty income while at the same time eliminating the
debt related to the Japanese business,'' John Eyler, president and
chief executive of Toys R Us, said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Comparable toy store sales in the United States rose 2 percent
for the quarter, while international comparable toy store sales
rose 7 percent. The company's Babies R Us unit also posted a 10
percent increase in same-store sales, while its Kids R Us
same-store sales decreased from a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   In April, Toys R Us said it would close 20 of its 205 Kids R Us
children's clothing stores and 15 underperforming international
stores in 2000 and would open stores geared toward babies and in
better-positioned overseas markets.
</P>
<P>
   The company also said it is in the midst of improving its
ToysRUs.com Web site and said it plans this year to focus on
resolving some highly publicized problems their Web site
experienced during the holiday shopping season last year. ``By the
2000 holiday season, ToysRUs.com will have approximately three
times the capacity to process orders as compared to the 1999
holiday season,'' Eyler said.
</P>
<P>
   Toys R Us shares inched up 3/16, or 1 percent, to 16 15/16 by
midday Monday.
</P>
<P>
   (For use by clients of The New York Times News Service)
</P>
</TEXT>
