<DOCNO> NYT20000515.0157 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 15:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5565 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-FARM-LAND-HNS &LR;      05-15 1230
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FARM-LAND-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CROP YIELDS GROW DESPITE LAND LOST TO URBAN SPRAWL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ERIC BRAZIL  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CASTROVILLE, Calif. _ From Mulligan Hill to Moro Cojo Slough
near the Salinas River mouth lie the foggy fields of noble thistle
that have won for Castroville the title ``Artichoke Capital of the
World.''
</P>
<P>
   The fields have shrunk 50 percent over the past two decades but
produce just as many artichokes, exemplifying a phenomenon that
sustains the vigor of California farming despite urban sprawl: more
crop from less land.
</P>
<P>
   California produces all of the artichokes grown in the United
States, and the industry's numbers stand as a fair example of the
efficient use to which farmland is now being put.
</P>
<P>
   In Monterey County, where most of the artichokes are grown, the
cash value of the 1998 crop was $38.8 million on 43,115 tons
harvested from 6,451 acres. In 1983, by contrast, the $27.3 million
harvest was 36,720 tons from 9,135 acres.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to have nearly 14,000 acres in 'chokes, now we've got
less than half that,'' said Hugo Tottino, co-owner of Ocean Mist
Farms, which, with 3,600 acres, is the nation's preeminent grower.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're planting different (closer) spacings, we know how to use
fertilizer better, we're using drip (irrigation) to use water
better,'' said Tottino, whose father started the business in 1923.
And ``these young fellas with computers, they've changed a lot of
things.''
</P>
<P>
   Ocean Mist, like other Salinas Valley growers, is experimenting
with 80-inch-wide beds for romaine, a variety of lettuce, to
increase its yield. The wider beds have five rows instead of two.
</P>
<P>
   ``This ground's expensive. You have to make the best use of it
you can,'' said Adrian Zendejas, pest management specialist and
field supervisor for Ocean Mist.
</P>
<P>
   The remarkable per-acre increase in artichoke production is
matched in several vegetable crops grown in the Salinas Valley,
including the iceberg lettuce, signature crop of ``The Salad Bowl
of the World.'' Whereas 400 cartons per acre was once an acceptable
yield, the average is now closer to 1,000, according to deputy
agricultural Commissioner Gerry Willey.
</P>
<P>
   The conversion of prime farmland has been a chronic concern in
California since the end of World War II as urbanization eats up
orchards, vineyards and vegetable fields in Santa Clara, Orange,
San Bernardino and other counties where agriculture once
predominated.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with 12 million to 14 million newcomers expected by 2020
bound to increase the pressure for farmland conversion in
California, what is needed to assure a healthy future for
agriculture is a rational land conservation policy emphasizing
urban infill, said state Treasurer Phil Angelides.
</P>
<P>
   Angelides believes that unless California policy makers start
focusing on community design that factors in agriculture and open
space, unplanned growth will inevitably bring on both economic and
environmental degradation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest hook the state has, its leverage, is that in the
next decade it's going to provide $70 (billion) to $100 billion for
capital investment in communities for infrastructure,'' Angelides
said. That money should be used to encourage building up urban
areas to spare farmland and open space.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes no sense to push money out the door for every project
that fosters irrational growth patterns,'' he said. ``It should be
done around strong regional plans supporting more sustainable
patterns of growth, and that (state) money is the most powerful
tool we have.
</P>
<P>
   ``Agriculture may be in a state of relative diminution as other
(economic) sectors rise in California, but it is the leading
industry feeding people in this nation and in the world. It's huge
and significant for our society,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1984 and 1996, California lost 218,243 acres of
irrigated land and 71,000 nonirrigated acres to urban conversion,
according to Greg Poseley, manager of the Department of
Conservation's farmland mapping program.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, because marginal land has been irrigated and
nurtured and brought into production to replace land lost to
streets and buildings, irrigated acreage farmed remains about what
it was in 1950, nine million acres.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had some remarkable changes in technology for farmers,''
including pest management, said Daniel Sumner, director of the
Agricultural Issues Center at the University of California at
Davis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Output per unit of irrigation water has gone up
substantially,'' and the state's farm productivity index _ a
complicated calculation measuring farm output divided by input _
has doubled since 1949, Sumner said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Department of Food and Agriculture's statistics
service, state farmers grew an average of 27,047,781 tons of field
crops, fruits and nuts, vegetables and melons from 1950 to 1954. In
1997, the last year for which statistics are available, comparable
tonnage was 68,457,770.
</P>
<P>
   While lacking the glamour and international cachet of the film
and high-tech industries, California agriculture is equally
unusual, producing 350 crops _ a dozen grown only in the state _
with an on-the-farm value of $26 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Among the ways in which farmers have compensated for the loss of
prime land on the urban edge, as well as rising production costs
and political problems associated with water use, is by shifting to
higher value crops.
</P>
<P>
   Almonds, pistachios, strawberries, walnuts and flowers are being
grown on land that was once pasture, barley and bean fields. They
have emerged among the state's most valuable crops.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Almonds, for example, a comparatively minor crop in 1950, are
now being grown on 460,000 acres in Stanislaus, Kern, Fresno and
other Central Valley counties and have become California's No. 1
export crop, valued at $759.5 million in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Low value sugar beets have disappeared from the Salinas Valley,
where Spreckels Sugar once had a huge plant to process a crop that
was second only to lettuce in acreage. Wine grapes, broccoli and
other row crops replaced the beets.
</P>
<P>
   With improved per-acre crop yields the rule, overproduction
remains a nagging problem in the fresh fruit and vegetable
industry. Consequently, some growers like David Mas Masumoto of Del
Mar, who grows peaches, nectarines and raisin grapes on his 80-acre
farm, have taken a different route to survival in what has
historically been a high-risk, free market business.
</P>
<P>
   Masumoto, whose 1995 book ``Epitaph for a Peach,'' has become a
minor classic among students of rural California life, has become
one of California's 727 certified organic farmers, forswearing
chemical pesticides and fertilizers and relying on Earth's
resources. ``My yields are just as good, but the management is a
lot more intensive. You have to be out in the field a lot, and
there's a lot more expensive hand labor,'' Masumoto said.
</P>
<P>
   On the upside, certified organic produce fetches a higher price
in its special niche. ``Organic customers don't buy with their
eyes, they buy with their taste buds in mind,'' Masumoto said. And
they have rescued from the woodpile his Sun Crest peaches which,
while juicy and tasty, lack the cosmetic appeal of some other
varieties that have longer shelf life.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
