<HEADLINE>
SPACEY, DEVITO REALLY SELL `THE BIG KAHUNA' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Resending for Lebanon Daily News)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
THE BIG KAHUNA 
Directed by: John Swanbeck 
Screenplay by: Roger Reuff (based on his play) 
Starring: Kevin Spacey, Danny DeVito, Peter Facinelli 
Running time: 91 minutes 
Rated: R (language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Willy Loman never died, not really. In ``The Big Kahuna,'' he's
very much alive in the souls of three industrial lubricant salesmen
sweating to land a big customer at a convention in the heart of the
heartland _ Wichita, Kan. There isn't a lot of mercy out there for
them. The veteran drummers played by Kevin Spacey and Danny DeVito
know this. They are not happy that their company's hospitality
suite budget does not extend beyond carrot sticks and a cheeseball,
while their rivals dangle platters of shrimp on ice to the
customers they're all wooing. So they're nervous.
</P>
<P>
   They handle it in different ways. Spacey's Larry expresses his
anxiety by running off at the mouth. Spacey running off at the
mouth has become one of the delights of contemporary moviegoing.
Ranging effortlessly between biting irony and outright insult in
his first film to be released since ``American Beauty,'' one has
only to note the wicked gleam in his eye, the chiseled mockery in
his tone, the slight curl of distaste at the edges of his lips, and
we know we're getting vintage Spacey as Larry lays into the
inadequacy of the hospitality suite and the callowness of the third
man on the team, Peter Facinelli's dewy-cheeked rookie.
</P>
<P>
   Spacey is a stage-trained veteran, and there's more of his
corroded, self-loathing Hickey from Eugene O'Neill's ``The Iceman
Cometh'' than there is of Willy Loman. Arthur Miller's salesman
necessarily remained self-deludingly optimistic in order to keep
doing his job. Not Larry. He's smart enough to know he's in
trouble. He tries to tame his panic by talking a lot. But the more
he talks, the less he's saying. Larry begins on a note of high
attack, then arcs downward as he struggles to maintain his
composure and the feeling that he's successfully repelling the
threat he perceives in the younger man.
</P>
<P>
   DeVito's Phil becomes the dominant presence. It's one of
DeVito's best performances, partly because in this film that
reveals its stage origins in excessive, static talkiness, Phil has
less to say. When he does speak, there's a weight of authority in
his words that convinces us it has come from a rethinking of the
priorities he has lived by all his adult life. The expression
DeVito puts on Phil's face convinces us that introspection and
salesmanship don't mix. But neither does the old glad-handing
extroversion. That's really what seems to have panicked Larry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Big Kahuna'' (the title refers to the big-bucks guy the
salesmen are chasing) doesn't bring any profound new insights to
its musings on American values. Many are on the fortune-cookie
level. But the pleasure of watching Spacey and DeVito work makes
the slenderness of the subject matter almost palatable. Roger
Rueff, who wrote the script from his play, does at least have an
update to offer. It has to do with the fact that while the sales
game remains the same, the moves are changing. What sells these
days is decreased obviousness about the selling. Which is why the
fresh-faced rookie, with his straight-arrow churchgoing and family
values agenda, embodies the latest sales tool _ authenticity. A
nice twist. It lifts ``The Big Kahuna'' out of the cheeseball
class, if not out of the carrot stick category. It's no meal, but
it'll tide you over.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
