<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-BATTLEFIELD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S NO SAVING `BATTLEFIELD EARTH' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Resending for Lebanon Daily News)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
BATTLEFIELD EARTH 
Directed by: Roger Christian 
Screenplay by: Corey Mandell, J. D.Shapiro (novel: L. Ron Hubbard) 
Starring: John Travolta, Barry Pepper, Forest Whitaker, Kim Coates,
Richard Tyson, Sabine Karsenti 
Running time: 117 minutes 
Rated: PG-13 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Battlefield Earth'' is yet another reminder that a book can
sell milions of copies, as this sci-fi best-seller has, and still
be so badly written that it defies even the most sustained
professional effort to bring it to anything like life. Its story of
a heroic man freeing the planet from enslaving alien monsters in
the year 3000 is so heavy and lifeless that you keep waiting for
those three little front-row kibitzers from ``Mystery Science
Theatre 3000'' to appear at the bottom of the screen to start
goofing on it.
</P>
<P>
   Although L. Ron Hubbard's novel was published in 1982, it has
the anachronistic flavor of the most generic pulp sci-fi of the
'50s. Essentially, it's Hollywood camp that not even the most
devoted ministrations of John Travolta, who spent almost two
decades getting the film made, can salvage. During that time he
aged from playing the lead to playing the bad guy. He can't make
the bad guy scary enough to make a difference, although he does
have fun playing the guy's hubris.
</P>
<P>
   Terl is his name and he's from a race of nine-foot bipeds called
Psychlos with six thick hairy clawed fingers on each hand, a
mouthful of bad teeth, and gray breathing tubes coming out of their
noses because Psychlos can't handle Earth's atmosphere. Despite his
respiratory problems, Darth Vader he's not. All he wants is gold,
and he's seething because he's been put in charge of security on
what he regards as a ratty little planet while his fellow Psychlos
finish strip-mining it.
</P>
<P>
   It's amusing that this heavy spends so much time playing
self-pity when he isn't torturing, killing, or doing nasty things
to everyone. Still, it's not nearly amusing enough in this film
that seems barely able to fend off a quality of amateurishness
having to do with clumsy plotting and less than comic-strip balloon
quality dialogue. ``Jonnie, I've always known this was going to be
your destiny,'' Sabine Karsenti's pretty cavewoman and
self-proclaimed lifelong mate cries, straight-faced, when the
earthling rebel is ready to kick the Psychlos off the planet.
</P>
<P>
   Never is it quite explained why the cave-dwelling humans living
in the snow-covered Rockies don't bundle up more. As it is, they
prance around scantily clad in bits of rag and the odd fur. To the
Psychlos, they're less than dogs, and when they're captured they're
penned in zoos when they're not doing forced labor in the mines.
When Barry Pepper's Jonnie Goodboy is looking for a concept to tie
his revolutionary impulses together, he conveniently is led to
what's left of the Denver Public Library and happens on a copy of
the Declaration of Independence.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of weaponry and machinery, the Psychlos are leagues
ahead of the humans. But after one session in front of a learning
ray that shoots his brain full of Psychlo knowledge, Johnnie is
substituting ingots of Fort Knox gold for the Rocky Mountain
nuggets he's told to mine, piloting Psychlo flying craft, and
telling the others who have been sprung from the zoo that they've
got seven days to save the planet. This includes mastering a remote
control device that will enable them to destroy the purple Psychlo
planet, light-years away.
</P>
<P>
   But even the battle scenes plod. You perhaps see the problem
faced by ``Battlefield Earth.'' It's too clunky to be taken
seriously, too dumb to be taken as comedy, too formulaic to have
any real personality. A lot of effort has been expended on models
and explosions and dark, oppressive visuals that suggest early
steel mills. But the material it's being expended upon is too
intractable to work on any level. ``Battlefield Earth'' begins as
retro pulp, ends up, figuratively speaking, as tons of wet
cardboard.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
