<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-WOMEN-360&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAPE VICTIMS MAY NOT SUE ATTACKERS IN FEDERAL COURT, SUPREME COURT
RULES 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court on Monday threw out the part of a
1994 federal law that allowed female rape victims to sue their
attackers in federal court, ruling 5-4 that Congress had exceeded
its reach and ventured into the domain of the states.
</P>
<P>
   The majority, in an opinion written by Chief Justice William
Rehnquist, voided the section of the Violence Against Women Act
that gave rape victims the right to sue their attackers for civil
damages. Monday's ruling does not affect sections of the act
providing for criminal charges and penalties.
</P>
<P>
   In passing the law, Congress went too far in relying on its
constitutional authority to regulate interstate commerce and to
enforce the 14th Amendment's equal-protection guarantees, the
Supreme Court said in its ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the law had argued that violence against women had
a substantial effect on interstate commerce by deterring women from
taking certain jobs, furthering their educations or traveling
freely, among other things.
</P>
<P>
   The case decided Monday concerned a freshman at Virginia Tech
who accused two football players of raping her in her dormitory
room in 1994. The student, Christy Brzonkala, sued in 1995 after
the school took no action against one of the players, James
Crawford, and gave the other, Antonio Morrison, a deferred
suspension that permitted him to keep playing football.
</P>
<P>
   Brzonkala did not file a complaint until several months after
the incident. Morrison maintained that the sex was consentual,
while Crawford denied any participation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the allegations here are true,'' Rehnquist wrote, ``no
civilized system of justice could fail to provide her a remedy for
the conduct of respondent Morrison. But under our federal system
that remedy must be provided by the Commonwealth of Virginia, and
not by the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   The chief justice was joined by Justices Sandra Day O'Connor,
Antonin Scalia, Anthony M. Kennedy and Clarence Thomas in upholding
a ruling by the 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, in Richmond. The
case is United States vs. Morrison, 99-5.
</P>
<P>
   Justices David H. Souter, John Paul Stevens, Ruth Bader Ginsburg
and Stephen G. Breyer dissented.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The lines of Monday's ruling had seemed predictable when the
case was argued on Jan. 11, setting off a spirited argument about
the relative powers of the federal government and the states _ an
issue the high court has been addressing often of late.
</P>
<P>
   In January, the five justices in the majority Monday told the
Clinton administration, which argued in favor of the civil claims
section of the law, that by extension its approach would call for
federal laws regarding alimony, child support and other areas that
are left to the states.
</P>
<P>
   But the justices in Monday's minority suggested in January that
leaving the federal rape-suit provision intact would just be one of
many instances of federal and state laws that are more or less
parallel.
</P>
<P>
   In his dissent Monday, Souter said Congress passed the law in
1994 because the states had been unable to curb gender-based
violence.
</P>
<P>
   And Souter noted the irony that while Monday's majority ruling
was protective of the states' constitutional powers, 36 states and
the Commonwealth of Puerto Rico had filed briefs asking the court
to rule the other way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
