<HEADER>
A5610 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-EXAMINER-SALE-HNS &LR;      05-15 1201
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXAMINER-SALE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TRIAL PUTS NEWSPAPER COMPANY IN UNCOMFORTABLE LIMELIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SETH ROSENFELD  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Suddenly, one of the nation's biggest media
companies found itself uncomfortably in the news.
</P>
<P>
   What began as a relatively straightforward newspaper acquisition
_ the Hearst Corp.'s $660 million purchase of the San Francisco
Chronicle _ has become a public relations nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   An antitrust suit to stop Hearst from buying the Chronicle and
selling its Examiner has turned into a corporate soap opera.
</P>
<P>
   One after another of privately held Hearst's executives has been
compelled to take the witness stand to answer questions about the
financial management of the Examiner, and about whether Hearst
sought to grab a newspaper monopoly in a town that loves freedom of
expression even more than gourmet food.
</P>
<P>
   All Hearst wanted to do was buy the Chronicle and turn it into
what it called a ``world-class newspaper.'' But on the second day
of trial the man whom it had picked to do that _ Examiner Publisher
Timothy O. White _ was suspended for having testified the day
before that he offered Mayor Willie Brown favorable editorials in
return for Brown's support of Hearst's purchase of the Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   The saga has cast a shadow on Hearst's avowed ``commitment to
journalistic excellence,'' media specialists said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea of a quid pro quo offer, it's a nightmare,'' said
Frank Woods, a former editorial writer at the New Orleans
Times-Picayune who now teaches media ethics at the Poynter
Institute in St. Petersburg, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``Timothy White essentially verified every fear expressed by our
readers, (that) we are for sale. I strongly believe he made an
offer that most journalists . . . would not have dreamed of, but
the public needs to be told that.''
</P>
<P>
   Hearst has denied that White's superiors knew of his offer and
said the company puts a premium on the editorial independence of
its 12 daily newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We value journalistic integrity as much as any other news
organization,'' said Debra Shriver, a Hearst spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been no rush to judgment here. It has been a
difficult situation, involving a very well-liked, well-respected
colleague. We have done the right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Hearst put White on indefinite paid leave pending an internal
review by a former federal judge of whether White or others
violated journalistic ethics. In a Hearst press release, White said
he had been ``tired and confused'' during his testimony.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Saturday, White said that he had wanted to
return to the witness stand to explain his testimony but that
Hearst's lawyers said no.
</P>
<P>
   White said his remark to Brown was a ``conversational throwaway
line.'' He said his testimony made the comment sound more
substantial than it was. ``In truth, it meant nothing,'' White
said, adding, ``In hindsight, it's not the kind of comment that
should be made by a publisher to a mayor.''
</P>
<P>
   The episode has highlighted the inherent tension between every
media company's profit-driven business side and its news gathering
and editorializing side, two sections that are supposed to be as
separate as church and state.
</P>
<P>
   It is the latest in a series of controversies involving clashes
between those interdependent parts.
</P>
<P>
   ``In newspapers, magazines and certainly broadcasting, it's more
and more a concern,'' said Thomas Leonard, associate dean of
Graduate School of Journalism at the University of California at
Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Los Angeles Times admitted _ without telling its
editorial staff _ that business executives had agreed to split the
profits from a special magazine on the Staples Center with the
sports center's owners. In a 1995 case dramatized in the movie
``The Insider,'' CBS allegedly sat on an expose of a tobacco
company while the network's parent company was negotiating a
business deal with the cigarette maker.
</P>
<P>
   In the San Francisco case, several media specialists said they
have been most troubled by White's testimony that he offered to
trade favorable editorials for Brown's support of Hearst's purchase
of the Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   Woods noted that, like the Staples Center case, White's offer
put the publisher's business interests above the paper's editorial
independence.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they both have in common is a business-side promise to
deliver something journalistically,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers said trial testimony raised questions about
whether George B. Irish, president of Hearst's newspaper division,
and other Hearst executives knew of White's offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``My jaw dropped when I read that,'' said Marion Lewenstein,
professor of communication at Stanford University. ``I find it
difficult to believe they didn't know this was going on. It seems
(White) is taking the fall.''
</P>
<P>
   The uproar stems from an Aug. 30 e-mail to Irish, in which White
reported on his lunch meeting earlier that day with Brown. ``I
asked Willie how I was going to justify to my superiors in New York
wanting to support him and cooperate with him when he was seeming
to go out of his way to make our lives difficult,'' White wrote.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Brown and other local politicians opposed Hearst's
purchase of the Chronicle and possible closing of the Examiner,
saying they wanted San Francisco to have at least two daily
newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   White later testified that he did not need to justify any
editorial position to his superiors, but wanted Brown to think he
did. White said he was trying to convey to Brown that his support
for Hearst's purchase of the Chronicle would result in more
favorable editorial treatment for him in the Examiner's editorial
pages.
</P>
<P>
   Irish has testified that he did not know of the offer, though he
acknowledged that White had briefed him on at least two meetings in
which the publisher sought Brown's support for Hearst's purchase of
the Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst's lawyers have said White's offer to Brown is irrelevant
to the legal issue: Did Hearst's plan to buy the Chronicle violate
antitrust laws?
</P>
<P>
   ``It adds up to nothing,'' said Gerald Connell, a Hearst lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph M. Alioto, the lawyer for the man who filed the antitrust
suit, claims White's offer was part and parcel of Hearst's effort
to engineer an illegal newspaper monopoly by buying the Chronicle
and selling its Examiner to the publishers of the San Francisco
Independent.
</P>
<P>
   Clint Reilly, who made an unsuccessful attempt to buy the
Examiner and the plaintiff in the antitrust case, is seeking an
order that permanently bars Hearst's purchase of the Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the outcome, the trial has been a painful reminder that
newspapers are businesses in a competitive marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   William Woo, former editor of the St. Louis Post-Dispatch, said
that even if Hearst wins the antitrust case, White's testimony has
hurt Hearst's main stock in trade: credibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truthfulness of the company is being brought into
question,'' said Woo, a Stanford journalism professor who also
teaches journalism ethics at UC-Berkeley. ``It has put the
journalistic credibility of the company at stake.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-00 1534EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
