<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 15:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5621 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-STORMTOURS-TEX     05-15 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STORMTOURS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TORNADOES, HAILSTORMS AND FLATTENED ROOFS ATTRACTING TOURISTS TO
U.S.
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CRYSTAL YEDNAK 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Flattened homes and overturned cars _ not
exactly the images tourism officials plaster on travel brochures.
</P>
<P>
   But the scenes of devastation from recent tornadoes are luring
some foreigners to the United States to spend vacations jaunting
through Tornado Alley.
</P>
<P>
   Customers of the Denver-based Storm Chasing Adventure Tours fork
out $2,000 for a two-week trip chasing severe weather in a
radar-equipped van.
</P>
<P>
   Tour season kicked off April 22 and will run through June, with
the van crisscrossing through tornado-prone Texas and Oklahoma,
tour operator Todd Thorn said.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, his group of mostly British travelers made a stop
in Fort Worth to fill up on gas, soda and fresh air. Having left
Waco in the morning, they were on their way to New Mexico to take a
break at Carlsbad Caverns.
</P>
<P>
   It seems Texas weather isn't cooperating.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen some good thunderstorms, but we're yet to strike
lucky on a tornado,'' said Steve Wakeham, a meteorologist on the
tour from Norfolk, England.
</P>
<P>
   Stuck in traffic near Dallas on Friday, the group also missed
the storms and deadly tornado that struck Hill and Bosque counties
south of the Metroplex.
</P>
<P>
   Wakeham said it is rare to find storms in England that are as
severe as those found in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Peering from under a sun visor, Rita Ashton of Cambridge,
England, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to see some really big hailstones,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Thunderstorms and cloud formations have fascinated Ashton since
childhood. Last year, she became particularly interested in
tornadoes after a British TV special on twisters that profiled some
storm chasers.
</P>
<P>
   So for her silver wedding anniversary, Ashton asked husband,
David, for a storm-chasing adventure tour for two through Tornado
Alley, which includes parts of Texas, Oklahoma, Kansas and
Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   She is fascinated with the power nature has, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can predict it but you can't do anything to stop it,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   A weather tourist's day starts with a check of the radars to
seek the best potential sites for severe weather. With an average
of 168 tornadoes a year, Texas is often a destination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is bigger in America, especially Texas,'' said
Wayne Webster, 25, of South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Driving from storm to storm takes up most of the time. The group
may log hundreds of miles a day in the tour van, which is equipped
with a radar, satellite equipment to bring in uninterrupted Weather
Channel signals, a lightning detection monitor, computers and
radios. Each of the seven tourists can watch the Weather Channel on
TV monitors in the van as they head to the next destination.
</P>
<P>
   But 1,300 miles, three days, a few books and several CDs into
this trip, Jon Nicholson still hasn't seen what he came all the way
from Cambridge, England, to see _ the power of nature such as the
March 28 tornadoes in Fort Worth and adjacent Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   Tornado chasing first intrigued Nicholson after watching TV
coverage last year of the deadly Oklahoma tornadoes.
</P>
<P>
   But tornadoes are not promised on every trip, Thorn said, even
though just about every other group sees one.
</P>
<P>
   A previous tour group had a bit more excitement, coming up on
the path of a tornado minutes after it touched down in Shreveport,
La., said Webster. He had a van seat on that first tour of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We actually had to stop in our tracks because a tornado was
passing five miles south of us. It was so exciting,'' said Webster,
who works as an environmentalist.
</P>
<P>
   In his hometown of Dundee, Webster said he and friends drive up
to the mountains to watch lightning coming over the peaks.
</P>
<P>
   Lightning, heavy rains and maybe some hail are the most South
African weather-watchers can count on. Webster said he made the
trip to Texas specifically to see a tornado.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the violence and the lightning and the thunder, that's
what I enjoy the most,'' Webster said.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Biggerstaff, faculty adviser to the Texas A&AMP;M Severe Storms
Data Acquisition Team, said tornadoes fascinate people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been told that in Oklahoma there are so many people
chasing storms that you almost can't drive down the highways,''
Biggerstaff said.
</P>
<P>
   The increased popularity has prompted concern that weather
enthusiasts could put themselves in harm's way, but Biggerstaff
added that he is unaware of injuries resulting from any organized
tour.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the movie ``Twister'' helped popularize storm
chasing, Biggerstaff said. Weather information has also become much
more accessible.
</P>
<P>
   For less than $2,000, weather-watchers can outfit their vehicles
with radars, laptops and TV monitors to track weather with near
precision, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't mean that they always find the tornadoes.
</P>
<P>
   Thorn cited the difficulties in seeking out tornadoes and timing
the group's arrival within a few minutes of a twister touching
down.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can be like finding a needle in a haystack,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the customers come for the thrill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like with parachuting or bungee jumping, they go for the
thrill,'' he said. ``And the unknown amount of danger in it.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
