<DOCNO> NYT20000515.0166 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 15:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5622 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT &LR;      05-15 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Io's Potent Moondust
</P>
<P>
   On Earth, a major volcanic eruption can spew billions of cubic
yards of ash and dust into the air. From there, it can be
distributed throughout the atmosphere and deflect enough sunlight
to lower temperatures worldwide for several years, as the massive
Krakatoa eruption did in 1883.
</P>
<P>
   Impressive, yes, but nothing like what an extraterrestrial
volcano can do, to judge from recent research involving Jupiter's
moon Io, which scientists consider to be the most active volcanic
body in the solar system.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers in Germany and Norway, analyzing data from the
Galileo spacecraft, which has been orbiting Jupiter since 1995,
have determined that volcanoes on Io are the source of streams of
dust that flow from the area of Jupiter into the rest of the solar
system. These dust streams, which were first discovered in 1992,
flow out about 175 million miles, or nearly twice the distance of
the Earth to the sun.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists, reporting on their work in Nature, analyzed the
frequency of peak impacts on Galileo's dust detector. They found
that the peaks coincided with the periods of Io's orbit and
Jupiter's rotation. The dust, made up of tiny grains as small as
particles of smoke, is strongly affected by Jupiter's magnetic
field. Further study may provide insight into how the much more
abundant dust in the early days of the solar system behaved under
the influence of the sun's magnetic field.
</P>
<P>
   Spices as Shields
</P>
<P>
   They are not suggesting that a meal of chicken vindaloo might be
the best protection in the event of World War III, but scientists
in India have made the intriguing discovery that certain spices can
prevent bacteria from being destroyed by radiation.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers, reporting in The Journal of Agricultural and
Food Chemistry, found that chili powder offered E. coli and other
bacteria the best protection against gamma rays, followed by black
pepper and turmeric. Antioxidants and perhaps other compounds in
the spices were found to help protect the bacterial DNA from
damage.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists noted that the spices offered only limited
protection, and that in irradiation of processed foods, the dosage
levels are high enough to kill off all bacteria, no matter how
spicy the dish. But the researchers suggest that their work may
someday lead to the use of spice extracts to protect healthy
tissues in people undergoing radiation therapy.
</P>
<P>
   El Nino, the Ancient
</P>
<P>
   There is a tendency to think of El Nino as a new phenomenon, as
modern as alternate side of the street parking, say, or microwave
popcorn. Scientists who study climate history, however, know that
El Nino events, when the waters of the eastern Pacific warm up and
influence the weather worldwide, have occurred for at least 5,000
years.
</P>
<P>
   Make that at least 17,500 years, according to researchers at the
University of Massachusetts. Writing in the journal Science, the
researchers describe evidence of a three- to five-year cycle of El
Nino events during the late part of the last ice age.
</P>
<P>
   That evidence was found not by trekking to the edge of the
Earth, but rather to the edge of the UMass campus in Amherst. The
scientists studied cores taken from a site usually used for
research on civil engineering.
</P>
<P>
   The cores were made up of sediments deposited toward the end of
the ice age, when what is known as the Laurentide Ice Sheet was
receding, leaving a huge lake that covered most of what is now the
Connecticut River Valley. The thickness of the annual sediment
layers in the cores reflects how fast the ice sheet was melting.
The researchers found that there was a cyclical variability in the
thick layers, when the warmth of El Nino events would have caused
the ice to melt faster.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers suggest that by showing that El Nino events
occurred under such vastly different conditions all those years
ago, their work will help scientists understand more about the
phenomenon today.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-00 1554EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000515.0167 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 16:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5627 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-G8-CYBERCRIME-0516-CO     05-15 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-G8-CYBERCRIME-0516-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    INTERNET CRIMINALS STAYING ONE CLICK AHEAD OF LAW ENFORCEMENT
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (f) Financial categories.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The world's law-enforcement agencies are struggling to
keep pace with Internet criminals who strike without warning and
then slip nearly unseen into cyberspace leaving behind few clues,
officials at an international cyber-crime conference said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The three-day conference, organized by the G8 group of
industrialized nations, is the first international gathering of law
enforcers, business representatives and government officials to
address the burgeoning problem of cyber-crime.
</P>
<P>
   A virtual crimewave is accompanying the surge in worldwide
Internet use that is forcing authorities to develop new sets of
skills to counter rivals who are developing sophisticated new scams
at rate that far outpaces conventional police tactics, industry and
law-enforcement officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, because the Internet has no national borders
authorities are hampered as they pursue cyber-criminals across
jurisdictions where laws and customs often have not been brought up
to date.
</P>
<P>
   David Aucsmith, the chief scientist at Intel Corp., said that
government and industry leaders are beginning to find some
consensus in how to approach the problems of Internet crime but the
gap remains.
</P>
<P>
   ``The technology has outpaced any of our ability to agree on
some of the social ramifications of it,'' said Aucsmith, one of the
industry leaders at the conference. ``The technology is much easier
to evolve than are policies or laws.''
</P>
<P>
   James Robinson, head of the U.S. Justice Department's criminal
division, said law-enforcement officials confront a dizzying array
of issues in combating cyber-crime.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson said cyber-criminals ``can sit at a laptop and commit a
crime across the street and weave it through seven countries and
pretty soon you don't have any idea where it's coming from,''
Robinson told reporters at the conference.
</P>
<P>
   International protocols will have to be changed to allow
investigators to move through various jurisdictions quickly. ``When
things are moving at such a speed, you can't sit there and work for
months and months to wait to have things translated and go through
this process,'' Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, the interests of law-enforcement agencies often
are in conflict with the desires of computer users to protect the
secrecy of their transactions and privacy of their communications,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a tension between finding a way to secure the system
to minimize misuses that still allows us to do the job we need to
do,'' he said. ``We all think about coming across encrypted
communications ... that may involve terrorist acts or kidnapping or
other ... criminal activity.''
</P>
<P>
   While officials say that it is very difficult to measure the
scope of Internet crime, there is a consensus that is growing
rapidly. The FBI opened an online fraud complaint center last
Monday and received 3,700 complaints in the first 3 1/2 days. ``We
were frankly kind of surprised because it isn't well-known, yet,''
said Tom Packard, the FBI's delegate at the conference.
</P>
<P>
   Despite heightened concerns about fraud with the explosion of
online financial transactions, many industry officials say they
worry more about viruses, such as the ``Love Bug'' variant that
struck hundreds of thousands of computers a week and a half ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The threat of serious crime is not that significant at the
moment,'' said Aucsmith of Intel, which produces the ubiquitous
Pentium microprocessors. ``However, the average person using the
Internet is actually subject to a considerable amount of attack.
Those attacks are the equivalent of cyberspace vandalism. They're
not fraud., not someone robbing you.''
</P>
<P>
   Packard said he was concerned by the apparent trust people put
in information on the Internet. ``What's more troubling to me is
the way people view the internet, and if it's on the Internet they
seem to be more trusting of it or more believing in it whether it's
a news article that they read in the Internet or baseball cards,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the thorniest issues facing the conference is defining
the limits of industry self-regulation. Generally, Internet
companies resist government involvement, seeing in it a potential
form of censorship and an invitation to let states meddle with the
sector's organic growth.
</P>
<P>
   They prefer fighting cyber-crime with technical innovation,
educating users and companies about security risks, and making
better use of existing laws.
</P>
<P>
   A conference delegate, Stephanie Perrin, chief privacy officer
at a Canadian company, Zero-Knowledge Systems. Inc., said firms,
while eager to uphold the law, are suspicious of ``extending the
arm of law enforcers into the private sector.''
</P>
<P>
   Delegates hope the conference will develop a consensus on basic
principles in policing cyberspace. However, it is unlikely to
produce any sweeping multi-national policies. It ends Wednesday and
will report its conclusions to the G8 summit in Okinawa in July.
</P>
<P>
   The G8 comprises the G7 group - Britain, Canada, France,
Germany, Italy, Japan and the United States - plus Russia.
</P>
<P>
   (Bert Roughton Jr.'s E-mail address is: BertR(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.cybercrime.gov
</P>
<P>
   ww.g8parishightech.org
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-00 1603EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000515.0168 </DOCNO>
