<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-RUSSIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA FAILED TO ARREST YUGOSLAV GENERAL INDICTED FOR WAR CRIMES 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WARSAW, Poland _ The Yugoslav defense minister, Gen. Dragoljub
Ojdanic, indicted for war crimes during the Kosovo conflict, spent
five days on an official visit to Moscow last week without being
arrested by Russia, a permanent member of the U.N. Security
Council.
</P>
<P>
   Ojdanic, who was the Yugoslav army chief of staff during the
Kosovo war last year, is believed to be the first publicly indicted
Yugoslav official to travel outside Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the Yugoslav president, Slobodan Milosevic, and three
other officials, Ojdanic was indicted a year ago, on May 26, by the
International Criminal Tribunal for the Former Yugoslavia on
charges of crimes against humanity and violation of the laws and
customs of war in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The tribunal itself was established by the U.N. Security
Council, of which Russia is one of five permanent members. All
member states of the United Nations are supposed to arrest indicted
war criminals if possible.
</P>
<P>
   According to Russian press reports printed the day after he
left, Ojdanic arrived in Moscow on May 7, coinciding with the
inauguration of Russian President Vladimir Putin. Ojdanic
reportedly met with Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev and attended the
May 9 military parade marking the end of World War II. He left
Moscow on May 12, after apparently helping to prepare the visit of
Yugoslav Foreign Minister Zivadin Jovanovic, who arrived in Moscow
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Risley, a spokesman for the tribunal, said the chief
prosecutor, Carla Del Ponte, ``is alarmed by these reports.'' In a
telephone interview, Risley said Del Ponte would ask Moscow about
the reports ``and why a person indicted before the tribunal was not
arrested.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia has been a traditional ally of Yugoslavia and the Serbs
but helped the West negotiate an end to the war in Kosovo. Russian
troops also serve with U.N. peacekeeping troops in Kosovo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
