<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH-HATERS MAY HAVE A LONG ROAD AHEAD OF THEM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Bush-haters must be discouraged. They haven't been swamping
me with nasty e-mails, scathing letters and vitriolic phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   These folks object to being described as ``Bush-haters,'' by the
way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't hate George W. Bush,'' they always say. ``I just don't
think that stupid, smug, smirking so-and-so is qualified to be
president of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   What do you suppose they'd say if they hated him?
</P>
<P>
   I've never been able to figure out what it is about the Texas
governor that invites so much antagonism. He is a perfectly
pleasant person with a self-deprecating sense of humor and a
sincere sense of gratitude for the success that he has achieved in
both the private and public sectors.
</P>
<P>
   But some of these people apparently loathe Bush with a passion
not unlike that of the Clinton-haters who look upon every word and
deed of the current president as a personal affront.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, the Bush-haters were ecstatic when the Republican
presidential nominee-to-be seemed to stumble in some of the early
primaries. They were thrilled by the media-driven John McCain
uprising that temporarily rattled the Bush campaign and sapped his
record-setting campaign bankroll.
</P>
<P>
   But then Bush crushed McCain's challenge, secured the nomination
and set about the business of gearing up for the general election
campaign against Democrat Al Gore. The Bush-haters were despondent.
</P>
<P>
   And they grow more despondent every day as poll after poll shows
Bush edging past Gore in the ``horse race'' phase of the campaign _
and also expanding his appeal among the various voter groups whose
support will eventually add up to victory in the Electoral College.
</P>
<P>
   Recent polls suggest that Bush has erased the ``gender gap''
that was so crucial to Bill Clinton's victories in 1992 and 1996.
At least two polls, in fact, show Bush with a slight lead over Gore
among female voters _ a group that could very well decide the 2000
presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   Face it, Bush-haters: The compassionate conservative is on a
roll.
</P>
<P>
   Last week was definitely one of the best he's had since nailing
down his party's nomination way back in March. Bush racked up
impressive numbers in several polls, won an endorsement from McCain
and came up with a flurry of policy initiatives. His proposal to
provide free trigger locks to gun owners was perfectly timed to
coincide with Sunday's Million Mom March in support of gun safety.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also fared well on the TV interview circuit, answering
questions in a confident and succinct manner that refuted his
detractors' frequent claim that he is less than competent in such
forums.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, meanwhile, seems to be mired in quicksand. He has settled
into a boring and redundant pattern of false and/or irrelevant
attacks against Bush that are guaranteed to provoke yawns, if not
flat-out hostility, from voters. The vice president even enlisted
the aid of the Great Attacker, Clinton, who said that Bush would
appoint Supreme Court justices who are committed to repealing the
Roe vs. Wade decision that guarantees abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, as Clinton well knows, has said again and again that he
will apply no such ``litmus test'' in his judicial appointments.
</P>
<P>
   It's certainly understandable that the Clinton-Gore crowd would
resort to fiction in their criticism of Bush, since Bush would
prevail in any honest comparison of the Bush and Gore visions for
the nation's future. After Gore rips the Bush tax-cut plan as a
``risky scheme'' and terrorizes senior citizens with preposterous
characterizations of Bush's plan to save Social Security, the vice
president doesn't have much going for him.
</P>
<P>
   Gore could make the argument _ and probably will, if he gets
desperate enough _ that a Gore presidency would be just like four
more years of Clintonism. Talk about your risky schemes.
</P>
<P>
   These are tough times for the anti-Bush folks, I know. But don't
despair, Bush-haters; after he wins the election on Nov. 7, you'll
have four whole years to complain about him.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787 or
billthompson(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
