<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TOURISM ON THE RISE IN ASIA 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (EDS: Stands for HONG-KONG)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAVID ARMSTRONG  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ What a difference a year makes.
</P>
<P>
   Last year at this time, tourism in East Asia was still reeling
from the financial crisis that battered the region in 1997 and
1998, with hotels, airlines and tour operators sharing the pain.
</P>
<P>
   All that is beginning to change, according to tourism
representatives gathered at the 49th annual conference of the
Pacific Asia Travel Association in Hong Kong earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   PATA, based in San Francisco from 1953 until the association
moved to Bangkok in 1998, is a worldwide trade organization for the
travel industry. PATA meetings are, accordingly, major
schmoozefests for tourism board officials, business executives and
politicians. Hong Kong's chief executive, Tung Chee-hwa, welcomed
the group in the spectacular convention center on the edge of
Victoria Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   According to numbers-crunchers at the PATA conference, tourism _
a bellwether business in the region _ is surging. Hotel occupancy
rates are up, the number of passengers on trans-Pacific flights is
rising, airlines are adding flights and buying new planes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the middle of 1999, we have seen the return of growth
and confidence across almost all of Asia,'' said David Turnbull,
the chief executive at Hong Kong-based Cathay Pacific Airways.
Turnbull said the airline's passenger traffic grew 8 percent in the
first three months of 2000, and its cargo business increased by 11
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong _ Asia's most popular destination, with some 11
million visitors a year _ is a case study in economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong counted 1.9 million tourists in January and February,
a healthy 12.2 percent jump over the same months in 1999, according
to the Hong Kong Tourist Association (HKTA).
</P>
<P>
   Lillibeth Bishop, the HKTA's publicity and promotions manager
for the Americas, attributed the dramatic rebound to ``improving
economies, competition among airlines, trade promotions and
positive media publicity.''
</P>
<P>
   That is good news for countries that depend on the millions of
tourists and the billions of dollars they spend _ and an
encouraging sign for investors and U.S. multinationals waiting for
the Asian tigers to regain their roar.
</P>
<P>
   It is also good news across the Pacific in San Francisco, where
tourism generates revenues of $6.5 billion per year, according to
the San Francisco Convention &AMP; Visitors Bureau. Presumably, when
East Asian economies recover fully, and their citizens resume
traveling abroad in large numbers, tourist towns like San Francisco
will benefit, too.
</P>
<P>
   Presently, growth in two-way international air traffic is
driving development of San Francisco International Airport's new
$944 million International Terminal, which is set to open Sept. 26.
International travel is growing twice as fast as domestic travel,
according to airport spokesman Ron Wilson. Traffic to and from Asia
outpaced growth in other areas through most of the 1990s, Wilson
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're nearly back to where we were before the Asian crisis,''
Wilson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
