<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SOCIAL-SECURITY (Undated) _ Texas Gov. George Bush and Vice
President Al Gore campaign at opposite ends of the country, each
touting his plan for Social Security. Bush outlines a proposal that
would allow some investment of Social Security money in the stock
market, while Gore calls the Bush plan risky and proposes shoring
up the current pension-style system with budget surpluses. By R. G.
RATCLIFFE and BENNETT ROTH.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-REACT (Washington) _ Supporters of Social Security private
investment accounts praise Texas Gov. George W. Bush's plan for the
government retirement system as a bold step in the right direction.
But critics charge that the plan _ which would allow younger
workers to divert part of their payroll taxes to the private
accounts _ would drain Social Security of funds needed to guarantee
its future fiscal health. By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COURT-RAPE (Washington) _ The Supreme Court strikes down a
federal law allowing rape victims to sue their attackers, saying
Congress overstepped its bounds and reached into an area that
states should handle. The 5-4 ruling invalidates a provision in the
1994 Violence Against Women Act that allowed victims of
gender-related violence to seek civil damages in federal court
rather than rely solely on state prosecutors and juries. By MARK
HELM.
</P>
<P>
   MOMS-LOBBY (Washington) _ The day after hundreds of thousands of
mothers rallied in the nation's capital for stricter gun
legislation, some stay on to lobby Congress. We check on the
efforts of the gun control side and the pro-gun moms, who held a
counter-demonstration Sunday. By AUSTIN ZALKIN.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (London) _ From a distance, the British
parliamentary system looks orderly and serene compared with our
messy political process. But up close, local politicians are as
adept at hurling insults, and the voters are as irritatingly
rebellious as our own. A foe kicked out of the Labor Party by Prime
Minister Tony Blair, for instance, was recently elected mayor of
London despite Blair's noisy opposition. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
</TEXT>
