<HEADER>
A5649 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-VITAL-SIGNS-ART-N     05-15 1265
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-VITAL-SIGNS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH AND FITNESS NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT3 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 (The Science Times)  
 &HT;     
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   THERAPIES: For Strokes, a Snake Oil With Results
</P>
<P>
   A new study has found that a purified form of snake venom can
act as an effective ``clot busting'' drug to lessen the damage of
strokes, potentially joining a growing arsenal of anti-stroke
medications.
</P>
<P>
   The study, published last Wednesday in The Journal of the
American Medical Association, represented the largest trial to date
of ancrod, a substance derived from Malaysian pit vipers. Over five
years, 500 patients suffering acute strokes were assigned to
receive infusions of ancrod or a placebo.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers, led by Dr. David Sherman of the University of
Texas Health Science Center in San Antonio, reported that 42
percent of patients receiving ancrod regained ``favorable
functional status'' compared with 34 percent of the placebo group,
and that fewer patients receiving the venom were left severely
disabled.
</P>
<P>
   An editorial that accompanied the article noted that ancrod is
not likely to replace the standard therapy, known as tPA, which is
easier to administer and has shown slightly better results. The
more promising line of research opened by the new study, it said,
is into ways of combining ancrod, tPA and other drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, the editorial said, the results of tests of ancrod
and tPA underscore the need to educate the public about the
symptoms of stroke and the urgency of seeking treatment, since both
drugs can be given safely only within three hours of the onset of
the attack.
</P>
<P>
   PREVENTION: Building Lyme Immunity in Children
</P>
<P>
   The vaccine against Lyme disease, so far given only to adults,
has been found to be safe and effective in children as young as 4,
according to research presented on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the vaccine appears to work better in children than
adults, said the study's lead author, Dr. Neal Halsey of the Johns
Hopkins School of Public Health. Speaking at a joint meeting of the
Pediatric Academic Societies and the American Academy of Pediatrics
in Boston, Halsey said that children ages 4 to 14 appeared to get
the same level of protection after two shots that adults got from
three.
</P>
<P>
   The vaccine was given to 3,063 children and 1,024 were given a
placebo.
</P>
<P>
   Parents of children receiving the vaccine did report slightly
higher rates of reactions like fever, headache and joint pain, but
these were described as mild and short-lived. After 13 months, all
of the children receiving the vaccine were found to have developed
immunity to the disease, Halsey said.
</P>
<P>
   The results of the study will be reviewed by the Food and Drug
Administration, which will decide whether to approve the vaccine,
known as Limerix, for use in children.
</P>
<P>
   SAFETY: When Excess Water Can Kill a Runner
</P>
<P>
   Runners who get dehydrated face obvious dangers, but drinking
too much water during a race can also be deadly, according to a
study in this month's issue of the Annals of Internal Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Allen Arieff of the University of California at San
Francisco and researchers at Baylor College of Medicine in Houston
investigated seven cases in which runners who collapsed after a
marathon were found to be suffering hyponatremia, a shortage of
salt in the blood. One of the runners died.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen other similar fatalities have been reported from
marathons. Arieff said he suspected that other deaths after
marathons were misidentified as heart attacks instead of
hyponatremia.
</P>
<P>
   Fears of dehydration have led to a mistaken belief that the safe
thing to do in a marathon ``is to drink as much as you can, as
often as you can,'' Arieff said.
</P>
<P>
   A complicated chain of metabolic events can lead to trouble, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Exercise leads the body to release antidiurectic hormone, which
block normal elimination of excess fluid as urine. (Taking drugs
like ibuprofen can strengthen this effect, said Arieff.)
</P>
<P>
   During a race, so much blood is diverted to the muscles that the
intestines are unable to absorb the water a runner drinks. Once the
race ends, however, that water floods into the blood stream,
disrupting the body's salt balance. This can cause the brain to
swell, which in turn sets off a mechanism that releases water into
the lungs.
</P>
<P>
   The treatment for the condition is simple: add more salt to the
bloodstream. But the fluid in the lungs and the circumstances of
the collapse often lead emergency room doctors to suspect heart
trouble and to order treatments that make things worse, he said.
</P>
<P>
   So how much water is enough? That varies from athlete to
athlete, Arieff said, and is definitely not a function of how
thirsty you feel. He recommends that marathoners weigh themselves
before and after a trial run, say a half-marathon, to figure out
how much water they will lose. And that's more or less the amount
they should drink, he said.
</P>
<P>
   PATTERNS: The Price of Ending `Drive-By Deliveries'
</P>
<P>
   A Pennsylvania law against ``drive-by deliveries'' _ limits set
by insurance companies on how long mothers and their newborn
infants can remain in the hospital _ has succeeded in extending the
average length of stay, but at a cost that may outweigh the law's
benefits, according to a study released Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jay Greenspan and Dr. Jennifer Culhane, neonatologists at
Jefferson Medical College in Philadelphia, compiled data on all
births in the city for two years before and two years after passage
of the law, which required that insurers cover at least 48 hours of
hospitalization for mothers and infants after vaginal deliveries
and 96 hours after Caesarean deliveries.
</P>
<P>
   They found that the average length of mothers' hospital stays
rose from 34 to 48 hours, and that the median cost rose from $5,200
to $6,800, with similar trends for infants. That added up to an
increased health care bill of $20 million to $25 million a year in
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The incredible increase in costs suggests that we might come
up with a better model to improve comfort and care and outcomes,''
Greenspan said. ``For $1,600, you can get a whole lot of outpatient
services that might have a bigger impact.''
</P>
<P>
   NUTRITION: A Dose of Fiber for Diabetes Regimen
</P>
<P>
   Fiber's reputation as a defense against cancer has taken a
beating lately, but a new study reported last week in The New
England Journal of Medicine reaffirms its value as a treatment for
adult onset diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   In the study, the researchers examined 13 patients who spent six
weeks on a diet that followed the American Dietary Association
guidelines and six weeks on a diet that contained significantly
more fiber than specified in the guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   When the patients were on the high fiber diet, their daily
plasma glucose concentrations were 10 percent lower, and other
measures dropped by similarly significant amounts.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers are from the University of Texas Southwestern
Medical Center and the Veterans Affairs Medical Center, both in
Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   In an editorial that accompanied their report, Dr. Marc Rendell
of the Creighton Diabetes Center in Omaha noted that the
improvement was roughly equivalent to the usual effect of adding
another drug to &QC; the treatment regimen of a diabetic patient.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be more desirable first to take full advantage of the
improvements that can be attained by dietary modification,'' before
adding medicine to medicine, he wrote.
</P>
</TEXT>
