<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SAY CHEESE: ODD SPORTING HABITS ARE VERY BRITISH 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JOHN FLINN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   On the last Monday in May, the semi-besotted young men of
Gloucestershire, England, will gather atop treacherously steep
Cooper's Hill to renew one of the strangest traditions in the
history of sport.
</P>
<P>
   A local dignitary will let loose an 8-pound wheel of Double
Gloucester cheese, and the young men will hurl their bodies down
the hill in pursuit. In theory, whoever catches the bouncing,
bounding wheel gets to keep it; in practice, no one ever does.
Whoever gets to the bottom of the hill first is awarded the cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Dating back to Roman times and perhaps earlier, it's a brutal,
full-contact sport. Bodies cartwheel down the hill, fanny-over-tea
kettle. Limbs and ankles twist and snap. Contestants and wayward
cheese wheels hurtle into the gallery.
</P>
<P>
   Ambulances line the bottom of the hill, and each year they're
kept busy carting bloodied contestants and spectators off to the
hospital. In 1995, 18 out of 20 entrants were injured. The
following year there were 33 casualties, the year after that 27.
</P>
<P>
   As the carnage mounted, the event was cancelled in 1998 while
the organizers decided on safety measures. They added new crash
barriers and a rescue team and, most importantly, moved the race
from 6 p.m. to noon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It stops people having too much to drink before they come,''
explained Richard Jeffries, one of the organizers.
</P>
<P>
   It appears to have worked: only one contestant was hospitalized
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since my wife Jeri and I hiked past Cooper's Hill on the
Cotswold Way 10 years ago, I've been morbidly fascinated with the
bizarre and peculiar sporting scene of Great Britain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing gives the English more pleasure, in a quiet but
determined sort of way, than to do things oddly,'' wrote Bill
Bryson in ``Notes from a Small Island.'' This goes doubly for
sport.
</P>
<P>
   In the Cotswolds market town of Chipping Campden, for example,
they engage in the sport of ``shin kicking.'' A featured attraction
of the Dover Games in early June, it was banned from 1852 to 1952.
But, as one guidebook put it, ``it has been enthusiastically
revived by the town's orthopedic surgeons.''
</P>
<P>
   According to ``The Customs and Ceremonies of Britain,'' the
following sports were once regularly practiced at British festivals
and celebrations: ``Grinning for the cake,'' ``Jumping in the bag''
and ``Chattering for a bladder of snuff by old women.'' Alas, the
book is cruelly silent about the details of these pastimes.
</P>
<P>
   None of these practices, though, is as perversely odd and
cringe-producing as the Yorkshire sport of ferret-legging.
</P>
<P>
   Here is how Donald Katz described the sport in a 1983 article in
Outside Magazine: ``Basically, ferret-legging involves the tying of
a competitor's trousers at the ankles and the insertion into those
trousers of a couple of peculiarly vicious fur-coated, foot-long
carnivores called ferrets. The brave contestant's belt is then
pulled tight, and he proceeds to stand there in front of the judges
as long as he can, while animals with claws like hypodermic needles
and teeth like number 16 carpet tacks try their damnedest to get
out.''
</P>
<P>
   It's important to note that these are hunting ferrets _ which
apparently make pit bulls look timid by comparison _ rather than
docile domestic ferrets.
</P>
<P>
   Katz suggests that the sport evolved out of the practice by
Yorkshire hunters of keeping their ferrets warm and dry in their
trousers on drizzly days. Others believe it is the outgrowth of a
medieval British law that banned working-class people from owning
animals that were so effective at poaching rabbits from the game
reserves of the nobility. Poachers apparently stuffed their ferrets
down their pants to conceal them from gamekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   Katz's story profiled 72-year-old Reg Mellor, the ``king of
ferret legging,'' who at the time held the world's record, a
scarcely believable five hours, 26 minutes. (He could have gone
longer, he said, but all the spectators went home and workmen began
to dismantle the stage.)
</P>
<P>
   The article has achieved a curiously enduring cult following;
people _ almost always men _ fax old copies to friends of friends.
It's been reprinted in both anthologies Outside Magazine has
issued. The second, ``Best of Outside: The First 20 Years,'' is
still in print.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, Mellor took his life a couple of years after the article
appeared. Some of his neighbors in the town of Barnsley thought the
sudden onslaught of publicity unhinged him; others said he had to
have been mentally unbalanced to participate in the sport in the
first place.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, ferret-legging in Yorkshire pretty much
died out with Mellor. However, I have heard rumors that it survives
in a remote corner of County Kildare in Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Thankfully, cheese-rolling shows no sign of fading away. ``They
say they'll keep doing it every year, no matter what,'' Rosemary
Hellerman, owner of the nearby Haven Tea House, told me when I
passed through. ``I doubt you could ever have anything like that in
America, not with all those lawyers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
