<BODY>
 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Tuesday, May 16. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Henry Warnken; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
warnken(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-PALESTINIANS (Jerusalem) _ For the first time in four
years, Israeli and Palestinian troops engaged in hours of gun
battles in the West Bank Monday as Israeli forces suppressed
Palestinian demonstrations by shooting tear gas, rubber-coated
bullets and live ammunition into stone-throwing crowds. Three
Palestinians were killed _ two police officers and a teen-ager _
and 350 were injured, according to Palestinian officials. Six
Israeli soldiers were injured, according to Israeli officials.
Against this violent backdrop, Prime Minister Ehud Barak won
Parliament's approval to transfer full control of three Palestinian
villages near Jerusalem to the Palestinian Authority, although
three parties in his fractious coalition did not support him and
one quit the government. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT6, and a map.
</P>
<P>
   GULF-WAR-MCCAFFREY (Washington) _ The Army said Monday that it
had no plans to reopen an investigation into an attack launched at
the end of the Persian Gulf war by soldiers under the command of
Barry R. McCaffrey, now President Clinton's senior drug-policy
adviser. An article published Monday in The New Yorker raised
several allegations about the attack, in which the 24th Infantry
Division pummeled retreating Iraqi forces near Rumaila in southern
Iraq two days after a cease-fire went into effect. By Steven Lee
Myers.
</P>
<P>
   GUATEMALA-FIRES (El Ceibal, Guatemala) _ Huge fires caused by
squatters threaten nature reserve and Mayan ruins. By David
Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT9, and map.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-WOMEN (Washington) _ Declaring that ``the Constitution
requires a distinction between what is truly national and what is
truly local,'' the Supreme Court Monday invalidated a six-year-old
law that permitted victims of rape, domestic violence and other
crimes ``motivated by gender'' to sue their attackers in federal
court. The 5-4 decision striking down the civil remedy provision of
the Violence Against Women Act was the latest, one of the most
sweeping, but almost certainly not the last application of the
court's newly restrictive view of congressional power and of the
degree of deference that Congress is owed by federal courts. By
Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   LOS-ALAMOS-FIRE (Los Alamos, N.M.) _ Developments: The Los
Alamos fire destroyed almost all of the buildings where scientists
helped build the atomic bomb that was detonated in 1945. It is also
threatening historic Indian ruins in the area. Firefighters worked
furiously to contain the fire amid worries that winds will kick up
to 50 mph on Tuesday. By James Sterngold.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-POLL (Undated) _ Results of the latest NYT/CBS News
poll. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CO2-EMISSIONS (Undated) _ As the economic and political
difficulty of reducing carbon dioxide emissions becomes ever more
obvious, a move is under way to manipulate the carbon cycle so that
it will remove more heat-trapping gases from the air. But the
ambitious idea is surrounded by questions of potential risks and
obstacles. Some researchers are looking for ways to remove carbon
from industrial emissions before they are released. But more
promising, many believe, are prospects for increasing the
absorption of atmospheric carbon dioxide by what is called the
terrestrial biosphere: the whole complex of living things on land,
mainly plants and various tiny inhabitants of the soil. The
expansion of these carbon reservoirs, or ``sinks,'' in vegetation
and soil has been sanctioned under the 1997 Kyoto Protocol. By
William K. Stevens. (2050 words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HANDEDNESS-GENE (Undated) _ The latest word on what makes
people left- or right-handed comes from a geneticist at the
National Cancer Institute laboratory here who has been working for
years with yeast and mutant mice and has developed a theory that he
believes explains why nine of 10 people in all cultures are
right-handed, why left-handed parents are more likely to have
left-handed children and why identical twins often have different
handedness. Most people, he says, have a specific dominant gene
that makes them right-handed. But about 20 percent of people lack
the right-handed gene, and these people without the gene have a
50-50 possibility of being right-handed or left-handed. By David E.
Rosenbaum. (1350 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT2.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   NY-INDIAN-LANDCLAIMS (Onondaga Nation, N.Y.) _ The six Iroquois
nations of New York state are at the epicenter of one of the
biggest, most volatile issues now in upstate New York: Indian
claims to land that was seized 200 years ago. By David W. Chen.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
