<P>
   &UR; PUTIN WANTS A STRONG RUSSIA _ BUT TO WHAT END? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PUTIN'S-RUSSIA-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Vladimir Putin was inaugurated Russian president on
May 7. On the surface, he seems to be a shot of fresh new blood for
the Kremlin. Yet doubts about Putin linger, even mount. While the
West should wish his presidency well, he will not gain the
confidence of westerners until he shows that he is his own man, and
that that man is someone who believes in civil liberty and the rule
of law, not just in the strengths of despots. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (775 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IS BRITAIN'S TONY BLAIR THE RIGHT MAN FOR THE WRONG PARTY? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TONYBLAIR-ENIGMA-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Nobody can accuse British Prime Minister Tony Blair
of not trying to imbue his new politics with missionary zeal. He
sermonizes at the drop of a hat. But after last week's dismal local
election results for his New Labour Party, there is no longer much
doubt about what ails his party. Whatever the merits of his ``third
way,'' it does not turn on Labour's heartlands like the old-time
religion used to. Hence the increasingly frantic calls on him to
turn left and woo back the ``heartland'' voters. &QL;
</P>
