</P>
<P>
   &UR; HATING-HILLARY-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK AND LITTLE ROCK _ She just can't win. In New York,
Hillary Rodham Clinton is widely seen as an Arkansas carpetbagger,
and is hated for it. In Arkansas, however, she is seen as a New
Yorker, and is hated for that just as keenly. How deeply does the
hatred go? Much more deeply than seems reasonable. In New York,
retailers report a brisk trade in nine-inch Hillary voodoo dolls
that carry the invitation to ``stick it to her.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (475 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ALAS, BACK TO SQUARE ONE FOR HANFORD'S RADIOACTIVE CLEANUP &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NUKE-CLEANUP-WASH.ST-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ If you have ever watched a glacier being deployed to
fight a house fire, you will have some idea of the speed of the
cleanup that has been going on, for the past 15 years, at the
Hanford Nuclear Reservation in Washington state. Hanford is
generally considered the most dangerously polluted spot in North
America. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Washington-State Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (725 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHY CARDINAL O'CONNOR WILL BE MISSED &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; O'CONNOR-LEGACY-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ By forming healthy friendships with many of the
people he publicly disagreed with, the late Cardinal John O'Connor
transcended his office as New York's top Catholic and became a
figure who will be much missed by people of all faiths and none.
His replacement certainly has a tough act to follow. &QL;
</P>
