<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SIERRA LEONE'S PREDICTABLE MESS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SIERRA-LEONE-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Sierra Leone is turning out to be as big a blow to
U.N. peacekeeping as were Somalia, Rwanda and Srebrenica. In fact,
the mess was all too predictable, dating back to the half-baked
Lome peace accord _ forced on all parties by the Americans _ which
put the elected government and the barbaric RUF rebels on the same
footing, thereby legitimizing them. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (850 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EUROPE &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MIKHAIL KASYANOV, RUSSIA'S NEW BIG WHEEL &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MIKHAIL-KASYANOV-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Under doddery Boris Yeltsin, Russian prime ministers
were the men who more or less ran the country, interrupted by the
odd snarl from the Kremlin. The job was exciting but usually brief.
In his nine years at the Kremlin, Yeltsin went through six prime
ministers; only one lasted more than a year. For 42-year-old
Mikhail Kasyanov, whom Vladimir Putin nominated as acting prime
minister after being inaugurated on May 7, things look set to be
rather different. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (1,000 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; `HELLO?...MEET ME AT THE CASBAH': MOROCCO GOES MOBILE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOROCCO-CELLPHONES-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RABAT _ Four decades after independence, 80 percent of Morocco's
villages and half of its population have yet to get paved roads,
electricity and running water. But at least the country's peasants
can now get mobile phones. Morocco is claiming the fastest
mobile-phone growth in the world _ albeit from a low base. The
number of subscribers in the country has quadrupled in six months
to 800,000. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (500 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SHAKESPEARE'S LESSONS FOR BUSINESS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SHAKESPEARE-LEADERSHIP-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ The well-informed manager has no time for
literature. His briefcase bulges with the incessant output of the
business-books division that every struggling publisher has now set
up. Yet the manager might occasionally put aside ``Beyond Greed and
Fear'' and reach, instead, for greed and fear in their original
forms: the plays of William Shakespeare. For when it comes to case
studies of ruthless business practices, he wrote the book _
literally. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (425 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; VOICE RECOGNITION SOFTWARE TAKES OFF &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; VOCAL-INTERNET-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ You don't need a souped-up cell phone to surf the
Internet when you're on the road _ just your own dulcet tones.
That's the idea behind a new breed of voice service that is popping
up all over the place. Voice portals could even become a new form
of interactive car radio. Commuters could eventually select their
news, answer their e-mail or do their grocery shopping. A fantasy?
Recently, Ford Motors and a speech-products company formed a
venture to look into just that. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (650 words) &QL;
</P>
