<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 16:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5702 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-GENETIC-SCREENING     05-15 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-GENETIC-SCREENING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE SIDE EFFECT OF GENETIC TESTS: FEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    Dr. Howard Markel is a fellow at the Center for Scholars and
Writers of the New York Public Library and an associate professor
of history and of pediatrics and communicable diseases at the
University of Michigan.
 By HOWARD MARKEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Soon, the human genome will be completely mapped allowing
doctors to detect, treat and prevent disease on a level
unimaginable a few decades ago. But while genetic screening tests
are remarkable diagnostic tools, they are not without potential
harm to those who happen to carry a deleterious trait. As a
physician who routinely orders such tests, I thought I long
understood this dynamic. But I needed my wife, Kate, for a more
definitive lesson.
</P>
<P>
   When Kate told me she was pregnant with our first child I was,
of course, elated. Soon enough, I began to worry about the
possibility of a less than perfectly healthy baby. Most expectant
parents nervously ponder this issue, but my work as a pediatrician
creates an especially skewed vision: Many of the children who
inhabit my world are among that tiny minority with the most serious
and often the rarest illnesses. In a strange sense, when
abnormality and disease dominate your view, it becomes ``normal.''
</P>
<P>
   On the advice of her obstetrician, Kate underwent a complete
battery of genetic tests but this only sharpened my fears. What if
one of us carried a deadly disease that might be passed on to our
unborn child? Such mental meanderings reminded me that like many
doctors, I absolutely hate the idea of my (or my loved ones') being
a patient.
</P>
<P>
   One evening, I came home to find Kate nervously hunched over a
cup of tea. Before I could even take off my coat, she told me that
she tested positive for the genetic screening test for Tay Sachs
Disease (TSD), a rare genetic disease that clusters among Ashkenazi
Jews, of Central and Eastern European descent. Coded by a recessive
gene, meaning that one can be a silent carrier, the actual disease
requires both parents to have the trait. Even then, there is only a
one out of four chance that their baby will receive both genes.
</P>
<P>
   TSD is a horrific malady resulting from the baby's inability to
produce one critical enzyme (beta-hexosamidinase A) necessary for
normal brain growth and development. First described in the 1880s
by a British ophthalmologist, Warren Tay, and a New York City
neurologist, Bernard Sachs _ each of whom had many immigrant
Ashkenazi Jews among their patients _ the disease is 100 percent
fatal. Although newborns with the disease appear normal, within
several months, they begin to exhibit severe muscular weakness _
pediatricians call them ``floppy babies'' _ and difficulty doing
the activities infants typically do: rolling over, crawling and
walking, feeding, swallowing and ultimately breathing.
</P>
<P>
   Compounding these problems are blindness, seizures and a
generalized haze of unresponsiveness. Death comes all too
mercifully for TSD babies long before a healthy child is readied
for kindergarten.
</P>
<P>
   Although no one in our families had been identified as a TSD
carrier, we most certainly fit the profile. Both of Ashkenazi
Jewish descent, our grandparents were close friends and members of
the same Yiddish social clubs, known as landsmanshaftn, that were
formed in America at the turn of century to help newcomers adjust
to a new life. Not only did Kate's grandfather Ben dance at our
wedding, 24 years before he danced at my bar mitzvah.
</P>
<P>
   Even with this intertwined family history, however, the odds of
our both being carriers, let alone the baby's having TSD were low.
Only one in 35 Ashkenazi Jews carry the trait and, before genetic
screening became available in the 1970s, about one in 3,500 to
4,000 of their newborns suffered from TSD. Today, the incidence is
much lower since more than 95 percent of the pregnancies are
terminated when TSD is identified by prenatal screening.
</P>
<P>
   The following morning as I rolled up my sleeve for a blood test,
I told myself that I ``knew'' all about TSD. I had even written
several scholarly papers on the stigma of genetic screening tests.
Such intellectualization, however, offered little comfort and did
not allay my fears. To worsen matters, when I told Kate that I had
discussed her carrier status with some of my friends, she was
perturbed that I divulged this information without discussing it
with her first, revealing how little I really understood about the
sensitivities of those labeled a ``carrier'' of a devastating
illness.
</P>
<P>
   Bad news finds you quickly, doctors like to advise their
patients, but you often have to wait for good news. Each night as I
walked home from work, I prayed that this child would pass this
first hurdle unscathed.
</P>
<P>
   I bargained with God on how I would be a model parent. I wept at
the possibility that I, too, was a carrier and the potential
options facing my wife and me. In a small sense, I felt the
anguish, the helplessness, and the uncertainty of a patient. I was
reminded of what a patient once told me when confronted with a
terrible diagnosis: before someone tells you that you or your loved
one is sick you may have a hundred problems. Afterward, you have
only one.
</P>
<P>
   A week later Kate called me at the office. From the tone of her
voice, I immediately knew it was good news. ``You're negative,
Howard,'' she exclaimed, ``the baby can't have Tay-Sachs.'' As I
rushed home to embrace my wife, I wept again, this time with joy.
We were particularly fortunate in that many genetic screening tests
do not provide such definitive ``yes'' or ``no'' answers.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the newer tests, like the BRCA1 genetic test for breast
cancer, only indicate a higher risk of developing a specific
disease without any clear guarantees one way or the other, creating
a host of new problems of decision making for patients.
</P>
<P>
   Kate is now in her eighth month of pregnancy and there are still
more tests for our unborn child to pass _ not counting a lifetime
of tribulations that await her or him a few weeks hence. We'll have
to take each day as it comes _ which is, most likely, how the noble
term patient originated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
