u i BC-U.N.-U.S.-TORTURE-370     05-15 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.N.-U.S.-TORTURE-370&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. PRISON PRACTICES VIOLATE INTERNATIONAL TREATY ON TORTURE, U.N.
SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ELIZABETH OLSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ Use of electric stun belts and restraint chairs, which
human rights groups allege are widely employed to restrain
prisoners in the United States, almost inevitably violates the
international treaty against torture, a U.N. monitoring group said
Monday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. Committee Against Torture, which examines the
compliance of 118 countries that have ratified the 1984 pact, also
singled out police brutality, chain gangs, sexual assaults of
female prisoners by law enforcement officials and detention of
minors as problem areas in the United States. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The committee's panel of 10 human rights experts urged U.S.
officials to ``abolish electro-shock stun belts and restraint
chairs as methods of restraining those in custody,'' on grounds
their use ``almost invariably leads to breaches'' of the treaty,
which the United States ratified in 1994. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate response from the Clinton administration,
whose representatives received the recommendations without comment.
</P>
<P>
   Stun belts, which are placed around a prisoner's waist, are
allegedly used in as many as 100 U.S. jurisdictions. The Clinton
administration's top human rights official, Harold H. Koh, argued
that no lawsuits had been brought that substantiate the accusations
of death or serious injuries to prisoners from such restraints. He
said such devices are used only to transport dangerous inmates,
although Amnesty International asserted that in at least one case,
a judge had ordered an electric shock be given to a prisoner during
a public court proceeding.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the first review of the United States' record on torture and
other cruel, inhuman and degrading treatment or punishment, the
committee also asked the U.S. government to ``ensure that minors
are not held in prison with the regular prison population.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The committee's conclusions, which took three pages to list,
came in response to last week's U.S. government report, which is
required for all countries that have ratified the U.N. Convention
Against Torture. The United States was nearly five years late
filing its report, a fact noted by the committee, which also asked
that the United States file its second report in November next
year. &QL;
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Drawing on numerous examples provided by Amnesty International,
Human Rights Watch and other rights groups, the experts closely
questioned U.S. State and Justice Department officials last week
about practices that fall under the rubric of torture. The
committee has no independent investigative capacity so it must rely
on information provided by human rights advocates and, in countries
like the United States, uncensored media reports. The expert panel
also has no authority to sanction countries. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Amnesty argued there were numerous instances of mistreatment by
police and custody officials ``disproportionately directed at
racial and ethnic minorities.'' The U.S. report, which admitted
that the U.S. record was not perfect, listed well-known cases like
Abner Louima, the Haitian immigrant who was beaten and sodomized
with a broomstick by New York City police. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Committee experts concluded that ``the number of cases of police
ill-treatment of civilians, and ill-treatment in prisons'' were
matters of concern. This was particularly true, they said, because
``much of this ill-treatment by police and prison guards seems to
be based upon discrimination.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
