<HEADER>
A5682 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-CLIBURN-REMINISCENCE-     05-15 1188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLIBURN-REMINISCENCE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAGICAL MEMORIES, MOM AND VAN CLIBURN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM MADIGAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Against the expanse of Van Cliburn's historic career, the
concert three years ago in San Antonio scarcely warrants a
footnote. Cliburn performed his signature piece that night,
Tchaikovsky's First Piano Concerto, which drew the crowd to its
feet, a common response for one celebrated among the musical giants
of the 1900s. There were no medals awarded afterward. No large
spread noting the event in The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   But for me, the concert lingers among a life's milestones. My
mother and I were in the audience, the first time either one of us
had heard Cliburn play in person. The experience largely defied
description, as mystical moments often do.
</P>
<P>
   I had known of Cliburn for several years by then. He was the boy
from East Texas who conquered the world with his talent in 1958,
winning the Tchaikovsky International Piano Competition in Moscow
at the height of the Cold War. I had seen photographs of his
ticker-tape parade in New York that resulted, and had heard of the
Cliburn celebrity that once rivaled that of Elvis.
</P>
<P>
   I first saw Cliburn in 1993, while covering the Fort Worth piano
competition that bears his name. He raced up and down the aisles
between performances, a lanky man always dressed in a navy suit and
tie, always among the most exuberantly appreciative members of the
audience.
</P>
<P>
   We met once during that competition, and I shook one of his
famously large hands. A few years later, an ankle injury I suffered
playing basketball forced me to cancel a coveted sit-down interview
with Cliburn. He responded by sending me a huge bouquet of flowers.
Another writer, Mary Rogers, went instead, and in the lovely
profile that resulted, she wrote this:
</P>
<P>
   ``Friends note that he is an old-fashioned man with a sense of
elegance, who doesn't own a pair of tennis shoes and dresses always
in a suit and tie, even as he practices his art in the small hours
of the morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is, they say, sentimental, generous and kind, with a
childlike trust in people and a deep faith in God. They say he is
simple _ unaffected by his fame _ and almost always late ...
</P>
<P>
   ``He prays, writes poetry, walks late at night and is composing
a sonata. He doesn't dwell on life's disappointments, has no time
for jealousies or betrayals and believes in the fundamental
goodness of people.''
</P>
<P>
   He was _ and is _ a man with an aura. It was natural, then, to
wonder at the aura's source. Finally, that night in San Antonio, my
mother and I experienced it. Cliburn, in his sonorous speaking
voice, narrated Aaron Copland's tribute to Abraham Lincoln. Then
came the concerto itself, the same music with which he had tamed
Moscow four decades before. A roaring San Antonio crowd would not
let him leave, calling him back for several encores, adulation that
seemed to surprise him.
</P>
<P>
   Most other specifics escape me. I do remember how fast his hands
moved across the keyboard, how those long fingers could produce
such delicacy, how the short hairs stood on my neck. And I remember
the sense of being transported, of partaking of something timeless.
I wondered if others remembered those things, too.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago, while a music student in Dallas, Lauren
Eberhart attended the finals of the Van Cliburn International Piano
Competition in Fort Worth, then a reception at Cliburn's mansion.
She has recollections of meeting him briefly that night, and of
seeing a piano in almost every room.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was pretty neat,'' Eberhart said when I called her last
week. ``It was like, `Wow.'''
</P>
<P>
   So that night in San Antonio, Eberhart awaited Cliburn's
performance with a mixture of excitement and curiosity. She had
taken a position playing trumpet with the San Antonio Symphony, and
thus would enjoy an intimate perspective of the legend's
performance. Some masters, she knew, did not always live up to
expectations when heard in the flesh. She wondered whether this
would be true of Cliburn.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he was wonderful,'' Eberhart said. ``He was just a
wonderful player with a lot of strength and a lot of control over
his instrument. He could really be strong on the piano, but pull a
beautiful sound out of it. You would see why he had the reputation.
And the audience absolutely loved him. They were on their feet in a
hall that was not acoustically friendly.''
</P>
<P>
   Eberhart said she kept the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just realize that you're hearing something and someone who
has a significant place in musical history.''
</P>
<P>
   Violist Daniel Reinker was also a member of the San Antonio
Symphony that night. Many great soloists have passed through San
Antonio, he told me recently, but few of Cliburn's stature.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were many people who came to that performance who don't
often come to hear our orchestra,'' Reinker said. ``They came to
hear him. That in itself was thrilling to have all those new people
in the hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the sort of performer who has a musical personality that
just transcends the normal musical performance. It was really
magical, his presence and knowing that it was an opportunity that
would not present itself again. ... It was the only time I've
performed with him, and I imagine it will be the only time. That's
part of what makes it magical. You know you've got to cling to it
because it might be your only chance to experience it.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got goose bumps just thinking about it,'' my mother told
me in a recent telephone conversation.
</P>
<P>
   She was a young woman when Cliburn triumphed in Moscow, and
witnessed the fame that followed. My mother lived for most of her
life in a small town in northern Minnesota. I remember her taking
us to a concert of the Minnesota symphony when it passed through
our town, but hearing someone like Van Cliburn was unthinkable. So
sitting next to me in the San Antonio concert hall, she thought,
``Am I really here? Am I really doing this?''
</P>
<P>
   Then Cliburn started to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was breathtaking,'' Mom said. ``It's hard to believe that
so much talent can be contained in one person, who can play so
beautifully and get the audience so enthralled. Hearing him play,
and watching his fingers fly over the keys ... I remember looking
around at the audience. He had everybody in the palm of his hand.
It was like everybody was under hypnosis. It was just crazy, how he
could get everybody right where he wanted them, or right where they
wanted to be, I guess you would say.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just one of those surreal experiences,'' she said. ``He
just gathered everybody up. The audience kept calling him back. I
thought, `My goodness. That man must be tired because he puts his
whole heart and soul and body into his music.'''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe she put her finger on it, the source of the aura, that is.
Cliburn, a man of unearthly talent, who puts his whole heart and
soul and body into his music. It is good fortune indeed to have
witnessed that result firsthand.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
