<HEADLINE>
HILLARY CLINTON: THE WOMAN EVERYONE LOVES TO HATE  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 475-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   NEW YORK AND LITTLE ROCK _ She can't win. In New York, Hillary
Rodham Clinton is widely seen as an Arkansas carpetbagger, and is
hated for it. In Arkansas, however, she is seen as a New Yorker,
and is hated for that just as keenly.
</P>
<P>
   How deeply does the hatred go? Much more deeply than seems
reasonable.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, retailers report a brisk trade in nine-inch Hillary
voodoo dolls that carry the invitation to ``stick it to her.''
Doormats bearing her likeness are also selling fast.
</P>
<P>
   The latest book attacking her, Peggy Noonan's ``The Case Against
Hillary Clinton,'' sits near the top of the New York Times
best-seller list.
</P>
<P>
   A daylong symposium on Hillary last month at the American
Enterprise Institute began with Christopher Hitchens, a left-wing
journalist, calling Mrs. Clinton a ``lachrymose professional
liar,'' and concluded with David Horowitz, a conservative, warning
his listeners that the first lady is a messianic socialist.
</P>
<P>
   The spectre of ``Senator Clinton,'' trumpeted through Web sites
such as HillaryNo.com, has helped Rudy Giuliani, her assumed rival,
to haul in an unprecedented $19 million in campaign contributions.
</P>
<P>
   He raised $30,000 of that, audaciously, on a one-day visit to
Little Rock, Ark., last summer. But it was a canny move on his
part, since if New York is one pole in the hate-Hillary axis,
Little Rock is undoubtedly the other.
</P>
<P>
   Last week Hillary was there again, hoping to raise money for her
New York race. She had not been to Little Rock for two years.
</P>
<P>
   Now, dressed just like a chic New Yorker in a luminous aqua
trouser suit, with perfectly coiffed hair, Mrs. Clinton told her
listeners how fondly she looked back on her days as the Arkansas
governor's wife.
</P>
<P>
   Some found that hard to believe. Arkansans always believed that
Mrs. Clinton, who was actually born in Illinois, thought herself
too good for a poor and rural Southern state. Yet she is not too
proud to come begging, and she flew back to New York with more than
$100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Is Mrs. Clinton to blame for all this bad feeling? In some ways.
She still seems unsure whether to be a sharp new woman or a
submissive housewife (not since Margaret Thatcher has anybody
delivered such brass-knuckled attacks while dressed in a ruffled
blouse).
</P>
<P>
   In New York she is undoubtedly a carpetbagger, and has pandered
excessively to various sectors of the electorate. She has some
White House scandals to haunt her.
</P>
<P>
   Yet her treatment still seems disproportionate. Apparently,
political opportunists in ruffled blouses are less acceptable to
the public than those who wear pinstriped suits.
</P>
<P>
   Some anti-Hillary campaigns carry an undoubted whiff of sexism.
An even larger number, though, seem to be motivated by a desire to
get even with her husband. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
