<HEADLINE>
QUIPS, QUIRKS AND QUOTES FROM THE CAMPAIGN TRAIL  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary, Political, Humor Editors)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 350-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   &UR; THE NRA CANDIDATE: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   In a video, a senior official of the National Rifle Association
suggested that the NRA would be able to ``work out'' of the Oval
Office if George W. Bush is elected in November.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Bush accused Al Gore, who staunchly supports gun
control these days, of being a member of the NRA. The NRA cannot
find any record of Gore's membership, but points out that Gore
received a high rating from them when he was a congressman from
Tennessee. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENDORSEMENT OF THE WEEK: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Senator John McCain finally endorsed Bush on May 9 after a
meeting between the two in Pittsburgh. McCain said he looked
forward to campaigning ``enthusiastically'' for the Texas governor.
But he also admitted the endorsement was a case of ``take the
medicine now.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HONEST ANSWER OF THE WEEK: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably because I liked the way it tasted. I _ there is
nothing better than a cold beer and Mexican food, cold beer and
barbeque.'' (Bush on why he took up drinking, ``20/20,'' ABC, May
5) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POP QUIZ: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I thought you meant some band. The Taliban in Afghanistan!
Absolutely. Repressive.'' (Bush in Glamour magazine, June 2000) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PREDICTION: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people are going to fall asleep watching the drab
debate the dreary.'' (Ralph Nader, Green Party candidate, warning
voters what to expect if third-party candidates are not involved in
this autumn's presidential debates,``Meet the Press,'' May 7) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMPLIMENT: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at Al Gore over the last ten days. He's been the attack
dog. I mean, he's been James Carville with more hair and less
charm.'' (Senator Mitch McConnell, CNN, May 7) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NOT-SO-WOODEN MAN: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   On May 8, the Associated Press reported that, in private, Gore
sings country songs with an exaggerated twang. Then the New York
Times reported that he wowed an audience of the Anti-Defamation
League with a routine about Jewish country music (sample: ``I was
one of the chosen people _ until she chose someone else.'') &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
