<DOCNO> NYT20000515.0203 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 17:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5724 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER-0516-COX     05-15 1195
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER-0516-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Bullish on social security choices
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   George W. Bush outlined a plan today that would allow workers to
invest part of their payroll taxes in private accounts. He also
promised to strengthen Medicare. Speaking at a senior citizens'
center outside Los Angeles, Bush didn't specify how large a portion
could be put in private accounts, but the most commonly discussed
option has been 2 percentage points of the current 12.4 percent
Social Security payroll tax. Bush also pledged to maintain current
benefits for those at or near retirement; put payroll taxes off
limits to prevent borrowing against the Social Security trust fund;
refuse to increase the current 12.4 percent payroll tax used to
fill the trust fund; preserve the system's current benefit payments
to widows, widowers and the disabled; and refuse to let the
government itself invest Social Security funds, preferring instead
to let individuals make the choice. Al Gore, speaking today outside
Philadelphia, argued that it is risky to chance retirement savings
on the whims of the stock market. He warned that taxpayers and the
government could be put in a position where they'll have to provide
``an S&AMP;L-type bailout for those retirees whose investments don't
pan out.'' But says Bush: ``He trusts the government to manage our
retirement; I trust individual Americans. I trust Americans to make
their own decisions and manage their own money.''
</P>
<P>
   BUT REPUBLICANS WITH AMBITIONS ARE WAITING
</P>
<P>
   Rudy Giuliani said today he still hasn't decided on what
treatment he'll get for his prostate cancer, let alone whether
he'll continue his Senate bid. He disputed a Newsweek report that
he had decided on surgery and radiation. He said he's learned from
talking with others with cancer that ``you change your mind about
it probably 10 times before you make the decision'' on treatment.
But he did say he had canceled planned fund-raisers in California
on Tuesday and Wednesday. Newsweek, citing unidentified sources,
reported that Giuliani chose ``the most extensive and
time-consuming course of treatment'' and that it would force him to
quit the race against Hillary Clinton. Democrats were predicting
that Giuliani's campaign is finished.
</P>
<P>
   THEY LIKE GOOD SCHOOLS, BUT NOT TAXES
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire Gov. Jeanne Shaheen, who has struggled with the
question of how to fund the state's schools, confirmed today she'll
seek a third term, but didn't say whether she'll renew her pledge
to veto an income tax. Shaheen had dodged the question for months,
prompting some to speculate she wouldn't take the traditional
pledge to veto the tax. New Hampshire, along with Alaska, are the
only states without a personal state income tax or general sales
tax, and anti-tax sentiment in New Hampshire runs high. But Shaheen
and state legislators have been grappling with an education funding
crisis triggered by a state Supreme Court order in late 1997 to
find a fairer way to pay for schools. Shaheen will face state Sen.
Mark Fernald, who supports a state income tax to solve the school
problem, in the Sept. 12 Democratic primary.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-BRADLEY POW-WOW IN THE WORKS
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore's aides, according to USA Today, anticipate an
announcement, possibly this week, about a joint appearance between
their boss and Bill Bradley. Such an appearance would end two
months of estrangement, the aftermath of a bitter competition
between a vice president who wanted a clear field and his
ex-senator challenger. Gore spokesman Chris Lehane was quoted as
saying the campaigns are in ``close contact,'' but Bradley aides
say the two sides have had a ``non-relationship'' since Bradley
quit the race March 9. He has not spoken to Gore since, and
aide-to-aide calls have been rare.
</P>
<P>
   CINDY TO LEAD ARIZONANS IN PHILLY
</P>
<P>
   In the end, John McCain got his wish: His wife will lead the
Arizona delegation to the GOP convention this summer. Cindy McCain
was chosen at a state convention over the weekend after Gov. Jane
Hull stepped aside, stressing the need for party unity. McCain's
home state is one of seven he won during the primaries. By
installing his wife as delegation head, McCain assures himself
additional media exposure at the convention in Philadelphia: She'll
be the one announcing delivering Arizona's 30 delegates on national
TV. Hull had endorsed George W. Bush, which ticked off McCain. The
dispute simmered even after McCain dropped out. When Hull disclosed
her desire to lead the delegation, McCain dismissed the idea during
a nationally televised interview, expressing the preference for his
wife. This, in turn, angered Hull and her supporters.
</P>
<P>
   McCAIN MIFFED IN MICHIGAN
</P>
<P>
   John McCain canceled plans to campaign for Michigan
congressional candidates this week in what the Detroit News called
``an angry reaction'' to the Michigan GOP's choices for convention
delegates. McCain political director John Weaver said Michigan Gov.
John Engler and state GOP chairman Rusty Hills ``failed to keep
commitments'' to elect ``true McCain activists.'' Instead, most of
them are George W. Bush supporters who are pledged to vote McCain
on the first ballot. McCain had captured 52 of the state's 58
delegates but released six of them to Bush so Engler and others
could attend the convention.
</P>
<P>
   `PRETTY GOOD CHANCE' IN TENNESSEE
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush says he can win Tennessee in November even though
it's Al Gore's home state, and that he'll campaign there often.
``That's a state where I have a pretty good chance,'' he told
interviewers in Austin, because a lot of Tennessee people don't
want four more years of Clinton-Gore.'' The reasons Bush thinks he
can win there: the Clinton-Gore ticket carried the state by 2
percentage points in 1996, and that Tennessee has a Republican
governor (Don Sundquist) and two GOP senators (Fred Thompson and
Bill Frist). The most recent Tennessee poll, a two-month-old
Mason-Dixon survey, showed Gore leading 47-41 percent, with a 4
percentage point margin of error.
</P>
<P>
   LOOKING FOR MR. GOODVOTE
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of an Al Gore presidency, the New York Times
reports, leaves many women unexcited, even those who are longtime
Democrats. ``I don't like the way he carries himself,'' the Times
quoted a Carla Hannan-Welch as saying. ``I see him putting his foot
in his mouth a lot.'' Helen Rabichow, a Chicago Democrat, has
conflicting feelings about Gore: ``I think he's kind of a nice
jerk. He's a well-meaning, nice guy. But that doesn't necessarily
mean that will make him a good president.'' But George W. Bush
doesn't seem to be impressing many women, either. ``I don't think
either one of them is really capable,'' an Irene Cohen was quoted
as saying. ``If I had to go to the polls right now, I'd vote for
Mickey Mouse.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
