<SLUG> BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T BE AGOG AT DEMAGOGUING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, May 21)  
(Eds: Items in bold should be set in italics.) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a rousing speech to an AFL-CIO convention in New Jersey, Vice
President Al Gore used the attack word  &UR; secret &LR;  seven times. It is
now his favorite adjective, having temporarily replaced  &UR; risky &LR;  (as
in the phrase, pronounced as one word,  &UR; riskytaxscheme &LR; ).
</P>
<P>
   He was blazing away at Gov. Bush's proposal, not yet detailed,
to allow individuals to divert a portion of their Social Security
taxes into the stock market. Gore charged that Bush believed ``it
would be best not to let you, the voters of this country, in on the
 &UR; secret plan &LR;  before the election .... He is suppressing the
details of how his plan would work and refusing to divulge what his
 &UR; secret plan &LR;  really is.''
</P>
<P>
   At a subsequent news conference, Gore evidently felt that
 &UR; secret &LR;  was not pejorative enough and added, redundantly, a
``private  &UR; secret plan &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   That sinister phrase _  &UR; secret plan &LR;  _ has resonance to veteran
rhetoricians and students of presidential campaigns. In the 1968
primaries, candidate Richard Nixon was searching for a way to
promise he would extricate the United States from its increasingly
unpopular involvement in Vietnam. The key verb to be used was
 &UR; end &LR; , though it would be nice to get the verb  &UR; win &LR;  in some
proximity to it.
</P>
<P>
   One speechwriter came up with the formulation that ``new
leadership will  &UR; end &LR;  the war and  &UR; win &LR;  the peace in the Pacific.''
Nixon made it part of his stump speech, and the juxtaposition of
 &UR; end &LR;  and  &UR; win &LR;  _ though it did not claim to intend to  &UR; win &LR;  the
war, but only the peace _ drove his major opponent for the GOP
nomination, Gov. George Romney of Michigan, up the wall.
</P>
<P>
   When a UPI reporter pressed Nixon for specifics, the candidate
demurred; the reporter wrote that it seemed Nixon was determined to
keep his plan  &UR; secret &LR; , though he did not quote Nixon as having
said either  &UR; secret &LR;  or  &UR; plan &LR; . But this gave Romney a chance to
slam back at his opponent's promise.
</P>
<P>
   In what became the centerpiece of his stump speech in the snows
of New Hampshire, Romney demanded to know, ``Where is your  &UR; secret
plan &LR; ?'' That question skillfully presupposed an assertion of not
just a general promise but also a detailed plan, and soon it became
widely accepted that Nixon had said, ``I have a  &UR; secret plan &LR;  to
end the war.''
</P>
<P>
   Years later, when a New York Times columnist attributed that
direct quote to Nixon, a White House speechwriter challenged him to
find the quote in anything taken down by pencil or recorder at the
time. The pundit searched high and low and had to admit the
supposed remark was unsourceable. (Look, the Nixon speechwriter was
me and the columnist was my current colleague, Tony Lewis; I didn't
have to research this.)
</P>
<P>
   During Ronald Reagan's run for re-election in 1984, Democrats
took a leaf from the Romney playbook and charged him with having a
 &UR; secret plan &LR;  to raise taxes after the election. This forced Reagan
to say defensively he would raise taxes only ``as a last resort''
and reminded politicians that the old  &UR; secret-plan &LR;  charge had
legs.
</P>
<P>
   Even Gore, a few weeks before he leveled the tried-and-true
phrase at Bush, showed he was aware of its old-chestnuttiness. In a
hilarious, deadpan, self-mocking speech to the Gridiron Club in
Washington, he was widely reported to have said he had a  &UR; secret
plan &LR;  to win the White House: He would claim credit for all the
good stuff that had happened in the past eight years and dissociate
himself from the bad stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, George W. Bush has been using an attack word of his
own to characterize the Gore approach to Social Security: ``For
eight years,'' he wrote in a fund-raising letter, ``Clinton/Gore
has had history's greatest opportunity to reform Social Security.
They chose to  &UR; demagogue &LR;  the problem, not repair it.''
</P>
<P>
   I kept this letter, sent to me by its recipient, Leila Hadley
Luce of New York, to note the use of the beslashed singular subject
 &UR; Clinton/Gore &LR; , followed properly by the singular verb  &UR; has &LR; , but
then followed incorrectly by  &UR; they &LR; .  &UR; Clinton/Gore &LR;  is a team and
takes an  &UR; it &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   But Luce's covering note questioned the use of the ``new verb,''
 &UR; to demagogue &LR; . Originally a noun, this was formed from the Greek
 &UR; demos &LR; , ``people,'' and  &UR; agogos &LR; , ``leading''; it meant ``leader
of the mob'' and now has the derogatory meaning of ``a politician
who appeals to people's emotions.'' The noun can be used
attributively to do the work of an adjective: Robert Southey in
1812 denounced ``the venom and the virulence of the  &UR; demagogue &LR; 
journalists.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush cannot be faulted for using  &UR; demagogue &LR;  as a verb. It was
coined in that form by James Harrington in his 1656 utopian theory,
``Commonwealth of Oceana.'' He picked up the noun coined five years
earlier by Thomas Hobbes and wrote of a time ``when that same
ranting fellow Alcibiades fell a  &UR; demagoging &LR;  for the Sicilian
war.'' In 1890, The Cincinnati Commercial Gazette wrote of
President Benjamin Harrison, ``The president never thought of
 &UR; demagoging &LR;  the matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Note the lack of a  &UR; u &LR;  in those usages of what most of us would
until recently spell as  &UR; demagoguing &LR; . But we live in a non-U
world; just as  &UR; catalogue &LR;  and  &UR; dialogue &LR;  have been dropping their
 &UR; ue &LR;  endings, so too will  &UR; demagogue &LR;  soon enough be spelled
 &UR; demagog &LR; , with its gerund  &UR; demagoging &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   It's a hard word for the mob to handle;  &UR; demagogic &LR;  is
pronounced with the final g soft, rhyming with  &UR; logic &LR; , but
 &UR; demagoguery &LR;  has the final  &UR; g &LR;  hard, rhyming with  &UR; toggery &LR; . (Get
away from that e-mail key; there is such a word. It means
``clothing.'')
</P>
<P>
   Will Gore now assail Bush for harboring a  &UR; secret plan &LR;  to
attack him for  &UR; demagoguery &LR; ? Will Bush lash back in a debate by
demanding he spell it? Both sides are now armed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
