<HEADER>
A5735 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-VOLCANO-RECOVER-A     05-15 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-VOLCANO-RECOVER-ART(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS MOUNT ST. HELENS RECOVERS, OLD WISDOM CRUMBLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(ART ADV: Photos 4,5 are being sent to NYT photo clients. Locator
map is being sent to NYT graphics clients. Nonsubscribers can
purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By CAROL KAESUK YOON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOUNT ST. HELENS NATIONAL VOLCANIC MONUMENT, Wash. _ Here at the
foot of a still snow-covered Mount St. Helens, a gentle, new spring
is hatching as alder trees leaf out, the first warblers sing,
salamanders squirm out of gooey eggs and the Toutle River rushes
toward its destination.
</P>
<P>
   But while peaceful today, 20 years ago this valley was rocked as
Mount St. Helens exploded in an eruption so powerful that it shot
ash and steam out at more than 200 mph, filled this broad valley
with the largest landslide in recorded human history and flattened
trees over hundreds of square miles _ in minutes, changing this
landscape forever.
</P>
<P>
   The eruption of Mount St. Helens, the two-decade anniversary of
which will be marked this Thursday, has also radically changed the
way that biologists look at the creation and recovery of natural
landscapes.
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, researchers say it was dogma among ecologists that
nature creates and recreates ecosystems in an orderly fashion with
predictable parades of species rolling in: the early pioneering
species first, which alter the environment, making possible the
arrival of the second wave of species and so on, until the final
array of plants and animals is in place.
</P>
<P>
   By providing the perfect laboratory to test such ideas _ more
than 200 square miles of newly devastated terrain _ Mount St.
Helens has turned that theory upside down. Biologists have
discovered instead the unpredictability of recolonization and the
pivotal importance of chance in the rebuilding of biological
communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew very clearly what was going to happen afterward,''
said Dr. Jerry Franklin, a forest ecologist at the University of
Washington, ``and we were very clearly wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   The lessons learned, researchers say, have provided critical
insights for foresters, conservationists and others looking to
rebuild ecosystems that have been drastically altered.
</P>
<P>
   Because St. Helens was also the first massive eruption in a
developed country within driving distance of a number of major
universities, it is unrivaled as a model for ecosystem recovery.
</P>
<P>
   ``The intensity of the work that is being carried out there,''
said Dr. Eldon Franz, an ecosystem ecologist at Washington State
University, ``I don't think it will be matched anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, at the 20-year mark, with tiny, forest-like patches of
alders taking hold, brave clumps of sedges, fireweeds and lupines
clinging to the rocky hills, and moths, trout and bluebirds
increasing their numbers, researchers are finally beginning to see,
not just how a few lucky survivors can hold on, but what happens as
whole communities of species begin to take shape.
</P>
<P>
   Pointing out the struggling young willows that have begun to
feel the effects of the growing corps of animals _ from stem-boring
beetles, to leaf-chewing elk to trunk-biting beavers _ Charlie
Crisafulli, an ecologist at the Forest Service's Pacific Northwest
Research Station, said, ``Now things are really going to get
interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Even while standing here on heaps of volcanic debris, staring
into the remains of the exploded crater, it is hard to take in the
enormousness of the events on that fateful day.
</P>
<P>
   Within moments, a lush Northwestern forest was transformed into
a variety of entirely novel habitats. The pyroclastic zone, also
known as the pyroclastic flow, was created where hot pumice poured
out of the volcano sterilizing the earth. The debris avalanche
consisted of a 14-mile landslide of ash and rocks, some the size of
large buildings. The blowdown zone consisted of countless conifers
burnt to a crisp and toppled over like so many seared toothpicks.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   According to the neat logic of ecological theory, mosses and
lichens, able to survive the harshest conditions, should have been
the first to take hold in these ruined places. Then wildflowers and
other herbs should have come in, followed by deciduous trees and
finally conifers like the firs and hemlocks. And re-colonization
should have rolled inward from the edges where life remained
unharmed to the core of the devastation.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, what created the new landscape was not this set of
rules but the organisms that were lucky enough to survive the
blast.
</P>
<P>
   In this largely lifeless scene, biologists soon discovered
pockets of survivors _ biological legacies as they are now called.
Moles, northern pocket gophers and ants made it through the blast
as they were hidden beneath the ground. Saplings and shrubs that
were still buried in early spring snow survived the blast that
killed the taller trees poking up above them. A few roots and bulbs
of wildflowers, like lupines and fireweeds, tumbled along the top
of the rolling avalanche, as opposed to being buried 600 feet
below, and set up shop as soon as the ground stopped moving.
</P>
<P>
   From a few such crucial hangers on sprinkled here and there
throughout the devastation, much of the first life here has slowly
sprung _ a process scientists now recognize as a critical part of
recovery in any disturbed biological system.
</P>
<P>
   ``St. Helens was the epiphany where finally the scales fell from
our eyes and we said, `Oh my gosh, we haven't been thinking
clearly,''' said Franklin. ``The most important things we need to
think about are the legacies left in the landscape. The richness of
the legacy of organisms that was there, the rapidity with which
recovery occurred and the incredible diversity of ways in which
organisms were able to survive _ it just astounded us.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result of these findings, many foresters now leave 15
percent or more of the trees and deadwood behind after a harvest as
a kind of biological legacy to speed the rebirth of a new forest.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real value of all these studies, is what we can learn
about management for other human created systems,'' said Dr.
Virginia Dale, an ecologist at Oak Ridge National Laboratory in
Tennessee. ``We have strip mines and road sides and all kinds of
devastation created by human activities.''
</P>
<P>
   At its most extreme, St. Helens provided a chance for biologists
to study the recreation of habitats from a clean slate in the
pyroclastic zone, where an entirely new, sterilized surface was
laid down that had never before supported life.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists are still sorting out the many factors that allow
crucial nitrogen and carbon, the building blocks for living
organisms, to accumulate in the pyroclastic zone. But Franz said
they already know that chance played an important shaping role.
Wherever lupine seeds happen to blow in and find a crevice to take
hold, they begin laying down carbon and nitrogen in abundance.
Lupine plants are particularly well suited to this habitat, as they
can, with the help of bacteria, create their own sources of vital
nitrogen.
</P>
<P>
   Around the volcano, curious new communities are also beginning
to take shape. In many of the 120 new ponds created in the debris
avalanche and in Spirit Lake, the northwestern salamander has taken
up residence. But a major challenge to these animals is their habit
of leaving the water in search of forest, which at Mount St. Helens
can leave them wandering and dying in desert-like landscapes.
</P>
<P>
   Despite these challenges, the northwestern salamander is
thriving here, with help in part from species like the northern
pocket gopher and the elk.
</P>
<P>
   Crisafulli said his team finds traveling salamanders in nearly
every gopher tunnel they inspect. These creatures appear to be
making their way across the harsh terrain via the gopher's cool,
moist subway system. The elk assist by collapsing tunnels with
their hooves as they tromp along, creating easy entrance for the
salamanders into the underground transit.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with areas in which organisms have had the benefit of
millenniums to get established, St. Helens, researchers say,
remains a system out of whack. There are strange goings on, from
surprisingly large numbers of typically rare species, to species
found in unexpected places.
</P>
<P>
   Birds like pipits and rosy finches, typically only found in
sparse, high elevation areas, can be found in the low elevation
pyroclastic zone. Species like the western toad and the red-legged
frog, which are endangered or threatened elsewhere, flourish at
Mount St. Helens.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers guessed it might take several hundred years to
return to what once was, a grand, old growth forest, for example,
on the debris avalanche where evergreen trees now come up to a
person's knee and most of the ground is still barren.
</P>
<P>
   But a number of things could interfere with that long-term
prognosis. One is global warming, but the biggest is Mount St.
Helens itself, the most active volcano in the Cascade mountains,
with an average eruption cycle of 200 years.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers say the mountain had still not completely recovered
from an eruption in the 1800s when it exploded again in 1980. The
treeline had returned only part way up the flanks of Mount St.
Helens when the latest eruption interrupted its upward march.
</P>
<P>
   Just 20 short years into the process, scientists say they have
yet to learn just where all this change is headed or what will be
here on this very spot 10, 100 or more years from now.
</P>
<P>
   ``The story,'' said Dr. Fred Swanson, a research geologist with
the Forest Service's Pacific Northwest Research Station, ``is just
unfolding.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-00 1718EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
