<HEADLINE>
NBC'S NEW FALL LINEUP INCLUDES SOME OLD `FRIENDS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NBC announced next fall's prime-time lineup Monday and this much
we know: No matter what Oprah says, magazines are out, newspapers
are in.
</P>
<P>
   It's the inescapable conclusion gleaned from a painstaking
analysis of NBC's direction for the 2000-2001 season. Besides
canceling the long-dead ``Suddenly Susan,'' a Brooke Shields sitcom
about magazine folk, the network is trimming to thrice a week the
number of times its own newsmagazine, ``Dateline NBC,'' appears.
</P>
<P>
   That alone is cause for sustained huzzahs and breaking out the
special-occasion hooch. But holy Lou Grant! There's more. Dick
Wolf, the man responsible for ``Law &AMP; Order,'' is producing a drama
series about a crusading newspaperman. Titled ``Deadline,'' it
features the bulldoggish Oliver Platt as Wallace Benton, a
columnist who lives life large and makes headlines on and off the
job.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Benton could investigate the real reason behind the
disappearance of ``Freaks and Geeks,'' another NBC cancelee. And
maybe Michael Richards could help him out. Richards, a three-time
Emmy winner as Kramer on ``Seinfeld,'' returns to NBC in his own
comedy as an off-kilter private detective.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Michael Richards Show'' _ when in doubt, name it after the
star _ will lead off a Tuesday night slate that also features
``Frasier,'' back from a two-year tour of duty as linchpin of NBC's
faltering Thursday-comedy quartet. (``Will &AMP; Grace'' will move to
the Thursday-at-9 slot, along with ``Just Shoot Me'' at 9:30.)
</P>
<P>
   Further surgery on the Thursday lineup was avoided, to no one's
great surprise, when NBC and Warner Bros. Television caved last
weekend and agreed to give each cast member of ``Friends'' as much
money per season ($16.5 million) as it takes TV critics to make in
three or four. Hundred.
</P>
<P>
   In all, NBC unveiled four new comedies and three new dramas for
the fall. It also will introduce ``XFL Football'' on Saturday
nights, beginning in February. The XFL is a joint venture of NBC
and the World Wrestling Federation, proving that peacocks can get
down and dirty when they want to.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a summary of NBC's fall entries. Other networks follow
suit later this week.
</P>
<P>
   The Michael Richards Show. Richards plays an offbeat private eye
in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   DAG. David Alan Grier (``In Living Color'') is back as a Secret
Service agent demoted to guarding the first lady (Delta Burke).
</P>
<P>
   Tucker. A teenager (Eli Marienthal) and his divorced mom (Noelle
Beck) move in with her perfectionist sister (Katey Sagal) and
loutish son (Nathan Lawrence).
</P>
<P>
   The Steven Weber Show. The former ``Wings'' star plays a
fast-track ad executive unlucky in love because of a hex placed on
him by a jilted blind date.
</P>
<P>
   Deadline. From Dick Wolf, this series has Oliver Platt playing a
Pulitzer Prize-winning columnist ``who lives his life in boldface
type.''
</P>
<P>
   Titans. Aaron Spelling's latest potboiler about rich white
people, about a young fighter pilot (Casper Van Dien) who returns
home to Beverly Hills to discover that his rich and filthy family
is in turmoil. Also starring Victoria Principal, Perry King and
Yasmine Bleeth.
</P>
<P>
   Ed. Tom Cavanagh (``Providence'') plays a New York lawyer who
moves back to the Midwest, hoping to kindle a relationship with a
former classmate _ the most popular girl in school _ who barely
knows he exists.
</P>
<P>
   Here is NBC's prime-time lineup for fall 2000, which will be
introduced in October after the summer Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   7-8 p.m.: ``Dateline NBC''
</P>
<P>
   8-9 p.m.: ``Ed''
</P>
<P>
   9-11 p.m.: NBC Sunday Night Movie
</P>
<P>
   MONDAY
</P>
<P>
   8-8:30 p.m.: ``Daddio''
</P>
<P>
   8:30-9 p.m.: ``3rd Rock From the Sun''
</P>
<P>
   9-10 p.m.: ``Deadline''
</P>
<P>
   10-11 p.m.: ``Third Watch''
</P>
<P>
   TUESDAY
</P>
<P>
   8-8:30 p.m.: ``The Michael Richards Show''
</P>
<P>
   8:30-9 p.m.: ``Tucker''
</P>
<P>
   9-9:30 p.m.: ``Frasier''
</P>
<P>
   9:30-10 p.m.: ``DAG''
</P>
<P>
   10-11 p.m.: ``Dateline NBC''
</P>
<P>
   WEDNESDAY
</P>
<P>
   8-9 p.m.: ``Titans''
</P>
<P>
   9-10 p.m.: ``The West Wing''
</P>
<P>
   10-11 p.m.: ``Law &AMP; Order''
</P>
<P>
   THURSDAY
</P>
<P>
   8-8:30 p.m.: ``Friends'
</P>
<P>
   8:30-9 p.m.: ``The Steven Weber Show''
</P>
<P>
   9-9:30 p.m.: ``Will &AMP; Grace''
</P>
<P>
   9:30-10 p.m.: ``Just Shoot Me''
</P>
<P>
   10-11 p.m.: ``ER''
</P>
<P>
   FRIDAY
</P>
<P>
   8-9 p.m.: ``Providence''
</P>
<P>
   9-10 p.m.: ``Dateline NBC''
</P>
<P>
   10-11 p.m.: ``Law &AMP; Order: Special Victims Unit''
</P>
<P>
   SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   8-11 p.m.: NBC Saturday Night Movie, to be replaced by ``XFL
Football'' Feb. 3-April 21, 2001
</P>
