<HEADER>
A5745 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-OXYGEN-FACIALS-LIFEBE     05-15 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OXYGEN-FACIALS-LIFEBEAT-700-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 FEEL-GOOD OXYGEN FACIALS MAY OR MAY NOT KEEP SKIN YOUNG  ART ADV:
(Photos of woman receiving oxygen facial available in JPEG format
by calling William Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.)  &HT;    Julianne Remington writes for ``HealthSurfing.com''
 &HT;    
 By JULIANNE REMINGTON  
 c.2000 InterNetwork News  
<TEXT>
 &UR; World rights &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
<P>
   Cathy Bucalo, 49, says that after her face lift, oxygen facials
restored moisture and helped her skin heal. ``It's very relaxing,''
she says. ``I think it's a combination of the facial and the way I
feel when I leave.''
</P>
<P>
   For more than 20 years, facials have been part of Bucalo's
cosmetic routine. ``I see the most results in my cheekbone area.
I'm very pleased.''
</P>
<P>
   Oxygen enthusiasts claim there's something about an extra dose
of oxygen that's revitalizing. Cosmetic specialists say it's good
for the skin, and that hydrogen peroxide cream helps water and
oxygen penetrate the skin better. But not everyone agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no scientific evidence to support the belief that
oxygen facials do anything for the skin,'' says Dr. Mitchel Goldman
of Dermatology Associates in San Diego. ``Oxygen is actually toxic
to skin cells. That's why most cosmetics contain antioxidants,
including vitamins C, A and E.''
</P>
<P>
   Oxygen reacts easily with other substances and causes metals to
rust. Hemoglobin in the blood contains iron that oxidizes or
``rusts'' in order to combine with oxygen in the lungs and carry it
to all the body's cells. There, oxygen oxidizes food to yield
energy.
</P>
<P>
   But oxidation of the body's own cells speeds aging. It's also
linked to heart disease and cancer.
</P>
<P>
   That's why antioxidants, like vitamins C, A and E, found
abundantly in fruits and vegetables, have become so popular. They
destroy harmful molecules called free radicals that are produced by
oxidation. Free radicals disrupt the DNA inside cells and advance
aging.
</P>
<P>
   ``The skin does better in a nonoxygen environment,'' says
Goldman. ``That's one of the reasons why I advise my patients to
use antioxidant creams for their skin.''
</P>
<P>
   Cosmeticians have a different take on the role that oxygen plays
in skin care.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the oxygen gets into the skin, the cell regeneration
speeds up,'' says Joyce Carboni, whose Skinsational Spa in
Carlsbad, Calif., specializes in oxygen facials. ``We apply
hydrogen peroxide cream to the face to help oxygen penetrate the
skin and get into the cells.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The relaxation that you get when you spend time giving
yourself a facial is absolutely incredible,'' says Bucalo. ``It's
about what's next, and what's new. I'm available and willing to try
anything these ladies have in mind for me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oxygen is extremely hydrating and healing to the skin. We've
seen the results,'' adds Carboni.
</P>
<P>
   The oxygen facial begins with cleansing. The client receives a
mild facial scrub with jojoba beads or an enzyme peel. A thin film
of 2 percent hydrogen peroxide cream is then applied. A plastic
wrap or facial steamer may be used for the next 10 minutes. Then a
mask containing hydrogen peroxide is placed over the skin for
another 15 to 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   To complete the facial, a hydrogen peroxide finishing cream is
gently massaged into the skin.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing about a facial is the therapeutic message,''
says Goldman. ``It can perhaps promote lymphatic drainage.''
</P>
<P>
   Cosmeticians say the skin absorbs oxygen like a sponge, but
medical opinion says otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a limit to how much oxygen your body can absorb,''
says Dr. John C. Nelson, of the American Medical Association. ``The
oxygen carrying capacity of the blood cannot be increased, except
by increasing the number of red cells.''
</P>
<P>
   Red cells contain hemoglobin molecules that bind oxygen in the
lungs and deliver it to the body's cells as needed. Nelson says
only people suffering from heart or respiratory diseases benefit
from extra oxygen. Regarding oxygen facials or oxygen-infused
beverages he says, ``To the extent that these are used as social or
entertainment types of activities, I think there's no detriment.''
</P>
<P>
   Surgery patients commonly receive 30 percent oxygen during and
after surgery (air is only 21 percent oxygen) because the lungs
don't work as well under anesthesia. Studies have shown that
boosting the oxygen helps reduce infection and nausea in
post-surgery patients.
</P>
<P>
   White blood cells called ``neutrophils'' use oxygen to kill
germs. The correct amount of oxygen in the body's tissues is good
for health, but doctors say there's a limit.
</P>
<P>
   Medical experts say inhaling oxygen recreationally probably
won't have any beneficial effect, and they warn that oxygen at high
levels can be toxic. However, no evidence shows that oxygen at the
low levels used in bars or facials can be dangerous to a normal
person's health.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (The HealthSurfing.com Web site is at http://healthsurfing.com)
</P>
