<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BRITAIN'S ROWDY POLITICS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ From a distance, the British parliamentary system looks
orderly and serene in comparison to our own messy political
process.
</P>
<P>
   But up close here in London, it is clear that the politicians
are as adept at hurling insults and the voters as irritatingly
rebellious as our own.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, a left-wing rascal nicknamed Red Ken, cast out of
the Labor Party for being politically incorrect, was overwhelmingly
elected mayor of London earlier this month despite the impassioned
opposition of Prime Minister Tony Blair. To make matters worse,
Blair's party simultaneously lost more than 500 local council seats
in nationwide elections, a thumping mid-term triumph for the rival
Conservatives and Blair's biggest electoral setback since coming to
power three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teflon Tony'' has been riding high in the polls but things may
be changing. The imminent arrival of the first baby in 150 years
born to a British prime minister and his wife _ both in their 40's
_ is bound to help his image. But it may not be enough.
</P>
<P>
   The new elected post of London mayor now occupied by Ken
Livingstone was created at Blair's insistence to extend his own
influence and generate public interest in city politics. Now Blair
must deal with a sworn enemy rather than the compliant friend he
had hoped to install.
</P>
<P>
   There was no public reconciliation between the two men, who were
even more reluctant than our famously independent Sen. John McCain
to bury the hatchet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to rattle their chains,'' Livingstone gloated. He
also noted slyly that if his victory is replicated nationally in a
general election, expected to be called next spring, Blair would
lose his majority and be out of work.
</P>
<P>
   One of Livingstone's closest advisers, Kumar Murshid, promptly
dramatized the coming storm by declaring that Prince Philip, the
husband of Queen Elizabeth II, is ``an unreconstructed racist'' and
by calling for the abolition of the monarchy. ``Prince Philip is a
waste of time. ... He gives the image of being very arrogant and
also fairly ignorant,'' Murshid said. Livingstone had no immediate
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Blair, trying to make the best of a very bad deal, professed to
believe that the elections were not a rejection of Labor policies
but a reflection of low turnout and voter indifference. His theory
is that there's nothing wrong with Labor's centrist message, it's
just not getting across at the moment. Sound familiar?
</P>
<P>
   Blair and President Clinton, amiable baby boomers who espouse
similar middle-road policies, often confer and are often compared
(although unlike Clinton, Blair has a happy, rumor-free marriage).
They echo each other's themes, remain relentlessly upbeat in the
face of disaster, prefer pragmatic ideas to ideology and do their
darndest to identify with ordinary people.
</P>
<P>
   But sometimes they are both too clever by half. Blair's cute
maneuvers to make Livingstone a political leper backfired. He was
too obvious, too self-serving against a cheeky underdog touring the
city in a purple bus, a British version of McCain's ``Straight Talk
Express.''
</P>
<P>
   After his defeat, however, Blair picked himself up off the mat
as Clinton always does and marched out dutifully to the House of
Commons to endure the weekly ritual of answering hostile questions
from the opposition Conservatives, also known as the Tories.
</P>
<P>
   Although this regular half-hour performance is usually
accompanied by shouts, boos, foot-stamping and other rude
expressions from legislators, it is an extremely useful tool of
government. We could do worse.
</P>
<P>
   Watching Blair defend himself from the Parliament press gallery
was a real treat for this American journalist. This was politics at
its rowdy best, bright minds locked in verbal combat, temper
tantrums barely controlled, no cunning obfuscations tolerated.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition leaders naturally ragged Blair about the London
mayoral debacle. ``I can't see many advantages to the situation but
one is that I'm not responsible for the new mayor's actions,''
Blair said wryly to a cacophony of unintelligible, competing noises
from the benches.
</P>
<P>
   The prime minister and Tory leader William Hague argued about
whose policies would protect the most jobs, which featured British
specifics but sounded just like the fights in Washington over
corporate mega-mergers and the complications of a global economy.
</P>
<P>
   Blair accused Hague of having ``a not a single constructive
solution to offer.''
</P>
<P>
   Hague countered, ``Since no senior member of the government has
ever worked in a business, why don't they listen to some people who
do?''
</P>
<P>
   This exchange produced additional hoots.
</P>
<P>
   Our traditions do not provide for such direct confrontations in
public between the leaders of the executive and legislative
branches, but perhaps it should. It clears the air. Open insults
are better than sneaky back-stabbing. And more fun for the public
as well.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address means(at)
hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
