<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5755 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a k BC-LEASE-COLUMN-NYTR &LR;      05-15 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEASE-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOPPING FOR CANDIDATES? CHECK THEIR GIFT REGISTRY 
</HEADLINE>
   by DARYL LEASE   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I've been sitting here trying to make up my mind about what to
buy as a wedding gift for Newt Gingrich and his bride-to-be,
Callista Bisek. I'm having a hard time choosing between the Ralph
Lauren tub mat ($24.99) and the Waterford ice bucket ($198).
</P>
<P>
   They're planning to get married in August, now that his divorce
from Marianne is final. Newt and Callie, you'll recall, were once
participants in the most secretive adulterous relationship in
politics _ behind Bill and Monica, of course, and apparently just
ahead of Rudolph Giuliani and his paramour.
</P>
<P>
   Newt's new career in speechifying seems to be going quite
nicely. The Washington Post reports that he and his betrothed are
getting ready to close a deal on a $1 million house outside the
nation's capital.
</P>
<P>
   The Post recently found not one but two gift registries on the
Internet for the charming couple. Turns out they've compiled a wish
list containing items worth more than _ ooh, how festive _ $14,000
at Macy's and Williams-Sonoma.
</P>
<P>
   I don't expect to be invited to the shindig, but I couldn't help
but sneak a peek at the gift possibilities. You can, too. (The
Macy's list was the only one still online when I checked). I think
I'll call dibs on the Ralph Lauren tub mat, but if you want to get
them the same thing, go right ahead. They asked for four.
</P>
<P>
   I read recently that some Americans are starting to feel
nostalgic for the Clinton era, even before it's over. I'm not among
them. I voted for the man twice, but I'm fairly agreeable to
letting him go. (Don't let the Oval Office door hit you on the way
out, Bubba.)
</P>
<P>
   I suppose I understand the wistfulness, though. Looking back, it
does seem like there was something quaint and predictable about the
days when Bill and Newt ran amok in Washington. As I ponder the
next four years, I find myself longing for the angry
finger-wagging, baldfaced lies and smarmy apologies.
</P>
<P>
   And don't forget the shakedowns. Bill and Newt were probably the
most adept in the nation's history at hugging corporate CEOs and
walking away with their wallets.
</P>
<P>
   They seem positively harmless, though, compared to the abandon
with which their successors are soliciting funds.
</P>
<P>
   From January 1999 through April of this year, according to the
watchdog group Common Cause, the Republican and Democratic parties
drummed up $160.5 million in soft money donations, the type of
fund-raising that corporations and politicians use to bypass
restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   That's twice the amount raised during the first 15 months of the
1996 election cycle, according to The New York Times. Before this
presidential campaign is over, the parties are expected to raise a
whopping half-billion dollars in soft money.
</P>
<P>
   There is some good news, though. The Times reports that 31 major
corporations have quietly chosen, at least for now, to spurn the
bridal registries set up by Al Gore and George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   These companies, without fanfare, are joining others _ General
Motors, Monsanto, Time Warner, to name a few _ in calling a halt to
soft-money contributions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suspect that there are more and more companies asking
themselves if this is really worth it,'' says Charles E.M. Kolb,
president of the Committee for Economic Development, a group of
CEOs pushing for campaign finance reform. ``What's just as
interesting, though, is the fact that companies are scared to tell
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Lanny Davis, a prominent Washington lawyer and lobbyist, says
clients are telling him enough's enough. ``Both political parties
have gotten so excessive in trying to beat the other in the
soft-money hunt,'' he says. ``I'm part of the problem, and I've
never seen such disgust with the practice in all my years here. It
has reached critical mass.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that doesn't explain the half-billion dollars on its
way to Al Gore, George W. Bush and their comrades in (open) arms.
</P>
<P>
   Some corporations, it appears, still feel a need to show they
care but are having a difficult time finding a more appropriate
gift.
</P>
<P>
   May I suggest the Ralph Lauren tub mat, at a relatively modest
$24.99? I have a feeling everyone involved could use a really good
scrubbing. If that doesn't work, we can always toss them a bucket
of ice.
</P>
<P>
   (Daryl Lease is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla. Contact him at daryl.lease(AT)herald-trib.com. The
Herald-Tribune is a member of the New York Times Regional
Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
