<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, May 16, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gusty winds will develop across the Southwest Tuesday,
exacerbating problems associated with containing wildfires in New
Mexico. The catalyst for increasing winds will be a potent
upper-level low pressure system over the Great Basin. Winds from
the west-southwest will average 25 to 40 mph.
</P>
<P>
   A cluster of potent thunderstorms will rumble across parts of
the southern Plains early Tuesday as winds in a narrow corridor
2,000 feet above the ground rapidly transport moisture from the
Gulf of Mexico into eastern Kansas. Storms will gradually weaken as
they move southeast.
</P>
<P>
   Isolated strong to severe thunderstorms will develop in
southeast Wyoming and northeast Colorado Tuesday afternoon, but
there will be outbreaks of severe thunderstorms Tuesday evening and
night over parts of South Dakota, Nebraska, Iowa and Missouri.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After a clear and cold start with scattered frost, sunshine will
raise temperatures into the 50s and lower 60s throughout the
interior Northeast Tuesday. Clouds will dim the sunshine in the
afternoon as high-level moisture arrives from the west. It will be
a bit milder in the central Appalachians, where readings will
approach 70 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: HEAD START
</P>
<P>
   Monday marked the beginning of hurricane season over the
tropical eastern Pacific. (Atlantic hurricane season begins June
1.) The May 15 start pays homage to an early pool of warm water
that traditionally develops off the western coast of Mexico south
of Baja, Calif. The catalysts for tropical storms are easterly
waves and systems of thunderstorms over the mountains of Mexico.
Easterly waves are disturbances that move westward over the
tropics, while systems of mountain thunderstorms can develop into a
tropical storm once they move over warm water. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
