<SLUG> BC-SCI-SPACE-STATION-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS THE SPACE STATION FALLS, NASA MOVES TO PROP IT UP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Colo., Russia)   (The Science Times)  
(ART ADV: Photo NYT1 has been sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By KENNETH CHANG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The space station is falling. As it orbits Earth, even at a
height of 210 miles, the nascent International Space Station
brushes against wisps of air, causing it gradually to lose speed
and altitude.
</P>
<P>
   The sun, as it approaches the height of its 11-year sunspot
cycle, churns in a more unruly roil, throwing out more high-energy
radiation that puffs out Earth's outer atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   The station falls faster.
</P>
<P>
   Since February, the space station has been dropping 1.5 to 2
miles a week. At that pace, its orbit would dip below 200 miles by
the time the next piece of the station, the Zvezda service module,
is launched in July.
</P>
<P>
   Two hundred miles is still a safe altitude, but any further
delay of Zvezda, already two and a half years late, could pose a
problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things won't really get precarious until the end of August,''
said Paul S. Hill, the space station's flight director. ``It'd be
September before you'd hear loud noises and see a big splash.''
</P>
<P>
   If necessary, Hill said, flight controllers could fire the
station's rockets to raise the orbit. But the station's limited
propellant is needed to dock the station to Zvezda, and until
Zvezda arrives, there is no way to refuel.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid that conundrum entirely is one reason the space shuttle
Atlantis is now on the launching pad. During an 11-day mission,
which is to begin Thursday morning, Atlantis is to nudge the space
station upward by 20 to 25 miles.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, Atlantis was to fly a few weeks after Zvezda joined
the two components already in orbit. But after the Russians put off
Zvezda's launching until July, NASA decided in February to split
the original shuttle mission in two.
</P>
<P>
   Under the revised schedule, Atlantis will bring up more than a
ton of supplies now _ including fans, air filters and replacements
for failing batteries _ and then revisit the station with more
supplies about five weeks after the launching of Zvezda.
</P>
<P>
   If successful, these flights will break the logjam that has
stalled work on the $60 billion project. ``I think we are
positioned to have a very big year,'' said W. Michael Hawes, NASA's
chief engineer for the space station. ``I think we're in a position
to make very good, rapid progress, as soon as we get the service
module in July.''
</P>
<P>
   The station's first full-time occupants are to arrive at the end
of October. For now, NASA wants to make sure that what is already
up stays up in working condition.
</P>
<P>
   ``The primary reason is to do maintenance work on the station,''
James Hartsfield, a spokesman at NASA's Johnson Space Center in
Houston, said of this month's trip. ``The re-boost is a close
second.''
</P>
<P>
   When it split the mission in two, NASA also split the crew,
reassigning three members to the later flight. The crew for the
first mission includes James D. Halsell Jr., the commander; Dr.
Scott J. Horowitz, the pilot, and Dr. Mary Ellen Weber and Jeffrey
N. Williams, the mission specialists, who have been training
together more than a year. Joining them will be two American
astronauts, James S. Voss and Susan J. Helms, and a Russian
astronaut, Yuri V. Usachev, who had been training in Moscow to be
the station's second crew.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, a shuttle crew trains six months to a year for a
mission.
</P>
<P>
   The short-notice shuttle crew shuffling is unusual, but NASA
says the newcomers should have no trouble with their new duties.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were extremely familiar with all of the systems of the
space station,'' said Rob Navias, a Johnson Space Center spokesman.
Adding the three to the current mission ``made perfect sense from
our standpoint,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The mission, which was postponed from last month by bad weather,
includes a six-and-a-half hour spacewalk to install a crane and
other equipment on the outside of the space station.
</P>
<P>
   On the mission's eighth day, after all of the cargo has been
unloaded to the station, the shuttle will use its leftover
propellant to raise the station to a higher orbit.
</P>
<P>
   Then the falling begins again.
</P>
<P>
   At the altitude of the space station, the thin upper atmosphere
is a better vacuum than what can be produced in the best vacuum
chambers on the ground _ but it is not empty.
</P>
<P>
   ``In space there are still some particles that impact the
spacecraft and cause drag,'' Hill said.
</P>
<P>
   The number of particles rises and falls with the sun's sunspot
cycle.
</P>
<P>
   When the sun is at its quietest, each cubic inch of space 200
miles above the ground still contains about five billion molecules,
mostly atoms of oxygen.
</P>
<P>
   When the sun is near the height of its solar activity, intense
magnetic fields erupt out of its surface that heat gases in the
sun's atmosphere to millions of degrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have things at two million degrees,'' said Dr.
Raymond G. Roble, a senior scientist at the National Oceanic and
Atmospheric Administration's Space and Environmental Center in
Boulder, Colo., ``they give off X-rays.''
</P>
<P>
   Only a small fraction of the sun's light is emitted as X-rays,
but the intensity of X-rays at solar maximum can be up to 10 times
as great as at solar minimum. (At visible wavelengths, the sun is
only an imperceptible fraction of 1 percent brighter.)
</P>
<P>
   Ninety-three million miles away, some of those X-rays, as well
as photons of short-wavelength ultraviolet light, slam into
molecules in Earth's upper atmosphere, heating them up.
</P>
<P>
   At solar minimum, the temperature of the atmosphere 200 miles up
is 600 to 800 degrees Fahrenheit. At solar maximum, temperatures
rise to more than 1,800 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   In the same way a hot air balloon rises upward, ``that extra
heating causes the atmosphere to expand outward,'' Roble said.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the density of the atmosphere is now nearly 10
times as great as when the sun is at solar minimum. The denser
atmosphere increases the drag on the station, and the station falls
faster.
</P>
<P>
   The rate of falling peaked at more than two miles a week, but it
has since slowed down again as solar activity entered a temporary
lull. The peak is expected in the middle of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The falling would never have been a concern at all, except for
the slipping launching date of the Zvezda service module.
</P>
<P>
   The 42,000-pound Zvezda, which is to provide living quarters,
propulsion and flight control and some laboratory space, was to
have been launched five months after the first two segments, the
Russian-built Zarya and the American-built Unity modules, were
launched in late 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Zvezda, which means ``star'' in Russian, was first delayed by a
lack of Russian financing. Then two Russian Proton rockets, the
type that is to lift Zvezda into orbit, exploded and crashed,
causing further delays.
</P>
<P>
   But according to some analysts, the rocket failures were a
blessing, giving both the United States and Russia more time to
test space station components on the ground instead of rushing them
into orbit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year's launch schedule was a game of space chicken, with
both sides roaring down the road, hoping the other would blink
first,'' said James E. Oberg of Houston, a former NASA engineer who
is an expert on the Russian space program. ``There was divine
intervention. Both sides were saved by a Russian rocket failure,
which gave the Russians the excuse everyone was hoping for.''  &QL; 
(MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   Since the two crashes, the Russians have successfully launched
three Protons with a fourth scheduled in June before the Zvezda
launching, which is now scheduled for sometime between July 8 and
14.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the July launch date is much more realistic than
anything we've had before,'' said Rep. Dave Weldon, a Florida
Republican who has been critical of Russian involvement in the
space station project. ``But there's also the track record of delay
upon delay upon delay.''
</P>
<P>
   A successful launching of Zvezda would be followed in September
by the first piece of the truss that would be the backbone of the
space station. The first three-member crew is scheduled to arrive
in late October via a Russian Soyuz rocket. The first solar panels
are to go up in November, and the American-built Destiny laboratory
module is scheduled for launching in mid-January 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this time, the U.S. elements are looking in pretty good
shape, and I think we'll be able to meet our launch schedule after
the service module,'' Hawes said.
</P>
<P>
   Other schedule snags may still arise. Because Russia is keeping
its aging Mir space station, there may not be enough rockets to
ferry supplies and crews to both over the coming year.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has also been building a substitute module for
Zvezda in case the Russians run into further delays. In February,
NASA's administrator, Daniel S. Goldin, announced that if Russia
did not launch Zvezda by early August, NASA would instead send up
its interim control module at the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   But that $200 million module will not be ready by Goldin's
December date. Part of the module's ground-to-station communication
system has failed and needs to be replaced. ``We're probably a good
seven weeks off the December schedule,'' Hawes said.
</P>
<P>
   Because the interim control module also uses a different docking
mechanism than Zvezda, astronauts would have to reconfigure the
dock in the Zarya module now in orbit. That would require a $4
million Russian-built metal pressure dome to provide the astronauts
an air-filled working space. Weldon said the space agency should
set a launching date for the interim module in order to keep the
pressure on the Russians. ``They don't understand talking,'' he
said. ``We should be prepared to work with them, and if they don't
deliver, we should be ready and able to work without them.
</P>
<P>
   If Zvezda is successfully launched on time, the interim control
module will still become part of the station, but in a slightly
different role.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the space station has already circled Earth more than
8,200 times, empty and falling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-00 1955EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
