<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5777 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-POPE-SUCCESSOR-2TAKES     05-15 1363
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPE-SUCCESSOR-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS JOHN PAUL NEARS 80, CHURCH WEIGHS QUESTION OF SUCCESSOR 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (Repeating for all needing)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON AND JEFF ISRAELY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The images of frailty are unavoidable: the elderly pontiff
nodding off at a Mass in Bethlehem, stumbling and cutting his head
in Warsaw, relying on a cart with wheels to traverse St. Peter's
Basilica.
</P>
<P>
   The once vigorous man who slipped away from the Vatican for
skiing holidays now physically trembles and slurs his speech,
apparent side effects of Parkinson's disease.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, Pope John Paul II's physical weakness seems to have
endeared him to the public _ the photographs of the frail old man
praying alone before the Western Wall in Jerusalem, shuffling
painfully across the Yad Vashem Holocaust memorial seemed to serve
as powerful images of spiritual intensity.
</P>
<P>
   But as John Paul approaches his 80th birthday on Thursday,
Catholics have quietly begun to consider the inevitable moment when
John Paul's death or, less likely, retirement will create an
opening for a new pope.
</P>
<P>
   The pope is the world's most visible and influential religious
figure, considered by observant Catholics to be infallible when
speaking on faith and morals. Not only is he the spiritual leader
of the largest branch of Christianity _ there are an estimated 1
billion Catholics _ but he also commands unrivaled access to the
media and to world leaders.
</P>
<P>
   John Paul has used his pulpit to speak out on a variety of
economic and social policies, from his lifelong fight against
communism to his ardent opposition to abortion and capital
punishment. The results have been mixed, but his moral suasion was
cited by the White House when explaining its support for
international debt relief and by the governor of Missouri when
commuting the death sentence for a triple murderer.
</P>
<P>
   The next leader of the world's Catholics will be chosen, as
virtually all popes have been, by an extremely select group of men:
Roman Catholic cardinals under the age of 80. Right now, there are
104 cardinal-electors, although that number could rise if John Paul
creates more cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   The cardinals aren't talking _ Cardinal Bernard F. Law of Boston
did not return a call seeking comment _ and when the time comes,
they will deliberate behind closed doors inside the Sistine Chapel.
But others have begun to write and speak about the first papal
election of the church's third millennium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Among journalists at the Vatican, talk of who will be the next
pope started around eight years ago,'' said Marco Tosatti, who for
the last 18 years has been the Vatican correspondent for La Stampa,
a Turin-based daily. ``I've seen so many candidates over the years,
cardinals who six years ago a lot of people would say this could
very likely be the next pope, who are now dead or forgotten or very
sick.''
</P>
<P>
   The cardinals believe the pope is actually chosen by the Holy
Spirit, who moves through them to guide their voting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the cardinals will be looking for a
characteristic and then trying to find the man to fit that,'' said
the Rev. Todd Lajiness, a Detroit native who now works inside the
Vatican. ``That's a political, or I guess you could even say,
democratic, outlook. That's good for government. The church is a
much different entity.''
</P>
<P>
   But most observers say the cardinals also weigh a number of
strategic and political considerations when they gather.
</P>
<P>
   Among the key factors to be weighed when considering the
candidates for pope: age, geography, ideology, diplomatic and
communication skills, and health.
</P>
<P>
   Scholars and church officials interviewed in Italy and the
United States generally seemed to agree that the cardinals are
likely to be seeking a pope who is:
</P>
<P>
   --Old. Karol Wojtyla was just 58 when he became Pope John Paul
II, and as a result, his papacy has already lasted 21 years. A long
papacy tends to concentrate church power in Rome, and the cardinals
are expected to look for a pope in his 70s who probably would have
a shorter tenure and accumulate less power.
</P>
<P>
   ``As much as they like the present pope, there are problems when
a pope stays too long,'' said Richard P. McBrien, a Notre Dame
theologian and author of ``Lives of the Popes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been a lot of complaints about this pontificate
because it has tended to recentralize authority in the Vatican, and
there is a lot of resentment of the way they treat bishops like
altar boys. They'd like some breathing space after such a long and
dominating pontificate as this one.''
</P>
<P>
   --European. John Paul is the first Slavic pope, and the first
non-Italian since Hadrian VI died in 1523. The Italian cardinals, a
declining plurality in the College of Cardinals, are expected to
make a play to win the papacy back, and there are also strong
candidates from Germany and France.
</P>
<P>
   The cardinals, having made a bold move in choosing a Pole in
1978, are thought likely to retreat to their comfort zone. There is
a long-shot chance that the cardinals would do something more
dramatic, choosing a pope from the Southern Hemisphere to
acknowledge that Africa and Latin America are rapidly becoming the
heart of the church.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say there is no chance the next pope will be an
American, because Americans are viewed as too liberal and too
powerful, and because the one American cardinal in recent years
widely judged to be electable, Cardinal Joseph L. Bernardin of
Chicago, died in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``An American has no chance,'' said Brian H. Smith, professor of
religion at Ripon College. ``The American church is looked upon as
too liberal, we have a very outspoken laity, and America represents
wealth and power in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   --Conservative, but less so than John Paul. The College of
Cardinals is a conservative group, dominated by appointees of John
Paul II. But scholars say the cardinals have historically tended to
oscillate between conservative and more moderate papacies, and
after such a long conservative papacy they may be looking for
someone more open to change.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cardinals are probably going to look for somebody who is a
bit more liberal, in terms of his views about authority, than the
current pontiff,'' said Fitchburg (Mass.) State College President
Michael P. Riccards, the author of ``Vicars of Christ: Popes,
Power, and Politics in the Modern World.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a historic type of occurrence, as the cardinals,
who are pretty sophisticated, realize the institution has gone as
far as it can in one direction and try to bring it back to an even
keel,'' Riccards said.
</P>
<P>
   --Media-savvy and diplomatic. John Paul is the most traveled
pope in history, having taken 91 international trips during his
papacy; as a former actor he has been praised for his use of the
media to communicate positive images of the church, and he has
successfully improved relations with other religions. These
characteristics, particularly in an Information Age in which popes
are sure to remain highly visible, seem certain to become permanent
requirements for future popes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are very few positions in the modern world that have the
kind of visibility and moral force to them that the papacy can
have, and I think John Paul II has utilized that,'' said the Rev.
Donald P. Senior, president of Catholic Theological Union in
Chicago. ``The travels of the pope, and his use of the media have
become ingredients of the modern papacy. You couldn't have somebody
who would ignore that.''
</P>
<P>
   This pope has succeeded at communicating despite his
increasingly slurred speech. He kisses the earth on arriving in a
new place, meets with youth, and prays in public.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the age of communication, the pope must have the ability to
communicate, . . . but there are many styles of communication,''
said Pietro Scoppola, an Italian religious history professor.
``This pope uses communication of the symbolical. There are times
he speaks and we can't understand everything he's saying, but the
image of him and his sickness symbolizes the weakness in all
humanity, the mystery of creation.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
