<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5798 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-SIERRA-LEONE-ART-(TRI     05-15 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIERRA-LEONE-ART-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH LIBERIAN LEADER AS MEDIATOR, REBELS RELEASE 139 U.N.
PEACEKEEPERS  
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This story was originally scheduled as a news analysis,
SIERRA-LEONE-ASSESS) 
(ART ADV: A locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By NORIMITSU ONISHI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone _ Even as U.N. officials on Monday
confirmed the release of 139 peacekeepers held hostage by rebels,
thereby delivering the best piece of news since the beginning of a
humiliating month in this corner of Africa, there was hardly
ringing praise for the man who had made it all possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever you might think or say of the role of President
Charles Taylor in the Sierra Leone crisis,'' Oluyemi Adeniji, the
U.N. special envoy to Sierra Leone, said at a news conference
Monday, ``I think you have to admit that he is playing a positive
role.''
</P>
<P>
   The comments signaled the United Nations' unease in dealing with
Taylor, the former warlord who terrorized a population into making
him president of Liberia, after fruitless negotiations with Sierra
Leone's top warlord, Foday Sankoh, led to the current crisis.
Indeed, Taylor has for years been the principal ally of Sankoh's
Revolutionary United Front, allowing the rebel group to smuggle
diamonds through Liberia and making arms available to it.
</P>
<P>
   And so, a week after Sankoh disappeared from his home in the
capital and Taylor was asked by neighboring countries to act as a
mediator in the hostage crisis, the rebels released the 139
hostages _ with 347 now left in custody.
</P>
<P>
   The 139 hostages, whose condition was not clear, were taken out
of eastern Sierra Leone on Sunday night and sent across the border
into Liberian custody in a town called Foya, said David Wimhurst,
the spokesman for the U.N. force. They were being flown Monday to
the Liberian capital, Monrovia, before their scheduled return here
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Adeniji, who visited Taylor in Monrovia on Sunday, said the
hostages had been released ``unconditionally.'' But Taylor appeared
to want an immediate cessation of hostilities, saying that the
lives of the remaining hostages might be in danger if
pro-government forces continued pushing rebels east into the
hinterland in ``RUF areas,'' Adeniji said, referring to Sankoh's
Revolutionary United Front.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``He mentioned specifically the case of Masiaka,'' Adeniji said.
</P>
<P>
   Masiaka, an important junction town only 40 miles from the
capital, has been the center of battle in recent days. The town had
been under government control before the rebel uprising early this
month, and drawing the line there would increase rebel-held
territory and widen the distance to the all-important diamond mines
in the east.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan said in New York Monday that
all of Sierra Leone should be brought under government control.
``You cannot have a state where a group of rebels arrogate to
themselves the right to exploit the riches of the country, either
for themselves or for a war,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The release of the hostages underscored Taylor's continuing
influence over the Revolutionary United Front despite what appeared
to be a cooling in his relationship with Sankoh a few months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, a convict who bribed his way out of a Massachusetts
prison, where he was awaiting extradition to Liberia on
embezzlement charges, began his war in Liberia in 1989. Taylor
needed Sierra Leone's diamonds to finance his war, and became
allied with Sankoh, who began his movement in Sierra Leone in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Through the years, the two men were allies in their respective
wars and used similar strategies _ kidnapping children, turning
them into soldiers through forced use of drugs, deliberately
targeting civilians to create terror. In 1998, Liberians elected
Taylor president, mainly because they were tired of war and
believed that Taylor would take up arms if he did not win.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Since becoming president, Taylor has tried to burnish his image.
Last year, he played a crucial role in the Sierra Leone peace talks
by encouraging Sankoh to sign the accord. He was rewarded in July
when President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah of Sierra Leone and President
Olusegun Obasanjo of Nigeria, which had fought against Taylor as
part of a West African intervention force, went to Monrovia to
commemorate the three-year anniversary of the end of the Liberian
war.
</P>
<P>
   But Taylor apparently thought he had not been rewarded
sufficiently for his involvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``He usually complains that he has not gotten any aid from the
West and he needs it to rebuild his country,'' said a diplomat who
was involved in the peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Liberia continued to be a conduit for diamonds smuggled out of
Sierra Leone. According to the Diamonds High Council in Antwerp,
Belgium, Sierra Leone exported only $31 million in diamonds last
year; Liberia, which has only a fraction of Sierra Leone's diamond
mines, exported $298 million.
</P>
<P>
   After Sankoh joined a power-sharing government here last year
and was made chairman of a commission that oversees the nation's
mineral resources, he made plans to deal directly with diamond
dealers in the West, effectively cutting out Taylor from the
picture, government officials here said.
</P>
<P>
   That plan seemed to have strained the two men's relationship.
Sam ``Mosquito'' Bockarie, who had been the rebel group's field
commander and was close to Taylor, fled Sierra Leone after a
falling out with Sankoh late last year.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Bockarie remained in exile in Liberia with men loyal to him. On
Sunday night, he spoke in Monrovia at the presidency, saying that
the rebels here should stop fighting with the U.N. force. He denied
that he was involved in the crisis here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is just fabrication,'' he said. ``I will not go back there
after they have spoiled things with the U.N. If I go there, I am
going to mess myself up.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   With Sankoh still missing, Taylor seems to be the best hope for
the United Nations and the Sierra Leonean government to obtain the
release of the remaining hostages and help deal with the RUF.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our interest is the stability of Sierra Leone, and so it is in
our interest to maintain good relations with Liberia,'' said
Septimus Kaikai, the spokesman for Kabbah. ``I don't know what
President Taylor's motivation is. But politics makes strange
bedfellows.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
