<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5801 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-BUSH-REACTION-HNS &LR;      05-15 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-REACTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PRIVATIZATION OPPONENTS BASH BUSH SOCIAL SECURITY PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAN FREEDMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Opponents of privatizing Social Security on Monday
said Texas Gov. George W. Bush's plan to set up private investment
accounts for younger workers would ``blow a hole in whatever
financial problem Social Security now faces.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's Democratic opponent, Vice President Al Gore, said in a
speech in Ambler, Pa., that the Bush plan ``could lead to greater
reward for some _ but far greater costs and risks for everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said Social Security must be preserved ``as a bedrock
guarantee of retirement security.'' He advocates using the budget
surplus to pay down the national debt and use the money saved by
the resulting lower interest costs to bolster Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Social Security, which provides $32.5 billion in monthly
benefits to 44.5 million retirees and persons with disabilities, is
shaping up as a cutting-edge issue in the 2000 campaign, with Bush
and Gore offering radically different visions of how to resuscitate
the 65-year-old federal pension system.
</P>
<P>
   Bush unveiled his plan in a speech Monday in Rancho Cucamonga,
Calif., saying it would bring a higher rate of return to
beneficiaries and restore the system to fiscal health.
</P>
<P>
   While Social Security benefits of those now retired or near
retirement would stay the same, an undefined portion of younger
workers' payroll taxes could be channeled into investment accounts,
Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of privatization praised Bush for articulating a
reasonable way to help Social Security dig itself out of the
financial rut it faces. Social Security's future imbalance stems
from the fact that the 44-million strong Generation X _ born
between 1965 and 1977 _ will have to shoulder the impending
retirement of the 77-million strong baby-boom generation, born
between 1946 and 1964.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Bush plan, ``Social Security would be made a program
that saves rather than spends,'' said Michael Tanner of the
Washington-based Cato Institute. ``Workers, not politicians, would
control investments.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Thau, the head of Third Millennium, an organization that
advocates public policies for members of Generation X, said private
investment accounts would offer younger workers a way to break out
of over-reliance on a system that pays an average of $804-a-month
in benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if the economy hums along and every worker gets
everything promised, you still haven't provided true retirement
security to baby boomers,'' Thau said. ``The fact is that $804 a
month, or the inflation-adjusted equivalent in the future, just
doesn't cut it.''
</P>
<P>
   Roger Hickey, co-chair of the liberal Campaign for America's
Future, said Bush's plan is the latest manifestation of ``Wall
Street money pouring into Washington to convince the Congress and
the American people that Social Security was in crisis, and that
privatization was the solution.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's ``program would blow a hole in whatever financial
problems Social Security now faces,'' Hickey said at a press
conference of privatization opponents.
</P>
<P>
   The AFL-CIO also sounded its opposition to the Bush plan.
</P>
<P>
   Diverting a portion of payroll tax money into private accounts
would ``undermine the foundation that Social Security provides for
our retirement and disability insurance,'' said Richard Trumka,
secretary-treasurer of the AFL-CIO. The plan, if combined with
Bush's ambitious tax cut proposal, ``abandons debt reduction and
fiscal responsibility,'' Trumka said.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, Bush stated that a young worker holding a private
account over the course of a working career would be in far
superior economic shape at retirement than a young worker without
one.
</P>
<P>
   But Hans Riemer, the 27-year-old director of the
Washington-based 2030 Center _ a liberal advocacy organization that
focuses on government entitlement programs _ argued that
``privatization is actually about the worst thing you can do for
young workers today.''
</P>
<P>
   Earning retirement dollars through a private investment account
would require a certain amount of investment savvy and plain old
good luck, he said. In contrast, Social Security offers ``a
guaranteed rock-solid benefit It is for everyone, no matter who you
are, what you look like (or) where you live,'' Riemer said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that his group hired a plane to fly over Rancho
Cucamonga Monday during Bush's speech trailing a sign reading
``Don't Privatize Social Security.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Freedman can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address dan(at)hearstdc.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
