<DOCNO> NYT20000515.0240 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5805 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-LOS-ALAMOS-FIRE-ART-N     05-15 1092
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOS-ALAMOS-FIRE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIAN OFFICIALS ARE ANGRY AT SLOW RESPONSE TO LOS ALAMOS FIRE 
</HEADLINE>
 (With LOS-ALAMOS-WARN) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT15 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JAMES STERNGOLD 
  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA CLARA PUEBLO, N.M. _ The battle to contain the wildfire
here has broken down into several diverging fronts, with modest
signs of hope in the city of Los Alamos, where some residents were
allowed to return Monday, but also growing anger over the threat to
ancient Indian dwellings and lands that tribal officials say had
initially not been well protected.
</P>
<P>
   A visit to the Santa Clara canyon at the northern perimeter
Monday brought an encounter with swirls of thick white smoke, brush
fires just yards from the road, occasionally exploding pine trees
and nervous teams of firefighters known as hotshots, able to do
little more than hope that blazes along the southern edge of the
canyon would not be blasted by the winds toward the invaluable
archaeological sites.
</P>
<P>
   In Los Alamos, at the southern edge of the wildfire, and at the
nuclear weapons laboratory nearby, officials said the fire was
largely contained and that perhaps 10 percent of the 11,000
evacuated residents may be permitted to return soon. But they are
now taking stock of the staggering losses, which include 405
housing units and, at the lab site, five dilapidated but historic
structures where parts of the original atomic bomb were assembled
for the Manhattan Project during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Just one of the old wooden structures remained, the building
where the conventional explosives portion of the first bomb, known
as Trinity, was put together. The actual building where the Trinity
bomb was assembled, a simple wooden structure, was taken down years
ago, said Turnel Martinez, a lab spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Fire officials said in Los Alamos that the pace of destruction
has slowed, and that the fire had consumed at least 44,323 acres.
More important, they said, the fire is 28 percent contained, mostly
along the south and southeast edge, near the city of Los Alamos.
</P>
<P>
   There are now 1,268 firefighters battling the blaze in the
wooded areas, and an additional 250 or so protecting homes and
other structures in populated areas, a level that Jim Paxon, the
Forest Service spokesman, said would likely be the peak. The fire
was set 10 days ago by the National Park Service in what was
conceived as a controlled burn to thin dense pine forests.
</P>
<P>
   Although the news was generally good on the level of containment
in the south, winds are expected to pick up, and a cold front is
predicted for Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Many residents have continued fear possible leaks of radiation
from the grounds of the lab, both from structures that might have
been damaged by fire or from old dump sites where, years ago, the
lab put low-level radioactive waste.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the lab said no buildings containing radioactive
materials had been damaged and that their sensors had detected no
radiation leaks. In addition, Gregg Dempsey, the director of a unit
at the Environmental Protection Agency that monitors radiation,
said that the government has placed 20 more monitors around the Los
Alamos region.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this time, we're not seeing any cause for concern for
radiological release,'' said Jim Straka, a Department of Energy
official involved in the monitoring.
</P>
<P>
   But to the north, Indian officials expressed concern over what
they said was a slow initial response to the fire in their area,
and the heavy blow they could suffer if the fire jumps across the
Santa Clara canyon, on the Pueblo, or reservation, northeast of Los
Alamos.
</P>
<P>
   The Santa Clara Pueblo covers almost 50,000 acres and has about
1,500 residents. It is also home to spectacular ancient dwellings
that are believed to have been constructed about 800 years ago into
the buff-hued sandstone of the Puye cliffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we lose that canyon and the creek, we lose quite a bit of
our resources,'' said Denny Gutierrez, the governor of the Santa
Clara Pueblo tribal authority.
</P>
<P>
   He said that a major source of revenues for the tribe are the
fees it charges for permits to hunt, fish and camp in the canyon
and for visits to the Puye cliffs. A big concern is that the fire
could dump huge amounts of ash into the Santa Clara creek, in the
bottom of the canyon, choking it off and making it unusable for
irrigation or recreation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Economically, that would probably devastate the Pueblo,'' said
Gutierrez.
</P>
<P>
   He said firefighters were doing an excellent job, but that when
the fire first burst out of control, firefighters were slow in
responding to suggestions that they build firelines to the north,
not just in the south near Los Alamos.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just sounded to us like this was not a priority,'' said
Charles Sisneros, a tribal council member. ``That's not the way we
see it. This is our home and we have an obligation to protect it.''
</P>
<P>
   Dale Baca, another member of the tribal council, stood in the
bottom of the canyon Monday watching the blaze send up huge plumes
of white smoke and brush fires burn to the road, and said he was
also angry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The indecision was the problem,'' he said. ``We asked them to
cut the fire lines on the Forest Service land and they just said
they hadn't gotten the permission.''
</P>
<P>
   Paxon of the forest service said the firefighters had done
everything they could. ``Our object is to minimize the impact on
the Santa Clara Pueblo,'' said Paxon. ``We do take their needs to
heart. We feel we have adequate resources there. We didn't delay.''
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters said the pueblo lands were now among the most
vulnerable, particularly if the wind does whip up as expected.
Jerry Soard, a member of a hotshot crew from Carson City, Nev.,
watched as the fire spread its dark fingers down the canyon and
tightened its grip over the heavily wooded Indian land. He
expressed some optimism because the fire was moving slowly and
burning highly combustible brush that could feed an even fiercer
fire if the winds picked up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's doing pretty much what we want it to do at this point,''
said Soard. ``This is beneficial. It's a real nice backing fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if this meant the fire might be brought under control
here, another hotshot team member, Chris White, laughed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Control? You can't say that,'' said White. ``Not with these
winds. The problem is that when they get into the canyon they get
so squirrelly. They blow every direction.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-00 1959EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000515.0241 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5808 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-BUSH-BOS &LR;      05-15 0384
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-BUSH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROCKING THE RETIREMENT BOAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   George W. Bush proposed on Monday the most drastic change in the
Social Security system since Franklin Roosevelt devised it 65 years
ago. Unlike Roosevelt's plan, which united all the elements of
society to provide retirees with a guaranteed pension, Bush's plan
would divide Americans into two groups: those with the resources to
speculate with their Social Security money and those who depend on
every nickel to scrape through their retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Bush would not change the system for those near age 65. But, he
said, ``reform should include personal retirement accounts for
young people.'' Some portion, perhaps 2 percent, of the 12.4
percent Social Security tax would be diverted to these accounts as
soon as they began working.
</P>
<P>
   People already amassing private retirement assets would know
exactly what to do with that money. But those with limited means
would be prudent to put the money into government bonds, which do
not pay much more than Social Security. If they speculated in
stocks and got caught in a bear market on the verge of retirement,
the government might not make up their losses.
</P>
<P>
   Bush makes much of the fact that many people already invest in
stocks to pay for their retirement, and every American who can
afford one should have a private retirement account. But every
American also relies on Social Security as a bedrock retirement
income, no matter what happens on Wall Street. There is no reason
to threaten what Bush acknowledges is ``the single most successful
government program in American history.''
</P>
<P>
   Social Security does face financing problems in about 20 years.
Bush is right that a bipartisan commission should be formed to
address this difficulty. Supporters of the system have already
advanced reforms to keep it solvent while preserving its essential
character, including investing some of the tax proceeds in the
stock market on a collective basis.
</P>
<P>
   Social Security is one of the great institutions of social unity
and financial stability in American society. The next president
should seek to improve the system while preserving its cohesive
force and its guarantee of a secure income for all retirees.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
