<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000515.0244 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5826 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-LOS-ALAMOS-WARN-NYT &LR;      05-15 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOS-ALAMOS-WARN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOS ALAMOS FIRE BOUND TO HAPPEN, STUDIES SAID 
</HEADLINE>
  (With LOS-ALAMOS-FIRE) 
 By GEORGE JOHNSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA FE, N.M. _ Whether sparked by lightning, a carelessly
tossed cigarette or a prescribed burn like the one now flaring out
of control, a catastrophic wildfire threatening Los Alamos National
Laboratory was bound to happen.
</P>
<P>
   A 1998 report by officials at the Santa Fe National Forest in
northern New Mexico, which borders the area, warned that the next
five years held a 30 percent chance of a fire exceeding 5,000 acres
striking the dense ponderosa pine forests on the western flank of
the laboratory _ just as is now happening.
</P>
<P>
   And an appendix of an environmental impact report published last
year by the Department of Energy describes a situation eerily like
the one now in progress: a fire beginning southwest of the lab
during a bone-dry spring, swept by unrelenting winds toward the
town and laboratory. ``A major fire moving up to the edge of LANL
is not only credible but likely,'' the report concluded.
</P>
<P>
   The implication of both studies, first reported in Forest
magazine last fall, is that it was only a matter of time before
something like the current wildfire occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Two other devastating fires have raged around Los Alamos in 23
years. The first, the La Mesa fire in 1977, burned 15,270 acres and
jumped onto laboratory property; the second, the Dome Fire in 1996,
burned 16,500 acres, reaching near the edge of the lab.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, in a region of spectacular summer thunderstorms, an
estimated 372 ``fire starts'' from 1975 to 1996 were ignited by
lightning in 40,000 acres of forests surrounding Los Alamos.
</P>
<P>
   The current fire, which has destroyed more than 400 housing
units in the city of Los Alamos and forced its evacuation, began
May 4 when Parks Service officials ignited brush on a ridge to
eliminate some dry wood and debris that could feed a rampaging
natural blaze.
</P>
<P>
   The fire was set despite predictions from the National Weather
Service of high winds and low humidity that could make the fire
difficult to control. On the six-point Haines index, which is used
to help measure volatility, the Weather Service estimated
conditions at six.
</P>
<P>
   Windy conditions are not unusual in the area. The Energy
Department report found that there was frequently a good chance of
winds capable of spreading a fire beyond control. It was ``not
uncommon,'' the report concluded, for strong winds to blow steadily
in the same direction for days at a time.
</P>
<P>
   These factors are particularly hazardous in dense, dry ponderosa
pine forests like those around Los Alamos. A century of suppressing
naturally caused wildfires has helped lead to arboreal growth that
is among the most plentiful in the Southwest. At the turn of the
20th century, before extensive settlement, according to Wallace
Covington, a professor at Northern Arizona University's School of
Forestry in Flagstaff, there were an estimated 20 to 60 trees an
acre. Now there are 300 to 900.
</P>
<P>
   This overcrowding was also encouraged by large-scale grazing
after the coming of the railroads in the late 19th century. With
little grass left to compete with, pine tree seedlings
proliferated.
</P>
<P>
   Tree ring studies show that when the forests were sparser, grass
fires swept through uneventfully every few years. Hugging the
ground, the flames consumed grass instead of giant pines. But with
overgrazing, grass was replaced by a thick carpet of explosive pine
needles _ the bottom rung of a fire ladder that sweeps flames
upward instead of outward, climbing the stunted midget pines right
to the tops of the towering ponderosas.
</P>
<P>
   The Energy Department says it had begun to take the warnings to
heart, clearing large areas of brush around the lab to reduce the
risk. ``A fair amount of precautions have been taken very
recently,'' said Lisa Cutler, a department spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   But Covington said that a far more extensive effort of thinning
the thick forests beyond the laboratory might have made all the
difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that kind of project had been put into effect around Los
Alamos, that would have stopped the fire well before it got into
town,'' he said. ``If the trees had been thinned and burned, they
would have caught it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
