<HEADLINE>
GUN BATTLES PIT ISRAELI, PALESTINIAN SECURITY FORCES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALIZA MARCUS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Underscoring escalating tensions over the peace
process, Israeli soldiers and Palestinian police fought gun battles
Monday even as Prime Minister Ehud Barak narrowly won parliamentary
approval to transfer three Jerusalem suburbs to Palestinian
self-rule.
</P>
<P>
   In the worst oubreak of violence in four years, at least three
Palestinians were shot dead by Israeli soldiers and another 300
were wounded during rock-throwing demonstrations that deteriorated
into open gun battles between Israeli and Palestinian security
forces in parts of the West Bank and Gaza. At least 11 Israeli
soldiers were also wounded in the clashes.
</P>
<P>
   The clashes appeared fueled by anger over the slow pace of the
peace process and Israel's refusal to release 1,650 Palestinians
held in Israeli jails. Palestinians regard them as political
prisoners, while Israel says they were jailed for security
offenses. Hundreds of the prisoners are on the 15th day of a liquid
fast to demand their freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Demonstrators congregated at intersections where Israeli
military checkpoints mark the boundaries of Palestinians'
self-ruled areas and hurled molotov cocktails and burned tires as
helmeted Israeli soldiers fired back with tear gas and
rubber-coated metal bullets.
</P>
<P>
   In some parts of the West Bank, Palestinian police on rooftops
and in the crowd opened fire on Israeli soldiers, who shot back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where is peace? Peace means no soldiers on the road, peace
means no more Palestinians in prison,'' said Ali Ismail Abu Subah,
a 28-year-old watching the protests in Bethlehem.
</P>
<P>
   The violence Monday, which also was the Palestinian day of
mourning on the anniversary of the founding of Israel 52 years ago,
took place as the Knesset, Israel's parliament, narrowly approved a
decision by the cabinet to transfer more land to Palestinian
self-rule, in a step that could give a much-needed boost to the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are at one of the most important junctions for the future
of the country and its people,'' Barak told the Knesset in a speech
frequently interrupted by hecklers. ``The peace process with the
Palestinians has reached the point of critical decision and we are
prepared to take historic steps.''
</P>
<P>
   But the 56-to-48 vote, with one abstention, may come at a high
political cost to Barak, who had to rely on the votes of three
small Arab parties and two leftist parties outside his coalition to
get the decision approved.
</P>
<P>
   Barak's decision to go ahead with his plans to transfer the
three suburbs bordering Jerusalem could mark the beginning of the
end of his broad-based coalition government, which has often feuded
over how to proceed with the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   One partner in the coalition, the National Religious Party,
which represents Jewish settlers in the West Bank and Gaza, said it
will pull out rather than support the land transfer, and former
Soviet dissident Natan Sharansky said he may take his party out as
well.
</P>
<P>
   The two parties, along with the Orthodox Shas party, either
refused to take part in the vote or opposed the transfer. If the
National Religious Party and Sharansky's Yisrael B'Aliyah party go
ahead with their threat, Barak will be left with a minority
government.
</P>
<P>
   The prime minister made a final plea in parliament to his
coalition partners, reminding them that the villages slated to be
transferred to full Palestinian control were already under
Palestinian civil rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``Changing the status (of these villages) does not seriously
change anything in the field, because the areas are already under
Palestinian civil control, and from a security perspective as well,
there is no danger,'' Barak said.
</P>
<P>
   Later, in another attempt to keep his coalition intact, the
prime minister's office said the handover of the land would be
delayed until Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat gave an explanation
for the violent demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   The conflict over the three suburbs _ Abu Dis, Azzariye, and
Sawahreh _ is in effect a fight over perceptions of what sort of
final agreement Barak intends to make with Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   The three towns border Jerusalem, which Israel claims as its
indivisible capital. But East Jerusalem was captured from Jordan in
the 1967 Middle East war, and Palestinians demand that it be turned
over to them to become the capital of their hoped-for independent
state.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Barak's own coalition members, as well as many in the
opposition, said that giving the Palestinians the three suburbs
will open the way for the eventual division of Jerusalem, something
Barak has repeatedly said he will not allow.
</P>
<P>
   In another sign of the difficulties Barak faces in moving ahead
with the peace process as the two sides try to reach a final
agreement by September 13, thousands of Israelis demonstrated in
downtown Jerusalem against transferring any more land to
Palestinian control.
</P>
<P>
   Amid banners accusing the Palestinians of not living up to their
commitments under past peace accords, opposition politicians and
activists told the crowd that Barak had gone too far by agreeing to
turn over more land to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are here to say that we don't want to commit suicide, that
we can't give the Palestinians a state,'' activist Nadia Matar told
the crowd. ``Look at the violence that is happening today. It is
suicide to give the Palestinians land.''
</P>
<P>
   The difficulties Barak faced in bringing the land transfer to a
vote _ he delayed it for weeks while he struggled to win the
support of his coalition _ is a reflection of the problems the
peace process has faced over the past few months.
</P>
<P>
   Talks between Israeli and Palestinian negotiators were supposed
to culminate last week in an outline for a final peace deal, but
the talks have stalled over the question of how much land the
Palestinians would receive for an independent state.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Ross, the United States' Middle East envoy, was expected
to arrive in Israel Monday night to help the two sides embark on
another round of talks.
</P>
</TEXT>
