<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5845 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-PROUST-BOOK-REVIEW-NY     05-15 1068
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROUST-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PROUST'S WAY':   ON A JOURNEY IN WHICH FLAWS CAN LIGHT THE WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Editors: Publication notes appear at end of review.)  
 y RICHARD BERNSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Marcel Proust, he of the little madeleines and the long
sentences and the redeeming power of memory, is not the Marcel
Proust of this intellectually powerful, deeply considered
evaluation by Roger Shattuck, the highly esteemed scholar of French
literary culture. Shattuck writes about the Proust beyond the
standard image. His new book, aptly titled ``Proust's Way: A Field
Guide to `In Search of Lost Time,''' learnedly guides the reader,
familiar with Proust or not, into the deeper moral and
philosophical dimensions of the writer.
</P>
<P>
   The heart of Shattuck's argument comes in two chapters titled
``Proust's Complaint'' and ``Proust's Binoculars: Memory and
Recognition,'' the sort of capaciously penetrating literary
criticism rarely seen these days. Shattuck's main purpose in these
chapters is to identify the themes that unite Proust's oceanic
comedy of French manners. Beforehand, he fills in the background on
Proust's novel _ whose title Shattuck translates as ``In Search of
Lost Time'' rather than the better known ``A Remembrance of Things
Past'' _ that any reader would need to follow his argument.
</P>
<P>
   Proust, sickly, sensitive, preternaturally aware, began writing
``Search'' when he was 35, having lived his life on the fringes of
fin de siecle high French society. Shattuck cites unflattering
critical judgments on Proust from the likes of Aldous Huxley and
Henry James to the effect that Proust's style was slack to the
point of incoherence and that his novel never transcended the
decadence and ennui that it describes. Shattuck, prefiguring the
themes that he will develop later, declares Proust ``guilty _ but
not as charged.'' Traits like ``snobbery, megalomania, boredom,
aestheticism, and instability of character'' do loom large in
``Search,'' but to understand Proust's greatness, he avers, one has
to understand ``the role they are assigned in a remarkably coherent
work of art.''
</P>
<P>
   If one knows anything at all about ``In Search of Lost Time,''
it would be that it is about the intense power of a certain kind of
memory _ the memory that the aging Marcel experiences when he dips
a madeleine into a cup of linden tea and the taste unexpectedly
restores the lost feelings of his youth at his aunt's country house
at Combray.
</P>
<P>
   For Shattuck, ``Search'' is about memory but is vastly richer in
themes and insights than that. In ``Proust's Complaint,'' for
example, he probes what Proust called an ``infirmity in my
nature,'' and what Shattuck calls ``this distressing perverseness
that dogs the most enterprising activities of the human mind and
seems to deprive it of satisfaction.'' The infirmity is the nasty
psychological law by which experience falls short of our
expectations of it, the existence of a kind of barrier between
perception and reality.
</P>
<P>
   This is, as Shattuck acknowledges, no more than the cliche that
the grass is greener on the other side of the fence. But Proust
elaborated on that cliche more than any other writer, he contends,
and his elaboration produced a masterpiece that is more comic than
tragic, more vibrant than sad. Marcel, who is both a character in
Proust's novel and one of its narrators, makes strenuous efforts to
satisfy his ambition and then loses interest just when he seems
about to succeed. Shattuck's assessment of one of Proust's more
famous scenes, when the young Marcel finally succeeds in kissing
Albertine, the chief object of his desire, brings this point home
to great effect. ``When he kisses Albertine, he confronts 10
Albertines, no one of whom he desires,'' Shattuck writes. ``Marcel
carries a pall wherever he goes.''
</P>
<P>
   Shattuck gives this theme historical resonance by tracing
Marcel's particular kind of self-doubt back to Montaigne, who three
centuries before Proust wrote: ``I attach too little value to
things I possess, just because I possess them.''
</P>
<P>
   Proust in this sense is a chronicler not so much of social mores
as of the universal human condition, manifested in Marcel's
paralysis in the face of what he most desires. Shattuck, drawing on
an impressive degree of erudition, shows some of the sources of
Proust's deliberation on these deep flaws in human nature, and he
links those flaws to another concept, which Proust called
``intermittence,'' the inability of people to be all of themselves
at any given time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The `Search' as a whole seeks not to transcend that condition
but to encompass it,'' Shattuck writes. ``The book becomes oceanic
in scale in order to contain the changing weathers and tides and
crosscurrents of a long voyage.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Proust's narrator arrives, in Shattuck's view, at a
kind of wise tolerance. ``Fully understood as part of our lot,
Proust's complaint leads not to despair but to a gentle smile at
the vagaries of human persons and at the time it takes us to
recognize ourselves for what we are,'' Shattuck writes.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Proust's Binoculars'' Shattuck traces a complicated
argument showing how the visual imagery in ``Search'' relates to
Proust's underlying concept of perception. Error of perception is
the critical concept in Shattuck's analysis. He leads the reader
through a series of literary byways to his belief that ``Search''
is less about memory than it is about what Shattuck calls
``recognition,'' specifically Marcel's recognition of himself as a
writer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The complex shuffling and sorting out of images that we call
`recognizing' a person arises from the reality of disappearing
selves, of death,'' Shattuck writes. ``The perpetual menace of
death, instead of discouraging Marcel, spurs him on anew toward his
`urgent, capital rendezvous with himself.'''
</P>
<P>
   Shattuck's arguments are sophisticated and subtle and not always
easy to follow. One reads certain passages and then one rereads
them to sift their meaning. The effort produces ample rewards.
Shattuck leaves us not only with a deepened appreciation of
Proust's great work but of all great literature as well, because in
the deepest sense he has done what all literary criticism strives
to do: he has taught us how to read.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES: `PROUST'S WAY,' a Field Guide to `In Search
of Lost Time'  &QL; 
By Roger Shattuck  &QL; 
291 pages. W.W. Norton. $26.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-00 2000EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
