u f BC-FED-DECISIONS-BOS &LR;      05-15 1053
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FED-DECISIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREENSPAN FACES MOST DIFFICULT JUDGMENT CALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Federal Reserve chairman Alan Greenspan, in his meeting Tuesday
with central bank policy makers to set interest rates, faces the
most difficult test of his remarkable career at the Fed: can he
ensure that the nation's longest economic expansion continues?
</P>
<P>
   Most economists expect Greenspan to boost interest rates by a
half point, continuing a campaign begun last summer to rid the
economy of inflationary tendencies. A few economists returned to
earlier predictions of a quarter-point hike after the newest batch
of economic indicators, released last week, showed wholesale prices
dropped and retail sales slowed.
</P>
<P>
   But while the world focuses on how much rates will rise,
economists said members of the Federal Open Market Committee,
headed by Greenspan, are focused on the policy dilemmas involved in
deciding how much to increase rates.
</P>
<P>
   A big hike in rates could further unsettle financial markets,
causing stocks to tumble and making it more difficult for the Fed
to engineer a smooth landing. But if the Fed does too little, the
market might soar or the economy might continue to barrel along,
unleashing inflation which has creeped up but has not yet entered
the ``red zone.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fed's goal of maintaining price stability is very much at
risk here,'' said Allen Sinai, president of Primark Decision
Economics, a Boston consulting firm. ``Finding the exact amount and
doling it out, with the right timing, is harder than the choices
the Fed has had to deal with in most of the 1990s.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fed's policy dilemmas are in addition to the unique concerns
posed by an election year, as was true in the early 1990s when
tight monetary policy was blamed for the incumbent party's loss of
the presidency when Republican George H. Bush was defeated by a
Democrat, Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Since last June, the Fed has raised interest rates five times _
a quarter-point each time _ in an attempt to cool the economy. Fed
policy makers will be concerned that the pace of economic growth,
which accelerated to a 7.3 percent annualized rate in the fourth
quarter of last year, continued at a strong 5.4 percent annual rate
in the first quarter of year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The economy continued to expand in April when 340,000 jobs were
created, in addition to 458,000 jobs in March. Two strong months
drove the April unemployment down to 3.9 percent _ it was the first
time the rate had fallen below 4 percent since January 1970. In
April, new data released Monday showed that US industrial
production of goods ranging from cars to computers rose at its
strongest pace in 20 months.
</P>
<P>
   Such unrelenting growth, economists said, require tough action
and a half-point increase to keep wages and inflation in check. ``I
think it'll be a half (point),'' predicted Nicholas Perna, an
economic consultant in Richfield, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   But Richard Yamarone, an economist for Argus Research Corp., an
independent research firm based in New York, argued that a
quarter-point hike would be more prudent, because it is too early
to tell whether prior Fed rates have begun ``to work through the
system'' and slow economic growth. There is typically a 9- to
24-month lag before a rate hike fully impacts the economy, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fed rate hikes _ the five _ have not had a chance or
opportunity'' to work, Yamarone said. ``There's an old adage
expansions don't die. The Fed kills them. I don't think Greenspan
really wants to go in with both barrels ablazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Fred Breimyer, chief economist at State Street Corp. in Boston,
shied from guessing what the Fed would do. But he said Greenspan
needs to ensure the stability of the nation's financial markets is
maintained.
</P>
<P>
   The stock market, at all-time highs, has been in a precarious
position for weeks. The Nasdaq Composite index of technology stocks
has plunged nearly 30 percent from its March high and has displayed
acute volatility. Yet, market analysts argue that the Nasdaq _ and
probably the Dow _ are well above levels justified by corporate
earnings or economic activity.
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq rose 2.2 percent Monday, or 78.62 points, to 3607.68,
though the tech-stock index for the year has lost more than 11
percent this year. The Dow, which is down 6 percent this year,
gained 1.87 percent Monday, or 198.41 points, closing at 10,807.78.
</P>
<P>
   ``These aren't markets that have traded well over the past two
months and could do less well over the coming two months. For the
Fed to have contributed to that or perceived to have contributed to
that would not be desirable,'' Breimyer said.
</P>
<P>
   But Breimyer, Perna and other economists stressed what is most
important is that the Fed clearly state its goals in the statement
that will accompany the latest announcement about interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``A strong statement would be that they're going to do this
until the economy shows signs of slowing,'' Perna said, because
``the last thing they want is to suggest'' is Tuesday's rate hike
might be the last. ``That would give them a big rally in stocks
which they don't want and don't need,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Fed's ultimate goal is stanching inflation _ not
coddling financial markets. While inflation is still far below
levels that had caused worry in past economic expansions, it has
creeped up. The consumer price index rose 0.7 percent in March,
producing a 3.7 percent inflation rate for the past year. That is
more than a point above inflation a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Sinai said anecdotal evidence of inflation has become pervasive,
from 10 percent to 15 percent increases in ice cream prices on
Martha's Vineyard to recent surveys showing companies and consumers
are anticipation higher prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wrong thing may well be not doing enough,'' Sinai said
about the Fed action. ``Even though we're at a very low rate,
inflation is on the march.''
</P>
<P>
   While economists differ on the fine points of how to conduct
monetary policy, none said Monday that Greenspan's decision would
be an easy one.
</P>
<P>
   Fed members ``are trying to exit themselves from the situation
gracefully _ the word gracefully should not be overlooked.''
</P>
<P>
   It comes down to a judgment call, he added _ Greenspan's
judgment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-00 2000EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
