<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5851 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-NY-OPERA-KELLOGG-ART-     05-15 1045
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-OPERA-KELLOGG-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: VISIONARY OF THE OPERA INSPIRES A TURNAROUND
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT7 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ANTHONY TOMMASINI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Paul Kellogg became the artistic and general
director of the New York City Opera in 1996, the company was
carrying a $5 million debt, had lost its sense of artistic
direction and was coping emotionally with the death from AIDS of
its previous director, the conductor Christopher Keene.
</P>
<P>
   Revitalizing the City Opera was going to be a formidable
challenge. And the greatest impediment to doing so, in fundamental
ways, was the New York State Theater itself, the City Opera's home
since 1965, which is shared with the New York City Ballet.
Rehearsal space and administrative offices had always been woefully
inadequate there.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate problem Kellogg confronted was the poor acoustics
of the 2,700-seat auditorium. Two earlier attempts to correct the
problem with minor architectural adjustments had not appreciably
improved the sound in the house. In exasperation, Kellogg, with the
support of the City Ballet, finally approved the installation of an
electronic sound enhancement system before the opening of the
season last fall, surely the most controversial decision of his
tenure.
</P>
<P>
   Natural sound has been a hallmark of the classical music
heritage, and there are few places left in the world, other than
opera houses and concerts halls, where audiences can experience
music without the sound being processed electronically.
</P>
<P>
   But Kellogg maintains that the sound system has been an enormous
success over all. Without exception, he asserts, the company's
music staff, orchestra players and singers support its use. And the
vast majority of City Opera audiences either strongly approve, he
says, basing his observations on feedback and mail he has received,
or at least are not bothered by it.
</P>
<P>
   During a recent interview, Kellogg vigorously defended his
decision to resort to an electronic solution for the house's poor
acoustics. Yet he also indicated for the first time that the system
was an ``interim solution'' for a problem that he hopes will be
solved architecturally by a major renovation of the house.
</P>
<P>
   Discussions are under way about renovations of the entire
Lincoln Center complex. A major redesign of the State Theater
auditorium to improve the acoustics is on the table, though the
project could easily be derailed by the sheer expense involved,
which could exceed $30 million for the State Theater alone.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the auditorium is a historic and justly acclaimed
space for dance. The City Ballet, which actually prefers to
minimize sound from the stage, has more interest in preserving it
as is.
</P>
<P>
   If the renovation plan does not come to pass, Kellogg stated
unequivocally, the company will find ``another solution.'' He
refused to specify what that might entail, but the only apparent
solution would be to move the company to a site outside Lincoln
Center. That idea was raised unofficially by Kellogg's exasperated
predecessors. Such a move would be Kellogg's boldest stroke by far,
challenging the idea of the urban arts complex.
</P>
<P>
   What Kellogg mostly wanted to talk about during the interview
was good news about the company's current finances and artistic
strength. The City Opera is thriving, and he has compiled the facts
and figures to back his case. Debt has been erased, and the company
now boasts a $12 million endowment. Fund-raising is up 50 percent
since 1996. The operating budget has increased some $5 million over
the same period, to $31 million for the 1999-2000 season, which
ended three weeks ago. In the last year attendance has increased by
10 percent: this season the company sold an average of 83 percent
of the house.
</P>
<P>
   How did this happen? Soon after arriving, Kellogg announced a
three-year revitalization plan with specific goals. Because the
Metropolitan Opera was right across the plaza at Lincoln Center, it
was essential, he felt, that City Opera distinguish itself by
performing repertory the Met was not known for, especially Baroque
operas and 20th-century American works. Even when the City Opera
presents the staples _ ``Carmen,'' ``Tosca'' and such _ it should
do so, he believes, in innovative modern productions that contrast
with the Met's grand traditionalism in the standard repertory.
</P>
<P>
   If the City Opera could not afford to hire renowned vocalists
for, say, ``Madama Butterfly,'' then it should present casts of
fresh-voiced, younger singers who looked like the characters they
were portraying and were strong actors.
</P>
<P>
   Yet every aspect of Kellogg's vision for the company was
contingent on making the house more acoustically vibrant. If
attractive singers with young voices were going to flourish there,
the sound in the auditorium had to become more alive. If Baroque
operas were going to be presented effectively, and if audiences new
to opera were going to be attracted to it, then the house had to be
made to feel more intimate.
</P>
<P>
   ``For so long, so many people complained about the acoustics of
the State Theater, its unfriendliness to young voices, the dryness
and unevenness of the sound in the house,'' Kellogg said. The press
complained continually, he added. The company had to find an
interim solution.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, until recently, the idea that the sound system might
become a permanent feature of even a renovated State Theater was
very much alive. When the system was installed, Kellogg asked wary
critics and audiences for a grace period. He promised to present a
demonstration for critics and patrons to hear just how subtly, in
his opinion, the system worked. Excerpts from operas would be
performed with the system switched off and on. That demonstration
has never occurred, he conceded, citing the expense involved.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall he also said that once the system was installed and
fine-tuned, the controls and levels would be set and never tampered
with. It was important, he felt, that the State Theater have a
distinctive house sound.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
