Arizona ranchers and millions of acres of federal lands across the
West, the U.S. Supreme Court upheld livestock-grazing regulations
imposed in 1995 by Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt. Among the
changes: Environmental groups like Forest Guardians may now compete
for grazing bids, and if they win, not put any cattle on the land.
Ranchers also will not be automatically re-issued grazing leases
every 10 years, a move they say could keep banks from granting them
loans. By MARK SHAFFER. Story will move in the `A` category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-00 2000EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000515.0256 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5853 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-NY-OPERA-KELLOGG-ART-     05-15 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-OPERA-KELLOGG-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: house sound. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   But even at the Met, with its quite good acoustics, the house
sound varies from production to production, mostly depending on the
size and placement of sets. Wouldn't it be impossible for
technicians at the State Theater to resist fiddling with the
controls from night to night? If the capability exists, it is human
nature to use it.
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, not only has daily tinkering become commonplace,
Kellogg conceded, but on some nights the system has been turned off
completely, he said, though no announcements were made to the press
and public. This put audiences, but especially critics who are
expected to offer informed evaluations, in an impossible situation.
Can we trust what we are hearing?
</P>
<P>
   That singers and musicians apparently support the sound system
is not really surprising. Why shouldn't they take advantage of
electronic assistance in an acoustically unfriendly house? That
audiences have largely embraced it is also to be expected.
Amplification has become pervasive, and the younger audiences the
company is attracting, having grown up with electronic sound, are
unlikely even to notice.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is, no matter what, people are going to complain
about the sound in this house,'' Kellogg said. ``This system is a
way of solving the problem on an interim basis. The audience is not
reacting, for the most part, on a matter of principle. Nor am I.''
Critics can ``wring their hands as much as they like,'' he added.
``It works for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Defenders, even among critics, argue that there is a difference
between real amplification, typical today in Broadway theaters
where singers wear body microphones, and systems that enhance the
acoustical properties of a hall itself. But whatever labels are
coined to describe the equipment, voices are still being picked up
by microphones, carried through wires and disseminated through
dozens, even hundreds, of tiny speakers that cover the walls.
</P>
<P>
   And just as on Broadway, the use of sound systems in opera and
concert music will eventually affect the way singers sing,
musicians play, audiences hear and composers write. Kellogg
maintains that the State Theater system ``allows voices to be heard
as they really are,'' and that it ``does not make a small voice
large or an ugly voice pretty.''
</P>
<P>
   I am not convinced, nor are some other critics, and at least a
vocal minority of audience members. Because of the enhancement
system, certain sounds _ a soprano's sustained, full-voiced high
notes, for example _ are almost always piercingly present. Some
sounds get oddly emphasized. During a recent performance of Virgil
Thomson's ``Mother of Us All,'' the opera sounded at times like a
concerto for snare drum.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, we have this adventurous and increasingly essential
company to thank for finally bringing us the first production ever
by a major New York opera house of Thomson's great American opera,
as well as many other important works, like Rameau's ``Platee'' in
the imaginative production by Mark Morris (which sold 95 percent of
the house in six performances). Next season come other rarities and
treats, like Prokofiev's ``Love of Three Oranges'' and Handel's
``Rinaldo'' with the splendid countertenor David Daniels in the
title role.
</P>
<P>
   Kellogg readily agreed that there was ``no substitute for a
house whose good acoustics are architectural.'' He hopes this can
be achieved at the State Theater. It falls to critics, then, to
point out the shortcomings of the current system.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Last week the company presented ``Showcasing American Composers
2000,'' an invaluable contribution to the city's cultural life and
the future of American opera. Over a period of two weeks, excerpts
of roughly 25 minutes each from 12 American operas, either
works-in-progress or existing operas that have yet to be produced,
were performed in open readings with a full orchestra and strong
vocal soloists at the Great Hall of Cooper Union.
</P>
<P>
   This is the second consecutive year that these free performances
were presented. The rehearsal schedule was tight but sufficient to
give the composers, interested singers and operagoers and, most
important, potential producers a good sense of the various works.
That Kellogg and his company secured funds for this important
project demonstrates how fully they are committed to the future of
American opera. The Met has done nothing remotely as helpful to the
cause.
</P>
<P>
   That the City Opera's showcase was taking place off-site,
downtown, not far from the home of the most famous organization to
bolt Lincoln Center, Joseph Papp's Public Theater, seemed
significant. What other bold ventures could the newly energized
City Opera undertake if it could just scrap that sound system and
fix up its house, or, maybe even get out of Lincoln Center and
start afresh?
</P>
</TEXT>
