<HEADLINE>
LYCOS MERGER RUMORS BOOST STOCK PRICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shares in Lycos Inc. rose 12 percent Monday on expectations the
Internet company may merge with the Internet unit of Spanish
telephone giant Telefonica SA.
</P>
<P>
   Telefonica's Terra Networks confirmed Friday it is in
discussions with Lycos to create a global Internet portal, though
executives cautioned no deal is certain.
</P>
<P>
   Neither company would elaborate Monday,  &UR; al &LR; though reports in
the Financial Times and the Wall Street Journal quoted anonymous
sources as saying Lycos was also considering selling itself
outright to Terra Networks.
</P>
<P>
   Lycos' sites are the fourth most popular on the Internet, but
analysts say the Waltham, Mass. company in danger of becoming an
also-ran in the battle for online eyeballs.
</P>
<P>
   For the three months ended Jan. 31, Lycos posted a net loss of
$31 million on revenue of $68.6 million. Lately, it has struck
partnerships with a plethora of online banks, car dealers and music
providers in an effort to extend its reach with relatively little
investment.
</P>
<P>
   But while those efforts have been applauded by analysts, Lycos
has gained little ground among Internet users since a year ago,
when shareholder opposition forced it to abandon a plan to merge
with Barry Diller's USA Networks Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Lycos's rivals have expanded their market reach.
About 59.8 million users visited America Online and its affiliated
sites in March, up from 47 million a year earlier, according to the
MediaMetrix firm in New York. Meanwhile, Lycos sites attracted
about 32.9 million unique visitors in March, up from 32.3 million a
year earlier, MediaMetrix reported.
</P>
<P>
   Terra is best known for its Spanish-language content and could
extend its offerings with the English material that Lycos could
supply from Waltham, from its West Coast properties such as Wired
News, and from its Lycos Europe division.
</P>
<P>
   The Wall Street Journal Monday reported that Lycos is seeking a
price of at least $90 a share from Terra, citing unidentified
sources. That would be a steep premium over the $61.625 at which
Lycos stock closed in Nasdaq trading Monday. The stock was up $7.50
for the day.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts who follow Lycos and said they would likely support a
deal with Terra as an exit strategy. Lycos lacks the cash available
to America Online and Yahoo, and may have to sell out eventually,
said Larry Haverty, analyst at State Street Research. He said he
doesn't own shares in Lycos.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a strategy standpoint, they have to do something,''
Haverty said of Lycos. ``They could survive, but eventually the
stock valuation would decline'' as its competitors continue to pull
away.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Moran, analyst for Jeffries &AMP; Co., said shareholders might
be more inclined to support a deal based on a specific valuation of
Lycos' shares, in contrast to last year's proposal from USA
Networks. That proposal did not specify a premium for Lycos shares.
</P>
<P>
   A deal with Telefonica might also need the blessing of Lycos'
largest shareholder, CMGI Inc. of Andover, Mass., and its chief
executive David Wetherell.
</P>
<P>
   Wetherell initially backed the agreement with USA Networks but
reversed course after shareholders bid down Lycos' stock by nearly
a third. Wetherell also quit the Lycos board and CMGI has since
reduced its stake in Lycos, to around 16 percent from 22 percent at
the start of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   CMGI remains the company's single largest investor, followed by
Fidelity Investments and Putnam Investments, according to filings
to the US Securities &AMP; Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, a CMGI spokesman declined to comment on Lycos' talks
with the Spanish company and said Wetherell and other CMGI
executives hadn't even been briefed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're on the sidelines,'' the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Diller still believes a deal with USA Networks would have been
better for Lycos shareholders in the long run.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we came out with that same transaction today, there would
be applause,'' he said at a conference in New York last week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
