<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUNS-MOMS-EFFECT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESSIONAL LEADERS TALK COMPROMISE ON `GUN-SHOW' LOOPHOLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As the ``Million Mom March'' participants filed out
of Washington Monday after rallying for gun-control laws, there
were fresh signs that a 10-month congressional deadlock on a
pending bill might be broken, but little prospect that the larger
goal of universal gun registration would be achieved anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the march, key congressional leaders discussed a
possible compromise Monday on how to close the ``gun-show
loophole'' that allows people to buy handguns without the kind of
background check required at gun stores.
</P>
<P>
   But there remained little support for the top goal of march
leaders, to require licensing and registration of all handguns,
including the 60 million already in circulation. Even Vice
President Al Gore, who hopes to benefit politically from the march,
supports licensing only for owners of newly purchased handguns.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of political support for what march organizer Donna
Dees-Thomases has called her ``ultimate goal'' shows how far the
Million Mom March movement has to go, even after the impressive
start on Sunday, when 500,000 or more marchers filled the National
Mall. March organizers said Monday that their effort will be
transformed into a gun-control lobbying group and urged mothers to
become active in the fall campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The most significant action sought by the marchers is spelled
out in their petition: ``We call on Congress to require all handgun
owners to be licensed and that they be required to register their
weapons with the proper authorities. It makes sense.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is little movement toward that goal in Congress. Texas
Governor George W. Bush, the all-but-certain Republican nominee,
opposes such a measure. During the Democratic primaries, former
Senator Bill Bradley took the strongest position on gun control,
calling for the registration of all handguns.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Million Mom March goes beyond the Gore proposal and is
actually closer to the Bradley proposal,'' said David Bernstein, a
spokesman for Handgun Control Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The big question is whether the march will provide a turning
point for gun control and for candidates who espouse the group's
goals. As the Million Mom March prepares to transform itself into a
lobby, it is preparing to go up against one of the best-financed
and most powerful such organizations in Washington, the National
Rifle Association.
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, the Million Mom March could provide incentive
for Congress to break the deadlock on gun legislation now stalled
in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened this weekend is very important,'' said Sam
Stratman, a spokesman for House Judiciary Committee chairman Henry
Hyde of Illinois. ``A large number of Americans spoke with one
voice, and it will helpfully focus a good number of legislators on
reaching a compromise.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, with Gore casting the tie-breaking vote, the Senate
passed legislation that would require background checks of
prospective purchasers at gun shows from unlicensed dealers,
eliminating what has become known as the ``gun-show loophole.'' The
House passed a weaker version of the measure, adopting a one-day
background check, which the Justice Department has said is too
little time to conduct an adequate investigation in a small but
significant numbers of cases. The difference between the House and
Senate bills must be decided in a conference committee, but the
panel has not met since August.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde, who heads the House side of the conference committee, last
Friday made a significant compromise, proposing that a one-day
waiting period be extended in certain cases deemed necessary by law
enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   That prompted President Clinton to say Monday that Hyde and the
ranking Democrat on the House Judiciary Committee, Representative
John Conyers of Michigan, are making ``some real progress to
resolve the impasse.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Conyers: ``Hyde and I are getting closer, but it is not
clear to me where that leaves the measure itself'' with the GOP
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Edward M. Kennedy said the Hyde proposal is still
``riddled with loopholes.'' Nonetheless, Kennedy said the march had
a tremendous impact on Congress. ``This institution isn't really
going to be the same after yesterday,'' Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   Some Democrats believe Bush is vulnerable on the gun issue
because he secured passage of legislation in Texas that allows
people to carry concealed weapons. But the governor on Friday
sought to soften his image on guns, announcing a Texas program to
provide free gun-safety locks that he wants to institute
nationally.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is counting on strong support from women in his
presidential bid, especially those who favor gun control and are
sympathetic to the goals of the Million Mom March. But Gore also is
wary of offending gun owners who oppose the gun laws proposed
during the march.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-00 2001EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000515.0259 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5862 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u p BC-NY-GIULIANI-BOS &LR;      05-15 0606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GIULIANI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI SAGA REMAINS ON HOLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The news from City Hall was that there was no news.
</P>
<P>
   And so, for the hordes of reporters, the hordes of advisers
whose paychecks are on the line, the hordes of Republican
officeholders whose reelections are tied to his coattails, and the
hordes of observers across the state _ many with vested interests,
more just curious _ it was just another impatient day of waiting
for Mayor Rudolph Giuliani to make up his mind.
</P>
<P>
   Will he dash all caution, setting aside worries about his
prostate cancer, his shattered marriage, his affair with another
woman, and continue his run for the US Senate against Hillary
Rodham Clinton? Or will he decide the pressures are too great, the
medical treatments too onerous, and pull out?
</P>
<P>
   A record crowd of reporters and 21 TV cameras squeezed into the
Blue Room at City Hall Monday for the mayor's daily ``press
availability.'' Aides had said earlier that nothing big would
happen, but nobody was taking chances.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani walked into the room a little after noon, smiling and
shaking his head. By the time he got to the podium, he burst out
laughing, and said, ``I'm sorry to disappoint you, but I have no
major announcement to make today.''
</P>
<P>
   He had a few bits of news. He would not be going to California
for a fund-raiser. At the same time, a nationally televised town
hall interview scheduled for Thursday night in Manhattan was, at
least for the moment, still on. And he suggested he would make the
big decision sometime this week, possibly as early as Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   He flatly denied a report in Monday's Newsweek that he has
decided to drop out of the Senate race and undergo an operation and
then radiation treatment to wipe out his cancer. Those treatments,
together, would take three months, longer than a Senate campaign
could tolerate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The report in Newsweek is just absolutely false,'' he said
Monday. He insisted he has not yet decided on the course of
treatment, and said until that question is settled, he would try
not even to think about his political future.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's disclosures about his personal life gave him less
time than he thought he would have to consult with doctors. So, he
added, ``I'm going to need to do that this week _ tomorrow, the
next day, I don't know, you can't put a time frame on this.''
</P>
<P>
   Another remark suggested his decision will come in the next two
days. Noting that he needs time for medical consultations, he said,
``Tomorrow and the next day, I will probably have a much-reduced
schedule'' for work and campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   He insisted that Republican leaders and fund-raising organizers
were not pressuring him to hurry up. ``They're more patient than
all of you are,'' he told the roomful of reporters, with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is well known that the state's Republicans are getting
nervous, with opinion divided on whether it would be better for
Giuliani to go ahead or withdraw. All, however, agree that a
definite candidate is needed soon.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic Party is holding its state convention in Albany
Tuesday, where Mrs. Clinton will be officially declared the
candidate amid great fanfare. She was endorsed Monday by a
builders' union that usually endorses Republicans. The polls still
show her running neck-and-neck with Giuliani, but with her numbers
rising and the mayor's falling, especially in New York City and
upstate. In the suburbs, the mayor still holds a commanding lead.
</P>
<P>
   The state Republican Party holds its convention May 30.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-00 2001EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
