<DOCNO> NYT20000515.0260 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5872 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-COURT-RAPE-HNS &LR;      05-15 1144
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-RAPE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     COURT DENIES RAPE VICTIMS RIGHT TO SUE ATTACKERS IN FEDERAL
COURT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court ruled Monday that rape victims
cannot sue their attackers in federal court.
</P>
<P>
   It struck down a provision in a 1994 federal law allowing such
lawsuits, saying that Congress, in passing the measure, had
overstepped its bounds and reached into an area reserved for the
states.
</P>
<P>
   In the hotly disputed 5-4 decision in a Virginia case, the court
invalidated the part of the 1994 Violence Against Women Act that
authorized victims of gender-related violence to seek civil damages
in federal court rather than rely solely on state prosecutors and
juries.
</P>
<P>
   The high court ruled against Christy Brzonkala, a former student
at Virginia Tech in Blacksburg, Va., who had filed the suit against
two school football players after alleging that they had raped her
in a dormitory room.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, President Clinton issued a statement saying
he is ``deeply disappointed'' that victims of such crimes may no
longer sue in federal court.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because I continue to believe that there should be remedies
for victims of gender-motivated violence, we plan to study the
Supreme Court's decision ... to determine the best means to help
these victims,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Rodgers of the NOW Legal Defense and Education Fund, which
</P>
<P>
   represented Brzonkala, said, ``I consider this to be a severe
blow for women's rights because of the chilling effect it will have
on Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodgers added that ``Congress identified a kind of gender
discrimination. Congress is trying to address that with a creative,
specific solution, and the court says, `No, you can't do that.'''
</P>
<P>
   But attorney Michael E. Rosman, who argued the case on behalf of
the two football players, called the decision a ``victory'' for the
Constitution. ``If we had lost, it would have opened the floodgates
to federal intervention in almost any crime,'' he said, adding that
``every crime has an economic impact of some kind or another.''
</P>
<P>
   Congress passed the law after hearing charges that state courts
were not doing enough to protect women from violence.
</P>
<P>
   The lawmakers cited Congress' constitutional power to regulate
interstate commerce as a basis for passing the act. They said
gender-motivated violence was related to interstate commerce
because victims were often unable to work for long periods and cost
the nation $3 billion to $5 billion a year in lost productivity.
</P>
<P>
   But the Supreme Court said Monday that the lawsuit provision of
the law would open the door to federal intervention in many areas
traditionally under the control of the states.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Constitution requires a distinction between what is truly
</P>
<P>
   national and what is truly local,'' Chief Justice William H.
</P>
<P>
   Rehnquist wrote for the court.
</P>
<P>
   Congress' argument ``would allow (it) to regulate any crime as
long as the nationwide, aggregated impact of that crime has
substantial effects on employment, production, transit or
consumption,'' Rehnquist said. ``Indeed, if Congress may regulate
gender-motivated violence, it would be able to regulate murder or
any other type of violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Joseph Biden, D-Del., who sponsored the Violence Against
Women Act, said he did not know what would happen to the rest of
the law. ``The court really went off here in a way that I find
extremely troublesome,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rehnquist's opinion was joined by Justices Sandra Day O'Connor,
Antonin Scalia, Anthony M. Kennedy and Clarence Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   Dissenting were Justices David H. Souter, John Paul Stevens,
Ruth Bader Ginsburg and Stephen G. Breyer.
</P>
<P>
   Writing for the four, Souter cited ``the mountain of data
assembled by Congress, here showing the effects of violence against
women on interstate commerce. ... Violence against women may be
found to affect interstate commerce substantially.''
</P>
<P>
   The case dates from 1995, when Brzonkala said football players
Antonio Morrison and James Crawford raped her in a dormitory room
when she was a freshman at Virginia Polytechnic Institute and State
University.
</P>
<P>
   However, Brzonkala did not report the incident, which allegedly
occurred in September 1994, for nearly seven months. When a grand
jury convened to examine the allegation, she refused to testify.
The grand jury declined to indict either player.
</P>
<P>
   The players contended that consensual sex had occurred. Crawford
was cleared by a university hearing. Morrison, who admitted that
Brzonkala had told him ``no'' twice before they had sex, was
suspended from school for a year. The charge was later reduced to
``abusive language,'' and the suspension was cut to three months,
which allowed Morrison to continue his football career. Brzonkala,
furious at the outcome, withdrew from school.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1995 she filed an $8.3 million civil suit in federal
court against the players and the university under the newly passed
Violence Against Women Act. But before the trial began, U.S.
District Judge Jackson L. Kiser dismissed her case in July 1996. In
March 1999, the U.S. Court of Appeals for the 4th Circuit, based in
Richmond, Va., agreed. The law, Judge J. Michael Luttig wrote,
``simply cannot be reconciled with the principles of limited
federal government upon which this nation is founded.''On Monday,
the high court affirmed that decision.
</P>
<P>
   Rehnquist wrote that if Brzonkala's allegations ``are true, no
civilized system of justice could fail to provide her a remedy ...
But under our federal system that remedy must be provided by the
commonwealth of Virginia, and not by the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1960s, Congress has used the Constitution's interstate
commerce clause to pass such federal civil rights laws as those
banning discrimination in housing and in public accommodations.
</P>
<P>
   For several decades, the high court allowed this practice, but
in a 1995 case from San Antonio, the justices said it amounted to
an encroachment of federal power over the states. In that case the
high court invalidated the federal Gun-Free School Zones Act, which
prohibited possession of firearms near schools, as an improper
infringement on an area of state concern.That decision prompted
lower courts to scrutinize the rationale for other federal laws,
including the lawsuit provision in the Violence Against Women Act.
</P>
<P>
   In discussing the constitutional distinction between national
and local matters, Rehnquist said that ``there is no better example
of the police power, which the Founders undeniably left reposed in
the States and denied the central government, than the suppression
of violent crime and vindication of its victims.''
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
