<P>
   MEXICO-POLITICS (Mexico City) _ The Institutional Revolutionary
Party, which has elected every president since 1929 and dominated
Mexican political life, is falling behind in the presidential race
and is suddenly on the defensive. By Julia Preston. (1500 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES (Lethbridge, Alberta) _ One year after more than
a million Kosovo Albanians fled the Serbian province, North America
is proving to be the world's most welcoming region for refugees who
want to become immigrants. With the weather warming and security
said to be improving in Kosovo, Western European nations and
Australia are pushing, in some cases forcing, 250,000 refugees to
return to their devastated homeland. Germany, with 170,000 Kosovar
refugees, has said it will deport those who refuse a $1,000
incentive to return. But in Canada and the United States,
three-quarters of the Kosovars who came last year have stayed.
Today, almost all are eligible for residency status. By James
Brooke. (830 words)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TRADE (Washington) _ An influential senior House Democrat
from New York signaled Monday that he is leaning in favor of a
decisive China trade bill, as the measure's supporters and
opponents geared up for a furious week of lobbying before next
week's scheduled vote. Rep. Charles B. Rangel, the ranking Democrat
on the House Ways and Means Committee, said in a telephone
interview that he is still officially undecided on a measure to
grant China permanent normal trading privileges But then Rangel
challenged several of the opponents' main arguments. By Eric
Schmitt. (1000 words)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO-SCHOOL-CHEATING (Chicago) _ Five years after shaming
their school by cheating to win a statewide academic contest, some
of the former Steinmetz High School students on the quiz team now
say they have a single regret: getting caught. ``Apologize for
what?'' Jolie Fitch, one of those caught cheating asked defiantly.
``I would do it again.'' By Dirk Johnson. (850 words)
</P>
<P>
   MOON-NUKE (Undated) _ The United States drew up a secret plan to
detonate a nuclear bomb on the moon as a show of military and
technical strength during the feverish post-Sputnik days of the
Cold War, according to a physicist involved in the plan. By William
J. Broad. (750 words)
</P>
<P>
   LABS-SECURITY (Undated) _ A panel of scientists and engineers
who advise the president and Congress issued a statement expressing
concern that heightened security measures at federal laboratories
appear to be damaging their ability to hire and retain foreign-born
and minority scientists. By James Glanz. (725 words)
</P>
</TEXT>
