<P>
   &UR; Lead story: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-WOMEN (Washington) _ Declaring that ``the Constitution
requires a distinction between what is truly national and what is
truly local,'' the Supreme Court Monday invalidated a six-year-old
law that permitted victims of rape, domestic violence and other
crimes ``motivated by gender'' to sue their attackers in federal
court. The 5-4 decision striking down the civil remedy provision of
the Violence Against Women Act was the latest, one of the most
sweeping, but almost certainly not the last application of the
court's newly restrictive view of congressional power and of the
degree of deference that Congress is owed by federal courts. By
Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   1-column hed.
</P>
