</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-POLL (Undated) _ Results of the latest NYT/CBS News
poll. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   With graphics.
</P>
<P>
   2-column hed.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move this story by 9 p.m. ET in `p' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FOLD: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-PALESTINIANS (Jerusalem) _ For the first time in four
years, Israeli and Palestinian troops engaged in hours of gun
battles in the West Bank Monday as Israeli forces suppressed
Palestinian demonstrations by shooting tear gas, rubber-coated
bullets and live ammunition into stone-throwing crowds. Three
Palestinians were killed _ two police officers and a teen-ager _
and 350 were injured, according to Palestinian officials. Six
Israeli soldiers were injured, according to Israeli officials.
Against this violent backdrop, Prime Minister Ehud Barak won
Parliament's approval to transfer full control of three Palestinian
villages near Jerusalem to the Palestinian Authority, although
three parties in his fractious coalition did not support him and
one quit the government. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT6, and a map.
</P>
<P>
   1-column hed.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move this story by 9 p.m. ET in `i' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SOCSEC-CANDIDATES (Rancho Cucamonga, Calif.) _ George W. Bush
and Al Gore both make major policy speeches on the future of Social
Security. Bush fleshes out his plan for allowing people to invest
part of payroll taxes in the market while Gore explains his plan to
pay down the debt and use the interest saved to shore up Social
Security. By Alison Mitchell and James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   2-column hed.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move this story by 9 p.m. ET in `p' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BOTTOM: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-ENVIRON-SUITS (Huairou, China) _ In this relatively poor
and extremely polluted country, there is often no simple remedy for
the millions of people like Zhang Jinhu, a farmer here whose 4,000
ducks were killed, and many others whose livelihoods have been
destroyed by pollution. Though China has enacted strict
antipollution laws in the last decade, enforcement is still lax in
many places. Flagrant violations occur without so much as an
investigation. Frustrated, Zhang is suing for compensation. His is
one of a small but growing number of environmental suits by
pollution victims that may become test cases. By Elisabeth
Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   3-column hed.
</P>
<P>
   2-column photo with story.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move this story by 8:30 p.m. ET in `i' news file.)
