<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIREFIGHTERS-FUND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORCESTER FIREFIGHTERS FUND CASH TIED UP IN IRS RED TAPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARCELLA BOMBARDIERI  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After a December warehouse blaze claimed the lives of six
Worcester firefighters, tens of thousands of donors, touched by the
sacrifices of the men who died, wrote checks to a fund set up by
the hometown newspaper to benefit the firefighters' families.
</P>
<P>
   But the 17 growing children, the five widows, and the aging
parents the men left behind have yet to see a penny of the $6.4
million earmarked for them. And tax rules may dictate that the
families can never receive all of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fund grew far beyond any expectations of what it might
be,'' said Thomas Cole, a Worcester Telegram &AMP; Gazette spokesman.
``I have to acknowledge that there's a possibility that the
families will not receive all of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper's charitable foundation is still filling seats on
a board that will distribute the funds, which they hope to begin
doing by September. The money is gathering interest in a bank.
</P>
<P>
   But Internal Revenue Service regulations essentially prohibit a
non-profit organization from making individuals wealthy. Because
there is so much money, some of it may have to be used for other
purposes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's millions of dollars and only six families, the IRS
is going to look at the amounts going to individuals,'' said Sally
Kaplan Levy, an attorney with the Boston office of McDermott, Will
&AMP; Emery. ``A rule of thumb suggests that if a family was paying for
a $300,000 house on a firefighter's salary, you can help them stay
in that home. But you can't help them move into a $1 million
home.''
</P>
<P>
   Another fund, set up by the Worcester firefighters' credit
union, received nearly 20,000 contributions and has already
distributed more than $2 million to the families. A Salvation Army
fund collected $171,000, which will soon be given to the families.
</P>
<P>
   ``The citizens of the city of Worcester have been great to the
families,'' said Frank Raffa, president of the local firefighter's
union. ``Our fund went off without a hitch. We divided it six equal
ways, which is what the families wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   What is different about the largest fund, set up by the Telegram
&AMP; Gazette, is that it has non-profit status that makes the 43,000
contribution it has received tax-deductible. According to Levy, the
IRS does not intend non-profit status for organizations that
benefit only a small group of individuals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hallmark of a tax exemption is that is has to benefit the
community in general,'' Levy said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the Telegram &AMP; Gazette's funds could be used for a
memorial or for the families of other Worcester firefighters who
die in the line of duty in the future, said Cole, as long as the
six families' short and long-term needs have been met.
</P>
<P>
   Cole defended the decision to open a fund for the families under
a non-profit umbrella, saying that many businesses would have been
unwilling or unable to make donations or contribute matching gifts
without it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tax deduction is a large factor in how much money was
raised. But it comes with certain responsibilities, and those are
difficult to meet,'' Cole said. ``We believe that we did the right
thing, and we would do it again.''
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper is meeting with lawyers, accountants and IRS
officials to figure out how to comply with the law, Cole said.
</P>
<P>
   The Worcester Telegram &AMP; Gazette is owned by the New York Times
Co., the parent company of the Boston Globe.
</P>
<P>
   Other funds have encountered similar difficulties. The
Denver-based Mile High United Way distributed $4.6 million after
the Columbine High School shootings. United Way spokeswoman Kelly
Cahill said that, after weighing the needs of victims and the
intentions of donors, $3 million went to victims and the remainder
went to community programs and services.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
