<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JERRY-RICE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     RICE'S AGENT PLANS HUDDLE WITH 49ERS STAFF 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JOHN CRUMPACKER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Jerry Rice's agent will meet with general
manager Bill Walsh in Santa Clara on Wednesday in what could be a
significant development toward keeping the wide receiver on the San
Francisco 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   Or not, according to Jim Steiner, the agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing really has developed yet,'' Steiner said. ``We've
received an offer from them which we're going to respond to next
week. We'll visit with Bill and discuss the situation in greater
detail.''
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers have made one- and two-year contract offers to
Steiner, both of which are designed to reduce Rice's salary cap
number for the 2000 season. At present he's due to count $5.49
million against the salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   Rice has said he wants to resolve his status with the 49ers by
next week, a time frame too optimistic for Steiner.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an easy task,'' Steiner said. ``Therefore, I think it
will take some detailed conversations. I don't have any
expectations to (reach an agreement) necessarily, but it doesn't
mean it won't happen. It will probably require more discussions
than next week, but not in a negative sense.''
</P>
<P>
   At last month's minicamp, an upbeat Rice said he was nearly all
the way back from his two 1997 knee surgeries and anticipated
returning to the 49ers this season. He led the club in receiving
last year with 67 catches for 830 yards and five touchdowns, well
below his usual standards but still better than anyone else on the
team.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
