<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5804 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      05-15 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     MOM KNOWS BEST, EVEN ABOUT TRUCKS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By TOM STIENSTRA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Mother always knows best, and that goes
especially with new 4-wheel-drive trucks and camping trips with
pals.
</P>
<P>
   This story started more than a year ago, when a friend of mine
named Darrell bought an expensive 4-wheel-drive pick-up truck. It
ended last week in what has become known as ``The Robby Saga,''
with a chain of events on a camp-out that provide a testimonial to
anyone that you best always listen to mama _ or disaster can
strike.
</P>
<P>
   You see, Darrell's new truck was gorgeous, powerful and
expensive, a deep emerald-green, chrome wheels, V8 and loaded
interior. But the family warning signs went on red alert by the way
his son, Robby, 22, was looking at it, like a quivering Doberman
staring up at a cat on a low tree limb, practically drooling and
teeth chattering.
</P>
<P>
   Darrell's wife, Nancy, spotted the look, and knew that trouble
was ahead. She was right, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Robby, who owned a 30-year-old 4-wheeler that wouldn't run, had
been getting around by driving a clunker of an old mini truck. But
hey, he could afford it. Then his imagination started to fly, the
idea of a new truck eating at him, and when a woman friend got in
financial trouble, he jumped at the chance at buying her mini
pick-up truck, nearly new, even though he was pretty much broke
himself.
</P>
<P>
   Mama, who didn't think this was a good idea to start with, also
didn't think this was a good idea to end with. ``Since it isn't a
4-wheel-drive, don't be asking to borrow Darrell's truck to go
camping with your friends.''
</P>
<P>
   This too started eating at Robby. Meanwhile, Darrell's truck was
still looking good. On a trip to Point Reyes last month, that truck
was still like a jewel, waxed and polished, so shiny it had a
mirror-like reflection. Robby started thinking about it, about how
the camping and adventure season was just starting, about how his
little mini truck just wouldn't do the job. But it would be perfect
if he could just have a full-size 4-wheel-drive to go camping with
his friends.
</P>
<P>
   At 20, he couldn't afford one. He knew his parents would object.
He knew that his mother, who knows best, would have a fit. But the
idea was being fed by a dream, of getting a truck just like
Darrell's, and two weeks ago, Robby found himself on automatic
pilot, driving to a car dealership with stars in his eyes. Before
he knew what was happening, he had signed the papers, had traded in
the mini pick-up, and was driving home in his brand new, full-size,
4-wheel drive pick-up, loaded, extended cab, custom painted a deep
metallic blue with silver panel, and would practically need to rob
banks to make the monthly payments.
</P>
<P>
   So one recent weekend, it was time to go camping with his
friends, of course. Watch out, said mom.
</P>
<P>
   Robby headed up to the Sierra Nevada with his pals, where they
knew a perfect little campsite along a stream, right next to a deep
hole, good for fishing. By the looks on his pal's faces, Robby had
the affirmation that his new truck was eye-popping beautiful, yet
powerful and tough, and would unlock adventures across the West. On
the way up to the mountains, they talked about how perfect the
truck was, and maybe taking a trip to Colorado later in the year.
</P>
<P>
   But then a funny thing happened.
</P>
<P>
   At that campsite, as Robby was explaining the virtues of owning
a brand new 4-wheel drive to his rapt audience, the truck started
to roll backwards, that is ``all by itself.'' Apparently it had
been left in neutral, and Robby jumped and ran toward the truck,
but gravity wins, you know, and there was nothing he could do as
4,500 pounds of metal kept rolling backwards down the hill, heading
toward the river.
</P>
<P>
   As the truck picked up speed, it pounded and crashed over
boulders, bushes and small trees. Over and over, the body was
dented and creased, the frame bunged in, the drive shaft, oil pan
and differentials hammered. Robby stood and watched. There were no
other sounds in the forest. The truck just kept pounding downhill,
right into the stream, right into a pool more than 4 feet deep. By
the time the truck came to a stop, water was flooding the interior
all the way up to the dashboard. The engine was completely
submerged.
</P>
<P>
   No problem, shouted his friends, we'll just tow it out!
</P>
<P>
   And sure enough, they were able to chain it up with another
4-wheel-drive, and slowly pulled that new truck out of the river.
</P>
<P>
   Well, the next morning, Robby woke up at camp and saw his truck,
all banged up, and decided it was time to go home. But hey, the
engine was brand new, so why not see if it will start?
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere in his conscience, his mother's voice was shouting,
``No! No! No!''
</P>
<P>
   But he turned the key anyway. In an instant, because water was
in the engine, it threw a rod, that is, the connecting rod between
a piston and crankshaft, or in other words, the engine blew up.
</P>
<P>
   When he finally returned home, getting towed all the way back,
the brand new pick-up truck was totaled, all just one day after his
first camping trip. One of the most expensive new 4-wheel-drives
out there was completely trashed, body, engine and interior
components.
</P>
<P>
   When the incident had to be explained, it reportedly started
with, ``Something happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Now this is a true story. The last names have not been included
to protect the guilty. Robby is now driving around in an junky
rental car, an old, beat-up Chevy Malibu, but it's cheap and it
runs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-00 2005EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
