<HEADER>
A5894 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKC-KNIGHT-BOS &LR;      05-15 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-KNIGHT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUMBLED KNIGHT GETS TO KEEP HIS JOB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The conversation with Bob Knight went on for an hour. Then two.
And then three. Through it all, Indiana University president Myles
Brand saw something in his basketball coach that he had not seen
previously: contrition and _ most importantly to Brand, who held
the fate of Knight in his hands _ sincerity.
</P>
<P>
   And that, perhaps as much as anything, is why Knight is still
the coach of the Hoosiers this morning.
</P>
<P>
   Brand, who met with Knight Saturday, announced the decision
Monday at a press conference in Indianapolis while also saying that
Knight was reprimanded, suspended, fined, and warned that the
behavior that prompted an extraordinary seven-week internal
investigation would no longer be tolerated.
</P>
<P>
   But Knight was not fired, contrary to widespread speculation in
the last few days.
</P>
<P>
   Brand outlined the following action taken by the university
against Knight, the basketball coach there for 29 seasons:
</P>
<P>
   --He is suspended for the first three games of the 2000-01
season.
</P>
<P>
   --He is to be fined $30,000, which will be taken out of his base
salary of $163,000.
</P>
<P>
   --He must apologize to several members of the athletic
department, whom he verbally or physically abused during the past
several years.
</P>
<P>
   --There will be a zero-tolerance policy for any further behavior
that is deemed inappropriate by a yet-to-be-selected panel.
</P>
<P>
   --Failure to follow the guidelines will result in dismissal.
</P>
<P>
   ``This behavior cannot and will not be tolerated at Indiana
University,'' said Brand.
</P>
<P>
   Going into Saturday's meeting, said Brand, his inclination was
to dismiss the coach for a series of vulgar acts and displays of
temper that were becoming more and more embarrassing to the
university. But when he heard the contrition in Knight's voice and
sensed a change in attitude, he decided to give Knight one last
chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never have seen him so contrite and apologetic,'' said
Brand. ``He made a pledge to me he would change his ways.''
</P>
<P>
   The investigation was triggered two months ago when former IU
player Neil Reed alleged that Knight had choked him during a
practice three years ago. A videotape subsequently surfaced that
backed up Reed, showing Knight grabbing the player by the throat.
</P>
<P>
   That triggered a firestorm of other stories and accusations,
which led to the internal investigation by the school's Board of
Trustees.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a lengthy pattern of troubling behavior by
Coach Knight,'' said Board of Trustee chairman John Walda, who said
29 people were interviewed during the probe. ``The trustees are
concerned about the reputation of this school. We will not tolerate
conduct from any persons who work for us that we consider to be
embarrassing or that does not live up to the high standards that we
expect from all who represent our university.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no scared cows at Indiana University, and that
certainly includes the basketball program.''
</P>
<P>
   Knight, who was not present at the press conference _ he
reportedly is on vacation in Scotland _ issued a statement that
said, ``I have absolutely no problem with the guidelines. I
recognize I have a problem with my temper.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Brand and Walda conceded that such warnings have not been
effective in controlling Knight, whom many perceive as being above
any code of conduct.
</P>
<P>
   Knight, who reportedly will submit to therapy to control his
anger, has developed a distinctive style of coaching over the past
three decades.
</P>
<P>
   On the plus side, it has produced 753 victories and three
national championships.
</P>
<P>
   It also has produced a series of incidents that range from
sarcasm with the media to verbal and physical abuse of those who
work for him and around him, including athletic director Clarence
Doninger.
</P>
<P>
   According to the IU officials, the action they are taking is
severe, the toughest policy the of any college in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Brand said that each incident individually was not considered a
cause for termination, but as a whole they revealed a disturbing
pattern.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he deserves a last chance,'' said Brand. ``And I think
he has a chance of pulling it off.''
</P>
<P>
   But can Knight, who is so used to running his program his way,
live within guidelines that could define every display of temper,
every sarcastic remark as a violation of the code of conduct?
</P>
<P>
   ``Judgments will be necessary,'' Brand conceded.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's made a commitment to change his behavior. Will he be able
to do it? Let's give him a chance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
