<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5820 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-WEB&AMP;MAGS-AZR &LR;      05-15 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEB&AMP;MAGS-AZR </SLUG>
  
BC-WEB&AMP;MAGS-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    WEB&AMP;MAGS(a) 
 &HT;    (Duplication warning: Moving in ``E'' and ``L'' categories) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By BILL MULLER(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are Bill Muller's reviews of a website and current
magazines:
</P>
<P>
   WEBSITE
</P>
<P>
   Jumptheshark (www.jumptheshark.com)
</P>
<P>
   Ever get into an argument at the dinner table about when a TV
show went bad? Like when Trapper John left ``MASH'' or George
Clooney split from ``ER''? Well, this Web site (which, for some
reason, calls such turning points ``Jumping the Shark'') will help
settle those questions, once and for all.
</P>
<P>
   Using polling, the site tries to pinpoint exactly when your
favorite TV shows headed south. The site features an alphabetical
list of shows, and also lists common plot points that often spell
doom: a character dying (like Edith on ``All in the Family''), a
young character hitting puberty (Kevin on ``The Wonder Years'') or
a character being replaced by a different actor (Dick Sargent for
Dick York on ``Bewitched'').
</P>
<P>
   There's also a list of shows that ``never jumped,'' that is,
they were good throughout their lives. They include ``The
Simpsons,'' ``The X-Files, `` ``The Bob Newhart Show'' and ``WKRP
in Cincinnati.''
</P>
<P>
   MAGAZINES
</P>
<P>
   ``ATLANTIC MONTHLY''
</P>
<P>
   Cover story makes the case that it's not girls who are ignored
and fall behind in school, but boys, who are trailing woefully in
academics. Facts seem to back up the premise, to wit, ``the typical
boy is a year and a half behind the typical girl in reading and
writing, he is less committed to school and less likely to go to
college.'' However, he is more likely to become a NASCAR driver. So
there. Story notes that two national images of gender emerged in
the last year: for girls, the sight of the U.S. women's soccer team
winning the World Cup; for boys, the grainy film from the Columbine
massacre. Also includes a terribly dull recounting of all the
digging into Abraham Lincoln's personal life. The story has you
waiting pages and pages for a payoff, which pretty much never
comes. However, the author does establish that Lincoln was our 16th
president. There is also a fascinating look into the Skull and
Bones, the Yale secret society that counted Texas Gov. George W.
Bush (and his dad) as members.
</P>
<P>
   ``BIOGRAPHY''
</P>
<P>
   The Kim Basinger onslaught continues, this time as the cover
girl of ``Biography,'' which has a decent piece about Basinger's
struggles to rise from a junior beauty queen from Athens, Ga., to a
major Hollywood star. Basinger succeeded in spite of suffering from
so-called ``panic attacks,'' which kept her paralyzed and homebound
for long periods. It also recalls Basinger's bankruptcy, brought on
by a suit filed after she backed out of a verbal agreement to star
in the macabre film ``Boxing Helena.'' Another interesting article
lets the readers choose the Top 10 onscreen couples, which is
headed by Bill Cosby and Phylicia Rashad, closely followed by Tom
Cruise and Nicole Kidman. The list is more remarkable for its
omissions. No Bogie and Bacall, nor Tracy and Hepburn, but Goldie
Hawn and Kurt Russell? I think even THEY(beginitalic)
(enditalic)got up and left in the middle of
``Overboard(beginitalic).''
</P>
<P>
   (enditalic)
</P>
<P>
   ``BOOK''
</P>
<P>
   Better grab this one up before it flies off the racks. After
all, it mentions the words Harry and Potter in the same sentence,
serving up an interesting piece on author J.K. Rowling, who struck
gold with the Harry Potter stories and is about to publish number
four (in July, tentatively titled ``Harry Potter and the Doomspell
Tournament''). Article notes that Rowling's success has attracted
both readers and non-readers alike, catapulting her to the top of
the bestseller lists, and to No.1 in our hearts. Or at least, most
of our hearts. There is also a sidebar warning that you shouldn't
read it if you don't want to know what happens to Harry. Strangely
enough, we don't. There is also a piece on Judith Krantz, who
churns out beach books like ``Princess Daisy''and
``Lovers(beginitalic).(enditalic)'' Interestingly, Krantz was 50
years old in 1978 when she hit it big with
``Scruples(beginitalic).(enditalic)'' A sample of Krantz's advice:
``A woman should get plastic surgery the minute she can see herself
starting to look like her mother.''
</P>
<P>
   ``NEW REPUBLIC''
</P>
<P>
   Fresh off the big win in Vermont, the magazine tells us that
``domestic partnership'' laws are not enough and that gay couples
should be able to get hitched like everybody else. ``Separate but
equal was a failed and pernicious policy with regard to race,'' the
author states, ``it will be a failed and pernicious policy with
regard to sexual orientation.'' Article also argues that marriage
is one of the most civil rights granted to Americans. Another story
notes that little has been done to punish the Khmer Rouge butchers
who perpetrated genocide between 1975 and 1979, but the current
Cambodian prime minister is trying to establish a special tribunal
to try some of the worst offenders. Meanwhile, former Khmer leaders
shop and tend their gardens. The weekly TRB column struggles to
evaluate the presidential timber of Texas Gov. George W. Bush and
Vice President Al Gore, with comparisons to former presidents from
Franklin D. Roosevelt to Bill Clinton. The result? A real sinking
feeling that we're in deeeep trouble.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-00 2006EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000515.0281 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5823 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-BOOMER-WOMEN-AZR &LR;      05-15 1874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOMER-WOMEN-AZR </SLUG>
  
 BC-SLUG-BOOMER-WOMEN-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    BABY BOOMER WOMEN RETURN TO BATTLE(a) 
 &HT;    (Duplication warning: Moving in ``A,'' ``L,'' and ``K''
categories) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By MAUREEN WEST(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (EDITORS {ndash} INFORMATION FOR A ``BOX'' OR SHORT SIDEBAR IS
AT THE END OF THIS STORY) A generation of women born into
affluence, liberated by the pill and empowered by the fight against
gender bias will not go quietly into old age.
</P>
<P>
   Baby Boomer women, born 1946-64, are reaching the edge of
retirement but, to say the least, are un-retiring in attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to be nasty. We aren't going to be submissive
about this,'' said Sue Reynolds-Scanlon, 55, describing how women
of her generation now face age discrimination in the workplace and
skimpy services for health care and elder care.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds-Scanlon is a researcher at the University of South
Florida who studies aging. She speaks for the first wave of the 40
million-strong pre-retirement Baby Boomer women who find themselves
responsible for the care of parents and worried about the prospects
for their own health care. They are becoming radicalized to push
for government programs that will help them as they age.
</P>
<P>
   Trained in a working world to network, organize and carefully
Daytimer their agendas, this generation of women is preparing to
body-slam the political establishment at the polls. Recognition of
this emerging voting bloc has in recent months stopped many
politicians from openly advocating ideas like privatizing Social
Security or cutting Medicare benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Women account for 80 percent of the 23 million Americans who
care for the elderly. A study by the National Alliance for
Caregiving and the American Association of Retired Persons found
that nearly one-third of caregivers must significantly curtail
their hard-won careers by taking leaves of absence, reducing job
hours, turning down promotions, retiring early or even quitting in
midcareer.
</P>
<P>
   These personal sacrifices, made for lack of care options, are
fueling the women's political determination.
</P>
<P>
   Locally and nationally, women are forming political alliances to
push for better elder care, said Roselyn O'Connell of Phoenix,
president of the National Women's Political Caucus. Many women are
radicalized by the difficulty they have in getting help for their
aging parents, she said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connell's group, which in the past pushed for federal funds
for child day care, now is focused on increasing federal funds for
``dependent care,'' and other women's groups are following suit.
</P>
<P>
   In Phoenix, a group of 30 women in their 40s and 50s recently
formed a health coalition, Healthy Women for a Lifetime, to lobby
health maintenance organizations for preventive treatment for
osteoporosis, heart disease and depression.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are also watching to make sure that Social Security will be
preserved, now that so many of us are closer to needing it,'' said
O'Connell, who is 55. In a recent National Public Radio broadcast,
O'Connell encouraged midlife women to seize political power. It's
hard to marginalize 40 million older women if they vote, she
contends.
</P>
<P>
   The Boomers' leading edge, those born from 1946 to 1955, is the
most politically active group of the tidal wave generation. Along
with women now 55 to 65, they changed women's status in the
workplace.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Bogre, 47, saw her own latent activism kick in after
her mother died in a Phoenix care home. Bogre believes her mother
was the victim of neglect.
</P>
<P>
   She pushed the state attorney general to investigate the case,
prosecute and convict the home operator. But she didn't like the
way the judicial system handled the case, and she wants to be part
of the solution.
</P>
<P>
   Bogre, director of photography at the prestigious Parsons School
of Design in New York, is going back to school to study elder law.
</P>
<P>
   Bogre agrees that there is a take-no-prisoners political mood
brewing among women. ``My generation is not going to disappear like
women of my mother's generation did,'' she said. ``And I don't
think I'll be less confrontational at 70 than I am now at 47.''
</P>
<P>
   Boomer women learned in their youth how to talk comfortably and
openly about their common problems and how to work in groups to
make changes, says Marilyn Powers, a Valley Phoenix psychologist
and author of a book published last year on midlife,
(beginitalic)Bridge Between Two Lifetimes(enditalic).
</P>
<P>
   The idea of radical, experimental change appeals to visionaries,
Powers said, and the Boomer generation has plenty of them.
</P>
<P>
   Powers argues that the Boomer women not only will reshape
politics by ``dropping in,'' but they may reshape corporate life by
``dropping out'' and forming organizations or business partnerships
to serve their needs.
</P>
<P>
   As a group, women Boomers are highly educated. Half the women of
retirement age in 2020 will have a college education.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women feel more powerful than earlier generations,'' said
Vicky Drake, 51, a member of the new women's health coalition,
Healthy Women for a Lifetime. ``We have been working women all of
our adult lives. We are better informed and we ask questions and
insist on answers.''
</P>
<P>
   Drake watched her mother become frail and eventually need
nursing-home care because of osteoporosis. Last year, at 50, Drake
was diagnosed with the bone-weakening disease herself. ``Almost
everyone I know is dealing with something or themselves or their
parents.''
</P>
<P>
   Drake is aggressively battling the disease through medication
and an extensive exercise regimen. As a result, she is optimistic
her older years will be better than her mother's. But she wants
other women to have the chance to be healthier, too, which is why
she is active in the Healthy Women group.
</P>
<P>
   Bogre, Drake and other midlife women are talking more openly
about the lack of employer- and government-sponsored support
programs, such as time off for care-giving.
</P>
<P>
   Of interest to political candidates: a growing number of midlife
women not only want Medicare and Social Security programs to be
preserved, they want them expanded.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have got to take this budget surplus, and this
extraordinary excess of revenue in our society and decide how to
provide better care for elders,'' Bogre said.
</P>
<P>
   The mood in Washington is changing quickly, according to Larry
Polivka, elder issues expert and director of the Florida Policy
Exchange Center on Aging at the University of South Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of trimming Medicare, it's likely that Congress will
expand the program to include a prescription drug benefit. Last
year, a $1,000 tax credit for caregivers passed,'' Polivka said.
``This year, there is talk about pushing it up to $3,000. The next
step may be paying family caregivers.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he concedes that some of these changes can be chalked
up to election-year promises, the tide has changed in favor of
larger government as assistance in elder care and health.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each year, as more Baby Boomers and their parents age, you are
going to see more demand for Social Security and Medicare
programs,'' Polivka said. ``The window is closing for trimming back
benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Who would have forecast that Medicare would add anything this
year?'' he said, pointing to the prescription drug benefit.
</P>
<P>
   Not only are Baby Boomers starting to have their own health
problems, two-thirds of women between 40 and 50 expect to be
responsible for an elderly relative or parents in the next 10
years, according to the National Alliance for Caregiving.
</P>
<P>
   Although married Baby Boomers are expected to be better off than
their parents in retirement, that is not the case with single
women. The number of midlife women who are divorced, never married
or childless is at a record high.
</P>
<P>
   As a group, they may need to rely more on public programs, says
Reynolds-Scanlon, who is specializing in Baby Boomers in her
research on aging.
</P>
<P>
   Although most Boomer women work outside the home, on average
they make only 74cents for every dollar a man makes. Their personal
pension plans are slim or non-existent because their jobs may have
been spotty, temporary, or simply low-paying.
</P>
<P>
   Many stepped away from work to raise children, which decreases
the amount of Social Security they receive. Less than half of
divorced, separated or widowed Baby Boomers own homes.
</P>
<P>
   The common need for housing and assistance may bring back
another institution from their young days in the 1960s: the
commune, at least in some form.
</P>
<P>
   Many women Boomers, not wanting to go to an elder care facility
like their parents, are talking with friends and relatives about
living together. Drake already lives with her twin sister and
brother-in-law, and they are talking with other family members
about forming a family compound for their old age.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Daniels of Washington, D.C., deputy director of the Social
Security disability program, plans to live with her sister and
cousin.
</P>
<P>
   The politics is thrilling, too; a return to the energies and
values of youth.
</P>
<P>
   Sherry Bell, 54, of Sedona, is thrilled that her activist
spirit, dormant for a long time, is being activated again. She cut
her political teeth years ago fighting racism and sexism. Then the
needs of her work took over her life. Her present involvement grew
out of her experience as a caregiver for her mother, who has
Alzheimer's disease.
</P>
<P>
   Bell plans to be among the women who will be fighting for
changes in public policy. ``Being out here (on the front lines)
again feels good,'' she says. ``It has been much too long.''
</P>
<P>
   By 2020, it's expected that Boomers will be talking about death
as much as they did in the 1960s about sex.
</P>
<P>
   Brigit Wilson, 47, a geriatric nurse from Omaha, Neb., and some
of her friends are already discussing end-of-life rituals or
parties they want to have some day. Boomers to the end, they refuse
to die without ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you see on TV the hot new funeral fads, you will know we
are there,'' Reynolds-Scanlon said.
</P>
<P>
   INFORMATION BOX BELOW ----
</P>
<P>
   Facts about Baby Boomers.
</P>
<P>
   BOOMER FACTS
</P>
<P>
   --It's the Baby Boom because 20 million extra kids were born
than were expected over a 19-year period, 1946-64. The peak year
for births was 1957, when 4.3 million children were born. During
the peak years of the Baby Boom, the typical family had four
children in quick succession.
</P>
<P>
   --Baby Boomers' motto is ``question authority.''
</P>
<P>
   -- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although married Boomers will have greater assets, pensions and
income than their parents had in retirement, there are more
unmarried and childless women at midlife than their parents'
generation. They could need more social services. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Boomers' family trees are looking more like beanpoles than
pyramids. Aging Baby Boomers have record-low numbers of children
and record-high numbers of living brothers and sisters. They have
more step and half kin due to higher rates of divorce and
remarriage. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Among the 76 million Baby Boomers, there are generational
differences. The leading edge Baby Boomers, those born 1946-1955,
are the social activists. The rear group, 1956-1964, are the
Yuppies.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Source: Sue Reynolds-Scanlon, University o N/NZfQ
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-00 2006EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000515.0282 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5824 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k BC-TVNEWS-AZR &LR;      05-15 1319
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TVNEWS-AZR </SLUG>
  
 BC-TVNEWS-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    TV NEWS STRAYS FROM MISSION(a) 
 &HT;    (Duplication warning: MOVING IN ``A'' and ``K'' categories.(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By RICH ROBERTSON(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 Special for The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX {ndash} (EDITORS {ndash} SHORT SIDEBAR AT END OF THIS
ARTICLE) When I told my television station's news director a few
months ago that I intended to end nearly 30 years in print and
broadcast journalism, I borrowed a line from a former British
minister's resignation letter. I said I wanted to spend more time
with my principles.
</P>
<P>
   I don't think he understood. How could anyone walk away from a
job that many people would kill to have?
</P>
<P>
   Pay and benefits were certainly not an issue. And I thoroughly
enjoyed and admired the people I worked with. The public
recognition was nice, too.
</P>
<P>
   But somewhere along the line, journalism's values (or, more
accurately, what journalism values) had diverged from mine.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not alone. A new study by the Pew Research Center for People
and the Press found that four in 10 journalists, both print and
broadcast, now admit to working in an environment that increasingly
asks them to avoid ``newsworthy'' stories to benefit the financial
interests of their ``news'' organizations. These journalists
believe market pressures are pushing them toward the salacious and
sensational and away from the complicated and important.
</P>
<P>
   I was among the four in 10 journalists.
</P>
<P>
   I began feeling I was doing a disservice to the TV audience by
telling them only what was happening rather than why. I felt it was
unfair to compress complex subjects into a few breathless seconds
or inches. I was embarrassed when my stories were so often
oversold, or just wrong, in ``promos'' and ``teases.'' I was
frustrated that news is defined as being whatever is urgent rather
than what is ``important.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Breaking news'' becomes the most important news, even if
there's no news to report.
</P>
<P>
   I cringed that every story had to be ``shocking'' or some kind
of superlative, even if it wasn't: ``a parent's worst nightmare,''
``a story you must see,'' ``an exclusive interview'' (with someone
who is constantly being interviewed).
</P>
<P>
   I once suggested to a news manager that we program the Alt-H
keys on the computer keyboard to automatically insert hype into
every story.
</P>
<P>
   Television, in particular, is increasingly in the business of
marketing itself, not the news. The primary criterion is that a
story be promotable. In fact, story promos usually get more air
time than the stories themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Putting out a competent, useful news product isn't the goal. The
only goal is to have the largest viewer- or readership.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, criticisms I'd dismissed for years - ``You're only doing
this to sell more newspapers or get higher ratings'' - are now
coming true.
</P>
<P>
   For example, I was heartened one morning a while back to hear a
group of news managers discuss doing a story about the local
fallout of the Asian economic crisis. The electronics industry, in
particular, could be affected, leading to lost jobs and distressed
families. It was an important local story.
</P>
<P>
   But the discussion fell silent when one producer asked, ``How do
we avoid the glaze factor?'' Those are the code words for ``It's
boring.'' Everyone looked at each other and shrugged.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, how about the double murder?'' someone else offered.
They were off and running.
</P>
<P>
   I've always known that news is a business. You have to have
readers and viewers to be able to attract advertisers who pay the
bills, including your salary. But we tried to separate ourselves by
saying that if we do good journalism, readers and viewers and
therefore advertisers will come.
</P>
<P>
   That is no longer true. Now, journalists are forced to pander to
the same gawker reflex that causes traffic to snarl near car
wrecks. We want viewers and readers to slow down to see us, so we
give them a whole bunch of car wrecks and other forms of mayhem.
</P>
<P>
   Now, stories are ``tested'' with random phone calls asking
people if they'd prefer a story about ``Deadly Germs on Your
Child's Playground Equipment'' to ``Welfare Policies and the
Poor.'' Public policy always loses in that kind of analysis.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't just television. Newspapers, radio and Web-based news
services are suffering from many of the same pressures cited in the
Pew Center study.
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers have pared their staffs or shifted them away from
fulfilling a socially critical but apparently financially
unprofitable role of public watchdog.
</P>
<P>
   Not too many years ago, there were full-time reporters from at
least three different news organizations covering the Maricopa
County courts, Phoenix City Hall and the city's police department.
Today, only two of those beats have full-time print reporters. In
their place is a cadre of government-paid information officers.
News organizations simply publish or air what they're told by the
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   As the pressures increase, journalists, both individually and
organizationally, have little time to think, let alone be
thoughtful.
</P>
<P>
   Get on the air or in print. Move on to the next story.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not suggesting that all news shows become the Bloomberg
Report or be like demolition derby. Somewhere, there's a balance.
</P>
<P>
   Do the crime/accident story, but don't bludgeon it with ``team
coverage'' and reaction sound bites from people who always say they
are shocked it happened in their quiet neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Give the headlines so that viewers and readers have a sense of
what's happening in their community, but devote time to the
important topics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Important'' is more difficult. It's hard to take pictures of
it; it's harder to understand and then explain it. And it's hardest
of all to make it compelling. But that's what professional
journalists are supposed to be able to do.
</P>
<P>
   It won't happen unless media companies commit to it. Not
abdicate it.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Rich Robertson is a former city editor and investigations team
leader for The Arizona Republic and investigative reporter for
Channel 5 (KPHO) and Channel 12 (KPNX) in Phoenix. He is now owner
of Robertson Investigations and Consulting in Phoenix. He can be
reached via e-mail at rich(a)rrrobertson.com.)
</P>
<P>
   SIDEBAR:
</P>
<P>
   By Rich Robertson
</P>
<P>
   Special for The Arizona Republic
</P>
<P>
   Nielsen Media Research, the firm that measures television
viewership, has the power to change American politics. It could do
it by moving the November ratings period to October.
</P>
<P>
   Here's why:
</P>
<P>
   There are four months in the year (February, May, July and
November) when the numbers of television viewers are counted, both
electronically and on paper journals. The results determine how
much stations can charge for advertising.
</P>
<P>
   So, news managers do what they can to attract the most viewers
during those so-called ``sweeps'' months. That's when you hear
television stories promoted on the radio; that's when billboards
spring up featuring perfectly manicured anchors, and that's when
some stations give away money.
</P>
<P>
   Planning for sweeps starts several months ahead of time.
Production of sweeps pieces is done during the month before they
air.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for democracy, elections are the first Tuesday in
November. There are three more weeks of sweeps after Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   Broadcasters are so busy during October handling ``daily''
mayhem and preparing stories for sweeps pieces for November that
they don't have time to do election stories, too.
</P>
<P>
   But, if the ratings period was October (ending, say, on the
first Tuesday in November), television stations would have a strong
incentive to work diligently during September to prepare
thoughtful, insightful, analytical, comprehensive profiles of
candidates and issues.
</P>
<P>
   And they could put up billboards bragging that their anchors are
the only ones in town who have actually heard of the candidates.
</P>
</TEXT>
