<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5897 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w BC-CLINTON-FINANCES-BOS &LR;      05-15 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-FINANCES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON DISCLOSES FINANCES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton's friends were generous with him
last year, but his foes continued to cost him money.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton accepted $23,602 worth of gifts in 1999, many of them
related to his favorite pasttime _ playing golf. He also accepted
$2.25 million to defray exhorbitant legal fees stemming from the
Monica S. Lewinsky episode, according to his annual financial
disclosure form released Monday by the White House.
</P>
<P>
   But with less than one year left in office, the president is
still in tremendous debt. Clinton reported carrying between $2.35
million and $10.75 million in liabilities, all of it in legal fees.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the four law firms listed _ Williams &AMP; Connolly, and
Skader, Arps, Slater, Meagher &AMP; Flom _ are each owed between $2
million and $5 million.
</P>
<P>
   The form requires only a range of figures rather than exact
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Clinton reported assets of $1.2 million to $5.57
million for 1998, the biggest chunk coming from a blind trust in
First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton's name. Those figures were
roughly the same as they were for 1997, but higher than the range
of $760,000 to $1.7 million reported for 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The president has between $1,001 and $15,000 in a local checking
account, this latest statement showed. Other non-earned income
assets include stock in AT&AMP;T, State Street Corp., Lucent Technology
and Bell Atlantic, worth between $33,005 and $145,000. But unlike
those Americans who have become wealthy investing in the ``new
economy'' Clinton lauds, the president garnered between just $402
and $2,600 in dividends.
</P>
<P>
   The president also holds between $1.15 million and $1.35 million
in three blind trusts _ healthy amounts, but still not enough to
pay off his legal bills.
</P>
<P>
   Among gifts the president accepted are a set of J.P. Tod bags,
given by Diego Della Valle of Milan, Italy, and valued at $2,750; a
$500 saxophone given by Pedro Ruiz of San Sebastian De Los Reyes,
Spain, and a man's suit, valued at $2,500 and given by Arnold H.
Simon of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Several fans of the president played to Clinton's widely known
affection for golf, contributing a total of $2,902 worth of golf
clubs and golf paraphernalia.
</P>
<P>
   Other presidential presents given last year were a burgundy sofa
($1,088), crystal ($1,215), a cashmere sweater set and tie ($900),
a Mont Blanc pen ($450), an antique Edison phonograph and two
musical cylinders ($650), a wooden Hano Mana doll ($1,000), a
framed Alfred Eisenstaedt photograph ($500), and a cashmere throw
($1,350).
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also accepted pottery ($1,550), a CD collection ($297),
silk ties and two handkerchiefs ($890), cuff links and a book
($1,515), a 1956 ``High Noon'' playbill ($700), a Harley Davidson
leather jacket ($320), a silver Tzedakah box ($650), a coat ($800),
a bronze relief of President Abraham Lincoln, a book on President
Franklin D. Roosevelt, and an antique book, ``Transatlantic
Sketches,'' which was listed as being worth $1,075.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Vice President Al Gore was unburdened by either
Clinton's legal debts or the breadth of generosity that came the
president's way.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from his $175,400-a-year salary, Gore reported a house in
Arlington, Va., and a home, farm and property in Carthage, Tenn.,
worth between $650,004 and $1,350,000. The farm is leased, drawing
$2,420 in gross income.
</P>
<P>
   Gore took in $20,000 in royalties from a mineral lease, and
$16,457 in royalties in his book, ``Earth in the Balance.'' Mrs.
Tipper Gore is listed as a shareholder in Aitchenson Real Estate
Inc., of Arlington, Va. Her asserts from that interest are between
$100,001 and $250,000, Gore's financial disclosure statement said.
</P>
<P>
   Other assets include between $32,004 and $131,000 in local bank
accounts, as well as between $500,001 and $1 million in Occidental
Petroleum stock. The stock is listed as being part of the estate of
Gore's late father, Albert Gore Sr.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's children also have their own assets: Albert Gore III has
between $50,002 and $115,000 in the bank. Sarah Gore has between
$3,003 and $45,000 in bank accounts, and Kristin Gore is listed as
owning between $1,001 and $15,000 in cash accounts.
</P>
<P>
   The only present the vice president listed was $1,550 in legal
time donated by longtime friend James Neal of Nashville, Tenn. The
Gores' only liabilities are home loans and personal credit,
totaling $250,003 and $600,000. Gore does not list any
campaign-related liabilities.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Ann Scales of the Globe staff contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-00 2006EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000515.0284 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5825 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-TVNEWS-AZR &LR;      05-15 1319
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TVNEWS-AZR </SLUG>
  
 BC-TVNEWS-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    TV NEWS STRAYS FROM MISSION(a) 
 &HT;    (Duplication warning: MOVING IN ``A'' and ``K'' categories.(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By RICH ROBERTSON(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 Special for The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX {ndash} (EDITORS {ndash} SHORT SIDEBAR AT END OF THIS
ARTICLE) When I told my television station's news director a few
months ago that I intended to end nearly 30 years in print and
broadcast journalism, I borrowed a line from a former British
minister's resignation letter. I said I wanted to spend more time
with my principles.
</P>
<P>
   I don't think he understood. How could anyone walk away from a
job that many people would kill to have?
</P>
<P>
   Pay and benefits were certainly not an issue. And I thoroughly
enjoyed and admired the people I worked with. The public
recognition was nice, too.
</P>
<P>
   But somewhere along the line, journalism's values (or, more
accurately, what journalism values) had diverged from mine.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not alone. A new study by the Pew Research Center for People
and the Press found that four in 10 journalists, both print and
broadcast, now admit to working in an environment that increasingly
asks them to avoid ``newsworthy'' stories to benefit the financial
interests of their ``news'' organizations. These journalists
believe market pressures are pushing them toward the salacious and
sensational and away from the complicated and important.
</P>
<P>
   I was among the four in 10 journalists.
</P>
<P>
   I began feeling I was doing a disservice to the TV audience by
telling them only what was happening rather than why. I felt it was
unfair to compress complex subjects into a few breathless seconds
or inches. I was embarrassed when my stories were so often
oversold, or just wrong, in ``promos'' and ``teases.'' I was
frustrated that news is defined as being whatever is urgent rather
than what is ``important.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Breaking news'' becomes the most important news, even if
there's no news to report.
</P>
<P>
   I cringed that every story had to be ``shocking'' or some kind
of superlative, even if it wasn't: ``a parent's worst nightmare,''
``a story you must see,'' ``an exclusive interview'' (with someone
who is constantly being interviewed).
</P>
<P>
   I once suggested to a news manager that we program the Alt-H
keys on the computer keyboard to automatically insert hype into
every story.
</P>
<P>
   Television, in particular, is increasingly in the business of
marketing itself, not the news. The primary criterion is that a
story be promotable. In fact, story promos usually get more air
time than the stories themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Putting out a competent, useful news product isn't the goal. The
only goal is to have the largest viewer- or readership.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, criticisms I'd dismissed for years - ``You're only doing
this to sell more newspapers or get higher ratings'' - are now
coming true.
</P>
<P>
   For example, I was heartened one morning a while back to hear a
group of news managers discuss doing a story about the local
fallout of the Asian economic crisis. The electronics industry, in
particular, could be affected, leading to lost jobs and distressed
families. It was an important local story.
</P>
<P>
   But the discussion fell silent when one producer asked, ``How do
we avoid the glaze factor?'' Those are the code words for ``It's
boring.'' Everyone looked at each other and shrugged.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, how about the double murder?'' someone else offered.
They were off and running.
</P>
<P>
   I've always known that news is a business. You have to have
readers and viewers to be able to attract advertisers who pay the
bills, including your salary. But we tried to separate ourselves by
saying that if we do good journalism, readers and viewers and
therefore advertisers will come.
</P>
<P>
   That is no longer true. Now, journalists are forced to pander to
the same gawker reflex that causes traffic to snarl near car
wrecks. We want viewers and readers to slow down to see us, so we
give them a whole bunch of car wrecks and other forms of mayhem.
</P>
<P>
   Now, stories are ``tested'' with random phone calls asking
people if they'd prefer a story about ``Deadly Germs on Your
Child's Playground Equipment'' to ``Welfare Policies and the
Poor.'' Public policy always loses in that kind of analysis.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't just television. Newspapers, radio and Web-based news
services are suffering from many of the same pressures cited in the
Pew Center study.
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers have pared their staffs or shifted them away from
fulfilling a socially critical but apparently financially
unprofitable role of public watchdog.
</P>
<P>
   Not too many years ago, there were full-time reporters from at
least three different news organizations covering the Maricopa
County courts, Phoenix City Hall and the city's police department.
Today, only two of those beats have full-time print reporters. In
their place is a cadre of government-paid information officers.
News organizations simply publish or air what they're told by the
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   As the pressures increase, journalists, both individually and
organizationally, have little time to think, let alone be
thoughtful.
</P>
<P>
   Get on the air or in print. Move on to the next story.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not suggesting that all news shows become the Bloomberg
Report or be like demolition derby. Somewhere, there's a balance.
</P>
<P>
   Do the crime/accident story, but don't bludgeon it with ``team
coverage'' and reaction sound bites from people who always say they
are shocked it happened in their quiet neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Give the headlines so that viewers and readers have a sense of
what's happening in their community, but devote time to the
important topics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Important'' is more difficult. It's hard to take pictures of
it; it's harder to understand and then explain it. And it's hardest
of all to make it compelling. But that's what professional
journalists are supposed to be able to do.
</P>
<P>
   It won't happen unless media companies commit to it. Not
abdicate it.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Rich Robertson is a former city editor and investigations team
leader for The Arizona Republic and investigative reporter for
Channel 5 (KPHO) and Channel 12 (KPNX) in Phoenix. He is now owner
of Robertson Investigations and Consulting in Phoenix. He can be
reached via e-mail at rich(a)rrrobertson.com.)
</P>
<P>
   SIDEBAR:
</P>
<P>
   By Rich Robertson
</P>
<P>
   Special for The Arizona Republic
</P>
<P>
   Nielsen Media Research, the firm that measures television
viewership, has the power to change American politics. It could do
it by moving the November ratings period to October.
</P>
<P>
   Here's why:
</P>
<P>
   There are four months in the year (February, May, July and
November) when the numbers of television viewers are counted, both
electronically and on paper journals. The results determine how
much stations can charge for advertising.
</P>
<P>
   So, news managers do what they can to attract the most viewers
during those so-called ``sweeps'' months. That's when you hear
television stories promoted on the radio; that's when billboards
spring up featuring perfectly manicured anchors, and that's when
some stations give away money.
</P>
<P>
   Planning for sweeps starts several months ahead of time.
Production of sweeps pieces is done during the month before they
air.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for democracy, elections are the first Tuesday in
November. There are three more weeks of sweeps after Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   Broadcasters are so busy during October handling ``daily''
mayhem and preparing stories for sweeps pieces for November that
they don't have time to do election stories, too.
</P>
<P>
   But, if the ratings period was October (ending, say, on the
first Tuesday in November), television stations would have a strong
incentive to work diligently during September to prepare
thoughtful, insightful, analytical, comprehensive profiles of
candidates and issues.
</P>
<P>
   And they could put up billboards bragging that their anchors are
the only ones in town who have actually heard of the candidates.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-00 2006EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
