<DOCNO> NYT20000515.0287 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5830 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-ALLEN-FEATURE-LADN &LR;      05-15 1605
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALLEN-FEATURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S ALL IN THE PERSPECTIVE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROB LOWMAN 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Woody Allen is talking about how he had contemplated becoming a
criminal before he turned to comedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think I'm being facetious when I say I had toyed with
the fact of a life of crime... At first I had thought about going
into law enforcement but (in those days) there were height
requirements. So then I turned to the idea of being a crook where
there were no height requirements.''
</P>
<P>
   The riff sounds a lot like something from the stand-up comedian
Allen of the '60s. But instead of a coffeehouse, the Oscar-winning
director was in town last week to offer some lessons and warnings
about the filmmaking business to an audience of students and others
at UCLA's Wadsworth Theatre. He also screened his new film, aptly
titled ``Small Time Crooks.''
</P>
<P>
   The film is the tale of an ex-con dishwasher (Ray Winkler,
played by Allen) in New York City who has a scheme to rob a bank
and get enough money so he and his manicurist wife, Frenchy,
(Tracey Ulman) can move to Florida in luxury. The plot is
reminiscent of Allen's first directorial achievement, the 1969 film
``Take the Money and Run,'' where he played an inept compulsive
criminal named Virgil Starkwell.
</P>
<P>
   When it's suggested that Ray is Virgil aged gracefully, Allen
responds, ``I have aged gracefully. I look good (audience laughs).
!ital!I do.!'' he insists, sounding again like one of his
characters. ``I'll be 65 in December. My father will be 100 this
year. We have youthful genes. I have no face work whatsoever. I
have good energy.'' Then he gets down to business, talking about
filmmaking. ``Take the Money and Run'' was made my a young person
and operates by gag by gag by gag, and fortunately there were
enough gags to keep the film afloat. ``Small Time Crooks'' is a
film that operates on character, and the characters are suppose to
be funny so you don't have to go on a frenetic surrealistic pace
all the time.'' Adding that ``it's a film by a more competant
gracefully aged filmmaker.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Small Time Crooks'' is Allen's 31st film (he makes about one a
year) and is being distributed by DreamWorks Pictures. The film is
lighter fare than Allen has turned out in recent years, most of
which have drawn critical praise but little at the box office. Best
known for ``Annie Hall,'' which took four Oscars, including Best
Picture, Allen has had few real hits since. His 1986 ``Hannah and
Her Sisters'' being a notable exception. He picked up a
screenwriting Oscar for that one, and Dianne Weist and Michael
Caine won best supporting acting awards.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, ``Celebrity'' with a post ``Titanic'' Leonardo DiCaprio
took in only $5 million, and last year's ``Sweet and Lowdown'' made
$4.5 million despite Oscar nominations for stars Sean Penn and
Samantha Morton.
</P>
<P>
   But this doesn't seem to bother Allen, whose films are low
budget and eventually make a profit when the overseas box office
and video are factored in. He admits that some people see his films
as being the same (``Oh, another Woody Allen movie''). For him,
they're all different _ murder mysteries, musicals, comedies,
dramas _ but other ``feel there's a sameness to them, the way one
could say there are 500 different Chinese dishes, but it's all
Chinese food.''
</P>
<P>
   For Allen making movies is about ``trying to make art head on.''
And awards don't mean anything. Though being a 22-time Oscar
nominee and four-time winner he's never attended the Academy
Awards.(``I don't believe in competition among !ital!alleged works
of art.'') Ultimately, he says, he wants to please himself. His
first screenplay was the 1965 film ``What's New Pussycat,'' the
Hollywood process soured him and he vowed never to go that route
again.
</P>
<P>
   But making a film, he tells the audience of perspective
filmmakers in a question and answer session, is no picnic for him.
(``I'm in trouble almost all the time on films.'')
</P>
<P>
   First, there's the writing. He says that inspiration can come
from anywhere, and if he has no inspiration he'll sit in a room and
think for hours. ``I use to write for television and that's the way
you had to do it because the show had to go on and eventually
something comes up.''
</P>
<P>
   But he quickly warns that you can get a million ideas that sound
good but 50 pages down the line you're stuck. ``It's very important
for me to see where the thing goes before I write it; otherwise you
end up with a charming idea that just runs out of gas.''
</P>
<P>
   So it's suggested that shooting the film would be more fun.
Allen looks slightly aghast. ``Making a film. That's not fun,
either. Making it, you're out there at six in the morning, and it's
freezing and everyone is saying hurry up, hurry up it's costing us
money, and the actor or actress is late to the set, and jokes
aren't working and the sun is in the wrong position and the
cameraman is having a tantrum. This'' he stresses, ``is not fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Then what about the post-production process?
</P>
<P>
   ``Editing is fun until you get your first cut ... then it's like
taking a cold shower,'' he says. ``You look at your first cut, and
you realize how god awful your work is really going to be and
there's no way out of it....''
</P>
<P>
   He then goes on to describe what must be the dream and reality
of many a filmmaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I start a film ... I'm thinking that this film will be so
much greater than the `Bicycle Thief,' so much greater than `Grand
Illusion' that the world will finally realize what an intense, deep
genius I am. Then when I see that first cut of the film, I'm
thinking, `God, just let me survive.' I'll do anything. I'll take
the end of the film and put it at the front.... I'll dub voices.
I'll do anything so I won't suffer a catastrophic embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that's the gamble,'' he warns the aspiring filmmakers in
the audience.``It's very rare that you have a pleasurable
experience. Just so you know. In case you want to change your
major.''
</P>
<P>
   As for working with actors, Allen finds that a more pleasuable
experience, and despite the low budgets on his film, the Hollywood
elite are happy to take part. Besides, DiCaprio, Penn and Caine,
Julia Roberts Hugh Grant, Drew Barrymore, Tracey Ullman and Kenneth
Branagh have all appeared in Allen films.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really pay a very low amount, shockingly low. Everybody
that works, whether it's Julia Roberts or Sean Penn or whoever it
is gets the same $5,000 a week. Whether they get $10 million on
another picture, they get $50,000 for our picture, and that's our
top.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen says he gives the script to the actors and get their
input. ``I tell them they can make changes as long as they make the
scene happen believably.... If they screw up I correct them, but
more often than not I'm working with first-rate actors and they do
a great job, better than I could do, and in the end I get the
credit for it.'' Dressed in a sweater and slacks, Allen appeared
very much like he does in his films, which raised another question
that vexes the filmmaker: That his onscreen persona is him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't me though,'' Allen insists. ``I've been knocking at
doors for 30 years telling people that.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen says that the confusion over his onscreen characters and
offscreen life stem from the fact that he looks the same. Unlike
Charlie Chaplin, Buster Keaton, W.C. Fields or Groucho Marx who had
onscreen characters different from their offscreen lives, ``I wear
the same clothes off screen as I do on screen. And I looked like
the same character in my real life as I do on screen. But I'm not
the same character.
</P>
<P>
   ``In really life I'm very competant, I'm very disciplined, hard
working and resonably calm. In movies I'm frenetic, I'm
hyper-neurotic and involved in extreme situations that never happen
to me in my real life.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Allen's life has been the subject of tabloids. His
scandalous relationship in 1992 with Soon-Yi Previn, his then 18
years old adopted daughter and the subsequent combative breakup
with actress Mia Farrow made him a villian in some people's eyes.
But today, the controversy has lost its sting, and no one in the
audience brought it up. A couple of women even thanked his for
making films that showed women in a real way, citing his 1988 film
``Another Woman''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of Marx, Allen remembered having lunch with him years
ago and thinking ``that this guy was like a Jewish uncle in my
family. No different.... And I thought if I acheive the greatness
I'd like to... that's what really what it is in the end. You lose
your teeth; you make those wisecracks to waitresses... you can see
where I'm going with this.'' But morbidity aside, Allen doesn't
show signs of slowing down. More films are in the works. Last year,
he and adopted a baby daughter, 14-month old Bechet, and recently
moved into an Upper East Side townhouse in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   And he's achieved his original goal (``I just wanted something
that would keep me interested my whole life''), even if it wasn't
as a card cheat or a safe cracker.
</P>
<P>
   But you get the feeling that despite why Allen isn't a
small-time crook, he sees himself as one in the world of art, never
quite measuring up to the Ingmar Bergmans and Francois Truffauts,
giants of filmmaking (``real heavy stuff.''), that he so admires.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's what keeps Allen going, always hoping the next film
will be a masterpiece. But there is one thing he's given us that
Bergman hasn't, a lot of laughs, and if the resounding applause
from the audience at UCLA is any indication, that counts big time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-00 2007EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
