<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 PERSONALS: The Swiss Architects and the UT Museum
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file.) &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By LEAH GARCHIK &QC;  &LR; 
 &UR; c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle &LR;  &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
A Metropolis story about the diversity of opinion on Herzog &AMP; de
Meuron's plans for the new de Young museum mentioned that in
November, the Swiss firm had quit designing an art museum for the
University of Texas in Austin with ``spectacularly bad blood on
both sides.''
</P>
<P>
   This sent Personals scurrying to the Austin American-Statesman,
which described the debacle and included several hilarious local
columns. But proponents of the new de Young can relax: The
villains, at least as reported in Texas papers, were the regents
displeased with the selection committee's choice of the firm.
</P>
<P>
   The regents wondered a) Why couldn't they have a good old
American firm design the museum? b) Why did the structure have to
be so modern? Couldn't the museum be designed to fit in with older
buildings on campus?
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a big problem with flat roofs,'' said one regent when
viewing the original design. ``I have a flat roof on my house. I
wouldn't want a flat roof,'' said another. The architects
redesigned the structure to have a curved roof, but complaints
continued.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Beverly Hillbillies vs. Bauhaus'' was the headline over a
column by the newspaper's  &UR; Michael Barnes &LR; , who called the
architects' resignation ``a victory of the modern Texas version of
the Know Nothing Party.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The regents' shortsighted opinions have resulted in blackening
the growing reputation of the arts at the University of Texas
throughout the world,'' said art department professor
 &UR; Michael Mogavero &LR;  at a protest rally after the architects resigned.
Architecture Dean  &UR; Larry Speck &LR;  quit a few days later.
</P>
<P>
   Columnist  &UR; John Kelso &LR;  suggested that if the regents wanted a
design that looked familiar, ``why don't they build an art museum
that looks like a Dairy Queen?'' As for the regents themselves,
``What do these people know about architecture?'' asked Kelso. One
regent's resume, he noted, states that he is an `` `avid
fisherman.' Great. Just what we need. An art museum that looks like
Roy Bob's Bait &AMP; Tackle.''
</P>
<P>
   In February, the regents changed the procedure that had mandated
a selection committee, and gave themselves total power to decide on
architects.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ARTISTS FOR HILLARY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Rudolph Giuliani &LR; 's attempt to cut off museum funds over the
``Sensation'' art at the recent Brooklyn show has apparently had
political repercussions among artists.
</P>
<P>
   A May 23 fund-raising auction for the first lady's senatorial
campaign is being supported by the likes of  &UR; Yoko Ono &LR; ,  &UR; Robert &LR; 
 &UR; Rauschenberg &LR; ,  &UR; Christo &LR; ,  &UR; Frank Stella &LR; ,  &UR; Richard Serra &LR; ,  &UR; Julian &LR; 
 &UR; Schnabel &LR; ,  &UR; Jeff Koons &LR; ,  &UR; Ross Bleckner &LR; ,  &UR; Ellsworth Kelly &LR; ,
 &UR; Cindy &LR; 
 &UR; Sherman &LR; ,  &UR; Jennifer Bartlett &LR; ,  &UR; Jim Dine &LR; , &UR; Frank Gehry &LR;  and  &UR; Nan &LR; 
 &UR; Goldin &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   ``There certainly is an anti-Giuliani factor to this enormous
response from the art community,'' &UR; Chuck Close &LR;  told the New York
Daily News. Giuliani ``is a bit of a dull monkey,'' said &UR; Larry &LR; 
 &UR; Rivers &LR; . ``Rudy's trying to come across as nuts but honest, and I
think generally that's not a bad combination. But now he's
wrestling with subjects that are a little too complex for him.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ First, some nominations for a new name for the Faked Outrage
Hall of Fame, as proposed herein last week:  &UR; Tamsen Armstrong &LR; 
suggests it be called the Captain Renault Award, after the
 &UR; Claude Rains &LR;  role in ``Casablanca,'' who comes into Rick's casino
and ``is shocked to find that gambling is going on!'' And
 &UR; Tony Enos &LR;  suggests the Doubtraged Community.
</P>
<P>
   Enos' nominee is the drivers who put ``Save the Rainforest''
bumper stickers on their SUVs.  &UR; Bo Pollard &LR;  suggests  &UR; Leslie &LR; 
 &UR; Shorb &LR; , an Oregon high school girl who showered with the boys after
gym, and then hired a lawyer to sue the school district when she
was punished. She was strutting her outrage (and legal case) on
CBS' ``Early Show'' last week.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``It'll be like `Rocky,' only with music and dance.'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Producer  &UR; Pierre Cossette &LR; , who has just signed a deal with
 &UR; Jesse Ventura &LR;  to make a musical based on the life of the
governor/wrestler. The New York Daily News says that  &UR; David &LR; 
 &UR; Hasselhoff  &LR; is rumored to be the lead of choice.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
