<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5904 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-CHINA-ENVIRON-SUITS-8     05-15 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-ENVIRON-SUITS-875(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLLUTION LAWS DO LITTLE TO AID CHINA'S TROUBLED WATERS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ELISABETH ROSENTHAL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUAIROU, China _ The nadir of Zhang Jinhu's career occurred in
the fall, when thousands of his ducks unsteadily waddled out of the
Huai River with singed feathers and burned feet, became paralyzed
and died.
</P>
<P>
   A prosperous farmer with a flock of 4,000 birds, Zhang had
weathered the sporadic deaths of some ducks from caustic river
water over the last few years. But he was not used to this sort of
prolonged carnage, which culminated one day in September, when
several hundred died.
</P>
<P>
   No one doubts that pollution in the sudsy green river killed the
ducks. In Huairou, on the northern outskirts of Beijing, Zhang said
he believed that he knew the culprit: chemicals from an upstream
pig farm.
</P>
<P>
   But in this relatively poor and extremely polluted country,
there is often no simple remedy for the millions of people like
Zhang hurt badly by pollution. Though China has enacted strict
anti-pollution laws in the last decade, enforcement is still lax in
many places. Flagrant violations occur without so much as an
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated, Zhang is suing the farm for compensation. His is one
of a small but growing number of environmental suits by pollution
victims that may become test cases.
</P>
<P>
   He turned to a new legal aid center in Beijing after local
government agencies gave him little satisfaction in the matter of
the duck deaths, which he calculates cost him $12,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``The deputy chief of the local environmental protection bureau
came and said they were powerless to correct it unless we could
isolate the source of the pollution,'' Zhang said as he
chain-smoked in the tin-roofed shack that he built on the
riverbank. ``But I'm just a farmer. How can I do that? There are
lots of things that dump waste water into this river, mostly in the
middle of the night.''
</P>
<P>
   Wang Canfa, who opened the legal aid office, the Center for
Legal Assistance to Pollution Victims, last fall, said, ``China has
many laws and regulations regarding the environment, but the
situation just gets worse, because they are often not
implemented.'' The center, the first in China, is affiliated with
the Law and Politics University in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   China's rivers are some of the dirtiest in the world. And an
aggressive central government campaign to identify and punish
polluters has failed to penetrate fully the vast rural areas, where
anti-pollution laws are often blithely ignored by local
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   Police are often reluctant to prosecute such businesses because
they are the cornerstones of the local economies and, in many
cases, are owned by the local government.
</P>
<P>
   Also, investigations are often prohibitively expensive for local
agencies and politically complicated, because the sources of river
pollution may be in other jurisdictions.
</P>
<P>
   And those who suffer the most are often people who are
frequently unaware of the hazards and their rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't understand the law or how to go about getting the
problem solved,'' Wang said. ``So polluters are not afraid, and
they keep skirting the law.''
</P>
<P>
   For three months, the news media have reported many cases of
serious unchecked water pollution. In central Anhui Province, a
spill devastated fish along a 15-mile stretch of the Haozhouguo
River, destroying the livelihoods of 179 families. In Leshan,
Sichuan Province, in the southwest, extensive fish deaths along 135
miles of the Minjiang River followed a chemical spill. No suits
have been filed and no compensation paid.
</P>
<P>
   Against that backdrop, the Center for Legal Assistance to
Pollution Victims is receiving more than 100 calls a month, mostly
from workers and farmers who have read the newspaper advertisements
of the center. Zhang, the duck farmer, was among the first to call.
</P>
<P>
   Zhang said many farmers had been economically devastated by the
river pollution, which peaked in fall. They complained but said
they seemed to have little recourse.
</P>
<P>
   Contributing to the pollution has been a severe drought, which
has lowered water levels, concentrating contaminants.
</P>
<P>
   When Zhang built his ramshackle complex of huts and pens to
raise ducks, it was on a bank of a river 330 feet wide. Today, the
river snakes a narrow winding path down the middle of a vast sandy
bed.
</P>
<P>
   As a child, Zhang used to swim and bathe in the Huai. Even five
years ago, he said, a fisherman could catch 300 pounds of fish a
day. But in the last year, the fish and river grass have died. So
do cows and pigs if they drink river water. ``If people go in, they
get covered with scabs,'' Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the Chinese government has acknowledged
problems with law enforcement and has buttressed its inspection
system, particularly along the seven major rivers. Nationwide, the
enforcement division has rapidly grown, to its current 30,000, with
plans to expand to 40,000 to 50,000 by 2002. In 1998, 39,754
polluters were penalized, mostly through fines. In addition, the
Environmental Protection Administration took 621 cases to court and
obtained 579 convictions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've strengthened our enforcement to make sure they meet
standards,'' said Chen Shanrong, deputy director of the
environmental inspection and supervision division in the
administration. But he added, ``We still have a long way to go.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Although such efforts have helped control industrial pollution
in some places, they have often had little effect on situations
like Zhang's, an environmental disaster in a small river with local
effects, where the suspected polluters are small companies that
enjoy good relations with local officials.
</P>
<P>
   Under Chinese law, environmental protection is primarily the
responsibility of local authorities, with the national
administration providing just backup support. Chen acknowledged
that there were ``local officials who, in order to follow their own
interests, don't cooperate.''
</P>
<P>
   The fledgling pollution-control efforts have largely focused on
industrial polluters, and government agencies are only starting to
look at agricultural wastes like the chemicals that Zhang believes
killed his ducks. Such chemicals can be harder to monitor, because
they enter the water through seepage, not by obvious effluent
pipes.
</P>
<P>
   When Zhang's ducks started dying, he unsuccessfully appealed to
every local agency he thought might be inclined to help, the local
government, the county environmental protection bureau and even the
township women's organization. He carried duck carcasses to the
local fish and wildlife office for autopsies.
</P>
<P>
   He and other farmers in the area have focused their attention on
the pig farm, because ducks upstream had no problem in the fall,
while ducks downstream died en masse.
</P>
<P>
   In response to Zhang's pleas, workers from the local
environmental protection bureau arrived and tested the river water
and found it highly alkaline. But they went no further in
determining the nature of the pollution or its source.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't even been able to figure out who owns the pig
farm,'' Zhang said. ``I don't think anyone investigated really.''
</P>
<P>
   Wang, the lawyer, said that the farm was partly owned by the
government of an upstream village and that the Huairou
environmental protection bureau had ``taken up some, but not all''
the issues.
</P>
<P>
   It is highly unlikely to do more without further pressure, he
said, adding: ``Local businesses pay taxes and are big employers.
So local governments need them and are reluctant to close them
down.''
</P>
<P>
   But Wang has great hope that suits like Zhang's will change
that, creating new incentives to fight pollution.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they knew that victims might claim compensation, that would
bring huge pressure on polluters, who would have to start paying a
price for their actions,'' Wang said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he added, it would be a hard battle, because such suits
are relatively new in China. Zhang's case will be first heard in a
local court here. But it can be appealed to a higher court in
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Zhang's neighbors who lost ducks are watching and say
they will file their own suits if he succeeds. Zhang is not holding
his breath.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've already sold the 200 ducks that remained,'' he said,
wandering through empty pens to a smelly shack fitted with
floor-to-ceiling cages, home to his new bird business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've switched to quails,'' he said. ``It's safer. They never
go near water.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
