<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-BRIEFS-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., May 21) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Six British Areas Change Phone Codes
</P>
<P>
   Telephone numbers in London and some other parts of Britain have
changed _ the third time in 10 years for London. The last time
London numbers were changed the Office of Telecommunications said
it expected no further changes, but it apparently did not foresee
the demand for new numbers caused by the Internet, fax machines and
the explosion in cell phone use.
</P>
<P>
   The area codes for London, Cardiff, Coventry, Portsmouth,
Southampton and Northern Ireland have changed from 1 to 2. After
dialing 44 (the country code for Britain), callers to these areas
from the United States now dial 2 _ followed by local codes that
have also been changed. The local code is followed by the old
personal number (seven digits in London). In Northern Ireland the
28 is followed by one of more than 30 revised district codes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The new codes in the six areas are now in use, although the old
codes will continue to work until later in the year. More
information about code changes is available at
www.numberchange.org. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For example, when making a local call in London you prefix the
existing number with a 7 (for a 207 number) or an 8 (for the 208
area). When not dialing locally but within Britain you need a zero
before the 2.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The numbers for all cell-phone, pager and personal numbers in
Britain are also changing, but existing numbers will work until
April 28, 2001. After that they will be prefixed by a 7.
</P>
<P>
   French Impressionists At the National Gallery
</P>
<P>
   Many first-time visitors to Argenteuil have a sense of deja vu:
they recognize parts of the small town on the banks of the Seine
northwest of Paris from the many paintings Monet, Manet,
Caillebotte, Renoir, Sisley and Boudin made there. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   More than 50 of those paintings can be seen in ``The
Impressionists at Argenteuil,'' the first exhibition to focus on
the second most important site, after Paris, in the development of
Impressionism. It opens at the National Gallery of Art in
Washington on May 28 and travels to Hartford this summer. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Monet started it all when he moved to Argenteuil for six years
in 1871. His Impressionist colleagues would often come to visit.
Inspired by the town's rustic charm, they painted its towpaths,
railway bridges, gardens, factories, sailboats, regattas, each
other and their families. At Monet's house in Argenteuil the group
planned what became the first Impressionist exhibition, which took
place in 1874. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The painters often worked together, capturing the same scene
side by side, and the exhibition includes several pairings:
``Sailboats at Argenteuil'' by Monet and Renoir; Caillebotte's
``Argenteuil Bridge and the Seine'' and Monet's ``Highway Bridge
and Boat Basin;'' and a cluster of trees in Boudin's ``Seine at
Argenteuil'' and Monet's ``Promenade at Argenteuil.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The show remains in Washington until Aug. 20, then moves to the
Wadsworth Atheneum Museum of Art, Sept. 9 through Dec. 3. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The National Gallery, on the National Mall between Third and
Ninth Streets at Constitution Avenue NW, is open daily. Admission
is free. Information: (202) 737-4215 or www.nga.gov. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Wadsworth Atheneum, 600 Main St., is open May 23 through
Sunday, 11 a.m. to 5 p.m. Dated and timed tickets, costing $17, are
available by calling (877) 600-6246. General information: (860)
278-2670 or www.wadsworthatheneum.org.
</P>
<P>
   Japan Abolishes Its 3 Percent Tourism Tax
</P>
<P>
   Traveling in Japan has become slightly less expensive with the
abolition of a local 3 percent tourism tax. The tax, which for more
than 40 years was applied to hotel rooms that cost more than about
$140 and meals of more than about $70, was discontinued on April 1.
Now only a countrywide 5 percent consumption tax and a tax of about
$1.30 a day for hot-spring use at some major resorts remain. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Japan National Tourist Organization likens the consumption
tax with the 6 percent or more sales taxes in many states, the
value added taxes of 10 percent or more in Europe, and the New York
City hotel tax of 13.25 percent. The consumption tax can be avoided
on goods costing more than about $94 when bought at tax-free
stores. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the tourist organization reported that about
700,000 Americans visited Japan last year, and she observed that
throughout Japan tipping is not expected in hotels, restaurants or
taxis. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Information about traveling to Japan is available at (212)
757-5641 in New York, (312) 222-0874 in Chicago and (213) 623-1952
in Los Angeles or on the Web at www.japantravelinfo.com.
</P>
<P>
   Face to Face With the Fishes in Keiko's Old Haunt
</P>
<P>
   Any kid can tell you: the moment you leave for college, your
bedroom is converted into something else. The same thing has
happened to Keiko the killer whale.
</P>
<P>
   The seagoing celebrity of ``Free Willy'' and ``Free Willy II''
spent nearly three years at the Oregon Coast Aquarium, cavorting in
a custom-made two-million-gallon tank and preparing for his
eventual release into the wild. In September 1998, he left for
college _ that is, he was sent to Iceland, where he is undergoing
more intense training before being freed, possibly this summer.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Keiko's presence gave the 10,200 residents of Newport, Ore., a
huge economic boost. But once their cash cow was gone, they were
stuck with a white elephant, in the form of an enormous, empty
tank. What to do? Turn the bedroom into something else, of course. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Opening on May 27 is the $6.9 million Passages of the Deep
exhibit. Keiko's tank has been converted into three large ocean
habitats connected by a 200-foot underwater acrylic tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors can walk through the tunnel, passing from Orford Reef,
depicting the habitat just off the southern Oregon coast; to
Halibut Flats, farther offshore; and the shark-infested Open Sea.
Vegetation and marine life particular to those habitats populate
the three different areas. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The acrylic tunnel is suspended eight feet below the surface and
eight feet from the bottom of the tank. Wave action, a sunken ship
and thousands of fish contribute to the undersea experience. There
are several 360-degree viewing areas, where visitors will always
have lots of fish in sight. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The aquarium is open every day except May 21 and Dec. 25. Hours
from Memorial Day weekend through Labor Day weekend are 9 a.m. to 6
p.m. Winter hours are 10 a.m. to 5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Admission is $9.25, $8.25 for seniors, $4.75 for ages 4 to 13,
and free for children under 4. For more information, call (541)
867-3474 or visit the Web site at www.aquarium.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
