<HEADLINE>
TRAVELING THE NET 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., May 21) 
 By L.R. SHANNON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   `IKES' ON THE WEB
</P>
<P>
   Older people surf the Web in disproportionate numbers for
shopping, travel and everything else, which, on the Web, really
does mean everything else.
</P>
<P>
   People aged 50 and older made up 21.8 percent of all those who
logged onto the Internet from home last month, according to Nielsen
Net Ratings. And you can read on www.senior.com that people 50 and
older represent 80 percent of the luxury travel bought in the
United States, typically spending 74 percent more on vacations than
people aged 18 to 49. It is not a surprise that they spend more;
they have more: 70- to 74-year-olds, followed by 65- to
69-year-olds, are the richest age groups in America.
</P>
<P>
   An article in the journal American Demographics in 1994, before
the Web was a factor, calls the generation that grew up when Dwight
D. Eisenhower was supreme allied commander and president the
``Ikes,'' and says they ``spend freely on grandchildren, new cars
and homes, and travel.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Where do seniors start shopping for travel online? Well,
www.senior.com (pay attention to the name) offers a selection of
articles about travel with links to sites for lodging, cruise lines
and such. Seniors.com (not the same thing) also has articles, but
no links. And www.generationa.com offers articles and travel tips
(``no self-respecting light traveler checks luggage''). You can
also try aarp.org, which has a few travel articles, some with
links, and also offers discounts to members, who must be 50 or
over, that may or may not be better than what you can get just by
asking the establishments.
</P>
<P>
   Any search engine _ Yahoo, Altavista, etc. _ will lead you to
scores of sites for older travelers and everybody else. An
exhaustive guide to all kinds of travel, including travel for
seniors, is at www.specialtytravel.com. Click on the Activity
Index, scroll down to Seniors/Retired, and then pick one of the
scores of countries. Bouncing around, I found six trips in England,
two in Greece and another six in New Zealand. When you select one
that sounds promising, you get a description of what the company
offers and where to get further information. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The prime site, if you don't mind stretching your brain cells,
is www.elderhostel.org, now celebrating its 25th anniversary. Last
year almost 175,000 people 55 and older visited universities,
national parks, museums and other such places in the United States,
Canada and more than 85 other countries. The programs consist of
one to four weeks of lectures, discussions, field trips and the
like.
</P>
<P>
   A MULTITUDE OF MAPS
</P>
<P>
   I pulled up a map of the small suburban town where I live in
less than a minute on www.mapblast.com, a recently redesigned site
for finding where you are going and how to get there. (Not that
anyone would travel here, but I am more likely to spot errors than
I would on a map of Paris.) If you have a street address, you can
also get driving directions, with up to 10 intermediate stops; the
locations of nationally branded places, like Starbucks; and maps
and driving directions in 41 European countries in nine languages.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-00 2013EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000515.0306 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
