u i BC-DOMINICAN-BALAGUER-BO     05-15 1162
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOMINICAN-BALAGUER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BALAGUER, 93, STILL A KEY AS DOMINICANS VOTE FOR PRESIDENT  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTO DOMINGO _ He's blind, hard of hearing and barely able to
walk, but Joaquin Balaguer, at 93, is running again for president
of the Dominican Republic.
</P>
<P>
   And to no one's surprise here, the enigmatic strongman, perhaps
Latin America's longest-surviving politician, is putting up another
tough fight, for his eighth presidential term since 1960.
</P>
<P>
   Although Balaguer is not expected to win election, most analysts
predict his conservative Reformist Social Christian Party will
place second or a close third, leaving him in the familiar position
of influencing this country's future.
</P>
<P>
   Many Dominicans are amazed _ and some are disgusted _ at the
seemingly endless presence of Balaguer, ruler for 22 of the past 34
years, in their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's incredible that in the year 2000, we're still talking
about Balaguer for president,'' said Daniel Castillo, a 22-year-old
newspaper vendor in the capital. ``It's like we're frozen in
time.''
</P>
<P>
   When millions of voters cast their ballots in this Caribbean
country where presidential politics is hotter than baseball,
Hipolito Mejia, a 59-year-old agricultural economist, probably will
take first place. His social democratic Dominican Revolutionary
Party has held a solid lead in public opinion polls for months,
hovering between 40 and 45 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But it remains unclear whether Mejia will receive enough support
for an outright victory _ 50 percent plus one vote _ or will be
forced into a runoff on June 30 against Balaguer or Danilo Medina,
candidate of the ruling centrist Dominican Liberation Party.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, the election appears more focused on second place,
and on whether Balaguer, once a close aide to the late dictator
Rafael Trujillo, will have his shot at another term in the National
Palace.
</P>
<P>
   Many foreigners have wondered how Balaguer can maintain the
respect of his people after making openly racist and hostile
remarks about Haitians as well as other people of African descent,
who make up a majority of the country's 8 million residents.
</P>
<P>
   His fans, however, say they admire the score of books he has
written and his drive to build the nation's highways and its
countless political monuments.
</P>
<P>
   Most people thought Balaguer's political career, which began
when Franklin D. Roosevelt was in the White House, was finally over
when he reluctantly left office in 1996 and threw his support in a
special election to Leonel Fernandez, the centrist party candidate
who is the current president. By law, incumbent presidents cannot
run for reelection.
</P>
<P>
   A string of squabbles between Balaguer's party and the Fernandez
government, the rise of Mejia's campaign and the lack of a strong
candidate for his own party brought Balaguer out of seclusion and
back into the limelight. When he announced his candidacy in
January, six months after his opponents had launched theirs,
Balaguer said he was doing it ``out of necessity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He really didn't want to run,'' said George Rodriguez, a
former television executive who is now Balaguer's campaign
spokesman. ``It's obviously a sacrifice for him, especially at his
age and in his condition.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts and diplomats, however, say Balaguer's candidacy is
more about control than sacrifice, and they worry that his election
could lead to a reversal of some of the policies that have
succeeded in igniting Latin America's fastest-growing economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't really work with Balaguer,'' one diplomat said last
week. ``It's him or his ring of people who try to run everything.
He doesn't understand why some things shouldn't be run by the
state.''
</P>
<P>
   Like that of front-runner Mejia, Balaguer's campaign platform
has emphasized the country's growing inequality _ about 60 percent
of the population lives in extreme poverty _ and has promised a
more active government in everything from roads to schools.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Balaguer's candidacy has relied more on his image and his
party's machine than on any political agenda. The candidate has
appeared only occasionally in public and he refuses media
interviews, relying instead on an aggressive publicity strategy and
a cadre of volunteers _ many of them youths _ to canvass
neighborhoods across the country.
</P>
<P>
   At a campaign-ending rally on Friday along the Malecon, the
capital's coastal drive, tens of thousands of supporters dressed in
red shirts waited hours in the afternoon heat to hear Balaguer,
who, after being gingerly lifted to his feet by aides, spoke for
less than 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Although Balaguer's own rivals credit the former president for
leading the Dominican Republic out of turmoil after the 30-year
Trujillo dictatorship ended in 1960, they say the country will not
be truly democratic until Balaguer is defeated.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's done much for this country and he's given out lots of
favors to people, but it's time for us to move forward,'' said Jose
Tomas Perez, secretary general of the governing party, as he
addressed a group of Dominicans who flew home from the United
States to vote.
</P>
<P>
   Medina, 47, the centrist economist who served as Fernandez's
chief of staff until he resigned last year to run for president,
has relied heavily on the government's record of promoting
privatization projects, tourism and high-tech manufacturing jobs
that has produced 7 percent economic growth and significantly lower
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   But Medina's candidacy has been hampered by his low-key
personality and fights within his party. As a consequence, many
observers predict that Balaguer would do better in a runoff against
Mejia than Medina would.
</P>
<P>
   Mejia, meanwhile, has run on pledges of ethical cleanliness,
taking jabs at corruption scandals that have rocked the Fernandez
administration. Mejia's supporters last week insisted they had
enough support for an outright victory.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps in anticipation of a poor showing, the ruling party has
accused the country's main electoral council and opposition parties
of creating confusion among residents by reassigning more than
300,000 voters to new balloting precincts. And there are rumors _
always present in a campaign involving Balaguer _ of plans to
meddle with the ballot boxes.
</P>
<P>
   Most opinion polls show Balaguer and Medina in a statistical tie
for second place. Should the elder rival, known for his dark suits
and black hat, place third, his endorsement will be key to deciding
the country's next president. Once again, Balaguer would play
kingmaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Joaquin Balaguer, this has been one of the nicest
campaigns,'' political columnist Jose P. Monegro wrote in the Santo
Domingo daily Listin. ``There's little he's had to do and he hasn't
received a single direct attack. The conditions have been set so
that this ancient ``caudillo'' _ boss _ can pass into history as
the politician to imitate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-00 2014EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
