r s BC-SOC-GALAXY-HERNANDEZ-     05-15 0400
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-HERNANDEZ-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOURCE: MLS `HOPEFUL' TO HAVE HERNANDEZ IN L.A.   TUESDAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA _ Major League Soccer officials in New York said they
were ``very hopeful'' that Mexican standout Luis Hernandez would
arrive in Los Angeles late Monday or early today to join his new
Galaxy teammates in time for Wednesday's game in San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   A Galaxy source said that Hernandez and MLS officials have
agreed to terms on a multiyear contract, but they have not
finalized a transfer fee with Tigres of Monterrey, Hernandez's
Mexican club team. Hernandez is under contract with Tigres for
another season.
</P>
<P>
   One MLS official who requested anonymity said he expected the
transfer fee to be finalized late Monday, possibly leading to an
official announcement this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Galaxy coach Sigi Schmid, tired of speculating on Hernandez's
arrival, said he will wait for word from MLS like everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is absolutely nothing new to report,'' Schmid said
Monday. ``I'll come to work tomorrow and we'll see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   MLS officials expected to announce Hernandez's signing Friday,
but Tigres is in the process of changing ownership, which
complicated the contract and transfer fee negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Because of speculation that Hernandez would join the Galaxy in
Dallas this past Friday night, a crowd of 20,417 attended the
Burn-Galaxy match at the Cotton Bowl, which ended in a 1-1 draw. It
was the fifth largest crowd in Burn history, giving MLS officials
an idea of Hernandez's drawing power.
</P>
<P>
   In one development Monday, Clint Mathis reported to the Galaxy's
practice Monday at the Rose Bowl. Mathis had not trained with the
team since Wednesday, when Schmid told Mathis and defender Joey
Franchino they would be offered in a special dispersal draft to
make room for Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   Franchino was not with the team Monday and neither Franchino nor
Mathis attended the Galaxy's game in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Midfielder Roy Myers, also expected to leave the Galaxy when the
Hernandez deal becomes official, played in the Dallas game Saturday
and hasn't missed a training session.
</P>
<P>
   Schid said he'll make a decision today whether to take
Franchino, Mathis and Myers to San Jose. All three remain property
of the team until the Hernandez deal becomes official. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
