r s BC-BKC-PEPPERDINE-RECRUI     05-15 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-PEPPERDINE-RECRUITS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAVES REAP BENEFITS OF NCAA BERTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VINCENT BONSIGNORE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not long after Pepperdine lost to Oklahoma State in the second
round of the NCAA Tournament last March, Waves coach Jan van Breda
Kolff was looking to the future.
</P>
<P>
   The loss to the Cowboys didn't dampen van Breda Kolff's trust
that last season's success was a precursor for things to come. The
Waves' regular-season West Coast Conference championship, NCAA
Tournament berth and first-round upset over Indiana was momentum to
build on, van Breda Kolff felt, and he planned to take advantage on
the recruiting trail.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly two months later it's obvious van Breda Kolff was on to
something. Pepperdine closed its 2000 recruiting class recently
with a late flurry, adding three players van Breda Kolff is
confident will help the Waves in the future and in some cases,
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the Waves landed five players, filling holes at point
guard and in the frontcourt while adding depth at off guard.
</P>
<P>
   Van Breda Kolff's hopes of expanding Pepperdine's recruiting
base beyond California didn't materialize, but he's certain that
will change next year.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, the Waves were locked in on their top guys long before
shocking Indiana, so it was too late to take full advantage of that
excitement nationally. But they've already targeted some intriguing
out-of-state prospects for 2001, and van Breda Kolff expects the
interest to be mutual.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we'll see the fruits of our labor even more later this
summer when we go see some of those players,'' van Breda Kolff
said.
</P>
<P>
   Of the players coming in next year, van Breda Kolff is
especially high on Micah McKinney, a 6-foot-3 point guard from
Dominguez High of Compton. McKinney helped lead the Dons to the
mythical high school national championship after capturing the
Southern Section Division II title and the Division II State
Championship. His maturity, aggressiveness and court awareness
could land McKinney a starting job as a freshman.
</P>
<P>
   For the Waves, who need a replacement for Tezale Archie,
McKinney's development is critical. Archie was a catalyst for
Pepperdine's frenzied offense and chief instigator in its
full-court press. In close games, it was Archie taking most of the
big shots, and he developed into an unofficial team spokesmen
during the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Van Breda Kolff notices some of those qualities in McKinney. The
only question is how quickly he can make the adjustment from high
school to college.
</P>
<P>
   ``Physically and mentally we feel he can play as a freshman,''
van Breda Kolff said. ``He's very strong mentally, and he's an
outgoing kid on and off the court. Obviously we have some big shoes
to fill with Tezale, but Micah is going to be a player we can put
in that position.''
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine's 2000 class reflects the style of play van Breda
Kolff brought to the Waves, an up-tempo system that relies on
pressure defense, turnovers and points in transition. The key is
versatile players and a high volume of athletic ability.
</P>
<P>
   It's a style most young players enjoy, providing them space and
opportunities to showcase their skills. That, coupled with the
Waves' on-court success and the fact they played their last three
games on national television certainly didn't hurt.
</P>
<P>
   When van Breda Kolff and his assistants visited with players,
they found willing listeners.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that the attention we got by playing in
the NCAA Tournament helped us get that national exposure.'' van
Breda Kolff said. ``People saw how we played, with the trapping and
getting up and down the court and that was appealing. Nowadays,
that's how kids want to play, so that helped tremendously.''
</P>
<P>
   The Waves also added two more athletic players in Michael Hall
from Pacific and Robert Turner, a 6-9 forward, from Western of
Anaheim. Van Breda Kolff expects both to flourish with the Waves.
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine's other two newcomers are 6-8 forward Will Kimball, a
teammate of Hall at Pacific, and Glen McGowan, a 6-9 forward from
Notre Dame (Mass.) Academy. McGowan was a prep standout at Venice
High.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good group of kids and we're looking forward to getting
them in here and seeing what they can do,'' van Breda Kolff said.
</P>
<P>
   The Waves did suffer one setback. Assistant coach Chris Walker,
a trusted confidant to van Breda Kolff, left to become an assistant
at Villanova, his alma mater.
</P>
<P>
   Walker and van Breda Kolff developed a strong friendship and
working relationship over the past four years, beginning at
Vanderbilt when van Breda Kolff was the head coach there. His
departure is a significant blow Walker is an excellent recruiter
and possesses a keen basketball mind, two qualities van Breda Kolff
will sorely miss.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, it's a step in the right direction for Walker,
who could be in position to take over as head coach at Villanova in
a few years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've enjoyed him as an assistant and a friend these last four
years. As a coach, he is outstanding in every way,'' van Breda
Kolff said. ``I would have loved to have him stay, but at the same
time this is a terrific career move so I'm happy for him. But there
is no question he will be missed.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-00 2030EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
