<HEADER>
A5928 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BRAZIL-AIRLINES-NYT &LR;      05-15 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-AIRLINES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG LOSSES FOR VASP AND 3 COMPETITORS THREATEN BRAZILIAN AIRLINES 

</HEADLINE>
  By JENNIFER L. RICH  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAO PAULO, Brazil _ The Brazilian airline Vasp has since January
received at least two federal threats to ground its fleet for
failure to pay airport fees. Last month IBM seized four of Vasp's
mainframe computers and 200 personal computers because of
delinquent bills.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the really bad news.
</P>
<P>
   Four of Vasp's MD-11 jetliners were repossessed two weeks ago,
forcing the carrier to cancel all intercontinental flights. And a
court order grounded three smaller 737 Vasp aircraft used on the
heavily traveled Rio-Sao Paulo route. An appeals judge has
temporarily restored the 737s to Vasp's use, but the future of that
route, and the airline, is far from certain.
</P>
<P>
   With growing debts now estimated at more than $1.8 billion, Vasp
is in the worst shape of Brazil's major airlines, with losses last
year of nearly $53 million. But Vasp's three main competitors are
not particularly healthy either. Varig, the largest airline, lost
$54 million last year. Transbrasil lost $50 million. TAM lost a
record $74 million.
</P>
<P>
   Their predicament reflects what the industry executives call the
hostile financial and regulatory environment for air transportation
in Latin America's largest economy. All the airlines have asked the
government to make drastic changes in the country's aviation
policies to ensure that the domestic industry will survive stronger
international competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government has to do its part, not just to reduce costs,
but to stimulate the entrance of new capital or new carriers in the
Brazilian market,'' said Claudio Toledo, an economist and aviation
consultant.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear how quickly the government will respond to the
industry's requests. But there is widespread agreement that the
Brazilian airline industry is in the midst of its worst crisis in
recent years. The devaluation of the real, Brazil's currency, in
January 1999 increased the industry's dollar-denominated debt load
by 30 percent overnight. Fuel and leasing costs were similarly
affected, at a time when economic weakness kept many Brazilian
travelers at home. According to Brazil's Department of Civil
Aviation, demand for international air travel fell about 14 percent
in 1999, causing all of the major carriers to cancel or reroute
flights.
</P>
<P>
   As part of an effort to halt the losses, TAM and Transbrasil
completed a code-sharing agreement a few weeks ago, which will
initially reduce by 16 the number of Transbrasil's daily flights
between Rio and Sao Paulo. As a result, the company will return six
leased aircraft. Although the two companies say that the agreement
is simply a business partnership, industry experts expect the
airlines to merge eventually.
</P>
<P>
   Varig, which dominates the international market, has taken steps
to cut costs. Last year it returned 14 leased planes and laid off
employees to help save money.
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, Swissair said it was talking to all four Brazilian
carriers about possible alliances that could lead to an equity
investment.
</P>
<P>
   The Brazilian carriers insist that they cannot return to health
on their own. One of their biggest complaints is that
government-imposed price ceilings restrict companies from charging
variable rates on tickets, one of the most common ways for airlines
in the United States to fill planes. Unlike air passengers in the
United States, a Brazilian pleasure traveler who books a ticket two
months in advance pays the same price as a businessman who buys his
ticket at the gate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pricing structure is frankly archaic,'' said Brigadier
Mauro Gandra, executive director of the National Syndicate of
Airlines, a trade group. ``If companies could charge business
travelers higher ticket prices, they could reduce prices for
regular passengers. It would stimulate domestic air travel.''
</P>
<P>
   Since only 2 percent of Brazil's 165 million people have ever
flown, the market has the potential to grow rapidly if the price
were right. Indeed, as the economy recovers, industry groups expect
the demand for domestic air travel to jump about 10 percent this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue from international routes has helped offset domestic
losses. But it is precisely in the international routes where
Brazil's lack of competitiveness is most visible. Ten years ago,
Brazil's then-flagship carrier, Varig, accounted for 65 percent of
international passengers. Today, all four airlines combined account
for less than 35 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In the North American market alone, Vasp, Varig, Transbrasil and
Tam offer 50 weekly flights to the United States, while their four
main U.S. competitors _ American, Continental, United and Delta _
provide 101 flights to Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem is that there are too many Brazilian
carriers going after a limited number of international travelers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't make sense to have four different companies flying
internationally,'' said Fernando Pinto, the president of Varig.
``We aren't competitive and it's the country that winds up
losing.''
</P>
<P>
   With Vasp's international cutbacks, Pinto said Varig's occupancy
rate on international flights had already started to creep up. He
said an eventual merger of Tam and Transbrasil would help as well.
</P>
<P>
   Aviation workers' unions have expressed concern, though, that a
decreasing number of airlines would mean far fewer jobs and would
turn the industry into an anticompetitive cartel. They argue that
the government must devise a way to help companies be more
competitive, while providing incentives for new capital to enter
the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``The companies themselves have the conditions to be
efficient,'' said Graziella Baggio, president of the National
Aeronautics Union. ``But financing costs, leasing costs, airport
costs, taxes are all too high.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-00 2035EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
