<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONFERENCE-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: COMMERCIAL ACTORS' STRIKE FOLLOWS A CONFERENCE TO
BERMUDA 
</HEADLINE>
   By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is a look at some of the highlights, lowlights and
sidelights of the 2000 management conference of the American
Association of Advertising Agencies, held last week in Southampton,
Bermuda:
</P>
<P>
   SOLIDARITY FOREVER? A last-minute addition to the agenda of the
conference was a presentation on the two-week-old strike against
the association, known as the Four A's, and its counterpart, the
Association of National Advertisers, by two unions that represent
commercial actors, the Screen Actors Guild and the American
Federation of Television and Radio Artists.
</P>
<P>
   Ira Shepard, counsel to the committee of the two associations
negotiating with the unions, began his upbeat assessment of the
strike from the management perspective with this quotation from an
editorial in The Wall Street Journal on May 2, the day after the
strike began: ``When the Screen Actors Guild is striking, the joke
goes, you can't find a waiter.'' The audience laughed.
</P>
<P>
   But the unions struck back, so to speak, by finding a way to
make their presence felt directly by the conference attendees, who
are top executives at the agencies that produce the commercials in
which the actors appear. On Friday night, a tugboat loudly blowing
its horn followed the ships taking the attendees to a dinner at the
Royal Navy Dockyard. Attached to the side of the tugboat was a
large sign with a message urging a ``fair contract for SAG/AFTRA.''
</P>
<P>
   And later, when the attendees returned to their rooms at the
Fairmont Southampton Princess hotel, they found under their doors a
leaflet listing dozens of striking members of the unions. The list
appeared under this headline: ``Just a short list of talent that
advertising agencies will not be delivering to their clients''
until the strike is settled.
</P>
<P>
   NAME THAT PRODUCT. The members of the Four A's are always paying
attention to brand names because most advertisers hire them to
promote those products. For instance, at a reception sponsored by
executives of TBWA Worldwide, part of the Omnicom Group, the
liquors served were Absolut vodka and other brands marketed by a
big TBWA client, the Seagram Co.
</P>
<P>
   The conference, however, was the first to be held in Bermuda and
exposed attendees to some brands they rarely see. The Esso brand,
which long ago became Exxon in the United States, is still in use
at gasoline stations around the island. Among the other unfamiliar
names were: Cadbury Crunchie candy bars, the Daihatsu Applause,
Humpty Dumpty potato chips, Lantic sugar, Outerbridge's Original
Sherry Rum Peppers Sauce and the Toyota Lite Ace.
</P>
<P>
   Attendees already seemed to have some familiarity with one brand
from Bermuda: Gosling's Black Seal rum. There was also an
automobile that ought to become a favorite among agency creative
executives hoping to win more awards: the Renault Clio.
</P>
<P>
   IS `ICON' SHORT FOR `ICONOCLASTIC'? There was some lively
discussion during a panel that was part of the general session on
Friday, devoted to the ``new, young icons'' among creative
executives at smaller agencies.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, the moderator, Andrew Jaffe, executive director at
the Clio Awards, part of VNU USA, asked the panelists to discuss
agencies that form stand-alone interactive advertising operations.
He gave as an example iDeutsch, the interactive unit of Deutsch
Inc. in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is iDeutsch a site about Donny?'' asked Alex Bogusky, vice
chairman and creative director at Crispin Porter &AMP; Bogusky in
Miami, referring to Donny Deutsch, the larger-than-life chief
executive at Deutsch. ``Is it all about Donny?''
</P>
<P>
   SPILL THE WINE. At another panel on Friday about creativity, Ken
Mandelbaum, chief creative officer at BBDO West in Los Angeles and
San Francisco, part of the BBDO Worldwide unit of Omnicom, was
asked to discuss trends on the West Coast, where many clients are
dot-coms.
</P>
<P>
   Mandelbaum said he had been compiling a reel of the best
commercials of the 1980s created by West Coast agencies, which were
``all for wine coolers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The parallels are terrifying,'' he added as the audience
laughed. ``We all know what happened to the wine cooler industry.''
</P>
<P>
   BY THE NUMBERS. For decades, the Four A's conference held in the
spring was known as the annual meeting. In recent years, as the
format was changed to focus on topics of interest to agency
managers _ and conferences were added to appeal to media and
creative executives _ that description was modified. First the
event was called the management conference and annual meeting, then
the words ``annual meeting'' were dropped.
</P>
<P>
   With that change, the venerable association also eliminated
almost all references to the conference's place in Four A's
history. So for those of you at home who keep track of such things,
it was the 82nd annual meeting.
</P>
<P>
   COINING A PHRASE. All during the conference, attendees were
closely following the developments in London and New York as Sir
Martin Sorrell, chief executive at the WPP Group, finally reached
an agreement to acquire Young &AMP; Rubicam Inc. after weeks of
on-again, off-again negotiations centered on honing the financial
terms of the deal. That provided fodder for several speakers,
including Philip B. Dusenberry, chairman of BBDO New York, part of
the BBDO Worldwide unit of Omnicom.
</P>
<P>
   Attendees enjoyed watching Bermudians ``diving for coins,''
Dusenberry said in a speech on Saturday after he formally became
the 2000-2001 chairman of the Four A's, ``and watching Martin
Sorrell trying to take the coins away from them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
