<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 20:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5945 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BOX-TV-SPORTS-NYT &LR;      05-15 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-TV-SPORTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV SPORTS NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD SANDOMIR    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jones Mauls Hall
</P>
<P>
   Richard Hall's game but losing performance against Roy Jones Jr.
Saturday night produced three unexpected fans for the
light-heavyweight challenger: HBO's announcers.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Lampley, George Foreman and Larry Merchant declared that
Hall was overmatched _ that was obvious, especially in two rounds
when Hall landed only two punches _ but they admired his courage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you what,'' Lampley said in the seventh round.
``Richard Hall has guts.'' Later, in the ninth round, Lampley
added, ``I'm embarrassed when I said three weeks ago this would be
an egregious mismatch.''
</P>
<P>
   In the sixth, Merchant: ``He's one brave dude, Richard Hall.''
</P>
<P>
   By the ninth round, the announcers started lobbying for the
referee Wayne Kelly to stop the punishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is absurd!'' Lampley cried with 1 minute 54 seconds left
in the 11th. ``Stop the fight. Stop it, Wayne. Come on. This isn't
competitive anymore. It's a bloodletting.'' After Kelly declared a
technical knockout, Merchant added, ``The referee ought to be
pistol-whipped for allowing that to go on.''
</P>
<P>
   An excessive punishment, but Merchant would not have said it if
Jones did not insist on fighting mandatory challengers whom talent
bypassed. Last year, he dispatched an embarrassing mandatory,
Richard Frazier, the World Boxing Council's No. 1 contender, in the
second round. Hall was the World Boxing Association's top
contender. And Jones is looking to face the International Boxing
Federation's highest-ranked challenger, to be chosen from the
winner of the little-anticipated Antonio Tarver-Eric Harding bout.
</P>
<P>
   But Jones does not want to lose any of his belts and HBO cannot
force him to surrender a belt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's maddening,'' said Seth Abraham, the president of Time
Warner Sports. ``For Roy, the belts represent a level of status
that we don't hear from Lennox Lewis, Oscar De La Hoya and Naseem
Hamed.''
</P>
<P>
   Technically, HBO could pay Jones his millions and not televise a
gross mismatch, Abraham said, ``but if we didn't, we'd open
ourselves up to a breach of contract lawsuit.''
</P>
<P>
   Only one fight remains on Jones' HBO contract. The fight must be
on TVKO pay-per-view, for which Jones is guaranteed no money. And
he will face Tarver or Harding, unless he wants to lose his IBF
belt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roy will earn whatever the public thinks that fight is
worth,'' Abraham said. Which won't be much. Jones' pay-per-view
appeal has been compromised by the weak light-heavyweight division.
Even Jones' talent can't make up for a mismatch when fans are asked
to pay $40 or $50. His appeal would increase if he moves into the
heavyweight division, if only for the novelty, even if the opponent
is a small heavyweight like Chris Byrd. A title fight against Lewis
could be a blockbuster.
</P>
<P>
   Airwaves
</P>
<P>
   The four National Basketball Association playoff games Saturday
and Sunday on NBC produced an average 5.8 overnight Nielsen rating,
down 13 percent from a 6.7 for two weekend games on the comparable
weekend in 1999. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To golf fans angered by CBS Sports' abrupt departure from the
Byron Nelson Classic on Sunday before Jesper Parnevik won on the
third sudden-death hole, add one more dissenting voice: the PGA
Tour.
</P>
<P>
   By leaving the playoff at 6:38 p.m., ET, CBS violated its
contract with the Tour, which requires it to stick with coverage
until at least 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement released Monday, the PGA Tour pronounced itself
``deeply disappointed'' with CBS. The Tour added that the network
had made assurances ``that an occurrence such as yesterday's, which
has never before happened with a CBS telecast of a PGA Tour event,
will not be repeated.''
</P>
<P>
   CBS' decision to withdraw before Parnevik and Davis Love III
teed off on the third playoff hole was not a golf decision. It was
all about entertainment, and the sanctity of the night's prime-time
schedule: ``60 Minutes,'' followed by ``Touched By An Angel,'' and
Part 1 of ``Jesus.''
</P>
<P>
   At no time was the golf tournament _ a nonmajor, no less _ to
delay for a nanosecond the start of prime-time during a crucial
sweeps month.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Jesus' was on the cover of virtually everybody's TV book and
we didn't want to push back prime-time,'' LeslieAnne Wade, a
spokeswoman for CBS Sports, said.
</P>
<P>
   As the tournament passed its expected 6 p.m. conclusion, CBS
made a rough calculation that the third sudden-death playoff hole
would not end until at least 7:02, with no guarantee that it would
be the last. So CBS chose to bail out at 6:38, after the second
hole, rather than show Parnevik and Love at the 18th.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, CBS's calculation was wrong: Parnevik won at the
third playoff hole, at 6:58 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody feels good about this,'' Wade said. ``These are
split-second decisions done with inexact math.''
</P>
<P>
   Had Tiger Woods been playing Love, CBS might have hung around to
show Woods hit his tee shot on the third playoff hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tiger would have added another component, but we would have
done the same thing,'' Wade said.
</P>
<P>
   The reflexive thought is that CBS would not dare pre-empt Woods
if he was in a position to win. But on this Sunday, even Tiger _
said to have messianic qualities by his father _ would have found
it hard to compete with ``Jesus'' in CBS's eye.
</P>
<P>
   From 9 to 10 p.m. ``Jesus'' battled ``Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire.'' Between 9 and 9:30, ``Jesus'' won, with a 14.9
Nielsen rating to ``Millionaire's'' 13.3. But from 9:30 to 10,
Regis struck back, winning 15.6-15.2.
</P>
<P>
   The Byron Nelson, incidentally, generated a 4.0 overnight
rating.
</P>
<P>
   And CBS will never cut away from golf again before 7 o'clock.
</P>
<P>
   Until ``Jesus II: The Return.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
