<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5946 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKC-KNIGHT-NYT &LR;      05-15 1199
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-KNIGHT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNIGHT KEEPS HIS JOB AT INDIANA 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOE DRAPE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Despite a seven-week investigation that concluded
that Bobby Knight displayed a ``pattern of inappropriate behavior''
that had embarrassed Indiana University, the school's president
said Monday that the long-time Hoosier basketball coach deserved a
``last chance'' and will be allowed to continue as coach.
</P>
<P>
   The president, Myles Brand, said Knight would be suspended for
three games next season and fined $30,000, and that he would serve
as coach under a ``zero tolerance'' policy that would be
stringently enforced. Brand threatened to dismiss Knight if he has
inappropriate physical contact with players or other members of the
university community or does not conduct himself with ``decorum and
civility'' on occasions when Knight is representing Indiana, such
as on the bench and in news conferences.
</P>
<P>
   Brand, along with the two university trustees who conducted the
investigation, conceded they were troubled by what Brand called
``persistent and systematic'' abusive behavior by the Hall of Fame
coach, who has brought Indiana three national titles in his 29
years as an icon in a basketball-crazy state.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation concluded that Knight grabbed a former player,
Neil Reed, by the neck for 2.3 seconds, had intimidated a
64-year-old secretary in the athletic department with foul language
and a thrown vase, and that he got into abusive arguments as well
as physical altercations with colleagues and subordinates. Still,
Brand, who had the final decision, said that there was ``no
incident by itself that rose to the level of termination.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the ethical approach is to give him one last chance,''
Brand said at a news conference. ``He has given me his word that he
will take extraordinary steps to change behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have established tough, specific guidelines to send a clear
message that abusive and embarrassing behavior will not be
tolerated,'' Brand said.
</P>
<P>
   Knight did not attend the news conference. John Walda, one of
the trustees who led the investigation, read a statement by Knight
in which he said he had ``absolutely no problem with the
guidelines.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The establishment of effective and proper guidelines can in
the long run help me become a better coach,'' the statement said.
``As I have said before, I recognized that I have a problem with my
temper. For those times it has ever caused me to do anything that
gave anyone understandable and justifiable reason to be upset, I am
sincerely sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   Brand said Knight would apologize to Jeanette Hartgraves, the
secretary whom Knight had bullied by throwing a vase in her office
in 1988. But the Indiana president said the general apology would
suffice for those involved in the other incidents.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation involved accusations that Knight had choked
and punched then-assistant sports information director Kit
Klingelhoffer in the mid-1970s; accosted then-assistant coach Ron
Felling in late 1999; upbraided his boss, athletic director
Clarence Doninger, in a near altercation earlier this year, and
that Knight choked Reed, the former player, at a practice in 1997,
an allegation that spurred the overall inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Walda said the Reed incident, which was caught on videotape, was
``clearly inappropriate,'' but stopped short of characterizing it
as a choking action and pointed out that the player was not
injured. ``We are resolved that if coach Knight persists in this
type of contact, it will not be tolerated,'' Walda said.
</P>
<P>
   In the course of the investigation, he said that 29 people were
interviewed, including 12 athletic department employees and 7
former players.
</P>
<P>
   Walda said Reed's charge that Knight brandished soiled toilet
paper to motivate his team had ``little credibility.'' He also
dismissed Reed's allegation that Brand was banished by Knight from
a Hoosier practice.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of Sunday's trustees meeting, where the inquiry
findings were given to eight of the nine trustees, Knight issued a
statement acknowledging that his temper had led him into
confrontations and promising to work harder at developing a more
diplomatic approach. He also made it clear he wanted to keep his
job.
</P>
<P>
   But Brand acknowledged that it was a two-hour meeting with the
coach at the president's home on Saturday night that had brought
his decision not to fire him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The conversation I had with Bob was clearly unique,'' Brand
said. ``I had never seen him before contrite and apologetic. As the
discussion proceeded and Bob expressed the view that he very much
wanted to change his behavior, then we began to talk about
sanctions.''
</P>
<P>
   The university president had come to Knight's defense in 1998
when the coach's support seemed to be eroding after a history of
boorish behavior and, by Indiana standards, sub-par seasons. Brand,
along with Walda, authored a letter citing Knight's average of 23
victories a season, a 77 percent graduation rate - nearly double
the national average for college basketball - and the fact the
program never ran afoul of the NCAA under Knight's 29-year reign.
</P>
<P>
   He cited the same factors Monday and expressed confidence the
volatile coach could live up to the tough, new guidelines set
before him. ``He will give it as good a try as he can,'' Brand
said. ``He has a good chance to pull it off.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone in the university community, however, was as
hopeful -- or happy -- about the prospect of Knight getting another
chance to check his behavior no matter how hyper vigilant his
superiors are about enforcing the guidelines. Brand named Doninger,
the athletic director, as the chair of a new commission to come up
with a code of conduct for all university coaches. Doninger, who
was upset that he wasn't a part of the inquiry, says he is not sure
he will remain as athletic director.
</P>
<P>
   In light of their recent clashes, he was asked if he could get
along with Knight?
</P>
<P>
   ``I always said I could get along with anybody. With the
guidelines, I think I can get along with coach,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But at least some faculty members were appalled but hardly
surprised Knight received another chance. Dave Pisoni, a
chancellors' professor of psychology and cognitive science, says
Brand and the trustees got what they wanted - for Knight to stay -
and it has sent a terrible message within the state and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   ``It displays the lack of principled leadership that we have at
the university. You really didn't think they were going to fire
Bobby Knight,'' said Pisoni. ``Our image is not tarnished, but
irreparably damaged. It sends the message that athletics are more
important than academics. That marketing and revenues streams means
more than scholarship.''
</P>
<P>
   But one of Knight's current players, Dane Fife, may have spoken
for the coach's supporters when he suggested there was only one way
for Knight to quell the debate over his fitness to represent
Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to be under a microscope, but we're going to help
him'' said the sophomore guard. ``I'm pretty sure if we won a lot
of games and won a national championship, it would cure all of
this.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
