<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 20:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5950 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      05-15 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   Britain: Blair Sues
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Tony Blair's wife, Cherie, who is to give birth
to the couple's fourth child this month, will go to court Tuesday
to challenge a government restriction on who is covered by a
provision permitting parents to take 13 weeks of unpaid leave to
care for newborn children. Blair, 45, a prominent lawyer, is
representing the Trades Union Congress in arguing that limiting the
new benefit to parents of babies born or adopted after last Dec. 15
unfairly excludes 2.7 million working parents.
</P>
<P>
   Northern Ireland: Inspectors Arrive
</P>
<P>
   Cyril Ramaphosa, former general secretary of South Africa's
African National Congress and Martti Ahtisaari, former prime
minister of Finland, met Prime Minister Tony Blair in London and
Northern Ireland's political leaders in Belfast to discuss their
coming mission to inspect Irish Republican Army weapon dumps. The
inspections are aimed at ending a deadlock over paramilitary
disarmament and restoring the power-sharing government in Belfast
next week.
</P>
<P>
   France: Diana Appeal
</P>
<P>
   A Paris court has set Sept. 15 for hearing an appeal on whether
to reopen an inquiry into the car crash that killed Diana, the
Princess of Wales, and two others in 1997. Prosecutors dropped
manslaughter and other charges against photographers pursuing her
car after investigating magistrates blamed the driver, Henri Paul,
for the accident. Lawyers for Mohammed al-Fayed, whose son, known
as Dodi, was also killed, immediately appealed. Paul was employed
by al-Fayed.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo: Serb's Trial Adjourned
</P>
<P>
   The first war crimes case in Kosovo opened in eastern Kosovo
when a Serb accused of genocide, Milos Jukic, 21, appeared before
ethnic Albanian judges. The trial was adjourned until June 20 after
Serbian defense lawyers failed to appear. They have requested the
case be transferred to a planned war crimes court.
</P>
<P>
   Greece: Uproar Over ID Cards
</P>
<P>
   Despite angry objections by the powerful Orthodox Church,
national identification cards will no longer identify the holder's
religion, the Justice Ministry said. The holder's thumbprints,
profession, nationality and spouse's name will also be excluded
from millions of cards to be issued next month. An angered
Archbishop Christodoulos, head of the church, called for a
referendum on the issue, saying the church was under attack by
``rabid hounds intent on rending its flesh.''
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: Mayoral Candidate Backed
</P>
<P>
   In an unofficial plebiscite, hundreds of thousands of Mexico
City residents cast ballots supporting the leading mayoral
candidate's right to stand for election despite challenges by
rivals to his residency status. Recent polls showed that Andres
Manuel Lopez Obrador had pulled ahead of his nearest rival by at
least 10 percentage points. A court is to rule soon on a suit
arguing he has not lived five years in Mexico City, as required by
law.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   Kashmir: Mine Kills 5
</P>
<P>
   Five men were killed when their bulletproof car ran over a land
mine. Among the dead was Ghulam Hasan Bhatt, the power minister for
the Indian state of Jammu and Kashmir. The anti-India group Hizbul
Mujahideen claimed responsibility for setting a trap to kill the
minister, according to Agence France Presse.
</P>
<P>
   Sri Lanka: Conflict Continues
</P>
<P>
   Heavily-populated areas near Jaffna were hit by Tamil Tiger
shelling, according to the government, which also said its own air
defenses had stalled the rebels' advance toward the crucial city.
</P>
<P>
   China: Trade Talks
</P>
<P>
   Chinese and European negotiators resumed talks in Beijing on
China's entry into the World Trade Organization. Pascal Lamy, the
European Union's trade commissioner, met Foreign Trade Minister Shi
Guangsheng, left, and said the talks would continue Tuesday
15-nation union is the most important of seven remaining WTO
members that must agree on the terms of China's membership before
it can join the trade body that sets global trade rules.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   Syria: Ex-Premier's Assets Frozen
</P>
<P>
   In a high-profile effort to demonstrate the government's
anti-corruption drive, the assets of former Prime Minister Mahmoud
Zohbi were frozen in connection with an investigation of his
possible misuse of public funds, the governing Ba'ath Party's
newspaper reported. Zohbi was prime minister for 13 years until
being abruptly replaced two months ago. The new government has
pledged to root out corruption.
</P>
</TEXT>
