<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5954 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-LYCOS-TERRA-560&AMP;ADD-N     05-15 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYCOS-TERRA-560&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LYCOS LEANS TOWARD LINK WITH TELEFONICA OF SPAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mass.)   By DOREEN CARVAJAL with ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lycos, one of the nation's biggest Internet portals, has agreed
to be acquired by Telefonica of Spain in a sweeping deal across
borders and languages worth more than $12 billion, a top executive
close to the talks said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, which could be announced as early as Tuesday, would
combine Lycos with Terra Networks, the Internet arm of Telefonica,
and link the new hybrid in an alliance with the German media
conglomerate Bertelsmann, the executive said. The portal would have
millions of users from Europe to Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   The three companies are expected to call a news conference
Tuesday to announce the union. But until then executives from the
various companies refused to comment about the deal, which would be
the first purchase of a large U.S. Internet company by a European
Internet access provider.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations were moving toward an advanced stage late Monday
night, the executive said. He said that Terra would buy Lycos in an
all-stock deal that would swap more than 1.7 Terra shares for each
share of Lycos, or more than $89.06 based on closing prices on
Friday. Shares of Lycos rose $7.50 Monday, to $61.625. Terra
slipped 0.90 euros, to 64 euros.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase would give Terra _ a fast-growing European Internet
company _ a wide opening into North America to sell its Web
services to the expanding Hispanic population. And for Bertelsmann,
an alliance would broaden its global reach, allowing the
conglomerate to sell John Grisham novels through Lycos in the
United States or offer Carlos Santana music that can be downloaded
through Telefonica cellular phones in Europe or Terra portals in
Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   The executive said Telefonica would pay Bertelsmann an
undisclosed sum for a 25 percent stake in a new online bookstore
that it would create called Bol.com South America. Bertelsmann will
retain the other 75 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the executive said two European companies were
expected to sign a five-year agreement that would anoint
Bertelsmann as the ``preferred content provider'' on Lycos in the
United States in exchange for $1 billion. That designation means
that the company's products will get more prominent display,
advertising and special promotions through Lycos portal, which
ranks fourth in size in the United States in terms of visitors.
</P>
<P>
   Lycos and Bertelsmann now jointly own Lycos Europe, the
third-most- visited network of Web sites in Germany. The executive
said that the latest agreement called for Bertelsmann to
``consider'' folding the Lycos Europe operation with the U.S.
counterpart by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear Monday who would run the combined companies
after the deal brought together Terra, based in Madrid, and Lycos,
which is based in Waltham, Mass. And the negotiations had not
yielded a new name for the hybrid. The chief negotiators in the
initial discussions included the chairman of Telefonica, Juan
Villalonga, and the chief executive of Lycos, Bob Davis. Over the
last few weeks, Bertelsmann's chief executive, Thomas Middelhoff,
joined in the discussions that were continuing through Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that the pan-American alliance to a certain extent
reflected the very forces that prompted Time Warner and America
Online to unite in a company that mixed old media and new _ one
offering a rich source of content and the other an Internet
platform.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``The media is converging and you've got some very strong
players _ one from the old media and one from the new,'' said
Andrea Williams Rice, the managing director of Deutsche Bank in San
Francisco. ``There's an interest to bring together two players and
make the sum greater than its parts. Lycos could not very
effectively extend its reach into the old-line world. It would have
had to pay a lot of money to pay for the distribution that
Bertelsmann has. And until now, Bertelsmann has not been able to
build an online presence comparable to its offline position.''
</P>
<P>
   The one disadvantage that this new union could face is the
difficulty in integrating companies with three different national
cultures. ``The risk with every merger is that you're bringing
together a number of players with different backgrounds and
agendas,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Henry M. Blodget, an analyst with Merrill Lynch Global
Securities, said that the union gave the various companies a
powerful global reach. ``This fits into the ongoing theme of
consolidation where you have a few strong players continue to get
stronger by either merging with each other or acquiring smaller
companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Lycos has had other suitors in the past, but a union never
happened. Last year, Barry Diller's media company, USA Networks
Inc., tried to buy Lycos, but that pursuit collapsed because of
opposition from Lycos stockholders. The acquisition was canceled
last May amid objections from shareholders led by David Wetherell,
chairman of CMGI Inc., which owns about 15 percent of Lycos.
</P>
<P>
   Telefonica has also recently weathered a failed merger attempt,
with KPN Telecom of the Netherlands. At the behest of the Spanish
government, bankers on the company's board vetoed a $58 billion
merger that would have created Europe's fourth-largest phone
company, with a market value of $125 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
