<SLUG> BC-BKC-KNIGHT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Foul shots cost Bobby Knight
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Indiana basketball coach Bob Knight received ``one last chance''
Monday to clean up his act.
</P>
<P>
   University president Miles Brand announced that Knight would
return for his 30th season with the Hoosiers. The coach returns to
Bloomington, however, under a set of specific sanctions and
guidelines for his future behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Violation of any of the guidelines, Brand said, would be cause
for immediate termination.
</P>
<P>
   ``We view this as a zero-tolerance policy concerning his
behavior,'' Brand said at a news conference Monday in Indianapolis.
``These are very specific and very tough guidelines that show that
abusive and embarrassing behavior will not be tolerated.''
</P>
<P>
   Knight was not there, but John Walda, president of the IU board
of trustees read a statement from the coach that apologized for his
past actions and said he agreed with the new guidelines. Knight
left Monday for a long-planned trip to Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   Brand's announcement ended weeks of speculation that Knight, 59,
might be fired or might be forced to resign after an investigation
into his behavior. The investigation began with charges from former
player Neil Reed that Knight had choked him during a 1997 practice.
In April, a videotape confirming Reid's claim was made public.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taken collectively, (the incidents) represented a pattern of
behavior that had to be addressed,'' Brand said. ``And we feel like
we've done that.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Knight issued a public apology for his past
behavior and promised that in the future he would try to do a
better job of controlling his emotions. That evening, he met with
Brand for more than two hours, and the president outlined what
Knight would have to do to keep his job.
</P>
<P>
   ``If coach Knight had not agreed to any of these guidelines, I
would have recommended immediate termination,'' Brand said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he thought Knight could change his confrontational
personality after all these years, Brand said, ``I think he will
give it his very best effort. I, for one, believe he can do it.''
</P>
<P>
   With 763 career wins, Knight is just 116 away from the record of
879 held by former North Carolina coach Dean Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Knight's recent teams, however, have struggled in the NCAA
Tournament. Last season, the Hoosiers finished 20-9 after
Pepperdine eliminated them in the first round by 20 points.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
