u s BC-CAR-PETTY-FUNERAL-COX     05-15 0500
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-PETTY-FUNERAL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NASCAR family bids Petty farewell
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HIGH POINT, N.C. _ The crowd of more than 1,000 stood in silence
as Kyle and Patti Petty entered the gymnasium here Monday to honor
the memory of their oldest child.
</P>
<P>
   Both wore sunglasses to hide the tears. Others wept openly.
</P>
<P>
   The city was filled with friends and visitors from the NASCAR
community to pay final respects to Adam Petty, 19, who died Friday
in New Hampshire during practice for a Busch race. Bill Elliott,
Dale Jarrett, Ward Burton, John Andretti, Joe Nemechek, Ernie Irvan
and Jeff Burton were some of the Winston Cup drivers there.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Petty, Adam's famous grandfather, was without his
trademark cowboy hat. Walking slowly behind the entourage of more
than 100 cousins and relatives was Bobby Allison, who lost two
sons, NASCAR drivers Davey and Clifford, to premature deaths.
</P>
<P>
   ``My brother was killed while doing what he loved best _
racing,'' said Adam's 14-year old sister, Montgomery Lee. She and
Doug Carty, a retired minister and long-time friend of the Petty
family, were the only two to speak during the 45-minute service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now you're gone,'' she said, choking on tears. ``You won't be
here when I graduate. You won't be here when I marry. You won't be
here when I have my first-born, which will definitely have your
name.''
</P>
<P>
   Austin Petty, 18, has shared the same bedroom since birth with
his older brother. In a letter read by Carty, Austin praised Adam
for being a Christian role model and positive influence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Adam and I were so alike. ... Adam was just a little taller
and skinnier,'' the letter read. ``Even though it looked like I was
always mad when people mistaked me for him and asked for an
autograph, it didn't really bother me. . . . I know in my mind Adam
is in Heaven. He is in a better place right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pettys were the first family to have four generations drive
on the NASCAR circuit. Great-grandfather Lee Petty, who died on
April 5 at the age of 86, was one of the sport's first stars.
Richard Petty retired as the all-time leader in Winston Cup
victories with 200. Kyle, who has had a solid career, always had
other interests, including grooming his son's racing career.
</P>
<P>
   By spending so much time together at the race shop and track,
Kyle and Adam became almost inseparable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kyle told me last night, `Isn't it wonderful how father and
son were best friends?''' Carty said.
</P>
<P>
   Adam's lifelong dream was to race against his father in Winston
Cup. Adam qualified for his first event on the major league circuit
at Texas Motor Speedway in April, but Kyle did not make the field.
Kyle entered the race late as a replacement driver, but it was 13
laps after Adam had dropped out because of a blown engine.
</P>
<P>
   Father and son were going to try it again in two weeks at the
Coca-Cola 600 in Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
