<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 21:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5962 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-HKN-FLYERS-COACHES-CO     05-15 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-FLYERS-COACHES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Neilson coming back _ but going nowhere
 &HT;    By Guy Curtright
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ High above the ice at First Union Center, Roger
Neilson settles into his chair and pulls a headset over the tan
baseball cap that covers the remaining, wispy strands of his hair.
</P>
<P>
   The Philadelphia Flyers are one round away from the Stanley Cup
Finals, but Neilson no longer is really a part of the quest.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of being on the bench, he has been kicked upstairs,
literally. His only contributions are to act as an eye in the sky
and send notes down to interim coach Craig Ramsey about possible
adjustments to be made between periods. Neilson doesn't go to the
dressing room.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little strange,'' the coach concedes, the pain evident
on his weathered face despite a faint smile. ``But I'm trying to
make the best of the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Is this any way to treat a cancer patient?
</P>
<P>
   In December, the 65-year-old Neilson was diagnosed with multiple
myeloma, a malignant cancer that strikes plasma cells. He continued
to coach through two months of chemotherapy, but he finally had to
leave the team to undergo a stem-cell transplant on March 10.
</P>
<P>
   Losing last shot at Stanley Cup?
</P>
<P>
   Neilson says he was promised he could return as coach when he
recovered. He knew this would be his best _ and probably last _
chance to lead a team to the Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   But Neilson did not get his job back for the first round of the
playoffs. Then, before the Flyers played Pittsburgh in the second
round, Neilson's hopes were dashed for good. General manger Bobby
Clarke met with Neilson and told him that he would not be returning
to the bench at all for the playoffs. Ramsey, the interim coach,
would lead the team.
</P>
<P>
   Clarke said it was because Neilson was not healthy enough to
withstand the rigors of coaching. Many people thought Neilson was
being pushed aside because Ramsey had led the Flyers to a 16-8-1
record to close the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   A disappointed Neilson lashed out on a radio talk show in
Canada. ``I don't think they want a cancer patient who's a friend
of (former captain) Eric Lindros behind the bench right now,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Contract is up
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Neilson tempered his words. ``I felt I was the coach
of the team, and if I was ready to coach, I should be coaching,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   It was the possibility of returning to his team that pushed
Neilson through the grueling cancer treatments.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I erred on the side of encouraging Roger too much, I'm
guilty,'' Dr. Isadore Brodsky said.
</P>
<P>
   Clarke said, ``The scary thing is, Roger almost put coaching
ahead of his health. People always say health is the most important
thing. In this case, it's been like, `To heck with my health, I
want to coach.'''
</P>
<P>
   But no matter how well Neilson recovers, it is assumed in
Philadelphia that Ramsey will remain as coach next season.
Neilson's contract is up. In April, he told reporters that he and
Clarke had agreed in principle to a two-year extension. Clarke
denied any agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Neilson knows what can happen when a team gets hot for an
interim coach. He took over at Vancouver when Harry Neale was given
a 10-game suspension late in the 1981-82 season, and Neale didn't
get the job back. Neilson led the Canucks to the Stanley Cup
Finals.
</P>
<P>
   Ramsey, 49, played for Neilson in junior hockey and with the
Buffalo Sabres. He was an assistant under him at Florida before
joining the Flyers.
</P>
<P>
   Tough situation for Ramsey
</P>
<P>
   Ramsey is in a no-win situation, which has nothing to do with
the Flyers being down 1-0 to New Jersey going into Game 2 tonight
in the Eastern Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a tremendous amount of respect for Roger,'' he said.
``But when I took over, it had to be my team. I have to coach that
way. There's no other way to do it. It can't work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said from Day 1, Roger and I are similar but we are not
the same, and there would be subtle differences. I've never
thought, `What would Roger do?'''
</P>
<P>
   Neilson said about Ramsey, ``He's a guy who doesn't get
flustered, and that gives the team an air of confidence. I think
he's the kind of coach players like playing for because he doesn't
panic and he doesn't get overtly excited.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Neilson, Ramsey has had to battle a serious health crisis.
In 1993, Ramsey found out he had peptic-ulcer disease, and doctors
had to remove his stomach to save his life. Ramsey's small
intestine now is connected directly to his esophagus.
</P>
<P>
   Neilson stood by Ramsey then. Ramsey says he wants to be there
for Neilson now. They were angered last week when a columnist said
that they no longer were speaking to each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where they get these things, I don't know,'' Neilson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``To just make up a story out of the blue, just because you feel
like it, is completely irresponsible,'' Ramsey said.
</P>
<P>
   Neilson showed up at practice Friday and put on skates for the
first time in three months.
</P>
<P>
   ``He must be feeling better, can do a little more,'' rookie
goalie Brian Boucher said. ``We want to see him around.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was great to see him out there,'' defenseman Chris Therien
said. ``He joked that he hasn't lost a step. Everybody in this room
loves Roger, and it's great to have him around.''
</P>
<P>
   But when the Flyers play the Devils tonight, Neilson won't be on
the bench or in the dressing room. He will be looking down from
above.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
