<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jury selection starts for Ray Lewis trial
 &HT;    By Bill Torpy
 &HT;    and Bill Rankin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NFL star Ray Lewis spent his 25th birthday Monday with a
courtroom full of Fulton County residents, some of whom will hold
his fate in their hands.
</P>
<P>
   Jury selection in the high-profile murder trial started with
Superior Court Judge Alice Bonner excusing more than a third of the
jury pool. The remaining 89 potential jurors then answered general
questions from defense lawyers and prosecutors in a process that is
expected to last the rest of the week.
</P>
<P>
   Fulton County District Attorney Paul Howard said he will help
prosecute the case, the first time he has done so since taking over
the office more than three years ago. Also, Howard's team during
the weekend secured the testimony of Rehana Grant, one of the women
riding with Lewis in his rented limousine the night of the
killings. Grant has been given immunity in exchange for her
testimony, according to her lawyer, Cynthia Roseberry. Grant is the
third person in the limo to get immunity.
</P>
<P>
   Two large jury pools filled four benches throughout the
questioning. Lewis, dressed in a conservative double-breasted suit,
glanced up infrequently and rarely made eye contact with the
jurors.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis and his friends Reginald Oakley and Joseph Sweeting are
charged in the Jan. 31 stabbing deaths of Decatur residents Richard
Lollar and Jacinth Baker. The killings occurred in a fight on a
Buckhead street hours after the Super Bowl at the Georgia Dome.
Lewis' lead attorney, Ed Garland, asked jurors if a stranger had
ever picked a fight with them, if they were ever mugged or if they
had ever feared for their life.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeting's attorneys, Steve Sadow and John Bergendahl, asked
jury pool members how many had ever had to defend themselves.
Thirty-one raised their hands. They also asked the jury pool if
anyone had used a weapon in self-defense. Five had.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, they asked if anyone had ever been shot at. Lewis'
limo was hit by five gunshots as it sped away. No one raised their
hand. Bruce Harvey said his client, Oakley, was struck over the
head with a champagne bottle during the fight. Harvey then asked if
anyone ever saw a bottle used as a weapon. Seventeen had.
</P>
<P>
   Also, forensic DNA expert Henry Lee, who impressed jurors while
working for O.J. Simpson's defense team, is now listed as a
prosecution witness.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
