<SLUG> BC-RAC-PREAKNESS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The big Preakness favorites
 &HT;    By John Crittenden
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two months before he won the Florida Derby, Hal's Hope finished
first in the Holy Bull Stakes at Gulfstream Park at odds of 40-1.
</P>
<P>
   The Florida-bred owned and trained by Harold Rose may be back in
the same category when the last bet is made on Saturday for the
Preakness Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   Interest still runs high in the colt's 88-year-old trainer. But
Hal's Hope, the star of the Florida winter season, has fallen to
the back of the pack in the betting favorites for the second event
of thoroughbred racing's Triple Crown.
</P>
<P>
   Last in the Blue Grass Stakes and the 16th horse to reach the
finish line in the Kentucky Derby, Hal's Hope is listed at 40-1 for
the Preakness at Pimlico Race Course in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   In the early betting line supplied by Las Vegas Sports
Consultants, Fusaichi Pegasus, the Kentucky Derby champion on May
6, is a 1-2 betting favorite.
</P>
<P>
   The final line will be determined by the bets on race day.
</P>
<P>
   A maximum of eight starters are expected for the Preakness, not
a supririse considering the one-sided nature of the finish of
Fusaichi Pegasus at Churchill Downs.
</P>
<P>
   Odds on the other six starters: Red Bullet 5-1, High Yield 7-1,
Imeachment 10-1, Captain Steve 10-1, Snuck In 10-1 and Hugh Hefner
75-1.
</P>
<P>
   Trainer John Kimmel announced Monday that Wheelaway, the Tampa
Bay Derby champion and fifth in the Kentucky Derby, will not enter
the Preakness. ``We'll get the horse ready for the Belmont
Stakes,'' said Kimmel, who is based at Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   Trainer Todd Pletcher, who entered four horses in the Kentucky
Derby, may start just one in Baltimore. More Than Ready is unlikely
to run, but Impeachment, third in the Derby, is a probable
Preakness starter.
</P>
<P>
   Red Bullet, Hal's Hope and High Yield, trained by Wayne Lukas,
are at Pimlico. Fusaichi Pegasus, Captain Steve, Snuck In are to be
flown in Wednesday from Louisville. Pletcher's horses are at his
Belmont barn. Hugh Hefner, to be ridden by Victor Espinoza, is
scheduled to come in by plane from California late in the week.
</P>
<P>
   johncrittenden(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
