</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MERRILL-FINE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERRILL LYNCH SETTLES CHARGES IN ROGUE BROKER CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Richard F. Greene was more than Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co.'s
biggest broker. He was part legend in Boston, where clients liked
to drop his name and everybody knew him downtown.
</P>
<P>
   But he could cost Merrill more than $30 million in the coming
months, as the Wall Street giant settles charges with Massachusetts
securities regulators that it failed to properly oversee the
retired broker and his risky investment strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Greene's is the fourth recent case where the firm allegedly lost
control of its brokers in this region, including one fraud charge
and two instances of improper trading. Merrill calls these isolated
incidents, but regulators worry that even the most venerable firms
in the business are failing to detect _ and are perhaps overlooking
_ rogue behavior by brokers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're making sure companies adhere to their own codes of
conduct and they sufficiently supervise their brokers,'' Secretary
of State William F. Galvin said. With a big firm like Merrill, he
added, ``The reliability of a brand name is really what's at
stake.''
</P>
<P>
   This is, after all, the biggest broker on Wall Street and not a
hard-sell factory of the ``Boiler Room'' movie variety. But the
state has spent the better part of the past year investigating
Merrill Lynch here.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill admitted no wrongdoing in the Greene case. But it has
agreed to pay $750,000, the biggest fine ever handed down by the
state securities division, and to negotiate payments with Greene's
clients, who claim to have lost more than $50 million on four
stocks he was pushing in the final stretch of his 38-year tenure
with Merrill.
</P>
<P>
   The fine and settlement also cover the misdeeds of Donald J.
Martineau, a longtime Boston broker who pleaded guilty to federal
fraud charges in February. He stole $9 million from clients between
1989 and 1998 to fund his options-trading account, telling them the
money was being placed in a real estate investment that didn't
exist.
</P>
<P>
   Other Merrill problems include John E. David, a former
Manchester, N.H., broker, who is being sued by customers who say
they lost $4.4 million from 1994 to 1997 on stocks he misled them
into buying. And there's also Donald C. Sarin, a Pittsfield broker
who traded his client's account heavily after she died in 1997, to
earn commissions for himself. His trades cost the victim's heirs
nearly $1 million; Merrill settled with them for about half that
amount.
</P>
<P>
   Both brokers have denied any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   What the four cases have in common is a lack of supervision,
regulators charge. Paul Fehrenbach, manager of the Boston office,
and his deputy, Kevin Chase, had responsibility for Greene,
Martineau, and the New Hampshire office. Sarin should have been
supervised by a manager in Stamford, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   In each instance, securities division chief Matthew Nestor said,
compliance officials in the regions and in New York should have
caught on to the schemes. The state has ordered Merrill to hire a
consultant within 30 days to review its compliance policies in
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill insists Greene's is an entirely different case from
those of the other three brokers, whom the firm fired when it
learned of their activities.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesman Bill Halldin calls Greene's a ``distinguished career''
as a financial consultant, ``helping countless clients
significantly increase the value of their investments and providing
excellent service.''
</P>
<P>
   Greene had five assistants, a stunning roster of 1,400 wealthy
clients, and $1.5 billion of their money under his watch. He made
big profits for people over the years, often betting large sums of
money on a few stocks a time. And he became a very rich man
himself.
</P>
<P>
   Customers say service with Greene was about hot stock picks.
Many people say they never talked to him for more than 30 seconds
at a time. Typically, one of his assistants would call to reach a
customer. They'd wait on hold, then Greene would come on, ask if a
buy order was OK, and hang up when the customer said yes.
</P>
<P>
   To say ``no'' was not typical if you wanted to do business with
Dick Greene, customers and regulators said.
</P>
<P>
   It was Greene's sudden and quiet retirement at age 65, in
December 1998, that took clients by surprise and perhaps sparked
the outrage over losses in accounts with huge concentrations in
four stocks: Indymac Mortgage Holdings Inc., Genesis Health
Ventures Inc., Orbital Sciences Corp., and Eldertrust Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Greene didn't tell clients he was retiring to Arizona. He didn't
send out letters. Nor did the firm. Instead, longtime clients
learned the news when they received calls from the new brokers
assigned to their accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Halldin, the Merrill spokesman, said problems with four brokers
out of 250 in the region is a small number. ``In any large
organization, you're going to have employees who violate
policies,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That said, Halldin added, ``We take the enforcement of our
policies and procedures very seriously and continuously take new
steps to enhance our efforts.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the settlement, Merrill must pay an
additional $100,000 to cover the cost of the state's investigation.
And it has agreed to mediations with Greene clients who had more
than half the assets of their Merrill accounts in the four losing
stocks that Greene recommended.
</P>
<P>
   Pete Michals, a Boston lawyer representing more than 20 of
Greene's former clients, said, ``We remain hopeful that the
mediation process will address our clients' concerns. But to be
successful, mediation requires a good-faith effort from all
parties.''
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch must bear the cost of the mediations, which could
run $3,000 to $5,000 per one-day session. Customers must request a
mediation, in a letter to Merrill, within six months. The division
will pick the mediator. Anyone not satisfied with the amounts
offered by Merrill in those meetings can take his or her case to
normal arbitration, before a panel of the National Association of
Securities Dealers, which regulates the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Halldin said 60 customers have complained about Greene's
investment picks for them since he retired.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will look seriously at any concern that anyone raises in
the overall picture of their financial portfolios,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
