<HEADER>
A5967 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MARKET-NYT &LR;      05-15 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALL ST. JITTERS RISE BEFORE FED RATES DO ON INFLATION CONCERN 
</HEADLINE>
   By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As Federal Reserve policy makers meet Tuesday,
investors are wondering more about what comes next than by how much
the central bank will raise its short-term interest rate target
when it announces its decision early in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street is forecasting an increase of half a percentage
point in the central bank's federal funds target rate on overnight
loans, raising that target to 6.5 percent. Until recently, most
analysts had expected a quarter-point move, matching the five
increases the Fed has made since June.
</P>
<P>
   But, more importantly, most analysts think that the Fed will
have to move well above 6.5 percent, perhaps this summer, before
economic growth is curbed and new inflationary pressures are
contained. And if inflation data worsens _ as some signs now
indicate _ the outlook may shift to even higher rates.
</P>
<P>
   Investors ``are going to see the decision, then immediately
thoughts will jump ahead,'' said Ethan Harris, senior economist at
Lehman Bros. ``How much more do we have to go?''
</P>
<P>
   What all this means for the stock market, however, is hard to
predict, both immediately and in the near term. Monday, equity and
bond investors did not seem concerned.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average rose 198.41 points, or 1.9
percent, to 10,807.78, while the Nasdaq composite index climbed
78.59 points, or 2.2 percent, to 3,607.65. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index jumped 31.40 points, or 2.2 percent, to 1,452.36.
But all three indexes are below where they were when the new,
disturbing data on inflation began appearing April 27.
</P>
<P>
   In the bond market, prices rose as yields, which move in the
opposite direction, fell. The Treasury's 10-year note rose 15/32,
to 100 14/32, with its yield falling to 6.44 percent Monday, from
6.51 percent on Friday. The yield remains well above the 6.13
percent on April 26.
</P>
<P>
   The size of the Fed's rate increase and the outlook statement it
will issue Tuesday with the announcement could have a crucial
bearing on the markets. The April report on consumer prices, which
is expected to be released this morning ahead of the Fed meeting,
could also have a major impact.
</P>
<P>
   If the Consumer Price Index's monthly increase, especially in
the core inflation rate that excludes food and energy, is
surprisingly big, as it was in March, both the bond and stock
markets could have sell-offs. With such a surprise, investors would
immediately speculate that interest rates would have to move much
higher this year, no matter how aggressive the Fed is Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   However, analysts are forecasting a tame CPI, with the core rate
up 0.2 percent and the overall rate flat or up just 0.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The change in the atmosphere on Wall Street has been almost
palpable over the last three weeks. In that time, new employment
figures have shown the economy still to be growing briskly, and new
data on prices and wage-and-benefit costs have signaled that
inflationary pressures are building.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got this overpowering private sector demand in conjunction
with some real inflation sparks,'' said Robert V. DiClemente, chief
U.S. economist at Salomon Smith Barney. ``This is not a false
alarm,'' he said of the data pointing to higherinflation rates.
</P>
<P>
   The new data forced him to raise his forecast for the Fed's
short-term interest rate target to 7.5 percent by the end of the
year, from 6.75 percent. Harris of Lehman said his firm's forecast
was now for a Fed funds target of 7.25 percent by August, up from
6.75 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Various indicators of investor sentiment on the Fed also show
expectations that rates will move much higher than thought just a
few weeks ago. For example, on April 24, the federal funds futures
contract for September indicated that investors expected an average
rate of 6.45 percent for September. That average for September has
now jumped to 6.93 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Harris said ``it will be hard to find a silver lining'' in
Tuesday's Fed action if, as he expects, the Fed does raise its
target by half a percentage point and signals that inflation is
still a concern, meaning that more rate increases are in the
offing. While Lehman is in the minority, he said there is better
than a 50 percent chance the Fed will raise its target another half
a percentage point when policymakers meet in the last week of June.
</P>
<P>
   What might soothe the markets some, he said, is the expected
increase of half a percentage point and a neutral statement that
investors could interpret to mean that Fed policymakers do not
think rates have to be pushed much higher. In 1994, the Fed made
two increases of half a percentage point each in its interest rate
target that came with such neutral outlook statements. Both the
bond and stock markets rallied. But Harris does not expect such a
soothing statement this time and in 1994 the Fed ended up pushing
rates much higher, despite the reassuring statements.
</P>
<P>
   DiClemente said that a surprisingly big increase in the core
rate of the Consumer Price Index, just a quarter-point rate
increase in the Fed's interest rate target or a soothing statement
from the Fed about the outlook for inflation could end up troubling
investors in the longer term. In all cases, he said it would be
possible for investors to begin to worry that the Fed was not
acting aggressively enough to curb inflation by slowing economic
growth.
</P>
<P>
   If that opinion begins to influence investors, he said, two bad
things could happen: First, investors would believe the Fed would
have to make bigger-than-expected rate increases later to regain
the offensive against inflation. More importantly, the threat of
larger rate increases and being behind in the fight to curb
inflation would make investors fear a ``hard landing'' for the
economy. That is Wall Street jargon for the threat of a recession.
</P>
<P>
   But DiClemente said if the Fed raised its interest rate target
half a percentage point and if the core CPI figure rose just 0.2
percent, then these might be comforting because investors would not
conclude that the Fed was losing the battle. That is what he is
predicting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-00 2109EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
