<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 21:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5971 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-HAMILTON-JORDAN16-COX     05-15 1856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAMILTON-JORDAN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For survivor like Hamilton Jordan, no such thing as living in
the past
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boll Weevils are up 3-0 on the Lookouts in the top of the
second inning, and have a chance to score again. At first base, the
man in tightly laced sneakers, sweat socks, black shorts and a
baseball cap pulled low over his brow is barking encouragement from
the coach's box.
</P>
<P>
   At the plate, a batter for the Boll Weevils lays off a low
pitch, and the umpire calls ball two.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good eye, good eye,'' Hamilton Jordan shouts, hands cupped to
his mouth. ``Find one you like.''
</P>
<P>
   It is the language of the sandlots, of childhood, of eternal
springtimes when someone will lose a game but life lasts forever.
</P>
<P>
   The players on the field at Frankie Allen Park are 8 and 9 years
old. If most know who the president of the United States is, few
could tell you much about the Iranian hostage crisis, the energy
crisis or crises of any kind. The world they know is Buckhead and
adjacent enclaves, all green with prosperity and promise.
</P>
<P>
   But many know that the man coaching first base for the Boll
Weevils _ as a woman in the stands told the boy beside her _ once
``worked for President Carter. It was before you were born.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years after what he dismisses as his ``15 minutes of
fame,'' Hamilton Jordan is used to being identified as who he once
was. At the Randolph School in Huntsville, Ala., where he went
recently to give a talk about his experiences with cancer, a
handsome brochure bears the words ``Hamilton Jordan, Former White
House Chief of Staff.''
</P>
<P>
   Titles come and go, and White House chiefs of staff can exit
faster than they entered. But Jordan, at 55, would have you believe
he has larger fish to fry than congressmen and Cabinet secretaries
wanting 15 minutes with the president of the United States, not to
mention the door-pounding Washington media. If the president is the
most powerful man in the world, his chief of staff might be second:
He is the gatekeeper to the Oval Office, trusted adviser and
guardian of secrets.
</P>
<P>
   It is a harder job than coaching first base, but all jobs have
their challenges, and some, it turns out, are closer to the marrow
of life than one might have thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``Got your mitt?'' he asks as 8-year-old Alex Jordan straps on
the catcher's gear between innings. The chest protector is on, the
shin guards are on and the mitt is in hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, go get 'em, son,'' the catcher's dad says.
</P>
<P>
   He has the purposeful stride of a football coach _ muscular
legs, broad beam, white athletic socks snug against his calves.
Soccer moms aren't taken as seriously as baseball dads, but nobody
said life was fair.
</P>
<P>
   When power fades
</P>
<P>
   Three times since 1985 Hamilton Jordan has listened as doctors
told him he had cancer _ first lymphoma, then melanoma, then
prostate cancer. Each time he chose aggressive treatment, and each
time he dodged a malignant bullet. And then, a few years ago,
Jordan and his wife, Dorothy, learned that daughter Kathleen,
second of their three children, had juvenile diabetes and would
need daily insulin injections.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us, sooner or later, are going to get a bad report,''
Jordan says, but he doesn't believe in waiting by the phone. He
paraphrases a line in a Bonnie Raitt song he likes: ``Life gets
more precious when there's less of it to waste.''
</P>
<P>
   In his new book, ``No Such Thing as a Bad Day'' (Longstreet
Press, $22), the architect of Jimmy Carter's improbable nomination
for the presidency tells how quickly power and position fade to
irrelevance and how one's sense of proportion can change between
his 30s and his 50s. The pundits of the Sunday talk shows may be
pains in the butt, but they are not pathologists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Amen,'' his old sidekick Jody Powell says by phone from
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The two of them are oldies-but-goodies from the 1970s, like the
Eagles and Fleetwood Mac. Powell was Carter's dry-witted press
secretary _ the best ever to have held the job, some think. Jordan
was the crafty rube who picked up a reputation for enjoying himself
too much in Georgetown bars and not returning calls. For members of
Congress put off by a brash outsider, there was also the matter of
getting used to the name. Barbara Jordan they knew, and the king of
Jordan. But this was Hamilton ``Jerdun,'' as Southern as sorghum.
</P>
<P>
   The speaker of the House, Tip O'Neill, never quite got the hang
of it and on occasion called him Hannibal Jerkin.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan made for good copy (``They say he was something of a
rogue in his day,'' a young man in his 20s admiringly tells a
friend minutes before Jordan's recent talk in Huntsville). He
showed up for White House press briefings in tennis clothes, once
called Zbigniew Brzezinski, Carter's national security adviser,
``Woody Woodpecker'' because of his spiky hair, and was accused of
appreciating too openly the bosom of the Egyptian ambassador's
wife.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was the baseless rumor that Jordan had used
cocaine at Studio 54 in New York. After an investigation, a federal
grand jury voted 24-0 against bringing an indictment.
</P>
<P>
   Happy to be alive
</P>
<P>
   It was all a long time ago. Powell's voice hasn't changed in 20
years, but he wants to tell you about his three grandchildren. Tip
O'Neill is dead and Jordan is happy just to be alive. His laugh is
a rich cackle, usually directed at himself. ``Hi darlin','' he says
into the car phone. His wife is telling him something that amuses
him, and to a person of a certain age he sounds a little like the
Big Bopper.
</P>
<P>
   They hang up and Jordan resumes a story about himself and Powell
in their salad days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody told Jody once he was the best White Press spokesman
in modern times, and Jody says, `If I was so good, then why did we
get such crappy press?'''
</P>
<P>
   He can indulge a rueful laugh on Powell's behalf, but still _
more than 20 years later _ goes out of his way to explain why it
wasn't his job to return calls that long ago lost their urgency.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'd be 5 o'clock and you'd find there were 50 people you were
supposed to call,'' he says from the wheel of a 1990 Lexus that he
admits hasn't been cleaned in a while. ``All of them think they're
the only one. And some of 'em I wasn't the person they needed to
talk to. Jody dealt with the press, Frank Moore dealt with the
Congress. But people started saying I didn't return calls, and
pretty soon the label stuck. No, I don't miss it at all.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't stop him from running, unsuccessfully, for the U.S.
Senate in 1986, but even that was three jobs back. He worked for
Whittle Communications in Knoxville for two years and was executive
director of the Association of Tennis Professionals for three
years. Today Jordan has a hand in a number of start-up companies,
many focusing on health, education and the media. In 1982 _ two
years before he learned he had cancer _ he and his wife founded
Camp Sunshine, a program for children with cancer or leukemia, and
they have begun a camp for children with juvenile diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably get 10 to 15 calls a week from people I don't know
who have cancer,'' he says. He has become an advocate, urging
people to educate themselves, act boldly and seek the best
treatment they can.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't ever want to forget the raw fear of death,'' he says.
``Today I lead a life I don't take for granted.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan came to prominence as a shrewd political infighter,
someone who, his own mother once said, had been ``a political
animal'' since childhood. ``If he didn't run himself, he'd run his
cousin,'' she told Kandy Stroud, author of the 1977 book ``How
Jimmy Won.''
</P>
<P>
   But politics doesn't enter Jordan's conversation much these
days. He is informed, but willing to let others do the analyzing.
``As I've gotten older,'' he says, ``I've gotten more conservative,
more cynical about what government can and cannot do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he's lost interest in politics,'' says Powell.
``My sense of it is that it has more to do with the change in the
political process over the years _ how much more nasty and partisan
politics has become.''
</P>
<P>
   Jay Beck, who was in Jordan's Cub Scout troop in Albany and
worked in the White House during the Carter years, recalls how
public affairs shaped Hamilton's boyhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were the kind of family that, when you went over and had
dinner, they talked about politics, books, the world,'' Beck says.
``Hamilton was always interested in politics. He took a year off
from going to the University of Georgia to work on Carter's
gubernatorial campaign in 1966. He always had this ability to
focus, but I think having cancer and having children have given him
even more. Every day means more now. He goes to every school play,
every soccer game, every baseball game.''
</P>
<P>
   A winning day
</P>
<P>
   It is a Saturday afternoon, and the sun is high in the sky.
Baseball games are in progress throughout Frankie Allen Park.
Parents and children are encamped in bleachers, many in sunglasses.
At 1 o'clock the temperature is on its way toward 80 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton Jordan is the only man in sight wearing long sleeves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two outs, guys _ run on anything,'' Jordan barks from first
base. He's good on the fundamentals, as baseball buffs like to say.
</P>
<P>
   The Boll Weevils would go on to win 10-0, the bags would be
packed and the players would trot off, knowing they would play
another day.
</P>
<P>
   As such games go, this one was easy, soon to be forgotten by
8-year-olds in the kaleidoscope of experience. It means more to
their coach than to the players. Into the sunshine he walks off _
wife and daughter on one side, son on the other _ like a man happy
to have taken it into extra innings.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton Jordan
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Born: 1944 in Charlotte, but grew up in Albany.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Residence: Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Family: Married to Dorothy Henry Jordan, a pediatric oncology
nurse, since December 1981. Three children: Hamilton Jr., 16;
Kathleen, 11; Alex, 8.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Education: Bachelor's degree from the University of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Occupation: Investor in a number of small businesses,
including Entremed, LexCaRe and Global Medical Products; vice
chairman of nschool.com; board adviser to Time Domain, a
Huntsville, Ala., research company.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Board duties: Emory University Board of Visitors; the Lasker
Foundation; Brady Clinic of Johns Hopkins University; First
Funding, a national effort to increase federal funding for medical
research.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Quote: ``I did a lot of bad things when I was young, but one
thing I didn't do was smoke.''
</P>
<P>
   Book signings
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton Jordan speaks at
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m. May 24 at the Atlanta History Center, McElreath Hall, 130
W. Paces Ferry Road N.W. Admission is free, but seating is limited;
R.S.V.P. to 404-814-4150 A reception and book signing will follow.
Jordan will also sign books at 7 p.m. June 7 at Chapter 11
bookstore in Peachtree Battle shopping center, 2345 Peachtree Road
N.E., 404-237-7199.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
