r l BC-HEARING-AIDS16-COX     05-15 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARING-AIDS16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Disposable hearing aid a boon to boomers
 &HT;    By Diane Lore
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The world's first disposable hearing aid might become the newest
rite of passage for hard-living baby boomers who have already
snapped up such products as disposable contact lenses, seamless bi-
and trifocals, Rogaine for hair loss and Viagra for impotence.
</P>
<P>
   For about a $2 a day, people with mild to moderate hearing loss
can try out a pair of ``Songbird'' disposable hearing aids, which
are designed to last about five weeks. The new devices will be
available in more than a dozen cities nationally this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very, very excited about this,'' said Helena Solodar, a
partner of Audiological Consultants of Atlanta, which will be
offering the devices. ``I think this product is going to
dramatically change how people view hearing aids.''
</P>
<P>
   Although more than 28 million Americans suffer from hearing
loss, fewer than one-fifth of them use a hearing aid, according to
Frederick Fritz, Songbird Medical's chief executive officer. That's
mostly because of the cost, which ranges from $900 to $3,000, and
to hearing aids' negative image.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're seen as a hassle to buy and a hassle to use,'' Fritz
said. ``And boomers see hearing aids as something for old and
disabled people.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet, increasingly, boomers _ an estimated 5 million of whom
are experiencing serious hearing loss _ need such devices. ``It
used to be that the average age in our waiting room was 75 years
old,'' said Solodar. ``Now it's dropped down to about 60 years old,
with a lot more patients in their 40s and 50s.''
</P>
<P>
   Songbird is aiming squarely at those younger patients. Even its
marketing pitch is different from its forerunners'. Whereas ads for
most hearing aids have concentrated on better technology, the
Songbird is hitting on two key points: affordability through
disposability and lifestyle vs. age. The company is trying to
convince people that hearing aids are no longer just for old
fogeys, but for people who live life loud.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it will become a badge of honor,'' Fritz said.
``But certainly we will be pushing the idea that noise pollution,
and not necessarily age, is the cause of your hearing loss.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 10 million Americans have permanent, irreversible
hearing loss from noise or trauma, according to the National
Institute on Deafness and Other Communication Disorders, part of
the National Institutes of Health. And more than 30 million people
are exposed to injurious levels of noise daily in the workplace. In
fact, noise-induced hearing loss is the most common occupational
ailment and the second most common self-reported injury, according
to the National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are losing our hearing at a younger age,'' said Marin
Allen, spokeswoman for the National Institute on Deafness. ``We're
living in a noisier, louder environment. Certainly, grandmother
didn't have hair dryers, blenders and leaf blowers.''
</P>
<P>
   Or loud music, whether it be rock or opera. And the music _
paired with louder industrial equipment _ may account for one major
difference between baby boomers and previous generations.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, men and women reported losing their hearing at
about the same rate. Now, twice as many male as female boomers
report hearing loss.
</P>
<P>
   For this reason, Songbird designed its one-size-fits-all hearing
aid to fit primarily men's slightly larger ear canal.
</P>
<P>
   And because the Songbird, which took four years to develop, is
disposable, scientists changed the design from conventional aids in
other ways. Because it doesn't need space for a replaceable
battery, it uses a microphone seven times larger than those of most
designs. It also has a soft silicone tip that can be molded deeply
into the ear canal, which would not be feasible if the aid had to
last longer than 40 days. It is not designed to be taken in and
out, and a prescription is written for one of the pre-programmed
acoustic levels so a wearer doesn't have to make frequent volume
adjustments.
</P>
<P>
   But the bottom-line cost of the Songbird is not significantly
lower than permanent hearing aids. A typical user would have to buy
two Songbirds approximately once a month, at an out-of-pocket
expense of about $80 a month, which puts it in the same range as a
$1,500 hearing aid that lasts a couple of years.
</P>
<P>
   But the Songbird could prove useful for those who want to
experiment or merely use it for special occasions, such as a family
reunion or an important business meeting, Solodar said. And, though
hearing researchers won't predict how well Songbird _ four years in
development _ will fly in the marketplace, they say it could help
more people get up the nerve to at least try hearing aids.
</P>
<P>
   On average, patients wait eight to 10 years from the moment they
suspect they have hearing loss to the point where they seek a
hearing aid consultation, Solodar said. But if the cost and stigma
of hearing aids are greatly reduced, more people may seek help
sooner.
</P>
<P>
   ``People wait too long to get the assistance _ they've got too
much permanent damage,'' Allen said. ``This might encourage more
people to at least get their hearing tested.''
</P>
<P>
   Diane Lore writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
