<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 21:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5973 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-NBC-FALLSKED16-COX     05-15 1016
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NBC-FALLSKED16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Black actors land new roles on NBC
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The face of network television may be changing this
fall. NBC has several African-Americans featured in its seven new
fall shows, including David Alan Grier in ``DAG,'' a comedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody I know got a deal,'' Grier said Monday, referring to
black actors who were in demand during this spring's pilot season.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall's TV season was famous for its dearth of
African-Americans on new shows, and the subsequent threats of
boycotts and meetings between the networks and the NAACP and other
groups.
</P>
<P>
   Grier said the networks were paying attention to minority
casting as a direct result of the furor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, if it'll help me, I'll be out tomorrow with Al
Sharpton,'' he joked at an NBC party following the network's
presentation to advertisers, the first in a weeklong series known
as the ``upfronts'' (because the advertisers then buy spots up
front, before the season starts).
</P>
<P>
   In ``DAG,'' Grier plays Jerome Daggett, a Secret Service agent
who is assigned to the B team covering the first lady (Delta Burke
of ``Designing Women''). Another African-American, Mel Jackson,
plays a fellow agent and appeared prominently in the clips shown to
advertisers. ``DAG'' will air at 9:30 p.m. Tuesdays.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Steven Weber Show,'' an ensemble comedy about a man who
is hexed by a former blind date, Weber's boss is Wendell Pierce, a
black actor from ``Third Watch.'' The show will air at 8:30 p.m.
Thursdays.
</P>
<P>
   Richards still Kramer-esque
</P>
<P>
   NBC's biggest ``new'' star may have his work cut out for him.
``The Michael Richards Show,'' starring the once-and-future Kramer
from ``Seinfeld,'' was described by NBC Entertainment President
Garth Ancier as ``a quirky physical comedy'' in which Richards
plays ``a modern-day Inspector Clouseau.'' At NBC's presentation at
the Metropolitan Opera House, Richards made an elaborate,
prat-falling entrance from the audience to the stage, knocking over
a camerman and dismantling a microphone. But when a five-minute
clip was shown of Richards as a private detective driving over
flowerbeds there was virtually no laughter in the audience of ad
agency buyers and affiliate managers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Richards'' is scheduled to air at 8 p.m. Tuesdays. Don't be
surprised if there is talk of ``retooling'' along the way,
network-speak for ``it didn't work the first time, so we're
completely redoing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Laughter in all the wrong places
</P>
<P>
   Even more ominous, there was plenty of laughter during the clips
for ``Titans,'' an unabashedly steamy soap opera from Aaron
Spelling that will air at 8 p.m. Wednesdays, the time slot
Spelling's ``Beverly Hills 90210'' will vacate after Wednesday's
finale. Ancier called the show ``a total guilty pleasure,'' and the
clips were heavy on rich people having extramarital sex. Yasmine
Bleeth, Casper Van Dien and Victoria Principal are among the stars.
</P>
<P>
   `Today' goes to three hours
</P>
<P>
   The ``Today'' show will expand to three hours from two starting
in September, running from 7 a.m. to 10 a.m., NBC News announced.
The existing ``Later Today'' will air at 10 a.m. in 13 cities with
NBC owned-and-operated stations. Atlanta is not among these.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today'' co-anchors Katie Couric and Matt Lauer, as well as
news anchor Ann Curry and weatherman Al Roker, will participate in
the third hour, which will be formatted similarly to the second
hour of the existing program.
</P>
<P>
   Also new from NBC
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Tucker,'' a comedy about a 15-year-old boy (Eli Marienthal)
who is forced to live with his aunt (Katey Sagal of ``Married ...
With Children''). It will air at 8:30 p.m. Tuesdays.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Ed,'' a comedy-drama about a nice-guy lawyer (Tom Cavanagh)
fired from his high-income job, who moves back to his small town,
buys a bowling alley and tries to woo his high-school crush. It
will air at 8 p.m. Sundays, a difficult time slot competing against
``The Simpsons'' and ``Touched by an Angel.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Deadline,'' a drama created by Dick Wolf (``Law &AMP; Order'').
Oliver Platt stars as a newspaper columnist who uses college
students to help him investigate crimes. It's set for 9 p.m.
Mondays.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Finally, theatrical movies will air from 8 to 11 p.m. Saturday
nights, but with a twist. Online viewers will be able to play
trivia quizzes based on the movie and the ads being shown and
compete to win $100,000. The movies will disappear in February and
be replaced by ``XFL,'' the new rougher-edged pro football league
in which NBC is a participant. No fair-catch rule in this league,
the network says.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The big events, as always, will air Sunday nights. That's when
NBC will start ``A Man in Full,'' its four-hour adaptation of Tom
Wolfe's best seller set in Atlanta (still no word on casting);
``Unforgettable: The Natalie Cole Story''; and ``Jackie Ethel Joan:
The Women of Camelot.''
</P>
<P>
   What's missing? ``Jesse,'' ``Stark Raving Mad,'' ``The
Pretender,'' ``Profiler,'' ``Veronica's Closet'' and ``Suddenly
Susan'' are among the shows NBC killed off.
</P>
<P>
   What's notable? When NBC moves ``Just Shoot Me'' to 9:30 p.m.
Thursdays, it will mark the first time in years the network hasn't
tried to launch a series at 8:30 p.m. and 9:30 p.m. Next fall, only
``The Steven Weber Show'' will be new on Thursdays; ``Friends,''
``Will &AMP; Grace,'' ``Just Shoot Me'' and ``ER'' will all be
returning.
</P>
<P>
   And what do the advertisers think? After all, Monday's
production was aimed at them. They're cautious at this point, and
don't want to commit much opinion _ let alone money _ until they've
seen full episodes rather than just clips.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no huge break-out hits on the surface, but we have
to see the shows. Right now it's just elements of the shows,'' said
Jennifer Leavens, manager of the national broadcast department for
Round Two Communications.
</P>
<P>
   Upfront presentations continue all week. WB and ABC are today,
CBS is Wednesday and UPN and Fox are Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
