A5974 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-NBC-SIDEBAR16-COX     05-15 0299
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NBC-SIDEBAR16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fall 2000: NBC woos advertisers
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ NBC's money may be on the returning ``Friends,'' but
it was the cast of ``Will &AMP; Grace'' who got the big applause Monday
when NBC presented its fall 2000 schedule to advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   Taking over the Metropolitan Opera House at Lincoln Center, the
network presented ``The NBC Upfront Operetta,'' with Eric
McCormack, Debra Messing, Sean Hayes and Megan Mullaly of ``Will &AMP;
Grace'' pitching the network to the people who buy commercials.
``Our demographic is what you're looking for,'' they sang, ``the
big-spending hotties you adore.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``upfronts'' are an annual TV ritual, attended by
advertisers, affiliates and series stars. The purpose is to
persuade advertisers to spend their money.
</P>
<P>
   NBC's presentation was nearly overshadowed by the ``Friends''
contract negotiations. Word came Sunday that the six stars will
each get close to $40 million over the next two years from salary
and profit-sharing, and will be back at 8 p.m. Thursdays. The
contracts are for two 24-episode seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Friends'' will be followed at 9 p.m. Thursdays by ``Will &AMP;
Grace,'' moving to NBC's most prestigious real estate. ``Frasier,''
which will move from Thursdays to 9 p.m. Tuesdays in the fall, took
a ratings hit this season from ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire.''
</P>
<P>
   ABC presents its fall schedule today, and there will be no
``Sports Night'' in its lineup. Creator Aaron Sorkin said Monday
that the network finally canceled it over the weekend. He said he's
still in talks with HBO about moving ``Sports Night'' there.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
