A5975 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-NEWSTAND16-COX     05-15 0402
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSTAND16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New magazines target shoppers, movie buffs
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two new magazines hit the stands this week with distinctly
different audiences in mind. Published by Conde Nast, Lucky ($2.50)
is a glossy, 202-page bimonthly publication that's all about
shopping. Articles include a list of 700 great finds, 71 cool
stores, 39 must-visit Web sites, tips on buying a dog and a shoe
guide that would excite Imelda Marcos. ``Lucky is a magazine
created for _ and, of course, by _ enthusiastic, even obsessive
shoppers,'' says Editor in Chief Kim France. Shopping, she adds, is
all about realizing your fantasies.
</P>
<P>
   Also new is ifcRant ($2.95), a joint venture between the
Independent Film Channel and indieWire.com that's aimed at movie
buffs who are interested in more than what the big Hollywood
studios have to offer. The debut issue features articles on Ethan
Hawke (``Hamlet''), Billy Crudup (``Waking the Dead''), the latest
in independent films, and a May-June viewer's guide to the
Independent Film Channel.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Literary storm: Two of the biggest book-related events of the
summer are the publication of J.K. Rowling's fourth Harry Potter
novel and the release of ``A Perfect Storm,'' the George Clooney
movie based on Sebastian Junger's best-selling book about a
maritime tragedy. Book ($4.95) correspondent Helen Jerome talks
with Rowling about her success and offers a sneak preview of
``Harry Potter and the Doomspell Tournament,'' which is due in
stores July 8.
</P>
<P>
   Writer John Clark accompanies ``Perfect Storm'' author Junger to
Gloucester, Mass., where filmmakers were shooting scenes of the
town and its seafaring residents. ``They're not used to being
admired for fishing,'' Junger says. ``Suddenly, being a fisherman
is kind of cool.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Uncivil union: Andrew Sullivan declaims in The New Republic
($3.50) that Vermont's new civil union status for gay couples is
``a pseudomarital institution'' that creates a two-tiered system
akin to laws that once prohibited sex between races. The freedom to
marry is a fundamental right accorded under the Constitution, he
says in an essay that disputes, point by point, the arguments
against gay marriage.
</P>
<P>
   _Contributing: Frank C. Rizzo
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
