<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 21:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5976 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-SPEARSCD-REVIEW16-COX     05-15 0593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPEARSCD-REVIEW16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Spears does it again, and fans will be happy
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   She's not the Love Bug virus, but teen queen Britney Spears
today unleashes an electronic invasion of America.
</P>
<P>
   Her new album, ``Oops ... I Did It Again,'' the highly
anticipated follow-up to the kittenish smash ``... Baby One More
Time,'' is officially available and being hyped to the max _ in
stores, on MTV, in teenage chat rooms and through dozens of Web
sites.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of the loud buzz, however, the record is nothing new.
Spears and her producers haven't stepped a pink-polished toenail
outside the ``baybee baybee'' formula that hypnotized little girls
(and plenty of older men) a year ago: a posturing, sexpot blend of
fat dance beats and Kewpie-doll groans. On most cuts, Spears might
as well be warbling, ``Baybee hit me two more times.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor does she stretch as a vocalist. The one-time Louisiana
schoolgirl relies heavily on an irritating faux-soul-sister speak
that's Foxy Brown after hostess training at the Magic Kingdom _ too
is ``tuh,'' you is ``yuh.'' Even on the emotional ballad ``Don't
Let Me Be the Last to Know,'' she sounds like she has a toy moo box
stuck in her throat.
</P>
<P>
   The main change here is that the 18-year-old pop star has grown
up lyrically, from the teasing parochial-school vamp of her early
videos to a femme fatale capable of a cocky kiss-off. ``I've had
enough, / I'm not your property,'' she growls on ``Stronger''
(cloned from the staccato hip-hop of She'kspere's ``Bills Bills
Bills''). In the album's one surprisingly creative moment, Spears
slows down the beat on a startlingly seductive cover of the Rolling
Stones' ``Satisfaction,'' changing the words to ``When I'm watching
my TV / and that girl comes on and tells me / how tight my skirts
should be, / she can't tell me / got my own identity.'' Not exactly
under Mick's thumb.
</P>
<P>
   While this CD proves that Spears is nothing more than a pop joy
ride, it has one redeeming quality that will sell millions and make
it the album of the summer: It's a lot of fun. Nearly every tune is
launched on the same blinking runway that lies under the Backstreet
Boys and 'N Sync, a funhouse mix of synthesizer blasts, loopy sound
effects and hooks you just can't get out of your head.
</P>
<P>
   As Leslie Gore did in the 1960s, Donna Summer in the '70s and
Madonna in the '80s, Spears has found a sound that works, and she's
sticking to it. And, like those Top 40 girlfriends, she's totally
plugged into the culture of her teenage fan base _ a pop smoothie
world of cell phone chatter, e-mail relationships, instant
messaging and dialing up ``Total Request Live.'' This is how well
she knows her audience: In between nearly each track here, there
are sound bites of Britney gabbing with friends.
</P>
<P>
   But underneath it all is the smoldering sexuality of young girls
trapped between pigtails and push-up bras. Spears giggles like a
teen in flannel pajamas but wears body-molding halter tops that
could be issued by an escort service. Eighth-graders buy her CDs;
dads watch the videos. It's a game as old as the genetic code
itself _ this one just happens to be stamped with a bar code.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : More about Britney Spears and her music:
www.gate.am/britney
</P>
<P>
   ``Oops! ...
</P>
<P>
   I Did It Again''
</P>
<P>
   Britney Spears. Jive. 12 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Our critic's Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _Miriam Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
