<HEADER>
A5977 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKC-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     05-15 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IU: TALK ABOUT A DYSFUNCTIONAL FAMILY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I watched this sitcom Monday about a really tight, really
dysfunctional family. I wish I could say it made me smile like
``Malcolm in the Middle'' does every week. But in truth all it did
was make me squirm.
</P>
<P>
   The Indiana University family is so much more messed up than
Fox's the Wilkersons. That much was obvious during a news
conference carried live by a cable TV network in which Indiana
University President Myles Brand and two of the university's Board
of Trustees members prattled on about there being nothing more
important than ``protecting and enhancing the image'' of their
great university, that they take seriously their responsibilities
as the guardians of the university's reputation, that there are no
sacred cows at Indiana University.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and that Bob Knight will be back next year for his 30th
season as the Hoosiers' basketball coach, his laundry list of
``abusive and embarrassing behavior'' notwithstanding.
</P>
<P>
   If I didn't see them talking out of both sides of their mouths,
I would have sworn Brand and the trustees were puppets, and that
somewhere out of the camera's range, hunched over in depraved
delight working the strings, was Knight.
</P>
<P>
   As I listened to Brand and university trustee John Walda drone
on, two white-skinned, white-haired men defending their own, I felt
sorry for all the Hoosiers in the Middle of this sorry production.
</P>
<P>
   For too many years, Indiana University has been teaching its
student body one lesson above all others: That an authority figure
can profanely demand perfection from his subordinates but be
himself terribly flawed and it's OK as long as the authority figure
is a good ol' boy with a distinguished record.
</P>
<P>
   ``The university could have done better in the past (policing
Knight),'' Brand was big enough to admit. ``The university will
rectify that.''
</P>
<P>
   Brand could have started by demanding Knight make an appearance
at his reprieve. Knight was caught by a television camera walking
on the Bloomington campus Monday afternoon, but he couldn't find
his way to the news conference in Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than say himself how sorry he was for his disgraceful
behavior in the past and how he looks forward to being a kinder,
gentler coach and a more empathetic human being in the future,
Knight left it to Brand and Walda to say what is deep inside his
heart.
</P>
<P>
   Knight's absence from Monday's news conference spoke louder than
that 330-word statement he issued over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   If Knight is going to follow through on his promise to apologize
to those he has wronged, he should have wasted no time getting
started. So many (ital)mea culpas(end ital), you know, so little
time.
</P>
<P>
   Short of breaking bread with ex-player Neil Reed, there would
have been no better way for Knight to demonstrate he is a new man,
a changed man, than to have cut short his morning turkey shoot to
address the gathered media, too many of whom he has treated like
that stuff on the toilet paper he allegedly waved in his players'
faces during one of his inspired pep talks.
</P>
<P>
   But then, what do I know? I thought Knight ought to have been
fired after he brandished a bullwhip at his star African-American
forward Calbert Cheaney in Albuquerque during the 1992 NCAA
Tournament. I was there, and trust me, nobody I asked, including
the president of the local NAACP chapter, got the joke.
</P>
<P>
   I thought he should have been disciplined and denounced at least
as roundly as John Rocker would be a dozen years later for his
comments to broadcaster Connie Chung in 1988. By way of describing
his attitude toward stress, Knight said, ``I think that if rape is
inevitable, relax and enjoy it.''
</P>
<P>
   I thought for sure he'd be shoved off his pedestal in Indiana
when he berated a media liaison _ bullied him, badly _ in plain
view of the cameras after the Hoosiers went out meekly to Missouri
in the first round of the 1995 NCAA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The thing I didn't realize about Indiana University until the
Neil Reed videotape surfaced in March is that its leaders are like
the parents of the preschooler who terrorizes every other child at
the neighborhood playground. He pulls the girls' hair, pushes the
boys to the ground and throws temper tantrums whenever he doesn't
get his way.
</P>
<P>
   The kid's mother sits on a bench a few feet away, pretending not
to notice her son's bad behavior, until one day another parent
videotapes the whole scene and shows it to the neighbors. The
mother, mortified that people are beginning to talk about what a
terrible parent she is, makes a grand public display of slapping
her son's hand at the playground one day, just to show everyone she
is a woman of authority and action.
</P>
<P>
   If you believe a child can modify years of bad behavior after a
single slap, then you probably are confident the 59-year-old Knight
will be able to shed his anger as easily as one of those hideous
plaid jackets he used to wear.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of us won't hold our breaths. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Karen Crouse's column appears in the Daily News four days a week.
She can be reached at (818) 713-3619. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
