u f BC-FOOD-UNILEVER-BESTFOO     05-15 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-UNILEVER-BESTFOODS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNIVLEVER CHIEF PRESSES BESTFOODS ON TAKEOVER OFFER 
</HEADLINE>
   By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stepping up the pressure on a reluctant takeover target, the
co-chairman of Unilever said Monday that he thought the $66-a-share
offer made earlier this month for Bestfoods was ``serious money''
and that the company wants the management of Bestfoods to meet with
Unilever to discuss it.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the prospect of the sale of Nabisco Group
Holdings to another food company, like Groupe Danone or Philip
Morris, intensified the focus on a Unilever-Bestfoods combination.
</P>
<P>
   Merging Nabisco with either Groupe Danone or Philip Morris would
create a global packaged-food giant that could leave Bestfoods
behind, one analyst said. ``Some powerhouses are being built,''
said the analyst, John R. McMillin of Prudential Securities.
``Where does that put Bestfoods?''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Antony Burgmans, the co-chairman of Unilever,
drew parallels between his company's pursuit of Bestfoods and its
recent successful acquisition of Ben &AMP; Jerry's Homemade. ``We have
respect for the company with whom we are negotiating, respect for
the brands and respect for the work they have done,'' Burgmans
said. ``In the end, that is why we were able to convince Ben and
Jerry to sit at the table with us.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Bestfoods, he added: ``What puzzles and amazes us is that
at that price, a premium of 34 percent over what the stock was
trading for, they haven't come up to talk to us.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bestfoods, at least publicly, is not budging from the
position it took earlier this month that the offer, worth $18.4
billion, is too low. ``Our board of directors firmly and
unanimously rejected Unilever's offer of $66 per share as
financially inadequate,'' said Gale Griffin, a company spokeswoman.
``Nothing has changed since then. The Unilever proposal was quite
clear. If they have further communications about value, they have
the ability to communicate with us.''
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts say they expect Unilever, which makes foods like
Breyer's ice cream and Lipton tea and household products like Dove
soap, to prevail. In a presentation at a conference hosted by
Goldman, Sachs Monday Unilever's other co-chairman, Niall
FitzGerald, also expressed bewilderment that Bestfoods executives
had not asked to meet to discuss the proposal. ``We fail to
understand why Bestfoods management will not engage in face-to-face
discussions,'' FitzGerald told the group, which Charles R.
Shoemate, the chairman and chief executive of Bestfoods, addressed
later in the day. ``Consolidation is inevitable in the food
industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Burgmans said Unilever wanted to take over not just the
Bestfoods brands, which include Hellmann's mayonnaise, Knorr soups
and Skippy peanut butter, but also the management. ``We know this
management well,'' he said. ``Their people would have leading
responsibilities in the new structure.'' The president of
Unilever's North American food business, Richard Goldstein, is
leaving Unilever at the end of the month, and no successor has been
named.
</P>
<P>
   If the merger went through, Knorr would become Unilever's
biggest brand, FitzGerald told investors, and Hellmann's would be
the third or fourth largest. Adding huge brands like those would
speed up Unilever's disposal of smaller brands, making the strategy
that Unilever announced in February go into effect faster.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been preparing our business case for the last 12
months,'' FitzGerald said. ``We believe we can execute the
integration program with relatively low risk.''
</P>
<P>
   In some cases where the two companies have overlapping
operations, Unilever's business would be folded into that of
Bestfoods, Burgmans said. ``They are very strong in food service
and we are weaker,'' he said. ``We would fold our food service unit
into theirs. In the U.S., we would become a powerhouse. In Latin
America, Unilever is strong but not in foods. They are not so
strong in Asia, but at a single stroke, we could have them in a
million shops.''
</P>
<P>
   McMillin said that Unilever's purchase of Ben &AMP; Jerry's for $326
million and Slim-Fast Food Cos. for $2.4 billion, both announced on
April 12, may have given Bestfoods the impression that Unilever had
done all its acquiring for the year. ``I think they were was
surprised to see Unilever bidding so quickly again,'' he said.
``They were breathing a sigh of relief, and then were caught by
surprise.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
