<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 21:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5982 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-SOCSEC-CANDIDATES-2TA     05-15 1082
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCSEC-CANDIDATES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH CALLS FOR A MAJOR OVERHAUL OF SOCIAL SECURITY
</HEADLINE>
  (With SOCSEC-ASSESS) 
(Eds: Note reference to text of candidates' remarks being available
on Times' Web site in 5th graf.) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL with JAMES DAO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RANCHO CUCAMONGA, Calif. _ Casting the overhaul of the Social
Security system as a ``test of presidential candidates,'' Gov.
George W. Bush on Monday proposed to fundamentally change the
retirement system by allowing workers to choose how to invest some
of their payroll taxes.
</P>
<P>
   With his formal call for the introduction of individual
retirement accounts, Bush, the presumptive Republican presidential
nominee, began a debate that could dominate the presidential
campaign. He and Vice President Al Gore differ sharply over how to
meet the fiscal challenge posed by the coming retirement of the
baby boom generation.
</P>
<P>
   Although Social Security has long been considered the ``third
rail'' of politics, which a candidate touches at his peril, Bush
took a gamble that in the new economy, with nearly 50 percent of
American households now owning stock, his proposal would prove
appealing. Bush also embraced a bipartisan proposal for Medicare
that would reshape it by giving beneficiaries fixed amounts of
money to chose from a variety to health care plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a fundamental difference between my opponent and
me,'' Bush said Monday at an appearance at a senior citizen center
here. ``He trusts the government to manage our retirement. I trust
individual Americans. I trust Americans to make their own decisions
and manage their own money.''
</P>
<P>
   A few hours later in Philadelphia, Gore came out squarely
against the plan, calling it dangerous for individual taxpayers and
for the economy overall. ``If we turn the Social Security system
into a system of winners and losers,'' he said, ``we will be
jeopardizing retirement security for too many Americans and in the
end we will all have to pay to make up the differences.'' (Text of
both candidates' remarks is available from The New York Times on
the Web, www.nytimes.com.)
</P>
<P>
   The sharp debate comes at a time when demographic changes will
soon threaten the solvency of Social Security. Starting in 2015,
the retirement system will start paying out more in benefits than
it will collect in payroll taxes, because of the retirement of the
large baby boom generation. Under current projections, by 2037 it
will be able to pay out only 75 percent in benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Shifting some of the payroll tax into individual retirement
accounts would amount to the most far-reaching change in Social
Security since its inception during the Depression. As it has
worked for decades, current retirees are paid from the payroll
taxes of current workers; under the Bush plan workers would be able
to hold on to a portion of their payroll taxes and invest them for
their own retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Bush argued it would both provide an infusion of cash to make
the program solvent and give people ``the security of ownership.''
</P>
<P>
   However, he largely skirted specifics in his speech, preferring
to talk about broad principles. It was unclear, for instance,
exactly how much money people could set aside for individual
accounts and what sort of investment options they would have. Bush
did say the investments would have to be in ``steady, reliable
funds,'' adding that ``there will will be no fly-by-night
speculators or day trading.''
</P>
<P>
   He also pledged that benefits would not change for current
retirees and ``near retirees.'' He said he would dedicate the
entire $2 trillion Social Security surplus to the retirement
program. He ruled out any increase in payroll taxes, but was silent
on whether to raise the retirement age.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the Texas Republican's address was devoted to drawing a
contrast between himself and the vice president, casting himself as
a leader who would pave the way for a bipartisan agreement on a
pressing policy matter. ``I am here with a message for America and
to put my opponent on notice,'' Bush said. ``The days of spreading
fear and panic are over. The days of delaying, dividing,
demagoguing are over. When I am elected this generation and this
president will solve social security.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that President Clinton and Gore had squandered eight
years by not addressing the problems posed by the retirement of the
baby boomers. ``At a time for leadership,'' Bush said, ``for
long-term thinking, my opponent proposes a Band-Aid approach. He
says, and I quote, `If it ain't broke, don't fix it.' But in the
lifetime of some people in this room, it will be broke and we must
fix it. With every day of delay, this becomes more difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore has in large part staked his candidacy on the health of the
economy and made paying down the debt the centerpiece of his
economic plan. He has proposed extending the life of the retirement
system until 2054 by devoting the interest saved by paying down the
debt to the retirement system.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, in his own appearance Monday, asked what would happen to
investments if economic prosperity abated. ``Today, when Wall
Street is booming, I know that plan sounds appealing,'' he said.
``It probably sounds like an easy way to make more money and have
more control over your retirement. But in reality, the Bush
privatization plan would weaken our economy and undermine the basic
guarantee of a minimum basic retirement.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked later in the day about his lack of detail, Bush called his
speech ``pretty darned detailed to be talking about a framework to
get something done.'' His aides said he had avoided specifics
because Hillary Rodham Clinton's abortive attempt to craft a plan
for universal health care coverage had shown that being locked into
one plan was a recipe for legislative disaster on a complicated
issue.
</P>
<P>
   But the lack of specifics on everything from what percentage of
the payroll tax would go to accounts, to what age group would see
the change, opened Bush to charges that he was masking some of the
hard choices ahead and trying to sidestep questions about how he
could afford the transition and his sweeping call for a $1.3
trillion tax cut across the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   The costs of making the transition to such a system would be
significant _ as much as $1 trillion _ because the government could
have to pay out full benefits to current retirees while that same
amount of payroll taxes were being diverted into individual
accounts.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of Bush and Gore feuded all day over which plan was
more risky and which would entail more of a shift of general tax
revenue into Social Security. Such a shift would either require
cuts in other programs or tax increases.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president asserted that Bush's plan would make it
nearly impossible to pay down the national debt. ``By leaving us
with a multitrillion dollar debt for as far as the eye can see, the
Bush plan could trigger higher interest rates and slower long-term
growth,'' Gore said. ``That undermines our chance to meet other
challenges, such as keeping Medicare solvent or providing an
affordable prescription drug benefit for seniors.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore has been lagging in recent polls and his advisers said
privately that they were pleased Bush had taken on Social Security,
because it sets up a clear policy difference between the candidates
and provides a big target to shoot at, much like former Sen. Bill
Bradley's universal health care proposal during the Democratic
primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Gore intends to talk about Social Security two more times this
week _ before younger voters at Fordham University in New York on
Tuesday and before older voters in Florida on Wednesday. In his
speech Monday, he reissued his challenge to Bush to hold regular
debates.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past few years an array of Republicans and Democrats
have proposed plans to overhaul Social Security that include an
element of private accounts. But the ideas have all died because of
sharp ideological differences, distrust between the parties and
fear of alienating the elderly, a reliable voting bloc.
</P>
<P>
   Generally the plans would allow 2 percent of the 12.4 percent
payroll tax to be put into individual accounts. But the programs
differ quite significantly in the details.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the economic complexities involved, a number of them
also call for such benefit reductions as raising the retirement age
or scaling back cost of living increases. And under one plan
workers would have to return their accounts to the government when
they retire and then receive a fixed monthly sum back.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also expressed his support Monday for an approach to
Medicare that had been drafted by a bipartisan commission, which
would have converted Medicare into an arena for public and private
competition. Bush said the elderly should be given a choice of
health plans to buy including one providing prescription drug
coverage. He said Medicare itself should provide full drug coverage
for the most low-income elderly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
