u i BC-ISRAEL-PALESTINIANS-N     05-15 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-PALESTINIANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIOLENCE ERUPTS IN PALESTINIAN TERRITORIES; ISRAEL CEDES 3
VILLAGES 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: 2nd take will move ASAP) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ For the first time in almost four years, Israelis
and Palestinians exchanged live gunfire in the West Bank on Monday
as a wave of violent protest swept through the Palestinian
territories. Despite the fighting, Prime Minister Ehud Barak won
his Parliament's approval to cede three villages near Jerusalem to
the Palestinian Authority in an effort to advance the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   The gun battle, which broke out a juncture near the Palestinian
city of Ramallah, accompanied chaotic confrontations throughout the
West Bank and Gaza, in which Israeli forces suppressed unruly
Palestinian demonstrators by shooting tear gas, rubber-coated
bullets and live ammunition into crowds charging at them with
stones and firebombs.
</P>
<P>
   In the chaos of the rioting, live bullets suddenly appeared to
fly at the Israeli troops from Palestinian military police
stationed on a hilltop north of Ramallah. The Israeli troops
immediately responded with live fire, and for several hours they
and the Palestinian police exchanged automatic weapon fire.
</P>
<P>
   Late Monday night, armed Palestinian men attacked Joseph's Tomb,
an Israeli enclave inside Nablus, shooting and throwing firebombs.
Another shoot-out ensued, in which a Palestinian youth was killed.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian officials said three Palestinians were killed _ a
police officer and two youths _ and 350 were injured. Israeli
officials said six Israeli soldiers were injured.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrations occurred on the anniversary of what the
Palestinians term the ``nakba,'' or ``catastrophe'' that
accompanied the birth of Israel. The protests were called also to
demand the release of Palestinian prisoners held by Israel. But the
violence expressed deep-seated frustrations among many
Palestinians, especially with the failure of the peace effort to
change their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Barak and Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian leader, spoke by
telephone Monday evening, and communicated through advisers several
times during the day.
</P>
<P>
   Information about the violence in the West Bank slowly reached
the Parliament, embroiled in its own struggles. And since the
shooting was seized upon by the right wing as justification for
concerns about the Palestinians, it was met with sober-minded calm
by Barak and his government. Officials said they did not know the
facts, and did not want to overreact.
</P>
<P>
   Though three parties in the prime minister's fractious,
six-party coalition did not support him, and one quit the
government, the legislature voted 56-48 to authorize the
long-delayed, much-disputed transfer of the three villages to full
Palestinian control, which was originally intended by Barak as a
gesture of good will to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   The move has ended up as an 11th-hour offering to salvage a
faltering peace effort as negotiations were stalled by the
escalating violence and the senior Palestinian negotiator quit.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian officials publicly expressed no thanks Monday night
for the three dusty, pothole-ridden villages, over which they have
exercised civil control since December 1995. In a speech to the
Parliament, Barak made it clear that Abu Dis, one of the villages,
was meant as a substitute for East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be in Jerusalem, and they in Abu Dis,'' Barak said as
he sought to explain why the concession of an Arab village did not
seem like a surrender from his point of view.
</P>
<P>
   This embarrassed and infuriated the Palestinians, who publicly
aspire to make East Jerusalem the capital of their future state.
Yasser Abed Rabbo, a senior Palestinian official, dismissed the
transfer as a ``symbolic step.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Parliament vote, as darkness brought calm to most of
the West Bank and Gaza, tens of thousands of Jewish settlers filled
the heart of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first mass right-wing protest against the
Israeli-Palestinian peace negotiations since Barak was elected last
May. From above, television cameras captured a sea of yarmulkes
that filled Zion Square and the Ben Yehuda pedestrian mall.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government has bowed to the Palestinian rioters,'' said
Ariel Sharon, leader of the opposition Likud Party. ``On the day
they shoot, it is handing them territory.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
