<HEADER>
A5988 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-ACLU-10COMMANDMENTS-C     05-15 0303
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ACLU-10COMMANDMENTS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Suit puts seal of disapproval on signet
 &HT;    By Rhonda Cook
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The American Civil Liberties Union sued Richmond County on
Monday over the county's century-old Superior Court seal that
includes an apparent image of the Ten Commandments.
</P>
<P>
   A federal appeals court has ruled that such images violate
constitutional church-state separation. But county officials say
the seal is not necessarily religious in nature, and that it has
been affixed to official court documents for more than a century
without complaint.
</P>
<P>
   ``The clerk of courts, her position is that it has been the seal
for at least 130 years and she doesn't feel like she should change
it. Nobody's complained,'' said Richmond County attorney Jim
Ellison.
</P>
<P>
   Gerry Weber, an attorney for the ACLU in Georgia, said he has
received complaints. ``The basic point of it is it sends a message
that Richmond County is a (Judeo-Christian) county and people who
are not (Judeo-Christian) are outsiders,'' Weber said. ``Government
is supposed to be a place for all people.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, the U.S. Supreme Court struck down a Kentucky law that
required posting the Ten Commandments in public schools. In 1992,
the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Atlanta ruled it was
unconstitutional to display a plaque of the Ten Commandments in the
Cobb County courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   The ACLU is negotiating with the city of Brunswick over a
gold-framed copy of the Ten Commandments that was mounted in the
temporary City Hall building
</P>
<P>
   The ACLU and Richmond County, which includes Augusta, have
fought over this issue since 1998. In Augusta, Richmond County
officials have argued the numbered tablets on the court seal.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-00 2126EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000515.0366 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 21:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5989 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-EMORY-GRADUATION-COX     05-15 0359
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMORY-GRADUATION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    3,200 grads take big step at Emory
 &HT;    By Joe Earle
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Something Viranga Pathiraja's mother said about her daughter's
graduation from Emory University put everything in perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm my grandmother's first grandchild to graduate from a
university,'' the 21-year old said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when it hit me: My grandmother will be very proud,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   About 3,200 Emory students graduated Monday during the
university's 155th commencement ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Former U.S. Sen. George Mitchell of Maine, a key negotiator in
peace talks in Northern Ireland, told the graduates in his
commencement speech that they should speak out against
discrimination and injustice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never forget that in the presence of evil, silence makes you
an accomplice,'' Mitchell said.
</P>
<P>
   During his brief address, Mitchell encouraged the students to
oppose any effort to deny education to all American children and to
demand public policies to protect the environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``You will find that real fulfillment in your life will come not
from leisure, not from idleness, not from self-indulgence, but
rather from striving with all your physical and spiritual might for
a worthwhile objective that helps others and is larger than your
self-interest,'' he said. Monday, Pathiraja's parents and younger
brother, Asanka, watched her start the family's new generation of
graduates. ``It's a dream,'' said her father, Ananda Pathiraja.
``We're very proud of her.''
</P>
<P>
   This summer, Pathiraja will have the chance to bask in her
grandmother's pride during a family vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Pathiraja was born in Sri Lanka. When she was 2 years old, her
family moved to Jamaica. Then, when she was about 6, her family
settled in Augusta.
</P>
<P>
   Pathiraja plans to return to Emory in the fall for a job as a
research assistant.
</P>
<P>
   Her younger brother also plans to return. He is enrolled as a
freshman.
</P>
<P>
   That suits his older sister. After all, education is important
in her family. Besides, she said, ``that way I can keep an eye on
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
