<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 21:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5990 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-ANDRUW-JONES-COX     05-15 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ANDRUW-JONES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Andruw Jones comes of age
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Andruw Jones hides it better than any player in the major
leagues. But this 23-year-old _ known to break out in an easy smile
at the plate, to run as if it takes no effort and to catch fly
balls near his waist _ is determined.
</P>
<P>
   His statistics give him away.
</P>
<P>
   After a couple of years of hearing the words ``offensive
potential'' associated with his name, along with the label of best
center fielder in the game, Jones has done something about it.
</P>
<P>
   He is rivaling the other Jones, reigning National League MVP
Chipper, as the toughest out in the Braves lineup.
</P>
<P>
   With all due respect, no one is talking about Andruw Jones'
defense right now.
</P>
<P>
   Jones is hitting .309 to lead Braves regulars, and has a .417
on-base percentage. He leads in runs scored with 25, his 10 home
runs are second to Andres Galarraga's 11, and he is third in RBIs
with 20. Since he moved into the second spot in the batting order,
a move he has eyed since the leadoff experiment failed a couple
years ago, Jones has hit .345 (22-for-87) with an on-base
percentage of .477 and a slugging percentage of .713.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday in Philadelphia, he was a single away from becoming the
fifth Brave this century to hit for the cycle.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just not fishing as much,'' Greg Maddux said. ``I've
actually seen him take a strike. I don't think I saw him take one
last year.''
</P>
<P>
   The formerly flailing Jones has found a new discipline at the
plate. Maddux and Jones agree that much of the credit goes to new
Braves hitting coach Merv Rettenmund.
</P>
<P>
   During batting practice, Jones will stand beside the cage at
Turner Field, with Rettenmund nearby. The matrix board will be
showing highlights from last season, including a shot of Jones
making one of his superhuman catches. Rettenmund will frown and
say, so that Jones can hear, ``Wonder why he didn't have any
offensive highlights.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones will give Rettenmund a stare before he gets in the batting
cage. Only then will Rettenmund break into a smile.
</P>
<P>
   Hours before the game, before batting practice, home or away,
Jones can be found wandering around the Braves clubhouse, bat in
hand, looking for Rettenmund for some one-on-one attention. When
they hook up and head for the cages, Jones might say something
like: ``Bring a camera. It'll be pretty.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Rettenmund will roll his eyes and say, ``I forgot,'' and
head for the training room. When he emerges, he says, ``Advil.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I like people that like to work,'' Jones said. ``He likes to
work, to go to the cage. ... We just talk. We like to have fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones is learning some pretty valuable lessons along the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``My coach is myself,'' Jones said. ```You're the one who has to
go out and do it.' That's what he tells me all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   This time last season, Jones was hitting .294 with an on-base
percentage of .372. He had struck out 29 times, while walking 16
times, three of them intentional. This season, his strikeouts are
down to 22 and he has walked 23 times, none intentional.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, he also was another month away from hitting his 10th
home run.
</P>
<P>
   ``More patient, more selective, quicker adjustments,'' Jones
said in explanation. ``I have a bad at-bat, (then) I can adjust for
my next at-bat. If I know the pitcher, I feel comfortable. I know
what he's going to do. Last year, I would just go out, see the ball
and hit it. If I hit, I hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's game was a microcosm of how far Jones has come and how
close he is to being something special.
</P>
<P>
   In his first at-bat, he doubled over the second baseman's head
into right field, an area of the field he wasn't much interested in
last year. The triple came cheap, because center fielder Doug
Glanville lost his popup in the sun and let it bounce in front of
him. But the same player who was benched for loafing in the
outfield in 1998 never hesitated and got to third on hustle.
</P>
<P>
   When it came time to try for his single in his fourth at-bat,
Jones laced a ball up the middle and only some outstanding reflexes
from pitcher Trever Miller stopped him. The Andruw Jones of
previous years would have been trying to pull the ball. In Jones'
final at-bat, Scott Aldred struck him out on a nasty slider. Jones
recognized it and tried to check his swing but couldn't. Last
season, he might have swung himself around trying to reach it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just trying to get better pitches to hit, not trying to
do too much,'' Maddux said. ``He's maturing, learning more about
himself as a hitter. Andruw's always been real good at learning
from his mistakes. He's continued to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, pitchers have to think about it,'' Brian Jordan said.
``Before, they could throw something up there and know he's going
to chase it. He's relaxed. He's a more confident hitter. ... He's
really taking it serious now. Before it was just fun: `I'm just
happy to be here.' Now it's, `I'll accept my role and live up to my
potential.'''
</P>
<P>
   Jones' toughest critic also is his greatest ally. Rettenmund
knows the disappointment of trying to reach a talented young player
and failing. He spent the past two years trying to get to Ruben
Rivera in San Diego and watching Rivera hit .209 in 1998 and .195
in 1999. But in Jones, Rettenmund has found an open mind and an
eager ear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Andruw is making progress,'' Rettenmund said. ``He
knows what he wants to do. He knows what he wants to be. If he just
keeps working like he is, what he's doing now, he's only scratching
the surface. He could be up there with anyone. The whole game is
his.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
