<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5993 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FORUM-ELIAN-COX     05-15 0619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORUM-ELIAN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nuns and the Elain case
 &HT;    By Bill Douthat
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   At the height of tense negotiations over Elian Gonzalez, Sister
Jeanne O'Laughlin presented her secret plan:
</P>
<P>
   Bring both families to the Rosarian Academy in West Palm Beach
for a reunion, followed by a hand-over of the Cuban boy to his
Cuban father.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was someplace where you could drive the child and avoid a
lot of the trauma,'' O'Laughlin said she suggested to Attorney
General Janet Reno.
</P>
<P>
   The Catholic school for preschool to eighth-graders was offered
during a mid-April session at the Miami Beach home of O'Laughlin,
who hosted talks between Reno and Elian's Miami relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Ten days later, federal agents seized the boy in a pre-dawn raid
on the Miami home.
</P>
<P>
   Rosarian Principal Mary DeVault said she learned of the proposal
through Adrian Dominican nuns housed at the school, nuns from
O'Laughlin's order. Devault said the school probably came to mind
because of its commitment to ``openness and reconciliation.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Laughlin recounted her role in the tug-of-war over Elian
during a Monday address to nearly 300 people at the Forum Club of
the Palm Beaches. Tears trickled from some when she pleaded for
Americans to understand the outrage of Cuban-Americans over the
possible return of Elian to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   O'Laughlin became an ally of the Miami relatives after she said
she saw how the Cuban government manipulated a visit by Elian's
grandmothers to O'Laughlin's Miami Beach home in January.
</P>
<P>
   The grandmothers seemed relaxed, eating cupcakes and drinking
soda, until their Cuban escorts entered, she said. A sit-down
dinner was prepared for the grandmothers from Cuba and for the
Miami relatives, but the Cuban officials wouldn't allow it, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never sensed fear as I did that day,'' she said. ``There
was terror in the hearts of those women.''
</P>
<P>
   She described Elian's affection for his 21-year-old cousin
Marisleysis Gonzalez, who became his surrogate mother after Elian's
own mother died bringing Elian to Florida on a small boat in
November.
</P>
<P>
   O'Laughlin said she was once called to the Miami house and found
a despondent Elian curled up in a patio lounger. Elian refused to
get dressed or leave the house until O'Laughlin promised to take
him to visit Marisleysis, who had been hospitalized for exhaustion.
</P>
<P>
   She said the family was sleep-deprived and ``making bad
decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   The family, perhaps irrationally, thought if they were to
stretch a reunion with Juan Miguel Gonzalez over several hours,
they could win him over, she said. Gonzalez's attorney insisted on
no more than 60 minutes, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps, in their hope of hopes, they dreamed he would
defect,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Elian saga showed her the anguish of Cuban exiles and how it
is misunderstood by most Americans, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had been living almost 20 years in South Florida, and it was
this terrible event that led me to understand the pain of the Cuban
people,'' said O'Laughlin, who is president of Barry University.
Returning Elian to Cuba, she said, was like tearing open their old
wounds.
</P>
<P>
   O'Laughlin said she got death threats because she sided with the
exile community to keep Elian here. She recited some of them
Monday:
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope you croak. ... May the fires of hell burn you. ...
Will bring a gun and shoot you in five places, one for each of the
wounds of Jesus.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hatred. Hatred. Why?'' O'Laughlin said in a voice heavy with
sorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of us removed from the roots of being newcomers cannot
understand the pain.''
</P>
<P>
   billdouthat(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
