<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 21:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5995 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-PALESTINIANS-2     05-15 1032
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-PALESTINIANS-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 JERUSALEM: them territory.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Barely miles apart, the violence in the West Bank and the
political turbulence in the Israeli Parliament seemed to be taking
place on different planes of reality. Israeli lawmakers, convening
for the opening of the summer session, bustled through the halls of
the Parliament, focused on the political game at hand: Who would
vote how and whether it would reshape the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is actually happening in Ramallah?`` Yitzhak Herzog, the
Cabinet secretary and a senior adviser to Barak, asked late Monday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   When someone said that the Palestinian street was exploding from
pent-up frustration, he gestured around him. ``Talk about
frustration,'' he said. ``This is frustration!''
</P>
<P>
   In the streets of the Palestinian territories, in Bethlehem,
Ramallah, Hebron, Jenin, Nablus, Tulkarem and Gaza, the Israeli
Parliament's vote seemed distant and irrelevant. The demonstrators
chanted, burned tires and hurled stones and firebombs at Israeli
soldiers, venting rage in a way that at times verged on giddy,
defiant festivity. From rooftops and balconies, they had a cheering
audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are here not only to demand the release of our prisoners
but to say that the peace process is a game and it has failed,''
said one teen-age protester at the Bet El junction north of
Ramallah. ``Israel wants us to react this way and we are ready to
confront them.''
</P>
<P>
   Israeli officials suggested that the Palestinian leadership
fomented the trouble to threaten the Israelis into making
concessions.
</P>
<P>
   But Palestinian leaders indicated that what they did was step
aside and let the people express themselves _ until the violence
got out of hand. Then they worked to quell it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was close contact throughout the day between our
commanders and theirs,'' Barak told the Parliament. ``That doesn't
always work. The issue will have to be investigated. I am not
certain that at every moment and at every stage there was
willingness on the other side to act resolutely in order to stop
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak said that he would delay the physical transfer of the
villages until the situation was calm and it was clear what
transpired.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the chaos Monday, Abed Rabbo, the senior Palestinian
negotiator, quit his post. He said that back-channel negotiations
were rendering the official, American-mediated ones meaningless.
</P>
<P>
   Back-channel talks began in Stockholm, Sweden, several days ago
among Shlomo Ben Ami, the Israeli internal security minister; Gilad
Scher, an Israeli lawyer; Ahmed Qurei, the speaker of the
Palestinian Legislative Council also known as Abu Ala, and Hassan
Asfour, a Palestinian Cabinet minister. Palestinian and Israeli
security officials are also holding talks on the quiet.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an Israeli game,'' Abed Rabbo said, suggesting that
the Americans were encouraging it, too. ``The Israelis think that
if they use several channels at once, they will find cracks in the
Palestinian position. So I am insisting on one channel, one team
and one position, and I leave it to those in Sweden.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid the commotion, Dennis Ross, the American peace envoy, left
Washington for the region to resume mediation between Israel and
the Palestinians, the State Department said.
</P>
<P>
   Given the day's violence, Barak found himself in an awkward
position when he argued to the Parliament that sober-minded
compromises in an intelligent negotiation were the only defense
against the region's descent into chaos and bloodshed.
</P>
<P>
   Amid right-wing heckling, he delivered a disjointed speech in
which he defended his diplomatic moves and uncharacteristically
belittled the opposition as petty, fear-mongering and hypocritical.
The Likud Party government that preceded him made numerous
concessions to the Palestinians and serious missteps, he said.
``Don't preach level-headedness and security activity to us,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Monday, Barak, also uncharacteristically, took on
Sharon, a fellow former general who served as defense minister in
the previous government. ``Don't tell us tales about Jerusalem,''
he said. ``You handed over Hebron, you recognized a Palestinian
state in Gaza and you brought Clinton there.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharon responded, ``That's a libel.'' And Barak shot back, ``You
are an old hand complaining about libels,'' referring to Sharon's
history of filing libel lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition, including members of his own government, was
trying to portray the transfer of the villages as a security risk
and an indication that Barak would eventually capitulate to the
Palestinians' demand for a piece of Jerusalem itself.
</P>
<P>
   The National Religious Party, which represents religious
Zionists, including the settlers, announced its five members of
Parliament would leave the government over the vote. The split was
a long time coming, although Barak issued a public plea for them to
stay.
</P>
<P>
   Although Barak has been actively negotiating for the support of
the Shas, an ultra-Orthodox, Sephardic party with 17 Parliament
seats, Shas ministers and many members of Parliament walked out of
the proceedings and did not vote. Those who stayed opposed the
government.
</P>
<P>
   Yisrael B'Aliya, the Russian immigrant party led by Interior
Minister Natan Sharansky, is also considering quitting the
coalition, which would reduce Barak to a minority government.
``Natan is determined to leave,'' said Yuli Edelstein, another
party member. ``Not because anyone fell in love with Abu Dis, but
because if you give Abu Dis as a down payment, the final payment
will be half of Jerusalem.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharansky spoke at the settlers' rally Monday night. It was a
tightly controlled demonstration, and its organizers repeatedly
appealed to the crowd to keep calm and avoid incendiary slogans.
There were still some blunt signs: Arafat's face as a skull and a
home-made poster that said, ``Mr. Barak has forgotten thee, O
Jerusalem.''
</P>
<P>
   Ora Zimmer, 64, a retired researcher from Hebrew University,
said she thought that the government was about to ``put Jerusalem
under siege.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How can we talk about peace today?'' she said. ``They showed
us today what kind of peace we'll have.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-00 2142EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
