<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 21:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5996 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-MEXICO-POLITICS-ART-(     05-15 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-POLITICS-ART-(1500)2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR FIRST TIME, MEXICAN ELECTION IS A REAL RACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By JULIA PRESTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ The Institutional Revolutionary Party, which has
elected every president since 1929 and dominated Mexican political
life, is falling behind in the presidential race and is suddenly on
the defensive.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble started for the party's candidate, Francisco
Labastida Ochoa, when polls showed that he had been outperformed by
an opposition rival, Vicente Fox Quesada, in the first televised
presidential debate, on April 25.
</P>
<P>
   Right afterward, Labastida deepened his followers' anxiety with
his reply to a college student who asked if he could lose the
election on July 2. He said he might.
</P>
<P>
   Last Thursday, an opinion poll commissioned by Reuters showed
for the first time that Fox had pulled ahead of Labastida, 46.3
percent to 41.6 percent, with a 3.2-point margin of error.
</P>
<P>
   The surge of Fox has rattled the governing party, known by its
acronym in Spanish, PRI, as never before in a presidential contest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the fourth quarter, and the scoreboard is against the
PRI,'' said Jorge Chabat, a political analyst. ``They've never
played the game like this. They don't know what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   After the debate, Labastida, acknowledging that his campaign was
hobbled with ``too much analysis and not enough action,'' rushed to
change its strategy and its staff.
</P>
<P>
   He stopped emphasizing that he represented a new incarnation of
the governing party, which he called the New PRI to distinguish it
from an old party notorious for corruption and economic
mismanagement. Now, Labastida has closed ranks with the old PRI and
conspicuously embraced its leaders, betting that he can win by
mobilizing the full powers of the party's vast political machine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Panic in the PRI!'' read the cover of the weekly newsmagazine
Proceso.
</P>
<P>
   The PRI has faced serious presidential challengers before. Many
Mexicans believe that Cuauhtemoc Cardenas Solorzano, a leftist
politician, won the election in 1988 but was squeezed out when PRI
officials altered the tally in their favor.
</P>
<P>
   But this year is different, because an independent election
agency is overseeing the vote and reforms have substantially
leveled the field. If Fox wins, he has a good chance of claiming
the victory.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, 57, the candidate of the center-right National Action
Party, is running a campaign with flashy commercials and
choreographed antics that keep him in the limelight. He has a
cowboy bravado that some Mexicans like, and he has turned his
pungent country-style language on Labastida, calling him a
``shorty'' and a ``wimp.''
</P>
<P>
   On a recent whirl through the big-vote state of Veracruz,
Labastida seemed cooler than his campaign's outward appearance
suggested. In an interview aboard the campaign jet, Labastida said
he was confident that the PRI's far-reaching house-to-house voter
networks, unmatched by any other party, would ultimately deliver
the vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are strengthening the presence of our militant members
while taking the party closer to the people,'' Labastida said of
the turnabout in his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The Veracruz tour showed that the PRI's problem is not its
candidate. Although Labastida, a former interior minister, started
the race with a reputation as a colorless bureaucrat, on the road
he proved to be a vigorous and spirited campaigner.
</P>
<P>
   At two Veracruz rallies, Labastida ignored humidity that made
even his eyelids sweat and rushed into the crowd to receive hot
bear hugs and kisses from his followers.
</P>
<P>
   Although a PRI presidential candidate was assassinated in 1994,
Labastida prefers minimal security by plainclothes guards he
routinely leaves behind. He insists on driving, even on the
campaign trail, and at one point brought his convoy of six vans to
a tire-burning halt to allow a family of pedestrians to cross a
city street. They and everyone else on the block gaped in amazement
at the uncommon show of courtesy from a man of power.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida has a knack for connecting with voters. A 37-year-old
single mother named Ana fought her way to him and tearfully
recounted that she had lost a job because employers had said she
was too old.
</P>
<P>
   The candidate, who is 57, comforted her, talking all the while
about his equal employment proposals. In a speech to PRI members
that evening, he tossed away a prepared text to give an emotional
replay of the encounter.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   If anything, the candidate's problem is his party's record.
Although the economy has recovered, Mexicans have not forgotten the
currency collapse of 1994 or the PRI graft scandals that keep
coming to light. But many Mexicans also value the continuity of
seven decades of PRI rule and depend on the welfare state the party
built.
</P>
<P>
   Banking on that tradition, Labastida decided to fix his campaign
by clipping the wings of its reformist manager, Esteban Moctezuma,
who forged the concept of the New PRI.
</P>
<P>
   Instead the candidate reinstated some of the party's hoariest
figures, known as dinosaurs, whom Moctezuma had left on the
sidelines. Oddly enough, the shift came only days after Labastida,
in the televised debate, had taunted Fox by saying, ``You remind me
of the old PRI.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ours is an inclusive party,'' Labastida said in an effort to
explain the contradiction. He said he had reached out to those
party veterans who accepted the once rigidly authoritarian party's
new, more democratic rules of play.
</P>
<P>
   First Labastida was photographed at a PRI luncheon with Carlos
Hank Gonzalez, a former mayor of Mexico City who became a
multimillionaire during his political career. Last fall, when
Labastida was fighting for his party's nomination, he said he would
not accept help from the Hank family.
</P>
<P>
   Another veteran party member Labastida named to his campaign was
Manuel Bartlett. As interior minister in 1988, Bartlett is widely
suspected of having rigged the presidential vote tally against
Cardenas.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida dismissed the ``things that have been said about
Manuel'' and praised Bartlett for siding with democratic change in
the PRI by running in the party's first primary last November and
accepting his loss to Labastida.
</P>
<P>
   ``Manuel Bartlett has good relations with most people in the
PRI,'' Labastida said, and added, ``He will not have anything to do
with overseeing the elections.''
</P>
<P>
   The old guard came back in a rush that slipped out of
Labastida's control.
</P>
<P>
   PRI leaders named Manlio Fabio Beltrones to help run the party's
legislative campaigns. In 1997, when Beltrones was governor of
Sonora, United States Drug Enforcement Administration documents
cited him as having ties to drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   Beltrones vehemently denied a report about the documents in The
New York Times and moved to sue for criminal libel. The Mexican
attorney general declined to press charges, noting differences
between freedom of expression laws in Mexico and the United States,
where the report was published. As governor Beltrones was popular
in his state, but he has not held public office since he stepped
down in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida was taken by surprise when asked about Beltrones'
appointment a day after it was announced. ``I'm sorry, but I
haven't seen anything about that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign is already picking up steam. James Carville,
President Clinton's political consultant, has been advising
Labastida on how to be more media savvy. Now the candidate is
running communications himself. Hours after the Reuters poll was
announced, Labastida's team assailed its reliability, announcing a
survey by a pollster hired directly by the PRI, Stanley Greenberg.
It showed Labastida in the lead with 40 percent and Fox with 36
percent.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the PRI has rolled out some of its well-worn
hardball tactics. According to an audio tape obtained by the
opposition, hours after the presidential debate, the PRI governor
of Chiapas, Roberto Albores Guillen, ordered his press staff to
lean on local newspaper editors to publish stories trumpeting a
victory for Labastida.
</P>
<P>
   To judge from the Chiapas headlines the next day, that is
exactly what they did. Four papers, including the leading one,
bannered headlines that read in one form or another that Labastida
had triumphed.
</P>
<P>
   When Fox was on a tour in the state of Puebla, a leader of the
oil workers' union there hung out the opposition candidate's
white-and-blue banner at the local headquarters. Top bosses of the
staunchly PRI union fired off letters ordering the local leader to
take the banner down.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a massive operation to tighten down the screws,''
charged Luis Felipe Bravo Mena, the chairman of Fox's party.
</P>
<P>
   PRI supporters, while skeptical, said they were ready to answer
the party's call. ``I'm going to vote for them once more,'' said
Salvador Alejandre Martinez, a 30-year-old PRI follower at a rally
in Veracruz. ``But believe me, if things don't change, this is the
last time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
