<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-POLL-METHOD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW THE POLL WAS CONDUCTED 
</HEADLINE>
  (With CAMPAIGN-POLL) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The latest New York Times/CBS News Poll is based on telephone
interviews conducted Wednesday through Saturday with 947 adults
throughout the United States. Of these, 716 said they were
registered to vote.
</P>
<P>
   The telephone exchanges called were randomly selected by a
computer from a complete list of more than 42,000 active
residential exchanges in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Within each exchange, random digits were added to form a
complete telephone number, permitting access to both listed and
unlisted numbers. Within each household, one adult was designated
by a random procedure to be the respondent for the survey.
</P>
<P>
   The results have been weighted to account for household size and
the number of telephone lines in the residence, and to adjust for
variations in the sample relating to geographic region, sex, race,
age and education.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, in 19 cases out of 20, the results based on such
samples will differ by no more than 4 percentage points in either
direction from what would have been obtained by talking to all
registered voters in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   For smaller subgroups, the margin of sampling error is larger.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to sampling error, the practical difficulties of
conducting any survey of public opinion may introduce other sources
of error. Variations in the wording and order of questions, for
example, may lead to somewhat different results.
</P>
</TEXT>
