<HEADER>
A5999 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-JAMAICA-FILM-NYT &LR;      05-15 1175
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAMAICA-FILM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIFE IMITATING ART IMITATING LIFE IN A JAMAICAN MOVIE  
 DAVID GONZALEZ  
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KINGSTON, Jamaica _ The sound of helicopters flying over the
Kingston ghettos was not the kind of buzz the producers of ``Third
World Cop'' had in mind before this movie's hometown opening here
last summer. But with life intimidating art, the premiere of this
violent tale about a hardened police officer named Capone who is
fighting ghetto gunrunners, was postponed for two months while the
police and soldiers engaged in deadly battles against heavily armed
gangs.
</P>
<P>
   The filmmakers wanted to be sensitive to complaints that it was
not the right time for movie mayhem while there were real-life
clashes in the streets. The military occupation that followed led
some Jamaicans to denounce what they called the routine use of
excessive force in some of the country's poorest and most violent
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Capone would have understood the drastic measures. He dispenses
bullets and justice with an icy gusto that makes Dirty Harry look
like Mahatma Gandhi. He would just glare at his critics _ film,
social or otherwise _ and remind them, ``We run things, things
don't run we.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever qualms anyone had about Capone's tactics apparently
vanished by the time the movie opened in October; it went on to
become Jamaica's highest grossing movie. Yet the success of a film
about a take-no-prisoners lawman comes at the very time when
Jamaicans are grappling with the issues of rampant urban violence
and police brutality. Last summer a newspaper poll revealed that 26
percent of Jamaicans were so fearful of crime that they said the
police should shoot known criminals on sight. At the same time
advocacy groups have been calling for official inquiries into the
role of the police in several violent incidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Third World Cop,'' the movie and its protagonist, reflect that
dual pull, occupying the same nebulous territory in the minds of
many Jamaicans.
</P>
<P>
   The story line is of a bad man who is a good guy and who can
answer the gunmen and criminals on equal terms and come out well.
Barry Chevannes, dean of the faculty of social science at the
University of the West Indies, said: ``There is a feeling among
some people, and it may sound contradictory, that on the one hand
police tend to be brutal and hostile in many inner-city
communities. On the other hand, you get the very same people
demanding strong action.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last 25 years or so there have emerged cops who have
had that kind of an aura about them, of a very strong man, some of
whom become legends in a way. They can deal with criminals, but
people are obviously ambivalent.''
</P>
<P>
   What has happened is that people can identify with Capone and
Ratty, his childhood friend, whose desperation leads him into a
gunrunning scheme.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is so individualistic down here, everybody thinks of
himself as the hero,'' said Chris Browne, the film's director.
``That's why we have such a hard time playing football, because
nobody can pass the ball to the next person to win. In Jamaica,
everybody wants to be a star. They look up to the novelty of a bad
man. That is because there is a certain thing in society here where
people identify with the bad man. He is the guy who takes the bull
by the horns and knows he's going to end up dead in a glorious
way.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie was inspired by the flamboyant exploits of a real-life
police officer who was an acquaintance of the film's producer,
Carolyn Pfeiffer. Through conversations with other police officers
and tag-along rides with special squads, the filmmakers learned how
guns were smuggled from the United States in barrels and hidden in
Jamaica.
</P>
<P>
   While many things they observed made it into the final film,
some did not. For instance, the role of the island's political
parties in arming gangs of partisans who turned the ghetto streets
into war zones in the 1970s and 80s is only touched upon.
</P>
<P>
   Browne said he was asked to stay away from politics. ``To me, it
was a difficult thing to write a movie about the inner city and
guns without writing about politics,'' he said, ``because they go
hand in hand. We touch on it, obviously not referring to any party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politics is like talking religion in Jamaica. People kill
themselves talking religion in the world. In Jamaica they do it
over politics.''
</P>
<P>
   What people do see in the film is a glimpse, simplified and
prettified by the casting of several famous dancehall music D.J.'s,
of the dead-end life that is all too common in the slums of
Kingston. It is a real world inhabited by characters like Ratty,
who forsakes the hard work needed to become a D.J. to make a fast
dollar smuggling guns. While Ratty is undoubtedly a bad guy, his
plight resonates strongly among younger Jamaicans who know that
many employers will not take a chance on anybody with a ghetto
address.
</P>
<P>
   ``That icon of the bad man in Jamaica, hustling to make things
happen for himself is very big,'' said Mark Danvers, who portrays
Ratty. ``Everybody can identify with that man. He is held up in the
songs and in the way that people in their early 20s carry
themselves. That is the man, the anti-state, anti-conformist fellow
because there is a deep distrust of the state. Lie after lie,
failure after failure and nothing ever gets better despite the fact
that people do work hard, nothing gets better.''
</P>
<P>
   The filmmakers also wanted to show the pressures that the police
are under as they confront a country that has been awash in guns
for decades and is now under the sway of dons, some of whom have
escaped the control of political leaders and allied themselves with
drug dealers. At times the situation has grown so chaotic that the
police have to enter neighborhoods under the protection of armored
personnel carriers. Nevertheless selling the idea of a tough cop as
a good guy is a daunting task in a society where news broadcasters
qualify attacks on the police as alleged confrontations.
</P>
<P>
   The $500,000 budget for the digital video production dictated
that some scenes, including those showing the heartwarming side of
villains, had to be left out, though there are hints of the side
when Capone begins to question his ways.
</P>
<P>
   The Jamaica that is portrayed in the movie is not one that most
tourists or many middle-class Jamaicans will ever encounter. While
it seems like a cartoon shoot 'em up at times, it retains an
essence of truth for many who know the hard-luck life of ghetto
residents. .
</P>
<P>
   ``Once people see themselves, that makes people think, if
nothing else,'' said Carolyn Gomes, a doctor who is a founder of
Jamaicans for Justice, an advocacy group active in low-income
areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps it will make those who are not so aware of life in the
ghetto a little more aware,'' she said. ``And hopefully it will
allow you to take a step back and see if that person is the person
you want to be, or if you want to do anything differently. That's
the function of all art, to see things in a different way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
