<DOCNO> NYT20000515.0375 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 21:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6003 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-SOCSEC-ASSESS-NYT     05-15 1074
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCSEC-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANDIDATES CHALLENGE BEDROCK OF RETIREMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (With SOCSEC-CANDIDATES)  
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Since it was established in 1935, Social Security
has had two fundamental principles. It has been a guaranteed
government benefit. And it has been self-financed, paid for out of
payroll taxes levied on workers.
</P>
<P>
   In reopening the debate Monday over how best to maintain the
solvency of the retirement system as the population ages, Vice
President Al Gore and Gov. George W. Bush each challenged one of
those principles.
</P>
<P>
   Taking one of the biggest political risks of the presidential
campaign so far, Bush proposed allowing individual workers to
invest a portion of their payroll taxes through private accounts.
His plan would give workers an opportunity to capture some of the
riches that Wall Street creates, but would also leave those workers
to suffer the financial consequences if their timing or judgment is
off.
</P>
<P>
   Gore wants to maintain the guaranteed nature of the Social
Security benefit, allowing it to remain a bulwark against poverty
in old age. But through a somewhat complicated mechanism, Gore is
calling for the bill to be paid in part over the long run out of
general tax revenues _ in effect, heaving the problem onto the
shoulders of taxpayers three decades from now.
</P>
<P>
   Those differing approaches to dealing with the financial
problems that threaten to afflict Social Security are at the heart
of a longstanding ideological dispute about the relationship
between government and individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Like most Democrats, Gore is comfortable with government as a
guarantor and sees Social Security as a collective commitment that
binds the generations. Like most Republicans, Bush is dedicated to
giving more power and responsibility to individuals.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, President Clinton and the Republican leadership
in Congress tried to find some common ground and failed.
</P>
<P>
   In elevating the call for private accounts to the presidential
campaign, Bush is asking for a mandate to break the deadlock.
Although Gore's approach would eventually require a fundamental
change in the nature of the system as well, the vice president has
cast himself as the defender of a program that has proved to be
perhaps the most popular and most effective of any administered in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   It is already clear that the clash between the two candidates
will be supercharged, with Gore in particular unleashing a
sustained attack on Bush's position. And the more heated the clash,
the greater the risk that the debate will so polarize voters and
unnerve politicians that it blocks progress for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a good issue to debate as long as the discussion remains
civil,'' said Robert D. Reischauer, a former director of the
Congressional Budget Office who is now president of the Urban
Institute, a research group. ``It could easily backfire and lead to
a situation where the lesson coming out of this campaign is, `Don't
try and deal forthrightly with the American people on this issue
when there isn't an immediate crisis.'''
</P>
<P>
   Polls suggest that voters are split. In a survey conducted last
week, The New York Times/CBS News Poll found that 51 percent
thought allowing individuals to invest a part of their payroll
taxes was a good idea, and 45 percent thought it was a bad one.
</P>
<P>
   Many Democrats and some Republicans wonder why Bush has chosen
to wade into such a polarizing issue. ``Politically it's not'' a
great idea, said Sen. Judd Gregg, R-N.H., one of the most prominent
advocates of adding private accounts to Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's a genuine act of leadership,'' Gregg said, ``because
if he's successful, he will have broken the iron triangle of
demagoguery _ Gore, Gephardt and the labor unions. And he'll have a
national mandate to do something in this area.'' His reference was
to Rep. Dick Gephardt of Missouri, the House Democratic leader.
</P>
<P>
   But both sides also have electoral strategies in mind. For
Republicans, putting Social Security on the front burner is an
effort to attract what they see as an emerging investor class. More
than 50 percent of households now invest in the market directly or
indirectly. Many of them have had great success as Wall Street has
boomed, and are presumed by Republicans to want greater control
over their finances.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans also see private accounts as a way to grab the
attention of young voters, who tend to believe that Social Security
will not be around when their retire.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Democrats think that in the end the only groups that will be
motivated to vote on the basis of the candidates' positions on
Social Security will be the elderly and those workers nearing
retirement. Those groups have consistently opposed any fundamental
changes to Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bush campaign is betting that young people will end up
voting on this issue,'' said Geoff Garin, a Democratic pollster.
``But recent history is pretty clear that the people who vote on
Social Security tend to be in their 50s and older, and their vote
is based on making sure that the system that's protecting their
parents is there to protect them.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush is trying to turn attention to the trade-off at the core of
Gore's plan, which is built around eliminating the $3.5 trillion in
national debt held by the public and capturing the interest savings
for Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   When all the complexities are stripped away, Gore's plan would
leave the government in financially sound condition _ but would
also transfer to future generations of taxpayers the burden of
keeping Social Security solvent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Gore plan will eventually require a 25 percent increase in
income taxes _ the largest in our history _ or a substantial
reduction in benefits,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is trying to keep the debate focused on the risks inherent
in investing Social Security money in the financial market _ and is
emphasizing that Bush's plan would leave less money to pay down the
debt.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush plan ``would weaken our national economy,'' Gore said,
and create the risk of millions of retirees ``left without enough
to make ends meet.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said one thing Monday that Bush would no doubt agree with.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a fundamental difference on this issue in this
election,'' Gore said, ``which offers the country the most critical
choice on Social Security since it was first enacted in 1935.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-00 2151EDT &QL; 
