<DOCNO> NYT20000515.0377 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 21:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6005 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-ACCESSORIES-FASHION-A     05-15 1219
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ACCESSORIES-FASHION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S NOT JUST SOMETHING `IN THE AIR': THAT'S MIUCCIA PRADA'S
INFLUENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT24,25 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By CATHY HORYN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The American fashion industry has been indebted to
Miuccia Prada for several seasons, and it looks as if she is still
the boss designer. Her shapes, colors and peculiar sense of luxury
were everywhere last week as retailers scouted the latest fall
accessories, and don't let some copycat tell you, ``It's just in
the air.''
</P>
<P>
   One spin around the Accessory Circuit, a trade show at Piers 92
and 94, told the story. The most ubiquitous handbag came in a
half-moon shape (think bowling ball dimensions) with clutch handles
and a retro color palette that favored maroon and light blue. Sound
familiar? Prada did the bowling bag for spring. If the Italian
company has moved on for fall, with its version of the doctor bag,
others are trying to keep up. Zerafa, a new company based in
California, was displaying a pair of rounded bags its
representative, Jenn Caig, called ``the large and small doctor.''
But, they still looked more like a strike and a spare.
</P>
<P>
   Prada's fall collection also included fur tippets tied loosely
at the neck. These were worn in a slightly careless manner, over
simple knits and sparkling evening sequins alike, and they made one
think of a tipsy but well-dressed matron emerging from Cipriani as
she hastily readjusts her clothes. On a gray dress form positioned
outside Elizabeth Gillett's booth at Pier 94, the tippet seemed to
lose some of its power. Still, the style will be among the most
prominent for fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel there's a major opportunity in fur _ fur handbags, fur
berets, fur-trimmed shoes and boots, and fur neck pieces,'' said
Sandra Wilson, the accessories fashion director at Neiman Marcus.
``It's part of a luxury statement in all fashion categories.'' Dana
Christy, who buys accessories for Saks Fifth Avenue, agreed, adding
that the most forward trends in handbags, scarves and other
accessories came from ready-to-wear designers like Prada, Donatella
Versace and Karl Lagerfeld of Chanel.
</P>
<P>
   But most manufacturers have been a step behind. ``I found that
the accessories market was way out of sync with what was going on
in ready-to-wear this season,'' Christy said. ``Designers were into
ladylike, put-together clothes while the accessories people were
still doing bohemian.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly there was a feeling of redundancy as one trooped down
the aisles at Pier 94 looking for signs of genuine novelty among so
many beaded or patchwork handbags.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired of all the embellishment,'' said Lisa Glass, a buyer
for Boyd's, a Philadelphia store owned by her father, Jerry
Gushner. Glass was with Debbie Blank, another Boyd's buyer,
inspecting soft totes in tweed and camel fabrics at the Clever
Carriage Co.'s booth.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Isaacsohn, the owner of the company, which she describes as
``the ultimate lifestyle collection for clever people,'' was
warming up with her sales pitch. ``The Louis Vuitton and Prada bags
are very heavy,'' said Isaacsohn, who worked for the British
retailer Marks &AMP; Spencer before starting her company. ``We don't
have a chauffeur to carry our handbags.''
</P>
<P>
   As Glass was saying she thought the tweedy bags jibed with
fall's casual chic, Liliane Wancer, who runs a buying office whose
clients include Lane Crawford in Hong Kong, stopped by. She ticked
off the big trends: ``Gold. Lots of big hoop earrings. Tweeds. Big
bags. Small bags are disappearing. Very ladylike looks.''
</P>
<P>
   Wancer said it's understandable if stores often gravitate toward
a single dominant style, like the Prada bowling bag, even if such a
look is widely copied. ``A woman wants something that says to her
friends, `I'm in fashion,''' Wancer said. ``Everybody needs
direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Accessories are a big business. According to the NPD Group, a
research firm that tracks apparel and accessory sales, more than $1
billion was spent on handbags alone last year. Many companies, like
Gucci, Prada, Louis Vuitton and Tod's, have found a successful
niche in the $500 to $900 luxury category, though most sales, the
NPD Group reported, are at much lower prices. The fact that many of
the accessory designers interviewed at the pier show started their
businesses less than two years ago is another indication of the
market's strength.
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie Layne was working for a doctor's office when she and
Jill Roeb, a promotions manager for Warner Brothers, started their
hair ornament and jewelry business, Haute Stuff, a couple of years
ago. Today, their Los Angeles-based company sells such things as
suede headbands and paillette-embellished necklaces to stores like
Henri Bendel and Nordstrom. ``The accessories business is so
competitive,'' Layne said, ``you have to constantly come up with
something new.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson of Neiman Marcus added: ``I think everyone wants to get
in on a look. The key is to know when to stay with it, and when to
move on.''
</P>
<P>
   As insipid as the trend toward ladylike dressing may sometimes
seem _ with its conscientious revival of suits, pumps and those
overtly old-money gestures like pearls and tweeds _ it is giving
new life to accessories like belts and scarves. Christy of Saks
pointed to the oblong scarves that Lagerfeld showed at Chanel with
suits and flaring coats, and to the suede belts with trophy-size
buckles at Dolce &AMP; Gabbana and Versace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Versace looked brilliant _ bombshell sex,'' Christy
said. ``This is the confident femme fatale, unlike the polished
one.''
</P>
<P>
   For polish and money, there is what Wilson calls ``the finishing
touches,'' so vital, apparently, in a season of put-together
dressing. That might mean a crocodile handbag, fur-trimmed boots or
a pair of rimless aviator sunglasses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Or it could be all of that together on the right person,''
Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   Python and animal prints are everywhere for fall, too. ``It's
sex and fashion,'' said Barbra Musial, the vice president for sales
at Eric Javits, as she put on a fuzzy leopard-print cowboy hat
called Bonanza.
</P>
<P>
   ``And she was a bonanza, too, in sales,'' said Musial, who
refers to all of Javits' hats _ Lucky, Dude and the other new
styles _ by the female pronoun. Musial said fedoras will be big for
fall, but there is still action in the sexier Bonanza, which she
calls a ranch hat, ``because that's where the money is going now,
to ranches in Montana.''
</P>
<P>
   Trade shows tend to be down-to-earth reminders that not everyone
is ready for the latest topper or tippet. ``In 32 years, I've seen
everything,'' said Selma Pustin, the owner of a store in Baltimore
called That Handbag Place, as she and Emily Rosenthal-Levitas, a
buyer, stopped to speak to a reporter. They were dubious about the
prospects in Baltimore for doctor or bowling bags. They seemed more
confident about handbags trimmed with brightly colored beads, as
long as it wasn't overdone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have women who come in for those nylon bags,'' Pustin
said with a sigh, referring to the older Prada style.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenthal-Levitas gave a knowing laugh and said to the reporter:
``Aren't you glad you stopped us?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
