u f BC-WIT-OFFERING-NYT     05-15 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIT-OFFERING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ETRADE AND WIT CAPITAL JOIN TO FACE OFF-LINE RIVALS 
</HEADLINE>
  By PATRICK McGEEHAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Acknowledging how hard it has been to break the stranglehold
Wall Street has on the underwriting of new stocks, two online
financial services companies, the ETrade Group and the Wit Capital
Group, said Monday that they would team up to compete against their
off-line rivals.
</P>
<P>
   ETrade, a leading electronic brokerage firm, said it would form
an alliance with Wit Capital after that online investment bank
acquires EOffering, a competitor that ETrade helped to finance a
year ago. Wit Capital, which started out as a boutique brewery in
New York's SoHo district, said it would issue stock worth $328
million to the shareholders of EOffering.
</P>
<P>
   The deal coincides with the arrival of a potentially formidable
competitor: an online investment bank in San Francisco that is
being developed by Epoch Capital Partners with backing from the
Charles Schwab Corp. and two other electronic brokerage firms, TD
Waterhouse and the Ameritrade Holding Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of the alliance, ETrade and Wit will form a mutually
exclusive relationship, with Wit as the sole provider of stock
research, initial public offerings and other new issues of stock to
ETrade's 2.6 million customers. ETrade expects to record a gain of
about $50 million on its investment in EOffering, a money-losing
venture that has had trouble building a stable management team.
</P>
<P>
   Christos Cotsakos, the cheerleading chairman and chief executive
of ETrade, proclaimed that the alliance would create ``a category
killer in the online financial services space.''
</P>
<P>
   But some analysts were less excited, characterizing the deal as
a trade-off that will allow each firm to concentrate on its core
business.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts and competitors said that the deal demonstrated the
difficulty of building an investment banking operation from
scratch. Some saw it as a signal of more consolidation among online
financial companies that are too small to compete effectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an admission that it is very, very difficult to move up''
the ranks of underwriters, said Richard Repetto, an analyst at
Lehman Brothers Holdings. ``Wit and EOffering were in a number of
deals, but they weren't the lead managers.''
</P>
<P>
   The role of lead manager of an initial public offering is the
most coveted on Wall Street. Those deals carry the biggest fees for
investment bankers, as much as 7 percent of the amount of money
raised from investors. But the firms chosen by corporations as lead
underwriters keep most of that money for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Online investment banks have tried to persuade technology
companies to hire them for their expertise in distributing shares
over the Internet and for the technological savvy of their
customers. But most of the recent crop of Internet companies to go
public have followed the beaten path to Wall Street and chosen the
likes of Goldman Sachs Group and Morgan Stanley Dean Witter &AMP; Co.
to manage their offerings.
</P>
<P>
   EOffering, whose other owners include the venture capital firms
General Atlantic Partners, Softbank Venture Capital and Battery
Ventures, had revenue of just $20 million last quarter and expects
to lose about $10 million in its current fiscal year. Faced with
the prospect of continuing losses if the market for new stocks
remains depressed, some of those investors approached Wit Capital
management about a deal a few weeks ago, people close to Wit said.
</P>
<P>
   The deal gives ETrade significant say in the operation of Wit,
which has about 100,000 customers. ETrade will have a stake of
about 7 percent in Wit, and Cotsakos and a partner in General
Atlantic will have seats on Wit's board. ETrade will also gain
access to a set of products that none of its competitors can offer.
</P>
<P>
   The deal has benefits for Wit, too, analysts said. ``They
basically were able to eliminate a competitor from the
marketplace,'' said Amy Butte, an analyst with the Bear Stearns
Cos.
</P>
<P>
   It will also weaken a competitive advantage Epoch Capital
Partners had been citing to potential clients. ``Epoch's pitch to
issuers against Wit Capital was that Wit had only 100,000 accounts
versus Epoch's millions'' through Schwab, Waterhouse and
Ameritrade, Butte said.
</P>
<P>
   All of those firms and their online competitors have been
scrapping for bigger pieces of stock offerings, especially initial
offerings. That has not changed, despite the wilting market for new
stocks, said Suzanne Richardson, president of Fbr.com, the online
arm of the investment banking firm Friedman, Billings, Ramsey
Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Online investors are primarily interested in IPO's,'' she
said. ``But that's going to change. We will start to see online
investors as opposed to online traders.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson said the deal would most likely lead more established
investment banks to make acquisitions or form alliances that will
give them access to an online distribution channel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
