<SLUG> BC-SEC-BIGDIG-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEC UPGRADES PROBE OF BIG DIG FINANCES TO FULL INVESTIGATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Securities and Exchange Commission has upgraded an
investigation into whether Massachusetts misled investors about
finances of the Central Artery-Third Harbor Tunnel Project.
</P>
<P>
   The news that securities regulators have turned their
preliminary inquiry into a formal investigation was disclosed
Monday in an unrelated state bond offering for construction on
college campuses.
</P>
<P>
   Information provided with the bond offering said the state
treasurer's office received notification a week ago that a formal
probe had been launched.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can confirm that the SEC has advised our office that they
are now conducting a formal investigation, and we will continue to
assist them as they move forward,'' Dwight Robson, spokesman for
state Treasurer Shannon P. O'Brien, said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the SEC and the Massachusetts Turnpike Authority,
which oversees the project, could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Also Monday, lawmakers released their plan to pay for what is
now estimated to be a $2 billion budget gap at the Big Dig.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC, which regulates the securities markets, is examining a
December prospectus prepared by the state for a sale of $200
million in MBTA transportation bonds. The prospectus failed to
mention that the Big Dig was over budget, despite the fact that
project managers had known for months of a massive project deficit.
</P>
<P>
   The former Massachusetts Turnpike Authority chairman, James J.
Kerasiotes, disclosed Feb. 1 that the project was over budget.
Kerasiotes was later fired for failing to reveal the financial
problems sooner.
</P>
<P>
   The Globe reported in February that the agency had begun a
preliminary inquiry into the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Sources have said that investigators want to know exactly when
state officials learned of the budget gap. The SEC wants to
determine whether investors buying state bonds were misled about
the cost of the Big Dig, as well as whether the project posed any
risk to the state's overall fiscal condition, which could affect
borrowing for other projects.
</P>
<P>
   Some state officials fear that the SEC is seeking to make an
example of Massachusetts for failing to be forthright about the
project. Bond buyers and others familiar with the SEC say the
agency has recently been cracking down on those who violate rules
for disclosure pertaining to the sale of municipal bonds.
</P>
<P>
   The agency has taken action at least 95 times in the past six
years for state and local government bond sales, mostly for lapses
in disclosure.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear what kind of action the SEC may take against the
state if it finds violations. The agency can seek criminal fraud
charges against public officials if it finds that they failed to
disclose relevant information that caused financial harm to
investors.
</P>
<P>
   But lawyers and others familiar with Wall Street have said that
it may be difficult for the SEC to make a case that the state's
failure to be truthful about the Big Dig overrun harmed investors.
</P>
<P>
   After the project's financing gap was revealed, Massachusetts
bonds sold at a lower rate of return than bonds sold last year.
That indicates that investors are not overly concerned about how
the Big Dig cost overruns affect the state's overall fiscal
condition and other state bond issues.
</P>
<P>
   Lesser penalties the SEC can impose include civil fines levied
against individuals or the agency and a cease-and-desist letter
designed to prevent future failure to disclose information.
</P>
<P>
   Governor Paul Cellucci has already admitted that he knew last
fall about a potential overrun. However, he insisted there were no
hard figures for the budget gap at the time.
</P>
<P>
   The governor and other state officials went to Wall Street in
December and won an upgrade in the state's bond rating from Moody's
Investor Service.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci said he told the rating agency at the time that a
financial analysis of the project was underway and costs could
increase. Since then, he has insisted that the state was
``straightforward with the people on Wall Street.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-00 2202EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
