<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-PARKINSON-FASHION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DESIGNER ON THE MOVE 
BARNEYS NEW YORK RETURNS TO FAMILIAR TURF 
A FILM INSPIRED BY ARMANI AND COMBS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATING to add photo note)   (ART ADV:  Photo NYT23  is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By GINIA BELLAFANTE  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gregory Parkinson is surely the only designer in New York,
probably the only one in Milan, Paris or Antwerp, too, whose
self-imposed bedtime is 8:30 p.m. Since he closed his Los Angeles
shop three years ago and gave up putting celebrities in big gowns,
Parkinson has led a hushed fashion life.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving Los Angeles, he returned to his native England
before relocating to New York nearly two years ago, where he
started designing whimsically patterned jackets, skirts and
sweaters using old couture and upholstery fabrics and hand-dying
them in his apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Parkinson's collections are tiny, with about 10 looks in each,
but his clothes were immediately picked up by Barneys New York and
Linda Dresner. Last year, Moeet &AMP; Chandon selected him to be in its
Bryant Park showcase of young talent. With his Fall 2000
collection, he tripled his orders over past seasons, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Stone, the owner of Savannah, the stylish Santa Monica
shop where Parkinson has developed a following, attributed his
growing success to the fact that his clothes are, ``if not one of a
kind, then close to it.''
</P>
<P>
   BARNEYS NEW YORK RETURNS TO FAMILIAR TURF
</P>
<P>
   With fashionably glossed concrete floors, rolling racks and
enough Kiehl's products to keep an entire ZIP code's complexions
glowing, Barneys New York opened its Co-op shop at 236 West 18th
St. on Saturday. The store has the kind of weekend-oriented date
clothes featured on the two Co-op floors of Barneys' Madison Avenue
flagship. They are priced below Barneys' usual fare and are among
the store's best sellers.
</P>
<P>
   The downtown version of the Co-op sits on a relatively
untrafficked patch of Chelsea around the corner from the store's
original Seventh Avenue site. It occupies the space where Barneys'
semiannual warehouse sales are held. That tradition, oddly enough,
will continue, with the Co-op closing for the six weeks of the year
the warehouse sales take place.
</P>
<P>
   For the remaining 46 weeks, Co-op shoppers will have T-shirts,
jeans and items like $300-plus suede skirts and beaded tank tops to
try on in dressing rooms that, like the office bathrooms on ``Ally
McBeal,'' are anomalously unisex. ``We wanted to make it more of a
social thing,'' said David New, executive vice president for
creative services at Barneys.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that there are men's clothes at all in the Co-op, as
well as the store's industrial design, distinguish it from girlish
shopping havens like Scoop and Calypso, which have fanned out all
over the city and attract the kind of shopper who, in another era,
would have looked toward the Co-op for things that weren't
everywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   The main purpose of the new Co-op is to attract ``the downtown
neighborhood customer who didn't come uptown,'' Judy Collinson,
general merchandise manager of Barneys, said.
</P>
<P>
   Julie Brown, founder of a nonprofit children's services agency,
Room to Grow, lives two blocks from the Co-op and visited it twice
over the weekend. ``I liked having all the cosmetics,'' she said,
but added that clothingwise, ``there wasn't much I could find that
was useful. They should have reached out more to the person who
doesn't want the slinky, beaded bias-cut dress or skirt.''
</P>
<P>
   A FILM INSPIRED BY ARMANI AND COMBS
</P>
<P>
   An aging Italian designer whose name is a megabrand is having
business problems. A brash young hip-hop star is aiming for fashion
moguldom. Hip-hop star sets his sights on taking over the Italian
house.
</P>
<P>
   Giorgio Armani's empire is not about to be bought by Puffy
Combs, but they are the inspiration for two characters in a fashion
film, ``Perfume,'' which finished shooting in New York last week.
Paul Sorvino is the Italian designer; the Gap model and actor Omar
Epps is the rapper.
</P>
<P>
   Nadia Leonelli, the producer, said the film, set for release
next year, features intersecting stories a la ``Short Cuts,'' and
all the acting is improvisational. Michael Rymer, an Australian
director whose family is in the fashion business, decided to make
``Perfume'' after taking acting lessons in the improvisational
technique.
</P>
<P>
   The movie, with Rita Wilson as an East Village designer,
Michelle Williams as a runaway daughter of a fashion editor and
Jeff Goldblum as a headhunter in search of new design talent, will
take shape in the editing room, Leonelli said, adding, ``Right now,
it's 10 movies.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-00 2202EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000515.0382 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6014 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBA-RANGERS-JONES-TEX     05-15 0505
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-JONES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JONES MAKES HOME DEBUT AS COACH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CARLOS MENDEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Bobby Jones is the winningest minor-league
manager in the Rangers' organization.
</P>
<P>
   If that doesn't impress Rangers fans, maybe this does: Asked
yesterday to name the best players he has managed, he laughed and
said, ``Sosa, Gonzalez, Pudge.''
</P>
<P>
   That short list _ former Rangers outfielders Sammy Sosa and Juan
Gonzalez and catcher Ivan Rodriguez _ demonstrates the depth of
Jones' roots in the Rangers' organization. He managed all three as
they came up in the minor leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, Jones further cemented his place with the Rangers
when he was named a full-time coach with the major-league team. He
had joined the staff on an interim basis last week after the
retirement of third-base coach Ed Napolean.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, 50, a former outfielder who spent parts of nine years
with the Angels and Rangers, will work with the outfielders, the
Rangers said. He had been manager of the Rangers' Double-A team in
Tulsa since 1995, managed at Oklahoma City in 1994 and 1993 and at
Tulsa in 1991 and 1992.
</P>
<P>
   He has also managed at Charlotte and has a managerial record of
832-866 with two championships _ the Florida State league title at
Charlotte in 1989 and the Texas League championship at Tulsa in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Also yesterday, the Rangers said Charlotte manager James Byrd
will manage the team at Tulsa effective tomorrow and that Bob
Miscik, roving minor-league instructor, would assume the manager
duties at Charlotte starting last night. Assistant coach Moe Hill
was scheduled to manage at Tulsa last night and tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you're in the minor leagues, as a player or a
manager, your goal is to get to the major leagues,'' Jones said.
``Since my first year of managing in '88, it's been a goal of mine
to get back up here.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones retired in 1986 as a .221 hitter with 23 career home runs
but holds the Rangers' record for pinch hits (42).
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been in the organization a long time. It's good to see
him get a chance,'' Rodriguez said. ``He knows a lot about the
game. He helped me a lot. He taught me a lot about baseball. He's a
great guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who signed his first professional contract in 1967 with
the Washington Senators, remembers the rising careers of Sosa,
Gonzalez and Rodriguez in the minor leagues. Perhaps the most
pleasant surprise was Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Juan, you knew he was going to play in the big leagues.
Sosa struck out 150 times for me one year and hit .220, .230,''
Jones said. ``But his work ethic, his determination and drive, was
outstanding. Of course, nobody could have predicted he'd hit 50
home runs. And he could fly. He'd hit a comebacker to the pitcher
and make it a bang-bang play at first.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sosa is the same today as he was an 18-year-old. He has the
same personality.''
</P>
<P>
   And Rodriguez?
</P>
<P>
   ``Pudge was another very hard worker. He didn't pull the ball as
much as he does now.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
