r s BC-GLF-COLONIAL-TEX     05-15 1423
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-COLONIAL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLONIAL'S FACELIFT KEEPS THE ORIGINAL CHARACTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ A shuffle of the course awaits PGA Tour
competitors this week at the MasterCard Colonial.
</P>
<P>
   Along with acres of resurfaced ground come new ground rules for
what is chic and not-so-chic heading into Thursday's opening round:
</P>
<P>
   Bunker putts are out. Sand saves are in.
</P>
<P>
   Boring bridges are out. Stonework facades are in.
</P>
<P>
   Unobstructed shots from the rough are out. New trees are in (68,
to be exact).
</P>
<P>
   Poa-annua grass is out. Heat-tolerant, velvet-smooth A-4 bent
grass is in.
</P>
<P>
   It is that latest addition, which has taken Colonial's greens
from first generation to fourth generation of bent-grass
development, that is at the heart of a $3.5 million renovation
project that has occurred at the club since the final putt dropped
at the 1999 tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The result, Colonial officials said, are rebuilt putting
surfaces that offer the truest rolls the course has seen since it
opened in 1936.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the pros, I don't think the course will play that much
different, tee to green. But if there's no wind during the
tournament, we may see some record scores,'' said David Hull,
chairman of the Colonial greens committee that oversaw the
reconstruction project. ``Once they get on these greens, the pros
are going to do very well. The greens turned out superb.''
</P>
<P>
   Best of all, in the estimation of club officials, they look just
like the old ones to the casual observer. In fact, the whole course
_ with rare exception _ meets that description. That was the charge
presented to Keith Foster, the St. Louis-based architect who gave
Colonial its face-lift between June 1999 and April 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Colonial officials sought to add strategic bunkers, make
existing bunkers more penal, rebuild the greens to original
specifications and rid the putting surfaces of an infestation of
poa-annua grass. In addition, they wanted to improve course
drainage, beautify the bridges and reroute cart paths to make them
less conspicuous. And they wanted to do it, Hull said, with enough
subtlety that ``85 percent of the members will look out there and
think nothing's changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Mission accomplished, in the estimation of club officials. Early
returns indicate the touring pros like the subtle nuances they've
noticed, although they don't expect them to significantly impact
scoring during the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should be a nice change,'' said Mark Brooks, a Fort Worth
resident. ``The greens are firmer, but they're not rock-hard.
That's good. There are a couple of holes that get your attention.
But overall, the changes aren't that significant.''
</P>
<P>
   Colonial, in other words, ``still looks like Colonial,'' said
Ben Crenshaw, a two-time champ who huddled with club officials
during the renovation process to lobby for keeping the contours of
the greens the same as they have been since the course opened.
Crenshaw's words, Hull said, helped sway some who thought the
rebuilt greens could use more undulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I told them was to keep it looking and playing like
Colonial ... because that's always been a great test of golf,''
said Crenshaw, who is preparing for his 30th consecutive Colonial
appearance, a tournament record. ``It's a very traditional course,
and it's stood the test of time. From a historical standpoint, I
thought it should play as closely as possible to the way it's
always played. I know \Rclub members\S are very pleased, and so am
I. I'm looking forward to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Since tournament officials slipped a plaid jacket around the
shoulders of Olin Browne to conclude the 1999 event, all 18 greens
have been rebuilt to eliminate the effects of erosion. Each putting
surface was laser-measured in 5-foot sections, assuring that all
contours were rebuilt within a quarter-inch inch of original
specifications.
</P>
<P>
   The greens were covered with A-4 bent grass, which is more
heat-tolerant and disease-resistant than its predecessor, a
Pincross bent. The new bent has almost twice as many blades per
square inch, resulting in truer rolls on putts.
</P>
<P>
   Around the course, some bunkers were added, others removed. Most
were given sharper lips to make the escape angles more severe. All
83 bunkers are equipped with drainage systems, and the new greens
have sub-ground air pumps that help eliminate surface moisture.
</P>
<P>
   Hull said the course had 82 bunkers during the 1999 Colonial.
Although there will be one additional sand trap this year, Hull
said Colonial's total bunker space has been reduced by 13,000
square feet because the new traps tend to be smaller but placed
more strategically.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, six holes have been lengthened by a combined 95
yards and roughly half of the 68 new trees were placed within 10
yards of the fairway.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of affecting play, the most significant alterations are
new tee boxes that lengthen hole Nos. 5, 7, 9, 11, 12 and 18. The
rebuilt greens will allow for new pin placements, many of them
behind bunkers that have been added or enhanced since the 1999
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can put the hole closer to the edge than before on some
greens. We probably picked up three or four tougher pin
placements,'' said Mark Russell, PGA Tour tournament director in
charge of setting up the course. ``Otherwise, I don't think it'll
play much different at all. It's such a great old course, you
wouldn't want to do anything to it to change it significantly.''
</P>
<P>
   Members point to the new bunkers as the course tweak most likely
to generate higher scores from the touring pros. In recent years,
Colonial's bunkers had ceased being a major concern for players
because they were too shallow and often allowed shots to roll in
one side and out the other.
</P>
<P>
   During last year's Colonial, only two of 120 drives charted by
tournament officials remained in a fairway bunker left of the first
fairway. Several others, Hull said, zipped through the bunker and
back into the rough, allowing players at least an outside chance to
reach the par-5 green on their second shots.
</P>
<P>
   A more glaring example of Colonial's toothless bunkers occurred
in 1991, when Tom Purtzer ``putted'' for birdie from a greenside
trap in the final round. The shot, which traveled 35 feet _
including the first 10 feet over sand _ is considered the signature
stroke in tournament history. It allowed Purtzer to build on a
one-stroke lead en route to a three-stroke victory.
</P>
<P>
   But it underscored that Colonial's bunkers were less than a
threat to the touring pros.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hate to have a deal classified as a hazard and watch
people be able to putt out of it,'' Hull said. ``He'll need a
60-degree loft on that putter to get out of that bunker now.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, more appropriately, a sand wedge. The course changes should
make that club more useful this season, especially at fresh or
rebuilt greenside bunkers at Nos. 3, 5, 11, 13, 15, 16 and 18. In
addition, strategic fairway bunkers were added or moved to pinch
drives at Nos. 1, 2, 3, 6, 9, 11 and 15.
</P>
<P>
   Hull cited a redesigned bunker complex left of the landing area
at No. 3 as the ``most severe'' alteration in terms of affecting
tee shots. Greenside bunkers at No. 11 are far more visible, and
more plentiful, than last year.
</P>
<P>
   But the most dramatic change is at No. 15. Three fairway bunkers
were brought more into play, the green was enlarged and a greenside
bunker was added.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the biggest change on the course,'' said Harold
Muckleroy, a tournament committee member and former club president.
``Not only the tee shot, but you've got a lot to think about with
more trouble around the green. It's subtle, but dramatic. It'll get
the pros' attention.''
</P>
<P>
   So will the greens. And the fairway bunkers. And the extra 95
yards, spread over six holes. Ideally, however, players and fans
will leave with a sense that little has changed at the course
Marvin Leonard founded in 1936.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no room here for anyone else's paw print but Marvin
Leonard's,'' said Scott Corpening, a tournament committee member.
``It's up to us to protect and defend what he built. And I think
we've done a decent job of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Hull concurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, the pros will say we took a traditional course and
made it better without changing its character,'' Hull said. ``If 95
percent of them think that, we'll be happy. There's always five
percent that will find something to gripe about. But those are
usually the guys who leave town on Friday night.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
