<SLUG> BC-BKC-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIANA ASSURES THAT ABUSES BY KNIGHT WON'T STOP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Indiana University assured us that there will be another victim
yesterday with a spineless slap on the wrist for embattled
basketball coach Bobby Knight.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of terminating the belligerent Knight for a litany of
embarrassing offenses that should have been enough to get him fired
long ago, Indiana's president and board of trustees once again took
a knee and kissed the hem of the coach's trademark red sweater.
</P>
<P>
   It is a dark day in college sports when a tyrant is allowed to
continue his dictatorship at the cost of yet another innocent
victim.
</P>
<P>
   Oh yes, somebody else will pay now.
</P>
<P>
   Another 18-year-old boy might be physically abused, choked,
kicked, pushed around.
</P>
<P>
   A 64-year-old secretary might be berated in a wall-shaking
explosion of obscenities. Hopefully, her boss _ and Knight's _ will
be there to protect her again the next time it happens.
</P>
<P>
   A flunky from the sports information office might be punched and
pushed around.
</P>
<P>
   An athletic director who has the audacity to offer consolation
to Knight after a tough loss might find himself under physical and
verbal assault.
</P>
<P>
   A sports writer, trying to do his job, will be humiliated and
intimidated when the ``great'' coach shouts him into submission
after a Hoosiers' loss.
</P>
<P>
   A fan in a restaurant might be slapped around for daring to
question the great Bobby Knight.
</P>
<P>
   That's what Indiana gave us yesterday in one of the most
cowardly stands by a major university in the history of sports.
</P>
<P>
   One more chance for Knight to make an ass of himself in public.
</P>
<P>
   That's real punishment, guys. Congratulations.
</P>
<P>
   But then, why should we have ever expected anything more. Until
somebody showed up with a ``smoking gun'' _ a few seconds of grainy
black and white videotape showing Knight choking player Neil Reed
during a 1997 practice _ the coach had done anything and everything
he wanted and gotten away with it.
</P>
<P>
   How many of us could scream obscenities at a senior office
secretary _ Knight called her a name we won't even begin to repeat
this close to Mother's Day _ and not be fired? How many of us could
physically threaten our boss and not be in the unemployment line an
hour later?
</P>
<P>
   How many could put a choke hold on an 18-year-old youth whose
parents we'd promised to protect like he was our own, and skate
away unscathed? How many times could we stand in front of our
company's logo and bully, intimidate, kick, throw chairs and act
like a total jerk?
</P>
<P>
   Knight did it, time and time again, while representing a major
university's athletic program. That doesn't even count tasteless
coaching tricks, like putting a tampon in a player's locker or
waving soiled toilet paper under his player's noses to show what he
thought of their play.
</P>
<P>
   And now that university has promised us that there will be yet
another victim.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the ethical approach is to give him one last chance,''
Indiana president Myles Brand, a close friend of Knight's, said at
yesterday's news conference. ``We have established tough, specific
guidelines to send a clear message that abusive and embarrassing
behavior will not be tolerated.''
</P>
<P>
   Gee, and it only took 29 years, too.
</P>
<P>
   Almost makes you forget that Knight's contract for years has
contained a clause that he can be dismissed if he ``has been guilty
of personal conduct which would be grounds for punitive discharge
of any employee of the university generally.''
</P>
<P>
   But let's not kid ourselves, as much as Brand might hope that we
would. Knight has never been held to the same standard as others at
Indiana or any other university. He has always gotten away with his
bullying, abusive behavior, even with his own son, and there's no
reason to believe he'll change now.
</P>
<P>
   Knight, who was calmly fishing in the Bahamas while the Indiana
board of trustees conducted an investigation into the latest
charges against him, didn't even take yesterday's event seriously
enough to show up for the news conference. Why? Because he was
doing something far more important: turkey hunting.
</P>
<P>
   And he's about to leave for a vacation in Scotland, which seems
appropriate since he walked away Scot free from this crisis. The
three-game suspension and $30,000 fine are meaningless. If Knight
is guilty _ and no one's ever bothered to deny that _ the only
appropriate response is termination. If he's not guilty, he
shouldn't have even been reprimanded.
</P>
<P>
   The saddest part of the whole tawdry Knight affair is the shadow
it casts on other coaches. Coaches, those I've had and those I've
known, have played a big role in my life and in the lives of others
I've known. They were the ones I looked to for discipline. Some
were tough but they were always fair.
</P>
<P>
   I've been grabbed by the shoulder pads, as many another junior
high and high school player has been, and shoved into the position
I was already supposed to have taken. But it was never purposely
abusive or bullying.
</P>
<P>
   The idea that you have to be like Knight to win games or have a
high graduation rate is ludicrous. He cannot hide behind the guise
of simply being a disciplinarian.
</P>
<P>
   That this was coming became obvious Saturday when Knight
released a conciliatory statement apologizing for his temper. This
was clearly orchestrated as a preliminary to the ``pardon,'' which
came yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   And who orchestrated this sickening charade? The see-no-evil
board of trustees? Brand, the gutless school president?
</P>
<P>
   None of us are naive enough to believe that.
</P>
<P>
   After all, they don't call Bobby Knight ``The Little General''
for nothing.
</P>
<P>
   He wants at least one more victim before he's through.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-00 2210EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
