<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6020 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBC-BAYLOR-SHOPPACH-T     05-15 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBC-BAYLOR-SHOPPACH-TEX </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ When he recruited catcher Kelly Shoppach out of
Brewer High School two years ago, Baylor coach Steve Smith
anticipated grand and instant developments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had visions of conferences on the mound between him and
\Rpitcher\S Jason Jennings where there would be so much talent
concentrated there that the field would slant,'' Smith recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings went on to win national player-of-the-year honors last
year, but Shoppach ran smack into the Freshman Cobwobblies, a
familiar malady for which there is apparently no cure _ except to
grow a year older.
</P>
<P>
   Mission accomplished. After last season Shoppach had a
heart-and-soul chat with Smith, then departed for the summer,
dropped 50 pounds, made a few mental adjustments and emerged as the
player he is today, helping lead Baylor to the Big 12 Conference
championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's as good a defensive catcher as I've ever been around,''
Smith said. ``He's the best in the Big 12 and one of the best in
the nation. He can play this game a long time just with those
skills, but there's no doubt he will also develop as a hitter. With
his strength, I'm not worried about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that he did poorly this season, hitting .309 with a
team-leading nine home runs. Now a grizzled sophomore, Shoppach
takes such praise in stride.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm shocked,'' he said of Smith's comments. ``Hearing that
really means a lot to me.''
</P>
<P>
   A two-time high school All-American catcher and two-time
1,000-yard rusher on the Brewer football team who was recruited in
both sports by Division I schools, Shoppach admits he has
encountered more than one shock in college.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big adjustment,'' he said. ``I'm afraid I didn't handle
it very well. I became confused about my role on the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith was also confused; he had figured the only thing Shoppach
had to worry about was kryptonite.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so impressed with him in high school,'' Smith said. ``He
hit .500, he hit home runs, he was the leading rusher, the leading
receiver, he kicked off, punted, returned punts... He was the
leader at everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time he graduated, he had almost become a legend. I
remember watching a game at a baseball camp at TCU that summer.
There were several other players sitting in the stands around me,
and I was listening to them. They were whispering to each other,
`Shoppach's here' ... and they were in awe. It was like they just
spotted Babe Ruth.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when he got here, he seemed to become pessimistic and
melancholy.''
</P>
<P>
   And so, Smith launched a drastic plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every year, I sit down with each player one-on-one at the end
of the season,'' he said. ``Usually, it's just a real cheery
have-a-good-summer type deal, but this was a little different.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not a dialogue, it was a 10-minute monologue. I told
him bluntly that I was disappointed and felt uncomfortable with the
situation. He was out of shape, gaining weight and seemed to have
no interest in much of anything. When he came in he was smiling;
when he left, he was ... stoic.''
</P>
<P>
   But in retrospect, Smith said, ``I can only hope that in the
future, my own kids respond as well as he has.''
</P>
<P>
   Shoppach agrees that those painful 10 minutes probably did
everyone a lot of good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it was what I needed,'' he said. ``I want to be a
leader on this team, and I think I can develop into one. It's hard
to do, though, when you're a freshman, and the realization can also
be a little hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's the natural thing, and as the catcher, you're in the
obvious position for it. ... So I played summer ball, dropped from
245 to 195, and came back with a better outlook. I'm back up to 215
now (at 5-foot-11), and that's about right.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, Shoppach has become adept at handling one of the top
pitching staffs in the nation, emerging victorious from spectacular
home-plate collisions, and playing the way Smith always figured he
would. Probably doesn't even miss football.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh yeah, I think about it,'' he said, grinning. ``Hey, I grew
up in Texas, didn't I?''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, given the present state of the Bears' football program,
Shoppach has considered becoming a two-sport athlete again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't rule out the possibility of my playing both at some
point, but right now I'm just concentrating on this game,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   So are Kenny and Gail Shoppach, his parents. In fact, his dad
recently stretched the concept of ``unwavering support'' to new
heights.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were driving down to College Station for the opener of
our series with Texas A&AMP;M, and my dad had a heart attack,''
Shoppach said. ``It was what they call a `minor' one _ just some
kind of blockage in the artery, I think, but they had to pull over
in Waco and take him to the hospital. But he recovered quickly, and
when we went to Ole Miss the next weekend, he was there.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, a lot of people are going out of their way to watch
Shoppach. After watching him chase down an errant pitch, wheel, and
throw a Texas runner out at third, Smith called it, ``Probably a
play nobody else could have made, and I thought it was the key play
of the series, because it took them out of a rally and allowed us
to win the deciding game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year is over. This year, he's been phenomenal.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
