<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-NCAA-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOST PEPPERDINE STILL IN SHOCK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The players discover at this time of season that this isn't a
leisurely day of hitting tennis balls around the court.
</P>
<P>
   This is the NCAAs. You win or you leave.
</P>
<P>
   The USC and UCLA women's teams could stand the pressure.
Pepperdine couldn't.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why when Stanford coach Frank Brennan called Pepperdine
officials to discuss logistics Monday, two days after the Waves
were upset by Louisiana State in the regionals, he heard voices
``in a state of shock and despair. It was like a death in the
family.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss was especially difficult to accept because Pepperdine
is hosting the last four rounds of the tournament, which begin
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like basketball, when if you've got a guy choking,
you can take him out,'' USC coach Richard Gallien said. ``We can't
do that.''
</P>
<P>
   The top six singles and top three doubles teams compete. There
are no substitutions.
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine coach Gualberto Escudero thought his team was playing
well. He felt even more confident after noticing LSU's lack of
depth.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, he was surprised.
</P>
<P>
   No.1 singles Ipek Senoglu hurt her back and pulled a stomach
muscle. As a result, she lost in a third-set tiebreaker to LSU's
top player and lost her doubles match because she had difficulty
moving quickly and had little energy.
</P>
<P>
   No.5 singles player Nadine Rastetter and the No.2 doubles team
of Maren Mueller and Dorothy Kurz unexpectedly lost.
</P>
<P>
   That's four losses right there. LSU won 5-4 _ only one of three
schools to defeat a host, joining Northwestern (over Tulsa) and
Tennessee (over William &AMP; Mary) in the finals.
</P>
<P>
   WHY PEPPERDINE? Because the NCAA wanted it.
</P>
<P>
   This is the second time the Malibu campus has hosted the tennis
championships. The tournament went so well in 1995 that NCAA
officials asked the school to make another bid.
</P>
<P>
   What made it so successful? The location _ Malibu is scenic _
and the number of courts on campus. The school also threw in a team
banquet and an indoor hospitality room with carpeted floors and
television.
</P>
<P>
   There will be no changes this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted something they wouldn't forget,'' assistant athletic
director and tournament director Roxanne Levenson said. ``I love
hosting stuff like that. People think I'm crazy for the work
involved. It's a challenge and a reward to watch it come together,
and the athletes appreciate it. That pleases me.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-00 2212EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
