u i BC-ISRAEL-SCENE-ART-NYT &LR;      05-15 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-SCENE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GAMES' TURN DEADLY AS CLASH QUICKLY SPIRALS OUT OF CONTROL
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ill.)   (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
 By WILLIAM A. ORME Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RAMALLAH, West Bank _ For nearly four hours, Palestinians were
riveted Monday by the spectacle of Israeli troops on Ramallah's
northern outskirts furiously trading automatic-weapon fire with
gunmen _ many of them members of uniformed Palestinian security
forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``Games,'' tersely commented a Palestinian officer in the red
beret and camouflage of the military intelligence services. ``Games
between them and us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli army said a detachment of the Palestinian military
police had initiated the exchange, firing live ammunition from a
hilltop at Israeli troops who had been battling stone-throwing
youths with rubber-coated metal bullets and tear gas.
</P>
<P>
   As the shooting increased, two Israeli Apache helicopters
suddenly swooped into view, detonating aerial flares in loud but
harmless bursts of smoke and light. Crowds of Palestinian
onlookers, mistaking the flares for bombs, scattered in fright.
</P>
<P>
   Then the gunfire abruptly stopped. The Palestinian snipers
decided that they would no longer shoot, knowing that the
helicopters could spot their positions, veterans of Ramallah street
battles patiently explained. The Israelis, too, held their fire.
</P>
<P>
   Sensing that the moment would last, Red Crescent ambulances that
had been trapped on side streets set off for the hospital, sirens
wailing. An independent Palestinian human rights group later said
that 375 people had been wounded _ at least nine seriously _ in
Monday's fighting in the West Bank and the Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
   In Ramallah alone, the scene of the fiercest clashes, 150 people
were wounded, the group said. The Israeli army unofficially
reported Monday night that it had killed four Palestinians in armed
exchanges Monday: two in Ramallah and two in Nablus.
</P>
<P>
   Several Palestinians said that the first live bullet had been
fired at Israelis by rooftop civilian snipers and that the
situation had spiraled out of control when Palestinian troops tried
to forcibly disperse Palestinian demonstrators while Israeli troops
fired rubber bullets at both.
</P>
<P>
   To Nader Nasser, 18, who moved here from Redland, Calif., in the
waning days of the Palestinian uprising known as the intifada eight
years ago, the scene was all too familiar.
</P>
<P>
   ``We shot first,'' he said proudly. ``The Israelis had been
using rubber bullets, but once the live bullets came, they said
that's enough.''
</P>
<P>
   But to his equally American neighborhood friend, Ashraf Shatat,
also 18, who moved here from Chicago a year and a half ago,
Monday's melee was all new, and disturbing. ``They want to frighten
people,'' he said, gazing up as an Israel chopper crossed low over
the empty Ramallah street. ``Well, it's working.''
</P>
<P>
   Israeli army officials said later that the purpose of the flares
had not been to control the crowd, but to deflect small
heat-seeking missiles _ an indication of the seriousness with which
they viewed the situation.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's violence began as a not uncommon collision between
Israeli troops and Palestinian protesters during an annual march to
lament Israeli independence and demonstrations demanding the
release of Palestinian prisoners. But the showdown evolved into a
diplomatic and political crisis between the Israeli government and
the Palestinian Authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Palestinian security people are supposed be our partners
now,'' grumbled one Israeli intelligence officer. ``Shooting at us
is not within the rules of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the fear and anger unleashed by Monday's clashes, an
undeniable air of excitement invigorated Ramallah. Hundreds of
Palestinians _ most of them young men _ crowded nearby streets for
a closer view of the gunfire, with the Israeli soldiers hunkered
down behind armored vans and inside a half-built hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Parked at a gas station not far off, Abdul Razul voiced warm
approval of the violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the response of the Palestinian people to 52 years of
occupation,'' said Razul, 65, gesturing with a satisfied sweep of
his arms toward the gunfire crackling in the background.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Palestinians are getting tired of peace talking,'' he
said. ``The Israelis aren't giving us anything. The Oslo accords
say that they should give us our prisoners, and the Israelis just
keep stalling.''
</P>
<P>
   One young Ramallah policeman, identified as Ahmed Abdel-Fattah,
was killed almost instantly by a burst of Israeli gunfire. At least
six other policemen were wounded _ one critically _ in the gunfire
with Israeli troops, who contend that they were returning fire from
the Palestinian police. Israeli Army officers said three of their
soldiers in Ramallah had been treated for gunshot wounds.
</P>
<P>
   During one furious exchange, Maher Abu Khater, a seasoned West
Bank reporter for The Los Angeles Times and the German news agency
DPA, was shot in the back by a distant Palestinian sniper. He was
being treated Monday night in Hadassah Hospital in Jerusalem and
was reported to be in stable condition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
