   (NYT13) ELLSWORTH, Maine -- May 15, 2000 --
SISTERS-INTERRUPTED-1-BOS --Jennifer King 16, with her mother, Debb
King. Jennifer, a former foster child, is the biological sister of
Julie Barnes, the 19-year-old homeless woman arrested after the
deadly fire in Worcester, Mass., in December: a terrible blaze in a
giant warehouse which left six firefighters dead and 17 children
orphaned. Though both girls are developmentally disabled, Jennifer
flourishes in a loving home, while Julie, who has been homeless, is
pregnant and in prison. (Tom Herde/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) AUSTIN, Texas -- May 15, 2000 -- FLATPANEL-SIDE-2-COX --
Zvi Yaniv calls it two-dimensional kinetic art: He programs a
series of digital images - either photos, other artists' work or
his own - onto a flat panel, liquid crystal display and inserts the
panel into a rectangular hole that he has cut in a painting or
lithograph, not his own. Yaniv's creation, ``Faces of the World,''
is on display at the IC2 Institute. (Peter Yang/The Austin-American
Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) AUSTIN, Texas -- May 15, 2000 -- FLATPANEL-SIDE-1-COX --
Zvi Yaniv calls it two-dimensional kinetic art: He programs a
series of digital images - either photos, other artists' work or
his own - onto a flat panel, liquid crystal display and inserts the
panel into a rectangular hole that he has cut in a painting or
lithograph, not his own. He is standing with two of his creations,
which are on display at the IC2 Institute. (Peter Yang/The
Austin-American Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) WASHINGTON -- May 15, 2000 -- CLINTON-POLICE --
President Clinton and Attorney General Janet Reno, left, during the
19th annual National Peace Officers Memorial Service on Capitol
Hill, Monday. Clinton also honored 139 police officers killed in
the line of duty last year and announced a new presidential award
for police valor. The ceremony took place one day after Sunday's
Million Mom March. (Stephen Crowley/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) El CEIBAL, Guatemala -- May 15, 2000 -- GUATEMALA-FIRES
-- Roan McNab, the Guatemala program director for the Wildlife
Conservation Society, stands in a section of the El Ceibal national
park which was damaged by fire. Though the park is home to Mayan
ruins, it is protected only on paper. The fires were set by
``invasores,'' or squatters, as they are known locally, more than
200 of whom have lived inside two settlements of thatched roof
shacks inside the park since 1998. (David Gonzalez/The New York
Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) UNDATED -- May 15, 2000 -- PROUST-BOOK-REVIEW -- Marcel
Proust, left, of the little madeleines and the long sentences and
the redeeming power of memory, is not the Marcel Proust of
``Proust's Way: A Field Guide to In Search of Lost Time,'' the
intellectually powerful, deeply considered evaluation by Roger
Shattuck, the highly esteemed scholar of French literary culture.
(W.W. Norton and Company/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- May 15, 2000 -- NY-OPERA-KELLOGG -- When Paul
Kellogg became the artistic and general director of the New York
City Opera in 1996, the company was carrying a $5 million debt, had
lost its sense of artistic direction and was coping emotionally
with the death at 48 from AIDS of its previous director, the
conductor Christopher Keene. Revitalizing the City Opera has been a
formidable challenge. Kellogg outside the New York State Theater
last week. (Sara Krulwich/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) BETHLEHEM, West Bank -- May 15, 2000 --
ISRAEL-PALESTINIANS -- In some of the worst violence in years,
Israeli troops and Palestinians clashed in the West Bank and Gaza
Strip Monday in confrontations that have left at least three
Palestinians killed and more than 320 injured. An Israeli soldier
watched as a Palestinian police officer intervened as protesters
hurled rocks at Israeli forces in Bethlehem, Monday. (Rina
Castelnuovo/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) MOUNT ST. HELENS, Wash. -- May 15, 2000 --
SCI-VOLCANO-RECOVER-2 -- The eruption 20 years ago of Mount St.
Helens has radically changed the way that biologists look at the
creation and recovery of natural landscapes. Fireweed started to
grow on the ridges near Mount St. Helens in 1985. (Lyn Topinka/The
U.S. Geological Survey/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) JOHNSTON'S RIDGE, Wash. -- May 15, 2000 --
SCI-VOLCANO-RECOVER-1 -- The eruption 20 years ago of Mount St.
Helens has radically changed the way that biologists look at the
creation and recovery of natural landscapes. Mount St. Helens, top,
on May 17, 1980, one day before the devastating eruption, from
Johnston's Ridge, six miles northwest of the volcano. At bottom,
the day after. (Harry Glicken/The U.S. Geological Survey/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- May 15, 2000 -- SCI-VITAL-SIGNS -- Runners
who get dehydrated face obvious dangers, but drinking too much
water during a race can also be deadly, according to a study in
this month's issue of the Annals of Internal Medicine. Runners
during a Central Park marathon in 1996 head towards table with
refreshments. (Steve Berman/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) FREDERICK, Md. -- May 15, 2000 --SCI-HANDEDNESS-GENE --
The latest word on what makes people left- or right-handed comes
from Dr. Amar J.S. Klar, a geneticist at the National Cancer
Institute laboratory, who has been working for years with yeast and
mutant mice. Klar has developed a theory that he believes explains
why 9 of 10 people in all cultures are right-handed, why
left-handed parents are more likely to have left-handed children
and why identical twins often have different handedness. (Marty
Katz/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) UNDATED -- May 15, 2000 -- SCI-SPACE-STATION -- During an
11-day mission, which is to begin Thursday morning, the space
shuttle Atlantis is to nudge the International Space Station upward
by 20 to 25 miles, a temporary solution of its decaying orbit,
until a Russia craft helps keep it in place. A computer drawing
shows a space shuttle docked at the space station as it may look in
2002 and beyond. (NASA/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
