<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Monday, 05/15/00. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) NEW YORK -- May 15, 2000 -- SUB-HAMMERSTEIN-BALLROOM-B&AMP;W
-- In the 1930s, the Hammerstein Ballroom in Manhattan was more
sedate than it often is these days. The ballroom - which juggles
boxing, concerts, and Fortune 500 board members - is also a
reincarnation of its former self: a turn-of-the-century opera house
that once rivaled the Metropolitan Opera. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) UNDATED -- May 15, 2000 -- KINGMAN-OBIT-B&AMP;W -- Dong
Kingman, an American-born watercolorist known for humorously
illustrational cityscapes, magazine covers and contributions to
Hollywood films, died Friday at his home in Manhattan. He was 89.
Kingman's cheerful urban scenes included ``Big Ben, London.''
(Midtown Galleries/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) NEW YORK -- May 15, 2000 -- ACCESSORIES-FASHION-2 -- The
American fashion industry has been indebted to Miuccia Prada for
several seasons, and it looks as if she is still the boss designer.
At the Accessory Circuit, a trade show, a necklace with multiple
chains dangling with paillettes by Stephanie Layne and Jill Roeb,
owners of Haute Stuff, left; Zerafa's group of two-tone bags that
in their colors and shapes seemed influenced by Prada. (Marilynn K.
Yee/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) NEW YORK -- May 15, 2000 -- ACCESSORIES-FASHION-1 -- The
American fashion industry has been indebted to Miuccia Prada for
several seasons, and it looks as if she is still the boss designer.
At the Accessory Circuit, a trade show, a fur tippet by Elizabeth
Gillett and inspired by Prada, left (Marilynn K. Yee/The New York
Times); one of many loosely tied fur collars at Prada's fall show
in February (Dan Lecca/The New York Times); animal prints on
display at Eric Javits' hat booth at the Accessory Circuit, right.
(Marilynn K. Yee/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) NEW YORK -- May 15, 2000 -- PARKINSON-FASHION -- Gregory
Parkinson designs small collections of fanciful clothes in New
York. Susan Stone, the owner of Savannah, the stylish Santa Monica
shop where Parkinson has developed a following, attributed his
growing success to the fact that his clothes are, ``if not one of a
kind, then close to it.'' (Carol Halebian/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) WASHINGTON -- May 15, 2000 -- SCOTUS-WOMEN -- The
Supreme Court on Monday threw out the part of a 1994 federal law
that allowed female rape victims to sue their attackers in federal
court, ruling 5-4 that Congress had exceeded its reach and ventured
into the domain of the states. Martha F. Davis, left, director of
the National Organization of Women's Legal Defense and Education
Fund, discussed the decision with Kathy Rodgers, president of NOW.
(Fred R. Conrad/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) MEXICO CITY -- May 15, 2000 -- MEXICO-POLITICS -- The
Institutional Revolutionary Party, which has elected every
president since 1929 and controlled a political system that
dominated Mexican life, is falling behind in the presidential race
and is suddenly on the defensive. Francisco Labastida Ochoa - the
party's candidate - and his wife, Maria Teresa Uriarte Castaneda,
mingled at a recent rally in Mexico City. (Gerardo Magallon/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) LAKE WORTH, Fla. -- May 15, 2000 -- MILLION-DOLLAR-KID
-- At Lake Worth High School, Matt Tanguay's good study habits got
him accepted at all five of the American military academies to
which he applied and earned him a total of $1 million in
scholarships. Despite the bonanza, Tanguay, 17, chose the U.S.
Coast Guard Academy, to which he will report on July 1, fulfilling
his desire to spend his life near the ocean. (Richard Graulich/Cox
News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- May 15, 2000 -- CAMPAIGN-POLL -- While many
Americans find Vice President Al Gore's issue positions more
appealing, he is not as well liked personally or viewed as
commanding a leader as Gov. George W. Bush, the latest New York
Times/CBS News Poll shows. Gore, foreground, and Bush during last
week's funeral Mass for Cardinal John O'Connor. (Ozier Muhammad/The
New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) WASHINGTON -- May 15, 2000 -- CLINTON-POLICE-2 --
President Clinton speaks as polic officer J.W. Harmon guards the
podium during the 19th annual National Peace Officers Memorial
Service on Capitol Hill, Monday. Clinton. honored 139 police
officers killed in the line of duty last year and announced a new
presidential award for police valor. The ceremony took place one
day after Sunday's Million Mom March. (Rick McKay/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) SYRACUSE, N.Y. -- May 15, 2000 -- NY-INDIAN-LANDCLAIMS
-- The six Iroquois nations of New York State are at the epicenter
of one of the biggest, most volatile issues now in upstate New
York: Indian claims to land that were illegally seized from them
200 years ago, totaling a checkerboard of 650 square miles, or more
than double the size of New York City. The three Chiefs of the
Onongada Indains outside their long house in April holding wampum
belts they claim represent pending land claims. Chiefs from left,
Irving Powless Jr., Sid Hill and Oren Lyons. (Keith Meyers/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) ESPANOLA, N.M. -- May 15, 2000 -- LOS-ALAMOS-FIRE-2 --
Julian Yazzie, center, and other members of the Ramah Navajo Type 2
Firefighting Crew, head for breakfast at their base camp in
Espanola, Monday. The fire that burned down 260 homes in Los Alamos
destroyed historic Indian ruins over the weekend and threatened to
turn back toward town with an increase in the winds Tuesday. (Jack
Kurtz/The Arizona Republic)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) SANTA CLARA CANYON, N.M. -- May 15, 2000 --
LOS-ALAMOS-FIRE -- Firefighter Barry Kennedy at work near the town
of Espanola, N.M., Monday. The fire that burned down 260 homes in
Los Alamos destroyed historic Indian ruins over the weekend and
threatened to turn back toward town with an increase in the winds
Tuesday. (Jack Kurtz/The Arizona Republic) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) WORCESTER, Mass. -- May 15, 2000 --
SISTERS-INTERRUPTED-2-BOS --Julie Barnes confers with one of her
lawyers, Louis R. Aloise, during her arraignment in Worcester
Superior Court in February in connection with a deadly fire in a
giant warehouse in Worcester in December. Barnes pleaded innocent
to six counts of manslaughter for starting the terrible blaze,
which left six firefighters dead and 17 children orphaned. (Betty
Jenewin/The Worcester Telegram &AMP; Gazette)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) ELLSWORTH, Maine -- May 15, 2000 --
