<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 22:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6030 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-TRIBUNAL-SERB-MINISTE     05-15 0320
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRIBUNAL-SERB-MINISTER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA FAILS TO ARREST SERBIAN MINISTER IN MOSCOW  

</HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN ERLANGER c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WARSAW _ The Yugoslav defense minister, Gen. Dragoljub Ojdanic,
who was indicted for war crimes over Kosovo, spent five days on an
official visit to Moscow last week without being arrested by
Russia, a permanent member of the U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   Ojdanic, who was the Yugoslav army chief of staff in the Kosovo
conflict last year, is generally believed to be the first publicly
indicted Yugoslav official to travel outside Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Along with President Slobodan Milosevic and three other
officials, Ojdanic was indicted a year ago, on May 26, by the
International Criminal Tribunal for the former Yugoslavia on
charges of crimes against humanity and violation of the laws and
customs of war in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The Security Council established the tribunal. All member states
of the United Nations are supposed to arrest indicted war criminals
if possible.
</P>
<P>
   Russian press reports printed the day after he left said Ojdanic
arrived on May 7 in Moscow, coinciding with President Vladimir
Putin's inauguration.
</P>
<P>
   Ojdanic reportedly met Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev and
attended the military parade on May 9 commemorating the end of
World War II.
</P>
<P>
   He left Moscow on May 12, after apparently helping prepare for
the visit of Foreign Minister Zivadin Jovanovic of Yugoslavia, who
arrived in Moscow Monday.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the tribunal, Paul Risley, said the chief
prosecutor, Carla del Ponte, was ``alarmed by these reports.'' In a
telephone interview, Risley said del Ponte would ask Moscow about
the reports ``and why a person indicted before the tribunal was not
arrested.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia has been a traditional ally of Yugoslavia and the Serbs
but helped the West negotiate an end to the Kosovo bombing. Russian
troops also serve with U.N. troops in Kosovo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-00 2220EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000515.0395 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 22:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6031 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT-VIRUS-NYT     05-15 0452
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-VIRUS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT REVISES PROGRAM TO PROTECT E-MAIL USERS  
 BY LAWRENCE M. FISHER  
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Microsoft Corp. said Wednesday that it had developed a
software update for its Outlook e-mail program that would reduce
the vulnerability to rogue computer programs like ``I Love You''
and ``Melissa.''
</P>
<P>
   The update will be available free next week from Microsoft's
Office Update Web site (http://officeupdate.microsoft.com).
</P>
<P>
   Taking advantage of security holes in Outlook, a rogue software
program, borne by an e-mail message proclaiming ``I Love You,''
propelled itself around the world earlier this month, jamming and
crashing e-mail systems and destroying data on millions of
computers.
</P>
<P>
   Known as a worm, the program was traced to a computer student in
the Philippines. The program was activated when a user clicked on
an e-mail attachment and could then be propagated automatically to
e-mail addresses found on the user's computer. Written in
Microsoft's Visual Basic scripting language, the program preyed
particularly on users of the Microsoft Outlook e-mail program.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft said the update would modify Outlook to prevent users
from getting access to several file types that are sent as e-mail
attachments. Those include executables, batch and other files that
contain code often used by hackers to spread viruses. An additional
feature prompts users with a dialog box when an external program
tries to get access to their Outlook address book or send e-mail
messages on their behalf, which is how rogue programs like ``I Love
You'' spread.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Sinofsky, senior vice president for Microsoft Office at
Microsoft, said: ``Given the global impact of the `I Love You'
virus and the growing threat of malicious hackers, we strongly
believe we must take the unprecedented step of limiting certain
popular functionality in Outlook to provide a significant,
additional security option for our customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``While this new security enhancement won't eliminate the threat
of viruses,'' Sinofsky added, ``we believe it can greatly help
eradicate the damaging class of viruses that have resulted in the
`I Love You' and `Melissa' viruses.''
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Russell, manager of information systems at Security Focus
Inc., said the changes to Outlook would slow, but not stop hackers.
``It certainly does not eliminate the problem, but it slows the
process down and gives people time to react,'' he said. ``That is a
significant win.''
</P>
<P>
   While the update removes two points of entry in Outlook, the
program remains vulnerable, he said. ``I think this will force the
worm writers to go a different route. It will create a little more
of an arms race.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
