<HEADLINE>
FRIENDS CONCERNED ABOUT TURNER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VINCENT BONSIGNORE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VENTURA, Calif. _ Friends of Oakland Raiders safety Eric Turner,
whom sources have confirmed is suffering from intestinal cancer,
are rallying in support of the former UCLA and Ventura High star.
</P>
<P>
   The Daily News reported Thursday that Turner, 31, was battling a
stomach disorder that one high-ranking Raiders official described
as ``a terrible, terrible situation.'' Sources later confirmed
Turner had cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Turner issued a statement through his agent Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realize people are concerned but I have chosen to keep this
issue within my family,''... I am not gravely ill. My family and I
appreciate the thoughts and prayers of my friends and fans. I will
make another statement when my family and I deem it appropriate. We
ask all those involved to please respect the privacy of my family
during this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner's friends in his hometown of Ventura are expressing
concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't about Eric Turner the Oakland Raiders football
player, it's about Eric Turner the kid we've known since he was a
kid, and someone I've known since he was in middle school,'' said
Chris Taylor, a Ventura High counselor. ``Everyone here is very
concerned about him and we want to let him know we are here to help
him any way we can.''
</P>
<P>
   Word of Turner's trouble began spreading after he stopped
showing up at the Ventura County Athletic Club, where he works out
in the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came by right after the (NFL) season ended and I thought he
looked a little trim,'' said Shaun Lynch, who plays basketball with
Turner at the gym. ``But that was the last we saw of him, which was
conspicuous because the guy always works out. That was the first
indication that something was wrong. Ever since then it's been one
rumor after another. All I can say is that it's a real drag. We'd
like to help if we can, or at least let him know we are there for
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner is believed to be at home resting in Westlake Village,
although sources have confirmed he has been in and out of a Ventura
County hospital for treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Lynch said Turner has remained a friend over the years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like, one day he'll be telling us stories about going to
a Lakers game and talking to Charles Barkley or hanging out with
some of his famous friends, then the next day he's gone for the NFL
season,'' Lynch said. ``But as soon as he gets back and he sees us
he remembers all our names and asks us how things are going and
what's been going on. The fact that he remembers us, just some
regular guys at the gym, tells you a lot about him. He's just a
great guy. I wish him the best.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner returns home to Ventura every offseason, spending time
with his family and son, Eric Jr. He's also been known to show up
unexpectedly to youth sporting events to show his support.
</P>
<P>
   It never takes long for the kids to notice the 6-foot-3 Turner.
Such was the case last year whn he was home during a Raiders bye
week and stopped to watch a Pop Warner football game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was out there by himself sitting on the grass just watching
the game, but after a few minutes the kids saw him and before you
knew it there was a big circle of kids around him,'' said Christy
Patterson, whose son Tyler was playing in the game. ``I thought it
was so neat that he stayed there and talked to those kids and
signed autographs for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner, a nine-year pro who attended UCLA, was the second
overall pick in the 1991 NFL draft by the Cleveland Browns. He was
selected to the Pro Bowl in 1994 after tying for the NFL lead with
nine interceptions, including one he returned 93 yards for a
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Turner signed with the Raiders as a free agent before the 1997
season. He led the team in tackles his first year with 111, but was
limited to just six games in 1998 because of a foot injury and
missed the final six games of last season with a calf injury. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
