<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-RAPE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICES REJECT U.S. LAW ON RAPE VICTIMS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court on Monday struck down a U.S. law
that permitted rape and domestic-violence victims to sue their
attackers in federal court, saying that Congress exceeded its
constitutional authority.
</P>
<P>
   In their 5-4 ruling, the justices said Congress went too far in
trying to open the courthouse doors to victims by enacting the 1994
Violence Against Women Act. While Congress lacks the authority,
states can and do allow women to seek compensation in local courts
for their physical and emotional injuries and to punish their
attackers financially, the majority said.
</P>
<P>
   The court's decision was the latest in a string of 5-4 decisions
in which the justices ruled the Constitution prohibits Congress
from encroaching on the states' traditional oversight of criminal
matters, including lawsuits against alleged criminals.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, a Virginia woman sued two men under the 1994 law,
alleging that they held her down and raped her. The court, while
expressing sympathy for the woman's alleged ordeal, said state law,
not the federal statute, was her sole source for relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the allegations here are true, no civilized system of
justice could fail to provide her a remedy,'' Chief Justice William
H. Rehnquist wrote in the court's majority opinion. ``But under our
federal system that remedy must be provided by the Commonwealth of
Virginia and not by the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   The dissenting justices assailed the court's ruling, saying that
Congress can enable women to sue their attackers as part of a
national effort to curb the immense financial costs of violent
crime.
</P>
<P>
   The NOW Legal Defense and Education Fund, which brought the
woman's case to the justices, derided the court for rejecting
Congress' considered decision that victims of violence deserve
their day in federal court.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court really substituted its judgment for Congress',''
said Martha Davis, the fund's legal director. ``(It) acted like a
superlegislature to strike down this law.''
</P>
<P>
   But Houston criminal defense lawyer Kent Schaffer hailed the
ruling, saying the justices properly reined in a congressional
intent on trampling the states' historical authority to deal with
violent crime within their borders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under the federal government's theory, they can take any
criminal act and turn it into a federal offense,'' said Schaffer,
immediate past president of the Texas Criminal Defense Lawyers
Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pretty soon, you're going to be seeing people in federal
prison for driving while intoxicated,'' he added sardonically.
``Not everything should be criminalized to the nth degree.'' &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; With its decision, the high court threw out Christy Brzonkala's
lawsuit against then-Virginia Tech students Antonio Morrison and
James Crawford, whom she alleged raped her in September 1994.
Virginia never prosecuted Morrison and Crawford for the alleged
attack.
</P>
<P>
   The school concluded that Morrison had violated its
abusive-conduct policy and required him to attend a one-hour
session with an equal-opportunity compliance officer. Virginia Tech
found no evidence on which to punish Crawford. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; The court, in ruling the federal law invalid, said Congress
could point to no constitutional provision that gives federal
lawmakers the authority to permit women to sue their attackers.
</P>
<P>
   The justices likened the case to its 1995 decision striking down
the federal Gun-Free School Zones Act, which banned firearms around
schools. In both cases, the high court, by identical votes of 5-4,
said the national laws encroached on the authority of states to
punish local crimes.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration, as it had tried to do in the school
zones case, argued that the Violence Against Women Act is a valid
exercise of Congress' constitutional authority to regulate and
protect interstate commerce. By allowing women to sue their
attackers, Congress is trying to discourage these assaults and the
subsequent $3 billion to $5 billion drain on the U.S. economy, as
victims often miss work and refuse to leave their homes, the
administration argued.
</P>
<P>
   The court, however, said the fact that violence also imposes
economic harm does not enable Congress to trample on the states'
sole authority to decide when its residents can take legal action.
If Congress could make a federal case out of every event that
affects interstate commerce, divorces could be heard by a U.S.
judge because they influence the national economy, the justices
added.
</P>
<P>
   ``Simply because Congress may conclude that a particular
activity substantially affects interstate commerce does not
necessarily make it so,'' Rehnquist wrote. ``Rather, whether
particular operations affect interstate commerce sufficiently to
come under the constitutional power of Congress to regulate them is
ultimately a judicial rather than a legislative question and can be
settled finally only by this court.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Joseph Biden, D-Del. and chief sponsor of the
anti-violence law, said the court has gone too far in favoring
states' rights over congressional authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Supreme Court has become bolder and bolder in stripping
the federal government of the ability to make decisions on behalf
of the American people,'' Biden said. ``Congress, and not the
courts, should have the primary responsibility for striking the
right balance between state and federal power.''
</P>
<P>
   Biden said the law is needed to stem the national epidemic of
violence against women by enlisting U.S. prosecutors and courts in
helping to stop attackers.
</P>
<P>
   Besides permitting victims to sue, the statute contains criminal
provisions and sections calling for federal funding of
anti-violence programs. The criminal and funding parts of the law
were not at issue in the case, U.S. vs. Morrison.
</P>
<P>
   In its decision, the high court also rejected the
administration's argument that the Constitution's equal protection
clause gives Congress broad authority to allow women to sue their
attackers. The administration said state courts have historically
denied women equal protection by failing to treat female assault
victims as seriously as they treat men.
</P>
<P>
   But the court said the equal protection clause gives Congress
the authority to regulate states, not individuals. The
constitutional provision does not allow Congress to give private
citizens the right to sue other private citizens, as it did under
the Violence Against Women Act, Rehnquist wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Joining Rehnquist's opinion were Justices Sandra Day O'Connor,
Antonin Scalia, Anthony M. Kennedy and Clarence Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   In a vehement dissent, Justice David H. Souter predicted that
the court's narrow reading of Congress' authority will eventually
be overruled by future justices more attuned to the relationship
between violent crime and interstate commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``Violence against women may be found to affect interstate
commerce and affect it substantially,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Joining Souter's dissent were Justices John Paul Stevens, Ruth
Bader Ginsburg and Stephen G. Breyer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
