u i BC-CHINA-TRADE-NYT &LR;      05-15 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TRADE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS VOTE ON TRADE BILL NEARS, UNCOMMITTED FEEL PRESSURE  

</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., N.C., Mass., Maine, Mich., Neb.)   By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ An influential senior House Democrat from New York
signaled Monday that he is leaning in favor of a decisive China
trade bill, as the measure's supporters and opponents geared up for
a furious week of lobbying before next week's scheduled vote.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Charles B. Rangel, the ranking Democrat on the House Ways
and Means Committee, said in a telephone interview that he is still
officially undecided on a measure to grant China permanent normal
trading privileges.
</P>
<P>
   But then Rangel challenged several of the opponents' main
arguments. ``I don't understand why labor would make this their
litmus test on human rights or give a priority to human rights in
China when there are so many problems in the U.S.,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On the question of whether the World Trade Organization could
adequately police Chinese trade violations once Beijing joined the
international body, as is expected, Rangel said, ``If we have no
leverage in the WTO, what do we do?''
</P>
<P>
   Organized labor and the Clinton administration have heavily
courted Rangel, in part because they believe he may influence the
votes of at least two other members of the congressional Black
Caucus, Gregory W. Meeks of New York and Eva M. Clayton of North
Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Rangel said he still wanted to discuss the measure with fellow
Democrats on the Ways and Means Committee before the panel meets on
Wednesday to vote on the measure. Approval by the pro-trade
committee is considered all but certain.
</P>
<P>
   One factor Rangel said he is weighing is how the China vote will
affect labor's support for Democrats in the November elections. If
Democrats reclaim the House, Rangel would become the committee's
first black chairman. ``We need labor's enthusiastic support,''
Rangel said.
</P>
<P>
   And in a significant lift for the Clinton administration Monday,
the United States International Trade Commission voted to levy
punitive anti-dumping duties on apple juice concentrate imports
from China. The administration is trying to convince lawmakers that
it can regulate trade with China to make sure that American
producers are not swamped by Chinese imports produced at prices
deemed below cost.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-0 ruling by the trade commission imposes a 52 percent duty
on Chinese apple juice concentrate. It backs up a ruling by the
Commerce Department, which determined last month that China was
selling the juice concentrate in the American market for about half
of what it cost to produce.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House Monday, the spokesman Joe Lockhart said
President Clinton will hold individual meetings this week with many
of the undecided lawmakers _ about 25 to 30 in both the Democratic
and Republican camps _ and step up a campaign that has involved
Clinton, Vice President Gore and Cabinet members who are calling
wavering legislators.
</P>
<P>
   Meeks has already felt the brunt of the lobbying onslaught. The
freshman Democrat said he heard Clinton's most persuasive arguments
while he and a handful of other uncommitted lawmakers flew aboard
Air Force One last week after the funeral of Cardinal John
O'Connor. But labor leaders have also buttonholed Meeks, whose
district includes Kennedy International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been intense,'' Meeks told Reuters. ``Any number of labor
leaders have called and continue to call, even when I was at
Cardinal O'Connor's funeral. There were a few labors who came up to
me and said, `We need your vote. We want to talk to you some
more.'''
</P>
<P>
   Many state governors are also turning up the pressure, including
the Republican governor of Massachusetts, Paul Cellucci, who is
lobbying three undecided House Democrats from his state: Martin T.
Meehan, Richard E. Neal and Edward J. Markey.
</P>
<P>
   Ratcheting up pressure from business groups, the U.S. Chamber of
Commerce on Wednesday will launch a new radio campaign targeting
about 10 undecided and opposed lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents also planned a week of rallies and counter-advertising
campaigns. Rep. John Baldacci, D-Maine, said Monday he would vote
against the measure ``absent serious and substantive'' parallel
legislation that permits congressional oversight of China's
compliance with trade and other international agreements.
</P>
<P>
   House Republican leaders are to meet on Tuesday to weigh such a
bill sponsored by Reps. Sander M. Levin, D-Mich., and Doug
Bereuter, R-Neb. Their bill would create a commission to monitor
Chinese compliance and would have a provision to protect against a
surge of imports from China.
</P>
<P>
   But Republican leaders fear the measure may cost more votes on
the floor than it will gain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
