<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000515.0402 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 22:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6050 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-COLUMBINE-REPORT-2TAK     05-15 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLUMBINE-REPORT-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMBINE VICTIMS WERE KILLED MINUTES INTO SIEGE, REPORT REVEALS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A graphic is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ The 13 people who were killed by two students at
Columbine High School last year were shot within the first 16
minutes of the siege as the authorities were still assessing the
situation, according to a report issued Monday by the Jefferson
County Sheriff. But it was more than 40 minutes after the shooting
began that the police entered the building, and hours before some
victims were found or rescued.
</P>
<P>
   As the first detailed account of the shootings, the report
offers a timeline that purports to show exactly what happened at
the school on April 20, 1999, when two students carried out a
carefully planned mission in which they hoped to kill hundreds of
students and staff members with guns and homemade bombs. Most of
the bombs did not go off, but the two gunmen, Eric Harris and Dylan
Klebold, succeeded in shooting to death 12 students and a teacher
and wounding 23 other students before they turned their weapons on
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the size of the report _ a CD-ROM that includes text,
photographs, sound recordings and video from surveillance cameras _
the presentation leaves unanswered many fundamental questions about
what drove the two teen-agers to carry out one of the worst mass
shootings in America. Nor did it try to interpret motives from
videotapes the teen-agers made a month before the killings in which
they expressed universal hatreds and showed off their formidable
arsenal of weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, as Steve Davis, a spokesman for Sheriff John P. Stone,
said Monday, the purpose of the report was only to reconstruct the
movements of the killers, their victims and the authorities on the
scene. The report made no judgments about the authorities' actions,
which has become a major issue for many families of victims who
feel the authorities did not act fast enough to save lives.
</P>
<P>
   The report, which the authorities said was based on 4,500
interviews and more than 10,000 pieces of evidence, included no
major revelations. At the same time, however, it dispelled several
rumors, including the possibility of a third shooter or that anyone
at the school had been accidentally shot by the police.
</P>
<P>
   But the report also reveals how perplexed and uncertain the law
enforcement officers were in responding, especially in the early
minutes, when conflicting information relayed through a barrage of
911 calls left them unsure what they were encountering. For
example, early reports said a shooter was on the roof of the
school, which was not the case. The person on the roof was an air
conditioning repairman, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem, as the report reflected, was the number of
agencies responding _ city, county and state _ with little
coordination.
</P>
<P>
   ``They let the killers take over our school,'' said Judy Brown,
the mother of a Columbine student, expressing anger and frustration
over the police response. ``They stood outside. They let this
happen. They let it continue. They should've gone in.''
</P>
<P>
   The backbone of the report is the chronology, starting with the
times Harris and Klebold, wearing long black coats to conceal their
weapons, arrived at school and, at 11:17 a.m., planted two duffel
bags in the cafeteria, each containing ``enough explosive power to
kill the majority of students who soon would be arriving'' for
lunch. Afterward, they returned to their cars, which were also
rigged with bombs, to await the explosions.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities found that ``blending in with 400 other
backpacks and bags scattered throughout the cafeteria,'' made the
duffel bags virtually indistinguishable.
</P>
<P>
   Neither those bombs nor ones in the cars ever went off. But
another did, on a nearby field planned as a diversion, prompting
the first emergency call at 11:19.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Harris and Klebold, standing at the school's
west steps, made their move, the report said. One of them said,
``Go, go,'' and they pulled out shotguns and began shooting ,
killing Rachel Scott and injuring Richard Castaldo, who had been
sitting on the grass together. Within seconds, at least eight more
students were shot, including Daniel Rohrbough, who died. A witness
heard one of the gunmen shout, ``This is what we always wanted to
do. This is awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   It would still be four more minutes, at 11:23, before the first
law enforcement officer, Sheriff's Deputy Neil Gardner, arrived at
the school, where calm had turned to chaos inside with loud
explosions, smoke and students cowering in fear. Harris spotted the
deputy and the two exchanged fire before Harris retreated inside
the school.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next four minutes, the gunmen walked down hallways,
``firing weapons,'' the report said, adding ``both are laughing.''
Another student and a teacher, Dave Sanders, were shot in a
hallway.
</P>
<P>
   The gunmen continued shooting at random targets, the report
said, and tossing bombs as they walked toward the library, where
they shot and killed another 10 people.
</P>
<P>
   To this point, they had been inside the school only seven and a
half minutes, while, outside, officers were scrambling to assess
the situation. According to the chronology, even after Harris and
Klebold had killed all but themselves, the authorities were only
beginning to amass _ to nearly 1,000 by later in the day _ and none
had entered the school.
</P>
<P>
   The final moments of carnage were almost surreal, as the report
described them. By then, many students had escaped from the school.
The gunmen left the library, making their way toward the science
area, shooting aimlessly and tossing bombs, some exploding. The
report said, ``Their behavior now seems directionless.''
</P>
<P>
   They returned to the cafeteria, where some students were still
hiding. Harris shot several times into the duffel bag left earlier,
but the bomb did not detonate. Then, the report said, ``The
suspects both take a moment to drink from water bottles left by
students on the school lunch tables.'' A witness later told the
authorities that one of them said, ``Today, the world's going to
come to an end. Today's the day we die.'' It was 11:44.  &QL; 
(MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   Over the next 24 minutes, as the authorities were still
grappling with the magnitude of events and beginning to get medical
attention to those shot outside the school, the killers roamed
inside with no apparent purpose, finally returning to the library,
where Deputy Kevin Walker ``sees a muzzle flash'' from a window.
</P>
<P>
   That flash, the authorities determined, was the gunfire the
killers turned on themselves. By then, they had fired 188 shots.
</P>
<P>
   The officers fired 141 times mainly in exchanges before the
gunmen entered the school and as the boys leaned out windows of the
building and fired at officers.
</P>
<P>
   It was not until 12:06, several minutes after the suicides, that
the first officers, a SWAT team of five, entered the building. But
almost 25 minutes passed before a second team entered to assist
them.
</P>
<P>
   By then, medical authorities had begun to reach some of the
injured students, more people were evacuated and SWAT teams began a
methodical search of the school. The authorities were still being
warned of possible bombs in the school, but the building was
gradually secured even though some injured students, including Pat
Ireland, who climbed out of a second-floor window at 2:38, were not
rescued until several hours after the shooting stopped. Rescuers
did not reach Sanders, the teacher, until 2:42, when they found him
gravely wounded. But medical personnel could not reach him, and he
was pronounced dead more than two hours later.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the first SWAT team did not reach the library until
3:22. Besides the dead, officers found at least two other students
who were injured, as well as the teacher, Patti Nielson, who had
made the first 911 call. Nielson was found hiding in a small room
in the library.
</P>
<P>
   It will, no doubt, be left to the growing number of lawsuits to
sort out other details about the siege. So far, 15 families have
sued Jefferson County, alleging negligence by the sheriff's
department for not intervening faster. Also, Gov. Bill Owens of
Colorado has appointed a special commission to investigate the
incident, giving it a much wider mandate than Stone had for his
report, including why the killers' motives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably what we really want is not going to be in there,''
said Connie Michalik, whose son, Richard Castaldo, was injured by
gunfire. ``What we really wanted was why they didn't do more to
prevent it before it started.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Shoeles, whose son Isaiah was killed, has been highly
critical of the sheriff's department. He repeated his call for a
federal investigation and said Monday from his home in Houston:
``The truth is not in that report. Bring people in here who did not
botch the investigation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
