<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABS-SECURITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANEL FEARS SECURITY AT LABS HURTS FOREIGN HIRING 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAMES GLANZ  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A panel of scientists and engineers who advise the president and
Congress issued a statement Monday expressing concern that
heightened security measures at federal laboratories appear to be
damaging their ability to hire and retain foreign-born and minority
scientists.
</P>
<P>
   If the laboratories could not attract those scientists, who make
up a large portion of the technical talent in the United States, it
could threaten the labs' abilities to perform tasks as as diverse
as ensuring the safety of the nuclear stockpile and cleaning up
toxic wastes, said the panel, the National Science Board.
</P>
<P>
   Energy Secretary Bill Richardson immediately disputed the
board's contention that the security measures are behind the
laboratories' hiring difficulties, pointing instead to ``an
atmosphere of fear'' generated by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The Energy Department, which runs the labs, ``is doing its best
to strike the proper balance between protecting that which
legitimately requires protection while encouraging the openness
that science requires,'' Richardson said.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, a former nuclear scientist at Los Alamos National
Laboratory, was arrested and charged with mishandling nuclear
secrets more than a year ago. Rules involving close scrutiny of
scientists' contact with foreign nationals, polygraph tests and
limitations on scientific collaborations have been imposed.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the measures have been criticized as needlessly
intrusive and unfairly burdensome to Asian and Asian-American
scientists at the laboratories, allegedly creating a hostile and
discriminatory workplace.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is a serious one, since, for example, more than a
quarter of all doctorates in technical fields awarded in the United
States each year are given to Asians or Asian Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The statement from the National Science Board, which also
governs the National Science Foundation, said that the security
concerns at the labs have led to a ``growing difficulty'' in
attracting foreign-born and minority scientists ``because of
perceptions based on nationality, ethnicity, or other
characteristics.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Eamon Kelly, president emeritus of Tulane University and
chairman of the science board, said that ``there's an accumulation
of evidence that the current environment is becoming a detriment to
the hiring of foreign-born and minority American scientists. This
can have an impact on the integrity of the scientific process,
which would be detrimental both to our national security and our
economic growth.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that while the board was mindful of suspicion
surrounding Asian scientists at federal laboratories, its concerns
went further, covering all foreign-born scientists.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has also placed a moratorium on visits to the labs by
scientists from numerous countries, except when special waivers are
granted by Richardson. An Energy Department official said that the
routine paperwork generated by the security rules was ``overlaid
with this sense of suspicion'' only because of the intrusion of
needless restrictions imposed by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson said that the security requirements by themselves did
not discourage international collaborations or intimidate lab
scientists. Rather, he said, ``it is Congress, by creating an
atmosphere of fear, that has caused concerns among the foreign-born
scientists.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
