<HEADER>
A6062 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY-HNS &LR;      05-15 1322
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH, GORE OFFER DIFFERENT APPROACHES ON SOCIAL SECURITY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See optional trim) 
 
By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
and BENNETT ROTH 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush told California senior citizens that
Americans should be allowed to invest part of their Social Security
payroll tax in the stock market. Vice President Al Gore told
Pennsylvania college students that the government retirement plan
is a ``solemn compact'' that should not be risked on the vagaries
of the market.
</P>
<P>
   Neither candidate broke much new ground Monday, but their
speeches on opposite ends of the country underscored Social
Security's place as a central issue in the 2000 presidential
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the probable Republican presidential nominee, discussed
his vision for Social Security with a gathering of senior citizens
in Rancho Cucamonga, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Accusing his opponents of tactics that ``frighten the elderly
for political advantage,'' Bush promised a bipartisan redesign of
Social Security and Medicare if he is elected president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am here with a message for America and to put my opponent on
notice: The days of spreading fear and panic are over,'' Bush said
to an audience of of about 100 at the Rancho Cucamonga Senior
Center. ``When I am elected, this generation and this president
will save Social Security.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, the apparent Democratic nominee, cited a ``fundamental
difference'' between him and his GOP rival, accusing Bush of trying
to create a ``system of winners and losers'' with his proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at Beaver College in suburban Philadelphia, Gore
advocated shoring up the retirement system by plowing money into it
from the projected federal budget surplus and from the savings
generated by paying down the national debt.
</P>
<P>
   He said this infusion would keep the system solvent into the
middle of the century. The vice president has rejected a major
overhaul of Social Security. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; The Gore campaign clearly believes that voters will be wary of
the risks of investing their basic government retirement money in
the stock market. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Bush is trying to stake out a reform position on a pair of
issues _ Social Security and Medicare _ that Democrats have used in
recent years to drive a wedge between elderly voters and
Republicans. But he said his interest goes beyond politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Senior Americans are not one more interest group, as far as
I'm concerned, not one more voting bloc to be polled, pandered to,
or written off,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said that the only way to save Social Security and Medicare
for future generations is to put part of each of the government
programs into private hands.
</P>
<P>
   Gore countered that privatization would be too risky because it
would no longer guarantee younger people that when they retired
they would receive a set amount of money.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Apparently sympathetic to Gore's position was the message on a
banner towed behind an airplane circling the senior center where
Bush spoke: ``Don't Privities (sic) Social Security;
WWW.2030.org.''
</P>
<P>
   The group with that Internet address describes itself as a
``public policy organization for young adults'' with a mission to
``advocate for the economic interest of young workers.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bush said the Social Security system will go bankrupt by 2037 if
nothing is done to change it because more people will be collecting
benefits than are paying into it.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said Gore has a simplistic approach to the problem that
``will eventually require either a 25 percent increase in income
taxes _ the largest in our nation's history _ or a substantial
reduction in benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   While offering few specifics of his own plan, Bush promised that
no current retiree or anyone near retirement would have benefits
changed under any reform he would sign.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he wants to ``lock box'' the current Social Security
surplus to be used only within the Social Security system. He
promised that payroll taxes would not be increased. The program he
proposes, he said, would preserve disability and survivor
components of the current system.
</P>
<P>
   Bush proposed that a bipartisan commission design a plan to
allow individuals on a voluntary basis to invest a portion of their
Social Security payroll taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, the real return people get from what they put into
Social Security is a dismal two percent a year,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush economic adviser Larry Lindsey said an individual could
earn 4 percent just by investing in government bonds that are
adjusted for inflation, and he said long-term investing in the
stock market has had a return of 7.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president said Bush's plan was economically unsound
because of the transition cost necessary to continue paying seniors
current benefits as younger people diverted their payroll taxes
into the stock market. The vice president estimated that cost to be
as high as $1 trillion. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Lindsey said a portion of any increased earnings would be
returned to the system to keep it solvent. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; He acknowledged that an unspecified amount of money from the
federal government's general tax fund would be required to support
Social Security during a transition phase from the old program to
the new program.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said investing a portion of Social Security into stock
markets would be no more risky than the investment approach now
used by many business and teacher retirement plans, which invest in
diversified portfolios often including stocks. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Gore said that while there is nothing inherently wrong with
encouraging people to invest in the stock market, Social Security
was never intended to be a high-risk investment scheme. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``Social Security is a solemn compact between the generations.
It is a basic guarantee of retirement security based on a
guaranteed minimum benefit,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You shouldn't have to roll the dice with your basic Social
Security,'' he said, and added that Bush would ``turn the Social
Security system into a system of winners and losers. We will be
jeopardizing retirement security for too many Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore noted that Bush, in comments quoted Monday in the Dallas
Morning News, would not guarantee that future Social Security
beneficiaries would receive at least what they would have under the
current system. When asked about such guarantees the governor
replied ``maybe, maybe not.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Gov. Bush admits that his plan takes the security out of
Social Security,'' Gore said. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; But in expanding on Bush's proposal for a bipartisan effort to
redesign the system, Lindsey said that any of six different private
investing plans floated by various Democratic and Republican
lawmakers would keep the system solvent.
</P>
<P>
   Among the 15 Congress members who have endorsed those plans are
Sen. Phil Gramm and U.S. Rep. Bill Archer of Houston, both
Republicans, and Rep. Charles Stenholm of Stamford, a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also advocated a bipartisan approach to improving Medicare,
the federal health insurance program for senior citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Bush in the past has voiced support for a Medicare reform plan
outlined by a bipartisan commission last year.
</P>
<P>
   The plan would extend Medicare coverage through the Federal
Employees Health Insurance Program but also would open more private
markets for alternative health care coverage. Medicare would cover
the cost for low-income individuals, but upper-income individuals
who want improved coverage would have to pay additional premiums to
receive it.
</P>
<P>
   The plan died in Congress last year because of a lack of support
from President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1996 elections, Democrats ran television commercials
attacking Republicans over protecting Medicare. The GOP referred
the ads as ``Mediscare,'' designed to motivate elderly voters
through fear.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
