<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME THINGS BETTER LEFT UNSAID IN LAKERLAND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL SEGUNDO, Calif. _ Phil Jackson didn't want to say the wrong
thing Sunday, so he said nothing at all. Or, at least, very little.
To his team, and to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   A 117-98 loss to the Phoenix Suns had him steamed, so Jackson
kept his halftime and postgame speeches to a minimum. But he did
not avoid the locker room, as some reports indicated.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not much you can say in a situation like that,'' he
said. ``Every individual on our team had lapses. ... I mean, you
point one finger, you've got three coming-back-at-yourself type of
thing. So it's better off left unsaid sometimes, and then in a
cooler moment, when you've had a chance to analyze some things,
it's important to then reason with people. And I think that
reasoning takes better, there's more growth that happens from
that.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE CLARIFYING: Jackson said he meant no disrespect to the Suns
by calling two timeouts in the final 18.4 seconds of Sunday's loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought in a game which has been completely ruined for the
viewing audience, it's very important that I get a timeout, because
there's a commercial that I have that might get a chance to run at
that particular time,'' Jackson quipped.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, he disagreed with what he termed an
``inconsequential'' foul called on John Salley, and called the
timeout in protest _ ``just to prove a point.'' Suns coach Scott
Skiles called a retaliatory timeout, and Jackson called one more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phoenix, in their own mindset, thought I was insulting them,
which is totally different than what I intended to do,'' Jackson
said. ``But Skiles is hard-headed, so we came back with our own
plan (another timeout) to get that commercial in for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   UNCLARIFYING: Rick Fox left the Lakers' practice site without
speaking to reporters, so it's still a mystery why he intentionally
fouled Clifford Robinson twice late in the fourth quarter, drawing
two technical fouls and an ejection.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said referee Joey Crawford, who assessed the technicals,
``jumped the gun.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Joey said he didn't want anything to happen during the game
which would make a situation flare up,'' Jackson said, ``and so you
have to give him the judgment call. But then again it's Rick Fox,
it's not some hothead, (New York's Chris) Childs or somebody else
that's known for doing that kind of thing. ... I think the
frustration got to him, and there it went.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox's frustration might have stemmed from the fact he played
only two minutes in the second half, behind rookie Devean George.
Jackson figured the athletic George could slow up Shawn Marion and
gain some playoff experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rick may have registered it wrong,'' Jackson said, ``but he
didn't want to talk about it after the game, so I didn't belabor
the point.''
</P>
<P>
   Writing on his Web site, Fox was vague about his motives, but he
apologized to fans and said, ``I hope they don't charge me for some
of the stuff I broke in the locker room.''
</P>
<P>
   ONE MORE TIME: After the Lakers lost twice to Sacramento in the
first round, Ron Harper predicted, correctly, a victory in Game 5.
He was back at it Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to win tomorrow's game,'' he said. ``No doubt in
my mind. Ain't no guarantee, but we're going to win tomorrow
night's game. ... I will stick by my words.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
