<SLUG> BC-NETWORTH--COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALPERS REJECTS PROPOSAL FOR INVESTMENTS IN DEVELOPING NATIONS  &HT;     BY KATHLEEN PENDER
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
For more than a year, the California Public Employees Retirement
System has been trying to come up with a better way to decide which
developing countries are safe and potentially profitable enough to
invest in.
<P>
   The giant pension fund's investment staff finally came up with a
plan, based entirely on economic criteria, and was hoping the
CalPERS board would approve it at their meeting in Sacramento
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But the plan was shot down, mainly by State Treasurer Phil
Angelides and other board members appointed by Gov. Gray Davis who
want CalPERS to invest in countries that are socially and
politically correct as well as economically sound.
</P>
<P>
   The staff was essentially told to go back to the drawing board
(negotiating table is more like it) and come back in August with a
plan that includes some sort of social agenda.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome of this battle will affect every current and former
state worker who's counting on a pension from CalPERS, anyone who
cares about human rights abroad, and big state pension funds that
follow CalPERS' lead.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, it could affect U.S. companies in which CalPERS
invests. Angelides yesterday proposed requiring CalPERS' corporate
governance staff to ``monitor'' American companies ``and seek, as a
shareholder, to improve the corporate practices of the companies
doing business in the emerging markets in which it invests.''
</P>
<P>
   After State Controller and CalPERS board member Kathleen Connell
put up a big fuss about how that proposal would affect California
companies, Angelides agreed to put it on hold until CalPERS can
first figure out  &LR; where  &LR; it wants to invest.
</P>
<P>
   The staff's biggest blunder was basing its list of
``permissible'' countries in part on ratings developed by the
Heritage Foundation, a conservative think tank in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Heritage rates countries based on their ``economic freedom,''
which includes factors such as trade policy, government
intervention, property rights and wages.
</P>
<P>
   At least four labor unions representing state workers last week
shot off to Michael Flaherman, chairman of the CalPERS investment
committee, saying they were ``alarmed'' or ``appalled'' to discover
that the staff was taking its cues from Heritage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Heritage Foundation promotes a hard-right, anti-worker
agenda. Heritage opposes minimum wage increases and child labor
laws,'' wrote Robert Balgenorth, president of the State Building
and Construction Trades Council of California.
</P>
<P>
   The unions preferred a plan from Angelides, which would have
excluded countries that don't uphold democracy, worker rights and a
free press. The Angelides plan was based in part on country ratings
developed by the Freedom House, a liberal think tank.
</P>
<P>
   The Freedom House list would exclude six countries permissible
under the Heritage criteria: Brazil, Egypt, Indonesia, Malaysia,
Peru and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   Angelides believes that political and social freedom leads to
long-term economic growth. ``There is not a disassociation between
political stability and economic performance,'' he told me during a
break in the action yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   But the CalPERS staff cited several studies that show ``linkages
between political and electoral freedom and future growth are weak
or do not exist at all.''
</P>
<P>
   It noted, for example, that Heritage rates Singapore as one of
the most economically free nations, while Freedom rates it as only
``partly free.'' On the other hand, India is rated ``free'' by
Freedom House and ``mostly unfree'' by Heritage. Yet Singapore has
been far more economically successful than India.
</P>
<P>
   Both the staff and the Angelides proposals would consider
financial criteria such as market liquidity, market regulation,
market openness and transaction costs.
</P>
<P>
   The difference between the two sides really boils down to this:
How do you best promote human rights and economic growth _ from
within the country or from outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm opposed to child labor, slavery and violation of basic
human rights,'' said board member Charles Valdes. But the best way
to correct those injustices is ``through a policy of inclusion
rather than exclusion. The worst way ... is to pick up your marbles
and go home.''
</P>
<P>
   The unions felt otherwise. Human-rights violations in developing
nations ``are so abhorrent'' that state workers should not be
putting any money into them, said Dave Low, assistant director of
the California School Employees Association. ``Our exposure is not
so huge that we can't find alternative investments.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; REAL ESTATE.COM: The CalPERS board had a much easier time
dealing with two other proposals. With little discussion, it agreed
to explore investments in agricultural land, and commit $500
million to tech-oriented commercial real estate in cities such as
San Jose, Boston, Seattle and Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   CalPERS wants to own enough buildings so that it can give
fast-growing tech companies the ability to move from office to
office or to tear up leases. In addition to the usual rents,
CalPERS ``would expect warrants, options or stock'' in tenant
companies, said Mark Albertson, CalPERS portfolio manager.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
