<SLUG> BC-WILLIAMS-CEO-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
S.F.'S WILLIAMS-SONOMA TO NAME NEW LEADER  &HT;     BY CAROL EMERT
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
San Francisco's Williams-Sonoma Inc. has settled a long-standing
succession question by naming its head merchant, Gary Friedman,
president of the company.
<P>
   Friedman, 42, is now in line to assume the retailer's reins from
Chairman and Chief Executive Officer Howard Lester, 64. An
announcement is planned for Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Lester was treated for prostate cancer in 1997, although he is
now healthy, he said in a telephone interview Monday.
Williams-Sonoma has not had a companywide president since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Friedman, who had been chief merchandising officer and president
of the stores division, is credited with revitalizing both the
Williams-Sonoma kitchenwares business and its home-furnishings
chain, Pottery Barn, since the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   With its stable of strong brands sold via catalog, stores and
the Internet, Williams-Sonoma has become a powerhouse in the
home-goods sector. Sales have doubled since the mid-1990s, hitting
$1.4 billion in 1999. This year, the company forecasts revenues of
$1.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Wall Street sources cautioned that Friedman has little
background in back-end operations, a crucial aspect of retailing,
in which the company has experienced significant problems in the
past.
</P>
<P>
   In another management change to be announced today, Pat
Connolly, 53, was promoted to chief marketing officer from
executive vice president. Connolly and several other top managers
will now report to Friedman instead of Lester.
</P>
<P>
   The management changes are designed to help Williams-Sonoma
leverage its brands across all channels of distribution, Friedman
said in an interview yesterday. Previously, Friedman ran the
stores, while Connolly ran the direct-to-consumer division, which
includes catalogs, the Internet and book and magazine publishing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want more synergistic merchandising and brand messaging in
all the formats,'' Friedman said, adding that by expanding ways to
connect with its customers, the company ``will make our brands more
powerful, relevant, authoritative.''
</P>
<P>
   Lester said he is confident that Williams-Sonoma's operational
side can be handled by Chief Financial Officer John Tate and
supply-chain manager Duane Weeks, although the company may hire a
chief administrative officer as well.
</P>
<P>
   Tate and Weeks were hired to replace Dennis Chantland, a
respected operations whiz who left the company last summer, causing
the company's stock to tumble.
</P>
<P>
   No timetable has been set for Friedman to assume the CEO's post,
Lester said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the first time in Gary's career to have this broad of a
set of responsibilities, so it's important for him to do this for a
while'' and strengthen the fast-growing company's management team,
Lester said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting older,'' Lester said. ``I'm certainly hoping they
can get along without me sooner rather than later.''
</P>
<P>
   Friedman has worked for Williams-Sonoma for 11 years and
previously worked for Gap Inc. Connolly is a 20-year company
veteran. Lester has been chairman, chief executive and sometime
president of Williams-Sonoma since buying it from company founder
Charles Williams in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Williams-Sonoma and Pottery Barn, the company
operates the Hold Everything stores and catalog, as well as a
bedding catalog called Chambers. This fall, it will introduce a
food magazine called Williams-Sonoma Taste and, if that goes well,
launch a shelter magazine tied to the Pottery Barn concept,
Friedman said.
</P>
<P>
   The company is also planning a series of interior-design books
related to Pottery Barn, Friedman said.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Carol Emert at  &LR; cemert &LR; sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
