<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 23:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6181 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-MURRAY--BOFA-SFCHRON &LR;      05-15 1304
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURRAY--BOFA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOFA EXEC THRIVES DESPITE TAKEOVER TURMOIL   &HT;     BY SAM ZUCKERMAN
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
The takeover of Bank of America by NationsBank 18 months ago has
produced its share of surprises. Few seem more unlikely than the
success of Michael Murray.
<P>
   Just a year ago, BofA watchers predicted that Murray, president
of the combined bank's global, corporate and investment banking
operations, was a marked man.
</P>
<P>
   He was the only top-ranking executive left from San Francisco's
old BofA. All his former colleagues, including old BofA's Chief
Executive Officer David Coulter, had been forced out or jumped
ship. His operations suffered huge losses when Asian financial
markets crashed in 1998, and some observers pointed fingers at him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard people write him off,'' said Michael O'Neill, a
longtime friend and chief financial officer of the old BofA, who
quit the combined bank early in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional wisdom held that Murray would stick around only
long enough for NationsBank executives to get a handle on the
businesses he ran. His replacement had even been identified _ Ed
Brown, the NationsBank corporate banking chief, who was dispatched
to San Francisco as Murray's second in command.
</P>
<P>
   By about now, BofA watchers figured, Murray would be gone. Once
he was out of the way, the &UR;  &LR; headquarters of corporate and global
banking would jump from San Francisco to the bank's home office in
Charlotte, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Well, so much for conventional wisdom. Murray isn't only
surviving _ he's thriving. His businesses are earning big money,
he's developed a close working relationship with Brown and his
position seems solid.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a good rapport between him and other senior
managers,'' said J.P. Morgan Securities analyst Catherine Murray,
no relation to the BofA executive.
</P>
<P>
   Those who know Michael Murray say they are not surprised by his
survival. They say it reflects adaptability, top-notch management
skills and an unflappable, no-nonsense approach to the job. It
probably also helps that he runs a sprawling network of businesses
that NationsBank executives don't fully understand.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just a bulldog,'' said O'Neill. ``I've never seen him
lose a bureaucratic battle.``
</P>
<P>
   In a wide-ranging interview, Murray said the acrimony that
marked the early days of the BofA takeover haven't scarred his
relations with his NationsBank colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get along fine. We've all got a shared goal,'' said Murray,
55, a compact and hearty man with an oval face, eyeglasses and a
full head of salt-and-pepper hair.
</P>
<P>
   Murray's Global, Corporate and Investment Bank is one the
world's largest wholesale banking operations, producing about $8.9
billion in revenue last year. It does business in 38 countries,
vies with Chase Manhattan for the title of largest U.S. corporate
lender and owns the former Montgomery Securities, renamed Banc of
America Securities, a major investment bank.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge of running such a vast operation is what keeps
Murray on board, he said. ``Why would you get up from the table as
the game becomes more interesting?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the corporate bank will stay in San Francisco for the
foreseeable future. ``This is the headquarters,`` Murray said. ``We
will expand here.``
</P>
<P>
   The presence of BofA's corporate bank is a big deal locally.
Some 2,190 people work for it in &UR;  &LR; the Bay Area, about 175 fewer
than in late 1998. Add in support staff at the bank's Concord
computer center and the current figure rises to about 4,390
employees.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Some departments, such as syndicated lending, have closed
shop here. But such job losses have been partly offset by a hiring
binge at BofA Securities. ``We've put a lot of people into the
(Transamerica) Pyramid,'' the investment bank's headquarters,
Murray said.
</P>
<P>
   If Murray has kept an even keel over the past 18 months, it's
probably because he's sailed these seas before.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, the old BofA bought Chicago's Continental Bank, the
institution where Murray built his career. Murray said he expected
to be shown the door once BofA took command.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, when Coulter became CEO in 1996, he found the bank's
executive suites rife with bureaucratic infighting. So he tapped
two former Continental executives, O'Neill and Murray, as his top
deputies. O'Neill became chief financial officer, while Murray got
the corporate banking job Coulter himself previously held.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, as Coulter was finalizing what he hoped would be a
``merger of equals'' with NationsBank, Murray was one of many
advisers who warned that NationsBank CEO Hugh McColl would &UR;  &LR; eat
Coulter alive, according to people familiar with the situation.
Coulter paid no attention.
</P>
<P>
   NationsBank completed its purchase of BofA as markets in Asia
and other developing regions were crashing. The old BofA was losing
hundreds of millions of dollars trading securities in Asia, Russia
and elsewhere, operations Murray supervised.
</P>
<P>
   Murray got through that period by keeping his head down and
concentrating on the job at hand _ combining the corporate and
international operations of two of the nation's largest financial
institutions.
</P>
<P>
   He won the trust of the NationsBank brass by showing a pragmatic
willingness to accept the new order. But he was no sycophant. At a
meeting of top executives in Dallas shortly after the takeover,
Murray quietly told McColl he had been wrong to humiliate Coulter
and force him out, according to several people familiar with the
incident.
</P>
<P>
   Now, more than a year later, ``everybody has reached a modus
vivendi,'' said Lawrence Cohn, an analyst at the New Jersey
brokerage Ryan Beck. ``Mike is well trusted by NationsBank
management and he's learned to live with these guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray's standing stems from his ability to produce strong
profits even as he is overseeing a monumental merger.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Murray's Global, Corporate and Investment Bank earned
$2.6 billion of the bank's total $8.2 billion in profits. That
represented a solid 18 percent return on equity, or &UR;  &LR; 18 cents of
profit for every dollar of capital allocated to the business,
slightly better than the bank as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   Murray's division did even better in the first quarter of this
year, earning $960 million and posting a return on equity of 26
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Strong corporate banking profits largely reflect a booming U.S.
economy, recovery in Asia and a sharp rise in stock price, results
that will be hard to duplicate now that markets have turned more
treacherous. ``The market has frankly been rather kind to us,''
Murray said.
</P>
<P>
   Murray produced strong earnings even as he was completely
rebuilding the investment banking operations of Banc of America
Securities. Most of the unit's investment bankers quit after former
Montgomery chief Thomas Weisel left to form his own firm in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Under New York investment banking chief Carter McClelland, BofA
Securities is back in the business of selling merger advice and
managing stock offerings. But the unit remains in the industry's
second tier, far behind leaders such as Goldman Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in a bow to NationsBank's low tolerance for risk,
Murray has sharply cut back on speculative investments in
developing markets, such as Russia. While the bank remains
committed to the Asian, Latin American and European markets, the
bank sees its most attractive opportunities in expanding business
with traditional U.S. corporate clients.
</P>
<P>
   So, will Murray really stick around to see through the
combination of two big banks? ``You come here a year from now and
we'll have another conversation,'' he said, grinning mischievously.
The implication was obvious _ Mike Murray isn't going anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Sam Zuckerman at  &LR; szuckerman &LR; sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
