<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYBAG--COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAD ENDING FOR A STOCK MYSTERY 
 &HT;     BY ARTHUR LOUIS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; Q: &LR;  I have two old stock certificates, and am trying to &LR; 
 &LR; trace the companies. One is Great American Bank, the other is &LR; 
 &LR; NVF Corp. I would appreciate any information you can offer &LR;   &LR; about
these companies. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; a  &LR; A: I'm afraid I can offer you only bad news and worse news.
</P>
<P>
   Great American Bank, a savings and loan based in San Diego, was
seized by federal thrift regulators in 1991 after its finances were
ruined by unwise investments and alleged fraud.
</P>
<P>
   The shareholders didn't get anything at that time, but a year or
so later, many of them did recover a pittance _ about 25 cents per
share, after payment of legal fees _ in a class-action lawsuit
brought against the company.
</P>
<P>
   The class action was spearheaded by the law firm of Milberg
Weiss Bershad Hynes &AMP; Lerach, of San Diego. You might want to ask
them whether you are one of the shareholders eligible for
settlement money, and if so, how to get it. Their phone number is
(619) 231-1058, cq &LR; and their address is 600 W. Broadway, San Diego,
CA 92101.
</P>
<P>
   Take care not to spend all your settlement money on telephone
tolls and postage.
</P>
<P>
   As for NVF, a maker of fiber insulation, the company filed for
Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection in 1993. It was reorganized in
1996, and the creditors got 47 cents on the dollar, but the
shareholders got zip.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; Basis of Inherited Shares
</P>
<P>
   &LR; q  &LR; Q: A relative of mine passed away on January 29, and I
inherited some stock. I understand that I need to know the prices
of the stock on that date, because that becomes my cost basis in
calculating capital gains or losses whenever I sell any shares. How
do I find out the prices for that date?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; A: January 29 was a Saturday, so your stocks weren't traded
that day. That means you will want to determine the prices for the
surrounding trade dates: January 28, Friday, and January 31,
Monday. You then must apply an intricate formula prescribed by tax
law to determine your cost basis. (I'll give you the details
below.)
</P>
<P>
   If you have access to the Internet, you can get the prices of
your stocks for that date from the Yahoo Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Go to  &LR; www.yahoo.com &LR; . Click on the link for ``Stock Quotes.''
Enter the symbol for the stock in question and click ``Get
Quotes.'' Then click on the ``Chart'' link, and when the next page
comes up, click the link to the ``daily'' table. You then can enter
the date or dates of any prices you are looking up.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't have access to the Internet, then one simple
alternative is to go to the nearest public library branch and
examine The Chronicle, the Wall Street Journal or any other
newspaper that provides full, daily stock listings.
</P>
<P>
   In your case, you would look up the high and low prices for
January 28 and January 31. Add the high and low prices for each day
and divide by two. Now, take the result for January 31 and add it
to twice the result for January 28. Then divide that answer by
three.
</P>
<P>
   Voila! That is your cost basis.
</P>
<P>
   The main point of that absurdly complicated exercise is to give
greater weight to the trading session nearest the deceased's date
of death. The date one day away from the death gets twice the
weighting of the date two days away.
</P>
<P>
   When someone is considerate enough to die on a trading day, the
calculation becomes simpler. You would take the high and low prices
for that day, add them and divide by two.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; Companies, Credit Cards
</P>
<P>
   Q: I hold a corporate credit card, issued by American Express,
that I use for business travel. There is currently a past-due
amount and my company seems in no hurry to pay it. If my company
remains delinquent, will this reflect badly on my personal credit
rating?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: Mie-Yun Lee, editorial director of BuyerZone.com, says
that as a general rule, if a credit card is issued to you
indirectly, through your employer, your credit rating will not be
jeopardized if the employer neglects to pay the balance due. If the
card was issued directly to you, on the other hand, then your
credit could be imperiled.
</P>
<P>
   However, it's not quite that cut and dried in the case of
American Express.
</P>
<P>
   Company spokesman Don Monroe says the responsibility for
delinquent payments can vary from employer to employer. He suggests
that you discuss the matter with your employer's credit-card
program administrator. He says you also should call the toll-free
information number indicated on the back of the American Express
card.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
