<SLUG> BC-APPLE--DELAY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFT-DELAYED MAC OS IS DELAYED AGAIN 
 &HT;     BY HENRY NORR
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Apple's next-generation operating system, scheduled for ``next
year'' since the mid-1990s, has been delayed again, at least for
users waiting for a final, fully tested version.
<P>
   Five months ago, the company said the new software, known as Mac
OS X, would go on sale this summer. But Monday, Chief Executive
Officer Steve Jobs, in an uncharacteristically low-key presentation
opening Apple's annual developers' conference in San Jose, said Mac
OS X 1.0 won't be released until January 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Impatient Mac users, however, will still be able to get a taste
of the long-awaited upgrade soon: The revised timetable announced
yesterday adds plans to make a ``beta'' test version available to
the public this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Apple still intends to begin preinstalling Mac OS X on new Macs
early next year, just as previously planned, according to
spokeswoman Nathalie Welch.
</P>
<P>
   Mac OS X (pronounced OS 10) promises more stability and higher
performance than the current Mac OS 9, thanks especially to new
technical underpinnings borrowed from the Unix operating system. In
addition, Apple is adding powerful graphics capabilities, plus a
user interface it calls Aqua.
</P>
<P>
   The Aqua interface Apple unveiled last January won only mixed
reviews: Its elegant design, bright colors and slick animated
routines evoked oohs and aahs, but some users and developers
complained that it went too far in modifying the long-established
Mac look and feel.
</P>
<P>
   The new version Jobs showed yesterday appeared to be a response
to that feedback, preserving Aqua's appearance but giving users the
option of making it behave more like the current Mac desktop.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really shooting to give people a level of fit and finish
never seen before in a desktop OS,'' Jobs said.
</P>
<P>
   The new system will run on all Macs with at least 64 megabytes
of memory and a factory-installed PowerPC G3 or G4 processor,
according to Apple. Virtually all current Mac applications should
be compatible with it, although they'll have to be modified to take
advantage of the system's enhanced features.
</P>
<P>
   To help programmers with that task, Apple delivered a new
``Developer Preview'' version of Mac OS X _ the fourth so far _ to
the 3,579 attendees of this week's conference. Reflecting the
company's recent success, attendance is up sharply _ in 1998 only
1,801 developers showed up, and last year there were 2,563.
</P>
<P>
   More than 200 companies have already promised products that take
advantage of Mac OS X, according to Apple. One of the latest is
Alias-Wavefront, which yesterday announced plans to bring Maya, its
high-end 3-D modeling and animation package, to the Mac for the
first time.
</P>
<P>
   Jobs also showed a new version of QuickTime, Apple's multimedia
software for both Mac and Windows. Due this summer, the new version
will let users encode and play back video in the MPEG-1 and MPEG-2
formats, which offer  &LR; provide higher quality than formats in
general use for downloadable clips today.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Jobs said Apple has slashed the price for an
unlimited, one-server license to WebObjects, its tool kit for
creating Web-based applications, from $50,000 to $699. Users of the
program, which runs on several operating systems, include AT&AMP;T,
Disney, Mercedes and Sony.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Henry Norr at  &LR; hnorr &LR; sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
