<HEADER>
A6185 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-ANNUITY--FUNDS-SFCHRO     05-15 1860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANNUITY--FUNDS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   Variable Annuities Are Not for Everyone &HT;       By Arthur M. Louis
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR; More than 20 million people have assets totaling $1 trillion
tied up in variable annuities. New money has been flowing into
these hybrid investments _ life insurance crossed with mutual funds
_ at a rate of more than $140 billion per year.
<P>
   Judging from their extraordinary popularity, one might assume
that variable annuities must be a great choice for just about
everybody.
</P>
<P>
   But financial experts suggest that many people who buy variable
annuities would be better off investing in mutual funds alone.
</P>
<P>
   Variable annuities are considerably more pricey than straight
fund investments, the experts point out.
</P>
<P>
   The average annual fee paid by variable-annuity account holders
is about 2.13 percent, compared with about 1.48 percent for
straight mutual-fund investments. Variable-annuity buyers pay extra
for the product's insurance component, which may or may not prove
to be an actual benefit.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, investors in variable annuities can be hit with
punitive ``surrender fees'' if they close their accounts within
seven years after opening them. The fees range up to 7 percent of
the annuity assets.
</P>
<P>
   Another drawback is that variable annuities receive less
favorable tax treatment than mutual funds when you withdraw your
money or pass it along to your heirs.
</P>
<P>
   Variable annuities are so complicated _ and subject to so many
mind-numbing rules _ that many consumers can't properly appraise
them.
</P>
<P>
   Often consumers simply succumb to pressure from
insurance-company salespeople, who emphasize the more enticing
features while soft-pedaling the drawbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Variable annuities are popular with salespeople because they
generate large commissions. The commission on a variable-annuity
sale is generally equal to between 5 percent and 8 percent of the
assets the buyer invests.
</P>
<P>
   Lately there have been signs that the variable-annuity market is
becoming more friendly to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Intense competition has caused some insurers to reduce their
fees and even eliminate surrender fees. And some are offering
expanded product lines that transcend the old rules and allow
buyers more freedom to tailor an annuity to their specific needs.
</P>
<P>
   If you think a variable annuity might suit you, it pays to shop
around.
</P>
<P>
   Variable annuities are designed primarily as retirement
vehicles: Any benefits they offer go almost entirely to the annuity
holder. They are not a good choice if your principal concern is to
pass money to heirs.
</P>
<P>
   They are offered by most leading insurers, such as Prudential,
Travelers and Equitable, and by the insurance arms of mutual-fund
groups (such as Vanguard and Fidelity) and brokerage firms (among
them, Schwab and Waterhouse).
</P>
<P>
   They allow you to sock away unlimited amounts of money in a
tax-deferred account, with the money invested in your choice of
mutual funds offered by the insurer. When you are ready to retire,
you can withdraw money from the account, usually in a stream of
monthly payments.
</P>
<P>
   As with individual retirement accounts and 401(k) plans, your
investment gains accumulate untaxed as long as you leave your money
in the annuity.
</P>
<P>
   At retirement, you can choose one of three basic ways to
withdraw money from the annuity.
</P>
<P>
   _You can take it in a lump sum.
</P>
<P>
   _You can take it in periodic payments _ usually monthly _
continuing for a fixed, limited number of years, with the option
that unpaid installments will go to your heirs if you die during
the payout period.
</P>
<P>
   _You can elect fixed payments continuing to the end of your
life. Their size will depend on your life expectancy and how well
your annuity investments have performed.
</P>
<P>
   With most variable annuities, if you begin receiving lifetime
payments, the insurance company keeps any money remaining in your
account when you die. That could amount to a substantial sum if you
die early.
</P>
<P>
   It is a gamble much like straight life insurance, but in
reverse. With straight life insurance, the consumer makes out
better _ financially, that is _ by dying early rather than late.
</P>
<P>
   The strongest argument for variable annuities, experts agree, is
that they allow you to put aside an unlimited amount of money,
tax-deferred.
</P>
<P>
   With IRAs, you are restricted to legal maximum contributions
totaling $2,000 annually. With 401(k)s, the limit maximum  &LR; is 15
percent of your salary to a maximum of $10,500, whichever is
smaller. (The dollar limit is indexed to rise with inflation.)
</P>
<P>
   If, after maxing out your IRA or 401(k) in any given year, you
still have a chunk of cash that you won't need for a long time and
that you are willing to invest in the market, a variable annuity
may be a viable choice. Bear in mind, however, that your investment
gains in a variable annuity will be taxed at ordinary income rates
when you take your money out. You won't be entitled to the lower
tax rates that apply to long-term capital gains you earn from
direct investments in stocks or mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   The tax man also takes a big bite if you pass your annuity along
to your heirs. People who inherit annuities are required to pay
taxes _ again, at ordinary income rates _ on any investment gains.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, if someone inherits stock or mutual funds, the cost
basis is stepped up to the value of the stock on the day the owner
died. The heir doesn't have to pay tax on any gains that accrued
before the owner's death.
</P>
<P>
   The extra annual fee charged for variable annuities enables the
issuer to guarantee lifetime payments and to promise a rock-bottom
reimbursement to the account holder's heirs, notes Tom Conner, vice
president and general counsel of the National Association of
Variable Annuities.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, the heirs will receive no less than the amount that
the annuity buyer contributed to the account, even if the
investments have been eaten away by a bear market.
</P>
<P>
   However, financial experts say this rock-bottom guarantee seldom
is worth much from a practical standpoint.
</P>
<P>
   Because the stock market tends to move up over the long term,
chances are your annuity will be worth more than you invested by
the time you die.
</P>
<P>
   The rock-bottom feature could make a variable annuity an
attractive choice in the sad, special case where the buyer is
terminally ill, notes Tom Tracy, a financial planner with the
Kochis Fitz firm in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Tracy explains that variable annuities allow such a person to
take big gambles in the stock market with complete safety.
</P>
<P>
   The annuity holder can choose the riskiest mutual funds. If
their value shoots up, well and good: The heirs will reap the gains
when the annuity holder dies.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, if the investments collapse, the heirs are
entitled to the money-back guarantee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had an actual client situation like this,'' Tracy remarks.
</P>
<P>
   While the average 0.65 percent difference in annual fees between
variable annuities and straight mutual-fund investments may not
seem like much, it can amount to a lot over the course of decades.
</P>
<P>
   To take a simple example, suppose one investor puts $50,000 into
a mutual fund charging annual fees totaling 1.25 percent, while
another buys a variable annuity charging annual fees of 1.9
percent.
</P>
<P>
   If both investments grow at a steady 10 percent annually, the
annuity will be worth $30,000 less than the straight fund
investment after 20 years because of the higher fees.
</P>
<P>
   This comparison glosses over the fact that the gains in the
variable annuity will be tax-deferred for the 20 years, while an
un-deferred fund investment will be subject along the way to taxes
on dividends and capital-gains distributions.
</P>
<P>
   However, someone who invests directly in mutual funds can
minimize the tax impact by choosing index funds. Index funds _
consisting of stocks that emulate a particular stock-market index,
such as the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 _ are passively managed, and
capital-gains distributions are relatively rare.
</P>
<P>
   Index funds also tend to have exceptionally low management fees
_ usually less than 0.2 percent of assets annually.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco financial planner Norm Boone says that investors
who take the trouble to do the math _ admittedly, a difficult
proposition, because few people know for sure how long they will
live _ may find that a buy-and-hold, unsheltered investment in a
mutual fund will do better, bottom line, than a tax-deferred
annuity.
</P>
<P>
   Annuity investors also must take into account the &UR;  &LR; large
surrender fees.
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, if you don't stick with your annuity for more
than seven years _ if you need to close the account sooner to meet
unforeseen expenses, such as a medical emergency _ the insurer will
confiscate a substantial portion of your investment.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, you will lose 7 percent of your annuity assets if you
close your account during the first year; 6 percent during the
second year, and so on down the scale until the fee phases out
after seven years.
</P>
<P>
   Danville retirement planner Richard DelMonte points out that
most buyers of variable annuities also get locked in at the other
end of the line when they start receiving periodic payments.
</P>
<P>
   Under most annuity contracts, once the account holders begin to
get their payments, they cannot withdraw the rest of their money no
matter what. They must stick with the predetermined payment
schedule, whatever crises they face.
</P>
<P>
   However, this rule is beginning to bend, thanks to the pressure
of competition.
</P>
<P>
   Conner notes that some insurers have begun selling annuities
that allow account holders to withdraw all their funds even after
the periodic payments have begun.
</P>
<P>
   Other rules are bending as well: Some insurers now guarantee
that annuity payments will not fall below a certain minimum level
no matter how the investments perform.
</P>
<P>
   And some insurers are throwing in bonus features that might
appeal to prospective retirees, such as long-term care insurance.
</P>
<P>
   There also have been some significant price breakthroughs. By
and large, annual management fees have been coming down, and some
issuers are either reducing or eliminating surrender fees.
</P>
<P>
   TIAA-CREF, based in New York, now charges fees ranging from a
stunningly low 0.37 percent of assets per year to 0.59 percent,
depending on which mutual funds the account holder selects.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, it does not charge surrender fees.
</P>
<P>
   TIAA-CREF is a not-for-profit organization _ the world's largest
retirement system _ primarily serving educators. It can charge
bargain rates because it doesn't have a paid sales force, says
Dennis Foley, vice president for annuities and mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   At present, the TIAA-CREF annuities are not available to the
general public. But they soon will be, Foley notes.
</P>
<P>
   The organization is seeking approval for this change from all
the state insurance departments.
</P>
<P>
   Other issuers with particularly low variable-annuity fees
include the Vanguard and T. Rowe Price mutual-fund groups and the
Waterhouse brokerage firm.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Arthur M. Louis at  &LR; alouis &LR; sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
