<HEADER>
A6186 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-LYCOS-MERGER-SFCHRON &LR;      05-15 0495
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYCOS-MERGER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LYCOS, SPANISH TELECOM FIRM MAY MERGE  &HT;     BY VERNE KOPYTOFF
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Terra Networks, the Internet arm of Spanish telecommunications firm
Telefonica, is negotiating to buy Lycos, the giant Web portal, in a
deal that could be worth nearly $10 billion.
<P>
   If the merger is approved, the combined companies would create
an international Internet powerhouse that would rank among the top
five Web properties in terms of users.
</P>
<P>
   Pablo Fuentes, a spokesman for Terra Networks, would not talk
about the negotiations other than to say that they are in progress.
Lycos refused to comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lycos has seen America Online and Yahoo shoot right past
them,'' said Emily Meehan, an Internet analyst with the Yankee
Group, a technology research firm in Boston. ``Wall Street is
looking for Lycos to differentiate itself from its competitors.
This seems like a good fit.''
</P>
<P>
   By buying Lycos, based in Waltham, Mass., Terra Networks would
be able to expand beyond its roots in offering Internet access,
Meehan said. The company could immediately take advantage of Lycos'
strength in online retailing and advertising revenue, she said.
Last quarter, Lycos had revenue of $44.3 million from advertising
and $24.2 million from e-commerce licensing.
</P>
<P>
   Meehan added that the deal gives Terra Networks, which has 2
million mostly Spanish and Portuguese language-speaking
subscribers, greater reach into Latin America, Europe and the
English-speaking world. Lycos has a strong international presence
with, for example, a third-place ranking in Germany, according to
Media Metrix, an online ratings service.
</P>
<P>
   uncx In March, Lycos was the forth-most-visited U.S. Web site
behind America Online, Yahoo and Microsoft. However, Meehan said
Terra Networks should not expect Lycos to gain much ground in the
United States because the Internet portal field here is already too
crowded.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Quinn, an analyst with the Yankee Group, said the deal
also positions Terra Networks to offer Lycos as the Internet portal
on wireless telephones. That market, she said, is particularly
profitable and has a big potential for growth, especially in Latin
America.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiations between Terra Networks and Lycos follow a
series of big acquisitions in the Internet industry as companies
try to increase their reach and offerings. In January, America
Online announced its intention to buy Time Warner, the media giant,
while Disney bought Infoseek, an Internet portal, in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, USA Networks, the cable television company headed by
Barry Diller, considered acquiring Lycos. But Lycos shareholders
ultimately rejected the idea because they thought that the $22
billion offered was not enough.
</P>
<P>
   Lycos stock has surged by nearly a third over the past few days
in response to the possible merger. Monday, the stock increased
about 14 percent, from $54.13 to $61.56.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Verne Kopytoff at  &LR; verne &LR; sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
