<SLUG> BC-BOFA--SPEND-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOFA TOPS ITS STATE GOAL FOR COMMUNITY SPENDING 
 &HT;     BY SAM ZUCKERMAN
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Bank of America said Monday that its 1999 California community
development spending handily beat the target it set when the North
Carolina bank bought San Francisco's BofA and took its name 18
months ago.
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  The bank's $12.3 billion of community lending and investment
in the state last year far exceeded the $7 billion minimum bank
officials had promised to spend annually before the takeover. About
$6.6 billion was spent in Northern California.
</P>
<P>
   BofA's 1999 results in the state _ the first full year following
NationsBank's purchase of the old BofA _ represented about 31
percent of its nationwide total of $39.6 billion in community
development financing.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, bank officials said, community development spending in
the state rose between 10 and 15 percent last year compared with
1998. The bank is using 1999 as its benchmark year and said
premerger comparisons are not accurate.
</P>
<P>
   Loans for affordable housing represented about three-quarters of
the bank's community development spending in the state last year.
BofA's $9.1 billion in affordable housing credits in California
represented a 7.4 percent rise from 1998, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
   But small business loans dropped slightly in 1999 to $2.28
billion. Bank officials said they are taking steps to increase
small business lending.
</P>
<P>
   Activist groups said they were impressed overall. The disclosure
appeared to ease fears that the bank would shortchange communities
in a state across the continent from its headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   But representatives of two of the most influential community
coalitions, Greenlining Institute and California Reinvestment
Committee, said they were troubled by several apparent
shortcomings, such as a decline in small business credits and low
lending levels in some black and Latino neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too early in the process to congratulate them, but we're
not willing to criticize them,'' said Greenlining policy director
Robert Gnaizda.
</P>
<P>
   The bank did not publicly break out loans by race or ethnic
group. But activists who have met with bank officials said data on
the bank's loans to Latinos and blacks were disappointing. ``The
numbers were very low,'' said Greenlining member George Bivins, a
black businessman from Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Community groups say they also worry that BofA headquarters may
be imposing its community development priorities, making it tougher
to tailor programs just for California. ``They have to say,
`Mother, may I' now,'' said Gelly Borromeo, president of the
National Council of Asian-American Business Associations.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, BofA officials emphasized the sheer size of the
bank's investment in California low-income communities. ``We
honored our commitments at a faster clip than the market was
expecting,'' said Connie Beck, the bank's regional president for
Northern California.
</P>
<P>
   When NationsBank's purchase of BofA was pending in 1998, the
bank pledged $350 billion for low-income and minority communities
over 10 years, the largest such commitment ever made by a bank. No
amount was formally earmarked for California, but bank officials
said they considered the old BofA's 10-year $70 billion program a
minimum they hoped to beat.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Sam Zuckerman at  &LR; szuckerman &LR; sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
