<SLUG> BC-WIT--DEAL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WIT, E-TRADE TEAM UP IN E-OFFERING DEAL  &HT;     BY ARTHUR M. LOUIS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Wit Capital Group, one of the more prominent investment banks
specializing in online stock offerings, said Monday that it will
buy E-Offering, a smaller online investment bank founded by Menlo
Park's E-Trade Group, in a stock deal worth $370 million.
<P>
   As part of the deal, E-Trade _ the second-largest online broker
after Charles Schwab _ will acquire the accounts of Wit's 100,000
brokerage customers.
</P>
<P>
   Neither E-Offering nor the Wit brokerage operation have proved
particularly successful. The two firms figure that Wit's
investment-banking expertise will breathe life into E-Offering and
that E-Trade's brokerage expertise will optimize Wit's brokerage
base.
</P>
<P>
   Although neither Wit nor E-Trade would say so, observers suggest
that the transaction _ which the firms described as a ``strategic
alliance'' _ could lead &UR;  &LR; to an eventual merger between the two
companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say that there is a great likelihood they will
merge,'' said Scott Appleby, an analyst with Robertson Stephens in
San Francisco. ``It may take two years. They will have kind of a
courting period during which the synergies between the firms will
become evident.''
</P>
<P>
   Wit, based in New York, and E-Trade certainly will be on
exceptionally cozy terms after the deal closes, sometime during the
third quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
   The owners of E-Offering _ the largest being E-Trade, General
Atlantic Partners and Softbank _ will receive 32 million shares of
Wit stock, or roughly 25 percent of the total outstanding. In
addition, E-Trade will buy 2 million additional shares more &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Wit stock closed at $11.56 on Nasdaq Monday, up $1.31.
</P>
<P>
   Wit _ through its Wit SoundView subsidiary _ will become the
exclusive provider of initial public offerings, secondary offerings
and other investment banking products to E-Trade's 2.6 million
customers. E-Trade customers also will gain access to Wit's
proprietary research.
</P>
<P>
   Christos M. Cotsakos, chairman and chief executive of E-Trade,
will join Wit's board of directors, as will Bill Ford of General
Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this strategic alliance, we are creating an
Internet-driven category killer that offers investors an expanded
world of financial opportunities,'' Cotsakos said in a press
release.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald W. Readmond, co-chief executive of Wit SoundView,
predicted a big improvement in E-Offering's performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``E-Offering is where we were a year and a half ago,'' he said.
``We have the experience and know the positives and negatives. The
negatives are minimal, the positives are spectacular. This deal
gives us a West Coast presence, really good people and E-Trade's
technology perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Arthur M. Louis at  &LR; alouis &LR; sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
