<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 23:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6197 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-LOS-ALAMOS-FIRE-1STLD     05-15 1133
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOS-ALAMOS-FIRE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRE IS LARGELY CONTAINED IN LOS ALAMOS 
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds: Updates lede and 3rd graf with most evacuated residents
returning to homes earlier than expected.) 
(With LOS-ALAMOS-WARN) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT15 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JAMES STERNGOLD 
  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA CLARA PUEBLO, N.M. _ The battle to contain the wildfire
here has broken down into several diverging fronts, with modest
signs of hope in the city of Los Alamos, where most residents were
allowed to return Monday, but also growing anger over the threat to
ancient Indian dwellings and lands that tribal officials say had
initially not been well protected.
</P>
<P>
   A visit Monday to the Santa Clara canyon, at the northern
perimeter of the fire, brought encounters with swirls of thick
white smoke, brush fires just yards from the road, occasionally
exploding pine trees and nervous teams of firefighters known as
hotshots. Some of them conceded that they were able to do little
more than hope that blazes along the southern edge of the canyon
would not be blasted by the winds toward the invaluable
archaeological sites.
</P>
<P>
   In the town of Los Alamos, at the southern edge of the wildfire,
and at the nuclear weapons laboratory nearby, officials said the
fire was largely contained and that about two-thirds of the 11,000
evacuated residents were permitted to return Monday afternoon,
earlier than had been expected.
</P>
<P>
   But officials continue to take stock of the staggering losses,
which include 405 housing units and, at the lab site, five
dilapidated but historic structures where parts of the original
atomic bomb were assembled for the Manhattan Project during World
War II.
</P>
<P>
   Just one of the old wooden structures remained, the building
where the conventional explosives portion of the first bomb, known
as Trinity, was put together. The actual building where the Trinity
bomb was assembled, a simple wooden structure, was taken down years
ago, said Turnel Martinez, a lab spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Fire officials said in Los Alamos that while the fire had
consumed at least 44,323 acres the pace of desctruction had slowed.
More important, they said, the fire was 28 percent contained,
mostly along the southern and southeastern edges, near the town of
Los Alamos.
</P>
<P>
   A total of 1,268 firefighters are now battling the blaze in the
wooded areas, and 250 or so protecting homes and other structures
in populated areas, a level that Jim Paxon, the Forest Service
spokesman, said would likely be the peak.
</P>
<P>
   The fire was set 11 days ago by the National Park Service as a
prescribed burn in an effort to thin dense ponderosa pine forests,
before high winds helped create a blaze out of control.
</P>
<P>
   Although the news was generally good on the level of containment
in the south, winds are expected to pick up, and a cold front is
predicted for Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Many residents have continued fear possible leaks of radiation
from the grounds of the lab, either from structures that might have
been damaged by fire, or from old dump sites where, years ago, the
lab put low-level radioactive waste.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the lab said no buildings containing radioactive
materials had been damaged and that their sensors had detected no
radiation leaks. In addition, Gregg Dempsey, the director of a unit
at the Environmental Protection Agency that monitors radiation,
said the government had placed 20 more monitors around the Los
Alamos region.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this time, we're not seeing any cause for concern for
radiological release,'' said Jim Straka, a Department of Energy
official involved in the monitoring.
</P>
<P>
   But to the north, Indian officials expressed concern over what
they said was a slow initial response to the fire in their area,
and the heavy blow they could suffer if the fire jumped across the
Santa Clara canyon, on the pueblo, or reservation, northeast of Los
Alamos.
</P>
<P>
   The Santa Clara Pueblo covers almost 50,000 acres and has about
1,500 residents. It is also home to spectacular ancient dwellings
that are believed to have been built about 800 years ago into the
buff-hued sandstone of the Puye cliffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we lose that canyon and the creek, we lose quite a bit of
our resources,'' said Denny Gutierrez, the governor of the Santa
Clara Pueblo tribal authority.
</P>
<P>
   He said a major source of revenue for the tribe were the fees
for permits to hunt, fish and camp in the canyon and for visits to
the Puye cliffs. A big concern is that the fire could dump huge
amounts of ash into the Santa Clara creek, in the bottom of the
canyon, choking it off and making it unusable for irrigation or
recreation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Economically, that would probably devastate the pueblo,'' said
Gutierrez.
</P>
<P>
   He said firefighters were doing an excellent job, but that when
the fire first burst out of control, firefighters were slow in
responding to suggestions that they build fire lines to the north,
not just in the south near Los Alamos.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just sounded to us like this was not a priority,'' said
Charles Sisneros, a tribal council member. ``That's not the way we
see it. This is our home and we have an obligation to protect it.''
</P>
<P>
   Dale Baca, another member of the tribal council, stood in the
bottom of the canyon Monday watching the blaze send up huge plumes
of white smoke and brush fires burn to the road, and said he was
also angry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The indecision was the problem,'' he said. ``We asked them to
cut the fire lines on the Forest Service land and they just said
they hadn't gotten the permission.''
</P>
<P>
   Paxon of the forest service said the firefighters had done
everything they could. ``Our object is to minimize the impact on
the Santa Clara Pueblo,'' said Paxon. ``We do take their needs to
heart. We feel we have adequate resources there. We didn't delay.''
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters said the pueblo lands were now among the most
vulnerable, particularly if the wind does whip up as expected.
Jerry Soard, a member of a hotshot crew from Carson City, Nev.,
watched as the fire spread its dark fingers down the canyon and
tightened its grip over the heavily wooded Indian land. He
expressed some optimism because the fire was moving slowly and
burning highly combustible brush that could feed an even fiercer
fire if the winds picked up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's doing pretty much what we want it to do at this point,''
said Soard. ``This is beneficial. It's a real nice backing fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if this meant the fire might be brought under control
here, another hotshot team member, Chris White, laughed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Control? You can't say that,'' said White. ``Not with these
winds. The problem is that when they get into the canyon they get
so squirrelly. They blow every direction.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
