A6210 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     05-15 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS ARE GOOD, JUST NOT GREAT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL SEGUNDO, Calif. _ Before the NBA playoffs go any further, an
apology is in order.
</P>
<P>
   To: the Lakers. From: those of us with pens, notepads and the
habit of forgetting our job is to write the rough draft of history,
not to set it in book type and glue on the embossed leather cover.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers asked us not to do something, and we charged ahead
and did it anyway. We projected them into the company of the
greatest teams in basketball history.
</P>
<P>
   The early evidence was compelling if incomplete. The Lakers won
67 games in the regular season as Shaquille O'Neal turned into the
NBA's dominant player and Kobe Bryant into its most stylish.
</P>
<P>
   That was the cue to begin comparing them with earlier Lakers
champions, those led by Jerry West and Wilt Chamberlain, and by
Magic Johnson and Kareem Abdul-Jabbar.
</P>
<P>
   It was natural to wonder whether, with O'Neal 28 years old and
Bryant 21, coach Phil Jackson might have a dynasty on his hands to
rival his Chicago Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   But the Lakers said the speculation was premature, that it was
presumptuous to raise such expectations for a team that hadn't won
a single NBA championship. And it turns out they were right.
</P>
<P>
   This year's Lakers might win the title anyway. They should,
although it's less of a sure thing now that the Portland Trail
Blazers are sharper than they are.
</P>
<P>
   They've shown, though, they are not yet a great team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not as good as we think we are,'' guard Ron Harper said
Monday after the Lakers watched a tape of their embarrassing 117-98
loss to the Suns on Sunday in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   They're certainly not as good as the rest of us thought they
were.
</P>
<P>
   Being the 11th team in NBA history to win 65 or more games in a
season raised expectations to a level that might have been
unreasonable.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 10 other 65-plus winners, nine went on to win the
championship, including the 1972 and 1987 Lakers and the 1992, 1996
and 1997 Bulls. Most of them roared through the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Compare them to these Lakers:
</P>
<P>
   __ Of the five champions in the group that played since the NBA
instituted a best-of-five-game first round in 1984, none lost even
a single game in that opening round. These Lakers were pushed to a
do-or-die fifth game by the Sacramento Kings.
</P>
<P>
   __ Of the nine champions in the group, only three suffered more
than three losses in the playoffs. Abdul-Jabbar's and Oscar
Robertson's Milwaukee Bucks went 12-2 in 1971, and Julius Erving's
and Moses Malone's Philadelphia 76ers went 12-1 in 1983. These
Lakers already have three losses, and the playoffs aren't half
over.
</P>
<P>
   __ Of the nine champions, only two suffered more than two losses
by double-digit margins in the playoffs. The 1971 Bucks and the
1986 Boston Celtics went 11-1 in double-digit games, the 1987
Lakers 10-1, the 1967 Sixers 8-0. These Lakers have already been
beaten by 13 (to Sacramento) and 19 (to Phoenix).
</P>
<P>
   __ Of the nine champions, none failed more than twice to win
potential series-ending games, the ones in which their opponents
could be eliminated. The 1972 Lakers were the most coolly
efficient, going 3-0 in elimination games. These Lakers are 1-3 in
elimination games, letting Sacramento off the hook twice and
letting Phoenix wriggle free Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Harper attributed this to the lack of the ``mean streak''
displayed by his and Jackson's Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   But it's more than that. The shortcomings Jackson effectively
worked around in the regular season are being exposed in the
playoffs _ the lack of a backup center, the need for a
championship-caliber power forward (A.C. Green has 1 point and 4
rebounds the past two games), a notable shortage of fast-break
speed, and a slowness to adjust that seems to frustrate the coach.
</P>
<P>
   When Glen Rice's shot is off, the Lakers are down to two
scorers. When Bryant is a diminished factor, as he was after
committing three early fouls in a Game 2 victory over Phoenix, the
Lakers are a one-man team.
</P>
<P>
   If they finish off Phoenix tonight at the Staples Center,
they'll go into the Western Conference finals (presumably against
Portland) not as candidates for Mount Olympus but merely as
championship favorites with a fight on their hands.
</P>
<P>
   They never said they were anything more than that. And give them
credit, they were right. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Kevin Modesti's column appears in the Daily News three days a week.
He can be reached at (818) 713-3616. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
