<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-FATES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIL FATES, 86, A TV PRODUCER OF SHOWS LIKE `WHAT'S MY LINE?'  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gil Fates, an executive producer of some of the leading
television game and panel shows of the 1950s and 60s, died on May 1
at Beth Israel Medical Center in Manhattan. He was 86 and lived in
Greenwich, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   In more than 35 years with Goodson-Todman Productions, Fates
helped to create programs like ``Beat the Clock,'' ``Winner Take
All,'' ``To Tell the Truth,'' ``I've Got a Secret'' and ``What's My
Line?,'' which he produced for its entire 25-year run.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Newark, he graduated from the University of Virginia,
where he was active in the Virginia Players drama society. He began
his career as an actor, appearing in the road company of ``Stage
Door'' and on Broadway in the George S. Kaufman-Moss Hart
spectacular ``The American Way.'' He was also stage manager for the
touring company of ``The Man Who Came to Dinner'' with Alexander
Woollcott.
</P>
<P>
   After three years Fates left the theater for the fledgling
television department at CBS. He produced and served as host of the
first regularly scheduled game show, ``The CBS Television Quiz,''
which began on July 2, 1941, and was broadcast from a loft above
the main waiting room of Grand Central Terminal.
</P>
<P>
   During World War II Fates served in the United States Coast
Guard and was commanding officer of a rescue cutter in the English
Channel during the allied invasion at Normandy.
</P>
<P>
   After rejoining CBS in 1946, in what he called ``the halcyon
days of the 8- and 10-inch screen,'' he wore many hats: overseeing
animal, cooking and art shows; covering elections; providing
commentary for sports events; and presiding over game shows,
including ``What's It Worth?''
</P>
<P>
   He left CBS in 1950 to produce ``The Faye Emerson Show'' and
joined Goodson-Todman in 1953. In 1978 he compiled stories of his
encounters with celebrities and contestants in a book, ``What's My
Line? The History of America's Most Famous Panel Show.''
</P>
<P>
   Fates also supervised the production of foreign-language
versions of ``Family Feud,'' ``Card Sharks,'' ``Password,'' ``The
Match Game'' and other shows. Most recently he had gone on the road
again, regaling audiences at clubs and on cruise ships with
anecdotes based on his experience in broadcasting.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Faye; a son, Dailey Gilbert of Santa
Barbara, Calif.; and two daughters, Amy, of Santa Monica, Calif.,
and Decia, of Greenport, N.Y.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-00 2335EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
