r s BC-BKC-UCLA-LAVIN-LADN     05-15 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-LAVIN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAVIN LOOKING TO FILL BIG HOLES AT UCLA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With star forward Jason Kapono the latest of three
UCLA basketball players to exit the program and enter the NBA
draft, coach Steve Lavin could probably use a vacation and take a
break from thinking about next year's roster.
</P>
<P>
   But Lavin said Monday he canceled his scheduled holiday in June
because of the large number of recruits seeking to make unofficial
campus visits following the recent defections of Kapono and
forwards Jerome Moiso and Jaron Rush.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because we've lost three players, it helps recruiting,'' Lavin
said. ``We've got a lot of parents flying in unofficially on their
own because they know a lot of minutes will be available. There's
wing players all over the country who want to step up and commit.''
</P>
<P>
   That was about the best possible spin Lavin could put on recent
events within his program, which culminated with last weekend's
announcement that Kapono would make himself available for the draft
but return to school if he was not a first-round draft choice.
</P>
<P>
   The consensus opinion is that Kapono is a near-certain
first-round selection, meaning UCLA could start next season with
only eight scholarship players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw (Jason) Saturday. I think he's really excited,'' Lavin
said. ``He feels excited he will be a first-rounder.''
</P>
<P>
   But where does that leave the Bruins?
</P>
<P>
   Lavin compared the situation to 1998, when UCLA lost Toby
Bailey, J.R. Henderson, Kris Johnson and Jelani McCoy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost 80 percent of our scoring and 70 percent of our
rebounding,'' Lavin said. ``We lost a lot. We signed 11 kids over
two years, and now we'll be doing a similar thing.''
</P>
<P>
   With one huge difference. All of those players, except McCoy,
were seniors, and Lavin had plenty of time to recruit to ease their
departures. There's little talent left in May that could actually
help UCLA next season.
</P>
<P>
   Lavin said he wants to add a post player for next season. UCLA
is recruiting Jair Valduis, a 6-foot-9 Dutch forward from Mill
Valley High in Northern California. Valduis has narrowed his
choices to UCLA and Villanova and visited UCLA last week. But he
has not qualified academically and may have to attend a prep school
next year.
</P>
<P>
   Another possibility is Tony Parker, a 6-2 guard from France who
impressed coaches during an all-star game at the Final Four in
Indianapolis, but he also has academic questions and his amateur
status could also become an issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Jason stays we could sign two more players, but probably
only one,'' Lavin said.
</P>
<P>
   However, as even Lavin pointed out, they would not be players of
Kapono's caliber.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we lose Jason, there's not a freshman that could come in
and make up for his loss,'' Lavin said.
</P>
<P>
   When asked Monday, Lavin said he never anticipated before the
season that Kapono would leave UCLA after just one year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming into the season, I wouldn't have projected that Jason
would be a first-rounder by the end of the first year,'' Lavin
said. ``But as the season went along ... he was in the spotlight
more than any freshman since I've been here. And at the end, when
we got hot (as a team), he got that much more exposure.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the accolades and awards started piling up, then the
concern developed that he's someone who could be a first-rounder. I
think he probably had _ short of playing in the Final Four _ as
good or as close to a storybook year as I can remember a freshman
having.''
</P>
<P>
   Kapono initially told Lavin that he was going to ``keep my
options open'' about a week after the season ended.
</P>
<P>
   His departure would place UCLA well below conference favorites
Arizona and Stanford in preseason projections.
</P>
<P>
   But the news hasn't been all bad for Lavin. Forward Matt Barnes
informed him that he would not attempt to play football next year,
and will focus on basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the next two years, he could start 60 games for UCLA,''
Lavin said of Barnes. ``Why would you want to set yourself back
behind incoming players and the returning players? I was happy
because now he can give a more concentrated effort.''
</P>
<P>
   NOTES: Mater Dei High point guard Cedric Bozeman, who committed
to UCLA last September before rescinding it this spring, visited
the campus last weekend. He remains undecided on where he will
attend college. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
