<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ETRADE AND WIT CAPITAL &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Team Up for Underwriting Acknowledging how hard it has been to
break the stranglehold Wall Street has on the underwriting of new
stocks, two online financial-services companies, ETrade Group and
Wit Capital Group, said they would team up to compete against their
offline rivals.
</P>
<P>
   ETrade said it would form an alliance with Wit Capital after
that online investment bank acquires EOffering, a rival that ETrade
helped to finance a year ago. Wit Capital plans to issue stock
worth $328 million to the shareholders of EOffering.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AOL AGREES TO SETTLE WITH SEC
</P>
<P>
   Case America Online agreed to pay a fine of $3.5 million and to
restate its books from 1995 and 1996 after the Securities and
Exchange Commission charged that the company had improperly
inflated profits by hundreds of millions of dollars. For America
Online, which stopped using the disputed accounting method in 1996,
the settlement is probably of minimal import now. But it could have
an effect on other companies in young and rapidly changing
industries because the commission's position will force them to
deduct all promotional expenses from earnings immediately. Shares
of AOL rose $3.125, to $58.50.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNILEVER PRESSURES BESTFOODS
</P>
<P>
   Stepping up the pressure on a reluctant takeover target, the
co-chairman of Unilever said that he thought the $18.4 billion
offer made this month for Bestfoods was ``serious money'' and that
the company wants Bestfoods' executives to meet with Unilever to
discuss it.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ASTRAZENECA TO SELL ALTERED RICE
</P>
<P>
   AstraZeneca said that it would sell a genetically altered strain
of ``golden rice'' with beta carotene in the developed world and
also make the technology freely available to the world's poorest
countries.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOUR MAIN BRAZILIAN AIRLINES STRUGGLE
</P>
<P>
   The four main airlines in Brazil are stuggling, reflecting what
executives call a hostile financial and regulatory environment for
air transportation in Latin America's largest economy. All the
airlines have asked the government to make drastic changes in
aviation policies to ensure that the domestic industry will survive
stronger international rivals.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRICELINE PRESIDENT TO BECOME CHIEF
</P>
<P>
   Priceline.com, the name-your-price Internet retailer, announced
that its president and chief operating officer would take on the
additional role of chief executive. Daniel Schulman, 42, left, will
take the chief executive title from Richard Braddock, 58, who will
remain chairman. The changes take effect June 15. Schulman joined
Priceline.com in June 1999 after 18 years at AT&AMP;T, where he led its
consumer markets division.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT UPDATES E-MAIL SOFTWARE
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft said that it had developed a software update for its
Outlook e-mail program that would reduce its vulnerability to rogue
computer programs like ``I Love You.''
</P>
<P>
   INDUSTRIAL PRODUCTION RISES 0.9%
</P>
<P>
   Production at the nation's factories, mines and utilities grew
0.9 percent in April, the fastest pace in nearly one and a half
years, as businesses scrambled to meet demand.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TOYS `R' US POSTS 41% GAIN IN PROFIT
</P>
<P>
   Toys ``R'' Us said that its operating earnings rose for the
first time in more than two years under its chief executive's plan
to increase sales. First-quarter profit from operations rose 41
percent, beating forecasts.
</P>
</TEXT>
