<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WARD IS THE FATHER OF REINVENTION AS A GO-TO GUY  

</HEADLINE>
   By STEVE POPPER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PURCHASE, N.Y. _ First, Anthony Carter emerged from anonymity
with tales of $1,000 playground games to become the unlikely hero
of Game 3 for the Miami Heat. Then, in Game 4, Charlie Ward wiped
off the criticism that has fallen on him like rain throughout his
Knicks career and played savior on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   In a series in which almost every X and O is accounted for in
marathon film sessions, Knicks Coach Jeff Van Gundy and Heat Coach
Pat Riley still fear the unknown: the player who slips through the
cracks in the reams of videotapes.
</P>
<P>
   It was Carter stepping in for Tim Hardaway and winning Game 3
with a circus shot with 2.2 seconds remaining in overtime last
Friday night. It was Ward leading the Knicks in scoring in each of
their two victories _ a feat he accomplished only twice in the
regular season _ to tie the series at 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``That happens always in the playoffs,'' said Don Chaney, an
assistant coach for the Knicks. ``It's not always the stars who
really are the X-factor in terms of wins and losses. It's always an
unknown, a guy who's not normally known for doing certain things,
either a bench player or a starter, as in Charlie's case, who
normally doesn't put up the big numbers. Those are the people who
normally are the key factors in whether you win or lose on a
consistent basis in the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   For Ward, scoring 20 points Sunday, a postseason high, brought
about disparate opinions. The Knicks looked at his performance as
the answer to the defensive pressure by the Heat. Ward was the
safety valve, the one to send the ball flying toward when the
double-teams came on Allan Houston, Latrell Sprewell and Patrick
Ewing.
</P>
<P>
   But Carter, Ward's counterpoint, thought that Ward's points were
a worthless, garbage-time contribution. While Carter's opinion that
the game was already decided when Ward ran off the final 9 points
is debatable, that Ward unexpectedly provided an offensive burst is
not.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks looked to their point guard for an advantage in
trying to expose the ailing Hardaway and the inexperienced Carter.
Now that Ward has responded, the Knicks have posed a choice to the
Heat: ease the double-teaming on Houston or Sprewell, or gamble
that Ward will not strike again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, Miami is a great defensive team,'' Ewing said, whose
12.8 points a game this series have been matched by Ward. ``They're
going to try to do things to take the ball out of Latrell, Allan
and my hands. Somebody has to step up. I'm not going to say it's
going to be Charlie every night. Somebody is going to have to step
up and get the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley coached Ward during the point guard's rookie season with
the Knicks in 1994-95 and has expressed respect for his skills,
maybe more respect than Ward gets now. But given the choice, the
Knicks expect the Heat to dare Ward to prove he can do it again.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said it wasn't scaring them, but who cares,'' Houston
said. ``The series is tied and, if anything, they know he's
capable. I think they'll try to play the same way. What helps is we
were able to get the ball where we wanted to get it. Sometimes if
you let them force your way out, they don't have to double. But if
we drive the ball in the paint or post up in the paint, whether
they double or not, something good is going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell said: ``As well as he was doing yesterday, there's no
way they can leave him if he plays like that. I don't know if
that's asking a lot or not, but he was in a zone yesterday. If he's
that hot, they're going to have to do something about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Chaney agreed, adding: ``I don't think they'll say, `OK, we have
to focus on Charlie and not focus on Allan and Sprewell.' I think
what they're saying is: `Charlie has a great game. It probably was
an unusual thing. We've got to check him but we still have to keep
our main focus on Sprewell and Allan and secondarily, Patrick and
Larry. You did it once. OK, now prove to us that that wasn't a
freak thing.'''
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not Carter is correct in his harsh assessment of
Ward, the Knick did contribute more than just points on Sunday.
Ward also gave the Knicks the sort of emotion, aggressiveness and
desperation they needed if they hoped to squeeze past the Heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because we won a game doesn't mean we're in a good
position,'' Houston said. ``We have to make it that way. And this
is a going to be a golden opportunity for us to do that. I'm not
going to say we're in a hole, but I'd say they're in a better
position than we are.''
</P>
<P>
   Ewing said: ``People thought we were going to come in and sweep
them. We came in here knowing it was going to be a dogfight and
we're prepared for that.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
