<SLUG> BC-SWIM-THORPE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE RECORDS IN 3 DAYS FOR AUSTRALIA'S THORPE  

</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN SHAW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ Ian Thorpe, the teen-age torpedo of world
swimming, said Sunday he had great expectations for himself. He
matched those quiet words with swift action Monday by delivering
the third of three world records in three days.
</P>
<P>
   Thorpe, five months shy of his 18th birthday, powered his
6-foot-6-inch frame in the 200-meter and 400-meter freestyle
events, breaking his world records in the Australian Olympic trials
over the weekend to qualify for those races in the Summer Games
here in September.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, in the 200-meter final, Thorpe was in
record-setting form, slicing an additional .18 of a second from his
record for a time of 1 minute 45.51 seconds. In the semifinals
Sunday night, Thorpe swam 1:45.69, cutting .31 seconds off the
world record he set last August at the Pan-Pacific championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's awesome,'' Michael Klim, 20, said after finishing half a
body length behind Thorpe.
</P>
<P>
   Klim also qualified for an Olympic start, giving Australia
strong reason to hope for two medals in the 200 meters.
</P>
<P>
   An hour before Thorpe achieved his third world record Monday,
Australia's chief swim coach, Don Talbot, said he thought that
Thorpe had looked ``a little strained and tired'' after breaking
two records over the weekend. But Thorpe was smiling and hardly
breathless tonight as he emerged to tell a poolside television
interviewer: ``I swam for an Olympic place, not a record. I was
feeling a bit tired, but I had the Olympic incentive.''
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, in the Australian team qualifiers, Thorpe began his
tripleheader by breaking by half a second his 400-meter world mark
of 3.41.83.
</P>
<P>
   Crowds of about 8,000 cheered Thorpe's records _ perhaps the
only sounds of popular approval organizers of the Sydney Games have
heard in a week. The lighting ceremony in Greece of the torch for
the 2000 Olympics produced criticism of Kevan Gosper, Australia's
most senior member of the International Olympic Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Gosper, who is a former Olympic track medalist, was forced to
apologize for what he called ``my lapse of judgment, clouded by
fatherly pride.'' He said he had accepted an official Greek
invitation for his 11-year-old daughter, Sophie, to be the first
Australian to run in the first stage of the torch relay last
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   That honor had been allotted months earlier to a
Greek-Australian high school student, Yianna Souleles, 15, who had
been chosen by Sydney's influential Greek immigrant community to
represent Australian youth at the ceremonial start of the torch's
journey to Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   Gosper was cleared Monday by the IOC ethics commission of having
violated rules on excessive travel and gifts during Salt Lake
City's winning campaign for the 2002 Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers of the Sydney Games hope that Thorpe's rush of
records, which boost Australian hopes of winning as many as nine
gold swim medals, will distract attention from Gosper's mistake,
the latest in a series of public relations disasters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-00 2343EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000515.0436 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 23:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6226 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-GIULIANI-NYT &LR;      05-15 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GIULIANI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI SAYS HE EXPECTS TO RUN, BUT HIS BACKERS ARE NERVOUS  
 
</HEADLINE>
  By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani raised more money Monday
night for his Senate campaign, telling a small crowd of supporters
at a Manhattan restaurant, ``I'm very much inclined to do this.''
</P>
<P>
   But earlier he continued to say that he had not yet decided on
his cancer treatment or whether he was definitely in the race.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans reacted with growing exasperation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like `Waiting for Godot,' we have `Waiting for Rudy,''' said
James Cavanaugh, the Westchester County Republican chairman, who
said the mayor needed to make a decision about the campaign this
week. ``There's a recognition that if we're going to go to a new
candidate, we have to start yesterday. We need a pretty fast answer
from the mayor as to whether he's in or out.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Minarik, the Monroe County chairman, sounded a similar
alarm. ``We need a decision,'' he said. ``Like tomorrow would be
nice. Because this is getting ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   But other Republicans said they were not going to pressure
Giuliani with a deadline for fear that he would use it to get out
of the race. Still others said that the mayor, who appeared relaxed
and tanned at a standing-room-only noon news conference in the City
Hall Blue Room, seemed more likely to stay in for now. At the
least, they said, Giuliani did not appear unhappy keeping the state
party on edge guessing his next move.
</P>
<P>
   ``He seemed to like the attention,'' said one top state
Republican official, who watched the mayor at the news conference.
``He seems to be going through some sort of catharsis in public.
And we're like psychiatrists watching it. I can't quite figure it
out. I don't think anybody can.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani did say at the news conference that he was canceling a
fund-raising trip to California Tuesday and Wednesday to meet with
doctors and think through his options, and added that ``things
involving my personal life'' had kept him from consulting with more
doctors last week.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani gave his usual campaign speech about the city's revival
at Monday night's $1,000-per-person fund-raiser, held at Martini's
restaurant at Seventh Ave. and 53rd St. The crowd of 50
enthusiastically applauded the mayor. Afterward, Giuliani spoke
briefly to reporters, telling them, as he has repeatedly in recent
weeks, that he hopes to be able to run.
</P>
<P>
   One supporter at the event, Thyra Hanna of Westchester County,
said it was important to support the mayor during a difficult time.
``I feel bad for the poor guy,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two and a half weeks, Giuliani has announced that he
has prostate cancer, has a woman friend and is seeking a separation
from his wife. He has also said he stands by earlier denials that
he did not have an intimate relationship with an aide, Cristyne
Lategano-Nicholas, as his estranged wife suggested last Wednesday.
Lategano-Nicholas said on Thursday that her relationship with
Giuliani had never been sexual.
</P>
<P>
   The State Republican Party has been incredulous at the
disclosures of the mayor, who spent last Friday night at a
restaurant and then strolled around the Upper East Side in a
explosion of flashbulbs with his good friend, Judith Nathan. It was
the same day that Giuliani's wife, Donna Hanover, left Gracie
Mansion with their two children to spend Mother's Day weekend with
her family in California.
</P>
<P>
   Hanover's press secretary, Joannie Danielides, said Monday that
Hanover would return to Gracie Mansion ``in a few more days'' with
her children, whom she kept out of school this week for the trip.
Danielides also said that Hanover had received various ``requests
and offers'' since the mayor announced their separation without
Hanover's knowledge last Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have been calling like there's no tomorrow,''
Danielides said.
</P>
<P>
   She added that Hanover and Giuliani would continue to live in
the large upstairs family quarters of Gracie Mansion as they worked
out their separation agreement.
</P>
<P>
   At his news conference, which was carried live by most local
television stations, the mayor said he felt under no pressure from
Republicans to make a decision, even though the party has to
nominate its Senate candidate in two weeks. The pressure, the mayor
said, was internal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel under pressure,'' he said, emphasizing the word ``I.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel it's right that I make a decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's comments came as Republicans appeared to be
coalescing around Representative Rick A. Lazio as their candidate
if the mayor does not run. Lazio's aides said Monday that he was
increasingly certain to seek the seat if Giuliani withdrew.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Gov. George E. Pataki said at a news
conference that he had no interest in the seat, and said he would
probably seek re-election in 2002. Theodore J. Forstmann, a Wall
Street investor and philanthropist, announced Monday night that he
would not run.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
