<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.N.-AFRICA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. IS ASKING FOR SANCTIONS ON ETHIOPIA AND ERITREA 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds. This story, previously eliminated, has been restored.) 
By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ The United States asked the Security Council
Monday to impose sanctions on Ethiopia and Eritrea until fighting
stops along their border.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed resolution would prohibit the sale or delivery of
all kinds of weapons and military equipment to either side. It
would also bar senior Ethiopian officials from international
travel.
</P>
<P>
   Ethiopia opened the latest phase of a three-year war by
attacking Eritrea on Friday and has rejected a council demand to
return to peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   The American proposal is meeting resistance in the council, said
Ambassador Nancy Soderberg, who represented the United States in
the discussions Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has a draft resolution of its own; it does not include an
arms ban but rather calls for more diplomatic missions to the
region. But Russia, which has been selling arms to both sides, is
not likely to veto an American resolution, diplomats say.
</P>
<P>
   China's ambassador, Wang Yingfan, who is this month's council
president, told reporters after the meeting Monday that China
generally opposed sanctions anywhere because of their effects on
the general population. But some diplomats say that China may be
swayed to support some kind of embargo, or at least not vote
against it, if African members of the council join in the call for
action.
</P>
<P>
   France is prepared to accept sanctions if they come with a time
limit, diplomats said after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The council will return to the issue on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, after war broke out over claims to disputed
territory, the council gave the two sides 72 hours to recommit
themselves to negotiations, which had collapsed two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   After the breakdown, seven council members on a peace mission in
Africa detoured to the Horn of Africa for last-minute talks with
President Isaias Afwerki of Eritrea and Prime Minister Meles Zenawi
of Ethiopia. By then, however, it seemed clear to the visiting
diplomats that the two sides were on an unstoppable march to
battle.
</P>
<P>
   Soderberg, who is a specialist on Africa for the American
mission to the United Nations, said Monday that two earlier rounds
of fighting between Eritrea and Ethiopia in 1998 and 1999 have
killed as many people as the United States lost in Vietnam.
Casualty estimates from those pitched battles _ carried out in
trench warfare _ range from 20,000 to 70,000 dead.
</P>
<P>
   France and several African nations have suggested that
arbitration of the border would be possible. Few differences
remained between the two sides in peace talks, diplomats say.
</P>
<P>
   Observing the 72-hour deadline they had been set, both countries
sent letters to the council Monday. Eritrea, which is getting hit
hard by Ethiopian troops, said it was prepared to return to talks.
Ethiopia sent what an envoy called a ``very belligerent'' letter
defying the council and rejecting mediation.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Meles of Ethiopia is assumed to be under intense
pressure from hard-liners who resent the agreement that gave
Eritrea independence from Ethiopia in 1993. When Eritrea separated,
it took Ethiopia's only port, at Assab on the Red Sea, making
Ethiopia a landlocked country.
</P>
<P>
   The port is not a target of fighting now, but some United
Nations officials say they think it remains Ethiopia's ultimate
goal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
