u s BC-BKN-HEAT-HARDAWAY-NYT     05-15 0603
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HEAT-HARDAWAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARDAWAY WILL START DESPITE FOOT SPRAIN  
 
</HEADLINE>
  By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COCONUT GROVE, Fla. _ Slowed by a sprain in his left foot, point
guard Tim Hardaway fielded suggestions after the Miami Heat's loss
to the Knicks on Sunday that he might be hindering his team.
Monday, after meeting with Coach Pat Riley, Hardaway announced that
he would start Wednesday night in Game 5 of the four-of-seven-game
series at American Airlines Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The 11th-year pro, who has made just 8 of 30 field-goal attempts
and has been a defensive liability in the series, would not discuss
what happened in his meeting with Riley. But that was not
necessary; earlier, Riley had given the news media an earful about
Hardaway's worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tim is absolutely playing as courageously as he can and
despite what people say, he has been a positive for us,'' Riley
said. ``He struggled in the third quarter a little bit yesterday,
but we need him. We need his heart, we need his savvy.''
</P>
<P>
   The more Riley talked, the more upset he became about the
pointed questions directed at Hardaway after the Knicks tied the
series at two games each.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe anyone's going to go after him and start
putting him on the burner,'' Riley said. ``Tim has given everything
he can give. I don't think his presence out on that court ever
hurts our team. I know guys who would have packed up and left for
the summer and people would accuse them of being cowards, right?
Tim is just the opposite.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Riley kept Hardaway on the bench in the fourth quarter
Sunday, the second consecutive game in which Riley has opted for
the quick rookie Anthony Carter down the stretch. But that absolved
Hardaway of blame in the Heat's collapse, in the coach's view.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't on the court and he didn't make nine turnovers and
he didn't miss four free throws and he did what he had to do to
give us an opportunity to win the game,'' Riley said. ``So I
wouldn't be pointing a finger at Tim Hardaway. That's totally
unfair.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley did acknowledge, though, that Miami was ``working our way
around'' Hardaway's limitations.
</P>
<P>
   Power forward P.J. Brown said it had become apparent early in
the game Sunday that the Knicks' game plan involved attacking
Hardaway with Charlie Ward and Chris Childs. Ward finished with 20
points; Childs had 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going after him, and trying to take advantage,'' Brown
said. ``All of us have to be held accountable in helping out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Heat is sticking with Hardaway in large part because of his
leadership and his long-range shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can't break defenses down or do the things he's used to
doing or wants to do, but he's still directing the team,'' Brown
said. ``The Knicks still rotate to him because his 3-pointer is
still deadly.''
</P>
<P>
   Hardaway cut off questions Monday about his injury, incurred
late in the regular season. ``Yes, I'm going to play on
Wednesday,'' he said. ``Everybody knows I'm hurt. It's not going to
get better until after I'm through playing. That's it.''
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledged that he was upset by reporters' questions on
Sunday and noted that Riley's defense of him made it easier for him
to turn the page. ``It's always good for him to blow up instead of
me,'' Hardaway said, ``because I say some outlandish things.''
</P>
<P>
   The light atmosphere produced by that remark was fleeting.
Hardaway's face tightened when someone asked about Ward's
elusiveness on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to deal with all these questions now,'' he said,
walking off. ``If I was 100 percent, we wouldn't be talking about
that.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
