<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-LEGAL-BILLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTONS STILL PAYING THE BILLS FOR INQUIRIES, STATEMENT SAYS  
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The financial holdings of President Clinton and
Hillary Rodham Clinton changed little in 1999 from the previous
year, but the president and first lady continued to pay large legal
bills arising from the Whitewater investigation and impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   In his annual financial statement, Clinton reported assets of
$1.2 million to $5.7 million, similar to the figure for 1998. The
government requires a range rather than precise numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The president paid $2.25 million in fees to four law firms but
still owes $4.3 million, the statement said. The payments came from
the Clinton Legal Expense Trust, which raises money from the
public. Clinton reported them as a gift.
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons' largest single holding is a blind trust valued at
between $1 million and $5 million. They also have relatively small
holdings in stock, bank accounts and life insurance.
</P>
<P>
   The couple's income dipped slightly in 1999, to $416,639, from
1998, when they reported an adjusted gross income of $504,109. The
difference came from a reduction in royalties from Clinton's book,
``It Takes a Village.'' The Clintons have contributed all earnings
from the book to charity.
</P>
<P>
   The president also reported receiving $23,602 worth of gifts
from individuals, including three golf drivers valued at $897 from
Greg Norman, the golf pro; a collection of CDs valued at $297 from
Tommy Mottola, the record industry executive; and a set of cuff
links and a book worth $1,515 from Erskine B. Bowles, the former
White House chief of staff.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
