</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UPI-UNIFICATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE UNIFICATION CHURCH'S NEWS AFFILIATE BUYS UPI 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER MARQUIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ United Press International, the 93-year-old wire
service that has struggled for years with red ink and a succession
of owners, has been bought by a news affiliate of the Unification
Church, company officials announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
   News World Communications Inc., which publishes The Washington
Times and was founded by the Rev. Sun Myung Moon, the leader of the
Unification Church, acquired UPI for an undisclosed sum, executives
from both companies said.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Moffit, special assistant to the president of News World
Communications, said his company would not interfere with the
editorial autonomy of the wire service.
</P>
<P>
   ``UPI will maintain its editorial independence and build on its
reputation for honest, fair-minded reporting that has made it an
essential and respected news agency for generations,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In its heyday, UPI was the chief rival of The Associated Press
and had a stable of future industry leaders _ including Walter
Cronkite and David Brinkley _ who scored a number of scoops.
</P>
<P>
   In 1963, Merriman Smith, UPI White House correspondent, first
told the world of the assassination of President Kennedy by
refusing to share a press phone in the motorcade with his AP
counterpart. Smith went on to receive the Pulitzer Prize, one of 10
given to the agency.
</P>
<P>
   Troubled by dwindling profits in recent years, UPI twice
declared bankruptcy and endured a nearly continuous stream of
layoffs and asset sales. The agency changed hands three times in a
decade, passing from the Mexican publisher Mario Vazquez-Rana to
California venture capitalist Earl Brian and then, in 1992, to its
most recent owner, a company controlled by the brother-in-law of
King Fahd of Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
   Arnaud de Borchgrave, UPI's president and chief executive
officer, will remain in his current position, Moffit said. Among
the few leadership changes announced was a move by Dong Moon Joo,
the president of the Washington Times Corp., to become chairman of
the UPI board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   De Borchgrave, who notified his staff of the purchase this
afternoon, voiced optimism about the sale, which he said would not
result in any layoffs. There are currently 157 UPI employees, he
said, with 107 based in Washington and the rest in London, Latin
America and Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I protected every single job,'' said de Borchgrave, who said
he fended off a more lucrative offer that would have laid off the
entire staff and moved the headquarters to London.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations will begin in the next few weeks to sell UPI's
headquarters building in downtown Washington, where the agency
leases space, he said.
</P>
<P>
   De Borchgrave expressed no reservations about working under the
corporate control of the deeply conservative Unification Church. De
Borchgrave, a former Newsweek correspondent, served as
editor-in-chief of The Washington Times until 1991, and complained
of no ideological meddling while there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not once in all my seven years as editor-in-chief was I given
any suggestions of any kind,'' de Borchgrave said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Moon, a South Korean evangelist who built a corporate empire of
hundreds of companies and a religious following known for mass
weddings and aggressive recruitment practices, founded The
Washington Times nearly two decades ago. He served a year in prison
after a conviction on tax evasion in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   While the paper has never challenged the much larger Washington
Post in circulation, it has become a touchstone for capital
conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   Moffit said News World Communications will encourage executives
at UPI to continue to expand their Internet services, while also
seeking to provide ``customized'' news in such fields as national
security, family issues, religion and morality and science and
technology.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-00 2350EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
