<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 23:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6236 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-POLICE-REPORT-NYT &LR;      05-15 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-REPORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE CALL FEDERAL RACIAL PROFILING REPORT RECKLESSLY UNFAIR  

</HEADLINE>
   By KEVIN FLYNN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a bitterly worded rebuttal, the New York Police
Department has denounced a draft report by the United States Civil
Rights Commission that accused the police of racial profiling. The
department asserted that the panel's research was slipshod and its
conclusions recklessly unfair.
</P>
<P>
   The vehemence of the department's rebuttal, which is scheduled
to be delivered to the commission in Washington Tuesday, was also
suggested by the length of the response _ 700 pages. The panel's
report was 250 pages long.
</P>
<P>
   In the response, the department says the panel was unfairly
selective in its use of facts and relied too heavily on what it
characterized as the unsupported allegations of a set of regular
critics of the police department, including the Rev. Al Sharpton
and Norman Siegel, executive director of the New York Civil
Liberties Union.
</P>
<P>
   ``The report is an unfortunate exercise in shoddy reporting, in
lieu of legitimate research methods, in order to publicly defame
the reputation of the department,'' the rebuttal says. ``As such,
the report is so poorly prepared that it is an embarrassment to the
United States government.''
</P>
<P>
   In its draft report, the panel, an advisory body made up of four
Democrats, three independents and one Republican, characterized the
police department's approach to race relations as seriously flawed
and said the department's data suggested that its officers had
routinely stopped black and Hispanic people largely because of
their race.
</P>
<P>
   Although Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani has dismissed the commission
report as an attempt to help his possible rival for the Senate,
Hillary Rodham Clinton, police officials said they would leave it
to others to decide whether the commission's motivations were
political.
</P>
<P>
   The commission declined to comment Monday on the police
response, a copy of which was obtained by The New York Times from a
police official. Ruby G. Moy, director of the commission staff,
said the panel had not received a copy yet, but pointed out that in
remarks on Friday, the panel's general counsel, Edward Hailes, had
defended the professionalism and the fairness of the commission's
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The findings and recommendations, if accepted, are fact-based
and not extreme,'' Hailes said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The city's Civilian Complaint Review Board, an independent panel
that investigates allegations of police misconduct, is sending the
commission its own response to the draft report. The draft had
recommended improvements in the review board's procedures. The
mayor's office will not respond to the draft report directly, said
Sunny Mindel, a spokeswoman for the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   The city's responses will be reviewed by the executive staff,
which will consider possible revisions to the report before the
commission's next meeting on June 16, said Kim Alton, a commission
spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   The commission's draft report cited an array of deficiencies in
the department, from its efforts to recruit minorities to the way
it teaches officers about cultural diversity. But police officials
appeared to be most stung by a finding that that the department
disproportionately stopped blacks and Hispanics during street
patrols by aggressive anti-crime units. For example, the draft
report found fault with the fact that 51 percent of those stopped
on Staten Island were black, even though the borough's population
is only 9 percent black.
</P>
<P>
   ``For such a critically serious finding, the report does not
contain a shred of the necessary analysis to even try to prove its
apparently predisposed conclusion,'' the department's response
states.
</P>
<P>
   The police response, which was crafted by the department's
lawyers, says more minority residents are stopped because more
officers are deployed in high-crime neighborhoods with large
minority populations. In addition, it says the race of those
stopped corresponds roughly with the race of criminal suspects as
reported to the police.
</P>
<P>
   The draft report had dismissed this argument, asserting that in
most cases, officers had confronted people on the basis of their
own observations, not identifications by victims or witnesses. But
in their response, the police suggest that most stops occur
precisely because an officer is familiar with the general
description of a criminal who may have been involved in a pattern
of robberies or violent gang activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless the commission is suggesting that officers ignore
descriptions and continuing crime patterns, this information will
and should be utilized to help develop reasonable suspicion to
legally stop a person,'' the response says.
</P>
<P>
   The police analysis appears to be at odds with the findings of a
report last year by Attorney General Eliot L. Spitzer, which
concluded that officers stopped citizens on the basis of their
resemblance to a known criminal suspect only about 30 percent of
the time. Police officials at the time said that that study was
flawed.
</P>
<P>
   City and police officials said they were pushing to have their
responses published as an appendix to the final version of the
report. But they said the draft report had already damaged the
department by maligning its programs to recruit and promote black
and Hispanic officers while ignoring its success in reducing police
shootings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where do we go to get our reputation back?'' asked George
Grasso, the police department's deputy commissioner for legal
affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Grasso said he was not impressed by parts of the draft report in
which the commission credited the department with improvements,
such as one section citing increased public confidence in the
department's ability to resolve incidents of police misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   Grasso said he viewed those sections as disingenuous, especially
since he felt so many other parts of the report were distorted. For
example, he criticized the commission for referring several times
in the report to its difficulty in getting the department to turn
over relevant documents.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were never denied any information request by the NYPD,''
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-15-00 2351EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
