<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 23:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6238 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-GYM-MILLER-NYT &LR;      05-15 1256
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-GYM-MILLER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER RESHAPING HER BODY AT 23, MILLER TRIES TO RESHAPE OLYMPIC
CAREER 
</HEADLINE>
   By JERE LONGMAN   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ She began nosing around the gym in Oklahoma City last
fall, nothing that would put any strain on her muscles or her new
lifestyle. Shannon Miller had retired after the 1996 Summer Games,
her career secure as the most successful American gymnast, with
seven Olympic medals, two of them gold. She was now married,
attending college. She was 23 in a sport that had come to treat
maturity as impediment, where the arrival of breasts and hips was
an occurrence as unfortunate as a broken ankle.
</P>
<P>
   Just after Christmas, Miller walked into the office of her
longtime coach, Steve Nunno, and said something that she hoped
would not leave him laughing. She wanted to compete in the 2000
Olympics in Sydney, Australia. She had been away from the sport
entirely for 18 months, but she wanted to come back.
</P>
<P>
   Three years after winning a gold medal in Atlanta, the American
women had finished sixth among six teams in the team competition at
the 1999 world championships. They seemed not to know how to train
or compete, she felt. She could help them.
</P>
<P>
   Nunno did not laugh, nor did he encourage Miller.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shannon, you're not an athlete anymore,'' the coach told her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know, that's why I'm here asking you,'' Miller said. ``I
want you to help me.''
</P>
<P>
   Five months later, Miller is making her first appearance here at
the Olympic training camp run by Bela Karolyi, the famed coach who,
like Miller, has come out of retirement in hopes of hoisting a
fallen American team, just as he lifted the injured Kerri Strug in
Atlanta. Of the so-called Magnificent Seven who won gold in 1996,
five are attempting to qualify for Sydney _ Miller, Dominique
Dawes, Amy Chow, Jaycie Phelps and Dominique Moceanu. Strug and
Amanda Borden have declined comebacks, choosing higher education
over the high bar.
</P>
<P>
   New selection rules for the six-member Olympic team will allow
for specialists in addition to all-around competitors. Miller is
the reigning Olympic champion on the balance beam. Among the
Magnificent Seven, she and Chow are given the best chance of making
the team for Sydney, though a final selection will not come until
August. If she can remain healthy and motivated, Miller would bring
her reputation, reliability and elegance to a callow team.
</P>
<P>
   ``She represents the visibility and dignity of the team,''
Karolyi said. He added: ``Based on her prestige and background and
her sturdy work ethic, I am going to give her more consideration
than for anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller also represents an urgent attempt by international
gymnastics to shed its bleak reputation as a sport of inarticulate
pixies and eating disorders, one in which some athletes reportedly
took so-called ``brake'' drugs to inhibit the onset of puberty. The
harshest critics dismissed the sport as a form of child abuse.
Careers bloomed and wilted before athletes were old enough to drive
or vote.
</P>
<P>
   To counter the mounting criticism, the sport's world governing
body has in recent years raised the minimum age for Olympic
gymnasts from 15 to 16. American gymnastics officials have also
made extensive efforts to counsel athletes on the importance of
such things as healthy, balanced diets. Professionalism has led to
increased financial opportunities and prolonged careers beyond one
Olympic cycle in gymnastics and other sports such as track and
field, softball, soccer and swimming.
</P>
<P>
   The average age of American Olympians in Sydney is expected to
be 26 &UR; . &LR;  If Miller makes the team, the 2000 Summer Games would be
her third.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Shannon is out to show that you can win medals at 23,
just as she won them at 19. I think she has every capability of
winning another medal on the balance beam,'' Nunno said. ``She can
do the skills the others are doing, but she does them with so much
power and grace.''
</P>
<P>
   This, however, was not what Nunno told Miller when she first
announced her intentions for Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   For two weeks he tried to talk her out of it. She was not in
shape. She had been spending her time in the classroom, not the
gym. She could not even run a mile. The only spinning and tumbling
she did involved the laundry. Plus, Nunno had three young kids of
his own. He had told his wife that he would not be leaving anymore
for extended trips.
</P>
<P>
   ``You got to answer one question,'' Nunno told Miller. ``Why?''
</P>
<P>
   Her response, he said, was: ``I'm embarrassed that the team
finished sixth at the world championships. I can help them. I'd
feel guilty if I didn't try.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a personal hunger, too, for the adrenaline rush of
competition. Even though she had begun studying finance at the
University of Oklahoma, Miller continued to look for thrills beyond
the sedentary life of college. She took up figure skating. She
parachuted from an airplane. And now she would try for her third
Olympics. The oldest American female gymnast to win a medal in the
last half-century was Kathy Johnson, who was 24 at the 1984 Los
Angeles Games, which were boycotted by the Eastern bloc.
</P>
<P>
   Nunno agreed to coach her. Forget the sentimental notion of an
athlete going out on top, he told her. Jack Nicklaus was still
playing golf well beyond his prime. Muhammad Ali won a third
heavyweight title on the decline. Even Michael Jordan had begun to
descend the peak of his skills when he won his sixth basketball
championship.
</P>
<P>
   She could come back, he told her, but first she needed 12 weeks
of strength and cardiovascular training, along with basic
gymnastics, before she could hope to begin to retrieve the more
advanced skills. Remember the hardships, not just the medals, he
told Miller, the days when she did not want to come to practice and
was so sore that each movement was heavy and painful.
</P>
<P>
   For three months, Miller trained two or three times a day, for
up to eight hours, lifting weights, running on a treadmill, riding
a stationary bike and relearning the rudimentary skills of
gymnastics. After two weeks, she was the top athlete in the gym,
Nunno said. He was stunned. She could not do the Olympic-level
routines, but her form was impeccable and her internal gyroscope,
her awareness in the air, seemed in perfect alignment.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has this fire in her eye that she didn't have in '96,''
Nunno said. ``In Atlanta it was all about winning a medal for your
country and trying to hang on because people were telling her she
was too old at 19. She's all business now.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that there have not been discouraging moments. Eleven weeks
into her comeback, Miller told Nunno: ``I've hit the wall. I have
no life. I don't have time to do the laundry or take my taxes to
the accountant. I've never worked this hard in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You've never taken two years off, either,'' Nunno fired back.
</P>
<P>
   He cut the conditioning phase short by a week and let Miller
regain her enthusiasm. Having reshaped her body, she is now going
through the grind of reshaping her career, spending hour after
repetitive hour in the gym refining old skills and learning new
ones. She has never been stronger and she knows the value of rest
and recovery now, when to push hard, when to pull back.
</P>
<P>
   Does she ever think about the possibility that her comeback will
fail?
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes those thoughts creep in, but I push them out as
quick as possible,'' Miller said. ``I can't think, `What if I don't
make it?' No matter what, I tried. That's when regret would set in,
if I didn't try.''
</P>
</TEXT>
